<HEADLINE>
TRANS WORLD AIRLINES SUFFERS $53.69 MILLION THIRD-QUARTER NET
LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Higher fuel costs and the negative effects of a
potential strike led to a substantial loss for Trans World Airlines
Inc. in its 1999 third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   For the three months that ended Sept. 30, TWA posted a net loss
of $53.69 million, or 87 cents a share. A year earlier, TWA lost
$5.31 million, or 18 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   TWA's results from operations also suffered. Excluding costs
related to the ratification of a new contract with the Machinists
union, TWA lost $25.41 million in operations in the quarter,
compared with an operational gain of $23.69 million in the 1998
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue was up slightly to $876.43 million from $863.16 million.
</P>
<P>
   About 16,000 Machinists ratified a new contract with TWA in
July, a process that cost the company $33.52 million. TWA had
warned that business travelers were booking other airlines during
its labor uncertainty, but the third-quarter loss still was bigger
than expected, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be a legitimate excuse that they struggled with the
labor issue and the loss of business travelers,'' said Bill
DiBenedetto, editor of Commercial Aviation Report, an industry
financial newsletter. ``But the excuses are starting to wear pretty
thin.''
</P>
<P>
   TWA's yield _ the amount passengers pay for each mile traveled _
dropped 6.6 percent quarter to quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When yield goes down, you're not booking the first-class and
premium business travelers that airlines want,'' DiBenedetto said.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem, which affected all airlines, was higher fuel
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Palumbo, TWA's executive vice president and chief
financial officer, said TWA paid about 28 percent more for a gallon
of fuel in the latest quarter, compared with a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to costs at TWA is its fleet modernization program,
Palumbo said. As planes are retired, more-efficient ones are being
added to the fleet. However, they are being leased, adding to
operational expenses.
</P>
<P>
   TWA has added 30 new aircraft this year, 15 of them arriving in
the third quarter, according to Palumbo. The airline is hoping that
higher leasing costs eventually will be offset by savings generated
by planes that are more fuel-efficient and less expensive to
maintain.
</P>
<P>
   By year-end, TWA said, 40 percent of the fleet will have been
replaced since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   DiBenedetto said: ``It's a real touchy position for them because
they're taking on new planes but still have the maintenance costs
of the old planes. The fleet isn't completely replaced yet.''
</P>
<P>
   TWA is working to reverse its fortunes, said William F. Compton,
TWA's president and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must improve the revenue side while ... reducing the cost
side,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   TWA continues to review its route structure, seeking to
eliminate unprofitable routes, Compton said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of TWA's strategy is to create ``focus cities,'' where TWA
will bulk up service. The first city will be San Juan, Puerto Rico,
where more flights will be added Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Compton said TWA planned to add a focus city in 2000 and another
in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   On the cost side, Compton said, TWA's reservation centers are
expected to become more efficient through technological upgrades.
In addition, TWA's labor force has shrunk from last year, and
Compton said he expected that trend to continue, mainly through
attrition.
</P>
<P>
   TWA employs about 3,500 people in Kansas City, including about
2,300 at its overhaul base at Kansas City International Airport.
TWA's lease with Kansas City on the maintenance facility will
expire at the end of May 2000, and city and airline officials
continue to negotiate a renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Nelson, president of Machinists Local 1640, said he had
been told that TWA had responded to some terms proposed by the
city. TWA apparently is awaiting a response from city officials, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get a new lease on the overhaul base to attract
third-party work there and make it a profit center again,'' Nelson
said.
</P>
<P>
   For the nine months, TWA's net loss was $81.46 million, or $1.48
a share, on $2.51 billion in revenue. In the 1998 period, the
company lost $41.34 million, or 98 cents a share, on $2.51 billion
in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   TWA is entering what historically has been its slowest period,
but it reported holding $240 million in cash on Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   TWA is ``not too worried,'' DiBenedetto said. ``They believe
their cash position is sufficient to get them through the winter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
