<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-EARNINGS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT'S SOLID QUARTER TEMPERED BY SOME LOSSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Solid third-quarter results in Sprint Corp.'s local and
long-distance businesses were tempered by widening losses from the
company's international joint venture and by ballooning costs to
develop and test its next generation of hybrid voice and data
services.
</P>
<P>
   The Westwood, Kan., company, which has agreed to be acquired by
MCI WorldCom, said Wednesday that its third-quarter profit fell 13
percent to $359 million, or 41 cents a share. That was down from
$415 million, or 47 cents a share, a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings were 1 cent shy of the consensus estimate of 42 cents a
share among analysts surveyed by First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue in the quarter rose 7.5 percent to $4.34 billion from
$4.04 billion. Including sales from the Sprint PCS wireless
business, revenue climbed to $5.11 billion from $4.34 billion, the
company's first $5 billion quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's shares closed Wednesday afternoon at 64 15/16, up 11/8.
Sprint PCS closed at 74, up 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go through the results operation by operation ... they
had a very solid quarter,'' said Tony Ferrugia, an analyst at A.G.
Edwards in St. Louis who recently upgraded Sprint's shares from
``hold'' to ``accumulate'' based on the premium that MCI WorldCom
agreed to pay to acquire Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Global One losses were slightly higher than we had estimated,
but those will mean less now that they're going to merge with
WorldCom,'' Ferrugia said.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with small losses in what the company calls ``other
ventures,'' Sprint's share of Global One's losses increased to 11
cents a share from 4 cents a year earlier. Sprint attributed the
losses to slower regional economic growth and price competition.
</P>
<P>
   Global One's problems stem partly from uneasiness among
multinational customers as the long-troubled venture unravels.
</P>
<P>
   It's not yet clear which of Sprint's two European partners,
Deutsche Telekom and France Telecom, will end up buying the
venture. But Sprint will exit the alliance, perhaps by year's end.
It has agreed to move international traffic onto MCI WorldCom's
networks.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint also is investing heavily to revamp its fiberoptic
network as a more efficient carrier of Internet and corporate data
traffic, the growth of which is far outpacing voice traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The company aims to introduce a service by year's end that
bundles multiple phone lines, high-speed data connections and
unlimited long-distance calling. Costs associated with the ION
services dragged down earnings by 7 cents a share in the third
quarter, compared with 2 cents a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Despite big price cuts in the long-distance industry _ which
Sprint initiated with its Nickel Nights promotion _ third-quarter
long-distance revenue rose 8.4 percent to $2.71 billion from $2.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company says its promotions have attracted customers who
make 30 percent more calls than its average customer. The division
also benefited from increased long-distance use by Sprint PCS
wireless customers, increased long-distance sales to the company's
local customers, and a 45 percent increase in revenue from data
services.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, minutes of use on the company's network rose 23 percent
from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Financial Officer Arthur Krause said Wednesday that
long-distance revenue and operating income in the fourth quarter
would rise by ``upper single digits'' on a percentage basis. The
company expects some softness in the business market through early
next year.
</P>
<P>
   In the company's local phone operations, revenue rose 6 percent
to $1.42 billion from $1.34 billion. Sprint added 5 percent more
phone lines as it met demand for Internet access. It ended the
quarter with 7.9 million lines.
</P>
<P>
   The local division successfully promoted its Sprint Solutions
bundle during the quarter, which combines local and long-distance
service with several premium calling features. Revenue growth from
local phone operations is expected to remain in the mid-single
digits, Krause said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's biggest growth engine is its wireless unit, Sprint PCS,
which added a record 720,000 customers in the third quarter,
bringing its total subscriber base to 4.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS launched its wireless Web service in the third
quarter, which lets subscribers access e-mail, popular Web sites
and a variety of news services. As part of its merger agreement,
MCI WorldCom will also become a branded sales agent of the wireless
service.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint expects to add 1 million customers in the fourth quarter,
traditionally the strongest quarter for wireless phone sales,
because wireless phones are popular holiday gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Average monthly revenue per customer was unchanged at $54. Total
revenue at the wireless unit was $844 million. Net loss for the
quarter was $615 million, or $1.31 a share.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
