<HEADLINE>
BRADY BENEFITS FROM TALE OF TAPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When he feels like he's not throwing accurately,
or when he's just plain struggling, Marcus Brady pops in the
videotape of last year's game against Montana State. That's a
horror flick as far as he's concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Brady, Cal State Northridge's starting quarterback, threw for a
career-low 152 yards and threw three fourth-quarter interceptions
that helped the Bobcats rally for a 32-26 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it was my worst game _ ever,'' Brady said after
practice Wednesday. ``I put it behind me. I learned from it. It was
just not executing.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady said he uses the Montana State game tape to correct sloppy
footwork. He said that contributed to his poor game, which
culminated in an interception by the Bobcats' Shon Flores with 22
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Other than correcting his physical mistakes, Brady doesn't dwell
on bad memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think about it,'' he said. ``There was nothing that
boggles my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Except those interceptions maybe. Brady only had 11 last year.
</P>
<P>
   __ Old school: Brady and Drew Amerson will see a familiar face
in a Montana State uniform Saturday. Jay Hackett, a freshman
defensive back, was their teammate at San Diego's Morse High.
</P>
<P>
   Brady said he's known Hackett since Pop Warner football and
Amerson said he and Hackett played in the same defensive backfield
at Morse.
</P>
<P>
   __ Revived: Sherdrick Bonner, a former quarterback at CSUN and a
member of the school's athletic Hall of Fame, was signed by the
Arizona Cardinals on Tuesday. Bonner has been a standout for the
Arizona Rattlers in the Arena Football League.
</P>
<P>
   __ Family ties: Marc Lubick, a junior linebacker at Montana
State, is the son of Colorado State head coach Sonny Lubick and the
younger brother of Matt Lubick, a former CSUN assistant coach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
