<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For THURSDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, Oct. 21.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-REFUGEES (Cucuta, Colombia) _ As Colombia's
longstanding civil conflict intensifies, the fighting is inflicting
a major social crisis on a country that is already deeply
fractured. Hundreds of thousands of civilians are being forcibly
uprooted and turned into fearful, persecuted migrants. The vast
majority are peasants caught in the crossfire between Marxist
guerrillas and the right-wing paramilitary forces that seek to wipe
them out. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Refugee map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-WAHID (Jakarta) _ A man-in-the-news profile of
Indonesia's new president: Who is Abdurrahaman Wahid and what does
he stand for? The question seems to be asked most often by people
who know him best. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ELDERLY-GAYS (Fort Lauderdale, Fla.) _ As the first openly gay
generation grows grayer and contemplates retirement, developers are
planning retirement communities and assisted-care housing that
would allow aging gays to grow old surrounded by other gays. In
Fort Lauderdale, Boston, Los Angeles, San Francisco, Atlanta and
other cities, these developers are promising a haven for those who
will become old and infirm, many of them without the support of
children or other family members. ``When you're old, the last thing
that you want to do is to have to hide,'' a Fort Lauderdale
businessman said. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM-SUIT (New York) _ For weeks, in the wake of the
controversial ``Sensation'' exhibit, Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani has
been talking about seizing control of the Brooklyn Museum of Art by
ousting its Board of Trustees. But the city's legal strategy has
evolved and now embraces a much more drastic solution, which is to
evict the museum and its vast holdings of artwork. City officials
acknowledge that this strategy could result in Brooklyn losing
possession of the nation's second largest art collection _ 1.5
million paintings, sculptures and decorative objects that took a
century to assemble. By David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT29) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-ASSESS (Phoenix, Ariz.) _ How the Republican race may be
affected by Elizabeth Dole's withdrawal: Good news for McCain; bad
news for Bush. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-CLEMENCY _ The Justice Department took extraordinary
steps to enhance the chances of clemency for a group of imprisoned
Puerto Rican nationalists after receiving regular expressions of
interest from the White House, according to newly released
documents. In one instance, the department's top officials
repeatedly urged the prisoners' supporters in Congress to persuade
them to fashion a statement of repentance to help their chances of
release. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT18) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   HOLBROOKE-LOBBY _ Since his confirmation as chief delegate to
the United Nations, Richard Holbrooke has turned himself from
high-flying diplomat to part-time lobbyist. He was campaigning
again Wednesday, and by midafternoon, the tally was 6 formal
appointments, 14 chance encounters and more meetings to go, all in
the cause of rescuing the United States' standing at the United
Nations. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
