   FALUDI-MEN (Los Angeles) _ It was here in a neighborhood bar,
next to a restaurant called Bourgeois Pig that Susan Faludi, 40,
and Russ Rymer, her 47-year-old boyfriend, hashed out ideas on bar
napkins that would eventually become ``Stiffed: The Betrayal of the
American Man'' (William Morrow &AMP; Company),'' her 608-page listening
tour through the postwar American male psyche. In the book, a
sprawling probe of men in crisis, Ms. Faludi examines a complex web
of social expectations and shifting values _ millenial fault lines
_ that she feels have trapped men. By Patrcia Leigh Brown.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-CONSERVANCY (Newbury, N.H.) _ ``Colette wanted to be
buried in her garden with a sign that said something like, `Here I
am, surrounded by le debris des reves,''' Frank Cabot said, using
the French for ``ruin of dreams.'' The founder of the Garden
Conservancy, a national group devoted to preserving unique American
gardens, was musing about the near impossibility of its mission.
``It isn't easy, trying to sustain the creator's vision,'' Mr.
Cabot said. ``But usually these people are wonderful characters,
who have a coterie of friends.'' And if those friends can form an
ad hoc charitable company, and hire an inspired horticulturalist to
carry on, they have a chance of saving the garden. By Anne Raver.
</P>
