<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS SHOW SOME FORWARD MOMENTUM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A visit to the Los Angeles Clippers museum of
unnatural history tells us the franchise rarely operates from a
position of strength before roll is called at the NBA draft
lottery. But after only two weeks of camp and four exhibition
games, a position of strength is emerging:
</P>
<P>
   Forward.
</P>
<P>
   While it might be a stretch to say the Clips are loaded, it is
accurate to suggest they have upgraded from slingshots to guns at
forward.
</P>
<P>
   The primary weapon is third-year power forward Maurice Taylor,
who's hanging by that contract-extension cord. Taylor has been the
poster man-child for happy campers, refusing to shoot off his mouth
or even shoot his jumper more than necessary.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Taylor responded to the consistent double-teaming by
the Suns during Tuesday's 103-96 exhibition loss at Phoenix by
handing out 11 assists. He's more altruistic these days, but a slow
adjustment to the newly enforced hand-check rule and a false-alarm
knee twinge in Toronto have conspired to keep his scoring down.
</P>
<P>
   As for Taylor's monetary aspirations?
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no new developments,'' his agent, David Falk,
said of possible trades or Clippers/Taylor contract accords.
``That's a dead issue at this point. He (Taylor) is the most
valuable asset they have and they're going to lose him when his
contract expires.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Taylor, Lamar Odom, the 19-year-old, 6-foot-9
southpaw who starts at small forward, has been as good as
advertised _ despite squeezing off 61 shots in four games. He's
only made 25 of those field-goal attempts (39 percent) but has been
a better defender than expected and twice has snagged eight
rebounds in a game.
</P>
<P>
   The reserves are Brian Skinner and Tyrone Nesby.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been our best player in camp from day one,'' coach Chris
Ford said of the 6-9, 250-pound Skinner, the Clippers' choice with
the 21st pick in the 1998 draft. Nesby, last season's rookie
free-agent revelation, scored 18 off the bench in Phoenix and had
19 in the opener vs. Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   __ Fast breaks: For Wednesday evening's workout, the Clippers
divided their squad into two (alleged) equally matched teams and
held a public scrimmage at the Sports Arena. . . . The left ankle
of Eric Murdock has recovered enough for the veteran point guard to
make his exhibition debut Friday in Vancouver. . . . Off-guard
Derek Anderson has produced a combined 54 points in the last three
exhibition games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
