<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3591 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-TEX     10-21 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
50 WAYS TO MOVE THE FOOTBALL: GET A NEW PLAN, CHAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a longtime, part-time local rancher, Fox TV's Terry Bradshaw
mentioned his hesitancy to rip heavily into the Cowboys, the team
of choice in his adopted ``hometown.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of years ago, I was on 'em real hard until somebody
shot my prized horse,'' Bradshaw said. ``But now I've got a new
barn. I can hide the horses. So I'm gonna have some things to say
this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradshaw, of course, is an NFL Hall of Famer who can also be
Hall-of-Fame wacky with off-the-wall, off-the-cuff opinions on
America's favorite pregame Sunday morning football show.
</P>
<P>
   I just hope he was kidding about that horse being shot.
</P>
<P>
   Terry, however, did make himself perfectly clear in one other
area: Chan is not the man. Or better yet, Chan Gailey's offense is
not the offense for today's NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's boring, it's not going to work, it's not best suited for
Troy Aikman, and if the truth were known, Troy has to hate it,''
Bradshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   All this, by the way, was told in a very public format, or at
least public on West Coast radio. It came on Tuesday afternoon's
edition of ``The Terry Bradshaw Show'', from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   I had been asked to be a guest on the show, but I did more
listening than talking, which, yes, ranks as a first.
</P>
<P>
   Bradshaw, of course, didn't say anything that isn't also being
preached from every local soapbox this week. Terry just promised to
take it from LA radio and go national with it, come Sunday. There
is no known football hell that compares to the Cowboys going bad,
and going bad offensively they certainly are.
</P>
<P>
   When Green Bay scored 10 points last week and Brett Favre looked
awful against a shell of a Denver team, did the cheese turn green
anywhere except Wisconsin? Heck no. And how does anyone explain
2-and-4 in Minnesota? The Vikings were the preseason favorite to
win the Super Bowl. But does any human outside of a few snowplow
drivers really care about Minnesota?
</P>
<P>
   A sudden Cowboys slump, however, gets everyone stirred up, one
way or the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cowboys are always going to be overrated,'' Bradshaw said.
``That's why they are Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   When Gailey arrived here 18 months ago, he said he knew the
perils of head coaching in this town. Hopefully, he really did. If
not, he's now finding out the hard way. And Bradshaw has promised
to tell him again Sunday, right there in front of Mr. and Mrs.
America.
</P>
<P>
   Does Gailey have a ``boring offense?'' And wasn't he supposed to
be an ``offensive genius?'' Isn't that why Jerry Jones, who also
has his butt hung way out there on this one, hired Gailey in the
first place?
</P>
<P>
   First of all, Gailey is boring with his play calling, at least
if you think the running game is a bore.
</P>
<P>
   And if anyone, including Jones, ever called him a ``genius,'' I
never heard it. What Jones said from the start, and still says, is
he wanted a head man who was offensively inclined, could call his
own plays, and would not be predictable. As opposed to Ernie
Zampese, the Cowboys' last offensive coordinator, who was hounded
by the ``too predictable'' tag.
</P>
<P>
   Do not assume, however, Ernie is now up there in New England,
privately laughing. As Ernie always joked about his play calling,
``if it works, I made the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   In case no one was listening, Gailey said from day one he was a
run-first offensive coordinator. He's got bells, whistles,
five-receiver sets and all kinds of other gadget plays, but first
and foremost, he believes the only way to win consistently is by
running the football.
</P>
<P>
   Norv Turner, still an offensive-coordinating god around here,
comes to Texas Stadium on Sunday with the Redskins, bringing the
exact philosophy. It worked in Dallas, and it's now working in
Washington because Norv finally found a competent quarterback to
complement the running game.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Gailey stuck with the run too long in Philadelphia, and
definitely too long in the Meadowlands. And he repeatedly stayed
with the wide stuff Monday night with Emmitt, trying to beat the
Giants' run-blitz, eight-man fronts. In the end, he looked foolish
because of that.
</P>
<P>
   A Terry Bradshaw gripe is Gailey tends to ignore the deep ball,
giving in to the deep coverage of an opponent. It's true. Gailey is
very big on the ``taking what the defense gives us'' philosophy.
Except when it comes to the run, which he tried to force against
the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   The truth about the past two games is the offensive line, which
had nothing but regulars on the field Monday night, got its tail
whipped repeatedly. And that eventually led to offensive turmoil,
no matter what play was called.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Gailey is given the blame. Which is the way it
should be. Except when it's the Cowboys involved, that blame is
always bigger, louder, more intense and more national.
</P>
<P>
   How Gailey handles all this _ both personally and with needed
adjustments on offense _ will eventually determine if Chan is the
man. Or if a Terry Bradshaw, among many at the moment, is actually
right. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 0034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3592 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-ANDERSON-     10-21 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-ANDERSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
If there's one thing Shandon Anderson learned during his days in
Utah, it's patience.
<TEXT>
<P>
   First, Anderson had to overcome the stigma of being a
second-round pick (1996, out of Georgia) and work his way into a
Utah lineup that had several veterans ahead of him. But through
patience, Anderson eventually became a valuable reserve on a team
that went to the NBA Finals in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Then Anderson could easily have played it safe a couple of years
ago. He could have re-signed with the Jazz and spent the rest of
his career in relative security. Instead, he decided to be patient,
thinking that perhaps good things would happen when he became a
free agent at the end of last season.
</P>
<P>
   They did. And Anderson suddenly found himself the hottest
commodity on the free-agent market, being courted by just about
everyone, including the NBA champion San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson patiently weighed his options _ a little too patiently,
perhaps, for the Rockets, who waited to see where the 6-6 swingman
would land _ and decided his best opportunity was in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just goes to prove that when you get out there and play,
you can show everybody what you can do,'' Anderson said. ``I wasn't
out there trying to show everyone, `Oh, I should have been drafted
in the first round.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just thankful for the opportunity I had in Utah, and I
made the best of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think back to what (Utah coach) Jerry Sloan told me in my
last year _ `Shandon, you put yourself in a good position; you came
in and worked hard for it.' He meant that I put myself in a
position to where I could go out and be a free agent and pick the
team I wanted to, instead of the team picking me. That's what I
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Rockets, desperately in need of athleticism, wanted
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has some things that are constant and are going to fit into
any system, and that's his approach to the game, which is
full-tilt, no-nonsense and hustle,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich
said of Anderson. ``He's a combination of strength and quickness at
his position. You can always find ways to make that a positive for
your team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, with the whole team, we're looking at different things
to try and find little niches for each guy where we can go to their
strengths. It'll take time to really hit 100 percent efficiency,
but this is just the right (system) for him right here. We really
wanted to get him, and now that we've got him, I feel great.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's a Rocket, Anderson is applying the patience he
learned in Utah to his game. After four preseason games, Anderson
is averaging just nine points on 38-percent shooting, but he's not
worried.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is content to let his game mature as he learns along
with the rest of the new-look Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going well,'' Anderson said. ``I think it's just a matter
of getting a feel for everything now. We have a lot of the plays
down, so now it's up to us to execute everything. But we're trying
to get a feel on how to do things defensively, how to do things
offensively, and where shots are going to come from.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a chance to watch tapes of the games so I can get a
better feel for it than when I'm playing. (By watching tapes) I can
visualize things better. Sometimes when you're on the court, you
may think a lane is there when it's not. But I think it's coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's coming,'' Anderson continued. ``Right now, I'm
thinking first and then reacting instead of just flowing smoothly.
But it's just a matter of time. That's all it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson worked on that in Wednesday's intrasquad scrimmage,
scoring 15 points on 5-of-11 shooting and hauling in six rebounds
before about 5,000 fans at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson couldn't help but notice the five turnovers he had,
an indication of how things have gone for the Rockets in the
preseason.
</P>
<P>
   They are averaging 27.8 turnovers per game, one of the biggest
reasons the Rockets are 1-3 heading into tonight's game against the
Orlando Magic at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, the biggest thing so far has been the turnovers,''
Anderson said. ``We've had a lot of those in the preseason. I know
we have a lot of new guys, but 30 or 35 turnovers in a game? We
can't win like that. We're losing games by eight or 10 points, and
we're having 35 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet we're still scoring 90, 100 points. So you figure if we
cut down those turnovers, maybe cut them in half, then you're
looking at 110 or 120 points. When you have those kind of point
(totals), then everybody's scoring and everybody's happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``And with this kind of team, we can have a defense that can
keep opponents around 42- or 43-percent shooting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
