<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3593 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBO-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     10-21 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROBERTSON-COLUMN </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATLANTA _ The Braves, who live by their pitching, almost died by
their hitting. They return to the World Series for the fifth time
in the 1990s because of how, in the end, they swung their bats.
</P>
<P>
   And the Astros, you may have noticed, still haven't gone because
of how they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The message in all this seems clear. Pitching is the crucial
element in the long march that is the regular season and will
almost always decide who winds up in the playoffs. That's why both
the Astros and the Braves were able to survive a spring and summer
full of catastrophes.
</P>
<P>
   But come the second season, it's the offense that tilts the
playing field and determines who ultimately participates in the
Fall Classic, then wins it. Everybody enters October armed and
dangerous. The hottest bats become the crucial variable, separating
the men from the boys. Score runs or become also-rans; it really is
that simple.
</P>
<P>
   Game 6 of the National League Championship Series, won 10-9 by
Atlanta in 11 tense innings, was the first in which either the
Braves or the Mets produced as many as five runs, assuming you
swallow the baseball logic of awarding Robin Ventura only a ``grand
single'' at the end of Game 5. The Braves' pitching, the sport's
reference standard over the decade and up to Tuesday almost perfect
against New York, failed horribly as a seemingly lopsided series
began to look like the worst disaster to befall this peachy
community since Gen. Sherman marched through with a box of matches.
</P>
<P>
   But having blown five- and four-run leads, the latter as late as
the seventh inning, the Braves finally sucked up at the plate,
something they had failed to do in the previous two starts in the
process of squandering a three-games-to-zip advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta hit so poorly, period, in the fourth game that it left
no men on base and so poorly in crucial situations in the marathon
fifth that it stranded 19, both LCS records.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the five-run outburst at the outset of the sixth
game was mostly a byproduct of Al Leiter's inability to do anything
right as he attempted to work on three days' rest for only the
second time in his career. The Braves did all their damage without
an extra-base hit, aided and abetted by two hit batsmen, a walk and
a throwing error.
</P>
<P>
   Then Atlanta's offense closed up shop for the next four innings
_ not an unfamiliar sight _ as New York chopped away at the lead,
first chasing Kevin Millwood with three runs in the sixth, then
routing a comically inept John Smoltz with a four-run flurry in the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   There was no small measure of arrogance in Bobby Cox's decision
to insert Smoltz there. But clearly a great starter does not a
great reliever make, something Cox figures to be acutely cognizant
of in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the Braves got to Armando Benitez that you began
to think they might survive. They had been 0-for-26 this season
against Benitez until Eddie Perez _ who else but? _ finally
finagled a single off him earlier in the series, and they would end
Benitez's scoreless string in the 10th with a leadoff single by
Andruw Jones and Ozzie Guillen's RBI single after Ryan Klesko had
walked.
</P>
<P>
   That was Benitez's second inning, and thus Bobby Valentine had
no choice except to turn to one of his starters, Kenny Rogers, in
the 11th. Rogers, of course, would walk in the winning run, his
downfall having begun with Gerald Williams' leadoff double.
</P>
<P>
   It's such a different game in the playoffs, when every pitch is
thrown with utter concentration and full intensity. If pitchers
wore the same game faces during the regular season, most of them
would be on the DL by September.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be risking life and limb,'' said Smoltz, who can speak
from experience on same after accepting Cox's invitation to work
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Fat offensive stats mean nothing when the slate's wiped clean as
the leaves begin to turn. The cheap at-bats are few and far
between, as everyone from Jeff Bagwell to Chipper Jones to Mike
Piazza learns. One of the reasons a lesser light such as Perez can
shine so brightly is because maybe pitchers ease off just a hair
against guys of his ilk after battling for all they're worth
against the heart of the order.
</P>
<P>
   Which, therefore, struggles accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, while you like the Braves' chances against the Yankees
because of their starting rotation _ super stoppers John Rocker and
Mariano Rivera are pretty much a wash _ the final World Series of
the '90s will be decided at the plate, not on the pitcher's mound,
with the contestants' respective fielding serving as a possible
tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had statistically the best gloves in history this
season, committing only slightly more than one error every two
games. Yet they made eight against Atlanta, virtually every one of
them costly.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting and defense _ that's the ticket to a happy ending in the
postseason.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
