<SLUG> BC-NEWHALL-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG EARNINGS REPORT EXPECTED FROM NEWHALL LAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON TAKENOUCHI 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Residential land sales are expected to fuel
another strong earnings report Thursday by The Newhall Land and
Farming Company, the largest developer in the Santa Clarita Valley,
a suburban community north of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Sutro &AMP; Co. estimates the developer will post earnings of 43
cents per partnership unit on revenues of $65.6million. Partnership
units are traded like stock but do not carry voting rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Clarita-based limited partnership posted per-unit
earnings of 48 cents in the third quarter last year, but quarterly
results in development often fluctuate greatly, based on the timing
of property sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the company's going in an excellent direction,'' said
analyst Craig Silvers at Sutro, the only firm that actively tracks
Newhall Land partnership units. ``It's in an enviable position,
having a considerable amount of residential land available in the
tight Southern California market.''
</P>
<P>
   Land sales will likely be a major contributor to the company's
quarterly results, including ongoing sales of lots in the
Bridgeport housing development.
</P>
<P>
   Silvers said the other major contributor will be
income-producing properties, including shopping centers and
apartment complexes.
</P>
<P>
   Newhall Land officials have pledged to sell many of the
income-producing properties to finance an aggressive effort to
repurchase about 6.3million partnership units, or 20 percent of
those outstanding units. Company officials announced last month
that they will repurchase 5.5million units in addition to about
800,000 already bought back.
</P>
<P>
   But the repurchase efforts have done little to revive prices for
Newhall Land's partnership units, which closed at $25 Wednesday,
far below the 1998 high of $34.75. The company's own conservative
estimate of net appraised value per unit is $29.72, and that
estimate was made before the approval of the company's 21,615-home
Newhall Ranch project.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the vast housing project, however, have languished in
court, and Attorney General Bill Lockyer recently weighed in on the
side of Newhall Ranch opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Silvers said uncertainty over the Newhall Ranch project would
have little immediate effect on the partnership unit price that he
said is already below its true value.
</P>
<P>
   And the company's main strengths _ including large residential
land holdings and a strong economy _ will likely keep Newhall Land
humming, Silvers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the long-term prospects are excellent,'' he said.
``The company is in an enviable position.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
