<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HARPER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' HARPER STILL MAD AT REDSKINS COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Alvin Harper couldn't have personally picked a
better time to begin his second tour of duty with the Cowboys than
this week against the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say that the 32-year-old wide receiver, who will be
activated for Sunday's game at Texas Stadium, will not be shaking
Redskins coach Norv Turner's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Turner ran him off without giving him a fair chance in 1997,
Harper said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what would be his dream scenario after what has
happened to him in failed free-agent bids with Tampa Bay and
Washington, Harper replied, ``It's not a dream. Norv knew he didn't
do me right. He didn't even give me a chance. They lied to me. They
were liars.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper said as much on Nov. 30, 1997, one day before he was
released: ``It's ridiculous the way I've been used. There's been
nothing but a whole bunch of lies. They expect me to come in for
one out of every 15 plays.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Harper was called into Turner's office and handed
his release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess (Turner) didn't appreciate me calling him a liar,''
Harper said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Turner called the decision to release the high-priced free agent
merely one ``based on production.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers would bear him out. Harper, who suited up for 11 of
12 games before his release, ended up catching two passes for 65
yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I said what I said in the newspaper: `Release me.
You're not going to play me.' I can go be a statue somewhere
else.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he and Turner ever tried to resolve their
differences before it came to that, Harper replied, ``The only time
we talked about it was when he brought me in to release me. That's
the only time we talked ... and I really didn't have any words for
him anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner, Harper said, told both fellow receiver Leslie Shepherd
and him at the start of the '97 training camp that they would be
vying for playing time, saying, ``No one is the starter right now.
Both of you guys will get equal play, and we'll just evaluate it
from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Harper now recalls, ``I never got `equal' anything.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked Wednesday if he had anything to say about Harper's
latest remarks, Turner replied, ``Nothing ... nothing. Sometimes it
works out. Sometimes it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper left the Cowboys after the 1994 season to become somebody
else's go-to guy after four seasons of playing in Michael Irvin's
shadow and signed as an unrestricted free agent with Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Harper has no animosity toward the Bucs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did what they had to do; I didn't do what I was supposed
to do. I don't fault them,'' Harper said.
</P>
<P>
   Harper twice was injured during practice Wednesday, first
dislocating the ring finger on his left hand, then pulling a muscle
in his right hamstring. Both times, he received treatment and
returned to team drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not in great shape yet,'' Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said
after practice. ``We'd like to have another week or two before we
had to throw him in there, but he will help.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice Wednesday, Harper went deep against cornerback Charlie
Williams and caught long passes from Troy Aikman. Even though the
offense has changed in Dallas, Harper is confident that he can
still make big plays if he is allowed to run some of his old
favorite routes: Deep post, stutter-and-comeback, stutter-and-go,
the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Harper, who hasn't played since November 1997, was sitting
around his living room in Fort Washington, Va., when he decided
that he was still better than some of the NFL receivers he was
watching on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I came to that decision (to play again) and made
the phone call (to the Cowboys),'' Harper said. ``There is some
ungodly material out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper called Cowboys vice president Stephen Jones to see what
was going on and ask for a tryout. This was 10 days before Irvin
suffered a spinal contusion in an awkward tumble after a tackle at
Philadelphia on Oct. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a ``courtesy tryout'' has developed into a
minimum-wage signing (Harper gets the $400,000 minimum for a
veteran) and has turned possibly into some playing time now that
rookie Wane McGarity (dislocated shoulder) is expected to be out
two to three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could be playing at New Orleans, but I didn't want to go
down there. Actually, I didn't want to play anymore (after being
released by Washington),'' Harper said. ``I began thinking that I
had had enough ... that I would just play me some golf every day
for the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Harper is thinking about reuniting with Aikman on Sunday
afternoons. This week, it will be against his old team _ and
especially his old coach _ that chased him off and, he believes,
nearly out of the league for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very exciting to make a big play, perhaps even
score a touchdown Sunday,'' Harper said, ``then I could go dunk the
goal post again.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be in lieu of a handshake for Turner.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
