<HEADLINE>
PAULIE AYALA'S FOE PACKING CONFIDENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE SANCHEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ As he waited for his interpreter to take him
to his first genuine Texas dinner, an expressionless Saohin Srithai
Condo rested in the lobby of the Ramada Inn.
</P>
<P>
   Hungry and anxious, he sat quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Just like he did in December, when Johnny Tapia bypassed Condo
to challenge then-champion Nana Konadu for the World Boxing
Association bantamweight (118-pound) title.
</P>
<P>
   And just like he did when Tapia dodged him to fight Fort Worth's
Paulie Ayala in June.
</P>
<P>
   In his first trip to the United States, patience has already
become one of the defining characteristics of the Thai challenger.
Patience combined with a right hand that has collected 19 knockouts
in 34 bouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to be a hero,'' said Condo, his words translated
by interpreter Anant Jethanamest. ``I want to be a hero to Thailand
and the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Condo (27-6, 19 knockouts) will finally get his chance at a
title Saturday night, when he challenges Ayala for his WBA
bantamweight belt at Will Rogers Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were ready to fight Konadu, Tapia, then, all of a sudden,
we don't,'' said Pai Rat, Condo's trainer. ``We were very
disappointed, but now we are happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fight between Ayala and Tapia (in Las Vegas) was close. It
was hard to see a winner. We could have beat Tapia, also.''
</P>
<P>
   Condo has brought only the necessities from Thailand. He arrived
in Texas with an entourage that consisted of his manager, an
interpreter, his trainer, and a sparring partner.
</P>
<P>
   He also brought plenty of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident, and I'm ready for Saturday's fight,'' said
Condo, a former kick-boxer. ``I am ready for a knockout at any
time, but I cannot predict which round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a champion. Whenever the chance comes, I will do
it. I am anxious to knock him out.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Condo won his past 10 bouts by knockout and has
not lost since 1995. He has been the WBA's No. 1-ranked
bantamweight for almost a year, though he has never fought or even
visited the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He has trained for the past 21/2 months and has endured more
than 120 rounds in preparation for Ayala.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paulie is good, but he can be beaten,'' said Niwat
Laosuwanwat, Condo's manager. Condo ``is very excited, and he is
anxious to get into it with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Condo's camp does not expect to be bothered by the hometown
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have 5,000 Thai people there, '' Jethanamest said.
``We will have support for our fighter. It will be a good fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Team Ayala, meanwhile, was impressed with the top contender's
silent confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is obviously ready, and prepared,'' said Rick Yuill,
Ayala's co-manager at Boxing Management, Inc. ``He seems very
confident and I am sure he will be going for a knockout.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
