<HEADER>
A3609 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-PUBERTY-MYSTERY-KAN &LR;      10-21 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBERTY-MYSTERY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MU RESEARCHERS HELP LEND CLUES TO FEMALE PUBERTY STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) A team of researchers, including two University of
Missouri-Columbia scientists, say they may have found some clues to
why young girls today reach puberty at younger ages.
</P>
<P>
   And the clues may point to a chemical that's commonly found in
plastic products.
</P>
<P>
   Kembra Howdeshell, an MU doctoral candidate, and Frederick vom
Saal, a biology professor, teamed with North Carolina State
researchers on a new study that appears Thursday in the scientific
journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   They exposed mice still in the womb to the chemical bisphenol A,
at a level similar to what humans are exposed to routinely.
Bisphenol A is a ``building block'' for polycarbonate plastic
products such as baby bottles, food can linings and food storage
containers.
</P>
<P>
   The exposed mice developed puberty earlier than normal, and they
also found that the mice exposed in the womb to the chemical
weighed 20 percent more than normal at puberty.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, an exposure in the womb could have effects after
birth, the study concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that the largest effects happened to the babies of
the pregnant mother,'' Howdeshell said. ``The chemical did not
affect the mother, but instead it altered the babies' growth
patterns and accelerated timing of sexual maturity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our study shows that this chemical may be a factor for
contributing to trends seen in human populations over the past
several decades.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chemical Manufacturers Association could not comment on the
new study. The group has yet to review it, said Frank Rathbun, a
spokesman for the industry group.
</P>
<P>
   But the manufacturers association has cautioned against jumping
to conclusions about studies of animals and the effects of
chemicals like bisphenol A, which can act in an animal's body like
a hormone. Any adverse effect in humans is far from proven, the
association has maintained.
</P>
<P>
   These chemicals, known as hormonally active agents, can mimic
the actions of sex hormones and have been associated with adverse
reproductive and developmental effects in wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   The Chemical Manufacturers Association points to the work of
Elizabeth Whelan, who directs the American Council on Science and
Health. Whelan has said the human body has demonstrated that it can
deal with these chemicals, in normal amounts.
</P>
<P>
   MU researcher vom Saal, one of the study's co-authors, agreed
that more study is required before scientists can say with more
certainty the threats posed to humans exposed to these chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not offering an answer concerning effects in humans with
these findings,'' vom Saal said. ``Instead the findings pose a
question regarding human health....We believe the medical community
should take a long look at this study and consider looking at
(bisphenol A) as a possible cause for the changes in growth, sexual
maturation and reproductive abnormalities that have been reported
in humans in the past decade.''
</P>
<P>
   In August, a National Research Council Committee concluded that
there is evidence of harmful health and ecological effects
associated with exposure to hormonally active chemicals. But it
added little is understood about the exposure to these substances
at low concentrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Determining the risk to humans from contact with these
chemicals in the environment is difficult because ordinary exposure
to these agents has not been routinely monitored,'' Ernst Knobil, a
professor at University of Texas Medical School in Houston, said in
August. ``Determining what these exposures actually are is
therefore of primary importance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
