<HEADLINE>
JONES' FAITH IN GAILEY STEADFAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Roughly 20 months and 22 games have passed since
Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones introduced an unknown assistant
coach from Pittsburgh as the fourth coach in Cowboys history.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the Cowboys (3-2) riding a two-game losing streak
heading into Sunday's rematch with the high-flying Washington
Redskins (4-1), Gailey is getting roundly criticized for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   His offense is bearing the brunt of the blame after scoring just
20 points in the past two weeks, and critics are starting to
question his tag as an offensive guru.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was less talkative than normal in Wednesday's media
briefing _ perhaps choosing to retreat quickly to his office to
work on correcting his team's problems _ Gailey seems to be holding
up well under the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   He did acknowledge, however, that there's a sense of urgency for
a turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``There better be,'' Gailey said. ``Something is wrong with us
if it isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who has received his share of criticism through the
years, remains unfazed. All the fuss means to him is that Gailey
has finally arrived as the Cowboys' coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in any way having any type of emotion or sensitivity
about Chan being criticized,'' Jones said. ``That's life. Where I'm
coming from with Chan having criticism doesn't surprise me. I've
said to Chan several times that over the course of time, they are
going to be on you and they are going to be on me. A lot of times,
it's because it's not working right. We've just got to stick to the
things we believe in _ your philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones readily admits that Sunday's game against the
division-leading Redskins is crucial to the Cowboys' season _
because it will allow the Cowboys to keep pace in the NFC East race
and boost their confidence heading into a stretch of the schedule
that includes Indianapolis, Minnesota and Green Bay. But Jones
remains firm in his support of Gailey and believes things will
improve.
</P>
<P>
   The primary source of Jones' optimism is Gailey, whom he calls
one of the hardest working and most creative coaches in the NFL.
Jones said he backs Gailey's decision to simplify things in his
offense and holds Gailey's willingness to adjust as an example of
why he thought he would make such a good head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's one of Chan's best qualities,'' Jones said. ``I
sit in there and look at film with him. And he says, `If I had that
to do over again, I wouldn't call that.' He will quickly
acknowledge mistakes and say we won't do that again, which I think
is very healthy for the team's future and franchise. I know he'll
figure out a way to move the football and score touchdowns.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the uproar over the Cowboys' two-game losing streak
is understandable and predictable. He said he's not worried because
of past experience. The Cowboys have suffered back-to-back losses
in a season and reached the playoffs five times since 1991,
including Super Bowl title seasons of 1993 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we should do is reflect back on our experience and look
back at when this has happened to us,'' Jones said. ``Everybody was
preaching doomsday then.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Starting safety George Teague (strained neck) didn't practice
Wednesday and is doubtful for the Redskins game. Teague said the
doctors don't think he would finish the game without re-injury and
that he won't play unless he shows progress over the next few days.
Izell Reese would likely start in his place.
</P>
<P>
   _ Defensive tackle Chad Hennings (strained neck) did not
practice Wednesday. He should get back on the field later in the
week and is questionable for Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cornerback Deion Sanders (sprained right ankle) did not
practice Wednesday. He's listed as probable for Sunday's game and
is likely to return to the practice field Thursday.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
