<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
Sore foot sidelines Finley 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
DALLAS _ Moments after he was examined by Dr. Jim Brodsky
yesterday, Mavericks guard Michael Finley wore a look of doom and
gloom.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finley had been told he will miss the Mavericks' remaining four
preseason games because of plantar fasciatis in his right heel. He
is scheduled to undergo a bone scan today, which will determine if
he has a stress fracture.
</P>
<P>
   Finley has played in 297 consecutive regular-season games, the
fourth-longest streak among active players. He concedes that the
streak might be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to go out there and play and not be able to help
the team, and be more of a burden to the team,'' Finley said.
``That's not going to help me.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I'll take the time off for some rest and relaxation.''
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Steve Nash also will be sidelined for the remainder
of the preseason. Nash was examined yesterday, and started rehab
after it was discovered he has a strained tendon in his right
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks trainer Roger Hinds said Finley and Nash should be
ready for the Nov. 2 regular-season opener against the Golden State
Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, center Shawn Bradley skipped yesterday's practice and
is listed as day-to-day with a strained lower back.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Hubert Davis practiced yesterday for the first time since
suffering the flu before Saturday's preseason game against
Charlotte. Davis said he is physically fit and will play tonight
against the Toronto Raptors at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Finley's heel had been so sore that he missed Sunday's preseason
game against Detroit. But he might have aggravated it when he
played in Tuesday's game against the Milwaukee Bucks in Madison,
Wis. Finley played at the University of Wisconsin, which retired
Finley's jersey before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before \RTuesday\S night the heel was fine,'' Finley said.
``Maybe I rushed back a little bit too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the pain is hard to explain. It's like getting kneed in
the thigh, but it's in your heel. The pain is there in the morning
and in the evening.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley, one of the Mavericks' co-captains, has led the team in
scoring the past two seasons with averages of 21.5 and 20.2 points
per game, respectively. With Finley, Nash and Bradley missing
yesterday's practices, embattled Mavericks coach/general manager
Don Nelson is unsure when to expect them back.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're out for a period of time,'' Nelson said. ``I don't
really know. I'm not really good at guessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but it's clear the injuries have muddled Nelson's
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cuts it down,'' he said. ``But it gives me a chance to play
some of these younger guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RPoint guard\S Kevin Ollie got a nice opportunity and I
thought played very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Guard Erick Strickland, who scored a game-high 26 points on
10-of-13 shooting in Tuesday's 107-96 loss to the Bucks, also has
an opportunity to continue playing. Both Ollie and Strickland are
expected to receive their share of playing time when the Mavericks
play host to Toronto at 7:30 tonight.  &QL; 
Master P arrives Robyn Hunter, advertising and promotions
coordinator for the Mavericks, said she gave away more than 200
tickets to various radio station listeners this week for tonight's
game. Hunter said most of the listeners were eager to see Raptors
guard Percy Miller, the rap artist known as Master P.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who used to play AAU basketball in New Orleans with
Mavericks guard Robert Pack, is trying to revive his basketball
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I get in the game, I do the best that I can do,''
Miller said yesterday afternoon from his hotel room in Denver,
where the Raptors were preparing to play the Nuggets. ``Hopefully,
if this thing works out, I'll be signing a contract next week.''
</P>
<P>
   This also will be Vince Carter's first trip to Reunion Arena.
Carter was the NBA rookie of the year last season.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
