<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3613 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-PUBLIC-MEMORIALS-KAN &LR;      10-21 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-MEMORIALS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC MEMORIALS ENABLE MOURNERS TO CONNECT WITH GRIEVING
FAMILIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY and JOHN MARTELLARO  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ Strangers cried for Pamela Butler.
</P>
<P>
   Mourners, many of whom had never heard Pamela's name until she
was snatched last week while skating in front of her home,
overflowed Wednesday's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   They cried for a 10-year-old girl they'd never met. They cried
for her family.
</P>
<P>
   And they cried for themselves. Pamela's face became their
child's face.
</P>
<P>
   Her kidnapper ``could have driven down my street,'' Ravon
Andrade, a mother who lives in Overland Park, said outside
CrossRoads Church after the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Across the metropolitan area, thousands of people who never knew
Pamela are mourning her loss, in much the same manner _ if not to
the same degree _ as the family and friends who loved her.
</P>
<P>
   People have always grieved over the loss of well-known
strangers, from tribal chieftains and Roman emperors to Princess
Diana and John F. Kennedy Jr.
</P>
<P>
   But grief experts say a death such as Pamela's touches a deeper
chord, because of the frightening way in which the Kansas City,
Kan., child was stolen from what should have been a safe place.
</P>
<P>
   Intense media coverage amplifies those emotions _ emotions that
people today feel more comfortable expressing.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, scenes of violent or tragic death are turned into
makeshift memorials where loved ones _ and often, strangers, too _
leave flowers, letters and other tributes or remembrances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are ceremonies. They are like memorials; they are the
ways that people heal themselves from the loss. It's one of the
most positive things people can do,'' said Kathy Smith, executive
director of the Grief Support Network, a coalition of local support
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like a phenomenon because that form of ritual was
lost from our society. People used to do things like that all the
time. That's something that needs to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who have already experienced a loss _ particularly the
loss of a child _ a case such as Pamela's can stir long-suppressed
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're still working on your own personal grief and any
subsequent loss simply triggers the unresolved grief,'' said
therapist Delpha Camp of Eugene, Ore., who is the national
president of the Association For Death Education and Counseling.
</P>
<P>
   At her funeral, Pamela was described as ``shy, but with lots of
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   She had no idea how many.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley Millican, 9, skipped school to be there _ with her
mother's permission. She wore her best dress and a purple ribbon
because she knew purple was Pamela's favorite color.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't think it odd that she wanted to attend. To hear her
explain it, there are no strangers among little girls that age.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was probably about like me,'' Ashley said. ``And I think
it's so sad that everything she did this year was her last
time...last Christmas, last birthday, last Easter...and she never
even knew it.''
</P>
<P>
   The public reaction to Pamela's tragedy has been enormous,
perhaps unprecedented: nightly vigils at her home, memorial
services at her school and at the Grain Valley, Mo., church near
where her body was found, live television coverage of her funeral
service Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A violent, unexpected death _ especially that of a child _
usually draws a community response beyond the immediate circle of
friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   But Nancy Crump, a bereavement counselor for D.W. Newcomer's
Sons funeral homes, said the intensity of the media coverage of
Pamela's case has helped to generate a higher level of response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we turn on the TV, there's an update on the search
or on the tragedy, so we get involved in it,'' Crump said.
</P>
<P>
   Renee Thomas, a Belton, Mo., mother of six, attended Wednesday's
funeral. Like most, she watched last week as the tragedy unfolded
in news reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hurting so much inside, I had to come today,'' Thomas
said.
</P>
<P>
   Her son, David Ramos, 21, was there from California.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my life, I have protected my little sisters,'' he said.
``Something like this scares me.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as the news media respect the boundaries set by the
family, Crump and others said, the attention can be a positive
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you love someone and that person dies, you want the world
to know this person existed and they meant something to someone,''
Crump said. ``All of this outpouring...confirms the loss and
confirms the value the person had for their family and friends and
schoolmates.''
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Davis, a community education specialist with Kansas City
Hospice, said public support can be very valuable for a family,
even though it can also be viewed on another level as an intrusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the community shows up and gives support is an
important statement to the family,'' Davis said. ``Down the road,
there may be a downside: `The whole world knows what happened to me
and my family' _ it's not a private matter, it's public.''
</P>
<P>
   Providing that kind of support was what drew Stacie Schemmel to
attend Pamela's funeral, along with her daughters Samantha, 5, and
Breana, 1. Schemmel said she was there for Cherri West, Pamela's
mother, whose face last week became a symbol of parental grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``She shared it with all of us,'' Schemmel said. ``I think she's
glad we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said the media have made grief more public than before,
which he believes is a good thing. American culture has tended to
encourage people to stifle or deny their grief, he said, but
depicting expressions of grief as normal and natural helps make it
more acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we see it, we see the tears and hugs,'' Davis said. ``It's
very healthy, but our society has always taught the opposite of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the CrossRoads Church Wednesday, there was talk of anger and
revenge, as well as sorrow. One man, a father, started to say what
he would do with Pamela's abductor. Then he caught himself. Church
music played.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a story for another day,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 0115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
