r a BC-EVICT-HELP-KAN &LR;      10-21 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVICT-HELP-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Victim of home-improvement debacle receives help from unlikely
source  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH E. IGOE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ About two weeks ago David Hyatt dropped by
the house on the hill.
</P>
<P>
   It was a common stop for Hyatt, who works for mortgage
companies, foreclosing on properties and clearing out residents.
Hyatt knew the drill: Drop in and forewarn residents about their
scheduled eviction day.
</P>
<P>
   But stepping inside that Kansas City home at 5117 Woodland Ave.,
something changed for Hyatt. He didn't like what he saw. Not one
bit.
</P>
<P>
   At the door was Martha Williams, 76 years old and barely
clearing four feet.
</P>
<P>
   Inside a house Hyatt guessed was hardly worth $10,000, Williams
had made a sparse but cozy home for her disabled adult son, Dusty,
and their shepherd mix, Bear.
</P>
<P>
   For Hyatt it meant a change of plans. He found himself getting
involved on her behalf, and he was not alone: In the last two
weeks, several different groups _ from the Kansas City mayor's
office to the local legal community _ have raced to aid Martha
Williams. Many were afraid that Williams was enticed into a
home-improvement arrangement that, while perfectly legal, is often
specifically directed toward low-income older adults.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had lived in the home 30 years, she told Hyatt, raised
all her children there and cared for her husband until he passed
away. She remains a companion for her son, who has cerebral palsy,
uses a wheelchair and spends his days tending to his baseball card
collection, watching out the porch window and greeting neighborhood
visitors with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day Williams told Hyatt, a remodeling company came
calling. Now, because she unwittingly took out a high-interest,
$15,000 home improvement loan _ and could not pay it off _ she was
losing her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think she knew what she was doing,'' Hyatt said. ``I
don't want to put out this little old lady.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday _ a day before her scheduled eviction _ those
parties convinced a judge to postpone it. Instead, there will be
another hearing on her case in two weeks in Jackson County Circuit
Court.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for ContiMortgage, the Hatboro, Pa.-based company that
holds the note for loan against the home, said he could not comment
on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, family members who have been taking time off from
work, calling agencies to find solutions, are relieved that they
have more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a blessing,'' said Williams' daughter, Maxine Williams.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing about Martha Williams' situation, several people
in the newly created Mayor's Neighborhood Advocate Office went to
work calling agencies for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all kind of went to work on it,'' said office member Regina
Chandler. ``She was attempting to pay (the loan) but couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The unfortunate part of Williams' situation, Chandler said, is
that she could have applied for a low-interest loan from a local
community development corporation had she known whom to contact.
The city can also help homeowners make wheelchair-accessible
improvements for free, Chandler said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said she never went looking for a loan, it came to her.
About two years ago, she said, several construction company
solicitors inquired whether she wanted home improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, she did. But she was retired, she recalls having told
them, and a widow caring for her disabled son. Her house was paid
off, but she didn't have much money to spend. They promised to be
reasonable, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talked so nice,'' she said. ``So I said: `Yeah.'''
</P>
<P>
   She didn't tell her children, she said. She wanted to surprise
them.
</P>
<P>
   Some improvements were made, Williams said, but she wasn't happy
with the work.
</P>
<P>
   Before she knew it, the payments got ahead of her. Now she feels
she was fooled by the solicitors who steered her to the
high-interest loan.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't believe how people can do you,'' she said Tuesday
in her home, her eyes tearing up. ``They talk to you so nice. Then
they turn around and throw you out.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, lending agencies that focus on the elderly have been
a concern, said Anne Deaton, a deputy director with the Missouri
Division of Aging. Complaints about such cases are rare in Kansas
City, she said.
</P>
<P>
   With senior citizens, Deaton said, the rule of ``buyer beware''
becomes more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really goes for seniors, because it may have been some
time since they've had some work done,'' she said, and their guard
is down.
</P>
<P>
   People working with Williams said they hope to arrange another
loan before the next hearing or work toward getting Williams and
her son new living arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Her would-be evictor, for one, is anxious to see that happen.
Hyatt is not sure he could bring himself to kicking Martha
Williams, her sweet-eyed son and tail-wagging dog out of their
little home on the hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are people,'' he said. ``She doesn't have anywhere to
go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
