<SLUG> BC-CHRETIEN-WTO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WTO PROTEST MISSES THE MASSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, B.C. _ Canada's Prime Minister Jean Chretien
Wednesday night extolled benefits of ``the new global economy,''
while outside the hotel where he was speaking a crowd of
anti-globalization protestors proclaimed the street ``a WTO-free
zone.''
</P>
<P>
   In a warmup for when the World Trade Organization convenes in
Seattle next month, a coalition of labor, environmental and civil
liberties groups sought to upstage the prime minister and gain
recruits for demonstrations planned in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   A music group called the Flying Folk Army performed. A group of
University of British Columbia students vowed to go on a seven day
anti-WTO hunger strike beginning on America's Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   But this anti-WTO mass protest lacked one essential ingredient _
the masses. It was all bullhorn and few cattle. Only about 300
people, less than one-third the crowd predicted by Vancouver
Police, showed up in the streets. They were easily contained by a
squad of police on bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Hyatt Regency Hotel, Chretien preached globalism to a
crowd of more than 1,300 supporters and raised $400,000 (Canadian)
for Canada's ruling Liberal Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``No longer will British Columbia or Canada be the best kept
secret in the global economy,'' declared Chretien. In what he
called the upcoming ``Century of the Pacific,'' the prime minister
vowed to intensify promotion of foreign investment in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   But the new global economy was seen as a Halloween-like house of
horrors to activists who used chalk to write out such slogans as
Wicked Tyrants Oppression on the pavement of Burrard Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WTO is a handy super-national forum for corporations to
downsize the importance of government and sell out our national
sovereignty,'' said Barbara Waldern, who is organizing
Vancouver-area volunteers to join in the upcoming Seattle protests.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ogilvie, active with the Public Service Alliance of
Canada, added: ``It is dangerous when the powers of democratic
governments are frozen or circumvented by actions of non-democratic
international trade organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   Until about 15 years ago, Canada was a very nationalist,
somewhat protectionist place.
</P>
<P>
   A Foreign Investment Review Agency had the task of keeping
American capital from expanding its hold on various sectors of
Canada's economy. A government-owned oil company, Petro-Canada, was
formed in part to break the hold of U.S. oil companies on Canada's
energy economy.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1984, newly elected Prime Minister Brian Mulroney
proclaimed Canada ``open for business.'' It has been ever since.
Chretien's Liberal Party was bitterly opposed when Canada signed up
with the United States and Mexico in the North American Free Trade
Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Once back in power, however, the Liberals have become
enthusiastic supporters of NAFTA, and Chretien played host to the
1997 Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation summit in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   The APEC conference did see big protests. At one point, Royal
Canadian Mounted Police officers ordered demonstrators to disperse,
and moved in nine seconds later with pepper spray. Chretien was
widely criticized for joking that he preferred pepper on his plate
at dinner.
</P>
<P>
   But the prime minister has had the last laugh. The latest
opinion poll in British Columbia shows Chretien's Liberals with 53
percent support compared to only 23 percent for the opposition
Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   An official inquirey is still looking into police conduct at the
anti-APEC protests, but Chretien was cracking jokes Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you so much I decided to have the APEC meeting here,''
he said. ``I do not know what I will do to keep you on the map, but
I will find something.''
</P>
<P>
   An anti-Chretien demonstration last November erupted into a
brawl when a few of the protestors tried to break through police
lines. Wednesday night, however, all was peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   Penned in by watchful police on motorcycles and bicycles, a
remnant of 75 to 100 demonstrators marched down Robson Street, site
of Vancouver's ritziest import shops. They banged drums and blew
whistles, which drew only momentary stares from restaurant diners.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is likely to see more seasoned activists when the
Emerald City plays host to a big anti-WTO protest on Nov. 30.
Colleen McRory, leader of the Valhalla Society _ one of British
Columbia's most resourceful environmental groups _ ignored
Chretien's speech but said Wednesday she will bring several vans
full of demonstrators to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WTO stands for a corporate takeover of all our
resources,'' said McRory, citing Weyerhaeuser's recent acquisition
of MacMillan-Bloedel, British Columbia's largest forest products
firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are legitimate issues out there for which we must get
attention,'' McRory added. ``We face a future of minimal
environmental controls for ancient forests already under stress.
Global agreements push management of land and forests and resources
away from local communities, and even countries.''
</P>
<P>
   The anti-WTO protest will bring ``unprecedented networking of
different movements in North America and all over the world,'' said
Bryce Scott, organizer for a group called Peoples Action for
Threatened Habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, however, the main networking was done by
Vancouver business leaders and Asian guests gathered for the
British Columbia Prime Minister's Dinner. The Hyatt Regency
ballroom was definitely NOT a WTO-free zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
