<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTMAN CHECKS OUT NEW DIGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Among the dignitaries at Wednesday's first Kings
game at the Staples Center was National Hockey League commissioner
Gary Bettman, who many credit with the boom in new arenas
league-wide.
</P>
<P>
   Bettman, who took over as commissioner in February 1993 after
years as a critical member of the NBA's growth, has seen the Kings
go from bankruptcy in the post-Bruce McNall era to a team with a
state-of-the-art facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bankruptcy, that's ancient history,'' Bettman said. ``You get
judged not by your problems but how you deal with them. This
franchise can say it has dealt with its problems. No franchise can
say it has better ownership or a better building than this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Bettman said he is especially pleased with the downtown location
of the arena, previously believed to be a difficult sell to fans
driving in from such a large metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   ``This building is going to be an important part of Los Angeles,
especially downtown L.A,'' he said. ``It gives the Kings a great
home for years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Bettman's first tasks as commissioner was overseeing the
Kings ownership shift from McNall to Jeffrey Sudikoff and Joseph
Cohen. McNall had left the team in financial trouble and the new
owners were stung by the owners lockout, which wiped out almost
half of the 1994-95 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at this arena, a lot of the credit goes to Gary
Bettman,'' said Rogie Vachon, the one-time Kings goalie and now an
assistant to general manager Dave Taylor. ``There have been a lot
of new buildings go up and that was his vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did it by taking control of the decision-making. Before he
got here, the NHL was very political and a lot didn't get done. He
got rid of the politics and that really helped move the league
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Missing Man: One of the reasons for the Bruins' 0-5-3 start
has been a lack of offense. Their 12 goals coming in tied Buffalo
for last in the league. But the team also is playing without
goaltender Byron Defoe, a restricted free agent who is sitting out
in a contract dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Defoe, who played with the Kings for two seasons (1995-97), had
his best season last year, earning a second-team All-Star
selection. He also was a finalist in the Vezina Trophy balloting
for the league's top goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   In 68 games, Defoe had a 1.99 goals-against average with 10
shutouts. In 12 playoff games it was 2.03 with two shutouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
