<HEADLINE>
TEN TO REMEMBER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
LOS ANGELES _ Ten firsts at the new Staples Center (in
chronological order): 
__ First sellout: A capacity crowd of 18,118 was announced, but
there were many empty seats on the lower two levels. Dedicated
fans. The Kings had announced capacity was 18,500 but downgraded
that number. 
__ First member of the Kings organization introduced in pregame
ceremonies: Assistant equipment manager Rick Garcia, a key cog in
the machine. 
__ First person to sing national anthem: Broadway star Davis
Gaines, whose spirited version might turn out to be the ``best'' in
the life of the arena. 
__ First shot: Luc Robitaille, which seems appropriate. Time:
1:16. 
__ First goal: Anson Carter, which seems inappropriate. He took a
pass from Jonathan Girard and flipped the puck past Kings goalie
Stephane Fiset from a few feet in front of the net. Time: 4:12 of
the first period. 
__ First penalty: Darren Van Impe of Boston, two minutes, roughing.
Somewhere in the scuffle that preceded the penalty, the first punch
was thrown by someone. Or was it a push? Time: 7:06, first period. 
__ First Kings penalty: Craig Johnson, two minutes, holding.
Johnson is one the least-penalized players on the team. He had 32
penalty minutes all last season and six in eight games this year.
Time: 10:00, first period. 
__ First disgruntled fan: A frustrated guy sitting below the press
box as the Kings squandered a power-play opportunity. ``Somebody
shoot the &AMP;% puck.'' Also the first expletive. Time: 15:50, first
period. 
__ First Kings goal: Rob Blake, which also seems fitting. The
Kings' captain blasted a slap shot from just inside the blue line
past Boston goalie Robbie Tallas on a power play. Time: 10:32 of
the second period. 
__ First tie: A boring way to start an era.!dlim!!end! 

<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
