<SLUG> BC-CHIMP-LAZOO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY CHIMP RESTING AT NEW HOME IN L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY AMY RAISEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Abandoned by her mother at a Florida zoo, the
8-week-old chimpanzee named Zoe arrived at LAX and was resting in
quarantine at the Los Angeles Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zoe is tired, she's a sleepy girl,'' said Brenda Irvine,
wildlife curator at Lion Country Safari and Zoe's main keeper since
her birth.
</P>
<P>
   Irvine accompanied the chimp on the flight from Florida and said
Zoe is adjusting well on her first day. ``She's drinking her
bottles and she even went through a laughing phase,'' Irvine said
Wednesday, describing the tendency of chimps to smile broadly when
happy.
</P>
<P>
   All animals new to the zoo must be quarantined to ensure the
health of rest of the animals, according to zoo officials, so Zoe
is expected to be separated from two other young chimps for a
maximum of 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Zoe's August birth at Lion Country Safari in West Palm Beach,
Fla., surprised the staff, since her mother had had tubal ligation
surgery in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Transferring Zoe seemed logical because the Los Angeles Zoo is
raising two other young chimps who were not safe in their
environments with older chimps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better to be raised with their own kind, and we have the
space,'' said Lora LaMarca, marketing and public relations director
for the Los Angeles Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Irvine, who was bringing Zoe to her own home at night for the
first two weeks of the chimp's life, will return to Florida
tomorrow. She is confident that this move will be best for the
animal.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's young and she's resilient,'' Irvine said. ``The older
she got, the more attached she would have become to her keepers, so
this is the right time for this.''
</P>
<P>
   After Zoe's quarantine is lifted, she will meet chimps Jean and
Jake, about five and four months old, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to come back for the introduction stage,'' Irvine
said, ``but I don't know when I'm coming back.'' &QL; 
The young chimps, together with Zoe, will be reintroduced slowly to
the zoo's older chimps, said LaMarca. ``Our plan with all three
babies is to begin to take them up to the adult exhibit and let
them hear them, let them smell them and observe them.
</P>
<P>
   ``After about two years, the babies could be introduced into the
actual exhibit,'' LaMarca said. ``You never just throw animals into
an environment.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 0154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
