<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3653 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG     10-21 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUMPEL'S GOAL SAVES THE NIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ New Los Angeles Kings coach Andy Murray knew the
Staples Center would be packed for opening night. But all week he
was a little worried whether his team would show up through all the
hype.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who guided the Kings through a successful seven-game
trip to open the season, had to waited until the second period
Wednesday night against the Boston Bruins to find out. That's when
Rob Blake scored the first Kings' goal in the new building on a
power play.
</P>
<P>
   It was good to see, but almost not good enough. After Sergei
Samsonov beat Kings goalie Stephane Fiset with less than two
minutes left in the game to give Boston a 2-1 lead, Jozef Stumpel
tied the game with just over a minute remaining and the two teams
skated to a 2-2 tie in front of a sellout crowd of 18,111.
</P>
<P>
   The downtown arena, the vision of Kings owners Ed Roski and
Phillip Anschutz, was rocking through most of the third period when
Fiset traded big stops with Boston's Rob Tallas.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings had a half-dozen scoring opportunities late in third
period. The best came when a shot from Ian Laperierre nearly
trickled past Tallas with seven minutes left, but at the last
second Tallas got a glove on the puck.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Boston's Sergei Samsonov fired on a diving Fiset
and hit the post.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few days Murray spoke openly about concerns that
opening night at the new arena could be a little overwhelming for
his players. The team had just two practices there and spent more
time wooing season-ticket holders at a Tuesday afternoon luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   For a team that has missed the playoffs five of the last six
years, the distractions were significant, even if they opened 4-2-1
on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings came out sluggish on offense, playing their worst
period of the season in the first. They outshot the Bruins 9-8, but
had very few true scoring opportunities. It didn't help that
Boston, who entered the game 0-5-3, scored the first goal at the
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Just 4:12 into the game, Bruins right wing Anson Carter took a
pass from Jonathan Girard in front and beat Fiset.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Saturday's 5-4 loss to Edmonton, the Kings regrouped.
</P>
<P>
   They regained their composure midway through the period when
they killed off a five-on-three disadvantage for 33 seconds with
Chris Johnson (hooking) and Garry Galley (boarding) in the penalty
box.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't score until the second, when Blake tied it with a
blast from the point with Boston left wing Steve Heinze in the
penalty box.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Luc Robitaille was credited with the goal on a
tip-in of Blake's shot, but replays showed Blake's goal went
through the legs of Tallas.
</P>
<P>
   The play showed the Kings' skill on the first line. Newcomer
Ziggy Palffy, who had three consecutive 40-goal seasons with the
Islanders, has impressed teammates with his all-around game. He
drew the Bruins to him before getting the puck to Blake.
</P>
<P>
   It hadn't been so easy to find the net for the first five games
of the Kings trip. They did not get a point from the second line of
Donald Audette, Bryan Smolinski and Johnson, but Robitaille was
named NHL Player of the Week for scoring seven goals.
</P>
<P>
   The first line disappeared for the final two games in Canada,
where the Kings went 1-1. In the first game, Audette and Smolinski
scored. In the second Johnson had a hat trick.
</P>
<P>
   Through two periods, Robitaille and Blake had four shots apiece.
The second line combined for seven.
</P>
<P>
   After the Kings scored the game opened up, although there were
no more goals in the period.
</P>
<P>
   With 8:01 left in the second, Audette broke in on Tallas and
tried to fire the puck over his right shoulder. It didn't go.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, Fiset made a sliding stop on a wrist shot in
front by Carter and covered up.
</P>
<P>
   On the ensuing face off, Johnson broke out of the pack and
sailed up ice on a breakaway. He fired low to the stick side, but
Tallas made the stop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
