<HEADER>
A3656 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-DOLE-ANALYSIS-SFCHRON     10-21 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-ANALYSIS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE PAVED WAY TO HER OWN EXIT _ REAL CAMPAIGN NOWHERE TO BE SEEN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Elizabeth Dole added a lot more than a skirt and two X
chromosomes to the 2000 presidential free-for-all. Females from 8
to 80 cheered when she got into the ring. But Wednesday, the first
female candidate with a serious shot at the title announced she was
quitting.
<P>
   And it was no surprise: For weeks, there were hints of what was
to come.
</P>
<P>
   Dole said Wednesday that money made the presidential version of
the ``Fight Club'' too rough. But for weeks, maybe months, she has
been perceived as taking the equivalent of a political fall _
failing to run an all-out campaign that aggressively showcased her
strengths and played to her advantages.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she didn't know how: Liddy Dole was the feisty woman
who amassed a truckload of goodwill and a lot of admirers when she
trekked up and down the state on behalf of her husband, Bob, in
1996. She hit the Central Valley in 100-degree heat and wowed them
from the back of pickup trucks, remaining cool as a cuke as she
argued to anyone and everyone about the importance of the Bob Dole
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   She donned leather and straddled the back of a Harley with Jay
Leno to poke fun at her own buttoned-down image.
</P>
<P>
   And when the former Red Cross president made herself candidate,
schoolgirls wrote essays and grandmothers smiled. It was: You go,
girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, when it came time to use that gutsy talk on her own
behalf, Dole clammed up. There were too few spontaneous moments.
She gave serious speeches on foreign policy, gun control and
education, but too often, the candidate seemed frozen, her message
stilted.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, she usually appeared to be running, literally running,
from the media. Consider:
</P>
<P>
   __ Dole's last trip to the San Francisco Bay Area two weeks ago,
a visit that looked, like many before it, more like a campaign for
school board president than for the presidency of the United
States: minimal publicity with last-minute media, no in-depth
interviews allowed, no visits to editorial boards to make her case.
She instead offered a brief, 10-minute meeting with reporters in
suburban Burlingame _ the kind of quickie that doesn't allow for
depth or details. Dole mostly took questions about when she was
dropping out.
</P>
<P>
   -- Dole's appearance at the California GOP convention in Anaheim
at the end of September, where dozens of reporters sought in vain
to find someone,  &UR; anyone,  &LR; in her campaign to advocate her views
for Sunday stories going to press. Rumors ran rampant that she was
about to quit the race. The candidate was holed up in the hotel and
MIA to the press; when she finally surfaced late at night for her
speech, she took only a few questions before running off. Bad
press.
</P>
<P>
   -- Dole's last major Silicon Valley appearance in June, where
she promised to hold a press conference for reporters and take
their questions on issues like education, taxes and crime. Instead,
she showed up early, answered a few questions and literally tried
to run out on her press conference. Reporters blew up; Dole did
damage control.
</P>
<P>
   The irony: When Dole actually agreed to a rare one-on-one
interviews _ as she did with The Chronicle _ she was substantive
and serious.
</P>
<P>
   She reminded voters about her experience as transportation
secretary and labor secretary _ and how her work in those jobs
affected the lives of average consumers and workers.
</P>
<P>
   And long before George W. Bush made news by suggesting that the
GOP shouldn't support tax cuts ``on the backs of the poor,''
Elizabeth Dole had the guts to be at odds with the right wing of
the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those, certainly within my party, who are going to
disagree. But I don't think there should be any special interests
that dominate the party,'' she told The Chronicle. ``Why would any
family need an Uzi or an AK-47 to defend themselves? To me, that's
just common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   When the reaction to Dole's withdrawal came Wednesday, her
former competitors were complimentary, calling her a pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   And she was.
</P>
<P>
   But Dole can't blame only money for her failure. The
presidential ``Fight Club'' is tough stuff _ but the knockout
punches are usually self-inflicted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
