<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICE PLACE TO CALL HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It is a little known fact that they had luxury
suites at the Colosseum in Rome. Ask Chick Hearn if you don't
believe me. They weren't very close to the playing field, either,
for perfectly good reasons having to do with wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   They have 160 of them at the new Staples Center, which the Los
Angeles Kings inaugurated sports-wise Wednesday night, along with
hundreds of other amenities humidors, wine cellar, even fireplaces
that the Romans undoubtedly would have given thumbs ups.
</P>
<P>
   But we're not sure whether any of them matter to rank-and-file
hockey fans, who are notoriously easy to please. Give a puckhead a
seat with a view, the freedom to yell, a couple of beers _ OK,
several beers _ and a few good cross-checks, and they're perfectly
content. Throw in a good team and you have a fan for life.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that, it's hard to get a true first impression on the
viability of the Staples Center. We may need a Laker game or two,
or a mid-season Kings game against Calgary, to see if it is a stand
alone attraction.
</P>
<P>
   It is without question attractive. I'm not an architectural
critic, but I'll play one here and say that the Staples Center is
the most impressive looking building in downtown Los Angeles south
of the Music Center.
</P>
<P>
   If Staples had been open during the NFL's recent
expansion-city-rape sweepstakes, Houston businessman Robert McNair
might have $700 million burning a hole in his pocket. It shows you
what a little initiative and $375 in PRIVATE money can do.
</P>
<P>
   With cool contours that dominate the eye, it's a terrific
addition to the landscape. The atmosphere outside Staples was a
reminder of how vibrant a downtown arena can be. There are few
feelings as electric as a walk-up crowd milling round a stadium in
the hours before or after a game.
</P>
<P>
   That feeling is as much a part of the ambiance at Wrigley Field,
Fenway Park or Camden Yards in Baltimore as the game inside. It's
amazing how energizing it can be to see people walking and
communing. Once the retail area around Staples is built up, it will
be a true destination stop.
</P>
<P>
   You could actually find patrons Wednesday night who had set up a
tailgate in a parking lot a few hundreds yards away from Staples. I
once thought I saw a tailgate party in the Forum parking lot, but
it turned out to be an old couch that someone had dumped and set on
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Inside also gives one pause but in both positive and negative
ways. There is more concourse room at Staples than at some
airports, and it works to everyone's advantage. It's nice to be in
a crowd and not necessarily feel like you're in one.
</P>
<P>
   But the Forum wasn't particularly intimate for hockey games, and
neither is Staples. The triple deck of luxury suites that ring the
arena serves as a separation between church (the real hockey fans)
and state (those rich enough to afford the real good seats).
</P>
<P>
   It isn't a good look. There should never be seats higher than a
scoreboard, and that's the case for one-third of all seats at
Staples. Disney's renovation of Anaheim Stadium succeeded in adding
suites subtly, but baseball stadiums have advantages that arenas do
not. There may simply not be a good way to put 160 suites in an
arena, and the Kings owners, Ed Roski and Phil Anshutz, needed 160
to build it.
</P>
<P>
   To the credit of the owners and developers, they went the extra
mile in putting a face on the players even if the seats were a
quarter-mile high.
</P>
<P>
   The audio system along the boards was crackling good for those
in the last rows. You could hear checks along the boards, the puck
whizzing along the boards behind the goaltenders, and even the
schuss (SP??) of skates on ice.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Avendano of Whittier has been attending Kings games since
1992, usually sitting in the upper reaches of the Forum colonnade.
His seat Wednesday was in the last row of Section 320, and it cost
his $25. But he liked it more than his old seats at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is actually better than the Forum,'' he said. ``I can see
the player's faces and hear everything. It's steeper, but I have a
better view.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where the true Kings zealot will sit, those who have the
new Kings crest jersey, but also never threw away their old
silver-and-black and purple-and-gold outfits. The true loyalist
moved to the colonnade once the Gretzky era priced them out of the
Forum loge, and has stayed there A.G. (after Gretzky) since the
ticket prices stayed exorbitant.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, you could scan the lower level and find patches of
empty purple seats. But every seat upstairs was filled, and by the
fans with the loudest lungs. New arena, old habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I remember about the Forum,'' said legendary Kings
goalie Rogie Vachon, ``was the shape. I had never seen a round
arena before. I look at this, and I don't see anyone topping
Staples for many, many years.''
</P>
<P>
   Can an arena help a team win? ``No,'' said Rogie. ``In the old
days, you could play in a barn and it didn't matter. But it can
definitely be more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Staples is, whether or not you have access to the humidor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 0235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
