<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3660 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-GLFCOL-LADN-(SLAN     10-21 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GLFCOL-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEISHER NOT BAD FOR A ROOKIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; From amateur whiz to forgettable pro to senior sensation, it
has been a memorable golf career for Bruce Fleisher.
</P>
<P>
   The former U.S. Amateur champion, often lost in the crowd during
his two decades on the PGA Tour, is holding off none other than
senior superstar Hale Irwin in a stretch run that could make
Fleisher a triple-crown winner in his first season on the Senior
PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie of the Year, money champion and Player of the Year _ it's
all within reach for Fleisher, who entered this week No. 1 in
earnings and tied for first in wins _ six _ with Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher, who will play in next week's Pacific Bell Senior
Classic at Wilshire Country Club, credits his senior success to a
fast start that eluded him on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``My early years on the PGA Tour were difficult,'' said the 1968
U.S. Amateur champion, who was low amateur in the '69 Masters as a
contemporary of Ben Crenshaw, Lanny Wadkins and Tom Watson.
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher had high expectations and felt he couldn't miss, but. .
.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tour at that time had Monday qualifying and the guys who
came out of the box fast, like Ben and Lanny, they never looked
back. I came out and struggled trying to make it on Mondays. If you
get beat up early, unless you are strong mentally, it's very
difficult to get back to the other side of the fence. It was very
difficult for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senior Tour has been a whole different story for the fit
51-year-old, who won two of this year's first three tournaments and
was second in his next two starts. By June, he had four wins and
four other top-five finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Already, with $1,921,822 in '99, he has eclipsed his career PGA
Tour earnings _ $1.7 million, highlighted by his only win, in the
1991 New England Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher is feeding on his senior momentum, having found success
30 years after he expected it.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the age of 50, you are on a much more even playing field,''
he said. ``If I live long enough, I might be able to beat Jack
Nicklaus . . . but the point is, I am in the right place at the
right time.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Shark field set: Former Occidental College star Olin Browne,
a 14-year PGA Tour veteran, will make his debut in the Franklin
Templeton Shark Shootout next month, pairing with another notable
newcomer. He and tour Rookie of the Year candidate Carlos Franco
will form one of 12 two-man teams in the Nov. 12-14 Greg
Norman-hosted team competition at Thousand Oaks' Sherwood Country
Club.
</P>
<P>
   Browne, the most successful Oxy athlete since football speedster
Vance Mueller made the jump from the NCAA Division III Tigers to
the NFL Raiders in 1985, earned the Shark invitation with two wins
in the past 16 months.
</P>
<P>
   Franco, who had played in just five PGA Tour events before this
year, jump-started his '99 campaign with a strong showing in the
Anderson Consulting World Match Play Championship in February, then
followed with wins in the Compaq Classic of New Orleans and Greater
Milwaukee Open. He entered this week ranked 11th in season earnings
with $1,732,884.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams in the $1.5 million event are defending champions
Norman and Steve Elkington, Fred Couples/David Duval, Ben
Crenshaw/Bruce Lietzke, Peter Jacobsen/John Cook, Chip Beck/John
Daly, Craig Stadler/Tom Kite, Scott McCarron/Scott Hoch, Corey
Pavin/Steve Pate, Duffy Waldorf/Glen Day, Brad Faxon/Jeff Sluman
and Andrew Magee/Jay Haas.
</P>
<P>
   __ Par-3 showdown: Jesper Parnevik will defend his title in the
Sun Microsystems Par-3 challenge Nov. 16 at Four Seasons Aviara
Golf Club in Carlsbad. The made-for-television event, to be
broadcast Thanksgiving Day on Fox Sports Network, includes three
players each from the PGA, LPGA and Senior PGA tours and three
celebrity players.
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik, Fred Couples and Hal Sutton will represent the PGA and
Nancy Lopez, Kelly Kuehne and Annika Sorenstam the LPGA. Johnny
Miller, Lee Trevino and Chi Chi Rodriguez are expected to be named
as the Senior Tour representatives. Celebrity players have not yet
been selected.
</P>
<P>
   __ Matadors update: Cal State Northridge, which tied for eighth
Tuesday in its Countrywide Invitational at Wood Ranch, continues to
get good play in nearly every match but not by enough individuals
at the same time, according to coach Jim Bracken.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't jelled all at the same time,'' Bracken said.
``Every round we've played except for one, we've had at least one
person under par. But it's been different guys every round and we
haven't been consistent. When we're not playing well, we'll shoot
78 or 79. We're going to be good. We still have a lot of
confidence. We've just got to figure out why we're so
inconsistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Bracken says College of the Desert transfer Paul D'Ambra, who
tied for eighth this week at 5-over-par 221, has been the most
consistent, with a low round of 66 and a stroke average under 73.
The Matadors also have received strong play from freshman Scott
Bashin, the ex-Birmingham High whiz who qualified for this year's
state amateur in his first attempt. He tied for 16th at Wood Ranch
with the help of a second-round 69.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
