<SLUG> BC-GEN-UNIBEAT-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASSO'S SEASON IS NO CHICKEN FEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ About the only thing to stop USC's Allen Basso
this season is bad chicken.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I get,'' Basso said of his bout with salmonella
poisoning last weekend in Stockton. ``No more chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   Water polo opponents would be wise to force-feed Basso more
fowl. The Trojans' senior driver has been making everyone else in
the Mountain Pacific Sports Federation sick. Basso, a returning
All-American, leads the conference with a career-high 36 points (30
goals, six two-point goals), or twice as many points as anyone else
on the team. He also has been named MPSF Player of the Week twice,
including two weekends ago when he scored a two-point goal against
Stanford in overtime to send the Trojans into the NorCal Tournament
final.
</P>
<P>
   USC then beat UCLA to assume the top spot in the U.S. Water Polo
poll. After victories over Pacific and UC Davis last weekend (in
which Basso scored just two goals thanks to the chicken), the
Trojans (14-1, 3-0) remained No. 1 heading into Saturday's home
match with No. 3-ranked Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't like he has come out of nowhere. Basso is a fifth-year
senior who earned All-American honorable mention last year when the
Trojans won the national championship (he scored 25 points despite
a partially torn elbow ligament). He also was voted team captain
his sophomore and junior seasons _ after hardly playing as a
redshirt freshman.
</P>
<P>
   His success stems from USC's depth. The Trojans have five
returning All-Americans, and teams can't guard everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Basso's dominance came at a key time because top scorer Marko
Pintaric graduated. Someone had to step up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach (Jovan Vavic) wants someone to seize the
opportunities,'' Basso said. ``I'm a good shooter, so he's given me
the green light more.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Lonzo wins award: Basso's reign as MPSF Player of the Week
ended when Pepperdine's Greg Lonzo won the award with a six-goal,
eight-point weekend in the Waves' victories over Cal and UC Santa
Barbara. Lonzo has 30 points (24 goals, three 2-point goals),
placing him third in the MPSF behind Basso and Long Beach State's
Cory Dolley.
</P>
<P>
   __ Simmonds honored: Cal soccer player Kendall Simmonds, a Royal
High graduate, earned MPSF Player of the Week honors after he
scored two game-winning goals against Sacramento State and No.
1-ranked Santa Clara to extend his team's unbeaten streak to seven
matches (6-0-1). The Bears returned to the National Soccer Coaches
Association poll with the victories. Simmonds has just three goals
this season, but all are game-winners.
</P>
<P>
   __ Showdown in WCC: Pepperdine's women's volleyball team,
leading the West Coast Conference with a 14-1, 5-0 record, travels
to Santa Clara this weekend for a key conference matchup. Santa
Clara traditionally presents unique challenges to Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   Toso Pavilion, where Santa Clara plays, doesn't have a permanent
roof. Instead it's enclosed in a white, air-supported roof similar
to the Metrodome in Minneapolis and the material that encloses
swimming pools in the winter back east. Pepperdine coach Nina
Matthies calls it a bubble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to play in,'' Matthies said. ``We handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Waves have had success there, going 8-6 in 14
matches. Santa Clara swept 15-9, 15-12, 15-11 last season, but with
middle blocker Jamie Hill, setter Melissa Plass and outside hitter
Stacy Rouwenhorst among the conference's hitting leaders, the
chances look better. A victory would give Matthies her 300th career
victory (she's 299-213 now).
</P>
<P>
   Also, San Diego beat Santa Clara last weekend. Pepperdine won at
San Diego Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for it to be the toughest match,'' Matthies said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
