<SLUG> BC-FBO-RECRUIT-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA LANDS HERALDED QB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Brock Berlin, perhaps the nation's best
high school quarterback, recently announced his decision to play
for Steve Spurrier at the University of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean that Spurrier will keep the two-quarterback
system for the next four years?
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-2, 195-pound Berlin, who plays for nationally
top-ranked Shreveport Evangel Christian, made his announcement at
the First Assembly of God in Shreveport, La., which is custom for
players at the school. He chose the Gators over Kentucky, Georgia,
LSU and Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin is the type of quarterback good programs are built
around. He completed 656 of 955 passes for 5,488 yard with 108
touchdowns during his first two seasons and is 144 of 246 for 2,082
yards and 20 touchdowns through seven games this year.
</P>
<P>
   Other happening include:
</P>
<P>
   UCLA will receive a visit from one of the nation's best
receivers -- Charlie Rogers (6-4, 185) from Saginaw, Mich. Rogers,
who has drawn comparisons to Randy Moss because of his size and
speed - also has trips planned to Tennessee and Florida State and
will probably also visit Michigan and Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has received a commitment from running back Albert
Tuipulotu (6-1, 250) of San Mateo Community College. He was part of
the Huskies 1997 class but left after three games that year. He'll
have two years of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Washington lost out on one of the state's best offensive linemen
when Eddie Keele (6-4, 285) gave a commitment to BYU. Oregon had
also offered a scholarship to Keele.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Mackey (6-0, 180) of Bakersfield High picked Colorado over
Nebraska, Arizona, Arizona State and Washington. Mackey was a prep
teammate of USC freshman linebacker Aaron Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona received a commitment from running back Anthony Fulcher
(6-1, 180) of Scottsdale Horizon. His father, Mark, was an option
quarterback at Arizona in 1980-81.
</P>
<P>
   One of the state's best defensive linemen, Nathan Goodson (6-5,
255) of Temescal Canyon, has his choices narrowed to USC, Arizona,
UCLA, Washington and Cal. He visited Arizona on Sept. 18 and has
trips planned to USC (Dec. 3) and Cal (Dec. 10). USC and Arizona
are the two favorites as of now.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Margarita quarterback Chris Rix and San Diego Mira Mesa
teammates Amon Gordon and Teyo Johnson were among the recruits
visiting Florida State last weekend. Rix, who transferred from
Bishop Amat and helped Santa Margarita beat his old teammates on
Friday, committed to the Seminoles before the season.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon and Johnson, who both transferred to Mira Mesa from
Everett, Wash., have yet to decide and could end up at the same
school. Gordon, a 6-foot-4, 250-pound running back-linebacker also
has trips planned to USC (Dec. 3) and Michigan (Dec. 10).
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a 6-foot-6, 242-pound tight end, is highly sought after
in football and basketball. His first love is basketball, but he
wants to play both in college. He visited Houston on Oct. 9 and is
also considering a number of other schools, including USC, UCLA and
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago-based recruiting analyst Tom Lemming's choices of the
nation's top recruiters in alphabetical order: Tim Cassidy (Texas
A&AMP;M); Jim Collins and Bob Sanders (Florida); Bill Conley (Ohio
State); Ronnie Cottrell (Alabama); Rodney Garner (Georgia); Danny
Hope (Purdue); Rob Ianello (Arizona); Greg Mattison (Notre Dame);
Larry Petroff (USC); Dave Roberts (South Carolina).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 0246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 03:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
