<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 03:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3679 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-ROOFTOP-ROBBER-SFCHRO     10-21 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROOFTOP-ROBBER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 YOU DESERVE A BREAK-IN TODAY: McBANDIT SAWS THROUGH ROOFS
OF  McDONALD'S 
 &HT;     By KEVIN FAGAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ He's as slick as a greasy french fry. And after
chopping through the ceilings of at least 35 fast-food restaurants
_ mostly McDonald's _ from coast to coast, the polite young thief
nicknamed ``the Rooftop Robber'' is frying the nerves of police
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Terrifying, he's not. At least so far.
</P>
<P>
   But judging by the reactions of frustrated detectives and
bemused victims from the San Francisco Bay Area all the way to
Virginia, this bandit with a taste for guns and saws is pushing for
the title of most original bad guy of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never even heard of anything like it before,'' said one
clerk who was about to start her morning shift at the Chilpancingo
Parkway McDonald's in Pleasant Hill, Calif., in August when the
``Rooftop Robber'' dropped in _ through the ceiling. ``He wiped
himself off when he got to the floor, was real polite the whole
time, and then told us, `Can you please get in the freezer?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't frightened, because he was so soft-spoken,'' said the
clerk, who said company policy prevented her from giving her name.
``It was all pretty weird.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that having a nickname makes what he does cute, police weary
of the mounting publicity say.
</P>
<P>
   The rooftop ripoff artist has knocked over restaurants in five
states _ always after closing time _ taking anywhere from $200 to
$2,000 each time, and he changes locations so fast he seems
unstoppable. He genteelly hands sweaters to his victims as he herds
them into meat lockers, softly says ``please'' and ``thank you'' as
he scoops the cash into a bag, and saunters away with a cheery
farewell.
</P>
<P>
   At one McDonald's in Benicia, Calif., in July, the prolific
robber even paused his getaway stroll to call police and tell them
he left a pack of people in the freezer. He waves a semiautomatic
pistol, and he gingerly put a bullet in a computer for effect once.
So far, nobody has been injured.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake, those who hunt him say. ``This guy is
dangerous, and the nature of what he is doing is very violent,''
said Dan Connelly, a police detective from Pleasant Hill, Calif.
``I wouldn't relax one bit on him. We want him off the streets now
before someone gets hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Connelly had to acknowledge, however, that the hoodlum has
cooked up a criminal game the detective hasn't seen before: ``I've
been at this a long time, but never seen an M.O. like this. It's
strange, I'll say that.''
</P>
<P>
   The robber began his binge at a McDonald's in Folsom, Calif.,
last Thanksgiving, knocking over restaurants all over the West at
will. From the start, he has had the same pattern: cutting through
the roof, then waiting in the space above the ceiling to strike
when workers come on shift. He headed East two months ago before
popping up again in Rancho Cordova, near Sacramento, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The latest count at the state Department of Justice shows he has
robbed restaurants in at least 18 communities in California, most
in the northern part of the state, and five more in Oregon and
Nevada. That is not counting the jobs he pulled in Virginia and
North and South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's alone has been hit at least 23 times _ so many that
the company is offering a $5,000 reward for information leading to
his capture. The bandit's other unlucky hosts have included Burger
King restaurants _ plus a couple Toys R Us and Blockbuster Video
stores, as if to vary his thieving appetite.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hitting so many places so fast in so many areas that
we're having a hard time even keeping count,'' said state
Department of Justice Special Agent Martin Horan. ``We're hoping he
screws up before too long so somebody catches him.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest heist, in Rancho Cordova, was just like the others.
He hacked through the roof of the McDonald's restaurant on Sunrise
Boulevard after closing time, waited for the morning shift, and
descended on the stunned workers as they fired up the grills.
</P>
<P>
   Then he calmly shooed everyone into the meat freezer, cleaned
out the cash registers and walked away.
</P>
<P>
   The bandit is described as a white male, 5 feet 10 inches tall,
weighing about 150 pounds, in his early 20s and having brown hair.
He always wears a black ski mask, bandanna or a dust mask over his
face, and he carries a bag filled with saws, drills and ropes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got us stumped, all right,'' said Sergeant C.M. Mise of
the police department in Raleigh, N.C., where the Rooftop Robber
knocked over a McDonald's in September. ``We were hoping you folks
out there would get lucky and get him.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just what police in California have in mind. ``We always
get our guy, and somewhere, somehow, this one will make a wrong
move, too,'' said Dublin, Calif., Police Sgt. Greg Ahern, who has
been chasing leads since the bandit hit a McDonald's on Dublin
Boulevard in August. ``A bad guy, even with a funny name, is still
just a bad guy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 0312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
