<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-AX-FALLS-ASAHI-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NISSAN WIELDS AX ON JOBS, PLANTS, SPENDING  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 475-word ``separate buy'' article is from the Asahi News
Service.)  
  
 (EDITORS: Get your news from Japan and the Pacific Rim straight
from the source _ the Asahi News Service. Its Monday through Friday
report of news, features and distinctive analysis is culled from
The Asahi Shimbun, Japan's foremost newspaper, renowned for its
integrity and thoroughness (with a daily circulation is 12
million.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``i'' international news and ``f'' financial news files.)  
  
 By ASAHI NEWS SERVICE  
 c.1999 Asahi News Service  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The drastic restructuring Nissan Motor Co.'s executives
announced on Oct. 18 is aimed to eliminate excess production
capacity and focus its financial and personnel resources on its
main business: making cars.
</P>
<P>
   The program, called the Nissan Revival Plan in the presentation
by Carlos Ghosn, Nissan's chief operating officer, will close five
domestic factories and will sell off non-automotive sectors such as
its ship- and aerospace-related businesses.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the executives said, Nissan will be able to
eliminate 21,000 jobs and trim its operating costs by 1 trillion
yen ($9.5 billion).
</P>
<P>
   Three auto assembly plants are to be closed by March 2001 and
the other two plants, which make engines, will be closed by March
2002.
</P>
<P>
   They include three automobile assembly plants, the Murayama
plant in Musashi-Murayama, Tokyo; Kyoto plant in Uji, Kyoto, and
the Minato plant in Nagoya, and an engine plant at Kurihama, in
Yokosuka, Kanagawa Prefecture, and an engine plant at its Kyushu
facilities in Kanda, Fukuoka Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
   The Kyoto plant is operated by Nissan Shatai Corp., a Nissan
affiliate, and the Minato plant is operated by Aichi Machine
Industry Co., another affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   The closings will reduce the number of automobile assembly
plants in Japan to four, from seven.
</P>
<P>
   Those that remain are the Tochigi plant in Kaminokawa, Tochigi
Prefecture; Oppama plant in Yokosuka, Kanagawa Prefecture; the
Kyushu plant; and the Shonan plant in Hiratsuka, Kanagawa
Prefecture. The Shonan plant is also operated by Nissan Shatai.
</P>
<P>
   In the three car assembly plants to be closed, however, some
small-scale production activity will be retained, including a
microbus production line at the Kyoto plant. Some parts
manufacturing and body panel presses will be retained at the
Murayama and Minato plants, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the properties involved in the plant closings will be
sold, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The plant closings will bring the work force at Nissan and
affiliated companies to about 127,000, a reduction of about 21,000,
or 14 percent of its current work force of 148,000.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 21,000, 4,000 jobs will be cut in the manufacturing
sector while 6,500 will be reduced by the integration of sales
agents and other marketing-related sectors, with 6,000
administrative job cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Five thousand jobs will be eliminated through selling off Nissan
businesses not involved in automobile activities. Those businesses
include forklift manufacture, ship-related projects and production
of rockets for the Defense Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The executives said the dramatic restructuring will trim 1
trillion yen from Nissan's operating costs by fiscal 2002, and will
bring down the debt on which it pays interest to about 700 billion
yen, from 1.4 trillion yen now.
</P>
<P>
   Katsuhiko Hagiwara, chairman of the Nissan labor union,
responding to the announcement, said, ``There are no other ways
except to deal with our management realistically.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 475-word article from the Asahi News Service, it
must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
