<HEADLINE>
E-TRADE `PARASITES' BUG STOCK-MARKET EXECUTIVES  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 675-word ``separate buy'' article is from the International
Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``f'' financial news and ``a'' domestic/general news files.)  
  
 By THOMAS CRAMPTON  
 c.1999 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK _ When top executives from stock markets around the
world sat down for a discreet closed-door discussion in Bangkok
this week the most recurrent theme was not recent market turmoil,
but the dangers of unregulated markets springing up on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impact of alternative systems for on-line electronic
trading kept popping up everywhere,'' said Gerrit de Marez Oyens,
secretary-general of the Federation International des Bourses de
Valeurs, which includes members representing 97 percent of the
world's market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main concern from traditional markets is that electronic
stock trading networks will dilute the inherent worthiness of stock
prices.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization led by de Marez Oyens, known as FIBV, has a
membership that includes global players like the main markets in
London, Tokyo and New York, along with exchanges in developing
markets such as Lima, Tehran, Bangkok and Ljubljana, Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executives from markets around the world expressed
fear that unchecked growth of unlinked, Internet-based markets
could fragment, undermine and dilute the value of stock prices
worldwide, de Marez Oyens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stock trading could turn into an experience like shopping for
silk in a Thai market: an individual transaction that is completely
untransparent,'' de Marez Oyens said, referring to Internet stock
trading companies as ``parasitical services'' that exploit
regulatory investments made by traditional stock markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stock markets pay for regulation, so why shouldn't the
parasites?'' de Marez Oyens said, noting that the New York Stock
Exchange employs a full-time staff of 500 regulators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regulations make for a protected and orderly environment that
ensures transparency, fairness and people getting paid in time,''
he said. ``Most of these electronic trading companies probably
don't have a single person looking into regulatory issues.''
</P>
<P>
   So far there is only a fledgling group of U.S.-based electronic
stock trading networks, known as ECNs, whose users trade stock
outside traditional markets. These markets are small and unlinked,
which critics say can result in different prices for the same
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the explosive growth of on-line stock trading _ an
electronic extension of traditional markets, for now _ indicates
that ECNs, too, could prove wildly popular.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents argue that the discounts offered by on-line trading
services have been a democratizing force that has helped bring many
individual investors into the market for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional markets have often failed to exploit opportunities
on the Internet, and in some cases entry costs for investors have
remained high, de Marez Oyens acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certainly not enough to just call on-line companies
parasites,'' he said. ``We need to concentrate on why these
companies have been sprouting up and why their market share is
growing and where the traditional markets missed the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, de Marez Oyens said, nobody benefits if competing
ECNs make users unable to know the real price for a stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a drink at the bar and discover you paid ten bucks
more than your friend who bought the same stock almost at the same
time, you feel ripped off,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The quickest solution, he added, is to allow on-line trading
systems to register as stock exchanges. ``If they are regulated
like stock exchanges, then traditional markets can compete with
them fairly for the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the Internet, the demutualization under consideration by
44 of the FIBV's 52 members _ with several considering public stock
offerings _ will be a major force pushing for more
consumer-oriented stock markets, de Marez Oyens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Users are not bound by membership rules or susceptible to peer
pressure,'' he said. ``It brings in a whole new culture when you
are forced to offer high-quality services at the lowest possible
price.''
</P>
<P>
   Increased awareness of consumer needs should help traditional
exchanges capture certain aspects of the business currently offered
by electronic trading networks, de Marez Oyens added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently we have left behind our business somewhere because
many of these alternative trading services actually offer the same
things we offered in the past.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 675-word article from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is: weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
