<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 03:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3686 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-WINERIES-CHINA-600&AMP;ad     10-21 1535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINERIES-CHINA-600&AMP;add-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOAST TO CHINA'S FLEDGLING WINE INDUSTRY  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Business Desks)   (This excellent ``separate buy'' article is from the International
Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS THREE HELPFUL OPTIONAL TRIMS, TOTALING 200 WORDS _ AT 600
(75 WORDS), 725 (75 WORDS) AND 1,100 (50 WORDS). TOTAL OF UNCUT
VERSION IS 1,150.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``i'' international news and ``a'' general news
files.)  
  
 By JONATHAN NAPACK  
 c.1999 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   QINGDAO, China _ A hot, sun-drenched summer day. Vines in neat,
disciplined rows climb the hillside behind you, the grapes ready to
be harvested, crushed and fermented in great barrels inside the
sprawling, whitewashed buildings below. Meanwhile, you admire the
wine, clear gold and deep purple, over a simple, delicious local
meal.
</P>
<P>
   This could be a scene anywhere in France, California's Napa
Valley or South Australia. Except that this is the People's
Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
   Years of experiments have led to breakthroughs on the Shandong
Peninsula, whose climate is uniquely suitable in Asia for
vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   During China's Tang Dynasty, grape wine was imported from
Central Asia, where small amounts of port-like wine are still made
_ ``rooster's heart'' and ``cow's udder'' being two indigenous
varietals.
</P>
<P>
   Asia's climate, however, is generally inhospitable to
viniculture. Wine grapes need long days to ripen and dryness to
concentrate their juice; they are also very sensitive to cold.
</P>
<P>
   East Asia's pervasive humidity and low latitudes present almost
insurmountable challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Shandong. The province stretches to the south of Beijing,
then juts out toward Korea, dividing the Gulf of Bohai from the
Yellow Sea.
</P>
<P>
   The ocean moderates the Siberian winters, while the northerly
latitude (similar to San Francisco's) and low summer humidity _ a
steady 60 percent _ allows temperate fruits like apples and
peaches, for which Shandong is famous, to flourish.
</P>
<P>
   The first to recognize this potential was Zhang Bishi, a Qing
Dynasty official who founded the Chang Yu Winery near Yantai in
1892. Zhang brought vines from Europe and appointed Yantai's
Austrian consul as winemaker, but the winery today mostly makes a
localized kind of vermouth.
</P>
<P>
   The real trailblazer was an Englishman named Michael Parry, who
founded the Huadong Winery. Parry came to Hong Kong in 1973 as an
accountant, and drifted through a series of jobs before ending up
in the wine trade.
</P>
<P>
   As China started opening up after 1978, Parry became consumed
with the dream of producing first-class wine in China. In 1982 he
discovered the Shandong Peninsula, and with his partner Gabriel Tam
started convincing the local farmers to plant grapes where, in
marginal soil conditions, they had been growing sweet potatoes and
peanuts. In 1985, they planted 42,000 cuttings.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year later, a typhoon destroyed the vineyard, but
Parry persisted and replanted. By 1986, he was producing chardonnay
and riesling with the help of winemakers from California and
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, however, having put up $1 million of his own
money, Parry went bankrupt and his stake (the joint-venture partner
was state-owned Tsingtao Winery) went to Hiram Walker, itself soon
bought by the British spirits company Allied-Domecq.
</P>
<P>
   Parry stayed on as adviser but his heart was broken. He died of
cancer two years later at age 43.
</P>
<P>
   His photograph hangs prominently at the winery's office _ a
giant of a man, with the glow of the bon vivant. His ashes are
buried on a hill overlooking the vineyard, and the farmers tend
reverently to his grave.
</P>
<P>
   Today's Huadong Winery sits among 14 hectares (35 acres) of a
steep, sun-facing basin in the Laoshan Mountains, 40 kilometers (25
miles) from Qingdao.
</P>
<P>
   The landscape is sublime _ severe, forbidding crags soaring
above green summer fields. In the Chinese way of looking at things,
it's definitely Northern majesty, not Southern mist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use this vineyard as a nursery,'' says George Zhao, the
winery's commercial manager. ``We sell cuttings all over the place
_ even Ningxia, Sichuan. People are planting vineyards all over
China.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 75 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 600) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is also used to experiment with varieties like pinot noir and
gamay. Huadong's white wines, however, come from a larger vineyard,
400 hectares of chardonnay and riesling 120 kilometers to the
north.
</P>
<P>
   ``The soil is limy, sandy gravel,'' Zhao says. ``Useless for
most crops, but perfect for white wines.'' He adds that the
microclimate strongly resembles that of the region of France that
produces Beaujolais. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Parry built the winery as a family residence, with living
quarters upstairs. They've since added a warehouse and cellar _ and
are building a guesthouse. ``Wine tourism,'' Zhao says, '' is the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The most surprising thing about Huadong is how good their best
wines are. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 75 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 725) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The riesling is refreshing and aromatic, in the Alsatian style,
while the mildly oaked chardonnay is subtle and complex, almost
flinty like a chablis, more Burgundy than California.
</P>
<P>
   The red produced for the domestic market is forgettable, but the
winery is planning to produce a cabernet franc _ used in reds from
Touraine and Anjou in France _ from the 1999 vintage, and samples
from the barrel taste promising. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is surprising because other Chinese wineries barely produce
anything recognizable as wine, much less good wine. Most of it,
anyhow, is drunk with Sprite or other mixers by status-conscious
drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   There is the Chinese-owned Great Wall, Dragon Seal (a
joint-venture with Pernod-Ricard) and, the best of the lot,
Dynasty, a joint venture with Remy-Cointreau in Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
   Set up in 1980 as only the second joint venture in mainland
China, Dynasty produces small amounts of premium chardonnay that is
at least drinkable. Huadong says it's made with their surplus
grapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We own our own vineyards just for that reason,'' says Lin
Keqiang, Huadong's general manager, ``to control the quality.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem, he says, is lack of government regulation.
``There are no AOC laws, no quality control. `Wine' only legally
needs to be 70 percent grape juice!''
</P>
<P>
   Li Peng's 1995 decree replacing baijiu, Chinese grain spirit,
with wine at banquets just led to officials drinking shots of wine
``down the hatch,'' like baijiu. Other obstacles include lack of
refrigerated storage.
</P>
<P>
   However erratic their support, Beijing does back the fledgling
wine industry, which after all produces a high-value product from
impoverished soils, not to mention freeing up scarce grain from
baijiu production and promoting healthier drinking habits.
</P>
<P>
   Duty on imported wine is 70 percent, clearly helping the locals
(even Huadong's premium wines sell for only 25 yuan or $3 in
China).
</P>
<P>
   But Huadong isn't satisfied with being the big fish in a small
pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make the best wine in Asia,'' Lin says. Mellowing a
little after several glasses and some wonderful Shandongese
cooking, watching bees skim wildflowers beneath the surreal Laoshan
peaks, it's hard not to cheer them on. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 1,100. 50-WORD TRIM FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Tours of Huadong Winery may be arranged at any China
International Travel Service in Qingdao. Accommodation will be
ready some time next year; in the meantime it is an hour's drive
from Qingdao. You can contact Huadong directly at: tel. (86) 532
881-729, fax (86) 532 881-8989 or winery(AT)public.qd.sd.cn &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Jonathan Napack is a journalist who travels
frequently in Asia.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
