<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANDIDATES-EYE-MARKETS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE WANNABES WATCH WALL STREET  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 950-word ``separate buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Wall Street opened for business Monday morning
it was not only investors, big and small, who waited in trepidation
to see which way the markets would move.
</P>
<P>
   The White House hopefuls who are already battling to succeed
President Bill Clinton were on tenterhooks, too, because a
sustained downturn in the longest peacetime boom the United States
has ever known could fundamentally change the political arithmetic
for next year's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, there has been a prevailing consensus, fueled by the
innate optimism of the current generation of Americans, that the
boom could only continue.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of last week, however, the mood started to change.
The previous five days had seen the steepest fall in share prices
for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a veiled warning to the banks from the Chairman of
the Federal Reserve, Alan Greenspan, about market volatility
combined with an unexpectedly sharp increase in wholesale prices in
September to send the Dow Jones plunging more than 250 points in
the day.
</P>
<P>
   It even dipped briefly below the symbolic 10,000 points for the
first time since April, registering a fall of a full 12 percent
from the record 11,326 struck in August.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the Wall Street Journal was awash with cautious
pessimism. ``Return to 10,000 _ Is this bear territory?'' read the
main headline of the investment section.
</P>
<P>
   Alongside, the second headline was even more worrying: ``Fed's
credibility as inflation foe may be weakening.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in a very long time, doubts were being raised
about the judgment of Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal
Reserve and hero of the Clinton economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as six weeks ago, next year's presidential
candidates were pleading with Clinton to reappoint Greenspan early
for another term.
</P>
<P>
   They all wanted to avoid the chairmanship of the Fed becoming a
political issue on the eve of the election and worried that
attendant uncertainty could upset the markets. Now, they could be
overtaken by events.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate who has most to lose from a serious downturn in
the economy would undoubtedly be Vice-President Al Gore. The
prosperity in which America has basked through Bill Clinton's
presidency is one of his strongest suits, and the one that Clinton
cites first when he campaigns on Gore's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Reeling off a string of statistics: economic growth, income,
unemployment, he invites his audience to compare America now with
America when he came to office. ``Do you want more of the same?''
his implied message runs, ``Just vote for Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   The strength of the economy could outweigh much of the negative
baggage from the Clinton presidency that drags down Gore's
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Remove that advantage, though, and the Gore campaign looks much
weaker; the candidate will be left having to explain how he would
set about reviving an economic boom amid falling expectations, and
a far more pessimistic national mood.
</P>
<P>
   He would also be left _ as would all the other candidates _
explaining to voters how he would pay for his string of election
promises if it suddenly looked as though the much-heralded domestic
budget surplus was not going to materialize.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, economic bad news could provide a
windfall for Bill Bradley. Not only is he not associated with the
White House _ a distinct plus if Clinton bequeaths an ailing
economy as well as the integrity issue to his vice-president _ he
has also positioned himself politically to the left of Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's unashamed recognition of the have-nots and his
promises of a more ``inclusive'' America could have more resonance
if the number of have-nots _ and those who perceived themselves as
such _ increases.
</P>
<P>
   Falling share prices would leave America's new generation of
private investors downcast (and out of pocket); it could also
depress wages, increase joblessness and endanger welfare reform
(which has succeeded so far largely because of the number of jobs
available).
</P>
<P>
   Job insecurity could also revive pressure for universal health
insurance, bringing Clinton's presidency full circle on health
policy. Bradley has already had something to say on all these
issues, and would need to change little in his campaign pitch to
appear a man for his times.
</P>
<P>
   But the leading Republican contender, George W. Bush, is also
neatly positioned to capitalize on Clinton-Gore economic distress.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks he has separated himself from Congressional
Republicans, accusing them of being unduly hardhearted towards the
poor.
</P>
<P>
   And only last week, he told New Yorkers: ``Too often my party
has focused on the national economy to the exclusion of all else _
speaking a sterile language of rates and numbers, of CBO/Central
Budget Office/this and GNP that...''
</P>
<P>
   So long as the economy thrives, such words convey the message to
voters that the prosperity of the Clinton presidency is not
everything. They could be easily adapted to leaner economic times,
however, offering reassurance to those who have lost out
economically and competing with Bradley's appeal to the newly
insecure.
</P>
<P>
   A further winner could be Pat Buchanan, the conservative
Republican who is on the verge of defecting to the Reform Party in
the hope of becoming that party's presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan is the candidate of the right who is most forcefully
protectionist, a message that will fall on fertile ground if
unemployment rises.
</P>
<P>
   Any gain in votes for Buchanan, however, is likely to be Bush's
loss, harming his chances and making it more likely that a Democrat
returns to the White House. &QL; 
