<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 04:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3697 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-SAINT-STOPS-TRAFFIC-I     10-21 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAINT-STOPS-TRAFFIC-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO BONES ABOUT IT _ CANONIZED SAINT HAS STAR QUALITY  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Religion Editors)   (This curious 750-word ``separate buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``a''
domestic/general/religion news file.)  
  
 By DAVID USBORNE  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Another star, another traffic jam. They get used to
it in New York. The President is in town? Stay away from The
Waldorf. Ricky Martin is stopping in Times Square? Don't go near
the place.
</P>
<P>
   But how many New Yorkers would have thought to dodge Fifth
Avenue because of a box of bones?
</P>
<P>
   Quite a number, in fact, especially if they were Catholics. They
would not have been surprised by the circus that erupted with the
casket's arrival just after dusk at the steps of St. Patrick's
Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   The weeping women, reaching out to touch. The devoted followers
gripping candles in their hands. It got so crazy, they had to close
Fifth Avenue for half an hour. That never happened to The Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the latest stop on the world tour not of a rock star
_ St. Patrick's, after all, is hardly Madison Square Garden _ but
of a saint, or rather the remains of a saint.
</P>
<P>
   This box was, more accurately, a reliquary of polished jacaranda
decorated with exquisite gold and silver filigree. And it contained
bones from the body of St. Therese of Lisieux, also known as the
``little flower.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything you will ever need to know about St. Therese is on
her website _ www.littleflower.org.
</P>
<P>
   You will see how she joined a Carmelite Convent at 16, how she
wrote a memoir, ``The Story of a Soul,'' and how, after a simple
life of devotion, she died from tuberculosis at 24 in 1897. The
book has become one of the most widely read works of Catholic
teaching.
</P>
<P>
   You will also learn about her gruelling global pilgrimage that
is already three years old. So far, St. Therese _ or at least half
her bones, the remaining half are in France _ has toured Russia,
most of western Europe, Argentina and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   She is scheduled to hurtle across the United States and Canada,
making appearances at 114 churches and monasteries, before heading
to the Philippines in January.
</P>
<P>
   Therese of Lisieux was canonized back in 1925. It was for the
normal pre-canonization investigative process that her body was
disinterred, which has ensured the continuing availability of her
bones today.
</P>
<P>
   But her status in the Catholic firmament was boosted further in
1997, the centenary of her death, when Pope John Paul II proclaimed
her to be a Doctor of the Church. She is the youngest of 33 saints
who have the title, which denotes a special holiness. And she is
one of only three women Doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, she has pulling power. At every stop, the
crowds of faithful come to venerate her. The lucky ones get to
touch the Perspex dome that surrounds the reliquary or to press
their lips against it.
</P>
<P>
   Her draw is not hard to explain. There was the simplicity of her
life _ there were no great deeds or miracles to her name _ and she
is accessible to worshippers today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not often that we get to see a saint, or at least the
relics of a saint,'' said Gerry Olsen as she stepped out from St.
Patrick's Monday. With her husband, Bill, she had come just to be
able to look at the reliquary in front of the altar. ``You feel
close to her.''
</P>
<P>
   There are the photographs of St. Therese that fellow nuns took
of her at the Lisieux Convent. The saint doing the laundry and the
saint lying in bed, stricken by the disease that killed her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can really feel her presence,'' said Roz Romero, a Wall
Street broker who had come to the cathedral. ``She tells us that
anybody is capable of being a saint.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Patrick's was well prepared for the surge of visitors that
was sure to come for the 40 hours that the reliquary was to remain
within its walls.
</P>
<P>
   There is an exhibition of her pictures down one transept, with
testimonials from famous devotees of St. Therese. Among them was
Edith Piaf who was blind until three, when she was taken to visit
Lisieux. For the rest of her life she thanked St. Therese for her
sight.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate the demand, services and liturgies were planned
right through until 5 a.m. when St. Therese was due to leave for
another parish in Brooklyn. At least at that hour, her departure
should cause only the minimum of traffic gridlock. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
