</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACAU-BOX-$ADV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHRONOLOGY OF MACAU, ASIA'S OLDEST WESTERN ENCLAVE
 &HT;    With CHINA-MACAU-$ADV24.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Oct. 24 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACAU _ Here is a capsule history of Macau, the last and oldest
Western enclave on the Asian continent that is about to return to
Chinese rule:
</P>
<P>
   1535 _ Imperial bureaucrats of China's Ming Dynasty allow
Portuguese vessels to dock and conduct trade in Macau port.
</P>
<P>
   1543-1639 _ Portugal enjoys a de facto monopoly on trade between
China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   1553 _ Portuguese sailors set up their first permanent
settlement on Macau, telling the Chinese they needed a place to dry
goods damaged by water.
</P>
<P>
   1557 _ Portuguese establish a walled village begin paying ground
rents for the right to live on the Macau peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   1622 _ Dutch vessels attack Macau in an effort to break
Portugal's century-long monopoly of trade with China and Japan. The
attack is repelled, but Dutch and British renew efforts to cut into
Portugal's trade.
</P>
<P>
   1700s _ Macau declines economically as China crimps trade and
rejects Portuguese envoys.
</P>
<P>
   1845 _ Portugal expels Chinese customs officials and declares
the Macau peninsula a free port, then expands its territory by
seizing nearby Taipa and Coloane islands a few years later.
</P>
<P>
   About 1860 - The Portuguese governor issues the first gambling
licences in Macau.
</P>
<P>
   1887 _ China's weak Qing imperial dynasty signs a ``Treaty of
Commerce and Friendship'' recognizing Portuguese sovereignty over
Macau and allowing it ``perpetual occupation'' of the territory.
Today's Chinese historians say the treaty was never ratified by
China.
</P>
<P>
   1939-1945 _ Macau escapes ravages of World War II and flourishes
as a free port because the belligerents recognize Portugal's
neutrality.
</P>
<P>
   1955 _ Portugal passes an ``organic law'' declaring Macau one of
its overseas colonies.
</P>
<P>
   1966 _ Portuguese installations are attacked by Red Guards
during China's Cultural Revolution, and a few are killed by
Portuguese troops.
</P>
<P>
   1974 _ After a coup in Portugal, the new anti-colonial
government declares it no longer has sovereignty over Macau but
continues administering it as ``a Chinese territory under
Portuguese administration.''
</P>
<P>
   1987 _ Portugal and China declare that China will ``resume'' the
administration of Macau on December 20, 1999, and that Macau's laws
and way of life would continue for at least 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
