</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3765 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-CENTAM-MITCH-$ADV23-C     10-21 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTAM-MITCH-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A YEAR LATER, CENTRAL AMERICA STILL FEELING EFFECTS OF HURRICANE
MITCH
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With MITCH-REBUILD-$ADV23.
 &HT;    EDs: For locator map purposes, Marcovia is a village a few miles
from the Gulf of Fonseca on the Pacific coast.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Oct. 23 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARCOVIA, Honduras _ Maritza Espinar spent four terrifying days
clinging to the high branches of a tree last year after Hurricane
Mitch flattened her home in a village near here.
</P>
<P>
   When new floods in September sent a tributary of the Choluteca
River once again rising toward the place she lived, she didn't
waste any time evacuating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get scared now when I see even a little bit of high water,''
said the soft-spoken mother of seven, who was plucked by a
helicopter from her tree-top perch after Mitch. ``It's something
you can never erase from your mind. I never thought I would make it
out alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Such stories are not uncommon around this poor, mountainous
nation of 5 million. Mitch was the worst disaster in more than a
century, killing some 9,000 people and leveling or damaging more
than 50,000 homes. Floodwaters severed roads, destroyed bridges and
wiped out crops _ bananas, sugar, cantaloupes and pond-raised
shrimp _ that provide employment for much of the rural population.
</P>
<P>
   The people of this Central American region had hoped that by
now, a year after Mitch blew ashore on Oct. 25, the storm would be
nothing more than a frightful memory.
</P>
<P>
   But the recent floods are evidence that Mitch is still having an
impact.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, raging waters have knocked down bridges,
washed out roads, toppled houses and killed more than 20 people in
Honduras, El Salvador, Nicaragua and Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   The disturbing fact is that the new floods have come not from a
hurricane, but from the normal rains that fall every year during
the wet season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still so much debris and sediment in the riverbeds
from Mitch that it doesn't take as much water as before to come
over the banks,'' said Phil Gelman, coordinator of emergency
services for Atlanta-based CARE, one of many international aid
groups here. ``The new floods have been very damaging
psychologically. People had just begun putting some distance
between themselves and Mitch, and now some of them are finding
themselves flooded out for the second time in a year.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, aid groups are pushing a program to help identify
and protect watersheds _ an idea backed by the Honduran government.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch's floods were exacerbated because much of the country has
been deforested by timber companies and people cutting wood for
fuel. Protecting upland areas will prevent erosion and lessen the
impact of future floods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mitch has made us aware of these things,'' said Moises
Starkman, head of the Honduran government's recovery efforts.
``Still, none of this can be done overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the new floods are fresh proof that a full recovery from
Mitch will take years. While many areas _ including the Caribbean
resorts that cater to foreign tourists _ are back to normal,
Mitch's damage was so severe that officials had to draw up a new
map of Honduras, showing the new river channels left by the floods.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 40,000 people are still without permanent housing,
with 13,000 living in temporary shelters set up by the government
and relief organizations, according to Honduran officials. The rest
are crowded in with friends or relatives.
</P>
<P>
   While main roads have been passable for months, there are dozens
of temporary bridges and countless hastily-repaired wash-outs on
dangerous, winding mountain highways that remain vulnerable to new
flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign governments have pledged $2.7 billion in aid to
Honduras, with much of that intended for infrastructure like roads
and bridges. In most cases the work hasn't yet begun because the
process of obtaining funds and drawing up plans is only now being
completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The permanent repairs on the bridges and roads will begin
soon,'' Starkman said. ``The good news is that we have been moving
forward on housing and sanitation. There were predictions that
after Mitch we would have widespread famine and outbreaks of
disease, and we managed to avoid that. What we have now is not
paradise, but it's much better than before.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of international aid groups _ including CARE, Ox-Fam and
the Red Cross _ have pitched in, building hundreds of new homes.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, the poor are receiving better-built houses than
they've ever known _ usually small, cement-block structures of a
few hundred square feet with tin roofs and no electricity or
in-door plumbing. But for people who lived in dirt-floor adobe
huts, the improvement is dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our house was taken by the river, along with everything we
owned,'' said Nettie Roosevelt, 17, who recently moved to a new
house in a community being funded by CARE. ``This new house is very
nice. Our old one was rented and it leaked every time it rained.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Marcovia, several international relief agencies are
building an entire new town, relocating people from six rural
villages that were flooded. The municipal government helped obtain
land on high ground, and local sugar growers provided machinery to
clear roads and truck in materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we told the people they would have to build the houses
themselves, many of them sat down and cried,'' said Carolina
Gamero, an architect who, working with CARE, designed the new town
and has overseen its construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had never done construction before, but they learned,''
Gamero said. ``At first many people were reluctant to say they
wanted to move here. But now that the houses are up, I get new
people every day saying they want to move here.''
</P>
<P>
   She wanted to wait until the town's sewer and water systems were
complete before moving the residents in, but the recent floods
created a new emergency. Temporary latrines have been set up, and
water is being trucked in.
</P>
<P>
   With the construction site suddenly transformed into a town, aid
workers are facing new challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building the houses was the easy part,'' Gamero said. ``What
we have to do now is get the residents to make it a community.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents are being asked to set up committees to plan how they
will deal with sanitation, rubbish disposal, employment and other
issues. Many lived in rural isolation previously, and now must
adjust to being in close quarters with neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one man say he had never used a latrine before,'' Gamero
said, ``and ask why should he start using one now.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
