r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV24-C     10-21 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: BERLIN UNDERGOES RADICAL CHANGE
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Oct. 24.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ It has been noted that a third of the world's
construction cranes are now at work in Shanghai. If that's so,
Berlin must be running a close second as the Germans strive to
restore some stately Prussian grandeur to their reclaimed capital,
along with a fresh topping of high-tech gloss.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, the German parliament voted, 337 to 320, to
move from Bonn, its snug postwar seat by the Rhine, back into the
historic Reichstag in the heart of town. The British architect,
Norman Foster, left in place some of the Red Army's graffiti from
1945 while raising an airy ceiling that invokes the next century.
</P>
<P>
   As seen from the newly opened dome, bright yellow cranes rise
high above the scarred earth in virtually all directions _ but
mainly to the east, where the Wall came tumbling down on the
bankrupt Communist regime a decade ago. Huge water-bearing steel
pipes, painted in pastel shades, line the building sites to bar
them from being flooded by Berlin's porous soil.
</P>
<P>
   As in the legendary era of Marlene Dietrich after World War I,
Berlin has emerged once more as a lively metropolis. The government
has already spent some $17 billion on official construction
projects. Outlays for private developments are eight times as much.
Fully a tenth of the city's 1.1 million workers are engaged in the
rebuilding process.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike London or Paris, Berlin seems to have been wrenched from
the sandy soil by some random force. There are no mighty rivers or
harbors here, nor any natural wealth. But even if Berlin's 3.5
million residents ``play in the second league,'' as one official
here put it, Germany, the top power in Europe, has made a clear
commitment to Berlin of the kind never extended to Bonn.
</P>
<P>
   That's because before World War II, Berlin served not only as
the political seat of government, as it does once more today, but
also as the core of the nation's economic, industrial, and military
life. Amid the Cold War, as a divided Germany rose from the ruins
imposed on the Nazis, the Western part opted for a decentralized,
federated structure.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the powerful Bundesbank, or central bank, was placed not
in Bonn but in Frankfurt. Similarly, the Federal Constitutional
Court, the supreme judicial arbiter, met in Karlsruhe, while the
Federal Crime Agency, the German counterpart of the FBI, sat in
Wiesbaden.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Hamburg emerged as the editorial headquarters for many
national news outlets, while vital national cultural institutions
arose in such cities as Munich, the Bavarian capital, and
Dusseldorf.
</P>
<P>
   Not all goes well, however, as consolidation proceeds at a rapid
pace. The U.S. State Department remains in a stew over Berlin's
refusal to shift two streets near the Brandenburg Gate by nearly
100 feet. Without such a move, says American ambassador John
Kornblum, security concerns won't make it possible to build a new
embassy in the now open field where it last stood in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Kornblum: ``The overall German view of things is, 'We have
a way of life here. We would like to find a way to deal with the
high-tech revolution and still preserve that way of life.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
