<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3795 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN24-CO     10-21 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: ``If It's Noon, We're In ... Where?''
 &HT;    (For release Oct. 24, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZURICH, Switzerland _ In the farcical 1969 film ``If It's
Tuesday, It Must Be Belgium,'' the principals _ tourists _ were
moving around Europe at a breakneck pace: something like Holland on
Sunday, France on Monday, and, on Tuesday, it must be Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   The premise wasn't quite far from wrong. The stereotypical
American tourist tends to rush through Europe, much as he would a
Taco Bell lunch. Maybe dashing from Frankfurt to Vienna and then on
to Budapest in just three days is a bit much, but sometimes there
is little reason to stay any longer.
</P>
<P>
   I am reminded of a classic Art Buchwald column from his Paris
days. In it, he wrote that only three things are worth seeing in
the Louvre: Venus de Milo, the Winged Victory, and the Mona Lisa.
``Everything else is junk,'' he asserted.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, he continued, there grew a competition to see how
fast one could whiz through the Louvre to gaze upon those three
objects. Thus was born ``The Six-Minute Louvre,'' a feat Buchwald
says was accomplished by an American student sometime around 1950.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, a new entrance has been built to the Louvre
(a considerable hurdle) and new sections opened to further impede
the path. As a result, any improvement on the ``Six-Minute Louvre''
has become inconceivable.
</P>
<P>
   That was on my mind the other day when my wife and I zipped
through portions of this little country. Armed with a SwissRail
ticket that allows unlimited transportation on trains, boats, buses
and trams, it wasn't so much a case of ``If It's Tuesday, It Must
Be Belgium''; it was more like ``If It's 1 p.m., It Must Be
Interlaken.''
</P>
<P>
   After spending the night in Thun, we planned to take a boat ride
across Lake Thun to Interlaken. But when I arrived at the dock
shortly after 10 a.m., the boat already had left and another wasn't
due until two hours later. Too long to wait. So we walked across
the street and hopped a train _ not to Interlaken but to Bern,
about 25 minutes away.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday in Bern is not an exciting time but we managed to find
open an art museum featuring Swiss artist Paul Klee. It was not an
extensive collection so the Kunstmuseum, three blocks from the
train station, was behind us in less than 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the Bern train station, and it approaching the
lunch hour, we were off again _ this time to Interlaken for still
another quick zip. (This can easily be done in Interlaken, as it
offers the careening tourist little more than souvenir shops.)
Lunch was a 30-minute exercise and we were back on the train to
Thun where we rushed to a nearby museum that was showing the work
of Japanese modern artists _ a huge cardboard shed on blocks; a
bunch of candles on the floor _ before spending time watching swans
on the Aare River in front of our hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The day was beginning to be a blur to us, much as it must have
been when that young man raced past Winged Victory in search of the
Mona Lisa. But what straightened our senses was when we inquired
about the prix fixe dinner being offered by our hotel. The maitre
d' informed us we had a choice of veal kidneys, venison or
``pferdefleish,'' which translates to horse meat!
</P>
<P>
   As so we were afoot again. If it's 8 p.m., it must be dinner
time but, hopefully, not at any place serving up horse meat. This
was not a restriction easily met. Ultimately, we found a place
that, while offering up a dish called ``Mustang-Teller'' _
translates on the menu as ``air-dried horse meat'' _ there were
significant other choices. And, besides, we just wanted to sit
down.
</P>
<P>
   It was a somewhat exhausting day and I'm certain others have
whizzed through myriad Swiss cities in equal or less time, but we
felt we had accomplished something.
</P>
<P>
   What that is, I do not know.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
