<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3803 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-MILNER22-COX     10-21 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MILNER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mysteries by Grimes, Hillerman feature quirky, fun plots
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Please don't tell my lovely wife, but I fear I've fallen in love
with Martha Grimes, author of the Richard Jury mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   I've never met Ms. Grimes, but I've read 10 of her novels
featuring Scotland Yard Superintendent Jury and his eccentric crew
of friends. Funny thing is _ one of many funny thins _ Ms. Grimes'
stories are set mostly in jolly ol' England and named for English
pubs, but Ms. Grimes herself is American and lives in Washington,
D.C, and Santa Fe, New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow that makes sense, the improbability of it, once you've
read a couple of her books. She tells her stories with the
quizzicalness of an outsider who is, somehow, yet an insider.
</P>
<P>
   In the one I just finished reading _ ``Stargazey,'' named, as
usual, for an English pub _ Jury and his pal, and sometimes
unofficial assistant on murder cases, Melrose Plant, investigate
the murder of a woman who at first seems to be the woman Jury saw
on a double-decker London bus. It turns out to be someone else, but
she is found wearing a sable coat like the woman Jury saw was
wearing.
</P>
<P>
   I realize the above effort to summarize the outset of this
Grimes mystery is no doubt confusing, but what can I say? That's
the way it begins. It isn't the confusing situations, or unusual
situations, that have caused me to fall for Ms. Grimes. That has
grown from reading her books and involving myself in her characters
and unique humor.
</P>
<P>
   I must point out that, although her stories are, indeed,
``murder mysteries,'' they are never gory or filled with details
that cause the reader to grimace from distaste. As in the stories
of, say, Agatha Christie and that ilk, the fun is in trying to
solve the mysteries rather than ride a roller coaster emotionally.
But these are very up-to-date, hip stories and atmospheres, both in
time and attitude, and much funnier than Ms. Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   I knew it would be difficult to explain the reasons I have
fallen for Ms. Grimes and her stories, and it is. It defies my
ability to express myself. You'll just have to try one or two
yourself and see if you don't find that her stories make you
chuckle from cover to cover as you wrestle with the puzzles she
presents.
</P>
<P>
   Another series author whose books always make me grab them from
the library and paperback shelves is Tony Hillerman, the writer who
once taught journalism at the University of New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Hillerman's books almost always feature the adventures of Navajo
Tribal policeman Jim Chee and his now retired boss Joe Leaphorn. In
the earlier stories, Leaphorn has not yet retired and the tension
between these two extremely intelligent and intuitive rural cops is
a large part of each story's suspense. Chee, the younger, is as
stubborn as his boss and they clash silently from start to finish.
A large part of the conflict is complicated by the high respect
each stubborn man has for the other.
</P>
<P>
   Hillerman's widespread popularity has put his books in most
bookstores as a paperback, and at all libraries in hardback. I
sometimes run across one I had somehow skipped and I am always glad
to discover it because it gives me another good one to get into.
Hillerman has written a couple of novels that do not involve his
Navajo heroes. One I recommend is ``A Fly on the Wall,'' which is
about newspaper reporters and their trials and tribulations in
covering crime and politics. Although it was written some time ago,
the current U.S. political condition makes it timely, except the
fact that nowadays reporters rarely use typewriters, which may seem
ancient to some, but bring back pleasant memories to others.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
