<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another tough loss
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ It's October, and my heart has been broken
once again. The Red Sox lost to the Yankees in the league
Championship Series. Once again, they're home for Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   Being a Red Sox fan teaches one the true meaning of that
hackneyed phrase, ``the agony of defeat.'' Sure, there are other
teams with long losing legacies: the Chicago Cubs and the Cleveland
Indians come to mind, and both the Astros and the Rangers are vying
to become the playoff pansies of the new millennium. I will match
my pain against fans of those teams anytime, because the Sox have
actually managed to get to the World Series three times in my life:
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1967, as I watched in the Allenstown, N.H., elementary
school cafeteria along with the entire school, the ``Impossible
Dream'' team, led by Carl Yastrzemski and Rico Petrocelli along
with Cy Young award-winning pitcher Jim Lonborg, made it to the
October Classic _ only to lose in seven games to the Cardinals and
fastballer Bob Gibson. It was the first time the team had made it
to the series since 1946, an event deemed momentous enough to
warrant school-wide viewing of the game. Of course, it was an
awfully small school. My seventh grade had 12 people in it.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1975, as I watched on a black-and-white TV in our tiny
duplex on Mitchell Street in Nacogdoches, Carlton Fisk frantically
waved his long ball fair to give the Red Sox the win in
</P>
<P>
   Game 6 of their Series against the Cincinatti Reds. The Reds won
Game 7, and I haven't liked Pete Rose or Johnny Bench since.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1986, I watched from my weekly newspaper office in San
Augustine, deep in the woods of East Texas, as Bill Buckner let a
ground ball roll through his legs that my grandmother could have
fielded cleanly, and the Mets won Game 6 and then Game 7 to take
the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's 1999. Their loss to those damn Yankees means the
century likely will end without them having another World
Championship. They have only more chance, next fall in 2000. The
Red Sox have not won a World Series since Babe Ruth was pitching
for them and Woodrow Wilson was president _ 1918 to be exact.
They're 0-for-5 in the Series in the past 80 years. Four
generations of my French-Canadian family have waited futilely for
the Red Sox to win the World Series. We're still waiting.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox did better than I thought they would, eternal pessimist
that I am. Ace reliever Tom Gordon, who achieved a certain
immortality when Stephen King earlier this year wrote a book called
``The Girl Who Loved Tom Gordon,'' went down for the season with a
bum arm. Batting title champ Nomar Garciaparra went on the disabled
list, and Brett Saberhagen, a previous Cy Young winner, is a shadow
of his fomer self.
</P>
<P>
   But then there's Pedro Martinez, with his preternaturally long
fingers, who went 23-4. Then the Sox swept the Yankees in New York
in August during the regular season. Hope floats.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians, the Sox's first playoff opponent, quickly
dashed those hopes by winning the first two games of the
best-of-five series, and I went into my ``Wait 'til next year''
mode. A man could have made a pile in Las Vegas taking the Sox to
win the next three by scoring 44 runs against what is arguably the
most-solid team in the majors, to advance to the next level and
play the Yankees. Of course, they didn't last long _ out in five
games _ bumbling balls, leaving a few dozen stranded, and being
victimized by some of the worst calls made by umpires I've ever
seen.
</P>
<P>
   I take back what I've said about the Aggies. Truth be known, I
root for the Aggies if they get to a bowl game and aren't playing
Texas. I'm not sure I would root for the Yankees if they were
playing the Iraqi Olympic team. The Yankees stole Babe Ruth,
beginning an eight-decade tradition of the Red Sox trading their
best players to their most-hated rivals. More recently, the Yankees
traded for Wade Boggs, a lock for the Hall of Fame, and now Roger
Clemens, a fellow UT grad who spent two seasons in Toronto before
arriving in the Big Apple. I will be rooting for Atlanta in the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are a hard team to keep the faith in, sort of like
trying to love a philandering husband who can't keep a job, but I
have managed to do so, though it will be sorely tested when Fenway
Park is torn down, sometime in the near future. There are few
better places to be on a cool summer night than Fenway. If the
baseball gods are listening, maybe they'll grant us gray-headed
fans one last World Series in the shadow of the Green Monster.
</P>
<P>
   But don't bet on it.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
