<HEADER>
A3807 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TAYEDIGGS22-COX     10-21 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAYEDIGGS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For actor Diggs, `Best' roles are those that inspire
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Taye Diggs is showing the effects of a long night in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   It's not in the 28-year-old actor's clean-cut look. He could be
an ad for Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch: the smooth, bright green shirt
topping a deep-blue, long-sleeved pullover, the perfectly pressed
tan carpenter pants (the long legs pulled up into nearly
4-inch-high cuffs), the unscuffed coal-black Doc Martens. They
easily help mask all the late-night partying.
</P>
<P>
   It's in his voice where reality creeps through. Didn't he get
any sleep?
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure enough didn't,'' he admits, the words coming slowly as
he sits on a couch in a downtown Ritz-Carlton Hotel suite, hugging
two small accent pillows while talking.
</P>
<P>
   In his first trip to Atlanta recently, Diggs spent most of the
night on the town. The Atlanta Fish Market. A bar or two. Drinks.
Music. The clock struck 3 a.m. _ or, really, sometime after. His
wake-up call came at 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know the name of where we went,'' Diggs confides.
``It was a little bar that played a little music and we had a
couple of drinks. It's a nice town. I'd love to come back. No, I
definitely want to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Diggs is here to talk about ``The Best Man,'' his new movie
written and directed by Malcolm D. Lee, cousin of Spike Lee,
opening Friday in metro Atlanta and across the country.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Best Man'' in a nutshell: Diggs plays Harper Stewart, a
young writer who reunites with his old college friends for a
wedding, considers rekindling a relationship with his former flame
(Nia Long) and, through his latest book, reveals intimacies that
set his friends reeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look for things that inspire me, that's got great images,''
Diggs says. ``And especially if it's working with great actors and
great directors. This is it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Speaking of images: Diggs was already known for his infamous
butt shot in ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back.'' In this summer's
``The Wood,'' one scene displayed his chiseled abs. In ``The Best
Man,'' the camera pans slowly up his body as Diggs reclines in a
bathtub full of floating rose petals. Co-star Sanaa Lathan takes
one petal and strokes his chest. At a recent early screening in
Atlanta, the scene made several female moviegoers gasp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't lie to you. I go to the gym,'' Diggs says. ``I'm aware
of what you need to be to survive in Hollywood. I'm vain. I take
pride in the way I look. It's all part of the game. And I haven't
reached the point where it's gotten in the way of pure acting.''
</P>
<P>
   _ One of his favorite ``Best Man'' scenes: Diggs, Morris
Chestnut, Harold Perrineau and Terrence Howard do some male bonding
while playing cards. Things unravel after the subject of fidelity
comes up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was intense,'' he says. ``We ran the gamut of emotions. We
were like guffawing on the floor and other times were were really
kind of frightened because Morris' intensity was something none of
us were expecting. None of that was scripted where he knocks over
the table and grabs Terrence. He got up and the table was flying
and there go the beer cans and chips and money.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Acting with ghosts in the remake of ``The House on Haunted
Hill,'' opening Oct. 29: ``It was like me and (actress) Ali Larter
acting against ourselves,'' he says. ``We were running and being
chased by this horrible, monstrous thing _ a manifestation of evil
_ that was added in later with a computer. You have to use your
imagination. A lot of times we were just screaming.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The career: In addition to ``Haunted Hill,'' Diggs will
co-star with James Caan and Benicio Del Toro in next year's crime
thriller ``Way of the Gun.'' Previous movies include this year's
``Go,'' ``Mary Jane's Last Dance'' and ``The Wood.'' He co-starred
opposite Angela Bassett in 1998's ``How Stella Got Her Groove
Back.'' On TV, he played Adrian ``Sugar'' Hill on ``The Guiding
Light'' and had guest appearances on ``Law &AMP; Order'' and ``New York
Undercover.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The vital stats: Height: 5'8''. State of birth: New Jersey.
Where he grew up: Rochester, N.Y. Siblings: He's the oldest of five
(two brothers are musicians, one sister is a dancer and another
sister is studying to be a veterinarian). School: Graduated with a
bachelor's degree in musical theater from Syracuse University.
Showbiz start: Was a member of the ensemble cast in Broadway's
revival of ``Carousel.'' Also on stage: played Benny, the evil
landlord in ``Rent.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The daily ab workout: ``It's a general going to the gym and
working out your whole body kind of thing. Reps vary by day.
Sometimes it's machines. I'm a dancer so sometimes it's dance
class. I really work on the lower regions. A lot of it is genetics
_ I thank my mom and dad. I do just the amount I need to do so I
can scrape by.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Why abs aren't really his obsession: ``I'll eat a cupcake as
soon as the next guy. You look in the mirror and you go, 'Well,
that's fine.' I'm not some crazy fanatic that's like every day, I
gotta work out. I do read those magazines. 'What Brad Pitt Does To
Keep In Shape.' It's interesting.
</P>
<P>
   _ The role not taken: ``I won't say the movie, but my agent
wanted me to do this really big budget action movie,'' he says.
``And I was going to get a lot of money to do it. My team is very
well aware that I always want to take care of my family and am
looking for ways to support them. So this opportunity came into my
lap. But I read the script for 'The Best Man' and needless to say
the writing for the action-adventure was nowhere near the writing
for 'Best Man.' So, uh, something in my heart told me to do what I
would have more fun doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
