<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3808 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN22-COX     10-21 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sweets lure public schools into private hands
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ One perusing the wires couldn't pass up this entry
from the Independent of London: ``The Whoring of American
Education.''
</P>
<P>
   It focused on an increasingly common presence in American
schools: corporate advertising. Businesses and products are getting
unlimited access to schools for the right price.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A is the increasingly popular notion of selling
multimillion-dollar exclusive vending contracts to companies like
Pepsi or Coke, or essential advertising packages to corporations to
kick in for athletic structures or other hard goods.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit B is Channel One, which delivers a morning news
broadcast to 8 million schoolchildren daily, including two minutes
each day of advertising, which helps pay for the free TVs and
satellite dishes schools get.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, the Independent didn't get around to Exhibit C, which
is the most glaring example of corporate encroachment: whole
schools being contracted to private companies.
</P>
<P>
   This is most prevalently modeled by the Edison Project, a
private firm which manages 51 schools in 12 states.
</P>
<P>
   Not coincidentally, Channel One and the Edison Project were
founded by the same entrepreneur, Chris Whittle. He knows erogenous
zones.
</P>
<P>
   Don't titillate with chocolates. Bring TVs. Don't bring flowers.
Bring computers, in the case of the Edison Project. And watch the
doors open to you.
</P>
<P>
   That would appear to be the case with the Dallas Independent
School District, where new Superintendent Bill Rojas proposes
contracting with the Edison Project to run up to 10 schools. Rojas,
former school superintendent in San Francisco, contracted with
Edison to run an elementary school there.
</P>
<P>
   The success of privatized schools is decidedly mixed, as is the
case with all of the ``wonder drugs'' for education, including
charter schools and vouchers. The major inducement Edison offers
school districts is computers _ home computers for students and
laptops for teachers. Edison also offers classroom phones for
teachers to be in better contact with parents.
</P>
<P>
   This provides an irresistible lure. Teachers groups in Dallas
see their schools underfunded. Understandably and rightfully, they
are suspicious of privatizing schools. But leaders admit it's hard
to resist the candy offered by these strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Taste-tempting gadgets aside, Edison appears to do nothing that
public schools couldn't already do. Supporters say one reason
Edison succeeds is longer school days and longer school years _ 20
more school days on average. But no Texas school district is
prohibited from lengthening classroom time if it thinks that's the
miracle cure.
</P>
<P>
   Note to subscribers: Edison, which has been in existence for
eight years, has yet to make a profit. That's understandable based
on the pricey inducements it offers to get its foot in the door.
Some day Edison will have to make money or it will cease to exist.
</P>
<P>
   But public schools will remain. The notion of turning to a
private company to run our schools presumes that we as a people
cannot find the will to invest properly in them, that we must find
venture capitalists to do it.
</P>
<P>
   The Independent is alarmed by the wrong commercial venture.
</P>
<P>
   Exclusive contracts with Pepsi or Coke are hardly a problem if
they'll help pay for stuff like stadiums and band uniforms. But
signing exclusive contracts with Acme Bros. Educational Concepts to
run our public schools is a troubling one.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, how can educators resist when their communities
can't find the will to act responsibly on public schools' behalf?
</P>
<P>
   So, nice candy. Nice big car. Hop in, children.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
