<P>
   These columns for release Friday, October 22, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   WOOTEN-COLUMN _ If you long for unrestrained power in a
democracy, here's the secret formula. (Wooten, Atlanta Journal).
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-GUNS _ Gun enthusiasts and control advocate should at
least agree to do everything possible to end the toll guns are
taking on our children. (Head, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-HELMS _ Sen. Jesse Helms is at it again,
single-handedly gumming up the works of America's foreign policy
machinery. (Atlanta Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ YAZOO CITY, Miss. _ I was looking for
memorials to the writer Willie Morris in the town of his birth.
Yazoo City has ``My Dog Skip'' tours that visit the sites that
Willie Morris wrote about. His cemetery plot is an attraction
itself, buried as he is just 13 steps from the Witch's Grave, the
occupant of which, local legend says, used her black magic to burn
down the town. No reason not to think that eventually he'll be
right up there with Jerry Clower, the country comedian, Yazoo
City's other famous son who died this past year. (Murray, Cox News
Service). MOVED. WEDNESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   EMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ This e-mail from a friend, who
couldn't wait for the bright lights and big city, offers her list
of ways to know if you might be from a small town. (Ernest Murray
is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ It's October, and my heart
has been broken once again. The Red Sox lost to the Yankees in the
league Championship Series. Once again, they're home for Halloween.
Being a Red Sox fan teaches one the true meaning of that hackneyed
phrase, ``the agony of defeat.'' (Gary Borders is editor and
publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel.) MOVED. EMBARGOED for
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Exclusive contracts with Pepsi or
Coke are hardly a problem if they'll help pay for stuff like
stadiums and band uniforms. But signing exclusive contracts with
Acme Bros. Educational Concepts to run our public schools is a
troubling one. (John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
