<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   BED-AND-BREAKFAST _ CLEARWATER, Fla. _ ``Now, how would you like
your eggs?'' Eggs? The guests at the Green Gables' table had not
considered such a thing. Already there had been warm banana
muffins, bagels and cream cheese, fruit cups with fresh peaches and
blueberries, whole grain toast, honey and marmalade, yogurt and
cereal, a coffee pot with contents that would delight Colombian
aristocracy. Lanning runs her three-bedroom inn, Clearwater's only
bed-and-breakfast, with maternal devotion. Those who come to the
Green Gables are obliged to surrender to it. Well, most do, anyway.
(Moffett, Palm Beach Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-PICKETTS-MILL _ PICKETT'S MILL, Ga. _ In this leafy
corner of north Georgia, on the fringes of the city men died to
capture and defend in 1864, lies what is probably the single most
unspoiled, most authentic, most evocatively pristine battlefield in
the whole long, fiery struggle during the ``War Of the Rebellion,''
as the victorious North called it. Among Civil War enthusiasts,
Pickett's Mill is unique. It is, in its way, perfect. ``I'm wary of
using the word most or best, but Pickett's Mill is probably the
best-preserved small battlefield for 1864-65, when the soldiers
marched with one hand on the rifle and the other hand on the
shovel,'' said Edwin Bearss, historian emeritus for the National
Park Service and one of the authorities of Civil War
studies.(Browning, Palm Beach Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ Falling leaves, fallen heroes. An autumn driving tour
along Georgia's Blue and Gray Trail _ a series of stops related to
Civil War battles in the the northwest portion of the state from
Chattanooga/Chickamauga to Pickett's Mill/Kennesaw Mountain. With
listing of fall events in the area. (Davis, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 40. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the current week.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 1019 -- For any hike into the Black Canyon of the
Gunnison National Monument in Colorado, you must get a backcountry
permit. That's so park rangers can keep track of who goes in. A
pamphlet on hiking the inner canyon offers this chipper bit of
advice: ``Hikers are expected to find their own way and be prepared
for self-rescue.'' (Abramson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art
includes 5-column color photo of canyon and 2-column color photo of
author catching a fish.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: DESTINATIONS -- Thermopolis, Wyo., offers the twin
benefits of a relaxing place to rest your body and a fascinating
place to study history. (McCarthy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL TIPS -- The Internet is a place where con artists prey on
naive vacationers. (Geewax, Cox Washington Bureau)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TAYEDIGGS _ Interview with Taye Diggs, 28, who stars in the new
comedy/drama ``The Best Man'' about friends who occassionally flash
back to college years before one of the pals gets married. It's a
far different film from this summer's ``The Wood'' (also starring
Diggs). ``Best Man'' is sort of ``My Best Friend's Wedding'' with a
distinct gender-switch. Diggs, earlier seen in ``How Stella Got Her
Groove Back,'' has been in Atlanta promoting the film with director
Malcolm Lee (cousin of Spike Lee). Diggs will star later this month
in the new horror remake of ``The House on Haunted Hill.''
(Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAIN PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet ENTERTAIN page for the current week.
This layout is available today after 2 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAINMENT 1022 _ Like the old ``Saturday Night Live''
skit starring John Belushi as the sword-wielding clerk in the
Samurai Hotel, the `bad kung fu movie' motif has lured viewers to
the Food Network show ``Iron Chef. '' (Kalijian, Palm Beach Post)
Art includes a 4-column color photo from ``Iron Chef,'' a 1-column
B&AMP;W photo of John Belushi playing the ``Samurai Chef,'' and a
2-column graphic color headline treatment.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO REVIEWS _ ``Election'' is a high school satire infused
with precise anthropological observation _ a combination that can
make you both giggle and wince. Also reviews of ``Life,'' and
``eXistenZ.'' (Staff, Cox News Service) Art includes an 18-pica
color photo from ``Election.''
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEWS _ Sting's latest album further establishes the singer
as a pop demigod emeritus, a once-major figure who has happily hit
midcareer autopilot. Also reviews of new CD releases from the
soundtrack of ``The Best Man,'' and Michael Fredo. (Staff, Cox News
Service) Art includes a 6-pica color mug of Sting.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY _ There are so many good shows on network TV, my four
VCRs are working overtime. I can't remember a season when there
were so many choices on so many nights. (Thompson, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet Books page for the current week.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 1019 -- Biographies or weighty missives on social
and international issues have long been a part of campaign
strategy. That said, John McCain's ``Faith of My Fathers'' does
much more than accomplish its political goal of helping a candidate
win attention. (Crowley, Palm Beach Post) Art includes 3-column
color photo of John McCain and 6-pica color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW PLAINSONG -- Kent Haruf's ``Plainsong'' weaves
together the voices of half a dozen people living in a small
Colorado town and turns their overlapping stories into a powerful
portrait of a community bound together by history, memory and the
simple bonds of neighborly responsibility and affection. (Kakutani,
N.Y. Times News Service) Art includes 6-pica color photo of book
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW FISHING -- ``A jerk on one end of a line waiting
for a jerk on the other,'' is the classic folk definition of
fishing that explains the title of Robert Hughes' witty testimonial
to the sport, ``A Jerk on One End: Reflections of a Mediocre
Fisherman.'' (Lehmann-Haupt, N.Y. Times News Service) Art includes
6-pica color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PROFILE FALUDI -- In her new book, ``Stiffed: The Betrayal
of the American Man,'' Susan Faludi says feminism was never a
separatist movement but rather a challenge to a social structure
that makes underdogs of ordinary people, men as well as women.
(Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 2-column color
photo of author Susan Faludi.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS -- It's not every day that star power is
given to a philosopher, but the spotlight on this occasion was
Jacques Derrida, pied piper of literary criticism for 20 years or
more. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 1-column
color photo of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ There is something weasly about the two words:
``journalistic'' and ``academic.'' As everyday adjectives, they
serve most frequently as slurs and slights. Yet they imply settled
habits of mind and standards of judgment. They mark off mutually
inhospitable spheres of influence, a strange thing when you
consider their incestuous ancestry. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 24.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, OCT. 24
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-BASQUE _ Review of Mark Kurlansky's ``The Basque History
of the World.'' (Brock, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 28.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, OCT. 24
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-NASLUND _ Sena Jeter Naslund was listening to a tape of
``Moby-Dick'' while driving with her daughter when it occurred to
her that two of the greatest American novels _ Melville's classic
and Mark Twain's ``Huckleberry Finn'' _ had almost no women in
them. The Birmingham native has rectified that with her
critically-acclaimed new novel, ``Ahab's Wife.'' We talk to Naslund
about how her re-creation of 19th century life and the roles women
_ real and fictional _ played. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Syndicated columnist P.S. Wall has been called a
female Dave Barry and Erma Bombeck with an attitude. Now Wall has
published her second book of essays, ``If I Were a Man, I'd Marry
Me,'' in which she muses about overweight cats, Elvis and $1500
Italian stilettos... Former Atlantan Michael Haskell has won a
$35,000 Whiting Foundation Award for poetry . . . ``Delirium of the
Brave,'' Savannah author William Harris' novel about murder and
politics in Savannah, is now out in a new hardback edition from St.
Martin's Press. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-AUTHORS _ A chat with two very popular children's authors:
R.L. Stine, best-known for his scary Goosebumps series, and Jon
Scieszka, best-known for putting a new spin on classic tales (The
True Story of the 3 Little Pigs and The Stinky Cheese Man and other
Fairly Stupid Tales). (Dayton, Daily News). 23.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-MILNER _ Jay Milner's review of a recently released book.
(Milner, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE NEWS AND REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-BESTMAN _ Review of ``The Best Man'' starring Taye Diggs
in a wedding story that in part flashes back to college
friendships. It's a comedy that makes a satisfying date movie.
Grade: B. (Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-DEAD _ ``Bringing out the Dead'' stars Nicolas Cage and
Ving Rhaymes. From director Martin Scorsese and screenwriter Paul
Schrader. (StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SODERBERGH _ Interview with Atlanta-born Steven Soderbergh,
whose new crime movie ``The Limey'' uses some of the same
interesting techniques from the popular ``Out of Sight.'' The
director also talks about Julia Roberts' next film. (StMurray,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 23.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, OCT. 24.
</P>
