<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 1019 -- Biographies or weighty missives on social
and international issues have long been a part of campaign
strategy. That said, John McCain's ``Faith of My Fathers'' does
much more than accomplish its political goal of helping a candidate
win attention. (Crowley, Palm Beach Post) Art includes 3-column
color photo of John McCain and 6-pica color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW PLAINSONG -- Kent Haruf's ``Plainsong'' weaves
together the voices of half a dozen people living in a small
Colorado town and turns their overlapping stories into a powerful
portrait of a community bound together by history, memory and the
simple bonds of neighborly responsibility and affection. (Kakutani,
N.Y. Times News Service) Art includes 6-pica color photo of book
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW FISHING -- ``A jerk on one end of a line waiting
for a jerk on the other,'' is the classic folk definition of
fishing that explains the title of Robert Hughes' witty testimonial
to the sport, ``A Jerk on One End: Reflections of a Mediocre
Fisherman.'' (Lehmann-Haupt, N.Y. Times News Service) Art includes
6-pica color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PROFILE FALUDI -- In her new book, ``Stiffed: The Betrayal
of the American Man,'' Susan Faludi says feminism was never a
separatist movement but rather a challenge to a social structure
that makes underdogs of ordinary people, men as well as women.
(Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 2-column color
photo of author Susan Faludi.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS -- It's not every day that star power is
given to a philosopher, but the spotlight on this occasion was
Jacques Derrida, pied piper of literary criticism for 20 years or
more. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 1-column
color photo of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ There is something weasly about the two words:
``journalistic'' and ``academic.'' As everyday adjectives, they
serve most frequently as slurs and slights. Yet they imply settled
habits of mind and standards of judgment. They mark off mutually
inhospitable spheres of influence, a strange thing when you
consider their incestuous ancestry. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 24.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, OCT. 24
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-BASQUE _ Review of Mark Kurlansky's ``The Basque History
of the World.'' (Brock, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 28.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, OCT. 24
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-NASLUND _ Sena Jeter Naslund was listening to a tape of
``Moby-Dick'' while driving with her daughter when it occurred to
her that two of the greatest American novels _ Melville's classic
and Mark Twain's ``Huckleberry Finn'' _ had almost no women in
them. The Birmingham native has rectified that with her
critically-acclaimed new novel, ``Ahab's Wife.'' We talk to Naslund
about how her re-creation of 19th century life and the roles women
_ real and fictional _ played. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Syndicated columnist P.S. Wall has been called a
female Dave Barry and Erma Bombeck with an attitude. Now Wall has
published her second book of essays, ``If I Were a Man, I'd Marry
Me,'' in which she muses about overweight cats, Elvis and $1500
Italian stilettos... Former Atlantan Michael Haskell has won a
$35,000 Whiting Foundation Award for poetry . . . ``Delirium of the
Brave,'' Savannah author William Harris' novel about murder and
politics in Savannah, is now out in a new hardback edition from St.
Martin's Press. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-AUTHORS _ A chat with two very popular children's authors:
R.L. Stine, best-known for his scary Goosebumps series, and Jon
Scieszka, best-known for putting a new spin on classic tales (The
True Story of the 3 Little Pigs and The Stinky Cheese Man and other
