<P>
   PUMPKIN-PUREE (Undated) _ If you want pumpkin puree, you can buy
a pumpkin, wash it, cut it in half, scrape out the seeds and
fibrous strings, place the halves in a roasting pan and bake for
about an hour at 325 degrees and then scrape the pulp out of the
shell. Or you can open a can. Chefs advise taking the easy way out.
By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALMON-FISHING (Albany, N.Y.) _ Every fall I buy a ticket to
dance with salmon. It is truly a dance we go to, although years ago
each of us learned painfully that a ticket never guarantees even
one partner. Every river offers a different symphony as background,
a blend of rushing currents and incessant winds. It is deliciously
lonely. By FRED LeBRUN.
</P>
<P>
   FISHING-GEAR (Albany, N.Y.) _ Strange happenings are commonplace
on a fishing stream, although few of them feature a reasonably
happy ending even for the fish, as this one does. By FRED LeBRUN.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-JETS (Oakland, Calif.) _ The only good break the Jets have
gotten this season is that the Yankees' and Mets' postseason runs
turned attention away from what has befallen a team that fell one
game short of the Super Bowl last season. But with the commencement
of the World Series, the Jets are just days away from becoming
headline fodder once again in New York. By MICHELLE SMITH.
</P>
<P>
   KNAPP-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Tonya Harding is back in figure
skating, which can only mean that fresh starts are now available to
all miscreant athletes. Let's see: Pete Rose as manager of the
first baseball franchise that moves to Las Vegas, Ryan Leaf as
chief executive officer for the Esalen Institute and Denny McLain
as Bill Bradley's running mate. By GWEN KNAPP
</P>
