<HEADER>
A3869 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-GORE-OFFSHORE-OIL-HNS     10-21 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-OFFSHORE-OIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE URGES BAN ON NEW OIL DRILLING IN CALIFORNIA, FLORIDA WATERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore, going beyond Clinton
administration policy on the environment, called Thursday for a
total ban on new oil drilling in federal waters off the coasts of
California and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said his proposal would enable a Gore administration to
make ``dramatic progress'' toward a cleaner environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The environment is much more than a policy position to me _ it
is a profoundly moral obligation,'' Gore said in remarks prepared
for delivery via satellite to environmentalists meeting in Los
Angeles. Gore spoke from Rye, N.H., during a campaign swing for his
2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have only one earth. And if we do not keep it healthy and
safe, every other gift we leave our children will be meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has imposed a 10-year extension of a
moratorium on leasing offshore oil tracts and a permanent ban on
leasing in national marine sanctuaries.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign position goes beyond this policy to halt ``all
new drilling'' in federal waters off California and Florida and to
prohibit drilling new wells in existing oil tract leases held by
oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will take the most sweeping steps in our history to protect
our oceans and coastal waters from offshore oil drilling,'' Gore
said. ``I will make sure that there is no new oil leasing off the
coast of California and Florida. ... I will do everything in my
power to make sure that there is no new drilling off these
sensitive coasts _ even in areas already leased for drilling by
previous administrations.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rubin, spokesman for the American Petroleum Institute, said
Gore's proposed ban would force American oil companies to shift
their new drilling abroad. This would make the United States more
dependent on foreign sources of oil and gas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line here is that because we are limited in our
access to federal lands, the companies are forced to spend their
exploration budgets overseas and this is going to simply further
that,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   A statement by Gore's campaign noted that the state of
California, led by Democratic Gov. Gray Davis, has raised concerns
about proposed new drilling off the coast. The Interior Department
has requested additional information from the oil companies
proposing new exploration.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Florida, led by Republican Gov. Jeb Bush, brother
of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a GOP candidate for president in
2000, has determined that proposed drilling off the Florida coast
``would be inconsistent with its coastal zone management plan,''
the Gore statement said. Chevron has appealed Florida's decision to
Commerce Secretary William Daley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am placing environmental protection at the very heart of my
campaign for the presidency,'' Gore said. ``I will have no higher
priority as president.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore faces a challenge from former Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.H., in
his bid to succeed Clinton as president. Gore's announcement may
help energize his natural constituency among environmentalists in
California, a key battleground with a presidential primary on March
7, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   A nationwide survey conducted for Cable News Network and USA
Today by the Gallup Poll that concluded on Oct. 10 showed Gore's
lead over Bradley shrinking to 12 percentage points, 51 percent to
39 percent. A survey in September showed Gore leading Bradley by 33
percentage points, 63 percent to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced a 10-year extension of the federal ban on new
oil and gas drilling off the nation's East and West coasts during a
visit to Monterey, Calif., on June 13, 1998. Clinton's compromise
position, seeking to balance environmental protection with the
economic interests of energy companies, disappointed some
environmental activists who had been seeking a permanent ban on oil
exploration.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., expressed disappointment at the
time. ``Our coastline deserves protection forever,'' said Boxer,
noting that Clinton's announcement moved the nation down ``the path
toward permanent protection.''
</P>
<P>
   The moratorium on new offshore drilling initially had been
imposed in 1990 by President George Bush, for 10 years ending in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
