<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUMPKIN-PUREE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANNED PUMPKIN MAKES BAKING AS EASY AS PIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ If you want pumpkin puree, you can buy a pumpkin,
wash it, cut it in half, scrape out the seeds and fiberous strings,
place the halves in a roasting pan and bake for about an hour at
325 degrees and then scrape the pulp out of the shell.
</P>
<P>
   Or, you can open a can.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs advise taking the easy way out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I'm a firm believer in using everything fresh, but
for the home cook, canned pumpkin isn't a bad product,'' says
Patrick Lofton, executive chef at Longfellows in Saratoga Springs.
</P>
<P>
   As long as you buy a quality name-brand, packed pumpkin, and as
long as the can is in good shape, the pumpkin should be just fine,
Lofton says.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Plummer, chef and owner of the Allegro Cafe in Troy, also
uses canned pumpkin, but he reads the labels carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I myself like to use the plain canned pumpkin,'' says Plummer,
``not the seasoned canned mix. I want to be responsible for doing
the seasonings. Use your own head to flavor it, the way you want it
to be flavored.''
</P>
<P>
   Other chefs suggest looking for cans labeled ``100 percent
pumpkin'' so you know that you're getting. Other than that, buying
pumpkin is as easy as, well, pie.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   PUMPKIN COBBLER
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 8 servings)
</P>
<P>
   Base:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsalted butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup whole milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Filling:
</P>
<P>
   1 (29-ounce) can pumpkin
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup whole milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup lightly packed dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   Topping:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup lightly packed dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   Scant 1/3 cup pecan halves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   Base: Heat oven to 350 degrees. Spray a 2-quart baking dish with
cooking spray. Pour the melted butter into the prepared dish. In a
small bowl, whisk the flour, milk, sugar, baking powder and salt.
Pour over the melted butter. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Filling: Whisk pumpkin, milk, cream, sugar and brown sugar in a
medium-size bowl. Whisk in the eggs, one at a time, blending well
after each addition. Stir in the spices. Pour the filling over the
base. Do not stir. The mixture will look mottled with the base
showing through here and there.
</P>
<P>
   Topping: Combine the brown sugar, pecans, flour and melted
butter in a small bowl. Scatter over the cobbler.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 45 minutes or until edges just begin to come away from the
pan. The center should be slightly wobbly. Serve warm the same day.
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``Bake it to the Limit'' by Dede Wilson (William Morrow,
1999)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   PUMPKIN NUT BREAD
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 1, 9-by-5-inch loaf)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour or 1 cup whole-wheat flour and 1 cup
all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh pumpkin puree or canned pumpkin
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar 1/2 cup skim milk
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 350 degrees. Grease a 9-by-5-inch loaf pan. Sift
together flour, baking powder, baking soda, cinnamon, salt and
nutmeg. In a large mixing bowl, combine pumpkin, sugar, milk and
eggs. Mix well. Add dry ingredients, oil and nuts, mixing until
moistened. Batter will be slightly lumpy.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon batter into prepared pan. Bake in center of oven for 65
minutes, or until a wooden pick inserted in center of loaf comes
out clean. Cool in pan 10 minutes. Use a knife to cut around the
edge of the bread to loosen from pan. Invert on a rack to cool.
Slice and serve.
</P>
<P>
   _ From the University of Illinois Extension
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   PUMPKIN PIE
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 2, 9-inch pies)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 (29-ounce) can pumpkin
</P>
<P>
   3 cups evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   2 unbaked 9-inch pie shells
</P>
<P>
   1 (12-ounce) package semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pint heavy cream Pecan halves
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 425 degrees. Combine sugar, salt, cinnamon, ginger
and cloves in a medium bowl. In a large bowl, beat eggs. Add
pumpkin and stir in flour mixture. Stir in evaporated milk. Pour
into pie shells.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 15 minutes. Lower oven temperature to 350 degrees and
bake 40 to 50 minutes, or until a knife inserted in the center
comes out clean. Cool on wire rack for 2 hours, chill thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   Place chocolate morsels in a large bowl. Heat cream in a small
saucepan until steaming but not boiling. Pour cream over chocolate
and let sit for about 30 seconds. Stir with a whisk until chocolate
is melted and blended with the cream.
</P>
<P>
   Divide chocolate evenly and pour half on top of each pie. Spread
over entire pie surface with the pack of a spoon, being careful not
to spread too thin. Decorate with pecans halves and chill, at least
2 hours, until serving.
</P>
<P>
   _ From Kraft
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3901 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-21 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOSE OF COMPETITION KEEPS LIVE OPERA ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ How often can I forget that times change and
``market forces'' dictate when and how?
</P>
<P>
   When San Francisco radio station KDFC-FM announced it would not
carry the 1999-2000 ``Live from the Met'' opera season, I was as
mad as anybody.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the last two decades, from early December to late
April, my Saturdays have been synonymous with Texaco's full-length
Metropolitan Opera broadcasts. Whether I was cleaning house,
running errands or just running (with radio headphones), I listened
to the opera from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Always during the broadcast, when I'd hear the scrape of stage
furniture, a prolonged pause between musical sections or just a
cough in the audience, a delicious thrill would run through me.
</P>
<P>
   This was LIVE. The real thing. Happening 3,000 miles away in
Lincoln Center. No retakes. No dubbing, no mixing, no digital
enhancing. Just the raw, exciting, scary, no-net leap that is a
live opera performance.
</P>
<P>
   Mess with that magic? I was ready to picket the radio station's
offices and boycott all of their annoying and noisy commercial
sponsors. And I wasn't alone. KDFC program director Bill Lueth said
that since the station announced it could not come to terms with
the Met, he has been ``harangued by listeners.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are threatening to call the FCC to try and have our
license lifted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, the FCC lifts licenses for malfeasance or
irresponsibility; neither is at work in the KDFC-Met divorce. If
anything, Lueth _ a former operatic bass-baritone with graduate
degrees in opera _ probably tried harder than most radio executives
would have to cut a deal with the Met.
</P>
<P>
   You want to blame somebody for no more live Met on KDFC? Blame
Alan Greenspan or anyone who has contributed to our highly
competitive, market-driven economy. Blame capitalism and free
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1997, when Bonneville International Corp. bought KDFC
and promised it would retain the station's classical music format,
the Salt Lake City company was a hero. The big money in radio was
not in Bach or Mahler, but in talk or all-news. For music stations,
the bucks were in lite rock.
</P>
<P>
   Bonneville may be Mormon-owned, but it's no nonprofit. For
commercial radio stations to ``stay competitive'' (or just
survive), they must hold their own in the ad wars. Sponsors don't
care what you air, just so long as your audience consists mostly of
money-spending 24- to 54-year-olds who can be blasted with 10
commercial spots per hour.
</P>
<P>
   When your format is van Halen or Tony Orlando and Dawn, you have
no problem. When it's symphonies in four movements or operas in
four acts, something's gotta give.
</P>
<P>
   Competing for sponsors with rock stations and easy listening,
KDFC transformed its format from serious classical into what some
of us derisively call ``classical lite.'' A cut here from
``Romantic Adagio,'' a Chopin nocturne there, the 25th rendition in
a week of ``The Moldau.''
</P>
<P>
   This format has hooked 100,000 new listeners into the 102.7 FM
spot, according to Lueth, and thus achieved something almost no
commercial classical station has these days: financial viability.
(The fact that no public, nonprofit station has rushed to fill the
Bay Area's classical music void speaks volumes about how few
programmers are courting the purist classical music audience.)
</P>
<P>
   The rub with the Met: Classical lite and the nation's premiere
opera company are not a great mix.
</P>
<P>
   The Met, which pays stations to air its shows, not the other way
around, is committed to live broadcasts; Texaco has sponsored them
since 1940. Steeped in power and tradition, the company will not
permit tape-delayed broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Like WCRB in Boston, which also dropped the Met operas this
season, KDFC's marketing surveys tell them that opera fans are a
small part of their audience. Saturdays, between 10 a.m. and 3
p.m., when ``Live from the Met'' airs, is prime time in the world
of classical lite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Radio has changed,'' Lueth said. ``The old idea of different
four-hour formats doesn't work anymore. You have to be consistent
and give listeners what they expect, 24 hours a day. You certainly
have to give it to them in prime time.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, for us opera niche types, free-market forces
sometimes give as well as take away. Saturdays, between 10 and 3,
are not prime time for everyone. Palo Alto station KBZS-AM (1220)
announced this week that it is only too happy to take the Met's
money and air ``Live from the Met.'' The first broadcast is ``The
Marriage of Figaro,'' Dec. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The irony: KBZS's usual format is financial and business news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
