<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW SHOWING: THE GREAT ESCAPE FROM REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The first rule of the Flight Club is you don't
talk about the Flight Club.
</P>
<P>
   The Flight Club meets in the middle of the day at the Sony
Metreon's 11-screen cineplex, within walking distance of most of
the office buildings in San Francisco. I'm sitting with a few dozen
escapee office workers, mostly male, watching Brad Pitt and Ed
Norton kick some yuppie butt in ``Fight Club.''
</P>
<P>
   We're kicking some butt, too. We fled work for a couple of hours
on some excuse or another, like being on assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, my editor did recommend ``Fight Club'' over ``American
Beauty,'' which I'd seen already anyway. I took that as an order to
get right on it.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, ``American Beauty'' and ``Fight Club'' are the
same movie, with different titrations of testosterone. In both
movies, a submissive white male office worker rebels against the
middle-class world instead of, say, slipping out of work to watch a
movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty'' and ``Fight Club'' both tell the age-old
American story of boy meets inner boy, tells boss to take that job
and shove it, then lights out for the territories of the mind and
ends up with his brains blown out by a semiautomatic.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry to give away the plot of both movies, but the movies do it
themselves at the beginning anyway. It's all in the acting, the
nuances, the writing and the great escapist choice between sex and
violence or violence and sex.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-ish office worker played by Kevin Spacey in ``American
Beauty'' drools over a teen-age cheerleader, while the 30-ish
office worker played by Ed Norton in ``Fight Club'' favors
homoerotic bloody fisticuffs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, who's more mature? That's right. It's us, the members of
the Flight Club, certified R-rated mature audiences in darkened
rooms having popcorn and wish-fulfillment for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Face it, if you tell your boss to shove it, you need a better
blackmail scheme than either Spacey or Norton concoct to get a
golden parachute.
</P>
<P>
   If you make time with an underage cheerleader, you should be
ready to do the time. And only in movies would she look at a
balding old guy anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I liked the first half of ``Fight Club'' for
its sick humor about testicular cancer support groups. I enjoyed
``American Beauty'' mainly for the conversation that followed.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't any conversation after ``Fight Club.'' All the guys
walked silently out of the theater, surreptitiously checking each
other out for scars or tell-tale signs of wimphood.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty,'' on the other hand, is this year's talker
movie.
</P>
<P>
   I've talked about it with a leather-clad Harley rider I see some
mornings at Peet's coffeehouse. I've talked about it with
stockbrokers, writers and my wife _ who didn't especially like the
movie except for its acting and as something to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   People have their favorite Kevin Spacey lines, like when he
raises his fist in the air and says, ``I rule!''
</P>
<P>
   OK, it's the ultimate boy line, and it's all in how he says it.
He's a great actor and he was at the peak of his form.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are those who like to talk about the moral lessons of
the movie. Just for starters, the high school kid next door is the
only thoroughly grounded character with a job he likes _ being a
drug peddler.
</P>
<P>
   All right, there aren't any moral lessons.
</P>
<P>
   As one African-American woman put it, ```American Beauty' is
about white men's problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but white men's problems have such a rich tradition in the
movies, from talkers like ``American Beauty'' to grunters like
``Fight Club,'' back to such masterpieces of white male alienation
as ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest'' and ``Five Easy Pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   I loved both movies. I also liked ``Fight Club,'' until the
fight clubbers went completely fascist, trying to undermine
American society by destroying public art, trashing franchise
coffeehouses and smashing BMWs with baseball bats.
</P>
<P>
   When I flee work for the Flight Club, I don't want to see
anything that looks remotely like real life in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
