<SLUG> BC-SIEGFRIED-ROY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIONS &AMP; TIGERS &AMP; SIEGFRIED &AMP; ROY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
Eds: Fact box at bottom.  
Our rating:   3   stars  
 
 
 
 
By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like most things about Vegas superstars Siegfried &AMP; Roy, their
new IMAX 3-D movie is as dazzling as it is hokey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Siegfried &AMP; Roy: The Magic Box'' is tricked up with all kinds
of comin'-at-ya, computer-generated effects that are supposed to
evoke a sense of magic being all around us in life. Sometimes they
do, but more often they remind you of those old ``Monty Python''
collage interludes, only more expensive and not as witty.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of the movie, as is the case with S&AMP;R's stage
spectaculars, is any of it that involves big cats. The white tigers
and lions that the showmen have been so instrumental in preserving
are magnificent, even more so in gargantu-o 3-D _ and even more
captivating in footage showing them at home with the guys,
frolicking amid the whacky splendor of S&AMP;R's tropical
paradise-themed estate.
</P>
<P>
   Also like the stage act, there's not enough time spent with the
cats. The main thrust of this movie, I think, is to tell the story
of two unhappy German boys who found escape in magic tricks
(Siegfried) and communing with animals (Roy), and then found each
other. It's hard to tell, though, since the narrative keeps jumping
around in time and focus, with snippets of biographical
re-creation, bits from the stage show, those weird mechanistic
effects and portentous narration by Anthony Hopkins all intermixed
and flashed around in an over-edited jumble.
</P>
<P>
   The director, Brett Leonard, played similar games with coherence
in his feature films, ``Virtuosity'' and ``The Lawnmower Man.''
Anyway, the legend goes that Siegfried and Roy grew up in families
that were emotionally shattered by the war, met on a cruise ship
where Siegfried was pulling rabbits out of hats and Roy had stowed
away his pet cheetah, and by combining their two interests into one
unusual act started down the magical road to living their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Nice for them, nice for the animals, nice to look at. A little
superficial and pretty darn corny? You bet. But hey, it's big and
it's dazzling, and Leonard at least films the magic acts in
360-degree uninterrupted shots, which makes them more impressive
than anything David Copperfield has done in his fixed-camera
specials. ``Magic Box'' will have its pointers and detractors, but
this trick has worked so well for so long, how could anyone really
want to spoil it? &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
The film: &LR;  ``Siegfried &AMP; Roy: The Magic Box'' (not rated). &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR;  Siegfried Fischbacher, Roy Uwe Ludwig Horn, Anthony
Hopkins (narration), John Summers, Andrew Dunlap, Dillon McEwin,
Cameron Alexander. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR;  Directed by Brett Leonard. Written by Lyn Vaus
and Leonard. Produced by Michael V. Lewis. Released by IMAX Ltd. &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  50 minutes. &UR;  &QL; 
Our rating: &LR;  3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
