<SLUG> BC-SFCHRON-BUDG-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Home&AMP;Garden
section plans to move Thursday, Oct. 21, on the New York Times New
Service wire. Questions? Please call Holly Ocasio Rizzo at
415-777-8811. &HT;     
 
High Point, N.C. _ HIGHPOINT _  The International Home Furnishings
Market _ the Paris runway show of the furniture world _ points
toward a return to comfort and nostalgia. Look for multiple-use
furniture pieces, easy-care finishes, soothing lines _ and even a
reissue of the original La-Z-Boy recliner, a wood-slat lawn chair. &HT;    Followed by:
 &HT;    SIDEBAR: Trends at a Glance
 &HT;    SIDEBAR: Celebrities attach their names to home furnishings.
 &HT;     By Holly Ocasio Rizzo 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
High Point, N.C. &UR; _ HIGHPOINT2 _ &LR;  Online furniture sales hold
promise for entrepreneurs, fear for furniture stores and excitement
for consumers. The debate over their existence raged during the
International Home Furnishings Market.
<P>
   &UR; By Holly Ocasio Rizzo &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3941 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-HIGHPOINT-SFCHRON &LR;      10-21 2234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHPOINT-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: Optional trends-at-a-glance sidebar and
celebrity  sidebar follow the end of the main story. Also see
HIGHPOINT2, a 
 report on the trend toward online furniture sales.   BEYOND COCOONING: World's largest furniture market points toward 
 a return to comfort and nostalgia  
   
   
 By Holly Ocasio Rizzo  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 HIGH POINT, N.C. _  Something looks familiar about the season's new
home furnishings. It's the '40s line of a chair arm, '60s
light-wood finishes, '70s deep upholstery _ the touches we came
home to, but abandoned, over the decades.
 &HT;    In fact, the fall International Home Furnishings Market, an
eight-day industry bazaar closing Friday in High Point, N.C., nods
to the past, but with distinctively year 2000 visual lines,
proportions and materials.
 &HT;    Futurist Faith Popcorn, in High Point to unveil her collection,
``Faith Popcorn's Home Office Cocoon,'' says furniture design
reflects consumers' desire to burrow deeper into their homes, away
from a chaotic world.
 &HT;    ``As people go into 2000, they are looking for comfort,''
Popcorn said.
 &HT;    Last year, Popcorn advised the furniture industry to step beyond
providing physical comfort _ to listen harder to customers about
making furniture easier to live with. And the industry did.
 &HT;    Consumer-driven features abound at the market, including
multiple-use furniture pieces and easy-care finishes. Pure physical
comfort is there, too, in frames that hug, upholstery that softly
caresses, colors that soothe.
 &HT;    In fact, some furniture makers introduced only new fabrics and
colors, not new pieces. ``You can transform a piece just by
changing the finish and color,'' designer John Mascheroni said as
he wound among suedes and tapestries in the Swaim showroom.
 &HT;    Nearly 2,500 exhibitors attend the market in High Point,
bringing with them enough home furnishings to fill Chicago's Sears
Tower twice. It's open only to industry professionals and
journalists.
 &HT;    We'll give you a peek at some of the furnishings you'll start
seeing in showrooms by the new year.
 &HT;     The Consumer Speaks 
 &HT;    Popcorn's home office collection for Hooker Furniture includes
all the accoutrements _ computer armoires, mobile files, credenzas,
bookcases and writing desks. But it steps beyond in details that
were developed after interviews with 4,000 women who work at home.
 &HT;    ``My favorite part is the built-in bud vase in the desk,'' she
said. In addition, the desktop is slightly higher than usual,
``because a woman, when she works, crosses her legs,'' and one
drawer includes velvet-lined jewelry compartments because, ``when
she works, she takes off her earrings.''
 &HT;    A baker's rack-style computer shelf accommodates small spaces,
and smaller-scale chairs fit women's smaller frames.
 &HT;    ``I want women to call me, because I want to know what else they
want,'' Popcorn said. ``We have one secret compartment (in the
desk), but is it secret enough? Would they like a little hot button
under the desk that's hooked up to a home alarm? If they have kids,
would they like a child's desk that swings out beside their own
desk?''
 &HT;    At Lexington Home Furnishings, consumer input played into the
design of `California Legacy,' a 55-piece collection blending
Spanish, Mediterranean and English influences. The scale is
generally large to help fill new homes.
 &HT;    Lexington is building a 50-member consumer board to offer ideas
and feedback.
 &HT;    ``It's so logical, you don't have to sell people on it,''
executive vice president Robert S. Stec said. ``Until now, the
process of buying furniture has been very intimidating. People
think there's a secret society on this side of the fence.''
 &HT;     British Accents 
 &HT;    Lexington also introduced ``Bob Timberlake Riverwood,'' a
collection of English and Irish cottage designs finished in natural
antique spruce or white crackled glaze with light distressing. The
scale is generally for a spacious cottage. Timberlake, a North
Carolina artist encouraged by Andrew Wyeth, has designed furniture
for Lexington since 1990.
 &HT;    At Vanguard Furniture Co., supermodel Kathy Ireland asked
Britain's Prince Edward for advice while developing the ``Kathy
Ireland Home Collection.'' The prince flew to California to meet
with her and her designers about the colors, woods and styles used
in Windsor Castle.
 &HT;    The result is smaller-scale furniture Ireland describes as
family friendly, with features such as easy-to-open toy drawers in
dressers and coloring-book storage in coffee tables. While the
collection pays homage to her English-born father, it also reflects
her upbringing in Santa Barbara, with light finishes, rattan and
iron accents.
 &HT;    ``You can't have an appreciation for things that are new without
the proper respect for things of the past,'' she said.
 &HT;    The Forbes Collection, launched at the market, is all about
respecting things past. The elegant collection is based on
furnishings in the Forbes family's Chateau de Balleroy in Normandy,
France, and Old Battersea House in London.
 &HT;    Seven companies are licensed to produce the items: Harden
Furniture; Chelsea House Inc. (pillows and lighting); Couristan
Inc. (rugs); Austin Horn Collection (bedding); O'Brien Ironworks
(outdoor furniture); Paragon Picture Gallery (framed prints); and
Interior Indulgences Inc. (candles and accessories).
 &HT;    There's one concession to Malcolm Forbes' rebellious side: a
sofa with tall turned legs and black leather upholstery, reflecting
his passion for motorcycles.
 &HT;    While the name of the ``British Open Collection'' might evoke
images of golf, Century Furniture had in mind the casual elegance
of the Royal &AMP; cq  Ancient Golf Club of St. Andrews when designing
it. Examples: the 60-inch round, eight-legged ``Turnberry''
cocktail table with maple veneer top and the three-shelf ``Colfax''
chairside table, evoking an antique English library table.
 &HT;     Make Mine Modern 
 &HT;    The clean lines and curves of Art Deco get a rebirth in
Bernhardt Furniture Co.'s ``Manhattan.'' A bowed-front buffet
features beaded, shaped feet with a green granite top; a master
chest with horizontal scooping on the door fronts offers
up-to-the-century hardware finished in brushed nickel.
 &HT;    Not quite modern enough? Take a look at Milo Baughman's
``Limited Edition'' day chaise, for Thayer Coggin Inc. The dramatic
white chaise features a curving, chrome-outlined underside.
 &HT;    ``My objective was to give my `Limited Edition' collection the
glamour and comfort of the late '30s and '40s moderne, but not in a
retro fashion,'' Baughman said. ``I hoped to achieve a synthesis
that would reflect the truly innovative spirit that I expect will
come in the new century.''
 &HT;     Outdoors Chic 
 &HT;    Outdoor furniture you could use indoors: That's how several
companies describe their new offerings.
 &HT;    Larry Laslo's ``Lyre Lyre'' pieces for Veneman Collections
feature lyre backs in aluminum and footed legs. It's based on a
garden chair he found at a Sotheby's auction in New York.
 &HT;    His ``La Couer,'' also for Veneman, offers wide seats and a back
pattern of entwined hearts found in a French bistro set from the
'40s. Designers in the '40s were looking back to the more
substantial shapes of the 18th century.
 &HT;    Brown Jordan's new releases actually are intended for indoors or
outdoors. Tubular vinyl plays the supporting role in
``Streamline,'' wrapped around a gently curving, brushed metal
frame. ``Fusion,'' of blond-colored resin strips woven tightly over
an aluminum frame, evokes the blond furniture finishes of the '40s
and '50s.
 &HT;    For a collection so new it barely made it to High Point, San
Francisco designer Michael Vanderbyl of McGuire Furniture looked to
Shaker designs, midcentury modernism and his own sailboat. The
result, ``Archetype by McGuire,'' combines aluminum frames with
teak grids and nylon webbing for 14 easy-going pieces.
 &HT;     Upscale Animals 
 &HT;    Animal motifs turn up all over the market, mostly in fabrics.
Leopard remains strong, but zebra and pony prints are catching up.
 &HT;    Swaim and Pennsylvania House are showing new upholstery
collections including a monkey motif.
 &HT;    But animals sneak into furniture in other ways, too. At Palecek,
based in Richmond, natural, brown and black wicker creates the
stripes on the ``Zebra'' chair.
 &HT;    Garcia Imports in Hayward is showing its ``Safari'' carved-wood
bench with hand-painted zebra side panels and a black muslin seat.
 &HT;     Really Retro 
 &HT;    Perhaps the most retrospective piece at the High Point market is
actually an intact oldie: the original La-Z-Boy recliner. Each
limited-edition reproduction La-Z-Boy comes with a certificate of
authorization, but it looks nothing like its upholstered progeny.
 &HT;    This recliner was a lawn chair made of wood slats in 1928 in
Monroe, Mich. Its popularity grew _ and grew _ until today, through
mergers and acquisitions, La-Z-Boy is the nation's biggest
furniture company.
 &HT;    What a long way La-Z-Boy _ and the 90-year-old High Point home
furnishings market _ have come.
 &HT;     
 
 
BEGIN OPTIONAL SIDEBARS: 
 
HOME FURNISHINGS TRENDS AT A GLANCE &HT;      
 Multiple uses.  Look for more coffee tables with drawers for kids'
crayons and coloring books, and drop leaves for extra entertaining
space; also, more sectional sofas to form seating arrangements
convenient for the moment.
 &HT;     Red.  It will be the next hot color, from stop-sign to burgundy
shades.
 &HT;     Metal on wood.  Metal tops headboards, holds up tabletops, puts
a gleam on corners. Go for the silver. Better yet, make it pewter.
And don't forget silver-leaf-on-wood accents for bedroom and living
room.
 &HT;     Expanded world influences.  The world of furniture is moving
beyond China, Australia and France to Africa, India and South
America, especially in hardware, upholstery and decorative
accessories. The English estate look crops up in entire
collections.
 &HT;     Animal influence.  The leopard look maintains its hold on lamp
shades and throw pillows, but zebra and pony patterns come on
strong in upholstery, area rugs and even in rattan weaves _ all
reflecting women's fashion trends. Ultra hot: monkey motifs.
 &HT;     Pastel leathers.  Think pink, peach, mint and butter.
 &HT;     Shimmering fabrics.  We'll see throw pillows and bedspreads
that sparkle subtly, a mother lode of gold and silver satin sheets,
and upholstery with a hint of sheen.
 &HT;     Instant age.  Expect painted finishes with corners and edges
worn to the wood; crackled color glazes; rustlike patinas on metal.
 &HT;     Easy-care surfaces.  Satin finishes, less likely to show
fingerprints, are the last word for wood. On top, several companies
are using Corian for tables and kitchen islands.
 &HT;     
 
 Big Names in the Furniture Biz  
   
   
 By Holly Ocasio Rizzo  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; HIGH POINT, N.C. _  &LR; You, too, could own a leather couch like the
one Jack Palance sat on last week at the International Home
Furnishings Market, drawing dozens of people to see the spectacle.
<P>
   Palance was one of several celebrities who visited High Point to
drum up business _ furniture business. Their names mean cash and
cachet for furniture makers _ names like Alexander Julian,
Christopher Forbes, Kathy Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a celebrity,'' supermodel Ireland said Friday as she
unveiled the Kathy Ireland Collection for Vanguard Furniture. Her
bodyguard stood nearby, and her limo waited outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a working mom. I've worked hard over the years on the
quality of my brand.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Indeed, as crows' feet crept onto her face, Ireland turned &LR; 
from modeling  &LR;  to design and marketing. &LR;  She keeps in touch with
consumers through her Web site,  &LR; www.kathyireland.com &LR; , she says,
and hopes to gather their feedback about her English-inspired
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Clothing designer Alexander Julian drew inspiration closer to
home for his ``Colourscapes,'' accent chairs and five new
upholstery groups made by BenchCraft. His new fabrics reflect U.S.
landscapes in typically soft-hued Julian fashion, including
blue-and-purple-tinged ``Misty Vineyards of Napa.''
</P>
<P>
   Folk artist Warren Kimble, known for his American primitive
style, told a private luncheon about his 30-year rise from a
blue-collar Vermont home to a licensing bonanza that includes
miniature furniture, hooked rugs and flags introduced at High
Point.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Christopher Forbes. The son of media magnate Malcolm held
his photo op just a little too far from the furniture-market action
to attract many foot-weary walkers. The launch of a
Faberge-egg-shaped balloon at the edge of downtown High Point
officially unveiled a 30-piece art-and-furnishings collection
inspired by his family's possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Action Lane showroom (a division of Lane furniture),
actor Palance moseyed onto a Western set featuring a brown sofa
with tack trim. Wearing a chambray shirt, red bandanna, jeans and
dust-free brown boots and chaps, he looked a bit confused about his
role as a sofa spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But his part soon became clear as he accepted a furniture
industry award for best television commercial of 1999, for a
national advertising campaign to be rolled out in November. As a
photographer set up a camera for all those who wanted their
pictures taken with the leather-faced star, Palance whipped out a
pen to sign autographs for adoring furniture buyers and sales
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
