<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3943 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-HIGHPOINT2-SFCHRON &LR;      10-21 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHPOINT2-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: Also see the main package moving as HIGHPOINT.   Online Onslaught for Furniture Dealers 
 &HT;       
   
   
 By Holly Ocasio Rizzo  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; HIGH POINT, N.C. _  &LR; Furniture stores call them ``dot commies,''
fearing they'll destroy retailing as we know it. But online
furniture sites, still in their infancy, captivate consumers _ and
the industry is preparing for the inevitable.
<P>
   How-to workshops and seminars about online selling and services
dot the agenda for the International Home Furnishings Market, which
ends Friday in High Point.
</P>
<P>
   For furniture customers, online sites offer a variety of
services, including complete home decor planning, links to
manufacturers' Web sites and retail sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our case, consumers are using the channel to get
information,'' says Steve Antisdel, president of FurnitureFind.com,
based in Niles, Mich. FurnitureFind.com provides product
information and sells online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our buyers are the working soccer mom who's found a way to
extend her day with this; the distance-confined, who live too far
from a store to shop; and retail refugees who've been pounced on or
ignored by furniture salespeople,'' Antisdel adds.
</P>
<P>
   Customers seem poised for online furniture shopping; San
Francisco-based Jupiter Communications, a market-research firm,
projects online sales in home-related categories to leap to $3.6
billion in 2003 from $100 million in 1998. Granted, that's a blip
in the $250 billion home-design industry.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Making the Leap Online
</P>
<P>
   Jay Busey is a skeptic-turned-optimist when it comes to Internet
furniture sales.
</P>
<P>
   When Busey's 27-year-old son, Andrew, an Internet pioneer, asked
whether they could sell online together, ``I said, `No way. You
have to touch furniture, feel it, smell it.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Busey gauged the reactions of ordinary people to the idea,
and in July, the father-son duo took Shaw Furniture Galleries, a
living.com company, to the Internet at  &LR; www.shawgalleries.com &LR; . It
ships via specialty carrier anywhere in the continental United
States and is building a call center and warehouse in Greensboro,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Busey says he needs to offer exceptionally high quality and
customer service to attract customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be able to provide the `wow!' factor,'' Busey says.
``When the customer opens it up, it had better be better than they
expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics within the industry point out the impersonal nature of
e-commerce customer service and the possibility that online sellers
will undercut the prices of neighborhood furniture retailers,
driving them out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Both Busey and Antisdel stressed the need for e-tailers to offer
customers reliable advice and to handle their complaints quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is like a very big small town,'' Antisdel says.
``Word gets out quickly, so you have to take care of the customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our research shows price is not the driving issue for our
customers,'' he adds. ``It's convenience.''
</P>
<P>
   To mollify angry retailers, one online company, San
Francisco-based GoodHome.com, plans eventually to sell only
furniture bearing its own label, chief executive officer Douglas
Mack says.
</P>
<P>
   How easy can shopping get?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our site is organized around making it easy for consumers to
find products,'' says Linda Lewi of homeportfolio.com, based in
Newton, Mass. ``Consumers can archive pictures of products or
e-mail them to a friend or relative. They can get a referral to a
retailer for any product.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the year, homeportfolio.com is expected to display
more than 100,000 products from 750 manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, several manufacturers recently moved online or said
they will do so.
</P>
<P>
   S.E.E. Imports of Hayward announced in High Point that it has
created a site,  &LR; www.seeimports.com &LR; , to show consumers its line
and tell them which retailers carry it.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  LifeStyle Furnishings International launched sites for its
divisions, including BenchCraft, Henredon, Lexington and Drexel
Heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Furniture Co.'s site,  &LR; www.stanleyfurniture.com &LR; , lets
consumers create layouts of their home offices outfitted with
Stanley furniture. It refers them to retailers to purchase the
products.
</P>
<P>
   On the horizon: shopping bots that scour the Web for the lowest
prices, much the way consumers can find cheap airfares, says Mack
of GoodHome.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
