<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3946 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-LIVE-MUSIC-LADN &LR;      10-21 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVE-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVE FINDS FOCUS ON FOURTH ALBUM, `THE DISTANCE TO HERE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
 
 
 
By FRED SHUSTER 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ed Kowalczyk, singer of the multimillion-selling
rock quartet Live, likes to tell how he made personal politics
universal in the current radio hit ``The Dolphin's Cry.''
</P>
<P>
   The song, taken from Live's fourth and latest album ``The
Distance to Here,'' opens with a restrained vocal and poetic
lyrics: ``The way you're bathed in light, reminds me of that
night/God laid me down into your rose garden of truth.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an uplifting number that takes the listener on a
roller-coaster ride via a wall of guitars.
</P>
<P>
   Kowalczyk, who is in his mid-20s, says the song came while he
was camping in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started playing the chords and an hour later I had an idea
of the melody,'' he recalled. ``The lyrics came after. It starts
out in a very intimate setting. When I talk about the dolphins,
it's an invitation to a kind of dreamscape. The real guts of the
message is, life is like a shooting star, and the song builds to a
realization of a universal love, starting with two people.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a standard message for Pennsylvania's Live, which rose to
success five years ago on the strength of anthemic music and
idealistic songwriting, two elements that drew frequent comparisons
to U2.
</P>
<P>
   After releasing their 1991 debut album, ``Mental Jewelry,''
Kowalczyk and company spent three years honing their second effort,
``Throwing Copper,'' the album that would spawn the crossover hits
``I Alone,'' ``Selling the Drama'' and ``Lightning Crashes.''
</P>
<P>
   The disc made Live stars, but the self-conscious ``Secret
Samadhi'' that followed in 1997 fell flat, especially compared to
the direct arena-oriented rock of the previous effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Distance to Here'' (Radioactive), produced like other Live
albums by ex-Talking Head Jerry Harrison, is a return to what Live
does best, while the first single, ``The Dolphin's Cry,'' chalks up
spins on rock and alt-rock radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty obvious `Dolphin's Cry' was going to be the
first single,'' Kowalczyk said. ``It has a dynamic and an emotion
that announces what we're about. The song is almost like a call to
arms not only for us but for where we're headed. It just felt like
the right song to announce the new record.''
</P>
<P>
   The new record zoomed into the charts upon release, debuting at
No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been able, nor have I wanted, to separate my desire
for truth and passion from my lyrics,'' Kowalczyk said. ``I've
always been into asking the big questions. I'm always the last guy
out the door at closing time 'cause I'm sitting around till the wee
hours with the others asking the same things. That's what it's all
about for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kowalczyk said Harrison, who essentially discovered the band 15
years ago while they were still in high school and shepherded them
through the recording of each of the four albums, ``is an expert
producer of bands. He understands the dynamic and chemistry of four
or five guys working toward a single goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kowalczyk admits, that single goal isn't always easy to
reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are pitfalls,'' he says. ``Anytime you have several
different visions, it's a challenge. But we've been able to keep
focused in a positive direction.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
