<HEADLINE>
`BLAIR WITCH' IS OUT THERE ... ON VIDEO AND DVD 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
 
 
 
 
 
By ROB LOWMAN 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Which old witch is the witch of the season? Why
``The Blair Witch Project,'' of course, which comes out Friday on
video and DVD.
</P>
<P>
   You've heard the story before, of course. Three college kids get
lost in the Maryland woods while filming a documentary about the
mysterious and gruesome legend of the Blair Witch and are never
seen again. The only evidence of their misadventure is the film and
videos that are found. On the film, we see their harrowing
experiences, which they shoot despite their fear.
</P>
<P>
   And you've heard the other story, of course. A couple of young
filmmmakers from Florida outsmart the Hollywood system by creating
a sensation with a low-tech movie costing anywhere from $35,000 to
$50,000 that has grossed about $140 million so far.
</P>
<P>
   It did benefit from a $15 million advertising budget, but ``The
Blair Witch Project'' had an early positive buzz from screenings at
such film festivals as Sundance, and there was all kinds of
Internet speculation about whether the footage was real. (It
wasn't).
</P>
<P>
   The real genius of the film was to do something that Hollywood
seems to have forgotten how to do (except for ``The Sixth Sense''):
create atmospheric terror. In one of the best films ever made about
Hollywood, Vincent Minnelli's ``The Bad and the Beautiful,'' a
producer (Jonathan Shields) played by Kirk Douglas has been told by
the studio to make a film called ``The Cat Men'' using guys dressed
up in bad cat suits. Realizing that actually showing the suit will
undercut the fright factor, Shields asks the question: What are we
afraid of? The answer, naturally, is the dark. So he instructs his
director to only shoot shadows in the night. The film is a success.
Well, this is a Hollywood movie. But the lesson that you don't have
to bludgeon your audience with gore to be frightening _ which
dozens of real directors like Hitchcock knew _ seems to have been
lost ... until now.
</P>
<P>
   The second stroke of genius by the ``Blair Witch'' filmmakers
was to have the characters' increasingly disoriented and frightened
state reflected in the way the movie was shot. At the beginning of
the film, the three characters _ who are played by actors using
their real names: Heather Donahue, Michael Williams and Joshua
Leonard _ are happy and playful. The trip is just a lark. The
camerawork, though amateurish, is assured. As the trio find
themselves lost and start hearing sounds in the night, as well as
finding indications that something is around them, the camerawork
grows bizarre and crooked. As smart as this move is, it can't be
duplicated without seeming trite. So beware of any imitations
Hollywood may have planned.
</P>
<P>
   On another level, the film more or less acts as a metaphor for
life on the edge of the millennium. But, hey, this is a video
column so we'll skip that.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the actors used their real names helped to fuel
speculation and maintain the illusion that the story was real, and
an interest in all things ``Blair Witch'' grew.
</P>
<P>
   The DVD and video versions offer extras for the fans ofthe
film. Both include the Sci-Fi Channel special, ``The Curse of the
Blair Witch,'' a fake documentary that interviews ``experts'' on
the Blair Witch. The DVD also includes interviews with the actors
and filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   And since the buzz on the Internet was so important to the
initial success of the film, if you have a DVD-ROM in your
computer, there is a map of the Black Hills Forest, a dossier and
access to the various Blair Witch Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   One of the interesting things about watching ``The Blair Witch
Project'' at home is that it looks like a home movie _ only a scary
one. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
