<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAURIE ANDERSON TAKES THE ROAD TO MELVILLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
Eds: Fact box at bottom.  
Our rating:   3   stars  
 
 
 
 
 
 
By REED JOHNSON 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In ``Songs and Stories From Moby Dick,'' her
dreamy, impressionistic homage to Herman Melville's classic novel,
Laurie Anderson talks quietly but carries a big harpoon.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's a customized, microprocessor-filled aluminum
tube, known as the Talking Stick, which Anderson skillfully uses to
conjure a vast oceanscape of eerie sounds and haunting musical
associations.
</P>
<P>
   During her 90-minute performance at UCLA's Royce Hall, Anderson
weaves an electronic tapestry of tolling bells, the underwater
clicking of whales, snatches of Celtic melody, a doleful church
organ (when the Pequod meets its untimely fate), Afro-Caribbean
polyrhythms and what sound like abstracted, angularized versions of
Middle Eastern and Polynesian strings.
</P>
<P>
   It's an inspired aural collage based on Melville's dense book,
which tracks a whaling crew's spiritual odyssey from the craggy
certainties of New England Calvinism to bloody disaster somewhere
off Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Songs and Stories From Moby Dick,'' which is playing through
Saturday, brings out the best in Anderson's sing-songy,
free-associating method of storytelling. Like an old salt with an
entertaining but unwieldy yarn to spin, she knows how to pick her
details carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson rarely scores a direct emotional bull's-eye with this
material, but that's partly because she's too savvy an artist to
try to nail down Melville's slippery text. Just as ``Moby Dick''
itself is less a traditional narrative than a whirling vortex of
philosophical conjecture and poetic digression, so is Anderson's
tribute an eccentric, highly personal reading of Melville _ an
interpolation of an interpolation.
</P>
<P>
   Divided into 30 vignettes of varying lengths, the piece uses
four live actors _ a first in Anderson's work _ plus a bass player,
Iceland's Skuli Sverrisson, whose funky, allusive fretwork
complements Anderson's more ethereal violin and keyboard
ruminations. Video projections of surging waves, whale-shaped
constellations and ghostly polar ice caps, along with witty cartoon
graphics and somewhat crude animation, lend imagistic substance to
an evening that otherwise might founder in too much Melvillian
metaphysics.
</P>
<P>
   Choreographed by avant-garde favorite Anne Bogart (credited with
``staging co-direction''), the piece may remind you visually of
Robert Wilson's postmodern operas. Silhouetted sailors cross the
multilevel stage in stately procession. A crewman waxes
philosophical from a movable crow's nest.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most effective episodes are the evocation of Pip, the
cabin boy, taking a tumble overboard into the heart of God's
mechanical creation. The piece takes an even creepier turn when the
madness of Capt. Ahab is portrayed by actor Tom Nelis, his
magnified, split-screen face looming behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Nelis' apoplectic Ahab casts off his crutches and does
a bizarre comic two-step _ a reference to ``Moby Dick's'' severe
case of mind-body splits. The closer you are to having read or
reread Melville's book, the more you'll likely glean from
Anderson's rich and strange responses to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Songs and Stories From Moby Dick'' makes Melville's 1851
masterpiece feel freshly mysterious and vital, like some exotic
pearl just dredged from the ocean depths. There is considerable
passion and perception in this postmodern salute to a premodern
masterwork _ and more than a drop of brilliance. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
What: Laurie Anderson performs ``Songs and Stories From Moby
Dick.'' &QL; 
Where: Royce Hall, UCLA, Westwood. &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. Friday, 2 and 8 p.m. Saturday. &QL; 
Tickets: $40, $30, $22; $13 for UCLA students with valid ID. Call
(310) 825-2101; www.cto.ucla.edu on the Web. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0115 </DOCNO>
