<SLUG> BC-CALIF-HOMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SAYS HOT CALIFORNIA PROPERTY MARKET MAY TAKE BREATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Home sales in California will moderate to a more
sustainable level in 2000 after setting records this year, the
California Association of Realtors said. Meanwhile, the state's
median home price is expected to rise by 5 percent to $228,400 in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, median home prices have risen 8 percent this year,
the association reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The California housing market is having its best year on
record, while the economic expansion in the state has not only
continued but has actually accelerated,'' said Diana Bull,
president of the association. ``Home prices in many regions of the
state are exceeding the peak levels of the previous housing cycle
set in the late 1980s or early 1990s.''
</P>
<P>
   A total of 653,390 existing, single-family home sales are
projected for this year in California, up 4 percent from 628,260 in
1998, the association said. The group expects sales to decline 8
percent to 601,120 in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economic growth in the United States will moderate in 2000, in
part because of Federal Reserve policies to raise interest rates,''
said Leslie Appleton-Young, vice president and chief economist of
the realty association.
</P>
<P>
   ``This trend also could be amplified by continued volatility in
the stock market,'' she said. ``Since American consumption is
somewhat leveraged right now to the stock market, a prolonged drop
in equity values could result in a significant slowing of the U.S.
and California economies.''
</P>
<P>
   John McInerney, managing broker of the TRI/Coldwell Banker
office in San Francisco, had another view entirely: ``If you are
living in an average place, the average means something to you,''
McInerney said of the statewide averages. His office is the largest
real estate office in San Francisco, with 100 agents.
</P>
<P>
   McInerney anticipates no hesitation in business despite the rise
in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statewide numbers are laughable when you put them in the
context of what is going on here,'' McInerney said of the San
Francisco area. ``I think this is the economic center of the
universe right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The California Association of Realtors also made these
predictions for 2000:
</P>
<P>
   _ There will be a 2.8 percent expansion in the nation's gross
domestic product, following a projected 3.6 percent GDP growth rate
this year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fixed mortgage interest rates are expected to average 7.8
percent, up slightly from the 7.4 percent average projected for all
of 1999. Adjustable mortgage interest rates are expected to rise
slightly from 5.8 percent in 1999 to 6 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ New housing permits are expected to reach 170,500 next year in
California, up 10 percent from a projected 155,000 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles-based California Association of Realtors has
95,000 members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3953 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-BRITAIN-PARENTING-$AD     10-21 1326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-PARENTING-$ADV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONTROVERSIAL AMERICAN PARENTING GURUS STIR DEBATE IN BRITAIN
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    With PARENTING-BOX-$ADV24.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Oct. 24 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Gary Ezzo, a 50-something evangelical Christian
minister, is a parenting guru dear to the hearts of more than a
million parents around the world. But he also strikes fear in the
hearts of pediatricians and child-care specialists.
</P>
<P>
   By recommending, among other things that children as young as 18
months be spanked, Ezzo has become one of the most controversial
parenting experts in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   It is a message, however, that has resonated with parents
increasingly frustrated by the permissiveness they believe is
promoted by mainstream child-care experts _ and with the
out-of-control children they see as the result.
</P>
<P>
   Ezzo's success over the last few years has brought widespread
attention to his huge, for-profit ``parenting ministry,'' Growing
Families International, based in Simi Valley, Calif. And his many
child-care guides, including ``On Becoming Babywise,'' have
consistently placed in the top 10 most requested parenting titles
on both mainstream and Christian booksellers' lists.
</P>
<P>
   This week(CQ), however, Ezzo will face a firestorm of
controversy when he and his wife, Anne Marie, come here to give a
series of lectures to thousands of British parents looking to raise
model offspring.
</P>
<P>
   Britain is home to psychologist Penelope Leach, another
well-known parenting expert who has achieved Dr. Spock-like
popularity with millions of parents worldwide since the 1970s. She
has written several parenting guides over the years, including
``Your Baby and Child,'' which was first published in 1977 and has
since been translated into 29 languages.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps no two parenting experts are more polarized on
nearly every point of child-rearing than Gary Ezzo and Leach.
</P>
<P>
   Leach is famous for her ``child-centered'' approach that abhors
spanking, and advises parents to feed babies on demand or risk of
dehydration, inadequate development, and other complications. She
recommends praising children when they do right rather than
punishing them when they do wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The debate of nurturing styles, and in particular discipline
techniques, is nothing new, but seldom have the attacks been so
fervid or so personal.
</P>
<P>
   Leach calls Ezzo a dangerous man who promotes child abuse, and
she has urged the British government to investigate his teachings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't allow pediatric pornography so we should not allow
this,'' Leach said.
</P>
<P>
   And in recent weeks, an alliance of more than 200 health-care
and other organizations here called Children Are Unbeatable also
has condemned the Ezzo's parenting regime.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Ezzo has been no less outspoken, however.
</P>
<P>
   He has blamed Leach's techniques for Britain's ``decline into
immorality.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that recent cases reported in the media of 12-year-old
girls giving birth in Britain highlight the need for a new ``moral
emphasis'' in child-rearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most destructive influences in England has been the
child-centered parenting plan; the Penelope Leach philosophy which
has dominated for the last 20 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ezzo has said that feeding on demand can make infants fussy and
confused. He emphasizes an adherence to schedules, writing that
``God is the God of order.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ezzos' visit here has been organized by Christian Education
Europe Ltd., a group that supplies Biblical teaching materials _
including those designed by the Ezzos _ to evangelical and home
education projects.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Thomas, a spokesman for the group, said Ezzo will address
four conferences, the largest being at Westminster Chapel in London
on Oct. 30, where up to 1,200 parents are expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe families here are in need of a lot of moral
guidance, and that the Ezzos are the ones to give it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is a ``moral guidance'' steeped in religious fundamentalism.
Before he started Growing Families International in1989, Gary Ezzo
served 10 years as an associate pastor at Grace Community Church in
Sun Valley, Calif. His wife was once a registered pediatric nurse.
They have two children and six grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, the Ezzos claim that their child-rearing courses
have been taught in as many as 8,000 churches around the world.
These courses include their accompanying workbook, ``Growing Kids
God's Way.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Severance, an assistant to the Ezzos, said their teachings
are about more than just how to feed and discipline children.
</P>
<P>
   ``They emphasize how to show love for your spouse and your
children, how to teach children to respect their elders, how to
make sure they grow up with integrity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Gary Ezzo has never wanted to be portrayed as the poster
boy for spanking, and that he has always offered alternatives to
spanking, such as isolation and verbal correction.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, on paper, the Ezzos' overall philosophy is that
``raising good children is not a matter of chance but a matter of
rightly applying God's principles in parenting.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of spanking, however, has perhaps garnered them the
most attention in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The Ezzos believe that children are born with a natural tendency
toward ``waywardness.'' They recommend swatting misbehaving babies
on the hand or thigh for wrongdoings such as putting fingers in
food. Spanking, or ``chastisement,'' can begin when the child is
about 18 months old. Parents can give up to five swats a day until
the child is three. Beyond that age, more swats are allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Leach disagrees vehemently. A co-founder of the group EPOCH, an
acronym for End Physical Punishment of Children, she argues that
swatting children legitimizes the use of violence in society.
</P>
<P>
   Many other parenting experts agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spanking is like road rage; there are always better ways to
solve discipline problems,'' said Marguerite Kelly, American author
of the book ``The Mother's Almanac.'' ``Spanking, threats and
bribes have one thing in common: they are so often escalated.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ezzos also teach parents to toilet train between the ages of
18 and 24 months, and that excessive cuddling will produce spoiled
children.
</P>
<P>
   For years, critics have charged that the Ezzos aren't qualified
to advise parents, and they have seen the Ezzos' views as
potentially dangerous teachings with little in the way of credible
research to back them up.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, for example, the Ezzos' approach drew ``letters of
concern'' from approximately 100 health-care providers to the
American Academy of Pediatrics.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, the world's largest organization of
pediatricians issued a ``media alert'' in which the group
emphatically reaffirmed its stance that the best feeding schedules
for babies are the ones that babies design by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics say the Ezzos' approach hearkens back to the 1930s
and 1940s, when mothers were often given discredited advice, such
as to ``look at the clock, and not at the baby'' when trying to
determine feeding times.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Ezzos may find a generally receptive audience
when they arrive here next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey published last August for BBC Radio 4's Today
program, seven out of 10 parents said they believe it is acceptable
to smack their children if they misbehave.
</P>
<P>
   Under current British law, a parent has the right to use
``reasonable chastisement'' but six other European countries _
Sweden, Austria, Cyprus, Denmark, Finland, and Norway _ have banned
all forms of physical punishment against children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ezzos teach parents how to raise good kids,'' Severance
said. ``Their message is really catching on with folks.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
