<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3954 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-MEXICO-SKEPTICISM-$AD     10-21 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-SKEPTICISM-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICANS' PERPETUAL DISTRUST INTRUDES ON POLITICAL CHANGES,
ELECTIONS
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Oct. 23 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRIS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ They range from highly educated financial experts
to homemakers and day laborers.
</P>
<P>
   But they share one thing in common: no matter how many reforms
are enacted, how many promises are made, they all think the Mexican
government lies, cheats and steals.
</P>
<P>
   They're Mexico's perpetual skeptics.
</P>
<P>
   After 70 years of virtual one-party rule in Mexico _ and many
crises and disappointments _ Mexicans often have trouble believing
the official word on anything.
</P>
<P>
   Many don't believe the official story that only one gunman
killed Luis Donaldo Colosio, the presidential candidate who was
assassinated during a campaign rally in 1994. Many don't believe
the official line that the fugitive governor of Quintana Roo state
_ Mario Villanueva _ was able to escape surveillance and flee the
country just days before he was to be arrested on drug charges last
April.
</P>
<P>
   And many still don't believe that the first-ever presidential
primary election _ to be held by Mexico's ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, on Nov. 7 _ represents a true step
toward more democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexicans live in a permanent state of suspicion,'' said
international economic consultant Rogelio Ramirez de la O(CQ), who
himself often doubts that political reforms here are genuine,
especially when it comes to the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI is the core of Mexico's national political life and,
some say, the reason why Mexicans tend to be so skeptical of their
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've swallowed the bitter pill too many times,'' said
Guadalupe Loaeza, who writes a column on politics and culture for
Mexico City's Reforma newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The presidency of Carlos Salinas de Gortari represented the
latest in decades of disappointments and broken promises, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas de Gortari vowed to pull Mexicans out of Third World
status in the late 1980s and early 1990s. But that ``seductive
vision'' faded after the Mexican peso crashed just after Salinas
left office, she said, plunging half of the country deeper into
poverty. Salinas' brother and some of his other PRI political
associates have been linked to drug traffickers who paid officials
huge bribes during his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans were left more disillusioned than ever during the seven
decades since 1929 that the PRI has controlled Mexico's highest
political office.
</P>
<P>
   After reforms pushed by opposition parties to make elections
cleaner, the PRI finally lost its absolute majority in Mexico's
Congress two years ago. The PRI still controls a majority of
governors' seats but it has lost several important states in recent
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the prospects of more losses _ perhaps even the
constitutionally powerful presidency _ the PRI has tried to remake
itself into a more attractive, democratic option whose sheer
experience outstrips the opposition. Key to that image is its
upcoming primary, which represents the first time voters will be
allowed to choose the party's nominee for Mexico's July 2, 2000,
presidential election. Up to now, the president of the republic has
always picked the party's nominee in a secret selection process
nicknamed the ``dedazo,'' or ``big finger.''
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging the public's jaded view of its old authoritarian
ways, the party has coined a new slogan plastered on billboards and
heard on frequent radio spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``A new PRI for the new millennium. A new PRI much closer to
you,'' is the message encouraging Mexicans to participate in the
November primary. Any Mexican with a voter credential will be
permitted to cast a ballot, not just PRI members.
</P>
<P>
   The public seems less than overwhelmed by the PRI's attempts to
show new colors, however.
</P>
<P>
   A poll this month found that only 36 percent believe the PRI
primary will be ``totally honest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a slight improvement over the poll we took in June.
That was only 31 percent,'' laughed Vicente Licona, director of
Mexico's Indemerc-Louis Harris polling operation, which did the
survey.
</P>
<P>
   In Indemerc-Louis Harris' June poll, taken before the primary
campaign was in full force, 50 percent of respondents thought the
party had already decided who would win the election. Fifty-four
percent thought Mexico's president, Ernesto Zedillo, had already
made his selection in a de facto dedazo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe a real democracy exists within the official
party (the PRI),'' said Antonio Reyes, a Mexico City chemical
engineer, whose views reflect that current of disbelief among
Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the method they're using to choose their candidate is
the same that it's always been,'' Reyes added. ``They've just
dressed up the 'dedazo' so they can say there is more democracy.
They've got four pseudo-candidates, but we all know who is already
the one who is going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Unusually aggressive campaigning by one candidate _ Roberto
Madrazo _ has convinced people that the competition among the PRI
is real, Licona said. But most people seem to believe that
Madrazo's chief rival, Francisco Labastida, already has the
election in the bag because he appears to be the favorite choice of
President Zedillo and the PRI elite.
</P>
<P>
   During a televised debate in September, the four PRI contenders
displayed unusual hostility and criticism toward one another.
Madrazo attacked Labastida with unprecedented vigor, challenging
his competence. Labastida shot back by labeling Madrazo a two-faced
liar.
</P>
<P>
   It was a rare display of competition that was billed as a sign
of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   But Ramirez de la O said he found himself staring at the screen,
searching for hints that the whole primary campaign was a ruse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think now that Madrazo's campaign has been sincere,'' he
said. ``But the possibility of a negotiation with the government
(for a powerful position if he loses) is still one of the cards
Madrazo has to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Licona was even more blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The internal election of the PRI is perceived as fraudulent
and dishonest and already fixed,'' he said. ``In Mexico we've never
believed in elections. We've always thought there was fraud by the
PRI. And so now people are supposed to believe in an election run
by the PRI itself?''
</P>
<P>
   Because Mexico's election laws do not govern primaries, the
party will supervise the balloting on Nov. 7. Betting much of their
party's bid for more credibility on the primary, the party's
leaders have pledged to make the election as clean as possible.
Polls show Labastida and Madrazo running about even. Insiders are
predicting that about 80 percent of those who turn out to vote will
be PRI loyalists. If they are not satisfied that the results were
legitimate, there is a chance the PRI could fracture into
quarreling camps and go into next summer's election weakened.
</P>
<P>
   Cecilia Martinez, an 82-year-old grandmother, says she won't be
one of those who goes to the polls on Nov. 7 or on July 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every election (presidential) candidates promise change, and
then they end their terms with things worse off than when they
started,'' she said. ``They say their party (the PRI) has changed.
But I'm old and I see the same deception I've seen every election.
Why pretend when we already know who is going to win?''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
