<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3956 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-RUSSIA-HIGHTECH-$ADV2     10-21 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-HIGHTECH-$ADV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA STRUGGLES TO KEEP UP IN HIGH-TECH WORLD
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-CHIP-$ADV24.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Oct. 24 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In a lab on the outskirts of Moscow, technicians clad
in white coats and peering through microscopes are busy assembling
tiny, wristwatch-like computers, part of a transportation safety
system that could save lives.
</P>
<P>
   In another part of the city, in a stylish office building near
the Moscow River, the man known as the father of the Soviet Union's
supercomputers, is now the proprietor of a thriving high-tech
company. Boris Babayan boasts that his microprocessor design could
make computers run at least twice as fast as anything U.S. giant
Intel Corp. is producing.
</P>
<P>
   In the troubled transition from communism to democracy, Russia
suffers profound economic and social problems of unemployment,
under-funded education and health problems like alcoholism. The
faulty economy has resulted in a brain drain to the West over the
past decade, with many of Russia's best minds taking their talents
to America and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the bad news, there are plenty of smart people left
in Russia who believe that their ideas can change the world, if
only they had some venture capital and a workable economy in which
to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the new challenge in Russia. You have to be active and
entrepreneurial. You can succeed, but you cannot just wait for
things to happen,'' said Nikolai Rogalev, who manages Izmaylovo
Science Park in Moscow, an American-style office cluster which
houses six small high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   The park was started in part with the assistance of the
University of Texas at Austin and its IC2 Institute, which promotes
and assists science and technology commercialization in America and
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to help Russia develop its high-tech potential, much of
the U.S. effort has centered on converting the Soviet Cold War
military machine to commercial enterprises. In his State of the
Union address this year, U.S. President Bill Clinton called for
spending $4.2 billion over the next five years to continue a
program to help Russia convert plants to civilian use, store its
nuclear materials safely and put its scientists to work.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, U.S. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson dedicated
a new supercomputer center in the formerly closed city of Sarov,
where Soviet scientists developed the nuclear bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The center is one of five projects planned in Russia under the
Nuclear Cities Initiative. The $30 million U.S. program is aimed at
converting Russia's 10 closed nuclear cities to peacetime work. The
computer center is expected to create 80 technology jobs in its
first year and as many as 650 in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   The IC2 Institute in Austin, will sponsor a workshop Oct. 29-30
in which they'll try to draw together U.S. companies and Russian
brainpower. The conference, entitled: ``Partnering With Russian
Nuclear Cities: Using the Best of Russian Computing and Software
Talent for U.S. Business,'' is co-sponsored by the U.S. Energy
Department's Los Alamos National Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Since the fall of the Soviet Union in 1991, multinationals like
Intel and Sun Microsystems have dabbled in Russia on a modest scale
to tap its brainpower. Sun Microsystems subcontracts software
development out to the Moscow company Elbrus International, run by
Babayan.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, American technology firms looking to
invest overseas or create joint production ventures have avoided
Russia in favor of emerging ``high-tech'' countries like Israel,
India and South Africa, where the risks of economic and political
instability are less.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has been plagued by economic uncertainty and by a bad
reputation as a place to do business, with crime and corruption
rampant. President Boris Yeltsin has been chronically ill for years
and Russia's commitment to democratic reforms has wavered.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. businesses naturally go to where it is easier to do
business and there's a good return on investment,'' said David
Gibson, director of global programs for the IC2 Institute in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are Russians who are working hard, who are educated,
honest, and entrepreneurial and who in relatively small but
important ways are creating wealth and jobs and positive role
models for the new, emerging Russia,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Russian colleges and institutes continue to crank out Ph.Ds who
have solid schooling, if not the kind of advanced computer hardware
to tinker with that their counterparts in America and Europe enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   But among the biggest problems is cultivating the idea among
Russian scientists that they can take an idea and run with it in
the open market.
</P>
<P>
   In Soviet times, graduates were guaranteed jobs in a multitude
of scientific institutes that were heavily subsidized and
controlled. The top talent was sent to work in secretive ``closed''
cities where scientists applied themselves developing computers,
communications, weapons systems and aerospace designs in the Cold
War race.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a leftover sentiment from the Soviet period _
that it is bad to be a salesman. You want to be a researcher, a
scientist, an engineer, but you don't go out and promote yourself
and your ideas,'' said Rogalev.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, Ivan Servyukov, 57, was an engineer working
in the obscurity of the Soviet aerospace effort building
communications systems for the Mir space station.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he and a group of younger colleagues are building on an
idea that he believes could make a profit in the world market, and
save lives.
</P>
<P>
   Their small company, Neurocom, operates from the Izmalovo
Science Park, near one of Moscow's most prestigious technical
colleges. There, it produces a wristwatch-like device that measures
the skin's electrical resistance. A tiny radio transmitter sends
the data to a microprocessor that in turn displays the wearer's
state of alertness.
</P>
<P>
   The contraption was designed as a safety device for pilots,
train engineers and long-haul truckers, giving them bio-feedback on
their state of awareness and _ in the case of train operators in
Russia, where the system is already in use _ shutting down the
locomotive should the instrument's measurement suggest the driver
is about to fall asleep.
</P>
<P>
   At a price of US$2,000 per unit, Servyukov hopes his gadget will
become successful first in the former Soviet Union, and then
perhaps spread to Western Europe and America. The idea is a good
one, he insists. All he needs is money to market the device, and
the chance to prove that it works.
</P>
<P>
   In the offices of the computer guru, Babayan, software engineers
and technicians huddle around glowing monitors. It is the kind of
humming workplace of computers and cubicles that would be right at
home in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are quite successful. But the main problem is money. We are
in Russia and maybe (potential investors) are afraid of that,''
said Babayan. ``We have a saying in Russia: 'Hope dies last.'''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
