<HEADER>
A3965 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-RUSSIA-CHIP-$ADV24-CO     10-21 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHIP-$ADV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MOVE OVER PENTIUM, RUSSIA MAY HAVE SOMETHING FASTER
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-HIGHTECH-$ADV24.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Oct. 24 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Imagine your computer running at least twice as fast as
it does now, maybe even faster.
</P>
<P>
   Move over Pentium. Move over Athlon. Is there an E2k chip in
your future?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not. But a Russian computer designer has invented a
microprocessor that he thinks could revolutionize the speed of the
world's computers, if only he had the financial backing to develop
it.
</P>
<P>
   The computer chip's architecture is radically different from
anything in production in the West. It is the brainchild of Boris
Babayan - known as the father of the Soviet supercomputer _ and his
team. They believe the microprocessor would be more powerful,
smaller, less susceptible to computer viruses and at least twice as
fast as other designs.
</P>
<P>
   The race is on. Intel is developing a new-generation chip called
Merced, believed to be akin in design to Babayan's project.
Likewise, other upstart microprocessor designers in the West are
experimenting with the next level of super-fast computers.
</P>
<P>
   Without backing, the Russian project will never get out of the
blocks. Babayan's company, Elbrus International, estimates that it
needs roughly $60 million and three years to convert its design to
a finished product for the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Today, at work dressed in jeans and a plaid cotton shirt, the
65-year-old Babayan looks nothing like a career Soviet egghead. But
that was his function until Communism began to crack a decade ago.
From the 1950s until the 1980s, Babayan and his team helped produce
three generations of Soviet supercomputers, including the ones that
ran the missile-defense system.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Soviet Union began to crumble, the team began to
design a microprocessor that, in theory, would outpace anything the
West had to offer at the time. Babayan went on to found Elbrus, a
private company, and the chip design has become the E2k.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the company has subcontracted to U.S. companies like
Sun Microsystems, developing software as its main source of income.
Elbrus employs 400 engineers, software writers and technicians at
three locations in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The work is steady and welcomed amid Russia's ongoing economic
crisis, Babayan says, but with E2k ``we could make history.'' He
hopes to have partners or financial backers by the end of the year,
acknowledging that if his company cannot develop the chip soon, it
will be overtaken by fast-evolving computer innovations elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The E2k may be more hype than hyperdrive, but some industry
analysts believe his microprocessor design is on the cutting edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the E2k never sees the light of day, it is a
fascinating device on technical grounds, and it could be a
harbinger of things to come,'' wrote Keith Diefendorff in the
respected Microprocessor Report, a U.S.-based trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
