</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-MILLENNIUM-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   In a series of technology-related think-pieces, The New York
Times Magazine has attempted to trace the evolution and influence
of science and technology.
</P>
<P>
   The articles described below have been written for the
``Millennium Issues'' of the magazine and are available for oneshot
purchase from The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   For purchase information, contact one of the following New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
</P>
<P>
   _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   _ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   _ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WILL THE INTERNET MARK A TURNING POINT FOR WOMEN?
 &UR; (1,300 words)
 &UR; By ESTHER DYSON
</P>
<P>
   Women now get the mike at business conferences in part because
organizers are consciously trying to balance things, and in part
because many of us simply deserve it _ but over all, women still
have trouble being heard. Can cyberspace change that? Powerful
tools in powerful hands tend to increase the concentration of
power, but the Internet isn't just a tool. It's a medium that may
change the balance of power.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-CYBERSPACE)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SEEKING CONTEMPLATION.COM, AWAY FROM THE ALL-SURROUNDING BUZZ
 &UR; (1,200 words)
 &UR; By PICO IYER
</P>
<P>
   The fact that we can get a connection to anywhere today, almost
instantly, means that we can be got anywhere, all the time. And the
fact that friends and bosses can find us so easily means that it is
ever more difficult to get lost amid the beepers, cell phones and
modems. But at a Benedictine hermitage 1,300 feet above the Pacific
Ocean on the California coast, tolling bells mark out a centered
universe.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-ADVENTURE-TECH)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EINSTEIN'S QUESTION: DID GOD HAVE A CHOICE?
 &UR; (1,000 words)
 &UR; By DENNIS OVERBYE
</P>
<P>
   ``What interests me,'' Albert Einstein once remarked, ``is
whether God had any choice in the creation of the world.'' The
question was just his way of asking whether the universe could be
any other way than it appears to be -- and if not, how much room
remains for chance and miracles? There is no reason to think we
will ever be Godlike enough in our comprehension to unlock this
cosmic secret. It may be that humans are fated only to know many
small truths rather than the one big truth, as we spin off
``marvels'' like space flight and the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-QUESTION)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFTER ALL THESE YEARS, HUMAN CONSCIOUSNESS IS STILL TERRA INCOGNITA
 &UR; (2,400 words)
 &UR; By GEORGE JOHNSON
</P>
<P>
   Standing among the ruins of Yapashi, in northern New Mexico, you
can almost feel the presence of the souls who inhabited this
abandoned plateau many hundreds of years ago. What were these
people thinking as they looked out at the distant mountains and up
at the stars? What might they still teach us about the nature of
human consciousness?
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged: BC-MILLEN-ME-JOHNSON-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GUTENBERG DIDN'T INVENT THE PRINTING PRESS
 &UR; (1,500 words)
 &UR; By JARED DIAMOND
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, the printing press is one of the greatest inventions
in history. Just think of its enormous consequences. Without
printing, millions of people wouldn't have read Martin Luther's 95
Theses, the Declaration of Independence, the Communist Manifesto or
other world-changing texts. Without printing, we wouldn't have
modern science. But Johannes Gutenberg does not deserve sole credit
for inventing it. He reinvented a technique previously developed in
Minoan Crete around 1700 B.C., if not long before that.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-INVENTION)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JOURNEY TO THE CENTER OF MY MIND
 &UR; (4,000 words)
 &UR; By STEPHEN S. HALL
</P>
<P>
   Of all the frontiers that await exploration, perhaps no other is
more intriguing than the terra incognita that lies between our
ears. Brain scans can locate the home of memory and the land of
language. They may eventually help to map consciousness. In this
article the author enters a Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI)
machine at Memorial Sloan Cancer Center in New York to set out on a
journey to the center of his mind.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-ADVENTURE-BRAIN)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHEN WE LEARNED TO SEE FASTER
 &UR; (2,800 words)
 &UR; By JAMES GLEICK
</P>
<P>
   Partway through the millennium, we figured out how to shape and
polish glass so as to see far and to see small. We noticed quasars
and we noticed viruses. Then _ and more importantly _ we learned to
see faster. Our sight expanded into the fourth dimension. We could
freeze time, expanding the reach of our eyesight in the temporal
domain, as microscopes and telescopes had expanded it in a spatial
one.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENIUM-SCENES-GLEICK)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW A CASE OF SMALLPOX LED TO THE MOST MODERN OF MEDICINES
 &UR; (450 words)
 &UR; By DR. JEROME GROOPMAN
</P>
<P>
   In 1796 Edward Jenner tried the first smallpox vaccine. Its
success signaled the first step in medicine's control over the
microbial world _ one that led to the discovery of safe,
inexpensive and effective vaccines. But the conquest of smallpox
had begun some 80 years earlier, with the disfigurement of Lady
Mary Wortley Montagu, a noted beauty of the time.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-MEDICINE)
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
