A3986 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-HALLOWEEN-COSTUMES-LA     10-21 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALLOWEEN-COSTUMES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE TRICK-OR-TREAT BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
Eds: note call for italics below. 
 
 
 
 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Little ballerinas, ghosts and superheroes may find
it a bit crowded on the trick-or-treat trail this year.
</P>
<P>
   They, and other traditional costumes such as witches, devils and
demons, have some major competition.
</P>
<P>
   It's Pokemon, that little computer game twerp with a tail,
reports Steve Moylan, spokesman for Mervyn's California stores. And
right behind him in popularity, says Moylan, are ``Star Wars''
characters such as Queen Amidala, Anakin Skywalker and Darth Maul.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same story at Target stores. ``Everybody wants Pokemon.
It's the hottest seller ever, but we're sold out and don't expect
any more deliveries,'' said Target's Woodland Hills store manager
Chan Parks. He says he has no idea why the costume is more popular
than others, such as the also-cuddly Furby and Teletubbies, but
reports the biggest Pokemon fans are boys under 10 who also collect
the Pokemon trading cards.
</P>
<P>
   Can't find a costume? Run to your nearest fabric store. They've
got patterns for those who can sew and wield a hot glue gun. Even
Pokemon and the more intricate ``Star Wars'' patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Why not a ghost or goblin?
</P>
<P>
   According to Home Sewing Association spokeswoman Judy
Mayenhofer, ``Trick-or-treaters celebrating the final Halloween
before the millennium will be struck by movie madness. Characters
from hit films, clever cartoons and TV shows are the
front-runners.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pokemon and his pals are just kid stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The really big deal is adult-sized monsters, mummies, aliens,
wrestlers, clowns and sexy devils who are horning their way into
the holiday ritual. We're talking (BEGIN ITAL)really(END ITAL) big
costumes, even a new line by Disguise Inc. (one of the nation's
leading costume manufacturers), that caters to plus-size women who
want to dress up as French maids or witches.
</P>
<P>
   Adults are also following that movies-for-the-millennium theme
at costume rental places. ``This year, it's costumes with a French
court theme from `Interview With the Vampire,' `Dangerous
Liaisons,' and the new KCET series `Aristocrats' that customers
want,'' says Jenny Eagan, manager of the Halloween division of
Western Costumes in North Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Think all this Halloween hooey is just media hype?
</P>
<P>
   According to the 1999 American Express Retail Index, 54 percent
of all consumers feel Halloween has become as much a holiday for
adults as for kids. And that's up from 48 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   So that means more costumed characters ringing doorbells and
vying for treats.
</P>
<P>
   The Halloween Association (yes, there really is one that works
as a clearinghouse for the costume trade) estimates that we're
spending about $1.5 billion annually on costumes, with 82 percent
of all children dressing up and 73 percent of all adults.
</P>
<P>
   American Express' report breaks that down to an average spending
spree of $98 per family, which doesn't go very far, since most
costumes are priced from $16 to $35, with accessories priced
separately.
</P>
<P>
   Then crank in the baby factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that parents would wait until their children
were toddlers to get them dressed up. Now adults are taking their
children more places, and they want them to look stylish. It's
definitely a case of have baby, will travel,'' says Jeff Coppens,
spokesman for Disguise Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the family who trick-or-treats together stays together. At
least parents will have their own candy stash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
