<SLUG> BC-DOLE-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE ENDS WHITE HOUSE BID, CITES BUSH MONEY MACHINE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican presidential field shrunk again
Wednesday as Elizabeth Dole abandoned her pioneering quest for the
White House because, she said, she was unable to compete with
George W. Bush's mighty money machine.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Dole, who had been running a distant second to
Bush in most polls, is likely to further strengthen the Texas
governor's front-runner status as the 2000 primary season
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   However, political experts said they were uncertain if many of
the young, independent female voters that Dole drew to her rallies
will remain engaged in the contest.
</P>
<P>
   Although she declined to endorse any of her rivals or discuss
future plans, Dole's decision to bow out stoked speculation that
she may want to be Bush's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   In her announcement, Dole took a subtle dig at Bush by noting
that the emphasis on his war chest made it harder for her to get
her message out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line remains money,'' she told a roomful of
reporters at a Washington hotel. ``There (is a tendency to make)
money the message ... And people outside the Beltway don't really
understand why their enthusiasm and these big crowds isn't the
measure of success.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole's departure may boost the presidential campaign fortunes of
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a maverick lawmaker who appeals to
independents and who has already replaced Dole as Bush's major
threat in the first primary state of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Her quitting also underscores what some experts believe is a
worrisome trend in presidential politics, where the need to raise
lots of cash early to compete in an increasingly front-loaded
primary season has forced many candidates out months before the
first votes are cast.
</P>
<P>
   Already the Republican field has dwindled from a dozen
candidates earlier this year to half that now. The remaining
contenders include Bush, McCain, millionaire magazine publisher
Steve Forbes, who is financing most of his own campaign;
conservative activists Gary Bauer, Alan Keyes and Utah Sen. Orrin
Hatch.
</P>
<P>
   Another former GOP candidate, conservative firebrand Pat
Buchanan, is expected to announce Monday that he will seek the
Reform Party nomination.
</P>
<P>
   A 63-year old Harvard Law School graduate who served in the
Reagan and Bush Cabinets, Dole enjoyed an initial burst of positive
media attention and voter interest last winter when she announced
she was leaving as head of the Red Cross to explore a presidential
bid.
</P>
<P>
   She had burnished her public image earlier with a polished
performance during the 1996 Republican convention where she roamed
the arena in talk-show like fashion touting the virtues of her
husband, GOP nominee Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   As the novelty wore off over the spring and summer, her
candidacy could not gain traction. Political experts attributed it
to poor organization, lack of a compelling message and inability to
compete with Bush's unprecedented fund-raising. Even a strong third
place showing in the Iowa straw poll in August did not direct the
money to her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of September, Bush had raised $56 million compared
with Dole's $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, who on the stump often spoke of her achievements in
overcoming gender barriers, said she did not believe that her
pulling out of the race would discourage other young women about
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we've done is pave the way for the person who
will be the first woman president,'' Dole said, adding that when
she addressed largely female crowds, ``it's almost as if you see
some women sitting up a little straighter because you're trying to
empower them to understand that they can do it; they can really
make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   During her withdrawal speech, Dole praised her husband, the
former Senate Republican leader, who stood behind her as she spoke
and even appeared tearful. But Bob Dole had made public comments
that undermined his wife's efforts. He publicly raised doubts that
she could win and said he would contribute $1,000 to McCain's rival
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Others said that while Dole's complaints about fund-raising are
valid, she also must share some of the blame for failing to
capitalize on the initial burst of publicity.
</P>
<P>
   The experts said she was not prepared to set up the state
organizations needed to marshal volunteers and build support. A
demanding boss, she suffered from high staff turnover that included
the loss of her press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   A North Carolina native who has spent most of her adult years in
Washington, Dole rarely deviated from her well-scripted speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Her fall in fortunes in New Hampshire, the first primary state,
are particularly striking. According to a poll released Wednesday
by the American Research Group, Dole was garnering only 3 percent
of the primary vote, tying for fourth place with Keyes. Last
February, the poll showed Dole with 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While Dole has frequently been mentioned as a possible running
mate for Bush, the Texas governor did not broach the issue at a
campaign appearance in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush called Dole ``a trailblazer. She is an inspiration for a
lot of women. She made a mark on the political process.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican political consultant Whit Ayres said he believed
Dole's supporters would split among Bush and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
