<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   Religion and spirituality have been powerful social and
political forces throughout the millennium. In a series of
articles, The New York Times Magazine looks at their impact on our
modern landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The articles described below have been written for the
``Millennium Issues'' of the magazine and are available for oneshot
purchase from The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   For purchase information, contact one of the following New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
</P>
<P>
   _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   _ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   _ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CRUSADES, EVEN NOW, CHURN MODERN LIFE
 &UR; (1,700 words)
 &UR; By KAREN ARMSTRONG
</P>
<P>
   When Pope Urban II summoned the knights of Europe to take part
in the First Crusade in November 1095, he could not have imagined
the enduring effects of his enterprise. The pope hoped a crusade
would bring peace to war-torn Europe and enhance the power of the
Western church. Instead of fighting one another in pointless feudal
wars, the pope believed, the knights should join forces, march to
Jerusalem and rescue Christ's tomb from the infidels. He had
envisioned a conventional military campaign but found to his
astonishment that he had launched a mass movement. With the
Crusades, the West found its soul. But it is their tragic legacy
that is felt most keenly today, particularly in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged MILLENNIUM-SCENES-ARMSTRONG)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LIVES OF THE MYSTIC SAINTS OFFER A CRUEL LESSON FOR TODAY'S
WOMEN
 &UR; (3,600 words)
 &UR; By JENNIFER EGAN
</P>
<P>
   An appetite for self-mortification would prove one of the Saint
Catherine of Siena's most enduring traits, and would lead to her
death, at 33, of starvation. In this respect, Catherine's behavior
in the 14th century foreshadowed that of a great many women today
for whom power and suffering _ often self-inflicted _ are curiously
intertwined. Modern-day anorexics, bulimics and self-injurers
experience an illusion of control through disciplining or
mutilating their bodies, echoing the pious self-punishments of
Catherine's time. The lives of Catherine and other saints like her
can help to explain why these impulses persist among women _ from
athletes and models to Princess Diana _ when both the world and the
position of women in it have been radically transformed.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-SAINTS)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EINSTEIN'S QUESTION: DID GOD HAVE A CHOICE?
 &UR; (1,000 words)
 &UR; By DENNIS OVERBYE
</P>
<P>
   ``What interests me,'' Albert Einstein once remarked, ``is
whether God had any choice in the creation of the world.'' The
question was just his way of asking whether the universe could be
any other way than it appears to be -- and if not, how much room
remains for chance and miracles? There is no reason to think we
will ever be Godlike enough in our comprehension to unlock this
cosmic secret. It may be that humans are fated only to know many
small truths rather than the one big truth, as we spin off
``marvels'' like space flight and the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-QUESTION)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ON THE ROAD WITH ST. FRANCIS of ASSISI
 &UR; (4,000 words)
 &UR; By GRETEL EHRLICH
</P>
<P>
   The road from Assisi to Gubbio is sometimes a footpath, a horse
track, a Roman street and now, a gravel road that winds through
peaks and valleys dotted with tiny farms and fortresslike
monasteries where 13th-century travelers could spend the night. It
is called the Sentiero Francescano della Pace because it is the
path that Francesco di Bernardone _ better known as St. Francis _
is believed to have taken after he stood naked in Assisi's central
piazza, renounced family and friends and set out on the journey
that effectively defined the rest of his life as wanderer, seeker,
ultimately saint. What is it in a life that leads a medieval
playboy to sainthood, and where does the path begin? That's what
Gretel Ehrlich wondered 800 years later as she stepped onto the
Sentiero and followed Francesco's footsteps out of Assisi.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POPE CELESTINE V WAS AN UNWILLING HOLY MAN
 &UR; (500 words)
 &UR; By A.N. Wilson
</P>
<P>
   Celestine V, the only pope in history to have resigned, is the
millennium's best pontiff, according to the author A.N. Wilson. The
85-year-old peasant mystic was elected in 1294, at a time when the
papal throne had been empty for two years, thanks to infighting by
the Mafia-style bosses who ran the medieval church. He resigned
five months later. Dante placed him in Hell for his gran rifuito,
his abdication. But this was an unwilling holy man who knew there
was no meeting place between the pursuit of power and the worship
of God.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-POPE)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `CITY ON A HILL' SERMON OFFERED THE BIBLE AS CIVIC BLUEPRINT
 &UR; (1,500 words)
 &UR; By PETER J. GOMES
</P>
<P>
   The definitive sermon of the last 1,000 years was delivered in
1630 when the layman Robert Winthrop, governor of the Massachusetts
Bay Colony, preached to his fellow immigrants while still at sea
aboard the ship Arbella. ``Christian Charity: A Model Hereof,'' is
what Winthrop called his sermon, and it would have languished in
obscurity were it not for its felicitous use of a biblical image _
that of the ``city set on a hill'' _ to describe the moral purpose
of the Pilgrims' adventure into the unknown. That image, familiar
to generations of Christians from Jesus' ``Sermon on the Mount'' in
Matthew's gospel, is what gave Winthrop's sermon life. And it
provided perhaps the most enduring metaphor of the American
experience, that of the exemplary nation _ the ``city on a hill''
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged MILLENNIUM-BEST-SERMON)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SEEKING CONTEMPLATION.COM, AWAY FROM THE ALL-SURROUNDING BUZZ
 &UR; (1,200 words)
 &UR; By PICO IYER
</P>
<P>
   The fact that we can get a connection to anywhere today, almost
instantly, means that we can be got anywhere, all the time. And the
fact that friends and bosses can find us so easily means that it is
ever more difficult to get lost amid the beepers, cell phones and
modems. But at a Benedictine hermitage 1,300 feet above the Pacific
Ocean on the California coast, tolling bells mark out a centered
universe.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-ADVENTURE-TECH)
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times Syndicate
</P>
