<HEADER>
A4013 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-REFLECT-MILLENNIUM-AD     10-21 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFLECT-MILLENNIUM-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   The special ``Millennium Issues'' of The New York Times Magazine
have sought to step back and reflect on some of the ``big picture''
questions and concerns: Is this the best of all possible times?
Could God have done it differently? What are the developments that
made us what we are?
</P>
<P>
   The thought-provoking articles described below are available for
oneshot purchase from The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   For purchase information, contact one of the following New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
</P>
<P>
   _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   _ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   _ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEST TIME TO BE ALIVE? `NO TIME LIKE THE PAST'
 &UR; (1,900 words)
 &UR; (A Panel moderated by RUSSELL BAKER) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Has there been in the last thousand years a single best time to
be alive? In this age of faith in progress, it's easy to answer
quickly: Yes, right now. But does that response stand up to
informed comparison with past times? How about the Ming Dynasty? Or
Puritan New England? To answer this tantalizing question,
Pulitzer-Prize winning columnist Russell Baker moderates a panel
discussion of brilliant scholars who tell us when and where they'd
have lived, given the choice. 1,900 words.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-TIME)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEST QUESTION: DID GOD HAVE A CHOICE?
 &UR; (1,000 words)
 &UR; By DENNIS OVERBYE
</P>
<P>
   ``What interests me,'' Albert Einstein once remarked, ``is
whether God had any choice in the creation of the world.'' The
question was just his way of asking whether the universe could be
any other way than it appears to be -- and if not, how much room
remains for chance and miracles? There is no reason to think we
will ever be Godlike enough in our comprehension to recognize the
cosmic secret. It may be that humans are fated only to know many
small truths rather than the one big truth, as we spin off
``marvels'' like space flight and the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-QUESTION)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MOST IMPORTANT CONCEPT OF THE MILLENNIUM
 &UR; (3,000 words)
 &UR; By RICHARD POWERS
</P>
<P>
   The most important idea of this millennium was set in motion by
a man named Abu Ali al-Hasan Ibn al-Haytham, born around the year
965. The idea he championed is so ingrained in us that we don't
even think of it as an innovation. But he resolved a scientific
dispute that had remained deadlocked for more than 800 years, using
observation rather than reason. Over the course of 1,000 years,
this conceptual shift would would transform every aspect of
existence.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-CONCEPT)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE IMPACT OF PRINTING WAS ENORMOUS, BUT GUTENBERG DIDN'T INVENT IT
 &UR; (1,500 words)
 &UR; By JARED DIAMOND
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, the printing press is one of the greatest inventions
in history. Just think of its enormous consequences. Without
printing, millions of people wouldn't have read Martin Luther's 95
Theses, the Declaration of Independence, the Communist Manifesto or
other world-changing texts. Without printing, we wouldn't have
modern science. But Johannes Gutenberg does not deserve sole credit
for inventing it. He reinvented a technique previously developed in
Minoan Crete around 1700 B.C., if not long before that.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-INVENTION)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRUE LOVE MAY LAST FOREVER, BUT IT HASN'T BEEN AROUND THAT LONG
 &UR; (1,100 words)
 &UR; By JOYCE CAROL OATES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Love in the Western world has come to mean, in the popular
imagination, romantic love almost exclusively. But it may come as a
surprise to learn that the very concept of ``love'' based on
emotion as a high value, and not as an outlaw passion, is
relatively new in the history of mankind. In the ancient world,
romantic love would seem to have been virtually unknown, and rarely
celebrated. Our generic term ``love'' didn't exist. The sentiment
of romantic love as we know it was the homoerotic love of older
Greek men for boys. Marital love, which surely existed, seems oddly
not to have been much honored, at least in surviving literature.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-IDEA)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO WAS THE BEST LEADER OF THE MILLENNIUM?
 &UR; (500 Words)
 &UR; BY GAIL COLLINS
</P>
<P>
   ``Just look how well she governs,'' the once-reluctant subjects
of Elizabeth I, the Virgin Queen, later would remark. For the
ravishing ruler exceeded all expectations, and by now she is
namesake to an era.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-LEADER)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEST RANDOM SHOT IN HISTORY?
 &UR; (500 words)
 &UR; By CHARLES McGRATH
</P>
<P>
   A nameless bowman in the forests of Normandy took a random shot
and from 100 yards pierced the right eye of King Harold of England.
It was during the Battle of Hastings in 1066, and that arrow in the
eye changed the English language.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-SHOT)
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times Syndicate
</P>
<P>
   (New York headquarters: 212-499-3300 or 1-800-972-3550; fax,
212-499-3382.)
</P>
<P>
   Visit our Web site at http://nytimes.com/syndicate.
</P>
