<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, Oct. 22:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-POLITICS (Jakarta) _ Megawati Sukarnoputri was elected
vice president of Indonesia, easing tensions; other political
developments. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ASSESS (Jakarta) _ A news analysis on the election of
Wahid and Megawati. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   ALBRIGHT-AID (Washington) _ Secretary of State Albright is
harshly critical of Congress' foreign aid cuts, noting that
Americans have the world's greatest economy while Africans ``are
left to dig themselves out of garbage.'' By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-U.N. (United Nations) _ The United Nations on Friday will
appoint an administrator for East Timor. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Developments on spending bills;
including action on the Interior Department's appropriations bill.
By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Senate votes to ban
partial-birth abortion, but falls short of the total necessary to
override an expected Clinton veto. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House is expected to pass an
education bill. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-CARE (Washington) _ A 20-year study shows early-childhood
education dramatically affects success. Researchers at the
University of North Carolina followed 111 poor, African-American
babies, half of whom had high-quality child care from infancy. As
they turn 21, those in the child-care program are more likely to be
in college or have graduated (35 percent compared to 14 percent)
and hold jobs (65 percent versus 50 percent). They also have higher
IQs (by 14 points) and, on average, had their first baby at age 19
rather than 17. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   WVA-STRIP-MINING (Washington) _ A federal judge has ruled that
West Virginia cannot issue strip mining permits for projects that
use stream beds to dispose of rock and dirt, a decision a state
official said would affect all mining in the state.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   COLO-COLUMBINE-THREAT (Denver) _ After a Columbine High School
student was arrested on charges he said he would ``finish the
job,'' only half the students showed up for classes on Thursday. By
Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   TEAMSTER-TRIAL (New York) _ Federal prosecutors make opening
statements in the trial of William Hamilton, the Teamsters' former
political director, who is charged with helping divert union money
toward the campaign of Ron Carey, the former president. By Steven
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-ENVIRON (Rye, N.J.) _ Al Gore says he will ban new offshore
oil drilling, including in tracts where oil companies have already
paid $1.2 billion for drilling rights off California, Florida and
other states. With the move Gore hopes to nail down the elusive
support of environmentalists, which he had initially taken for
granted. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-POVERTY (New York) _ John Kennedy said America had to
race for the moon; Bill Bradley, seeking to similarly shape a broad
national goal, said the target now should be to reduce poverty
among children. Bradley calls child poverty a ``slow-motion
national disaster.'' By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ALZHEIMER (Undated) _ New findings on brain development open
up possibilities for treating Alzheimer's. By Gina Kolata. (1000
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OLDEST-DINOSAURS (Undated) _ Fossils from two calf-sized
animals that lived in a period before the Jurassic era are thought
to be the oldest dinosaur remains ever found, researchers report
Friday in Science. The upper and lower jaw bones, from two new
dinosaur species, are more than 227 million years old and shed
light on the time when dinosaurs were dividing into the meat-eaters
and the plant-eaters. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-JOURNAL-ETHICS (Undated) _ The New England Journal of
Medicine said Thursday that it is developing new ethical guidelines
for its reviewers. The announcement follows a Los Angeles Times
report that the journal apparently violated its own strict
disclosure policy by publishing articles from researchers whose
ties to drug companies were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BANKS-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The conference committee that is
putting the final touches on a bill overhauling the nation's
financial system meets again. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   With sidebars as warranted.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks were down, led by a slump in
computing stocks. At 1:20 p.m., the Dow Jones industrial average
was down 129 points, the S&AMP;P 500 down 12 points and Nasdaq down 15
points. European markets were also lower: London down 1.02 percent
and Frankfurt 1.44 percent. Tokyo's Nikkei closed down 0.49 percent
and Hong Kong closed up 0.20 percent. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-CHIPS (Singapore) _ The personal-computer industry has
a variety of things to worry about this holiday season, but supply
problems from last month's deadly earthquake in Taiwan may not be
one of them. Although several American companies have warned that
semiconductor shortages could crimp earnings and make it hard to
meet demand for personal computers this Christmas, some of the
biggest suppliers to those companies say a month later that they
are not only back to normal, but filled most of their September
orders. By Martin Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   SYCAMORE-IPO (Undated) _ Looking at the much anticipated initial
public offering of Sycamore Networks, the first big name in the
small, but growing optical network industry to go public. These
companies make products that transport voice and data over
wavelengths of light. Sycamore starts trading on Friday. By Seth
Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MEDICARE (Undated) _ Reflecting a widespread health-care
trend, the Clinton administration is asking Congress to offer the
most popular and least disciplined type of managed care as an
option in the Federal Medicare program. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly economics column by Floyd
Norris.
</P>
<P>
   MATTEL-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Mattel says third-quarter profit
fell 42 percent on slow software sales, and warns that earnings for
the year will be lower than expected. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Coca-Cola reports an 8.8 percent
decline in third-quarter earnings, matching expectations, because
of slow sales in Eastern Europe, Turkey and Russia and a recall in
Europe. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   IRS-CHARITY (Undated) _ The government is moving to shut down
the latest version of the accelerated charitable remainder trust,
sometimes known as the ``chutzpah trust,'' under which a legitimate
charitable giving device is used to let wealthy donors escape
capital gains taxes. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   MONSANTO-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Monsanto reports a third-quarter
profit from continuing operations, a turnaround from a loss a year
ago, but less than expected.
</P>
<P>
   REUTERS-WARNING (Undated) _ Shares of Reuters Group tumble as
much as 14 percent in London after the company says U.S. sales
growth at its Instinet electronic trading division stalled in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   MANNESMANN-ORANGE (London) _ Mannesmann of Germany agrees to buy
Orange, Britain's third-largest cellular operator, for $36 billion.
By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   VIACOM-EARNINGS (New York) _ Viacom Inc. says third-quarter
profit rose 28 percent, in line with expectations, led by higher
advertising revenue at its MTV and VH1 cable-television networks.
By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The weekly marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   A.M. Rosenthal's ``On My Mind'' and Gail Collins' ``Public
Interest.''
</P>
<P>
