<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4026 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-GAYS-RETIRE-ART-BOS &LR;      10-21 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-RETIRE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY COMMUNITY MARKS OUT FUTURE HOME FOR ELDERLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In 1969, when police raided the Stonewall Inn in New
York's Greenwich Village, its gay patrons believed they were
harassed because of their lifestyle and vowed not to let it happen
again.
</P>
<P>
   It was a watershed event that helped to politicize gays and
lesbians around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Some say Boston will soon be the site of another defining moment
in gay and lesbian history: Stonewall Communities, a retirement
community like no other.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project will give gays and lesbians one of the first
visionary models for a community that draws on the best in
retirement thinking done to this point, and tailors it to us,''
said Janet Stambolian, 51, director of a design and construction
company in Burlington, Vt., and one of the organizers of the new
community.
</P>
<P>
   But although the ideas animating this community may be radical,
it is not intended as a home for radicals, or necessarily even for
activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also want to evoke the comfort and practicality of a good
New England stone wall,'' said David Aronstein, 47, of Boston, a
social worker and managing partner in the new venture, which
organizers hope will provide 70 to 100 ``gay-friendly'' units in
about four years in the heart of downtown Boston.
</P>
<P>
   As baby boomers move into old age, a growing number of elders,
including gays and lesbians, are looking to have their housing
needs met. This construction project reflects one of the biggest
changes in the gay and lesbian community, which is becoming more
confident and more demanding in asserting its needs.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Census Bureau and the Human Rights Campaign, a
gay rights group in Washington, D.C., the number of people who are
openly gay and over 65 will jump from at least 1.6 million to 3.5
million in the next 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   While gay seniors in the past often felt they had to keep their
sexual preferences hidden, the generation that followed them has
experienced more social approval and ``a more tribal lifestyle,''
said John Goode, 47, a real estate agent for Hunneman-Coldwell
Banker in the South End and another managing partner in the
Stonewall venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby boomers are redefining everything, including what it
means to retire,'' Goode said. ``We're out to change the
paradigm.''
</P>
<P>
   So, for instance, say goodbye to the notion that retirement
communities should be situated in placid, pastoral areas in the
balmy South or Southwest. These organizers think that living in a
city like Boston, with its vibrant cultural opportunities and urban
conveniences, can help to keep a person young. They don't want to
be cut off from supportive friends and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bond together more than other people because of the things
we've had to go up against,'' Goode said. ``To keep those bonds
strong as we get older, that's the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   But he and others stressed that Stonewall Communities will not
be limited exclusively to gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us have spent our lifetimes fighting discrimination,''
Aronstein said. ``We don't want to start doing it ourselves now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to build a fortress,'' he continued. ``We want
to create a special residential community that's integrated into
its neighborhood, as well as the gay and lesbian community. We want
to encourage diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   And unlike many retirement homes and assisted living facilities,
the Stonewall Communities will be a place where people will choose
to live because it offers opportunities for privacy or for
socializing, a complex of shops and services and homes where the
young-old can go and happily ``age in place,'' Aronstein said.
</P>
<P>
   The project is still in the research phase, so exactly what it
will look like, where it will be located, and how it will be
financed have not yet been determined. But organizers foresee 70 to
100 units, priced for middle and upper-middle income homeowners,
most over 55 years old.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Aronstein said, Stonewall Communities may include:
</P>
<P>
   --A small-business center, with shared office support machines
and services.
</P>
<P>
   --A public day care center, to encourage interaction between
generations.
</P>
<P>
   --A health club with exercise and nursing facilities.
</P>
<P>
   --A community center, including a small auditorium or theater.
</P>
<P>
   --A restaurant, for public and private dining.
</P>
<P>
   --A rooftop garden.
</P>
<P>
   There may also be services not provided at traditional
retirement homes, such as a tool and carpentry shop for women as
well as men.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the development grew out of a survey done in
conjunction with Gerontological Services, Inc., and sent to 3,600
gays and lesbians, age 40 and older, in the six New England states
and upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 328 who responded, 86 percent said they would like to
live in a gay and lesbian environment as they age. Some had heard
stories about harassment of homosexuals at places like Sun City,
Ariz., and some senior housing facilities in the South.
</P>
<P>
   But more were focused on building a community of people who
could age together, openly and creatively.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking for a community that's hard to find,
particularly as they get older,'' Aronstein said. ``They don't want
a retirement home or a leisure resort. They want to redefine what
it means to retire.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
