<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4027 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-LABYRINTH-MOVEMENT-BO     10-21 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABYRINTH-MOVEMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CIRCULAR PATH TO PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWTON, Mass. _ Boston College senior Patrick Hess walks the
labyrinth with his bare feet, the sensation of the cold earth
beneath him adding to ``the most intense'' prayer he's ever
experienced.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Taylor, a junior, has sought out the labyrinth in times of
stress, ``to put things in perspective.'' Graduate student Arwen
Lietz once romped through it at a stormy midnight hour, splashing
through puddles, delighting in her solitude in the black of night.
</P>
<P>
   By walking, dancing, or even crawling through BC's labyrinth,
these students have joined a spiritual movement that is just
catching fire in the United States, even as it harks back to the
practices of religious pilgrims in medieval Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The campus labyrinth, a circle 50 feet in diameter that encloses
a 28-loop path of 300 yards, is based on the labyrinth at Chartres
Cathedral in France and is sponsored by the French honor society Pi
Delta Phi.
</P>
<P>
   But the labyrinth's appeal is much broader. Students say they
find it a peaceful escape during a frenzied time of life when
studying and socializing often leave no room for quiet reflection.
</P>
<P>
   A 4,000- to 5,000-year-old concept, the labyrinth today is a
sensation once again. Enthusiasts say its popularity lies in its
ability to create sanctuary amidst the chaos of modern life.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible to buy a ``finger labyrinth'' _ to be traced with
a finger _ or to sign up for a weekend labyrinth workshop. Prisons
and hospitals have used them, and it has been estimated that 1,000
labyrinths have been constructed in the 1990s in Europe and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College first built a labyrinth last fall, drawing
hundreds of visitors from campus and beyond, according to Pi Delta
Phi's president, Timothy Sullivan, a senior who coordinated the
project along with Romance languages professor Rebecca Valette.
</P>
<P>
   The simple formation of painted lines on the grass _ the same
method used to mark boundaries on a football field _ is back this
month, and will be repainted as necessary every few weeks until the
first snowfall.
</P>
<P>
   A vehicle for meditation is sorely needed on a college campus,
said Sullivan, whose field is art history and French studies.
Sullivan spent his summer doing historical research on labyrinths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life as a college student can be very hectic and stressful,
and that's precisely why the labyrinth holds such an attraction,''
Sullivan said. ``We always have assignments to do and theses to
write and graduate applications to send in. Students want and need
to calm themselves down.''
</P>
<P>
   Labyrinths were a common feature in ancient cultures, say people
who have studied them. Ancient Scandinavian fishermen, for example,
constructed labyrinths on the beach to trap evil spirits and ensure
a safe journey, according to the Reverend Bruce Morrill of Boston
College, who wrote a chapter on labyrinths for a forthcoming book
called ``Bodies of Worship.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite popular usage, the word labyrinth does not necessarily
describe a maze, though in the Greek myth the hero Theseus needed
Ariadne's string to wind his way out of the labyrinth in Crete
after killing the Minotaur. Many may also remember the 1986 Jim
Henson movie ``Labyrinth,'' in which a young girl navigates a vast
maze of monsters to save her baby brother from the goblin king
played by David Bowie.
</P>
<P>
   In a classic labyrinth, however, there exists one path in and
out, a design meant to calm, rather than confuse, the mind.
</P>
<P>
   Labyrinths built more recently in the United States are usually
modeled after those that drew European pilgrims in the Middle Ages.
Most Christians could not make the costly and dangerous pilgrimage
to Jerusalem. Instead, they made pilgrimages to shrines and
cathedrals, some of which, like Chartres (built around 1230),
housed labyrinths.
</P>
<P>
   One name for the labyrinth at Chartres, according to Sullivan,
was ``le chemin de Jerusalem,'' or ``the road to Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   Patti Keeler of Harwich, Mass., a certified holistic nurse who
runs several labyrinth seminars each month, called the labyrinth
``a tool whose time is due.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's steeped in ritual and in antiquity, yet it's a wonderful
modern tool to bring us back to our own center and to God,'' said
Keeler, who called her first labyrinth a life-changing experience.
</P>
<P>
   Moving through a labyrinth brings mind and body together in a
way that few other forms of prayer or meditation can, Keeler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a body prayer,'' she said. ``It serves as a metaphor for
whatever you're going through. As you move through it, knowing
you'll get to the center and that there's only one path to take, it
allows for other forms of consciousness to bubble forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts has at least a dozen public and private labyrinths
at parks, churches, and even a retail shop, Annie's Garden and Gift
Store in Amherst.
</P>
<P>
   Some visitors enter a labyrinth with a particular vexing
question in mind, some repeat a mantra, and others simply enjoy the
walk. The process appeals to seemingly unlikely enthusiasts. Keeler
said her daughter's entire high school basketball team made a trip
to a local labyrinth before every game last year. Prison inmates
and those in wheelchairs have even made use of finger labyrinths,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hess, 21, returned to the campus labyrinth on Tuesday after
several visits last fall. As he prepared to kick off his flip-flops
and let his feet touch the grass in the chilly dusk, Hess said he
has found the experience gives him spiritual clarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of walking step by step, conscious of every breath,
helped me think a lot more about being present in the moment,
instead of living my life caught up in the future or the past,''
Hess said. ``It's good to remember that before you can take the
second step, you have to take the first step.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Taylor, 20, pointed out that the labyrinth reminds students
that life has meaning beyond Wednesday's midterm or Friday's party.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something higher than schoolwork, believe it or
not,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
