<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-MILLENNIUM-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   In a series of millennial commentaries for The New York Times
Magazine, Pulitzer Prize-winning columnist William Safire offers
the kind of perspectives that have made his ``On Language'' column
a Sunday staple for millions of readers.
</P>
<P>
   The Safire commentaries described below have been written for
the ``Millennium Issues'' of the magazine and are available for
oneshot purchase from The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   For purchase information, contact one of the following New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
</P>
<P>
   _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   _ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   _ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DRAWBACKS OF `UNSEXING' THE LANGUAGE
 &UR; (1,000 words)
 &UR; By WILLIAM SAFIRE
</P>
<P>
   In wiping away the undoubted masculine tilt to a thousand years
of English, and in attempting to imbue our language with gender
equality, are we going too far too fast? Contrariwise, in making
our language reflect a belated sense of fairness, should we tell
tradition-bound male chauvinists, ``Sorry, buddy, but you can't
make an omelet without breaking eggs''? (Or contra-contrariwise,
should we use an egg metaphor at all in this discussion?)
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-LANGUAGE)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A MEMORABLE SPEECH EXTOLLED A FRIEND, `FAITHFUL EVEN IN DEATH'
 &UR; (1,000 words)
 &UR; By WILLIAM SAFIRE
</P>
<P>
   There have been many ``great'' speeches on momentous occasions:
Patrick Henry's ``Give me liberty or give me death!'' Or Lincoln's
``Four score and seven years ago ...'' Or even Robert Emmet's
gallows speech, ``Let no man write my epitaph!'' But there were
also some shorter remarks made by lesser-known figures that sparkle
in the sands of our time. William Safire casts an appreciative nod
toward George Graham Vest, who, as a young lawyer, made ``a
sentimental little speech that is the best I can find of its
kind.'' It was a tribute to a dog.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged MILLENNIUM-BEST-SPEECH)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REFLECTING ON THE FALL AND RISE OF `SELF'
 &UR; (1,000 words)
 &UR; By WILLIAM SAFIRE
</P>
<P>
   ``Self'' used to be a dirty word. ``I celebrate myself,'' Walt
Whitman sang in his ''Song of Myself.'' Since then, however, the
notion of self as something to be celebrated has been taking a
beating. We think it is bad to be selfish, good to be selfless. And
yet, ``self'' is making a comeback. Showing some self-confidence,
it has even become the name of a Conde Nast magazine aimed at women
interested in their own bodies and minds.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged: BC-MILLEN-ME-SAFIRE)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REBIRTH AND REDEMPTION FOR SOME BATTERED WORDS
 &UR; (1,000 words)
 &UR; By WILLIAM SAFIRE
</P>
<P>
   The word ``adventurer'' has had a wild ride through the
millennium. Not that long ago ``adventurer'' meant a brawler, a
plunderer, and even the Devil himself. But today, an adventurer is
no longer a person to be feared. The word has reasserted the
romantic, courageous quality that the poet Keats once gave it.
Meanwhile, ``hellmouth'' is an archaic word that has returned to
vogue as a result of a popular TV series.
</P>
<P>
   (Slugged BC-MILLENNIUM-ADVENTURE-WORDS)
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times Syndicate
</P>
<P>
   (New York headquarters: 212-499-3300 or 1-800-972-3550; fax,
212-499-3382.)
</P>
<P>
   Visit our Web site at http://nytimes.com/syndicate.
</P>
</TEXT>
