<HEADER>
A4030 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-21 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEAPONS THAT KEEP ON KILLING BOTH SIDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marcus and Atsuko spent the summer with my friend Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   They came to Marblehead after spending the winter traveling from
Auschwitz to Hiroshima on a peace walk to commemorate the 50th
anniversary of World War II. They spoke so passionately about the
spiritual benefits they'd gained that Lynn and I were inspired to
accompany them on a Walk for Peace that began at Starmet Corp. in
Concord, Mass., and ended _ on the anniversary of the bombing of
Nagasaki _ with the arrest of five of the peace walkers at Raytheon
Corp. in North Andover, Mass..
</P>
<P>
   The sun was shining as Lynn and I stood by the side of the road,
practicing the Buddhist chant Marcus and Atsuko were leading: ``Nam
Myoho Renge Kyo.'' I beat out the rhythm on a drum I carried, as
about a dozen of us stretched out along a route chosen to dramatize
the fact that these two firms have been helping our government wage
a ``radioactive'' war against the people of Iraq and Yugoslavia,
using munitions made with depleted uranium. DU, a byproduct of
uranium enrichment, burns and oxidizes upon impact, creating
radioactive particles that are easily inhaled and ingested. These
can cross the placenta, enter semen and breast milk, and cause
cancer and leukemia as well as chromosome and immune system damage
for generations to come.
</P>
<P>
   Since DU has a radioactive half life of 4.5 billion years, we're
now waging wars that will last for eternity.
</P>
<P>
   As our group walked and chanted, I had time to brood about the
consequences of deciding to use such potent weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Felicity Arbuthnot, a London-based journalist who won a British
award for her coverage of Iraq, reported from Basra after the war
that ``cancer, leukemias, and malignancies have risen up to 70
percent since the Gulf War, increases linked to the depleted
uranium weapons used primarily by the US and UK, leaving a
radioactive dust throughout the country, which according to experts
has entered the food chain via the water table and the soil. . . .
One doctor's thesis compares abnormalities since the Gulf War with
Hiroshima. Dr. Jenan Ali's photographs for 1998 show full-term
babies . . . reminiscent of the Pacific Islands after the 1950s
nuclear testing. Others _ no face, no eyes, twisted limbs, no
limbs, no brain.''
</P>
<P>
   This would a terrible enough consequence if it only affected the
children of our enemies, but it is also mirrored in the plight of
the sons and daughters born to some of our own returning Gulf
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1995, Life magazine ran an article titled ``Tiny
Victims of Desert Storm,'' which raised the possibility that DU was
implicated in these American youngsters' otherwise baffling
deformities. For those who had the heart to look, there were photos
of the children of American soldiers, some with no arms, no legs,
or misplaced inner organs, some without thyroids, with two hearts
or hearts on the wrong side, enlarged heads and abdomens, and
abnormal blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   We have reached the point where our weapons, in their awesome
power, make no distinction between combatant and bystander, victor
and vanquished, or soldier and offspring. In seeking to destroy
others at any cost, we are placing ourselves directly in harm's
way.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Starmet Corp., whose armor-piercing DU bullets are
designed to inflict pain on an enemy, has contaminated ground water
on its own property in Concord with concentrations of uranium up to
3000 times what are now considered safe levels. We've not only
turned battlefields in Iraq into killing fields for countless
generations, we're poisoning our own future.
</P>
<P>
   As I walked, I wondered. Why didn't we reconsider what we were
doing to ourselves after aboveground nuclear tests showered deadly
radioactivity upon our own citizens? Why won't we acknowledge that
the pesticides we are using in our war against insects are damaging
our own cells? What will it take to teach us that as long as all
living things share this one tiny interrelated biosphere, the more
powerful our weapons, the more likely we will become the victims of
our own hostility?
</P>
<P>
   I took one step after another, lost in the rhythm of the chant.
Walking seemed such a slow process that I was surprised to find I'd
already gone 5 miles. One small step after another. One painful
lesson after another. One moment of understanding after another.
</P>
<P>
   Someday soon we will have to give up hating our enemies in order
to save ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Linda Weltner's website is at www.shore.net(tilde)weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
