<HEADLINE>
DID RED SOX HAVE A DATE WITH DESTINY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is ``The Secret Language of Destiny,'' a just-published
tome, 824 pages, and at $34.95 for 4 pounds 14 ounces, worth its
weight in good, if not great, chocolate, and almost as much fun.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Goldschneider, the astrology columnist for Mirabella
magazine, and co-author Joost Elffers, have devised a system they
call ``personology,'' which outlines the karmic path each of us is
destined to undertake and reveals our (drumroll, please) Destiny.
Mine is the Way of Study, which came as a surprise, but my specific
personal karma seemed familiar, ``wacky, distracted . . . likes to
be left alone . . . pessimism . . . self-doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Could there be something to personology? I checked out a few
friends and family members. Some descriptions were uncanny, my
husband's for example. It begins, ``Simple stubbornness may be the
biggest pitfall.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, we've heard so much talk about Destiny, Fate,
Fortune, Karma both good and bad. Could personology be applied to
the Red Sox?
</P>
<P>
   First, soon-to-be-manager-of-the-year, Jimy Williams. Born Oct.
4, 1943. His karmic path is the Way of Resolve. His greatest
challenge: ``Not floundering in the sea of public opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   There's more. The self-effacing Williams is one of those who
``tend not to take their own needs seriously.'' They must find
their karmic fulfillment in ``clarifying who they are and what they
want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He must be well along his karmic pathway after Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Next up, clutch-hitting but error-prone third baseman John
Valentin, born Feb. 18, 1967. His karmic path is the Way of
Satisfaction. His profile begins, ``The individual born in this
week may find life a bit difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. The greatest challenge for Valentin and his karmic
ilk? ``Getting a grip on their insecurity.''
</P>
<P>
   Or in his case, maybe just getting a grip on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the incomparable Pedro Martinez. His karmic path is the
Way of Freedom. ``Brilliant and creative in the extreme,'' his
profile begins, ``. . . a rare combination of strong mental
orientation together with an equal measure of passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Next is second baseman Jose Offerman, born Nov. 11, 1968, with a
bat, if not a glove, in his hand. His karmic path is the Way of
Wonder. The biggest challenge for Offerman and those born the same
week? ``Slacking off on their intensity level.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Just when personology is starting to look like an exact science
I see that Nomar Garciaparra, born July 23, 1973, and Monica
Lewinsky share a karmic profile. How can this be? Theirs is the Way
of Consolidation. Their biggest challenge? ``Developing a safety
valve they can use when their moods overwhelm them.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that explains Nomar's fidgeting.
</P>
<P>
   It would be interesting to know which karmic path the Red Sox
are on as a team. I'd guess it's the Way of Transcendence, ``The
destiny of those born to this karmic path is to learn how to
transcend limitations.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps fans could improve the Sox karma by ceasing to endlessly
revisit that fateful moment in the sixth game of the 1986 World
Series. Speaking of which, Bill Buckner was born Dec. 14, 1949, on
the Way of Individuation. The biggest challenge of those on this
karmic path is ``off-loading enough of their responsibilities to
allow for some self-exploration.''
</P>
<P>
   He just happened to off-load at the wrong moment. But that's
(drumroll again, please) Destiny.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
