<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4035 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-MUSIC-VELASQUEZ-HNS &LR;      10-21 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-VELASQUEZ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS CHASES JACI VELASQUEZ 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOEY GUERRA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Pop stars rarely make their own phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   If there are digits to be dialed for an interview, the task is
usually taken care of by an agent, a publicist, a manager. We
wouldn't want our fragile singer breaking a nail, would we?
</P>
<P>
   Contemporary Christian superstar Jaci Velasquez is a little
different. Her call for a last-minute interview was indeed made by
someone else, but it wasn't some slick record exec or overeager
yes-man. And she had a legitimate excuse for not making the call
herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just trying to connect you with my daughter,'' said Diana
Velasquez, calling from her home in Nashville, Tenn. ``We just got
in from a trip from Guam, so we're both like half-dead. We're
trying to make coffee to wake up. Jaci goes, `Mom, get him on the
phone.'''
</P>
<P>
   When Jaci Velasquez takes the phone from her mother, she seems
wide awake, despite just coming down from a whirlwind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just woke up, but I'm not like completely messed up, which
is really good'' said the performer.
</P>
<P>
   If Velasquez had been a little disoriented, we wouldn't have
held it against her. Her 3 1/2-day trip to Guam included two
concerts and a special performance for the governor's birthday
party. It also had resulted in some unexpected side effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never got over the time change. My head is just gone; I'm so
messed up,'' Velasquez said. ``I felt so bad for those poor people.
They probably thought, `This girl always has bags under her eyes.'
I looked tired. And I haven't adjusted to the time here yet, so
it's funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides crooning for other people's birthdays, Velasquez found
time in between appearances in Guam to celebrate her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big 2-0,'' she said with mock enthusiasm. ``I would
definitely have to say this birthday feels different from the rest.
I feel a little weird saying (I'm 20). It's kinda scary. It's like
a milestone. There's no excuse for all my mess-ups now.''
</P>
<P>
   A quick glance at Velasquez's track record, however, indicates
no glaring missteps so far. After singing in church and with her
parents, the Houston-born singer was asked to open a concert for
Christian-pop outfit Point of Grace. The group's manager was so
impressed with her that he referred her to Myrrh Records.
</P>
<P>
   After some serious discussion, Velasquez signed to the label at
age 15 and released her first album, ``Heavenly Place,'' in 1996.
It was certified gold and stands as the fastest-selling debut album
for a solo artist in Christian music history.
</P>
<P>
   Velasquez's self-titled second album was released in 1998 and
also was certified gold for sales in excess of 500,000 copies.
Throw in a slew of Dove awards, eight No. 1 singles and ``A
Heavenly Place,'' her inspirational book aimed at teens, and she
seems poised for a long and prosperous career.
</P>
<P>
   She says that so much success was an unexpected result of a
simple love for singing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know or think that any of those things would
happen,'' Velasquez said. ``You grow up, and you think, `Maybe I'll
be a doctor one day or an astronaut.' I was still doing that. I
never had a chance to go, `Maybe I'll be a singer.' It was an
exciting thing happening _ unfolding in front of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Velasquez's expressive, crystal-clear voice is reaching even
more ears with the recent release of ``Llegar a Ti,'' her first
album of all Spanish-language tunes. It's a perfect showcase for
her burgeoning talents, blending positive messages, dreamy ballads
and salsa-tinged up-tempo numbers. The album's title track is
already No. 2 on Billboard's Hot Latin Tracks list, primed to
dethrone Marc Anthony from the top position.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Spanish) wasn't my first language, but my dad would always
teach me Spanish hymns, and I'd have to sing them in church,'' she
said. ``I knew that I loved to sing in Spanish because it's such an
emotional and a passionate language.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her successful cross-over onto the Spanish pop charts
and radio, Velasquez made sure her messages of faith and hope were
retained in the translation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really important to me to be able to relate to the
songs that I sang,'' Velasquez said. ``I can't relate to, `Hey
baby, come on over here.' I can relate to the love I have for my
family, the love I have for God and the love one day I will have
from a guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that responsibility to those little girls who look up
to me and who listen to my music. I feel the responsibility to
their parents, as well, that they know when they buy my CDs that
it's something that their kids can listen to all the time and never
get the wrong idea about life.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are reassuring words from a young artist whose pop-music
contemporaries regularly indulge in come-hither pouts and
show-business excesses. For Velasquez, though, it's simply part of
being true to herself and making time for everyday pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's so important to have that balance in your life,
and I do have friends,'' Velasquez said. ``I really have a great
family that keeps me balanced, and they keep me pretty accountable.
People know me from the get-go. They know what I do, and they have
to like me with or without it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night I went out with a friend to go drink coffee. And I
have, like, a special guy who's really cool. I make time for
life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
