<HEADLINE>
BOLD `WITCH' SCARES WITH ITS STORY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `THE BLAIR WITCH PROJECT'
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Artisan, CC, VHS $22.98, DVD $29.98
</P>
<P>
   ust three months ago, a bold little film entered a forest of
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after $139 million at the box office, countless parodies, a
barrage of backlash and an absurdly short ``wait,'' its footage
will be found in video stores starting Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Is this ``Witch'' worth the fuss? Yes and no.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, because it dares to scare by appealing to the imagination,
not gorging on gore or special effects.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, because this cheap yet realistic look at film students
tracking a witchy legend in the woods, getting lost and never
returning struck a major chord with viewers weary of film artifice
and spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   No, because for all its effectiveness, ``Blair Witch'' doesn't
come close to the best modern horror films, from ``The Exorcist''
to ``The Texas Chainsaw Massacre.''
</P>
<P>
   And no, because ``Blair Witch'' isn't truly original so much as
lightning that struck at the right time _ and was backed by a
wildly effective marketing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is ``Blair Witch'' for all tastes. Its jerky camera
movements made some people nauseous in theaters (although they're
easier to take on a TV screen), and its documentary feel is far
from today's state-of-the-art filmmaking, even for low-budget
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   But at least ``Blair Witch'' shows _ as if the lesson were
needed _ that good films don't require big stars and big budgets.
Strong, well-told stories will do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   (Also on video _ for $14.98 _ is ``Curse of the Blair Witch,''
the pseudo-documentary TV special about the pseudo-documentary
movie. You also can catch exclusive new footage from ``The Blair
Witch Project'' shoot at www.amazon.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`ELECTION' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Paramount, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $29.99
</P>
<P>
   And Matthew Broderick thought Godzilla was a monster? He'd never
met Tracy Flick.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy (Reese Witherspoon) is a baldly ambitious girl campaigning
for student-body president at the high school where Jim McAllister
(Broderick) is a science teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Jim sees through Tracy's school-spirit facade and into her heart
of darkness. She's amoral and mean and would do anything to get
ahead. He must nip this power-hungry flower in the bud.
</P>
<P>
   Their war of wills and dirty tricks serves a delicious black
comedy that's awash in a sea of grays.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`eXistenZ' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Dimension, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $29.99
</P>
<P>
   One weird movie, this concerns near-future, virtual-reality
games that seem to transport players to alternate worlds.
</P>
<P>
   A genius game inventor (Jennifer Jason Leigh) is pursued by
murderous rivals and joined on the run by an earnest young
assistant (Jude Law).
</P>
<P>
   But what is reality, and what is the game-generated dream?
</P>
<P>
   Director-writer David Cronenberg delivers a dark tale filled
with bizarre imagery and sexuality. It's for adventurous tastes _
but it has its rewards.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BONDING WITH DVD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seeing a stunt man race across crocodiles is creepy enough, but
even scarier is the thought that the role of James Bond almost went
to _ Burt Reynolds?
</P>
<P>
   Both of those frights are among the revelations in a new set of
``Special Edition'' DVDs for seven 007 films.
</P>
<P>
   With the DVD market exploding _ and with the new Bond film,
``The World Is Not Enough,'' due in theaters Nov. 19 _ MGM spied a
chance to make hay.
</P>
<P>
   Some Bond movies already are on DVD, but these new discs add far
more than the movie (although that remains all you get on new
videotapes costing $14.98).
</P>
<P>
   Two Sean Connery Bond films get ``Special Editions'':
``Goldfinger'' and ``Thunderball.''
</P>
<P>
   The latter includes two documentaries, five TV spots, 10 radio
spots, three theatrical trailers, a gallery of more than 600
stills, the featurette Inside ``Thunderball,'' an ABC broadcast
promotion, audio commentary by the director and writer, and a
behind-the-scenes booklet.
</P>
<P>
   The two Roger Moore ``Special Editions'' are ``Live and Let
Die'' and ``For Your Eyes Only.''
</P>
<P>
   The former has a half-hour documentary narrated by ``The
Avengers''' Patrick Macnee, who reveals that Reynolds almost got
the role when Connery gave it up, but Moore prevailed via
friendships with the producers at gaming tables.
</P>
<P>
   Moore and co-stars Yaphet Kotto and Jane Seymour are seen in
recent interviews. We learn that Clifton James' allegedly humorous
redneck sheriff was added to offset the fact that the film's
villains _ and, thus, losers _ were blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, a stunt man runs across crocodiles as if the beasts
are steppingstones. (He somehow survives the five takes.) There's
even a milk commercial enacted by the cast on location in Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   The DVDs also include one Timothy Dalton film, ``Licence to
Kill,'' and two with Pierce Brosnan, ``Tomorrow Never Dies'' and
``Goldeneye,'' each with similar arrays of extras. (``Goldeneye''
also has Tina Turner's music video for the title song.)
</P>
<P>
   The discs cost a suggested $34.98 each or $199.98 in a set. Be
advised that substantial savings are available online.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
VIDEO RATINGS &QL; 
4 stars _ Excellent &QL; 
3 stars _ Good &QL; 
2 stars _ Fair &QL; 
1 star _ Poor
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
