<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RELAUNCH FOR AMERICAN PROSPECT MAGAZINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been a journalistic mismatch. While conservative
periodicals like The Weekly Standard and The American Spectator
generate energy and headlines, the journals of the left _ from The
Nation to Tikkun _ struggle for attention and survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the money and the current prevailing momentum has been
with the right,'' admits Robert Kuttner, founding co-editor of the
Boston-based American Prospect.
</P>
<P>
   The decade-old Prospect _ published six times a year, with a
circulation of about 25,000 _ has evinced some of the symptoms
afflicting the liberal press. Earnest and thoughtful, it
nevertheless carries that commercially damaging aura of what
Kuttner calls ``an academic quarterly.'' Now, with an infusion of
$1.5 million in grants, Kuttner is rolling the dice with a dramatic
relaunch and redesign of the Prospect as a four-color biweekly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the old Prospect was better than it looked,'' says
Kuttner, whose column appears regularly in the Globe. ``We felt
that the material deserves a bigger audience than it gets. We felt
there was a huge market for a publication with a niche between The
Nation and The New Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Prospect, which will reach subscribers by the middle of
next week, includes major pieces examining George W. Bush's
popularity in the Hispanic community and dissecting Bill Bradley's
and Al Gore's decisions to tack left in their presidential battle.
In reaching for a bigger audience _ projections call for 100,000
subscribers in five years, and a direct mail campaign has already
netted about 15,000 acceptances of a trial offer _ it's clear that
the Prospect will be less ``wonky'' and a little hipper. With a
staff now beefed up to about 30, the magazine will include former
US World &AMP; News Report editor Jim Fallows writing about technology
and culture and regular TV and movie criticism _ or what Kuttner
calls a ``full-service magazine for liberals.''
</P>
<P>
   That has traditionally proved to be no mean feat, but Kuttner
believes that ``we had a better chance of ensuring the survival of
this magazine in the long run with a bigger magazine.'' The
blueprint, he adds, calls for the Prospect to ``get within spitting
distance of break-even'' within five years.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he initially referred to that projection as a
``five-year plan,'' before quickly amending that language. The
Prospect faces a tough-enough challenge without conjuring up the
Evil Empire.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who says journalists are cynical? In Newsweek's new Voices of
the Century issue, 57-year-old Muhammad Ali, debilitated by
Parkinson's disease and 18 years removed from his last fight,
announced he would ``shock the earth'' by getting in shape and
fighting an exhibition bout with ``two or three contenders.''
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek obviously made a tactical error when, in touting the
special issue, it published a straightforward press release
highlighting that statement. Because news of the Ali ``comeback'' _
without even a suggestion that it might be farcical _ circulated
all over the world from CNN to the Associated Press. (An item also
appeared in the Globe.) A piece in the Scottish Daily Record
solemnly warned that Ali ``must be prevented from returning to the
ring.'' The AP said that ``it sounds improbable, but Muhammad Ali
says he wants to get back in the ring one more time.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to play the story straight ``took me totally by
surprise,'' says Newsweek's John Leland, who conducted the
interview and points out that the paragraph containing the comeback
line began with Ali saying: ``Now I'm fighting Parkinson's
disease.''
</P>
<P>
   When he got to work on Monday, Leland got a call from Ali's
wife, who was befuddled by the spreading news of her husband's
return to the pugilistic wars. ``They were as surprised as we
were,'' he said. Ali quickly released a statement that ``my claim
to return to the ring was said in jest,'' before gratefully noting
that it is ``exciting that I can still get this kind of response
from the press and public.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Husband-and-wife author team Alex Jones and Susan Tifft
conducted roughly 500 interviews, amassed about 60,000 archival
documents, and ended up toiling on their new book for seven long
years. (``Very biblical, don't you think,'' jokes Tifft.) But the
most difficult obstacle to writing ``The Trust: The Private and
Powerful Family Behind The New York Times'' might have been winning
that family's cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jones, who left his job as Times media writer to
write the book, he first sent a letter to former publisher Arthur
Sulzberger in 1992 proposing the project and requesting access and
independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response came back very fast,'' recalls Jones. ``No.'' In
a later meeting, Jones says, Sulzberger asked whether the book
would delve into personal family matters and was told that it
would. That prompted a polite goodbye. But, says Jones, Sulzberger
summoned him to his office a few days later and asked simply: ``Are
you sure you and Susan want to do this?''
</P>
<P>
   In explaining this family's success at maintaining its newspaper
empire through a time when family ownership is dying, the authors
describe just how heavy lies the crown of the Times legacy. Of the
challenges facing current publisher Arthur Sulzberger Jr., Jones
quotes one Times executive as saying: ``Arthur knows if he blows
this, he'll burn in hell.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
