<HEADLINE>
RULING STRIPS THE POLICE LAWSUIT RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A federal judge has struck down a 17-year-old
California law that allows police officers to sue citizens for
filing false complaints. The American Civil Liberties Union
heralded the ruling as a significant constitutional victory against
intimidation by the police.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling in Southern California was handed down Monday, the
same day a San Francisco Superior Court judge ordered a city police
officer to pay $52,000 to the lawyers for a woman he had sued under
the 1982 law. The woman had accused the officer of police
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a powerful one-two punch to what has been a
longstanding problem with police officers retaliating against
people who file valid complaints,'' ACLU lawyer John Crew said.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, a federal court ... strikes down the law. Then, the
Superior Court in San Francisco shows there will be financial
consequences for police officers' trying to retaliate against
people for exercising their First Amendment rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The California law, the only one of its kind in the country,
explicitly gave police officers the right to sue people who filed a
false complaint against them.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Gary L. Taylor declared that law
unconstitutional, ruling it violated the First Amendment right to
free speech.
</P>
<P>
   However, a police spokesman said the law was necessary to
protect officers from people who made false accusations against
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is how will peace officers in the future be
able to attempt to clear their good names when there are frivolous
charges brought against them by the public that are unfounded and
unwarranted,'' said Kelly Moran, director of political affairs for
the California Organization of Police and Sheriffs.
</P>
<P>
   The judge addressed that very issue in his ruling: ``Significant
protections from false complaints are already afforded to police
officers by their internal oversight agencies, in addition to the
possibility of perjury charges for false complainants.''
</P>
<P>
   Citizens have a right to file complaints against any government
official. The 1982 law was enacted after lobbying by police groups
made a special exemption for law enforcement officers, giving them
the right to sue citizens who filed complaints that were knowingly
false and made with ``spite, hatred or ill will.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew said the law had been used by officers to intimidate people
from proceeding with their complaints, creating a chilling effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be faced with these sorts of threats has been a major
barrier to police reform, and frankly, to getting management in a
position to deal with problem officers,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
