A4046 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-GARDEN-FALL-BOS &LR;      10-21 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-FALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOOSING REPLACEMENT PLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Autumn finds many gardeners looking for replacement plants.
Decisions have been made, nursery prices often have been lowered,
and it's just a great time to plant, better in some ways than
spring.
</P>
<P>
   That's because in the cool of fall shrubs and trees put their
energy into developing roots, not tops, which is a good thing for
new plants, and because there tends to be consistent moisture,
which won't be followed by a hot dry spell.
</P>
<P>
   This fall finds me planning to replace a hyacinthiflora lilac.
The one I lost had reached only 6 feet tall, so, while its loss is
a disappointment, it is not a disaster. Another is easily obtained.
</P>
<P>
   Not so the two plants John Peterson wants to replace. His have
to match two that are closing in on a century old with trunks more
than a foot in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, president of the Massachusetts Horticultural Society,
of which I am a member, is involved in the restoration of a
turn-of-the-century formal garden at the Elm Bank Reservation in
Wellesley, where the society is developing 36 acres into a
horticultural education center.
</P>
<P>
   The garden, done in the Italianate style as part of a
landscaping by the Olmsted Brothers, with the passage of time
largely disappeared as plants died or became overgrown. Last
summer, the horticultural society raised the required match of a
$100,000 grant it received from the Massachusetts Preservation
Projects Fund through the Massachusetts Historical Commission to
restore the garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two trees in there that are the only plants that are
original,'' Peterson said. ``We would like to hunt out some similar
trees.'' One is a Camperdown elm, with a trunk 14 inches in
diameter, the other a weeping larch, with a trunk 16 inches in
diameter.
</P>
<P>
   Got any? Peterson is looking for somebody to donate trees of
matching size. Maybe they are overgrown for their current site,
maybe they are in the way of future plans, or maybe their owners
would just like to do a good deed. ``It's going to have a lot of
visibility and recognition with it,'' Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson knows the trees are out there.
</P>
<P>
   Camperdown elms in particular were very popular at the turn of
the century. Ulmus glabra ``Camperdownii'' has a rounded, pendulous
canopy grafted onto an understock. The American elm understock is,
Peterson said, the only American elm that has survived Dutch elm
disease at Elm Bank. It turns out that the disease enters only
through the leaves, and the Camperdown has Scotch elm, not American
elm, leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Weeping larch is Larix decidua ``Pendula,'' a member of the pine
family. Like other larches, its needles turn yellow in fall and
drop. The one at Elm Bank is an attractive tree with gracefully
drooping branches.
</P>
<P>
   The restoration of the garden to its 1926 Olmsted design is made
easier because it is an Olmsted design, and the company's records
survive at its former offices, now the Frederick Law Olmsted
National Historic Site in Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is there the landscape plan, but ``we have the plant
lists, as well,'' said architect Marion Pressley of Pressley
Associates in Cambridge, who is undertaking the restoration.
</P>
<P>
   The trees are necessary to the restoration because the
Italianate garden is a formal garden, on an axis with the adjacent
manor house. Viewed as a rectangle, with a marble fountain in the
center, it has the Camperdown elm in one quadrant, the weeping
larch in the quadrant diagonally across. The new trees will balance
this.
</P>
<P>
   Pressley said the main axial evergreens and a beech hedge
surrounding the garden is being restored. Interior beds will have
boxwood edging and are to contain three-season displays of annuals.
The fountain and garden gates and pathways also are being put
right. Restoration of a collection of evergreens ``spottily
placed'' throughout the garden will come another day, Pressley
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get the bones in,'' Pressley said. The work is
to be completed this fall, which means Peterson needs to find those
trees.
</P>
<P>
   While he has found several trees of the right size so far,
Peterson has yet to find a donor. When he does, he will offer to
replace the mature trees with young versions, and the society will
take care of the removal.
</P>
<P>
   That is being handled by the donated services of Acorn Nurseries
in Boxborough, operated by brothers Sean and Christian Bilodeau,
who are certified arborists. Can they handle this?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, last year we moved 13 45-foot sugar maples over to
Harvard Business School,'' Sean Bilodeau said.
</P>
<P>
   They have huge truck-mounted tree spades. One of these can scoop
up a mature tree, haul it to its new home, and plunk it in the new
hole. It can dig the receiving hole, too, though the Bilodeaus
prefer to dig oversize holes, just a better planting practice.
</P>
<P>
   My project, the lilac, will be a tad smaller, if I even get
around to it. Maybe I'll live vicariously through the Massachusetts
Horticultural Society. I'm certainly looking forward to visiting
that restored Italianate garden _ with two Camperdown elms and two
weeping larches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
