<HEADER>
A4049 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-21 1549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWING IN OLMSTED'S FOOTSTEPS, NATURALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston is the intellectual cradle of America's landscape design
profession, and these days the cradle is rockin'. The U.S. Postal
Service launched a commemorative stamp here last month honoring
Frederick Law Olmsted, the Victorian founder of the profession,
while 6,000 attended the centennial meeting of the American Society
of Landscape Architects at the Hynes Veterans Convention Center.
Lectures there, heavy on history and public planning issues, ranged
from ``The Forest as Avant-Garde'' to ``The Exclusion of Teens from
Public Spaces.'' (It was not a how-to.)
</P>
<P>
   This is a golden age for all who create gardens and landscapes.
Commissions outnumber the garden professionals available to do
them, thanks to the building boom, new money, and the groundswell
of real interest in gardening. Building architects have been
surpassed by landscape architects in earnings. And college programs
are not minting new ones fast enough to fill job openings, says
ASLA president Barry W. Starke of Casanova, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Other landscape professionals are equally busy. Many top lawn
irrigation contractors won't even talk to you in this market unless
you're referred by another customer, says Brian Vinchesi, president
of Irrigation Consulting Inc. in Pepperell, Mass. ``They don't want
to take time to talk to someone who is just price-shopping
around,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone I talk to in the business is kind of going wild,''
says Laura D. Eisener of Saugus, Mass., a landscape designer who
teaches in the Graduate Landscape Program at Radcliffe Seminars.
``It's a golden age, but it's also a maddening age because there's
more than they can keep up with.''
</P>
<P>
   At the high end, the money is being spread thick as bark mulch.
Onetime luxuries such as in-ground lawn irrigation systems are
popping up all over. Stone terraces, until recently confined to the
bosoms of matronly old mansions built when labor was cheap, are now
being expensively retrofitted onto younger, comelier homes. And
humble blacktop is being blackballed by the newly wealthy, who
demand driveways paved with brick and stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to work on maybe one quarter-million-dollar residential
landscaping job a year in Metrowest,'' said Tim Smith, owner of
Moisturetek, a lawn irrigation company in Medfield, Mass.. ``Now
I'll see a dozen a year in Wellesley, Weston, Brookline, with
swimming pools, terraces, large trees installed, everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Residential landscape architect J. P. Shadley of Carol R.
Johnson Associates Inc., one of several celebrated Cambridge firms,
has recently done two half-million-dollar landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   But even Bostonians with big bucks are conservative compared to
the new rich of the New South and the wild, wild wealth out West.
Todd Steadman, publisher of Landscape Architecture magaazine, says
he recently heard of a $17 million private residential landscape
commission in California.
</P>
<P>
   Like politics, all landscaping is local, and you won't find many
backyards around here with the grossly modern forms, angular
minimalism, and very bright colors that are considered high style
among avant garden designers. Some people's idea of backyard beauty
may be 30 bright pink poles spaced out on a grid, but not in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few clients who have estate-type places who
want innovation,'' says Shadley. ``There's more ecological
sensitivity to the site here now. It's a slow burn. It's more
subtle here, as compared to the rest of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether wealthy, wannabes, or worker bees, homeowners here have
embraced two major home landscaping trends. One is toward having
less lawn and more naturalistic plantings with native wildflowers,
a tribute in part to the New England Wild Flower Society, one of
the country's most influential horticultural societies.
</P>
<P>
   A newer trend is gardens redesigned to match the period of their
older homes, an outgrowth of Boston's lively garden history
movement. Even people with reproduction Victorian or Colonial homes
are planting antique gardens these days.
</P>
<P>
   But what will future garden historians write about our own
period? It may well be remembered not for all the expensive
stonework and Beaux Arts axis views, but for the simple rediscovery
of plants.
</P>
<P>
   This sounds a tad obvious, since we're talking about gardens.
But except for trees and shrubs left over from earlier times,
interesting plants were almost absent from both public and private
American landscapes through much of this century.
</P>
<P>
   Until fairly recently, most landscape architects worked with a
palette of only 50 or so standard trees and shrubs. Many spent five
years studying engineering and drainage patterns, but needed only
one plant identification course to get their degrees. The result
was excruciating monotony in both commercial and private plantings.
</P>
<P>
   But today, homeowners are no longer satisfied with a ring of
yews and rhododendrons around the foundation, a flowering tree in
the front lawn, and a hedge of hemlocks screening out the
neighbors. Homeowners don't just want color and low maintenance
anymore. They want antique flowers and herbs. They want butterflies
and ecosystems. They want lots of different kinds of plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clients are more knowledgeable,'' says Eisener. ``Why are they
suddenly spending $6,000 or $7,000 on landscaping instead of on a
boat or a car? It doesn't seem to be an interest in increasing
their property values. They want to enjoy their gardens, and they
have more interest in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of this interest traces its roots to the 1970s, when baby
boomers started growing curtains of spider plants as symbols of
their embrace of ``the natural,'' bought homes, then tried
``getting back to the earth'' with vegetable gardening (under the
tutelage of ``Crockett's Victory Garden'' on WGBH-TV) and found
that too laborious. You had to grow the stuff and cook it. Still
enthusiastic, these beginners switched to perennial flowers,
because they didn't have to be grown from seed and promised to be
easy.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't. But by the time new gardeners became acquainted
with weeds, summer drought, and botrytis blight, they were hooked
on the diversity of perennials, and gardening had become America's
favorite hobby.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these impassioned gardeners, especially women, started
taking courses at garden design programs like the Radcliffe
Seminars. More than a few started home businesses designing
intricate gardens of unusual plants for their friends. Only the
most deluded thought they would ever earn a living at it. And then,
suddenly, they could.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1980s, there were a lot of new gardens designed by
these unlicensed but often very artistic plant experts. Calling
themselves ``landscape designers,'' they were stealing a march on
the highly educated, mostly male, and mostly more expensive
``landscape architects.''
</P>
<P>
   But many landscape architects don't seem to care much. They've
set their sights (and their sites) elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Residential work is not where the excitement is for landscape
architects, except for planned communities,'' says ASLA president
Starke. ``We're focusing on larger-scale issues, like reduction of
suburban sprawl and building livable communities. Landscape
architecture is moving from an art toward being more of a science.
It's the broader landscape of hills and rivers, not planting shrubs
and trees in someone's backyard!''
</P>
<P>
   Landscape architects are looking at the Big Picture _ the bigger
the better. Past ASLA president Dennis Y. Otsuji of San Diego
designed one 24,000-acre island resort and typically works on
hundred-acre planned communities in California, where the thorny
Coastal Commission makes environmental planning a must.
</P>
<P>
   Often landscape architects like him are the preservation
advocates on developers' teams, trying to take the sting out of the
suburban sprawl that is, paradoxically, their bread and butter.
``We try to have respect for what was originally on the site, the
hills and valleys,'' Otsuji says. ``We take the high road, while
the developer wants to cut off the tops of the hills to save
building costs. And we meet in the middle.'' He smiles, with a
graceful swoop of his hand outlining an imaginary hill that's
somewhat lower, but still there.
</P>
<P>
   Working on big corporate and civic land projects is also
lucrative, and the slight disdain some feel for residential work
may be linked to feelings that landscape architects lost out in the
1960s boom. ``There was a huge movement in greenbelts and open
space then,'' says Otsuji, ``and the planners and architects ran
with that, while landscape architects stayed in residential work.''
</P>
<P>
   New superhighways were laid out cheap, fast, and straight, at a
cost to scenery and driving pleasure, Otsuji believes. If only
landscape architects hadn't been busy designing Mrs. Biddle's
backyard, maybe they could have been designing better roads, and
getting more money and respect, too. Meanwhile, the modest,
plant-obsessed landscape designers from Radcliffe are only too
happy to design Mrs. Biddle's daughter's backyard.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, there's plenty of work for everyone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1443EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
