<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4051 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-21 1550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDDLE CHILDREN FIND THEIR OWN NICHE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 9-year-old Stephanie Sideris of Watertown, Mass., whose
brother, David, is a year older and sister, Emily, is two years
younger, being the middle child is not a big deal. ``It's mostly
good and mostly bad,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie is not troubled by her contradiction, and neither is
psychologist Kevin Leman of Tucson, a specialist in birth order.
``Her comment is perfect,'' he says. ``It epitomizes the way
middle-borns think. They see both sides so easily.''
</P>
<P>
   The influence of birth order on child development is widely
debated among clinicians and researchers. Some, like psychologist
Joseph Lee Rodgers of the University of Oklahoma, say it is not as
important as parents tend to think. Others, Leman among them, see
it as a dominant force.
</P>
<P>
   From a research standpoint, the middle child is the most
ignored. ``Just like the child himself,'' quips Leman, the author
of ``The New Birth Order Book'' (Revell). But there are tendencies
everyone agrees to. A middle-bornis typically:
</P>
<P>
   --Independent. A second- or third-born may do sleepovers younger
than the first-born did, have a wider circle of friends than the
first-born at the same age, or be the first among his friends to
dye his hair purple. (A first-born may never do that!) Parents
typically attribute this to older siblings' influence, but
psychologist Frank Sulloway says there's more to it. By virtue of
birth order, first- and last-borns tend to bond most intensely with
parents. Middle-borns, no matter how many there are in a family,
tend to be less connected in comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Don't panic; this doesn't mean they aren't connected at all or
that you don't have a good, loving relationship. But it does make
them more able to make close connections outside the family and
thus to be more independent at a younger age, sometimes more
rebellious, says Sulloway. A professor at the University of
California/Berkeley, he is one of the nation's preeminent birth
order researchers and the author of ``Born to Rebel: Birth Order,
Family Dynamics and Creative Lives'' (Vintage). His research bears
him out. In a recent survey of 7,000 siblings, Sulloway asked,
``Who would you turn to for help in a crisis?'' First- and
last-born children said Mom or Dad, but middle-borns were more
likely to say they would turn to a peer or a sibling.
</P>
<P>
   --Adaptive. With a first-born, the family's schedule revolves
around the baby. With the second-born, the schedule revolves around
car pools for the first. ``If the (second-born's) nap isn't as long
as it should be, oh well,'' says developmental psychologist Linda
Dunlap of Marist College in Poughkeepsie, N.Y. When a new baby
comes along, the now-middle child's schedule gets compromised even
more.
</P>
<P>
   This shouldn't necessarily make parents feel guilty. ``It's a
fact of life,'' says Dunlap, whose area of specialty is child
development and birth order. ``In the short run, the middle-born
may be cranky or have sleep disturbances because her needs aren't
prioritized. In the long run, this is a person who learns to be
flexible.'' That makes for a good human being, she says: As a
child, a middle-born tends to be a better friend than a first- or
last-born, and, as an adult, he's likely to be a better marriage
partner.
</P>
<P>
   --The peacemaker. With a sibling on either side, the middle
child is typically caught in all sorts of dynamics. ``I have to
share with the older and the younger because I have stuff both of
them like. And I'm always getting blamed for things.''says
Stephanie Sideris. Feeling this squeeze can result in the less
intensified bonding that leads to independence, but it can also
motivate a middle-born to excel at negotiation, compromise, and
peacemaking, says social worker Meri Wallace. She is the director
of the Heights Center for Adult and Child Development in Brooklyn
and the author of ``Birth Order Blues'' (Owl Books).
</P>
<P>
   ``She has to deal with the personality of the younger and the
older,'' Wallace says. ``She becomes the mediator, sometimes even
between a sibling and a parent.'' Understanding the viewpoints of
other family members may begin as a survival tactic, but frequently
becomes a source of satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean middle-children can't also be mean. ``On the
one hand, they can be peacemaker and nurturer,'' says Wallace. ``On
the other hand, they can be disdainful and fiercely competitive,
even being the one who tattles.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind all of this is the need to find a niche in the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``This child always feels as if he's in a race,'' Wallace says.
``Above you is the child you are racing to catch up with, below you
is the child you are racing to stay ahead of.''
</P>
<P>
   It can lead a child to wonder: ``If I'm not special for being
the oldest and I'm not special for being the youngest, what am I
special for? If I don't have the privileges of being oldest and I
don't inherit the right to be babied, what do I get?''
</P>
<P>
   In the toddler and preschool years, frustration can lead to
acting out. Dinner is prime time for it, says Wallace: ``Dad's
talking to the older child about school, Mom is feeding the baby,
and the middle child feels left out. Suddenly he's throwing food.''
Or take bedtime: One parent is doing homework with the third
grader, the other is bathing the 3-year-old, and there's the
6-year-old standing in the hallway waiting for attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does he do?'' asks Wallace. ``Goes into his room and
trashes it.''
</P>
<P>
   A steady diet of this can be horrific for parents, of course.
``In the early years, it's not unusual to identify this child as
The Problem Child,'' says Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   The antidotes she and others offer are surprisingly simple:
</P>
<P>
   --Make a point of asking for his opinion. The middle child can
be the most agreeable or disagreeable, depending on how squeezed
he's feeling at any given moment. The more you explicitly ask,
``What do you think?'' the less he'll feel lost in the shuffle and
the less he'll need to seek negative attention, says Leman.
</P>
<P>
   --Make time alone with her. Maureen Sideris says if there's one
thing that makes her daughter, Stephanie, light up, it's the chance
to do something alone with her. That's not unusual, says Leman:
``Any one-on-one time you spend with this child really pays off. It
makes them feel special.''
</P>
<P>
   --Support his uniqueness. Many middle children who follow in an
older sib's footsteps do it with a sense of competition _ ``I'll do
it better!'' _ or a sense of failure: ``No matter how hard I try, I
can't be as good.'' Help her identify an area of interest that
belongs only to her, even when it comes to chores; if he likes to
draw, for instance, perhaps his special job is to make place cards
or decorations for family meals. ``You get into trouble when his
chores are leftover jobs the older child doesn't want, or when his
only responsibility is to watch out for the younger brother,'' says
Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   If a middle child insists on playing soccer just like his
brother, it doesn't mean he shouldn't; in fact, says Wallace, it
may mean a lot to him to be able to prove to himself that he can
cut it. But don't compare him to how his brother played at this
age, she warns, and help him find some activity that only he does.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the trickiest question for parents is whether a
middle-born chooses an activity because of innate ability or by
default. It's hard to know. Wallace's advice is to support a
child's interests, whatever they are, and to tolerate the
fickleness that often occurs. ``A middle-born who never seems to
stay very long with one activity or interest may subconsciously be
looking for a gap in the family that she can fill. It takes some
kids longer than others to find it,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Because of gender distribution and spacing, some middle-borns
don't feel squeezed at all. Leman has five children but only one
boy, right in the middle of the girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way he has any attributes of a middle-born,'' he says.
``He's a first-born, because he's the only son.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, if there's a five-year or more gap between the
middle-born and a sibling on any side, the effects of placement are
erased. Rodgers says temperament can wipe it out, too, although
that is controversial.
</P>
<P>
   For parents who worry that a middle-born may harbor resentment
toward siblings or them, Sulloway is comforting. ``Growing up, they
recognize they get less attention but they adapt by shifting their
focus outside the family'' and they never seem to resent that, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   These are children who grow up to be what Wallace calls ``People
pleasers: sociable, flexible, easy to be with.'' It's no surprise
to Sulloway, for instance, that middle-born children are
overrepresented among Nobel Peace Prize winners.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Toddlers are easily frightened by Halloween; they
can't tell the difference between what's real and what's not. Don't
push costumes or masks on them, don't wear a mask yourself, ask
trick-or-treaters to remove their masks, and stress that this is a
day for pretending.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara F. Meltz welcomes letters and comments and can be
reached via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
