<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-HITCHCOCK-AND-SELZNICK-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE CLASH: ALFRED HITCHCOCK, DAVID O. SELZNICK AND A SHOWDOWN
ON THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and slides of director Alfred
Hitchcock and producer David O. Selznick. 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``It is my unfortunate and distressing task to tell you that I
am shocked and disappointed beyond words by the treatment of
`Rebecca,'''
 &HT;    So cabled film producer David O. Selznick on June 12, l939, to
Alfred Hitchcock, the British director whom he had brought to
America to turn Daphne du Maurier's classic novel into a movie.
 &HT;    ``I regard it as a distorted and vulgarized version of a
provenly successful work,'' Selznick continued, ``in which, for no
reason that I can discern, old-fashioned movie scenes have been
substituted for the captivatingly charming du Maurier scenes.''
 &HT;    Selznick, then basking in the success of ``Gone With the Wind''
(1939), was for once misled by his famous producer's instinct:
``Rebecca,'' starring Laurence Olivier and Joan Fontaine, would go
on to be a tremendous success, winning the Academy Award for Best
Picture of 1940. And Hitchcock and Selznick would make three more
films together, two of them hits _ ``Spellbound'' (l945) and
``Notorious'' (l946) _ and one a resounding flop, ``The Paradine
Case'' (l947).
 &HT;    From beginning to end, however, the director and the movie mogul
would battle each other. Their collaboration was profitable and
artistically successful, but rarely anything more than polite.
 &HT;    It's hardly unusual for writers to slam directors for
``distorting'' their masterpieces _ among living authors, Stephen
King has complained repeatedly about shoddy adaptations of his
work, while Tom Wolfe deliberately distanced himself from the
notoriously awful movie version of ``Bonfire of the Vanities''
(1990).
 &HT;    But Selznick was a producer, though he assailed Hitchcock as if
he'd penned du Maurier's prose himself.
 &HT;    ``The few million people who have read the book and who worship
it would very properly attack us violently for the desecrations
which are indicated by the treatment,'' Selznick raged.
 &HT;    It's a compelling story, one which is put under the microscope
in an intriguing new documentary, ``Hitchcock, Selznick &AMP; The End
of Hollywood,'' an installment in the ``American Masters'' series
which will premiere on PBS Nov. 1.
 &HT;    When he first hired Hitchcock, the 36-year-old Selznick was
already a legend. He had run a major studio before he was 30 and
created his own studio by the time he was 33. He had enormous
power, dealing on equal terms with studio bosses such as Louis B.
Mayer, Jack Warner and Darryl Zanuck.
 &HT;    Hitchcock, on the other hand, was the new kid in town, coming to
Hollywood after a modest string of suspense-film hits in Britain
which had led him to be pigeonholed as ``a cops and robbers
director.''
 &HT;    ``The dynamic between these two men especially intrigued me,''
says Michael Epstein, the documentary's writer/producer/director,
``in that, despite their dramatically different approaches to
filmmaking, their collaboration resulted in some of the best films
in Hollywood's `Golden Age.'''
 &HT;    Selznick was the only American producer to offer Hitchcock a
job, Epstein says, and the lugubrious Englishman appreciated it.
Every Selznick film was special: At a time when the major studios
churned out more than 40 films a year, Selznick ran a kind of
boutique operation, making no more than two or three a year.
 &HT;    But conflict between the two was inevitable, the documentarian
says, because they approached their business in totally different
ways.
 &HT;    ``Hitch was workmanlike, precise and methodical, while Selznick
was manic and indecisive, usually way over budget,'' he says.
``They were also both control freaks, and each tried to wrest
control from the other.''
 &HT;    In late July, at the Ritz-Carlton in Pasadena, Calif., Epstein
sat down with Hitchcock's daughter Pat and Selznick's
producer/director son Daniel to discuss why these two legends
butted heads yet managed to produce such great pictures.
 &HT;    Their relationship, Epstein believes, is also the story of the
transition from the old Hollywood studio system, in which the
producer was seen as the creative force behind every film, to the
movie world of today, in which that respect is accorded to the
director _ or, as French critical theory calls him or her, the
``auteur.''
 &HT;    ``Both men had giant egos,'' Epstein says. ``But it's the nature
of filmmaking to be a control freak and have an ego. I don't think
there are very many producers or directors who don't have egos.''
 &HT;    Pat Hitchcock was a child of 10 when her father made
``Rebecca,'' and she says that above all he was devoted to his
craft.
 &HT;    ``Work was the most important thing to him,'' she recalls. ``He
started out very early, and he loved working. He had tremendous
respect for David, but he was driving him nuts with telegrams.''
 &HT;    The evidence in the documentary suggests that, despite
Selznick's zeal to defend ``Rebecca'' against desecration, it was
Hitchcock who had the better taste of the two.
 &HT;    One of the biggest disagreements between the two men, for
example, concerned the final fiery destruction of the mansion,
Manderley, at the end of the story.
 &HT;    For that final scene, Selznick wanted the smoke to form the
shape of an ``R'' in the sky. Hitchcock was understandably
appalled. He chose a much more subtle metaphor _ the memory of
Rebecca goes up in flames as an ``R'' embroidered on her pillow
dissolves in flame.
 &HT;    Daniel Selznick _ whose mother was Irene Mayer, daughter of MGM
studio tycoon Louis B. Mayer _ recalls his father as an unorthodox
man whose spirit was more like that of a writer or director than of
today's producers, most of whom are simply skilled managers and
money-raisers.
 &HT;    ``I think he was fond of Hitchcock,'' he says, ``but he did say
he thought the director might have been a little tired of receiving
14-page telegrams delivered at 10:00 at night.
 &HT;    ``My father would stay up 22 hours and then sleep six or nine,''
he recalls. ``If there hadn't been sunrise and a sunset, I wouldn't
have known which was day or night, watching him. Work drove him
totally.
 &HT;    ``He tried to have a creative collaboration with the great
directors he worked with,'' Selznick adds, ``even though the legend
is that he simply told them what he wanted. But he also listened.''
 &HT;    Despite Hitchcock's many complaints, Epstein says, both men
benefited from their uneasy relationship.
 &HT;    ``Hitchcock grew enormously from his liaison with Selznick,''
the documentarian says, ``particularly on pictures like `Rebecca.'
I think he learned about a woman's picture, but also learned how to
make a Hollywood picture.''
 &HT;    And their collaboration spanned a critical period in cinema
history. By the time the director and the mogul parted ways,
Selznick's career was virtually over and Hitchcock's greatest films
still lay ahead. The studio system was on the wane, and directors
were well on their way to becoming Hollywood's ruling class.
 c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Hitchcock, Selznick &AMP; The End
of Hollywood,'' consult the official Website at
www.wnet.org/ammasters/hitchcock.html. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
