KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Thursday,
Oct. 22. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   STARVE: Charges likely today against a Kansas City woman who
allegedly starved one of her children to death. The mother could be
charged with a child abuse law that carries up to life in prison.
Police say a second child may die today. Police say the children in
her northeast home looked like starving refugees. However, the
refrigerator was well stocked with beer, police say. Police say the
woman told them she locked the two children in a room as punishment
and withheld food and water for weeks. This latest shocking death
of a child comes just a week after Pamela Butler's and E'lexis
Crawford's deaths. Neighborhood and community reaction to the
crime, too. Checking with schools and DFS to see if they noticed
any problems with the children. Donna McGuire and Christine Vendel.
35. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   ABUSE (with STARVE): We're checking to see if child abuse cases
are up on both sides of the state line and what laws are in place
to stop abuse. Donna McGuire. 15. Graphic
</P>
<P>
   ACCRED: The state Board of Education is expected to vote to
withdraw accreditation for the KC and St. Louis school districts.
Ben Demps will make a last-minute plea today to the board for a
reprieve. Assuming the vote yanks accreditation anyway, the KC
district will file suit Friday in federal and state court
attempting to block the move. The federal suit would seek to
reinstate the state as a defendant in the desegregation lawsuit, on
the grounds that losing accreditation would cause the district to
become more segregated because white students would flee. The state
suit will contend that the accreditation was pulled before complete
and accurate test information was submitted to the state. Photo.
Phil O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   LONER. What kind of guy is Keith D. Nelson? Some say he is
really polite and a hard worker; others remember the time he
allegedly poured acid in the Butler, Mo., public pool. He's a high
school dropout who never put roots down anywhere and never had
friends; his mother moved her sons to California, Texas and back to
Missouri. Trisha Howard. Mug. 35.
</P>
<P>
   NELSON (with LONER): Federal indictment likely today against
Keith Nelson. Those charges could include counts for murder,
kidnapping and sexual abuse. All of those counts could carry the
death penalty. Mark Morris. 20. Photo
</P>
