<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-PUMPKINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RISE OF THE LOWLY PUMPKIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH S. FOSTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pumpkins, pumpkins, pumpkins are everywhere. It's the new
commercialism that inundates us with signs of the season so we will
buy, buy, buy more.
</P>
<P>
   This pumpkin commercialism harks back to symbolism of earlier
times when the harvest was finally in, which was a good thing. But
also the spirits of old dead English witches and ghosts came back
on Halloween, which was a bad thing, as well as a very silly
superstition.
</P>
<P>
   People had to build big bonfires for protection, which are now
outlawed. So we content ourselves with hollowed-out pumpkins,
jack-o'-lanterns, to light the night as the fall settles upon us.
</P>
<P>
   However modern we become, these very, very old folk fears remain
as part of our cultural continuum. They become convoluted,
commercialized, occasionally worshiped. Today they have become a
holiday, a metaphor, like Mayan religious festivals. The residual
folk fears are now a reason to do something fun, in costume, like
ring doorbells for candy.
</P>
<P>
   And upon what does today's metaphor fall? Why, upon the lowly
pumpkin, which is just a big squash. It originated in South America
and comes in many varieties that we eat or use to adorn our houses,
like a Mayan festival to mark the harvest season. The symbolism is
fun, especially if you have children, but if not, then to remind
one of times long past.
</P>
<P>
   The best places to buy pumpkins are our local farms, where they
always have tons in any size, any shape. Plus a trip to the farm is
an enjoyable ride down memory lane, even if just to buy the crisp
fresh apples and newly pressed cider, not to mention the pies,
jellies, and more. The harvest season is not a time for dieting.
</P>
<P>
   For a list of local farm stands, call the state Department of
Food and Agriculture at 877-627-7476 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Monday to
Friday. After hours you can leave your telephone number or use the
Web, www.massgrown.org.
</P>
<P>
   But what if you want to grow your own next year? Well, it's not
too difficult if you have a nice big open space, in full sun, with
good soil. The old books have the best detailed information, and
the devil is always in the details.
</P>
<P>
   To grow your own
</P>
<P>
   First, dig a hole and fill it with well-rotted manure or mix
one-fifth composted manure with four-fifths loam and good compost.
Then pile back good soil to make a hill 18 inches wide and 3 inches
high. Fertilize about three times during the season. Some people
put a plastic bottle with the bottom cut out in the center of the
hill for giving liquid fertilizer as well as water. Plant six seeds
two inches apart and one inch deep when all chance of frost is
past. If you started seedlings indoors, which is a good idea, do
not disturb the roots when transplanting. When they are three
inches high, thin to the best three plants.
</P>
<P>
   Pumpkins take all season. Do not cultivate deeply, as roots are
near the surface, but do pull out weeds. The plants will spread
widely, up to eight feet square. As soon as several pumpkins set on
each plant, pinch off the tips so all the strength will go into the
pumpkins that have formed. As they get big, you may put a small
board underneath to protect the bottoms from rot. Wait until the
stems turn a light greenish yellow to harvest. Cut the stems. Do
not pull the pumpkins off. Then let them dry in the sun for two
weeks until the stems turn gray.
</P>
<P>
   Problems are squash beetles, which come in June and puncture the
leaves, which then wilt. Spray regularly with pyrethrum and
rotenone. Same for stem borers (which lay their eggs June through
July) and thrips and aphids, which carry diseases. For diseases and
blight, dust the plants with a fungicide at first sign.
</P>
<P>
   Old pumpkin soup recipe
</P>
<P>
   Boil center meat, cubed, (2 pounds) with butter (1 ounce), pinch
of salt, sugar (1 ounce), and water (2 cups). Simmer for 1 1/2
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Drain in a colander. Put back in pot with 3 cups of boiled milk.
Boil for one minute more. Season to taste and pour into a soup
tureen that has bread chunks in it. Other additives might be
apples, nutmeg, whatever tickles your fancy.
</P>
<P>
   Pumpkin seeds
</P>
<P>
   Take them out with a big spoon. Wash them, then slowly bake with
salt, or cinnamon and sugar, or vinegar or spices. Children love to
wash them. You won't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
