<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIPS ARE UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This summer, maybe you should have bought chips, not stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the usual ups and downs, the Dow Jones industrial
average has been flat since April. Meanwhile, memory chip prices
have gone ballistic. A 64-megabyte stick of SDRAM chips, the kind
most newer PCs use, was selling for about $95 in August at my
favorite computer parts store. Today it's $150. This is bad news
for consumers, because cheap memory chips have driven the shift
toward cheap-but-good home computers.
</P>
<P>
   It's also no fun for computer makers. Dell Computer Corp. said
Monday that third-quarter profits would fall below expectations,
because the soaring price of memory is driving up the cost of
building PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean a return to the days of home PCs costing $2,000
or more? Not a chance. But computers won't be getting cheaper
during this holiday season. And machines may not be as
well-equipped as before. Dell says it'll start shipping PCs with
less memory. Don't be surprised if other companies do the same.
This way, they can prop up profits by lowering costs, not raising
prices.
</P>
<P>
   But the consumer does pay a price: Less memory under the hood
often means worse performance. For some jobs, a 400-megahertz
Pentium II with 64 megabytes of memory may outperform a
500-megahertz Pentium III with only 32 megabytes of memory.
</P>
<P>
   How much memory is enough? These days, anything less than 64
megabytes is a sick joke; both the Apple Macintosh operating system
and Microsoft Windows are memory hogs.
</P>
<P>
   If you run memory-intensive software, you'll want still more.
For instance, speech-recognition software like Dragon Systems's
Naturally Speaking needs lots of RAM. So do 3D games, graphic arts
programs, and large databases. And even if you run relatively
light-duty software like word processors, you need lots of memory
to run many different tasks simultaneously. For this kind of heavy
lifting, 128 megabytes would be nice. Only these days that's about
$400 worth of memory. In some places you can buy a whole computer
for that kind of money.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, blame the earthquake in Taiwan, a vital chip-making
region. It's the easy answer, and like most easy answers, it's
wrong. Or mostly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Right after the quake, memory prices spiked as nervous computer
makers rushed onto the spot market to buy up loose inventory. Peter
Goodman, president of PCs For Everyone, bought $70,000 worth of
memory. A lot of other dealers and computer manufacturers made
similar moves, and those who didn't got into trouble. A guy at the
Cambridge Micro Center told me they were out of some memory
products for two weeks after the big jolt.
</P>
<P>
   But the memory market had actually begun to tighten in July. One
chip distributor told me the shortage developed when manufacturers
began making fewer cheap RAM chips, to focus on higher-priced
``flash memory,'' the kind that goes into digital cameras and those
new audio devices that play music downloaded from the Net. But
Goodman blames the retooling of major Asian chip plants, in
preparation for the next generation of memory chips.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, this retooling will drive prices down. If you
buy a stick of memory today, each chip on the stick will generally
hold 64 megabits of memory. You need eight such chips to get 64
megabytes, because a byte is eight bits.
</P>
<P>
   The next-generation RAM chips, due out next year, will carry 128
megabits or even 256 megabits per chip. But these chips will be the
same size as today's, and factories will crank them out at the same
rate.
</P>
<P>
   This is what happened in the mid-'90s, when memory makers went
from eight-megabit chips to the 64s we now use. It was this
multiplication effect that caused memory prices to plummet, and
that helped launch the age of the cheap PC.
</P>
<P>
   New-generation RAM chips should send memory prices to
bargain-basement levels next year. And with the earthquake panic
past, wholesale memory prices are already slipping. So despite
recent history, there are two things you can count on. In the long
run, stock prices go up, and microchip prices go down.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Hiawatha Bray at Bray(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
