<HEADER>
A4062 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     10-21 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FORAY INTO THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can Tom Lee, king of the leveraged buyout, make it in a cyber
world?
</P>
<P>
   The Thomas H. Lee Co. of Boston is renowed in the world of
private equity for its ability to buy companies like Snapple
Beverage Corp. and General Nutrition Cos., build them into
something more valuable and make a fortune on the way out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Now Lee is raising money for a decidedly differnet kind of
investment vehicle. TH Lee Internet Partners, a limited partnership
targeting Web investments, is in the process of raising $650
million and many believe the total will reach $1 billion when the
fund closes before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   If you've got a few extra bucks in your bank account, forget
about it. Minimum investment here: $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the team that will manage the money joined Lee just this
fall, jumping from the GE Equity venture capital arm of GE Capital
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Coats, the leader of GE's 20-member venture team focused
on electronic commerce, is running the Lee fund from New York.
Colleague Sharon Pipe in London and some other members of their
former GE group are also on board.
</P>
<P>
   Coats and other Lee officials declined to talk to us while they
were getting their venture off the ground. But we have a good idea
about some of the investments that team made for GE, putting
venture money into companies like Net2Phone Inc., StarMedia Network
Inc. and Interactive Pictures Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer size of the Lee fund is a sign of the times, when the
Internet has provided staggering returns for savvy early investors.
</P>
<P>
   The venture funds of CMGI Inc. of Andover, Mass., can raise
money almost at will. Softbank Capital Partners, operating from
Newton, Mass., raised $1.25 billion for its first later-stage fund
over the summer and expect to collect a similar amount before their
second fund closes in the first quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
   On the West Coast, Benchmark Capital Partners closed on a $1
billion fund last month and Redpoint Ventures, a new firm led by
well-known Internet venture investors Jeff Brody and Geoff Yang, is
said to be raising more than $500 million in another fund to close
soon.
</P>
<P>
   They all compete with internal investment arms inside giant
technology companies like Intel Corp., which are often prepared to
risk similar amounts.
</P>
<P>
   All that money is being soaked up by larger than ever venture
stakes, particularly in the later rounds of private equity
investments. Late-stage venture rounds of $30 million to $50
million or even more, once very rare, are commonplace today.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its principals, the Lee fund has organized an advisory
board that includes the likes of autobytel.com chairman Michael
Fuchs, former NBC executive Don Ohlmeyer, Net2Phone chairman Cliff
Sobel and Howard Anderson, chairman of the Yankee Group in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect that Tommy is going to have no trouble raising
money,'' said Anderson. ``He's going to be doing some muscular
deals.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he expected the Lee fund would have enough
financial firepower to begin organzing groups of portfolio
companies that could help each other grow, in much the same way as
Internet ventures backed by CMGI, Softbank and other investment
firms.
</P>
<P>
   But competitors think Lee is going to have a harder time in the
Internet venture world, where other big firms already have
established Web investing reputations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be a tougher landscape than he (Lee)
probably believes,'' said Charles Lax, a general parnter of
Softbank Capital Partners. ``If they are focused on late-stage
(investments) they have to compete with established players like
us, CMGI and even Benchmark.''
</P>
<P>
   The huge Internet venture capital returns generated by leading
firms and the following interest of investors have created
extraordinary situations across an entire industry.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes reports that the Coats team, then investing in electronic
companies for GE, had proposed a compensation plan to give them a
cut of profits from their deals instead of a pay package based on
the corporate profits of the entire General Electric.
</P>
<P>
   When a note detailing the idea reached GE chairman Jack Welch,
he reportedly wrote ``NOT IN MY LIFETIME'' across the top. Soon,
Coats was working with Lee on more lucrative terms and other GE
venture investors have left for yet other opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Internet venture firms themselves are also reaping exceptionally
big rewards in an industry that typically charged limited partners
2 percent fees plus 20 percent of investment profits.
</P>
<P>
   In California, Benchmark will reportedly take 30 percent of
profits off the table. The Lee fund is said to be structured to
take 20 percent to 30 percent, depending on performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet funds are obtaining rates of 25 to 30 percent,'' said
Steven Galante, editor of Private Equity Analyst, based in
Wellesley. ``There's so much enthusiasm right now for
Internet-related venture funds that institutions are willing to pay
the higher rates.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
