<HEADLINE>
RACING TO GET A RACE IN ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Maura Conron is faced with almost 200 foreign rowers in
need of beds this weekend. Ed Holland is faced with 45 crew teams
in need of oars, boats, or a coxswain. And Katy Bonnin is faced
with making all 200 portable toilets are put in the right place
along the Charles River.
</P>
<P>
   The Head of the Charles Regatta has always been about sleek
shells nagivating the 3-mile stretch of river on a late October
afternoon. But increasingly, spread sheets, e-mails, and faxes have
become as much a part of the race as the sculls and the oars.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnin, the operations manager who was hired last March, has
rowed in the Regatta, but has never helped run it. Sometimes she's
at the main office at the Cambridge Boat Club as early as 4 a.m. to
get in touch with rowers in a different time zone and ``because the
phone seems to be ringing 24 hours a day.'' She knows about the 98
boat trailers on Magazine Beach on the banks of the Charles, about
the 100 tents that are being set up, and there is about 400 feet of
temporary dock to assemble. More than 900 volunteers in 32
committees will deal with rules and appeals, awards, and weigh-In.
There is even a volunteer committee called ``Volunteers.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the entries for the 35th annual event come from
colleges, high schools, and clubs all over the country, it's no
longer a novelty to get entry forms from abroad. This year's list
of almost 6,000 athletes includes crews from Germany, Ireland,
Belgium, Italy, and France.
</P>
<P>
   So after their entry form is approved, Conron asks the foreign
crews to submit a housing request and Holland asks for an equipment
request. That's when the spead sheets come out.
</P>
<P>
   Conron and Holland have to figure out what the rowers need and
what the Head of the Charles can provide. In Conron's case, that
might mean a French crew who won't have a car and is allergic to
dogs, and in Holland's case that might mean a lightweight eight
boat oars.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have no idea where everything is, it's like us if we'd go
over there,'' said Holland. ``So we're glad to help them get their
feet wet, and know they'll reciprocate if a crew from the US goes
over there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, all the boathouses on the river are lending their
boats, so are small schools, like Brandeis. And if a school like BC
can't help with boats, they offer volunteers.''
</P>
<P>
   Holland, a rower who has been volunteering for 20 years, moved
from Boston last year and is national sales director for a biotech
company in Lawrenceville, N.J. He'll come to town Friday afternoon
to see the result of his work, pairing boats with rowers. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so large, I'll never see some of the people I've
gotten boats for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Conron, a Brown graduate who is former president of the
Riverside Boat Club in Cambridge, said she got involved when
someone asked her to be the international housing liasion three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now Conron's become part tourist information bureau (she directs
them to local pubs), part innkeeper (she's boarding a Swiss rower
this weekend), and part UN ambassador (she speaks some Italian) as
she directs the rowers to their weekend residences.
</P>
<P>
   And she's apt to do even more. Earlier this week she picked up
Swiss rower Marco Briganti at the airport. She is lending him her
boat to use in the lightweight singles race, as well as giving him
a place to stay at her apartment. (``But you get the pullout
sofa,'' she told Briganti with a laugh.)
</P>
<P>
   Conron, an artist who designed the Head of the Charles' Web
site, said she's grateful for the computer age. She gets
information from the potential hosts, then e-mails the foreign crew
with their name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the host and rowers can talk together directly,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   And she has learned from experience that there are bound to be
snags in her volunteer job.
</P>
<P>
   One year, three days before the regatta, Conron stood up at a
committee meeting, and asked, ``Does anyone want 24 lovely English
schoolboys?'' (She did find three houses for them, but one was in
Ashland, her farthest location ever).
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the time when one group of rowers drove away from
the airport in three rented vans and took a very different course
to the Cambridge Boat Club than Conron, who was leading them, had
in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know happened to them, but they got hugely lost, and
one van showed up six hours late,'' Conron said. ``But they were
English-speaking, and I figured they would find themselves at some
point, so I didn't get too upset. There are just some things I
don't worry about anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   But Conron said glitches are by far outweighed by the upsides,
like when a British rower presented his host with a national team
jacket, or the Irish crew brought over a pint of whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   Brigtani, who has never been to Boston, never seen the Charles
River, and had never met Conron before Tuesday, seemed more than
willing to trust Conron, as he looked over the boat she'll let him
use. ``Dangerous,'' she said, as if that had not occurred to her.
Then she laughed. ``But it all works out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
