<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND NOW A WORD FROM THE READERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To paraphrase Art Linkletter, you readers say the darndest
things.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years at the Globe and I've never encountered a more
fervent band of readers than those I'm dealing with now as auto
writer. Write something you like (favorite cars of the last 50
years; car wreck songs) and the e-mail and snail-mail pours in.
Make a mistake (label an engine a 442 instead of a 440 for
instance) and I'm caught like a deer in the headlights.
</P>
<P>
   I appreciate the feedback, good and bad _ excepting, perhaps,
the guy in Florida who wrote to say the only way to cure my brand
of writing would be to break all my fingers.
</P>
<P>
   The debate is lively, the questions almost always good ones.
Let's answer a few:
</P>
<P>
   I write frequently about ``torque'' and have noted I am
particularly fond of cars whose torque surpasses its horsepower.
What's torque? many of you have written.
</P>
<P>
   Think of torque as a circular, twisting force. Picture yourself
seated, leg straight out on an ottoman. I grab your foot and twist
it. The pressure I apply, even if your foot doesn't bend to the
side, is torque. Or hold one end of a baseball bat while I hold the
other. I twist the bat even as you grip it tightly. That's torque.
</P>
<P>
   Torque is power you can measure at the end of the crankshaft;
it's the transmission of force. Think of horsepower as the powerful
flame in a maple syrup hut. It's cooking up the sap. What you end
up with is syrup: torque.
</P>
<P>
   To demonstrate, picture yourself a sprinter in a 100-yard dash.
The long muscles of your legs are going to propel you straight
ahead in rapid steps. That's not torque. That's horsepower. Now
picture yourself as a backpacker who has come upon a steep, rocky
step. You put one foot up on the step, knee almost waist-high.
Picture your knee from the side and realize that your upper leg
bone, with your knee as the axis, will move in a semi-circle around
that axis. Torque is the power that will boost you up through that
arc.
</P>
<P>
   Torque can make a car doggedly powerful or catlike quick.
</P>
<P>
   If your vehicle is producing 400 lb-ft. of torque at under 2,000
RPMs, you're pulling something, hauling a heavy load, or plowing
snow, or ought to be. This is low-end, raw power.
</P>
<P>
   If your vehicle is cranking out 400 lb-ft. of torque at 7,000
RPMs, you're in a high-horsepower, high speed car and ought to be
watching the rearview mirror for blue lights. This is top-end,
speed-inducing power.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of torque, others have written to ask: What is
torque steer?
</P>
<P>
   You encounter torque steer in front-wheel drive cars. When these
cars (think Saab 96) were low-powered, it was not a problem. Now
that high horsepower and high torque have been added to the
equation, it can be.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you didn't know what it was, you'd know torque steer the
first time you felt it.
</P>
<P>
   In a low-powered auto, torque steer means a slight but
noticeable tug of the wheel _ the car trying to pull itself off the
intended steering line _ during a quick start from stop.
</P>
<P>
   As cars got more powerful, torque steer meant the steering wheel
would veritably spin in your hands as the front wheels pulled
themselves off the intended line.
</P>
<P>
   You don't get torque steer in rear-wheel drive cars because
power in these cars goes from drive shaft to rearend and out to
fixed wheels.
</P>
<P>
   In front-wheel drive, however, the ``axle'' must be flexible _
that is, not only feed power to the driving wheels, but also allow
them to bend _ steering.
</P>
<P>
   A constant velocity joint is what lets the ``axle'' do this. But
a CV joint is an imperfect thing because it allows power to be
delivered in an imperfect way out at the wheels on the spindles _
at an angle. This causes a ``twist'' that makes the car pull in one
direction even as its steering wheel indicates it is being turned
in another. Increased power only amplifies the phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of power, another reader wrote to chastise me for
praising the Ford Lightning, a supercharged, throwback hot rod of a
pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy your column, but praising such beasts as the Lightning
(and SUVs) puts you way out of the new trend in cars. Recent
detailed studies show these vehicles . . . to be: 1) killers, 2)
gas guzzlers, and 3) contributors to the world climate change
phenomena.''
</P>
<P>
   To which I say, right, in some ways, on all counts.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm not the environmental writer here. It doesn't matter,
when I am testing a car, whether I approve of people buying it. My
job is to assess the intended purpose of the car and how its buyers
might use it. Then I try to impart whether it will perform as it is
intended, for the buyer for whom it is intended.
</P>
<P>
   You mix enviornmental politics with assessing automobiles and
you have the threat of an ugly hybrid. I suspect the author of the
above letter would approve if my environmental politics were the
same as his own and I espoused them in my car reviews.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect, as well, he would be outraged were I, say, a chaos
theorist who used my auto columns to promote the notion that it is
supremely arrogant of humans to think that a big hole in the ozone
layer could wipe out life on earth. Sure, I'd say, while promoting
the latest V-12 engine: Humans might be wiped out, but other forms
of life would flourish under the extra ultraviolet light.
</P>
<P>
   I do have environmental opinions. I hope you never detect them.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, a reader wrote to say:
</P>
<P>
   ``You and your editor should be ashamed. It's well known that
RPM stands for rotations per minute or revolutions per minute, and
it is incorrect when you refer to RPMs in your column.''
</P>
<P>
   The reader, of course, is correct. But I consider RPM to be an
acronym that has become a word (at least among car folks) unto
itself. If you try to write in a conversational manner _ a good
thing, I think _ then when you have more than one RPM, you have
RPMs. I'll stop referring to RPMs in stories when the first
sportswriter writes that Nomar Garciaparra ``had 10 RBI in last
night's win over the Yankees.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
