<HEADLINE>
ON ALL FRONTS, VOLKSWAGEN JETTA IS SOLID 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   With some cars, a single word can be used to describe many of
its attributes.
</P>
<P>
   For the 2000 Volkswagen Jetta GLS VR6, that word is solid.
</P>
<P>
   As in: solid suspension, solid braking, solid acceleration,
solid seats, even solid interior door handles.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's aimed at younger drivers, this is a car that comes
down somewhere between pocket rocket and sports sedan. It's a
little too big and not quick enough for the rocket tag, not quite
big enough for the sedan label. But with its V6 engine turning out
174 horsepower, it will move five people about their appointed
rounds comfortably and quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Its outside look begins with the narrow eye slits that are its
headlights, and travels up over the short, rounded snout, the big
sloping windshield, high roofline, and raised, truncated trunk.
</P>
<P>
   The headlights _ single, clear-lens slits _ hold halogen lamps,
turn signals, and side lights. The windshield gives a clean view of
the road as the hood drops away immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the leather seats are broad and give good support. They
could use a bit more lateral support in the form of ridges running
up the sides of the seat backs. Headrests at all five seats are a
nice touch. There is plenty of room for the two front-seat
passengers, adequate leg room for three in back.
</P>
<P>
   The interior ergonomics are simple: a small, easily-read screen
behind the wheel holds tachometer, speedometer, temperature and
fuel guages, and digital readouts for time and odometer. At night,
the lighting for the guages basks the car in a rich
indigo-and-orange glow.
</P>
<P>
   All light controls are to the left _ some on the dash, dimmer
switch on a stem on the steering column. Controls for the heated
outside mirrors, door lock buttons, trunk and fuel cover are in the
driver's door.
</P>
<P>
   Rectangles define the lineup of controls at center-dash.
</P>
<P>
   At the top, an assortment of odds and ends: controls for heated
seats (you can cook buns on these babies), the off switch for
traction assist, the emergency flasher button, and the rear window
defroster.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately below, the slim rectangle that pops out with two
cupholders that get a good grip on your drinks. Below that, a slot
for miscellaneous items.
</P>
<P>
   The audio package is next and, in a day when too many
manufacturers are making these controls look like the inside of an
airplane cockpit, these are wonderfully simple.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for the climate controls below. See a button or
dial, push or turn it. Voila.
</P>
<P>
   Seven vents on the dash distribute heat and air in a studied
flow through the auto.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to storage _ and I'm talking mostly small, useable
bins here _ some manufacturers get it. Others don't. Volkswagen
does. The Jetta has a reasonable glove box, rare in the days of air
bags in the dash. The bins in the sides of the front doors are deep
and you can actually put a clenched fist down into one. There is a
money slot between the seats, the fold-down center armrest opens to
reveal a bin, and the backs of the front seats have pockets.
</P>
<P>
   At the rear, the trunk is deep _ golf clubs fit nicely _ and the
60/40 fold down rear seats lets you haul longer items.
</P>
<P>
   Settle in and drive, and, again, the first word that comes to
mind is solid.
</P>
<P>
   The acceleration is steady up through third, fourth and fifth
gears _ though for quick passing at highway speeds, you'll need to
drop down to fourth _ and the Jetta's nimble stiffness lets it move
through traffic with ease. On sharp corners, at steady speeds, it
holds its line with little sense of body roll.
</P>
<P>
   All this is owing to a stiff suspension that includes struts,
independent coil springs, telescopic shocks and a stabilizer bar up
front; an independent torsion beam axle, coil springs, pressurized
gas shocks and a stabilizer bar in the rear.
</P>
<P>
   The rack-and-pinion steering is tight and immediate.
</P>
<P>
   Combine power with front wheel drive and you have to deal with
torque steer. Volkswagen has done a good job of it here. It was
barely perceptible even when I tried to induce it.
</P>
<P>
   All-speed traction control is standard on the GLS. Aiding that
system is a feature called Electronic Differential Lock that, up to
24 miles per hour, uses brakes to slow slipping wheels. This will
be good in snow. It's also got another feature dubbed Anti-Slip
Regulation and it uses electronics to control the throttle when it
detects slippage. The ABS, all-wheel disc brakes gripped fast and
stopped the car firmly, even from pretty high speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Running down the road, the transverse mount engine _ DOHC, two
valves per cylinder, cast iron block, aluminum alloy heads _ purred
quietly. Even in heavy acceleration, the engine produced a distant
rumble rather than a piercing whine.
</P>
<P>
   The five-speed manual transmission is not as tight in its
pattern as I'd expect in a quick European car with too many
clicking sounds and too long a throw for my taste.
</P>
<P>
   I played the roll of soccer coach/tream transporter, commuter to
Boston, and guy-who-gets-the-newspapers-in-the-morning last week
and the Jetta got just over 24 miles per gallon _ fine mileage for
a car that moves as powerfully as this one.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touches
</P>
<P>
   --The dimpled rubber bottoms in each bin. Put coins, glasses,
pens, anything in them and the items will not slide.
</P>
<P>
   --The tuck-away handles above each door. Great aids in getting
in and out of the car.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances
</P>
<P>
   --The placement of the clock in the left quadrant of the main
panel behind the steering wheel. Only the driver can see it. You
can only listen to ``What time is it now, dad?'' so many times.
</P>
<P>
   --The manual seat adjustments. Stiff wheels up the outer sides
of the seats are hard to reach, hard to turn.
</P>
<P>
   (Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1454EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
