<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4068 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MA-FLEET-MERGER-BOS &LR;      10-21 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-FLEET-MERGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET BOSTON FACES CHALLENGE MERGING TWO CULTURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's knitting time at Fleet Boston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In a rough environment for merged banks, the nation's eighth
largest bank faces a woolly task: blending contrasting cultures and
stitching businesses together, all while keeping investors
convinced that plans won't unravel and targets won't be missed.
</P>
<P>
   It is Terrence Murray's toughest job yet. But so far, things
look good.
</P>
<P>
   In the seven months since announcing its $16 billion acquisition
of BankBoston Corp, the new Fleet has won regulatory approval for
one of banking's more controversial deals, picked key managers,
sold billions in deposits, and crafted integration strategies. The
company's two leaders _ one hard-knuckled, the other more patrician
_ are slowly finding ways to work together. With Wall Street wary
of combined banks' promises and unforgiving of missteps, Fleet has
been deft and fast.
</P>
<P>
   But despite solid earnings reported Wednesday, a track record at
making acquisitions work, and general optimism among investors, New
England's largest bank could face snags in coming months, according
to some industry analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based Fleet, reporting results for the first time as a
combined company, said third-quarter profits rose 41 percent to
$711 million, or 74 cents a share. The result, which Fleet credited
to higher investment banking and credit card revenues, beat
analysts' expectations by a penny.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet, which restated previous earnings to reflect the merger,
earned $506 million, or 52 cents a share, in the year-ago period.
Russia's financial crisis depressed BankBoston's third-quarter 1998
earnings, which is one reason the latest results are such an
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers give Murray, Fleet's chief executive, the momentum
to confront make-or-break matters in coming months and to prove he
can run banks as deftly as he buys them. Any stumbles or delays
could spook investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very upbeat _ this deal has the potential to be a grand
slam if executed right,'' said Gerard Cassidy of Tucker Cleary Inc.
``But Fleet sold this deal to investors on cost savings, and now it
has to make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray, 60, has to find a way to combine his trademark
cost-cutting ethic with BankBoston's traditional focus on revenue
growth _ a hallmark of Chad Gifford, BankBoston's former head and
the number two in the new Fleet. And Murray has to do so without
alienating customers or shrinking his revenue base. With bank
stocks battered and investors sour on banks' post-merger
performance, it is not an easy task.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Fleet has put its feet to the fire by promising to cut
$600 million in annual costs and to boost earnings by 21 percent in
2000. A veteran of more than 50 deals, Murray has already started
wielding the ax, planning staff reductions in coming months and
beginning to consolidate facilities and computer systems. Judah S.
Kraushaar, an analyst who covers the bank for Merrill Lynch, wrote
in a recent report that ``management appears hell-bent'' on
achieving savings and financial rigor.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which aims to be a broad financial services
provider, has a crazy quilt of businesses ranging from Latin
American operations and investment bank Robertson Stephens to
discount stock brokerage Quick &AMP; Reilly and commercial finance.
Such breadth gives Fleet an enviable arsenal of accelerated
earnings potential and makes the bank unique among its peers.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet, with $185.3 billion in assets, estimates that 40 percent
of profits will come from its overseas business, investment
management, asset-based finance, and private equity _ all
high-growth businesses. No single line of business accounts for
more than 10 percent of earnings, with the exception of retail
banking, at about 20 percent. But Fleet's diversity also opens room
for quarrels over how to allocate resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger and more diverse you are, the greater the
challenges, '' said Thomas D. McCandless, who covers Fleet for CIBC
World Markets. ``The next two quarters will be critical.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Fleet and the old BankBoston do not share operations in
many areas outside retail banking, tying things together will be
easier than appears, chief financial officer Eugene McQuade said.
``The minimal overlap makes things manageable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other challenges.
</P>
<P>
   One, according to Merrill Lynch's Kraushaar, who has a long-term
buy rating on the stock, is Fleet's backburner positions in
investment management and stock brokering. Tasks include
confronting a slow-growing asset base and revitalizing Quick &AMP;
Reilly _ a move underway as Fleet prepares to offer brokerage
services in one click to the combined bank's 500,000 on-line
banking customers.
</P>
<P>
   A second sticking point is wholesale finance strategy.
BankBoston is more focused on large, national companies requiring
large loans, investment banking, and capital markets services,
while Fleet has concentrated on middle-market businesses in New
England needing cash management and asset-based financing.
</P>
<P>
   And with 20 million retail customers, analysts say Fleet still
has to decide whether to adopt BankBoston's consumer-friendly model
or to go with its bottom-line attitude _ an approach that has
alienated customers in the past. ``This is where the big argument
in the company is going to be,'' said Nancy A. Bush, who covers
Fleet for Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has not been kind to banks whose mergers stumble _
and for good reason. ``The industry's consolidation record is a
gentleman's C,'' said Henry C. Dickson, an analyst at Salomon Smith
Barney. ``But so far, Fleet's doing a pretty good job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
