<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCRETE PORCH FLOOR NEEDS INSULATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have a ground-level heated porch with a concrete
slab-on-grade floor that is very, very cold. How can I insulate the
floor without raising it more than an inch; I have a very low
overhead. Will a carpet insulate the floor?
</P>
<P>
   MARTIN BARRETT, North Attleborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. No, a carpet will not insulate the floor, which is pulling
nearly as much heat out of the room as would be lost through all
the open windows.
</P>
<P>
   There is no compromise: You have to put some insulation on top
of the slab. Apply polyethylene plastic to the floor, set down 2 x
4 sleepers on their wide side, 12 to 16 inches apart, then put 1
1/2-inch-thick styrofoam between the sleepers, and install the
floor; if you put hardwood flooring on the sleepers, you will save
a little thickness. This will raise the floor by 2 1/4 inches. If
that is too much, use 1 x 4s instead of 2 x 4s; they are half as
thick as the 2 x 4s. In that case, apply 3/4-inch-thick foam
insulation and finish off with the hardwood flooring. This will
raise the floor by 1 1/2 inches; you cannot do it effectively with
less than this thickness.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the hardwood flooring, you could put down 5/8-inch
plywood and carpeting or plastic tile, but it will not reduce the
thickness of the floor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My stone retaining wall is 4 1/2-to-5-feet high, and is
bowing outward a bit. I think the bow occurred because there is no
drainage behind the wall, and no weep holes to relieve the
pressure. Can the wall be straightened out? It is chiseled into
ledge, and it is the part above the ledge that is bulging.
</P>
<P>
   JIM KILEY, Boston
</P>
<P>
   A. It is unlikely that you can straighten the bow without
rebuilding the wall. But if the bulge is not so severe that the
wall is threatening to collapse, you can keep it from bowing
further.
</P>
<P>
   Your first priority is to drill some holes in the wall for
drainage; weep holes they are. Drill holes a foot or so above the
ground, spacing them every 4 feet horizontally. Put other holes 2
feet up from the first row of holes. Make a hole by driving a steel
reinforcing bar through the wall. Install copper or sturdy plastic
tubing in the holes. Quarter to half inch will do nicely.
</P>
<P>
   Priority 2: Dig out the earth behind the wall as deep as you can
get, and install crushed stone along the wall. Water will drain
into the crushed stone and the weep holes will carry it away before
it does any more harm.
</P>
<P>
   If you have to dig out a lot of earth on the held side of the
wall, it might be worth tearing down some of the stones and
correcting the bulge. If you do that, don't forget to do all the
other things as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Two long hairline cracks appeared six months ago in the
concrete basement floor of my 3-year-old house. That seems kind of
a short time for cracks to appear anywhere. A mason said I can't do
anything about them. There are no leaks. What can be done?
</P>
<P>
   FRANK GIANNITO, Saugus, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The mason was right in that you cannot do anything about the
cracks, but he could have been more reassuring. So the handyman
will try to be: There is nothing you can do, and nothing you have
to do.
</P>
<P>
   A slab floor is not structural, and is not attached to the
foundation. If it is not reinforced with steel bars or steel mesh,
it is bound to crack. Concrete is strong in compression (it will
hold heavy weights such as houses) but weak in tension (sideways
strength), and if the ground settles under the slab, the slab will
settle too, and will break at the point where it did not settle. If
water comes up through the cracks, that is another kettle of fish
that I really don't want to get into.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am repairing my brick steps by chipping out old mortar and
putting in new mortar between the bricks. How long should I let the
mortar set before using a pointing tool to press in the mortar?
What can I use to fill some hairline cracks in the mortar? If the
hairline cracks go through some of the bricks, can they be filled,
too?
</P>
<P>
   AMERICO PERPETUA, Braintree, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. When you insert new mortar beween bricks, there is no waiting
period before pressing the mortar compactly with a pointing tool.
Actually, you can use the pointing tool (an elongated S-shaped
steel rod) to insert the mortar as well as compact it. And, as you
know, the compaction is important; if the mortar is not compacted
very thoroughly, it will fail in months.
</P>
<P>
   As for the hairline cracks, you can try painting them with a
masonry sealer; enough coats (four or five or more) can actually
fill those cracks, in both mortar and brick. And fill them you must
to prevent water from entering them and freezing in winter, making
them even wider and eventually ruining the steps.
</P>
<P>
   Short of filling the cracks, the only other cure is to replace
the cracked mortar and the cracked bricks. Then again, the steps
could last for years even if the work is not done.
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
