<HEADLINE>
NO NEED TO RUSH, BUT YOU CAN BOOK YOUR SPACEFLIGHT NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Zegrahm Expeditions is booking tourists for their
first flights into space as early as 2003. But would-be space
travelers may have to wait beyond that date for takeoff, according
to aerospace experts.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle-based Zegrahm Space Voyages says it has lined up 250
prospective space travelers, many of whom have put down deposits
for the $98,000, 2{-hour trip into suborbit, where space officially
begins.
</P>
<P>
   Zegrahm's engineering partner, Vela Technology Development Inc.,
is developing the system that would transport these tourists 100
kilometers into space in as few as four years, give them a
2{-minute taste of weightlessness and then return them to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Space Voyages takes you on civilization's next great
adventure; and takes humankind to the brink of a space-faring
civilization,'' said Pat Kelley, the president of Vela Technology,
in a company statement.
</P>
<P>
   Although space tourists eventually will get a chance to head
starward, some experts warn it may take longer _ up to seven years
or more _ before they get that opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia-based Vela Technology is developing a plan to carry six
passengers above Earth in a two-stage process. A jet-powered
``sky-lifter'' would carry the ``space cruiser'' to roughly 50,000
feet. The cruiser _ which resembles a business jet _ is then on its
own.
</P>
<P>
   The space cruiser would use rocket engines to travel to 100
kilometers. It would then employ retro rockets to slow down as it
re-enters the atmosphere. The cruiser would land at a conventional
airfield powered by jet engines.
</P>
<P>
   The $98,000 fee buys a customer more than just the space trip.
Touring astronauts would receive their own spacesuits and and
boots, five days of training, hotel accommodations and other perks.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics, however, warn that tourist space travel isn't around
the corner. They cite a litany of concerns, ranging from the
availability of financing and insurance to the length of time it
may take to secure regulatory approval. They don't say it's
impossible, they just say it may take awhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would take these predictions with a big, big grain of
salt,'' said Adam Bruckner, chairman of the University of
Washington's Department of Aeronautics and Astronautics. ``This is
rocket science and rockets and space vehicles are very complex.''
</P>
<P>
   It took The Boeing Co. 4{ years to obtain government approval to
fly passengers in its wide-body 777 _ and that was based on
technology of earlier passenger jets.
</P>
<P>
   Like Boeing, space entrepreneurs must secure the blessing of
federal regulators. Vela is talking with the Federal Aviation
Administration and expects a faster review process.
</P>
<P>
   However, the FAA is focusing more of its attention on unmanned
flights, according to one government official, who requested
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA), on the
other hand, has applauded some of the efforts. Space tourism is
``going to generate a large amount of money eventually,'' said
Dwayne Brown, a NASA spokesman. ``These companies are for real.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the timing may not be set, as long as the economy
continues to thrive there likely will be some customers for
spaceflights, according to John Pike, director of space policy for
the Federation of American Scientists in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the big bucks people pay for the price of getting
killed climbing Mount Everest,'' Pike said. ``I would have to
imagine there would be a certain category of entrepreneur that
would not mind having those (space) bragging rights on the golf
course.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Zegrahm Space Voyages says 4,000 people have at least
asked for information about earning those bragging rights. And
Zegrahm isn't alone. Virginia-based Space Adventures also is
talking to customers.
</P>
<P>
   The interest and the high-priced tickets don't mean launching a
space travel business isn't risky, Pike and others said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about the most speculative business I can think of,
both from the investor getting his money back and the customer
coming back in one piece,'' Pike said.
</P>
<P>
   The speculative nature raises one of the biggest questions
facing space travel entrepreneurs: money. Vela expects to finalize
the financing for the development of its space cruiser system by
the end of the year, according to Kelley.
</P>
<P>
   But in an age of Internet startups and software success stories,
the handful of firms developing reusable space vehicles are
generally having a hard time attracting venture capital, said Eric
Stallmer, president of the Space Transportation Association.
</P>
<P>
   The Zegrahm-Vela project is a private venture, according to
officials from both companies, and so isn't relying on government
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Those financing challenges could delay the first commercial
spaceflight by a few years, Stallmer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think something like this along these lines is closer to
being ready in five to seven years,'' Stallmer said.
</P>
<P>
   (For more information about Zegrahm Space Voyages, contact
www.spacevoyages.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
