<SLUG> BC-FILM-DEAD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM THAT PRODUCED `TAXI DRIVER' TRIES AGAIN, WITH LESS SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty-three years ago, director Martin Scorsese and
screenwriter Paul Schrader collaborated on a grim portrait of a New
York City loner called ``Taxi Driver.'' Despite its relentlessly
ugly vision of life, it somehow tapped into the zeitgeist of the
time, and became an instant classic.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Bringing Out the Dead,'' this partnership has reunited
for a long-time-in-coming follow-up about another Manhattan loner
with a stressful job. Schrader says it's not so much a sequel as a
``bookend,'' but, clearly, they're trying to make lightning strike
twice in the same place.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it doesn't. Scorsese's legion of admirers will
find pockets of brilliance, and the movie has a certain morbid
fascination, but it has no real bite, and finally seems so
contrived and pointless it borders on being out-and-out
exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the early '90s, it's about Frank Pierce (Nicolas Cage), a
burnt-out paramedic on the verge of a breakdown who works the
graveyard shift in hell _ Hell's Kitchen, that is. Zooming from
tenement to crack house to back alley, and one crisis after
another: cardiac arrests, gunshot wounds, drug overdoses, births,
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The script is episodic, following the near-psychotic character
over three days with three different partners _ each crazier than
the last _ as he constantly sees the ghosts of patients he's lost
(hence the title), and stumbles into a sort of relationship with an
ex-junkie (Patricia Arquette) whose estranged father he tries to
rescue.
</P>
<P>
   As always with Scorsese, the film has a shimmering technical
polish, an overlay of dark humor (much of it delivered by Scorsese
himself, as the voice of the dispatcher), strong supporting
performances (especially Ving Rhames as a Jesus-freak paramedic)
and a good star turn: Cage plays the character with an appealing
world-weariness and intensity.
</P>
<P>
   But it's never hugely engaging, possibly because the character
is never especially believable, and the crux of his emotional
ordeal _ why he became a paramedic, why he stays one, why he feels
such smothering personal guilt _ somehow gets lost amidst all of
Scorsese's camera tricks, and Schrader's cheap laughs.
</P>
<P>
   As hard as they try to come up with another ``Taxi Driver,''
they also just can't make this film rise up to be more than the sum
of its uneven parts. In the end, it seems the calculated work of
two wealthy filmmakers who are now so far removed from these mean
streets that they can only approach them in terms of an
insensitive, dehumanized, burlesque show.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing Out the Dead. Directed by Martin Scorsese. Screenplay
by Paul Schrader. Cast: Nicolas Cage, Patricia Arquette, John
Goodman, Ving Rhames, Tom Sizemore. Paramount/Touchstone. 118
minutes. Rated R for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1509EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
