<HEADLINE>
SCELZI'S THE TOPS, AND WANTS TO STAY THERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the NHRA makes its annual autumnal visit to the Texas
Motorplex this weekend, here is all you need to know about Top Fuel
driver Gary Scelzi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been anything but Winston champion,'' said Scelzi,
neatly summarizing his 1997 and 1998 seasons. ``I don't want to
lose it. I don't want to lose it because I like it. I like signing
my name with `No. 1' after it. There's not any less drive in me not
to compete as a champion.''
</P>
<P>
   For the six other drivers still mathematically eligible to win
the National Hot Rod Association's most prestigious championship,
those words are fair warning. Beginning with the 14th annual
O'Reilly Fall Nationals in Ennis, three events remain on the
22-race schedule.
</P>
<P>
   And Scelzi is still hanging around. He sits in third place, 66
points behind first-time title contender Tony Schumacher and 46
points behind five-time Winston Top Fuel champion Joe Amato.
</P>
<P>
   A maximum of 138 points is available this weekend, which means
Doug Herbert (75 points out of first), Kenny Bernstein (98), Mike
Dunn (124) and Doug Kalitta (135) remain viable players at The
Plex. Some, of course, will be more viable than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the seven teams in this deal, I would think Gary Scelzi
with \Rcar-owner/tuner\S Alan Johnson is going to be the hardest to
beat,'' said Herbert, winner of consecutive races in Topeka, Kan.,
and Memphis, Tenn. ``Gary gets pressure on him, and he's driving
like a maniac. Not crazy, but good. Alan gets pressure on him,
he'll put the thinking cap on and start figuring out what he needs
to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're motivated. They've got something they could lose. In
my opinion, they're the ones I'd be most worried about going into
these last three races.''
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, the all-concrete Motorplex quarter-mile has been
one of the favorite venues for Scelzi, Johnson and Team Winston.
When it appeared that Scelzi was about to disappear from the Top
Fuel radar screen five races into the season, a victory in the
Castrol Nationals in Ennis in late April reinstated the car known
as ``Big Red'' as a player. Scelzi won two more races, in Commerce,
Ga., and at the end of June in Madison, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Scelzi lowered the NHRA Top Fuel national elapsed-time record to
4.525 seconds and won the fall race at the Motorplex last year, key
elements to his second consecutive championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those super racetracks,'' Scelzi said of Billy
Meyer's facility. ``Our car is suitable to tracks that make a lot
of power. It's going to be interesting. I don't think you'll see
cars that normally don't win end up in the final here. And the last
three tracks we go to, you'll see some incredible ET and speeds.''
</P>
<P>
   In between one-on-ones against Cory McClenathan, Bernstein and
Kalitta, Scelzi has wheeled the division's dominant car since
succeeding the late Blaine Johnson in the fall of 1996. Scelzi won
five races as a rookie in 1997, including his first two starts, and
another six in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But this season has been notable for its inconsistencies,
punctuated by the fact that Schumacher has led the standings since
the U.S. Nationals on Labor Day weekend despite never having won a
race. And Amato, whose five victories lead the division, somehow is
stuck in second.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never not been a dominant car in all the seasons
I've been around Winston Drag Racing,'' said Scelzi, a 39-year-old
resident of Fresno, Calif. ``I've never seen it like that. Normally
there's some that's hot, but even when they cool off, they're not
that bad. The inconsistency among the teams is probably the
strangest thing I've seen this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I do understand why. There's so many teams that can run
low numbers, that you can't run soft. You've got to run it like
it's a final round every time, or you're going to get beat. A lot
of times they'll send you home packing.''
</P>
<P>
   Scelzi said this points race has been great for team morale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alan and I always assure our crew they're the baddest on the
planet,'' Scelzi said. ``Morale is good, but Alan's going to give
them a pep talk when we get to Texas Friday morning, and turn the
stereo up and have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Scelzi also said this points race has been great for the
two-time reigning series champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single round is a factor in the points chase,'' Scelzi
said. ``I'd rather have it like \RFunny Car champion\S John Force _
win it early and keep the lead. But nobody wants to see a chase for
second. They want to see a chase for first.''
</P>
<P>
   And for as long as he has been racing in Top Fuel, that is all
Gary Scelzi ever has known.
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT ON... Ray's `off-season' full of testing tires, trucks
Newly crowned Indy Racing League champion Greg Ray says he has a
dream vacation all planned. Ray would love to take his wife,
Angela, and sons Winston and Simon, on a wind-surfing vacation in
Aruba.
</P>
<P>
   But probably not this year.
</P>
<P>
   And actually ... ``forgetaboutit''.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week after wrapping up his first IRL title at Texas
Motor Speedway, Ray has been booked to start four days of tire and
engine testing at Indianapolis Motor Speedway. Ray and Team Menard
are Firestone's lead tire-testing team, and he is scheduled to
spend Friday and Saturday turning laps for the manufacturer using
the league's current 4.0-liter Aurora V-8 engine for a baseline.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then we'll go to the 3.5-liter engine on Sunday and
Monday, and we won't see a 4-liter engine again,'' said Ray,
referring to the rules package that goes into effect in 2000. ``We
don't have the new \RDallara\S chassis yet, but we're already
working on tire development for next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the engine, we'll find out its nature and quirks. It's
going to turn more RPMs, like 11,000 RPMs. They've reversed the
crank angle so it's going to change the sound. With the new chassis
and gear boxes, although we'll lose horsepower, you can count on
the cars being about as fast as they were this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray laughed at the notion that after a season that stretched
from January to mid-October, his comp time was about to kick in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between now and June is my busy time of the season,'' said
Ray, whose four poles and three victories led the series in his
first season of driving for car-owner John Menard. ``We have a lot
of things going on under the tent.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray said he and Menard have abandoned the idea of an appearance
in the Championship Auto Racing Teams season ender Oct. 31 at
California Speedway. Menard is partners in Robby Gordon's CART
adventure, and Ray said the possibility of running with that
series' regulars on the two-mile speedway was intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity is still there, but we're so focused on our
IRL program,'' Ray said. ``It'd be fun to do that, if you had great
equipment. But they have a championship coming down to the wire,
and we have our own agenda in front of us. I don't think there's
anything to gain from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ray said he definitely will figure into Menard's
plans to compete in the NASCAR truck series in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``With John Menard purchasing the No. 3 truck team, over the
course of the winter we'll do some testing and probably run a
couple of truck races for fun,'' Ray said. ``Because driving
different cars broadens your horizons.''
</P>
<P>
   Menard reportedly has agreed to purchase seven Chevrolet
Silverado trucks from the inventory of owner Richard Childress. Jay
Sauter, current driver of the No. 3 GM Goodwrench Service Plus
truck, won the O'Reilly 300 from the pole at TMS on Oct. 15. The
series concludes Oct. 30 at California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Menard has hired 1996 truck-series rookie of the year Bryan
Reffner as his driver and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how the truck team goes,'' Menard said. ``I'd like
some day to get to Winston Cup with that team, but you have to walk
before you run. If we start winning races in the truck series, you
can figure that team is going to get ready to go to Winston Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray, who has completed only the first year of a five-year
contract with Menard, said he is excited by the seemingly endless
possibilities afforded by the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``If for any reason we become bored or complacent \Rwith the
IRL\S, and if we decided collectively we wanted to go CART racing,
then we would do that,'' said Ray, speaking of Menard and team
manager Thomas Knapp. ``If we decided collectively we wanted to go
Winston Cup racing, then we would do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exciting thing for me is my team owner is John Menard. If
we want to go do it, there's no questions asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny Car driver Force's hints Fuel speculation
Eight-time Funny Car champion John Force is promising a blockbuster
announcement about his current two-car team during the NHRA's fall
tour through Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Force said the announcement, backed by high-profile sponsors
Ford and Castrol GTX, could be about his long-rumored Top Fuel
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a dragster or a Funny Car,'' said Force, who is
bearing down on his record ninth NHRA Funny Car championship.
``We'll either do it at Dallas or Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   The NHRA visits the Texas Motorplex in Ennis for the 14th annual
O'Reilly Fall Nationals this weekend, then heads to Houston Raceway
Park in Baytown on Oct. 28-31.
</P>
<P>
   Force said his victory against Top Fuel ace Bob Vandergriff Jr.
in the final of the inaugural Winston Showdown at Bristol (Tenn.)
Dragway in July was ``a very big high.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bristol win against the dragster really got me thinking
dragsters,'' Force said. ``You talk about a high; it felt like they
put me on straight nitro. My head wanted to come off. I got to race
Kenny Bernstein and Bob Vandergriff, and it was just really
exciting. It was just kind of unique. It was probably the biggest
high in my career, bigger than my first championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something neat is going to go down. A dragster would be
exciting. It's going to be something where you say, `That goofy
sonofagun did it again.' I talked to a number of crew chiefs, a
number of drivers. Just hang on. I'm excited about it. Get me
drunk, I'll tell you. Otherwise I can't tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   QUICK HITS Sonntag replaces Starr Fort Worth's David Starr is
out as driver of the No. 73 Chevrolet owned by Joey Sonntag in the
NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series.
</P>
<P>
   B.A. Wilson of Carrollton is scheduled to debut for the team at
the season-ending NAPA 200 at California Speedway on Oct. 30.
Originally from Bonham, Wilson drove the No. 85 Ford to a
24th-place finish in the O'Reilly 300 at Texas Motor Speedway on
Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Starr started a season-high eighth but finished 32nd at TMS
after an early brush with the wall. Starr's best finish in 23
starts this season is 14th, in the Pronto Auto Parts 400 at TMS in
June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been thinking about this as long as two months ago,''
said Sonntag, whose team is based in Little Elm. ``I wanted to make
this deal work and let it go. At Texas, we mutually agreed it was
time for me to have a fresh start with a new driver and for him to
open up his options.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr has been rumored to be under consideration for trucks
rides with Petty Enterprises and Roush Racing. Rain follows Outlaws
Promoter Lanny Edwards has been flat out of luck when his Devil's
Bowl Speedway plays host to the World of Outlaws. Two of the three
appearances by the Outlaws at the half-mile dirt track in Mesquite
were hampered by rain this year.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the final night's main event was stopped after eight
laps because of rain and made up one month later. Saturday's
championship main event also was rained out. Gary Wright, who won
Friday's preliminary, was declared the champion.
</P>
<P>
   The rain came after 18 drivers had qualified in front of what
Edwards said was the biggest crowd he had played host to. He
estimated the attendance at more than 9,000.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said fans who purchased tickets for Saturday night's
event can exchange them for tickets to one night of next year's
Spring Nationals, scheduled for March 17-18, or send a
self-addressed, stamped envelope to Devil's Bowl for a refund.
Merchandise on sale Racing fans can stock up on merchandise from
top drivers during the annual ``NASCAR Sale-abration'' at Texas
Motor Speedway on Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Speedway trailers will feature merchandise from the inventories
of Dale Earnhardt, Dale Earnhardt Jr., Mark Martin, Terry and Bobby
Labonte and Jeff Burton, among others. Greg Ray, the newly crowned
Pep Boys Indy Racing League champion, also will have merchandise
available, as well as new 2000 logo TMS items. Most will be priced
from 25 to 50 percent off.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers will receive a one-lap ride around the 1.5-mile
racetrack for each $50 spent on driver and/or speedway merchandise.
Fans spending $100 or more will receive a pair of qualifying
tickets for the 2000 NASCAR Winston Cup race in addition to the
track ride.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call 215-8500. Cobra group to gather The
Shelby Cobra Association of Texas' 22nd annual Shelby Texas
Nationals automotive festival is scheduled for tomorrow through
Sunday at the Motorsports Ranch in Cresson.
</P>
<P>
   The event is open to all Ford-powered vehicles. This year's
program will include some of the country's finest Shelby Cobras,
GT350s, GT500s, Panteras, Mustangs, Sunbeam Tigers, Thunderbirds
and Ford-powered race cars. A banquet, classic car show and road
racing benefit the Carroll Shelby Children's Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Racing in three classes is scheduled for tomorrow and Saturday
on the 11-turn, 1.8-mile natural-terrain course. Motorsports Ranch
is located approximately 20 miles southwest of Fort Worth off Texas
377.
</P>
<P>
   For event information, call (972) 289-4336. Texas Raceway silent
The resurfacing schedule at Texas Raceway in Kennedale has been
shuffled because rains that soaked the area this week.
</P>
<P>
   Resurfacing of the eighth-mile drag strip got underway
yesterday, but plans to be in operation this weekend have been
shelved, with the track now scheduled to reopen Oct. 30 for a full
schedule. Minority drivers to test
</P>
<P>
   Three drivers selected for CART's inaugural African-American
Driver Development Program are scheduled to log their first test
miles Tuesday at Buttonwillow Raceway, north of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Selected for the test in a Toyota Atlantic race car are David
Francis Jr. of Los Angeles, Andrew Kelley of Columbus, Ohio, and
Bill Lester of Oakland, Calif. The drivers are to receive a seat
fitting and be familiarized with the open-wheeled cars Monday at
the Cal Wells-owned PPI race shop in Rancho Santa Margarita, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Each driver is scheduled to run approximately 100 miles during a
test conducted by Arciero-Wells Racing. The PPI team plans to make
a series of changes to the car and evaluate how each driver
responds on the track. A debriefing session follows.
</P>
<P>
   If merited, one of the three could move to an Indy Lights test
with Team KOOL Green, as the Championship Auto Racing Teams looks
to discover and develop minority drivers. Last words ``When I was a
kid _ which goes to show you how old A.J. is now _ I remember
reading a book about him when I was in the fifth grade. I idolized
him.'' _ IRL champion Greg Ray of Plano
