<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-TAILBACK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU TAILBACK TOMLINSON GAINING YARDS, NATIONAL ACCLAIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It is 1 o'clock on Monday afternoon, and the
guy on the line from ``USA Today'' wants to know how many earrings
LaDainian Tomlinson wears.
</P>
<P>
   ``One in each ear,'' Tomlinson says, looking puzzled. ``But I
take them out during the games.''
</P>
<P>
   Get used to it, L.T.; when you're the leading rusher in the
nation, they'll ask you anything.
</P>
<P>
   Oh. They already asked about the tattoos?
</P>
<P>
   Four. One is a picture of his mother, Lorene Chappell. One bears
the initials, ``L.T.'' One is a representation of God's hands,
folded in prayer. The fourth is a picture of the Waco University
Bulldog, his high school mascot.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few others, actually _ most of them adorning the
helmets of TCU opponents. They look like cleat marks.
</P>
<P>
   In only six games as the lone resident at the tailback position,
which he shared last year with Basil Mitchell, Tomlinson, a
5-foot-11, 217-pound junior, has become a burgeoning star with a
rapidly expanding audience.
</P>
<P>
   With 178 yards against Tulsa last week, he became the first back
in TCU history to top the 1,000-yard mark in six games. He has
1,060 yards on 145 carries, averaging 7.3 yards per pop. At 176.7
yards per game, he leads the nation by a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
   He has used his 4.3-second speed to break for scoring runs of
74, 79, 80 and 89 yards and has bulled his way through a tangle of
defenders on close-in scoring thrusts. In three of the past four
games, he has been selected offensive player of the week in the
Western Athletic Conference.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a 300-yard explosion against San Jose State, he
was approached by a weary foe, who said, ``What are you trying to
do, win the Heisman Trophy in one day?''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago, a national publication identified him as
the best unknown back in America. Now, he is being interviewed from
afar on the cultural significance of body-piercing.
</P>
<P>
   When he walked into the TCU football offices Monday, secretary
Jennette Forrester high-fived him. And, as revealed in a local news
item this week, in regional rushing statistics, he ranks just ahead
of Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm surprised at some of the things he's done ...
well, that he's leading the nation,'' coach Dennis Franchione said.
``But I'm not surprised at the way he's played. We thought he could
perform this way, and in fact, I think his rushing total is about
what he and Basil together had at this point last year. It's just
that now, he's doing it by himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with a few friends. After a scolding by Franchione
following a loss in which Fresno State keyed exclusively on
Tomlinson and held him to 49 yards, TCU's offensive linemen have
developed a steamroller complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of weeks, the holes have been unbelievable,''
Tomlinson says. ``On that (TCU record) 89-yard run against San
Jose, I wasn't thinking about a long run, just about helping us
punch out and start a drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I saw the hole, I knew it was a touchdown. Actually,
I was kind of running for my life, because I figured that after the
hole they opened, these guys would kill me if I let anyone catch
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, I think they enjoy those plays as much as I do,
because we're all involved in it together. But I may have to take
everyone out to dinner at the end of the season. Probably have to
borrow some money from my mother, though.''
</P>
<P>
   A logical thought. Tomlinson's parents divorced when he was in
grade school, and Lorene, a real estate agent who lives in Dallas,
became the strongest influence on his youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still talk to my dad, and I also had a stepdad for awhile,''
he says. ``But my mother raised me. Everything I needed to know
about being a man _ how to act, what to do _ my mother taught me.''
</P>
<P>
   It has always been one of the more impressive things about
Tomlinson, which is why, Franchione says, it was such a shock when
Tomlinson and former TCU basketball player Lee Nailon, among
others, were arrested last summer at a motel where a robbery had
taken place and where police found evidence of a controlled
substance. Eventually, the players were released and no charges
were filed, but Tomlinson said he learned a lesson about being in
the wrong place at the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went over there that morning to see Lee, because he had just
got back in town and that's where he was,'' Tomlinson says.
``Something had evidently happened there a few hours earlier, but I
didn't know anything about it. But the police came, and we all got
taken to jail. I was still wearing my sweat suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchione said that ``when I got the phone call, I said, `That
doesn't sound like L.T.' I was stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, I give them a speech about how when you sign to
become a Division I player, you have a responsibility to be careful
in your relationships and in where you go, but they don't always
listen. L.T. is a guy who simply takes everyone at face value and
just doesn't think about those things happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson, however, said he is a changed man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned that anything can happen,'' he said. ``Mostly, I
just stay at home now with my girlfriend (Lakesia McKinney). I
don't go out much anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tomlinson and younger brother LaVar, a two-way player at
Dallas Samuell, manage to keep Lorene on the run.
</P>
<P>
   When Tomlinson burst through the startled Spartans on the
89-yard run, Lorene was on her feet at Amon Carter Stadium, tears
streaming down her cheeks. When he went 74 on a pitch moments
later, it was a bit much. She had to sit down.
</P>
<P>
   ``She missed the Tulsa game,'' he said, laughing, ``because
Samuell had a game that night and she went to see LaVar play.''
</P>
<P>
   So, she missed the 80-yard option on which he burned through a
seam, outran the pursuit down the sideline, cut back inside a final
defender, and delivered the blow that signalled the beginning of
the Golden Hurricane's end. At this rate, he will create enough
highlight film to open a studio by season's end.
</P>
<P>
   His favorite run? Why, that 9-yarder in the fourth quarter
against Arkansas State, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think that's the best run I've had,'' he said,
``because it got us a first down when we needed it, and I stayed in
bounds, too. That allowed us to run about two more minutes off the
clock, and that's what we were trying to do to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchione agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember it because he landed right at my feet on the
sideline,'' he says. ``We didn't block it very well, but he broke a
tackle and dove for the first-down marker and made it. And stayed
inbounds to run the clock. Those are the kind you remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he already has one more carry than he had in all of
last season, Tomlinson, whose longest run in '98 was 36 yards, said
he is one of those tailbacks who gets better as the game wears on.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, you're a little tentative, you don't know where the
seams are,'' he said. ``And last year, it was hard to get in a
groove coming in and out of the game. This way, you see the seams
better as the game goes on, you know what the blockers are going to
do, you know where to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, no argument from Franchione.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, you worry about the wear on him,'' he said. ``But
against Arkansas State, he had 40 carries and proved he could
handle it (269 yards). If you have a big weapon, you use it.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, Tomlinson agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm rested and still hungry,'' he says. ``Tailbacks are made
to run.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1515EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
