<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEBRASKA MYSTIQUE STOPS AT TEXAS BORDER
</HEADLINE>
 12 REPORT-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the only Division I-A school to win three national
championships in the 1990s, Nebraska has every right to crow about
being college football's team of the decade. Not even the
staunchest football fan from Florida State can quibble with that
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there is a stunning reversal of fortune when the Big Red
butts heads with teams from the other side of the Red River. Since
the creation of the Big 12, Nebraska is 29-4 against conference
opponents and owns winning records against all but two schools.
</P>
<P>
   The dissenters are Texas (0-2) and Texas A&AMP;M (1-1).
</P>
<P>
   This puzzles the Cornhuskers, who lost as double-digit favorites
on three occasions. But it makes sense to me. And the theory is
seconded by players, all of them native Texans who were not
brainwashed from birth by the Midwestern misconception that
Nebraska perfected the sport of college football.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put: Children of the Corn, you've got no fear factor down
here.
</P>
<P>
   Showing up in those white helmets with an ``N'' on the side
might be worth 14 points against Kansas, Iowa State and Oklahoma
State. It was worth more than that against Kansas State until a
quarterback from Texas, Michael Bishop, helped alter the mind-set
in Manhattan, Kan., and ended a 30-year losing streak in that
series.
</P>
<P>
   But the third-ranked Cornhuskers (6-0, 3-0) won't have any
mental mojo working for them when they meet No. 18 Texas (5-2, 2-1)
on Saturday in Austin. Nor will they take the field against a bunch
of intimidated Aggies when No. 13 A&AMP;M (5-1, 2-1) visits Lincoln,
Neb., on Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Let's do the math that unravels this mystery. The majority of
today's college players are 20-22 years old. Their most
impressionable childhood years came and went between 1987-93.
During that stretch, Nebraska lost seven consecutive bowl games.
</P>
<P>
   For budding football stars in Texas, those postseason contests
offered a rare glimpse of Nebraska football in the pre-Big 12 days.
And it was not an impressive sight. Contrast that to players who
grew up watching weekly telecasts from the old Big Eight, when
Nebraska steamrolled everyone. The residual effects are evident
today.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Texas receiver Ryan Nunez, an Austin native who played
his freshman season at Colorado (1996) before transferring.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could be very true,'' Nunez said of the inherent Big Red
fear that cripples North Division teams but fails to impact Texans.
``I think that's a mind-set that's in our subconscious. We may not
talk about it, but it's there ... The northern schools, like
Colorado, put more emphasis on Nebraska than we do. When I was at
Colorado, people were talking about the Nebraska game before
two-a-days. With that goes more pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that to the advice of Texas coach Mack Brown, who urges
players to ``take the logo off the helmet'' and treat the
Cornhuskers like any other team. That is easier to do, admitted
Texas cornerback Ahmad Brooks, if you haven't been inundated for
years with tales of Nebraska's invincibility.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, a sophomore who grew up in Abilene, said he ``wasn't
familiar with the Nebraska mystique'' until he began getting
recruiting letters as a junior in high school.
</P>
<P>
   But how long was he aware that A&AMP;M and Texas played the sport at
a high level?
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I was a boy,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   Others downplay the native Texan angle as a factor in adopting a
fearless approach when facing Nebraska. Texas defensive end Cedric
Woodard, a Sweeney resident, said it boils down to ``being lucky
and being prepared.'' Texas A&AMP;M strong safety Michael Jameson, who
grew up in Killeen, cites the need for self-confidence and a
short-term memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go out there scared of Nebraska's tradition,''
Jameson said. ``On that day, tradition goes away. It's just a
matter of who makes the plays on that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent history suggests players who carry a Texas driver's
license have the best chance of looking past Nebraska's glowing
credentials on game day. Such a development validates a theory
lofted in 1996 by Rice coach Ken Hatfield in the wake of the
Southwest Conference breakup.
</P>
<P>
   When a new league is formed, Hatfield said: ``You've got to
establish your position in the conference pecking order, instead of
having it grandfathered in like in the past. You're playing four or
five new teams and none of them are awed by your mystique.''
</P>
<P>
   Some day, Longhorns and Aggies might arrive wide-eyed and
trembling for showdowns against Cornhuskers, just like Jayhawks and
Cyclones. But not this year. The Big Red mystique has yet to take
root in points south of the Red River.
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT ON: NORTH MIGHT SEPARATE SOUTH'S CLOSE CONTENDERS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the South Division race in a virtual dead heat among five
schools, the teams that could play the greatest role in determining
the outcome might not be listed in the South standings.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the championship could be impacted heavily by North
Division schools Nebraska and Kansas State. Both the third-ranked
Cornhuskers (6-0, 3-0) and seventh-ranked Wildcats (6-0, 3-0) have
two crossover games remaining against South opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska plays Texas (5-2, 2-1) and Texas A&AMP;M (5-1, 2-1). Kansas
State meets Oklahoma State (3-2, 1-1) and Baylor (1-5, 0-3).
</P>
<P>
   Notice that Texas Tech (3-3, 2-1) and Oklahoma (3-2, 1-1) are
not on the remaining schedules for the league's only Top 10 teams.
Unless upsets occur, the Red Raiders and Sooners figure to pick up
a pivotal game down the stretch, courtesy of Nebraska and Kansas
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important in this race how you do against the other half
of the league,'' Tech coach Spike Dykes said. ``That's why beating
Colorado (last week) was such an important win for us. We've still
got Missouri and Iowa State left to play from the North Division.
They're tough teams. But it's not like playing Nebraska and Kansas
State.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas coach Mack Brown, whose lone league loss came against
Kansas State, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some years, you hit the schedule right. Some years, you
don't,'' Brown said. ``Obviously, it's not a plus for us this year.
You'd have to say the teams playing both Nebraska and Kansas State
have the toughest road.''
</P>
<P>
   Among South schools, only Texas and Oklahoma State play the
Cornhuskers and Wildcats.
QUICK HITS PIVOTAL WEEK
</P>
<P>
   A clouded South Division title race could swing in any of five
directions this week, depending on Saturday's outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the five contending teams, each with one loss in the
league standings, two are underdogs against top-10 opponents
(Texas, Oklahoma State). Two square off in a potential elimination
match (Texas A&AMP;M, Oklahoma). Only Texas Tech is a clear favorite,
and the Red Raiders have yet to win consecutive games heading into
a contest at Baylor that follows a victory against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``This next week will open a lot of eyes,'' Tech coach Spike
Dykes said. ``A lot of different scenarios could unfold. When the
smoke clears on Sunday, we'll have a little better idea what's
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum said: ``This is a week where you either
take a step forward or you take a big step back. This is a big week
for everyone in the South Division.'' PRIMARY SECONDARY
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska defensive backs wear T-shirts beneath their uniforms
emblazoned with the slogan ``Secondary to None.'' They rank third
nationally in pass efficiency defense, allowing opponents a 42
percent completion rate. The Cornhuskers have 20 pass breakups and
nine interceptions and have permitted only four touchdowns passes
in six games.
</P>
<P>
   How good are they?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll find out this week,'' said cornerback Ralph Brown,
looking ahead to a matchup against a Texas passing game that
averages 305.4 yards per outing. ``This will be the biggest test
we've faced all year, but I think we'll be up to the challenge. We
want to show people we really do have the best secondary in the
country.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
