<HEADLINE>
IT'S A SCREECH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What Alfred Hitchock understood with ``The Birds,'' and Steven
Spielberg understood with ``Jaws,'' is that when you make a ``when
animals attack'' movie, it helps to have humans who are at least as
interesting as the animals. ``Bats,'' like too many other films,
forgets this, giving us stock characters _ stolid sheriff (Lou
Diamond Phillips), spunky zoologist (Dina Meyer), her wisecracking
assistant (Leon, in a role that's a little too ``feets, do yo'
stuff'' for my taste), earnest Centers for Disease Control official
(Carlos Jacott) and mad scientist (Bob Gunton) _ battling
computer-generated imagery and really ugly puppets. The scientist's
nefarious experiments result in hordes of genetically altered bats
attacking a small Texas town (why do these things always happen
away from population centers?).
</P>
<P>
   It's as trashy as it sounds, but it's also kind of entertaining,
in a turn-off-your-brain sort of way. Louis Morneau directs with
enough play-with-camera style to make you think he has some
promise, until you find out that he already has a half-dozen
straight-to-video titles to his credit. The bat attacks are pretty
cool, though _ and the bats, with their screeching, have the best
dialogue in the movie. Filmed in Utah, despite the Texas setting.
89 min. PG-13 (strong language, violence, ugly bats, guano)
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
