<SLUG> BC-SALMON-FISHING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BRUNSWICK OFFERS FLOOR FOR A SLOW DANCE WITH SALMON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRED LeBRUN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Every fall I buy a ticket to dance with salmon.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 20 years, Robert Dewell, my fishing partner since
childhood and now of Cooperstown, and I pack a rental with all the
gear and clothes we need for a week of fly fishing for Atlantic
salmon on one or another Canadian river.
</P>
<P>
   In recent times, we've been joined by Frank McCaffrey of New
Scotland. For years we would head for the little-known Stewiacke in
upper Nova Scotia and be virtually alone on a 20-mile river. When
that precious gem closed due to a mysterious lack of returning wild
fish nearly a decade ago, as have most Bay of Fundy rivers, we
moved with an increasing sense of the ominous to others in the
province. We tried the East, the West, St. Mary's, many others.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, they closed, as well, for the same reason. That left
us only the muscular Margaree far out on Cape Breton Island, Nova
Scotia's last, best hope for preserving a once proud and prolific
salmon fishing tradition.
</P>
<P>
   But even there, the fishing pressure has become so intense for
often a limited run of fish, that civility and cordiality have been
sorely stressed. Too many fishermen, too few fish. It's not much
fun dancing on the Margaree these days.
</P>
<P>
   So during the '90s we switched our affections to New Brunswick's
main branch of the Miramichi.
</P>
<P>
   It is truly a dance we go to, although years ago each of us
learned painfully that a ticket never guarantees even one partner.
Every river offers a different symphony as background, a blend of
rushing currents and incessant winds. It is deliciously lonely.
Waist deep in 41-degree water, fighting to maintain balance, hour
after hour we cast over and over into a promising seam of pitch
black water with tensed muscles, waiting. Waiting for a partner.
</P>
<P>
   A salmon's ``take'' on the small wet fly free-floating down
river is usually unmistakable. It's as if the fly hits a brick
wall. The line goes taut, there usually are a couple of quick head
shakes, and soon after the salmon goes airborne, tailing along the
surface. Over and over, dancing on its tail. Then running upstream
or down with a power and purpose as amazing to feel and marvel at
the hundredth time as the first.
</P>
<P>
   Too soon, it's over, although by the clock it might be half an
hour. Either the salmon breaks loose, or we release it, coaxing it
back to full strength before letting go.
</P>
<P>
   As the late Lee Wulff said years ago, an Atlantic salmon is too
precious a commodity to be caught only once. That's also become the
law in North America. Big salmon, the breeders, must be released,
there are so few of them anymore. Some small, one-sea-run salmon,
called grilse, may be kept, but most fishermen I know release those
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Because we're all feeling a sense of doom settling over Atlantic
salmon, and we desperately want to keep the dance going as long as
we can.
</P>
<P>
   From any perspective, the facts are deeply discouraging. In the
last two decades, 80 percent of the Atlantic salmon stock in Europe
and North America have simply disappeared, and in general that
decline continues. The why of it is mostly a mystery, although
there is no lack of suspects, from long-haul commercial nets in the
ocean, to disease brought in by huge fish farms, to natural
predators such as seals, cod, and stripers. And always, and
especially, us. Greedy fingers.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is so desperate right now in Maine that Trout
Unlimited and the Atlantic Salmon Federation are calling for
immediate, emergency listing of indigenous wild salmon as an
endangered species. Otherwise, the prediction is they will be
extinct in as little as two to five years.
</P>
<P>
   Our anecdotal report from the Miramichi this year is cautiously
optimistic, or at least, not wholly negative. We hooked and landed
fish every day, which constitutes an excellent fishing trip. A
total of 15, mostly grilse. That's much better than the past two
years. And we saw markedly more salmon this year, rolling on the
surface and flashing through, because we arrived, fortunately, well
after the disastrous drought months of July and August.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, salmon have the option of hanging out in bays until
there's enough water in a river to make a spawning run. We
benefited from good water, and excellent guides.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the big commercial fishing camps catering to well-heeled
sports from the states took a shellacking again this year. There
were fewer this year than last. No water, no fish during prime
time. Even small operations we encountered are openly saying what
was unspeakable a few years ago. There is talk about closing cabins
and camps along this majestic river on beats that have been fished
with the devotion of a religion every year for centuries. No water,
no fish. No point.
</P>
<P>
   I did hook and land a bright hen of about 30 pounds, according
to my conservative guide, a torpedo of a fish that slammed a 12
black bear. She danced and danced, and kept me running for the
better part of an hour. At the end, I was more exhausted than she
was. We had the best time.
</P>
<P>
   God willing, we'll both be back next year. Wouldn't miss the
dance for anything.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
