<HEADLINE>
HAPPY ENDING FOR A FRUSTRATED FISHERMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRED LeBRUN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Strange happenings are commonplace on a fishing
stream, although few of them feature a reasonably happy ending even
for the fish, as this one does.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Silverman was fly fishing for giant chinooks with three
buddies on Lake Ontario's Salmon River last Wednesday, along the
privately owned Douglaston run. The fishing was good, at least for
his companions, each of whom hooked up muscular fish during what
seems to be the last big spurt of king salmon coming into the
river. But none of this rubbed off on Silverman, who had a
frustrating day of misses. Then again, although he is a lifelong
spin fisher, he is only a beginning fly fisher, and there is the
learning curve to get through.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he was trying too hard, or he was just plain sloppy, which
he couldn't afford to be because he wasn't wearing spiked Korkers
underfoot. The Salmon is a river slippery as goose spit on the best
day, and on this occasion a sudden drop in temperature loosed algae
that made every rock a bowling ball.
</P>
<P>
   In his eagerness to get out into four feet of water to cast to
some moving fish, Silverman took a royal header. It's instinct to
throw your arms out in front to break the fall, which he did.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, an Orvis DXR reel, Orvis fly line and Heritage 8
wt. rod all went sailing into the current and disappeared. Big
bucks. Fruitlessly, the four searched the river bottom for hours
and couldn't find the rig.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Silverman was one dejected puppy on that ride home, and told
his wife when he walked in the door that it was the worst day of
his life. But then on the weekend he got a call from a chiropractor
from Queens, who found the rod and reel and wanted to know how to
get the stuff back to Silverman, who had wisely left his name and
address at the check-in booth at Douglaston.
</P>
<P>
   It was like Silverman's buddy, Patrick Sisti, said in
consolation while they were searching: ``You just want to pray a
fly fisherman finds your rod, because he or she can understand how
you feel right now.''
</P>
<P>
   If just getting a top-end rig back from a stranger isn't odd
enough, consider what the chiropractor had to report. It seems
Silverman had his pink egg fly attached to his hook keeper when it
went flying. But when the rod was found, all the line was out plus
a lot of the backing. The fly was gone, and so was a foot of the
tippet.
</P>
<P>
   The best guess is the fly came loose from its guard, a Chinook
scarfed it up and went for a merry fin down river. The fish finally
snapped off, which is common enough even when a rod is being
well-played by a human at the other end. Which means that as a
final indignity to the day for Silverman, the only time a salmon
found his fly appealing was when he wasn't fishing it, which
doesn't say much for his technique.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe it does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
