<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BODYSHOTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BODY SHOTS' TAKES AIM AT PRURIENT INTERESTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somebody involved in the advertising of ``Body Shots'' actually
had the nerve to come up with the tagline, ``There are movies that
define every decade ...''. Yeah, there are, but ``Body Shots''
isn't one of them, unless you've spent the decade with your nose
buried in magazine sex-advice columns.
</P>
<P>
   This overdirected, pretentious film has about as much depth as
an average ``Friends'' episode, although come to think of it,
``Friends'' is more decade-defining, even with its well-chronicled
lack of diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Let's cut the malarkey, OK? What ``Body Shots'' is about is sex,
baby. Its eight characters talk about its various forms, often in
annoyingly staged faux interviews during which they directly
address the camera. They not only talk, they take action, and
director Michael Cristofer _ a Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright
who should know better _ spends a good deal of time showing them in
the act. He may be after a ``mature'' movie that says that we're
all desperate for love or at least a connection, but what he
delivers often looks like soft-core porn.
</P>
<P>
   Cristofer and screenwriter David McKenna _ who wrote the
similarly oversimplified but much better-executed ``American
History X'' _ create superficial characters, all good-looking
people who, after about five minutes, seem about as desirable as a
case of pinkeye. The message, apparently, is that looks can be
deceiving. Well, duh.
</P>
<P>
   The movie sets them up in teams _ girls vs. boys _ who
rendezvous at a club, pair in assorted ways, and wind up having an
eventful night.
</P>
<P>
   The central event happens to Michael (Jerry O'Connell), a pro
football player, and Sara (Tara Reid of ``American Pie,'' a much
more honest movie about sex), an aspiring actress. After he spirits
her away from her nice-guy prospective boyfriend, they go back to
her place, and she later accuses him of date rape. Cristofer and
McKenna linger on this plot thread, with Michael and Sara each
telling their versions of the story with the movie graphically
depicting each side. It's here that the movie takes a turn from
shallow to offensive; even as it cops out by refusing to take a
stand, it still has a lot of ``Well, she asked for it'' in its
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   There's a couple that we're meant to root for, played by Sean
Patrick Flanery and Amanda Peet, each of whom takes a turn as
surrogate counselor/attorney with their friends entangled in the
rape case. But the movie keeps them apart for so long, it doesn't
allow us to become involved in their budding romance. Instead, it
dwells on scenes of back-alley sex and cartoonish bondage among its
other principal characters.
</P>
<P>
   The movie would be a lot less irritating if Cristofer and
McKenna weren't so convinced that they were saying something
profound, or if it its actors didn't look so much like they bought
into the baloney. At times, you wonder how they said some of their
lines without bursting out laughing. If you met any of their
characters in real life, it would probably take only a couple of
heartbeats to spot them for the phonies they are. So why waste a
couple of hours with 'em?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Body Shots''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Michael Cristofer
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Sean Patrick Flanery, Jerry O'Connell, Tara Reid
</P>
<P>
   Length: 102 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ strong language, nudity, violence including a rape
scene, sexual situations and much sexually frank but silly dialogue
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1525EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4106 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-BOYS-TEX     10-21 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BOYS' IS ALL GROWN UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hilary Swank, the star of ``Boys Don't Cry,'' represents a
peculiar kind of culture clash. Slender and hipless, she resembles
the wiry, androgynous trailer trash whom Larry Clark (''Kids'')
stared at through his camera lens and Calvin Klein employed as
underwear models a few years ago. Swank, who glowered at Mr. Miyagi
as ``The Next Karate Kid'' a few years back, looks like Matt Damon,
but the Matt Damon of ``Courage Under Fire'' _ toothy and
emaciated. Astonishingly, she also resembles Teena Brandon, the
real-life person upon whom Swank's role is based. Brandon was
dissatisfied with her life as a girl and decided to live as a boy:
She bound her breasts, cropped her hair and switched her name
around, becoming Brandon Teena. With her happy lope of a walk, this
Brandon Teena is ripe for experience _ she comes across as nothing
so much as hungry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys Don't Cry'' displays a unique intimacy. Director Kimberly
Peirce makes the movie seem both intensely felt and modest in
scale, a story of a small-town kid with epic feelings. (It's
reminiscent of ``East of Eden.'') The women communicate in
unactorly ways; the camera often seems to be a voyeur in the girls'
locker room, which is exactly what Brandon is.
</P>
<P>
   Teena's openness is just what these small-town girls want;
they're tired of the drunken macho louts around them. Especially
Lana (Chloe Sevigny), who comes to life as she falls for Brandon _
she desperately wants an alternative to the bad-tempered John
(Peter Sarsgaard). But Brandon has a wild streak, too, if only
because she wants to experience life as a male.
</P>
<P>
   Those who know the story may be a little disappointed by the
simplification of Peirce, who co-wrote the film with Andy Bienen.
The Brandon Teena of ``Boys Don't Cry'' is an innocent, a sexual
martyr in a world she never made; the real story is a bit more
complicated. The real Brandon Teena was a predator who read
people's weaknesses and preyed upon them. She used the feminine
side of herself to gain the trust of the young women she dated and
used. It's a fascinating story, and the movie, while compelling,
strays far from its source. (The Brandon Teena documentary of a few
years ago is being repeated this month on Showtime.)
</P>
<P>
   But Peirce is angling for an emotional clarity, which she gets.
Brandon is as turned on by getting into costume and posing in front
of the mirror as a guy, as she is by women. Peirce is also after
emotional power _ the fear about what could happen if Brandon is
exposed in front of the angry John and his tag-along buddy (Brendan
Sexton III). We get a taste of it early on, when Brandon is run out
of her hometown after her imposture was revealed. And she was giddy
over it, pixilated by the tempest she stirred up. She relishes the
troublemaking aspect of being a man _ she gets into a fight and
rubs the bruised side of her face as if it were a brand new car and
she were examining the curves. ``Boys Don't Cry'' is the eruption
of a new star _ Swank _ and the debut of a major director. Peirce's
capacity for layering important psychological detail and building
to a climax shows intelligence and willfulness. I can't think of
another American director of the past few years who has exploded
onto the screen in this way, especially with such an honest
depiction of women. Even a woman who wants to be a man is still a
woman.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Boys Don't Cry''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Kimberly Peirce
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Hilary Swank, Chloe Sevigny
</P>
<P>
   Length: 114 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ adult language and sexuality, violence, nudity and a
rape scene
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
