<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4109 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-DEAD-TEX     10-21 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DEAD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICOLAS CAGE'S PALE-FACED PERFORMANCE HAUNTS SCORSESE FILM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Bringing Out The Dead,'' Nicolas Cage looks so exhausted,
even his eyes have a five o'clock shadow. He's Frank, a beaten-down
emergency medical technician, as desperate as many of the junkies
he treats. Except Frank gets high on saving lives, and when we meet
him he's chasing down this life-sustaining and transcendent buzz.
``Saving lives is like falling in love,'' he murmurs in the
narration that carries the film. Without the rush, he's the color
of parchment. Frank's haunted because in the sea of ghosts that
washes over the night streets, he sees the sullen baby face of a
girl he couldn't save. The few times he dozes off, she haunts his
dreams.
</P>
<P>
   This is director Martin Scorsese's return to the streets of New
York, and he gives ``Dead'' a sense of place that's unmistakably
Manhattan. (The streets are so slick from being hosed down, you'd
think they were trying to keep it from spontaneously bursting into
flame. Given Scorsese's intensity, that's not outside the realm of
possibility.) ``Dead'' was written by Paul Schrader, who gave us
``Taxi Driver'' 23 years ago, and it's a movie about hope, if not
optimism, although it's soaked with the traditional Scorsese thirst
for redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Frank drags himself through the movie in a numb haze _ he can't
sleep _ so the movie is jacked up for him, with a VH1 soundtrack to
suggest the synapses firing and misfiring in his head. It's also
the signature of Scorsese, perhaps the world's most exhibitionistic
director, who's working here with one of the most flamboyant of
cinematographers: Robert Richardson, who worked with Oliver Stone
on some of his best-known films, including ``Natural Born
Killers.'' When you add Cage (referred to by a fellow star as ``the
world's most over-the-top actor'') to the mix, it sounds like a
lethal cocktail. The images pop from the screen; often, people are
backlighted by street lamps or delineated in shadows. But Cage is a
weary blur, his eyes fried to a crackly crunch, so he doesn't get
to fall back on his quick, tantrum-y bleats.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is carried by its supporting actors. Solid-as-a-rock
(and big-as-a-boulder) John Goodman is the closest-to-normal
partner Frank has, and he's as goofy as a fruit bat. Ving Rhames,
sporting a perm of black patent leather, is a preacher, a fighter
and a lover given to comic rants right out of an old Robin Harris
routine (''If you see me with a white woman, I'm holding her for
the police.'') And Tom Sizemore's eyes gleam with malice. He lives
to fight, especially with a freaked-out wraith of a junkie played
by Marc Anthony. You know it's the eve of the millennium when Cage
is the straight man in a movie, as he is here and was in ``8mm.''
</P>
<P>
   Cage's Frank is like a biblical figure, attempting to fight a
plague on his home _ a type of heroin called Red Death. He's torn
about trying to keep alive the father of a woman he falls for
(Patricia Arquette), a man who cries out, in a voice only Frank can
hear, that he doesn't want to suffer anymore. He's a rather
heavy-handed manifestation of Frank's conscience, representing the
girl Frank couldn't help.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, it must be horrible to be Martin Scorsese, with
every film pounced upon by people waiting to judge it as a work of
art. ``Bringing Out the Dead'' doesn't labor to offer new insight
on the human condition. Not even from the screenwriter, who must've
been attracted to Joe Connelly's handsomely sculpted, grim dream of
a novel because it's close to areas Schrader's covered before.
Scorsese seems relieved to take a little pressure off himself. The
result is an enjoyable, if minor work, full of jokes: Scorsese is
the voice of a dispatcher, as is Queen Latifah; the wives of the
star (Arquette) and the writer (Marybeth Hurt, as a hectoring
admitting nurse) are in it; and a fireworks scene is a grisly
parody of ``Manhattan.'' With his perfunctory artistry, Scorsese
seems to be using this film to take a breath of fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Bringing Out the Dead''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Martin Scorsese
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Nicolas Cage, John Goodman, Patricia Arquette
</P>
<P>
   Length: 118 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ adult language, violence and drug use
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
