<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4113 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MAN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      10-21 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE BEST MAN': PARTY, BUT BE TRUE TO YOUR SWEETHEART 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end)) 
(jt) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the genial ensemble film ``The Best Man,'' Taye Diggs puts on
glasses to play a Chicago novelist whose book has been selected for
Oprah Winfrey's book club. He also appears in a candlelit bathtub
covered with rose petals, since the movie doesn't forget to get its
priorities straight. The main point about the novel written by
Harper Stewart (Diggs) is that it is called ``Unfinished
Business.'' Harper has some. It seems that he closely modeled one
character on an old flame named Jordan (Nia Long) who once kissed
Harper to the tune of a Stevie Wonder song when they were in
college. ``Jordan's the best girlfriend you never had,'' one of his
buddies remarks.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with minimal surprise that the film finds Jordan at a
New York wedding that Harper also attends. (See title.) The two
take a walk in Central Park, during which Jordan, now an ambitious
career woman, pronounces herself ``a horny nutbasket.'' Soon
afterward she lures Harper into a clinch, and the film emphasizes
the crucifix behind them. This is a reminder that back home,
probably cleaning the petals out of the tub, is Robin (Sanaa
Lathan), to whom he has promised to be true.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Malcolm D. Lee, ``The Best Man'' is another
demonstration that current movies about upscale black characters
have much more traditional values than ones about catty white
teen-agers. Marital fidelity is its main issue, since it involves
the imminent marriage of a once-philandering star athlete (Morris
Chestnut) to his longtime sweetheart (Monica Calhoun). Now that he
is ready to renounce his wild past (mention is made of ``those
honeys at the Cotton Bowl''), this guy likes boasting about his
fiancee's virtue. One of the film's minor messages is that it's
dangerous to marry a jealous football player.
</P>
<P>
   But its major message is an affirmation of marriage, fidelity
and religious faith, with an enjoyable group of the groom's friends
(Harold Perrineau, Terrence Howard) to hash over these issues.
Meanwhile, there is time for them to tease the literary Harper as
``Richard Wrong'' and ``Langston Snooze'' and, of course, to party.
The film's cure for many ills is celebrating and dancing. Despite
the story's underlying wholesomeness, it thus has an excuse to work
lap dancers into the plot.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   THE BEST MAN
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``The Best Man'' is rated R. It includes profanity, many
sexual references and cheerfully raunchy humor.
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Malcolm D. Lee; director of photography,
Frank Prinzi; edited by Cara Silverman; music by Stanley Clarke;
production designer, Kalina Ivanov; produced by Spike Lee, Sam Kitt
and Bill Carraro; released by Universal Pictures. Running time: 118
minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Taye Diggs (Harper), Nia Long (Jordan), Morris Chestnut
(Lance), Harold Perrineau (Murch), Terrence Howard (Quentin), Sanaa
Lathan (Robin), Monica Calhoun (Mia) and Melissa DeSousa (Shelby).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1532EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4118 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-VIETNAM-SPIRITUALITY-     10-21 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-SPIRITUALITY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW VIETNAM CHANGED THE FACE OF AMERICAN RELIGION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DIANA BUTLER BASS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   After tucking our toddler into bed one recent evening, my
exhausted husband commented, ``I remember what I was doing 30 years
ago tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Since I can barely remember what I was doing 30 minutes ago,
this caught my attention. ``What?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, 30 years last night, actually. October 15, 1969. I was
at a big protest of the Vietnam War in Washington. A month later,
another protest. After that, everything broke loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans remember 1969 for two events: Neil Armstrong walking
on the moon and Woodstock. But 1969 was also a crucible for the
antiwar movement.
</P>
<P>
   Although people had protested the war throughout the decade, by
1969 antiwar sentiment became increasingly difficult to ignore. The
largest cohort of baby-boomers turned eighteen; Richard Nixon had
just taken office. The clash between protesters and establishment
could no longer be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   The American experience of Vietnam is as varied as the memories
of those who lived through it. Politicians, soldiers, reporters,
parents, college students, schoolchildren. North and South; black
and white and brown; rich and poor. Whether or not one served in
Vietnam, we all fought the war together. It was waged on Asian
battlefields, American campuses and the evening news.
</P>
<P>
   And in church.
</P>
<P>
   Few events have transformed American religion as did the Vietnam
War. And few have been more difficult to analyze.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, the Yale historian Sydney Ahlstrom wrote of the times,
``The sharp crescendo of social strife seemed to demonstrate that
the time-honored structures of American church life were irrelevant
to the country's actual condition-- churchgoing America came to be
regardedas an obstacle to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in the 1970s, traditional religion seemed completely
outmoded, a relic of an earlier, more innocent age. God appeared
dead. One more casualty of the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, the late University of California professor Walter
Capps identified two major religious trends resulting from
Vietnam-- the ``revitalization of conservative religion'' and ``the
new spirituality.'' Pent-up patriotism fuelled a backlash against
the 60s radicalism and formed the basis for the religious right.
People went back to church. But they did not return to traditional
ones. Instead, they joined conservative churches in droves,places
that enshrined romanticized, pre-Vietnam views of family and
country.
</P>
<P>
   Capps described ``the new spirituality'' as ``the rise of
contemplative religion, the daily practice of meditationand even
the new and perceptibly strong interest in mysticism.'' This ``new
spirituality'' was more concerned with self than community-- ``an
appropriate response'' since traditional community had broken down.
</P>
<P>
   With older structures in chaos, a diffuse interest in
spirituality replaced institutional religion. God was not dead. God
had only changed his address.
</P>
<P>
   Both impulses were aspects of the American soul. One honored
tradition, the Bible, God and country; the other reflected
individualism, experimentation, ambiguity and questioning. These
differing religious interpretations of Vietnam led to a 20-year
cultural war-- ``a quarrel that has not yet been resolved'' at the
time Capps wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But we are 30 yearsand a generationaway from 1969. Despite
persistent bickering by some politicians and pundits, the quarrel
has been largely resolved. It was resolved by default and
demographics, by an aging baby-boom generation and the
coming-of-age of their own children, Generation X. For the most
part, these two groups have embraced some form of the ``new
spirituality.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, it looked as if the religious right's patriotic
``return to normalcy'' would prevail. It has not. Conservative
evangelicals have realized that they are a distinct minority-- a
large one but still a minoritywhose views do not resonate with
contemporary values and opinions on religion.
</P>
<P>
   Even the venerable evangelical magazine ``Christianity Today''
recently posed the question, ``Is the Religious Right Dead?''
</P>
<P>
   The ``new spirituality'' of the Vietnam era has become
mainstream. Contemplative, personal, mystical, eclectic. Some
traditional religious institutions -- Ahlstrom's ``irrelevant''
ones-- have adapted this ethos and have begun to experience new
growth. The baby-boomers, so shaped by the first wave of ``new
spirituality,'' now lead America's churches and synagogues. They
are quietly reforming the nature of the institutions they once
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   But much of American spirituality remains outside institutions.
The powerful impulses toward alternative religious expression and
mystical spirituality are consumer-oriented, Web-accessible, and
seeker-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   The pull is so strong, and the new consensus around these values
so real, that most younger Americans imbibe this spirit. The break
with the past, even among very conservative religious people, is
surprisingly complete.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years. A generation. Gone is traditional American
religion. We left it in the rice paddies of Vietnamor maybe on the
Mall in Washington one long-ago autumn.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1533EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4119 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-VIETNAM-SPIRITUALITY-     10-21 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-SPIRITUALITY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW VIETNAM CHANGED THE FACE OF AMERICAN RELIGION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DIANA BUTLER BASS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
