<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4127 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOLLY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     10-21 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOLLY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MOLLY': TAKING THE TEARS OUT OF A POTENTIALLY TEAR-JERKING PLOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a mentally retarded woman who, thanks to brain surgery,
briefly achieves a state bordering on normalcy, Elisabeth Shue
slowly unfurls through John Duigan's film ``Molly'' like a flower
reaching for the sun. But if Ms. Shue infuses ``Molly'' with a
flicker of joy, her sweetly likable performance is the only
coherent element in a film that has the impersonal feel of a
television drama slapped together in a rush.
</P>
<P>
   In its plot outline, ``Molly'' is so similar to ``Charly,'' the
1968 hit starring Cliff Robertson, that you wonder why no official
credit has been given to the earlier movie or to its source, Daniel
Keyes' novel ``Flowers for Algernon.'' Both films tell essentially
the same story of someone who, through modern medical science,
emerges from the shadows of a disability to experience a moment of
euphoric illumination before retreating back into the darkness. But
``Molly'' is so mechanically detached and emotionally void that a
potentially tear-jerking fable is rendered merely stupefying.
</P>
<P>
   When we first meet Molly, she is discharged from a nursing home
in the care of her brother, Buck (Aaron Eckhart), an advertising
copywriter and boating enthusiast who lives in Venice Beach. Molly
is a formidable handful: curious, clumsy, hyperemotional,
desperately needy and incapable of discharging the must mundane
tasks. One day, after Buck takes Molly to his office and instructs
her to wait in the reception area, she complains about the heat,
pulls off her clothes and barges naked into her brother's meeting.
Buck soon loses his job.
</P>
<P>
   Informed of a risky operation that could increase Molly's
intelligence, Buck persuades his sister to agree to the surgery. At
first the operation appears to have been unsuccessful. Then Molly
begins to show signs of a growing intelligence. Addicted to
television soap operas, she also becomes increasingly interested in
sex. After watching a video of ``Gone With the Wind,'' she
transforms herself into a ludicrous parody of Scarlett O'Hara and
throws herself wildly at Sam (Thomas Jane), her closest friend from
the clinic. As the two embark on a semi-grown-up love affair, Buck
and Susan Brookes, Molly's doctor (Jill Hennessy), also begin
playing footsie.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Ms. Shue (who is no match for Juliette Lewis in a
similar role in ``The Other Sister''), the movie's other
performances are so blank and chilly that the characters never come
to life. As Buck, Eckhart, who was so provocative in two Neil
LeBute films, is gawkily opaque, and Jane's Sam is barely more than
a prop. By the end of ``Molly'' you have the sinking sense that,
except for the star, this was a movie made by people glumly going
through the motions.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   MOLLY
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Molly'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly cautioned).
It has sexual situations and some strong language.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by John Duigan; written by Dick Christie; director of
photography, Gabriel Beristain; edited by Humphrey Dixon; music by
Trevor Jones; production designer, Sharon Seymour; produced by
William J. MacDonald; released by MGM. Running time: 103 minutEs.
This film is rated PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Elisabeth Shue (Molly McKay), Aaron Eckhart (Buck McKay),
Jill Hennessy (Susan Brookes), Thomas Jane (Sam), D.W. Moffett
(Mark Cottrell) and Elizabeth Mitchell (Beverly Trehare)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
