<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4134 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-BESTMAN-TEX     10-21 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BESTMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEST MAN' IS SON OF `BIG CHILL'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like one of those novels on the order of ``Milk in My Coffee,''
``The Best Man'' is a romantic comedy about the confusion that sex
can bring into friendships. Taye Diggs is attending a wedding for
which his best friends from college are convening. He's the best
man who's determined to get groom Morris Chestnut ``over the broom
if it kills me.'' And it just might, as novelist Diggs has written
a book that could potentially wreak havoc at the scene of football
superstar Chestnut's wedding. (Ironically, it was Diggs who brought
the bride and groom together.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Best Man'' is built around a piece of information that is
supposed to build suspense, but it's so obvious that it makes the
characters look silly for not having figured it out until the
weekend of the wedding. If you're willing to suspend disbelief for
the length of the picture, you'll have a good time. Writer-director
Malcolm Lee (cousin of Spike Lee, who is listed as a producer on
this film) isn't untalented; ``Best Man'' has a sweetness, and more
important, an earnestness that's powerfully touching with its
buppies-in-the-making. This movie is more subversive than
``American Beauty'' because this genre _ comedies about a thriving
black middle class _ is still so new to mainstream film. (And,
unfortunately, a comedy with a predominantly black cast is still
likely to scare off a mainstream _ white _ audience.)
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of his gleaming cool in ``Go'' _ where he was
so suave, it made no sense that he would hang out with the geeks he
was chasing girls with _ Diggs hasn't had much of a chance to
display the talent he showed onstage in ``Rent.'' (He does finally
get to dance a little bit here, though.) Because his role requires
him to look apprehensive all the time, Diggs looks stricken.
Mostly, he acts with his pecs, as does Morris Chestnut. (The rest
of Diggs' performance comes from the fact that, for one of the few
times in film history outside a Woody Allen movie, the glasses his
character wears are obviously necessary; you can see the
magnification in them.)
</P>
<P>
   But ``Best Man'' is worth seeing for one of the best
performances of the year, that of Terrence Howard. Howard is the
mack-tastic member of the crew whose hooded cynicism is a thing of
beauty; it's his world, and all we do is live in it. Howard's
introduction, as he nonchalantly blazes through a flamenco guitar
solo while keeping an eye on the honeys, almost turns the picture
on its ear. Fortunately, all his scenes are just as good. He's the
truth teller who turns out to have a soul after all. (Lee doesn't
sentimentalize Howard, either; he's still self-centered and vain at
the end.) And Melissa De Sousa, who plays the spoiled-rotten
blossom of a girlfriend to Harold Perrineau, is deliciously
manipulative. Any director who can deliver comic characters this
well-rendered has something going for him. Now, if Howard and De
Sousa were the center of ``The Best Man,'' it'd live up to Lee's
promise. Still, in the end, it offers a promise. No small thing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Best Man''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Malcolm D. Lee
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Taye Diggs, Nia Long, Morris Chestnut
</P>
<P>
   Length: 118 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ adult language and situations, and mild violence
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
