<HEADLINE>
GOOD GOLLY, THIS `MOLLY' IS A LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a review I don't entirely agree with, Pauline Kael described
Dustin Hoffman's Oscar-winning performance in ``Rain Man'' as
playing ``one note on a piano for two hours and 11 minutes.''
Elisabeth Shue finds more than one note in ``Molly,'' but they all
sound like nails being raked across a chalkboard. Shue's title
character starts the movie as a barely functional autistic, and the
actress takes this as her cue to overdo it: She mocks, she screams,
she even barks. When one of those miracle movie operations makes
Molly more functional and she has to do nearly 30 years of maturing
in a matter of days, Shue confuses her character's growing
self-confidence with smugness. And if you've seen ``Awakenings,''
you know what happens next. Aaron Eckhart, sporting a surfer-blond
'do, plays the estranged brother who bonds with the new, improved
Molly. Although it has some things to say about caretakers' woes
and the autistic's world, ``Molly'' mostly just plays like a
glorified TV movie. In fact, with its brief length _ which it
achieves by jumping from point A to point B so fast it seems as if
entire hunks were lopped out _ it'll fit in perfectly on the
Lifetime channel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Molly''
</P>
<P>
   Length: 85 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ nudity, profanity, sexually frank dialogue
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
