<SLUG> BC-SHOTS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BODY SHOTS': VENUS AND MARS COLLIDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the opening scenes of ``Body Shots,'' a groggy young man
rises from his date's bed, urinates on her closed toilet and mops
up the mess with her bathroom rug. Moments later, a distraught
young woman at the wheel of a car speeding through the night in a
blinding downpour skids to a spinning stop, shoves open the door
and vomits onto the rain-swept road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Body Shots'' is not the sort of movie to leave much to the
imagination, and when a passing remark about a class on oral sex is
buttressed by images of a group of women seated on a floor around a
table whose centerpiece is a model of a penis, the conclusion is
inescapable that the film's pretensions to significance are doomed
by its graphic style.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad, because in broad outline ``Body Shots'' seems eager to
grapple with questions like the difficulty of dating in the 1990s,
men versus women, sex, the definition of love and date rape.
</P>
<P>
   But the film, written by David McKenna and directed by Michael
Cristofer, who won the 1977 Pulitzer Prize for drama for his play
``The Shadow Box,'' is more focused on surface than true
revelation.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the eight principals _ four men and four women in
their 20s who sometimes address the camera _ speak frankly about
sex and their views of the opposite sex, but seeming more like
types than true individuals, they prove to be a lightweight lot.
</P>
<P>
   An allegation of date rape frames the story of ``Body Shots,''
and had the film focused steadfastly rather than briefly on its
impact on the eight principals and the workings of the law, the
exercise might have been more fruitful. But insistent on repeated
showings of the foreplay and coupling from the viewpoints of the
man and woman involved, ``Body Shots'' reveals itself to be neither
``Rashomon'' nor serious sociology.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the film takes place in the form of a flashback to the
night preceding the morning when the disheveled, bleeding Sara
(Tara Reid), an actress, turns up at the apartment of her friend
Jane (Amanda Peet) to tell her that she was raped by Mike (Jerry
O'Connell), a cave man in the guise of a hulking professional
football player.
</P>
<P>
   Jane, a clerk in the district attorney's office, sends away Rick
(Sean Patrick Flanery), the lawyer who woke up on her bed, and the
film proceeds to show its characters in the hours before the
disputed event.The four male friends, roommates and acquaintances,
include not only Rick and the belligerent Mike but also Shawn (Brad
Rowe), who is sweet on Sara; and Trent (Ron Livingston), who runs
pornography on his office computer and boasts that he works hard
and likes to play hard.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Jane and Sara, the women include the quiet Emma (Sybil
Temchen) and the cool, blond Whitney (Emily Procter), who works at
the frenetic dance club where, well fueled by alcohol, they have
all arranged to meet.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the film's emphasis on style, the cast is
attractive and talented, but some dramas call for more than meets
the eye.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   BODY SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Body Shots'' is rated R (under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes sexual
situations, nudity and uninhibited language.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Michael Cristofer; written by David McKenna;
director of photography, Rodrigo Garcia; edited by Eric Sears;
production designer, David J. Bomba; produced by Jennifer Keohane
and Harry Colomby; released by New Line Cinema. Running time: 115
minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Sean Patrick Flanery (Rick Hamilton), Jerry O'Connell
(Michael Penorisi), Amanda Peet (Jane Bannister), Tara Reid (Sara
Olswang), Ron Livingston (Trent), Emily Procter (Whitney Bryant),
Brad Rowe (Shawn Denigan) and Sybil Temchen (Emma Cooper).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
