u e BC-THREE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     10-21 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THREE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THREE TO TANGO': HE'S NOT GAY, BUT PRETENDS TO BE. CHAOS ENSUES. 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Three to Tango,'' a leering screwball sex comedy set in
contemporary Chicago, is like an overly boisterous party guest who
is so nervous meeting strangers that he compulsively spews out
bawdy jokes in a loud, belligerent voice.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the movie has plenty of reason to be nervous.
For the tolerance toward homosexuality exhibited by the story of
Oscar Novak (Matthew Perry), an avidly heterosexual architect who,
for business reasons, is coerced into pretending he's gay, often
feels strained and shallow.
</P>
<P>
   This allegedly liberated comedy has some nasty undercurrents
that lend it a slightly sour taste. For the duration of his
charade, Oscar goes around in a state of barely controlled panic.
He finds it almost unendurable to be thought gay.
</P>
<P>
   After reading a newspaper article in which he comes out of the
closet, Oscar's parents go ballistic and his closest straight pals
shrink from him, even after he swears that he's really straight. In
the movie's portrayal of relations between gay men and straight
women, a group of women treat Oscar as a fellow ``girlfriend'' who
has had to put up with the same kinds of harassment and lame sexual
pitches they have.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it is funny up to a point, in a crude barroomy sort of way.
And had someone other than Perry, a bluff, competent actor of
decidedly limited charm, played Oscar, the movie's tone might have
seemed a bit less overbearing.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar's troubles begin when he and his gay architectural
partner, Peter Steinberg (Oliver Platt), compete with another team
to design a $90 million cultural center. The billionaire
entrepreneur underwriting the project is a lean, gimlet-eyed
lothario, Charles Newman (Dylan McDermott), who is married but
having an affair with Amy Post (Neve Campbell), a glass sculptor.
</P>
<P>
   On being deliberately misinformed by the rival team that Oliver
is gay, Charles, deciding that Oliver would be ``safe'' companion
for his girlfriend, pressures him to spy on Amy at her gallery
opening to make sure she isn't flirting with her former boyfriend,
Kevin Cartwright (Cylk Cozart), a professional football player and
legendary stud.
</P>
<P>
   The evening evolves into a madcap adventure in which Oliver
saves one of Amy's glass works from destruction and the pair suffer
various mishaps including eating tainted tuna melts, which leaves
them vomiting side by side on the street. (What a way to bond!)
</P>
<P>
   Although Oliver is instantly smitten with Amy, whom Ms. Campbell
portrays with a breezy free-spirited bounce, he has to conceal his
true feelings. Eventually Oliver, having been chosen man of the
year by a gay professional organization, finds himself compelled to
give a televised acceptance speech and at long last rebels.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Three to Tango,'' as in the amiably nonsensical ``Happy,
Texas,'' you can feel Hollywood suffering from the box office
jitters as it strains to be cool about a touchy subject. The movie
has a lot in common with the recent (and more likable) ``Happy,
Texas,'' which gave us two straight men feigning gayness and an
ostensibly straight town sheriff (sweetly played by William H.
Macy) who turns out to a doe-eyed gay man pining for one of the
impostors.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Three to Tango'' the equivalent of the sheriff is the
football player, who has only recently discovered he's gay and
comes on strong to Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   Once it gets its ducks in a row, ``Three to Tango,'' directed by
Damon Santostefano, follows a totally predictable path. In trying
to be both bold and nonthreatening, the movie ends up seeming tame
and mildly offensive.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `Three to Tango' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly cautioned). It
has sexual situations and many off-color jokes.
</P>
<P>
   `THREE TO TANGO'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Damon Santostefano; written by Rodney Vaccaro and
Aline Brosh McKenna, based on a story by Vaccaro; director of
photography, Walt Lloyd; edited by Stephen Semel; music by Graeme
Revell; production designer, David Nichols; produced by Bobby
Newmyer, Jeffrey Silver and Bettina Sofia Viviano; released by
Warner Brothers. Running time: 115 minutes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Matthew Perry (Oscar Novak), Neve Campbell (Amy Post),
Dylan McDermott (Charles Newman), Oliver Platt (Peter Steinberg)
and Cylk Cozart (Kevin Cartwright).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1550EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4141 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     10-21 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UBERPRODUCERS ARE MONOPOLIZING THE TUBE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It takes either a lot of talent or a lot of nerve to make a TV
series that's essentially a sharply edited rerun of your first
series and expect people to actually sit still and tune in. David
E. Kelley, he with the golden touch, has done it and, surprise,
people aren't buying it.
</P>
<P>
   Ally doesn't command ``Ally McBeal's'' audience loyalty, even
though 8 million people watched the half-hour series when it
debuted, and 6 million or so are apparently hanging around waiting
for it to get better.
</P>
<P>
   That's 4 million fewer than those tuning in to ``Snoops,''
Kelley's new series about wacky private eyes airing Sundays on ABC;
11 million fewer than those putting aside Sunday nights for
Kelley's prickly law drama ``The Practice''; and 5 million fewer
than those catching ``Chicago Hope,'' the medical drama Kelley
created in 1994, abandoned in 1996, and has returned to for a
last-ditch exorcism.
</P>
<P>
   Don't bother counting. That's five shows on three networks, most
of them with Kelley as sole writer, head writer, rewrite guy or
script supervisor who, if the Kelley myth is to be believed, has
quite the heavy hand.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the movie scripts. Two this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   All that and Emmys, too.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder it's become fashionable to take a shot at the guy, to
say he's spreading himself way too thin, or even charge him with
forgetting that quality more than quantity fueled his early,
blemish-free reputation.
</P>
<P>
   But try as you might to be fair, to let the bandwagon whiz on
by, it's obvious that although Monday's season premiere of ``Ally
McBeal'' looks awfully strong, ``Snoops'' and the new ``Chicago
Hope'' look equally lifeless. And ``The Practice'' so far this
season is Kelley-lite, which begs the question of whether he's
merely spinning his wheels.
</P>
<P>
   When discussing the topic of producers who have taken on more
than they can handle, retreading is the chief symptom. The well is
only so deep, they say, and it's just a matter of time before all
their work starts showing dangerous signs of sameness. See Steven
Bochco.
</P>
<P>
   But producers continue to spin off other shows anyway, partly
for the money, partly for the power, partly for the creative
release, partly because they can.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Spelling and Norman Lear always had their hands in a
number of cookie jars during the '70s (Spelling still does), but
television these days is looking a lot like corporate America,
where everything is being concentrated in the hands of a very few.
</P>
<P>
   This season alone, ``ER'' creator John Wells has ``Third Watch''
and ``West Wing,'' Chris Thompson is producing ``Action'' and
``Ladies Man,'' and Joss Whedon created ``Angel'' to follow ``Buffy
the Vampire Slayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Amy Lippman and Chris Keyser will add ``Time of Your
Life'' to ``Party of Five,'' Joel Silver has both ``The Strip'' and
``Action,'' and Dick Wolf has cloned his ``Law &AMP; Order'' franchise.
Yvette Lee Bowser, executive producer for The WB's ``For Your
Love,'' is developing series for NBC and The WB.
</P>
<P>
   Only Aaron Sorkin, however, truly comes close to rivaling Kelley
as a madman/writer, handling duties on ``Sports Night'' and ``West
Wing'' single-handedly.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Farquhar is one producer who doesn't get the
spread-your-talent theory. He left the coming-of-age comedy
``Moesha'' this season to co-create and produce the new UPN series
``The Parkers.'' ``I'm a writer, too,'' says Farquhar, who also
penned ``South Central.'' ``And I don't know how (Kelley) does it.
But then, I don't know if I want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of these uberproducers do it by hiring ``show runners,''
who look over the daily details while they shuttle from one show to
another. But do any of these shows have the full attention and full
expertise of their creator? And are audiences paying the price for
that?
</P>
<P>
   Kelley may be considered the point man for this trend, but I
blame the invasion of feature film writers who, after being bullied
on the film set, see TV as a wide-open playground.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Williamson wrote ``Scream'' before bringing ``Dawson's
Creek'' and ``Wasteland'' to TV. Sorkin penned ``The American
President,'' ``A Few Good Men'' and others, and Silver is the man
behind ``Lethal Weapon'' and ``Die Hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Whedon, whose film writing credits include ``Speed,''
``Twister'' and ``Toy Story,'' for which he received an Oscar
nomination, talks often about the rush of seeing what he puts down
on paper come out of Sarah Michelle Gellar's mouth on ``Buffy.''
</P>
<P>
   What a stark change, he notes, from the hierarchy in film, where
a director is in charge and the writer is a nonentity. (He also
wrote the 1992 ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' film, but says he hated
the results.)
</P>
<P>
   As for leaving ``Buffy'' with less than his best, Whedon says he
won't, describing the series as ``a drug'' he can't kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it an impossible workload?'' Whedon says of working on both
shows. ``Yes, it is. Will I have a nervous breakdown? Yes, I will.
But will `Buffy' fans get shortchanged? No, they won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Williamson, busy writing the recent film ``Teaching Mrs.
Tingle'' and launching ``Wasteland,'' pulled out of ``Dawson's
Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You shortchange your audience because you don't have the time
to think about the characters. You're just hitting a deadline,''
Williamson says. ``I never want to be in that spot creatively.''
</P>
<P>
   I thought about this whole issue while watching ``Snoops'' the
other night when Jane Krakowski was brought on as a guest, playing
her ``Ally McBeal'' character Elaine.
</P>
<P>
   I'll spare you the details and only say that it didn't work,
and, in fact, turned out to be choppy and forced.
</P>
<P>
   A Kelley show choppy and forced. Now that's one we haven't
heard.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1550EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4142 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BATS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      10-21 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BATS': YOU'LL WISH THEY WERE JUST IN THE BELFRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the beginning were the biblical plagues. In the fullness of
time, they begat cinema's plagues of ants, bees, spiders, birds and
various viruses.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes ``Bats.''
</P>
<P>
   A pox on it.
</P>
<P>
   Masquerading as a Halloween season horror film, this noisy
version of a washed-out formula is cause for fright in only one
respect: the possibility that it could spawn sequels.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly an excuse for igniting flames, cooking cars, shattering
windows and launching fireworks of sparks while littering the
rather pretty Western landscape with corpses, ``Bats'' manages to
overlook suspense and terror.
</P>
<P>
   Among its characters, only Lou Diamond Phillips as Emmett
Kimsey, a small-town Texas sheriff, manages to suggest a human
drawn from life rather than a rash of old movies. And Dina Meyer,
as the wildlife zoologist and bat specialist called in when the
local toll of mysterious deaths begins to mount, succeeds in
investing the role of Dr. Sheila Casper with energy and wit.
</P>
<P>
   But Leon as Jimmy Sands, her assistant, is the only mammal in
the movie capable of making the audience squirm. Under the
direction of Louis Morneau, working from a screenplay by John
Logan, the bat-fearing Jimmy is saddled with lame lines struggling
to rise to the status of jokes and kick-me-in-the-script moments,
including the one where he shouts that the plague of bats ``is not
funny.'' Here it sometimes is, which is not the film's intention.
</P>
<P>
   To Bob Gunton as Dr. Alexander McCabe falls the role of evil
scientist responsible for the deadly bat attacks in Gallup, Texas
(pop. 7,000), where F.W. Murnau's 1927 vampire movie,
``Nosferatu,'' just happens to be playing in the local theater. And
as ``Bats'' progresses, Dr. McCabe's sidelong glances and
remoteness give way to the familiar loony tics, sabotage and
megalomaniacal declarations that customarily end in what Winston
Churchill liked to call condign punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was batty Dr. McCabe, a slavish believer in science as
the path to betterment, who mutated a couple of bats that escaped
from his lab and are now busily turning their generally fruit- and
bug-eating gentle ilk into aggressive omnivores with enhanced
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   So after a teen-age couple meet a bloody death right at the
start of a make-out session on a lonely road one night, Dr. Casper
is summoned by the Centers for Disease Control to have a look at
the corpses, while Dr. McCabe stands by.
</P>
<P>
   She quickly realizes what the problem is, but the townspeople
fail to heed a warning to evacuate, and soon the plague (two real
bats and the others animatronic and computer-generated) is upon
them.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy, a computer wiz, shows one and all that it is only a
matter of time before North America is overrun by beastly bats but
that, of course, there is a chance to nip the onslaught in the
roost. That is, if the meddling government agent behind Dr.
McCabe's project and the military don't blow up the abandoned mine
where the bats are snoozing and scatter them to the winds.
</P>
<P>
   As the heroes plods through guano to a predictable finish, the
pulse remains steadfastly unaccelerated.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `BATS'
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Bats'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly cautioned). It
includes gruesome deaths and coarse language.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Louis Morneau; written by John Logan; director of
photography, George Mooradian; edited by Glenn Garland; music by
Graeme Revell; production designer, Philip J.C. Duffin; produced by
Brad Jenkel and Louise Rosner; released by Destination Films.
Running time: 91 minutes. This film is rated PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Lou Diamond Phillips (Emmett Kimsey), Dina Meyer (Dr.
Sheila Casper), Leon (Jimmy Sands), Carlos Jacott (Dr. Tobe Hodge)
and Bob Gunton (Dr. Alexander McCabe).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
