<HEADLINE>
LYNCH'S LATEST PLAYS IT `STRAIGHT' AGAINST THE GRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Lynch is one of the few successful American filmmakers who
seems to have made little or no concession to commercial
considerations throughout his career. Consistently, he makes
whatever film interests him at the time.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, at this low point in his career _ after the flops
of ``Twin Peaks: Fire Walk With Me'' and ``Lost Highway'' _ the
wise thing for him to do would be to chase a hit, either with a
star vehicle or with a film full of Lynchian elements that have
worked for him in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he's given us ``The Straight Story,'' a low-key,
low-budget, G-rated inspirational film for the Disney company about
an old man on a journey. I loved it, but it's exactly the kind of
underwhelming movie that seems guaranteed to get lost in the
multiplexes.
</P>
<P>
   It's the based-on-a-true-story of a 73-year-old Iowa man named
Alvin Straight (Richard Farnsworth) who decides to visit his
estranged brother (Harry Dean Stanton) in Wisconsin after learning
his brother has suffered a debilitating stroke.
</P>
<P>
   But Alvin's own health is badly deteriorating, he's nearly
blind, and he has no driver's license. So the only way he can make
the trip is on his 1966-vintage John Deere lawn tractor _ puttering
along the highway at less than 10 mph.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of his six-week journey, he has a few mechanical
problems and a few harrowing adventures, and he meets some
interesting and mostly friendly people who seem eager to help him.
But he remains determined to ``finish the trip the way I started
it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an enjoyably eccentric but thin story that might have been
easily handled in an afternoon TV special for kids. And Lynch's
approach is so understated _ avoiding the obvious emotional and
inspirational scenes _ that it often seems to vanish before our
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it has its own lazy charm and some unforgettable moments,
as when Straight exchanges horrific war stories with another old
veteran. And it has some subtle bite: Its G-rating and upbeat
ending nothwithstanding, the movie is a somber meditation on the
helplessness of old age.
</P>
<P>
   The film also has an Oscar-worthy performance from 78-year-old
Farnsworth, the veteran Hollywood stunt man who turned into a
venerable character lead (``The Grey Fox,'' ``Comes a Horseman'')
well after age 60 but has recently been in semi-retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Without trying very hard, Farnsworth commands a unique and
immensely appealing screen presence that could be called ``a
compilation of all the great western heroes of the movie past.'' He
gives the character and his quest an honesty and dignity both
inspiring and heartbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   The Straight Story. Directed by David Lynch. Written by John
Roach and Mary Sweeny. Cast: Richard Farnsworth, Sissy Spacek,
Harry Dean Stanton. Walt Disney Pictures. 111 minutes. Rated G,
suitable for all audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
