<SLUG> BC-FILM-TANGO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TANGO' TWISTS TO AN ALL-TOO-PREDICTABLE PLOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where have we seen this movie before? From ``Some Like It Hot''
to ``Tootsie,'' from ``The Associate'' to ``Happy, Texas,'' film
characters have long pretended to be something they're not in order
to achieve a goal: love of a woman, a big job _ or both.
</P>
<P>
   The films' current trend, which features heterosexual characters
playing gay, is certainly no different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three to Tango'' stars TV actors Matthew Perry (``Friends''),
Neve Campbell (``Party of Five'') and Dylan McDermott (``The
Practice'') also charading as big-screen movie-star material. Perry
(``Fools Rush In'') has had sketchy luck beyond the small screen;
Campbell and McDermott have had hit movies _ ``Scream'' and ``Steel
Magnolias,'' respectively _ but also have suffered box office
blues.
</P>
<P>
   Their current outing is a tepid if moderately likable romantic
comedy, but it's highly unlikely to be a conduit to movie-star
status. Still, it has some charm; Perry seems looser and more
relaxed than usual even though he's playing a role similar to that
of Chandler on ``Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Novak (Perry) is, along with his gay associate Peter
Steinberg (Oliver Platt), a talented architect. The pair are up for
bid on a $90million renovation job sanctioned by billionaire
Charles Newman (McDermott). But their opposition, Strauss (John C.
McGinley) and Decker (Bob Balaban), aren't going to play fair. When
a moment of support between Oscar and Peter is overheard by
Newman's assistant, Lenore (Deborah Rush), the duo are taken to be
romantic as well as business partners, a status Strauss
</P>
<P>
   and Decker heartily confirm.
</P>
<P>
   Newman pits the teams against each other and asks the
motor-mouthed Oscar for a favor as well. The jealous, suspicious
businessman keeps an independent, arty mistress, Amy Post
(Campbell), and wants Oscar, being gay and no threat, to keep an
eye on her moves at an art gallery opening. Of course, Oscar, who
is really quite a ladies man, falls head over heels.
</P>
<P>
   The vapid plotline follows the same narrative arc as ``Tootsie''
but hasn't the heart or purpose of that film, most because its
script tries to stay trendy by tossing in offbeat humor out of
``There's Something About Mary.'' It's ultimately just a mish-mash
of movie moments without any fresh invention.
</P>
<P>
   Three to Tango. Directed by Damon Santostefano. Written by
Rodney Vaccaro and Aline Brosh McKenna. Cast: Matthew Perry, Neve
Campbell, Dylan McDermott. Warner Bros. 98 minutes. Rated PG-13 for
language, sexual themes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1612EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
