<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-1600(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT `NOISE' YOUR KIDS ARE LISTENING TO IS HEAVY METAL AND HIP-HOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parents have always listened to their kids' rock 'n' roll and
wondered, ``What is that noise?''
</P>
<P>
   It's been true since the '50s, it was true in the '70s _ with
the advent of metal acts such as Black Sabbath and Led Zeppelin _
and it's certainly been true in the '80s and '90s, as hip-hop and
grunge established themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For kids, that's at least half the fun _ giving Dad and Mom the
willies because what you're listening to doesn't sound like what
they used to listen to, be it Elvis or Ted Nugent or Public Enemy
or Nirvana.
</P>
<P>
   Well, parents, it's happening again: 1999 has seen
heavy-metal-hip-hop make a huge surge in popularity via acts such
as Limp Bizkit and Kid Rock and the continuing arena-filling
popularity of Korn.
</P>
<P>
   All three acts have taken their stylistic cues from such
established groups as 311 and the politically charged Rage Against
the Machine and have sold millions of copies of their latest CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Rock's ``Devil Without a Cause'' and the Bizkit's ``Significant
Other'' have sold more than 3 million copies each.
</P>
<P>
   The kids are listening. But to what?
</P>
<P>
   From a distance _ say, the other side of your son's bedroom door
_ the mingling of metal and hip-hop (dubbed ``rip-hop'' by some)
might just sound like loud, aggressive hard rock has always
sounded: loud and aggressive, with lots of guitars and some angry
young guy hollering.
</P>
<P>
   But the current crop of young rip-hop acts is funneling the
grinding/thrashing guitars (and us-against-them attitude) of
Metallica and mixing it up with beats and emphatic raps that recall
any number of hip-hop acts, such as Ice Cube, Run-D.M.C., Public
Enemy, Dr. Dre, Tupac and Snoop Doggy Dogg.
</P>
<P>
   Metal and hip-hop always belonged together: Both emphasize hard,
insistent beats, male braggadocio, hard living, bucking the system,
having plenty of female companionship and generally making one's
way on one's own terms. The two have been fused for more than a
decade, since the Beastie Boys debuted in 1986 with the ``Licensed
to Ill'' LP and its attendant hit single, ``(You Gotta) Fight for
Your Right (to Party).''
</P>
<P>
   But with other forms of hard rock (industrial, grunge) having
long ago peaked commercially, thousands of young music fans from
all demographics have latched onto rip-hop as a way to reject
mainstream society, act tough and assert their independence _ and
their allegiance to urban music and the high-living inner-city
gangstas they would so love to be.
</P>
<P>
   Confused yet? Don't be.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned? Maybe you should be.
</P>
<P>
   Below is a parent-friendly guide to rip-hop's major acts _
including which are nasty as they wanna be and which are
(relatively) nice.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Limp Bizkit
</P>
<P>
   Home: Jacksonville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Latest CD: ``Significant Other''
</P>
<P>
   Notable stuff: Currently the biggest rip-hop act in the country,
this is the band that encouraged Woodstock attendees to ``smash
stuff'' right before the fires began to burn. Perform with a giant
toilet onstage. Lead singer Fred Durst was recently made an
executive at the band's label, Interscope. Their big hit this
summer was ``Nookie,'' which is about exactly what you think it's
about.
</P>
<P>
   Sound: Led Zeppelin meets Ice Cube, as performed by a bunch of
white kids who like girls, making money, more girls, and destroying
stuff because they're having a bad day. Really. They wrote a song
about this.
</P>
<P>
   Nasty scale: 7 out of 10. They like the ladies (including adult
film actresses), but since their audience is 14-year-old guys who
have never seen a naked woman anywhere but on the Internet, they're
more funny than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Kid Rock
</P>
<P>
   Home: The mean suburbs of Detroit _ did anyone say ``Vanilla
Ice''?
</P>
<P>
   Latest CD: ``Devil Without a Cause''
</P>
<P>
   Notable stuff: This is the shirtless guy with lank blond hair
you saw kickin' it with Run-D.M.C. and Aerosmith on the latest MTV
awards show. He brags of once having been a small-time crack dealer
and of his years in the hip-hop wilderness. He's the
self-proclaimed spokesdude for all the rap-loving white boys out
there. ``You're straight outta Compton? I'm straight outta the
trailer!'' he raps on ``Cowboy,'' one of several hits on ``Devil.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound: Some big, greasy guitars, plenty of hip-hop beats,
country touches and that good ol' Detroit attitude. He's making
money left and right and meeting lots of young ladies, and he'll be
more than happy to tell you about it.
</P>
<P>
   Nasty scale: 8 out of 10. The Kid's all about the women.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   311
</P>
<P>
   Home: Nebraska. No snickering in the back, you.
</P>
<P>
   Latest CD: ``Sound System,'' which came out last week
</P>
<P>
   Notable stuff: Nice guys, apparently, who were merging rock and
rap before anyone had ever heard of Fred and the Kid. Tour like
mad. Had two big hits, ``Down'' and ``All Mixed Up,'' in 1996.
Photogenic, hard-working, sincere _ and their new CD comes along at
the perfect time for them to capitalize on the craze.
</P>
<P>
   Sound: Musically, these guys may well be the most astute band of
the whole bunch. Rap merges with enormo guitar, but there are also
smartly placed nods to reggae, R&AMP;B and funk.
</P>
<P>
   Nasty scale: Basically zero. 311 songs are about spiritual
topics, the joy of music, dealing with the modern world and so on.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Korn
</P>
<P>
   Home: Bakersfield, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Latest CD: ``Follow the Leader''
</P>
<P>
   Notable stuff: Massively popular depressed-rock for the masses _
it's almost a requirement that every suburban high-school kid wear
a Korn T-shirt these days. Lead singer Jonathan Davis gave up a
career as a mortician to concentrate on music _ and sounds like it.
</P>
<P>
   Sound: Cathartic world-of-gloom despair with grinding, fuzzy
guitars _ and, ye sons of Scotland, Davis occasionally bleating
away on the bagpipes! Korn songs deal with homophobia, abuse,
incest and other unpleasantness, with Davis screaming out his
unhappiness to a sea of fist-punching fans.
</P>
<P>
   Nasty scale: One out of 10, maybe. These guys deal with adult
topics, but bragging about all the babes they've bagged isn't one
of them.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Rage Against the Machine
</P>
<P>
   Home: Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Latest CD: The band will release its third CD, ``The Battle of
Los Angeles,'' on Nov. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Notable stuff: The most politically charged and potent rip-hop
band out there _ by a wide margin. Lead singer Zack de la Rocha is
a disciple of Che Guevera and Allen Ginsberg (he used to recite the
latter's poetry on stage).
</P>
<P>
   Sound: Incendiary and thunderous _ musically and lyrically. For
example, the band has done songs about the evils of cultural
imperialism and racism and in support of the rights of Native
Americans. Guitarist Tom Morello is very inventive, and de la Rocha
(a small guy who always looks as though he's about to explode with
fury) is one of the most compelling vocalists currently performing.
</P>
<P>
   Nasty scale: Almost minus.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Pimpadelic
</P>
<P>
   From: Fort Worth, Texas
</P>
<P>
   Latest CD: The new ``Southern Devils''
</P>
<P>
   Notable stuff: Pimpadelic has become one of the Metroplex's most
popular live acts in the past year or so; their shows are notable
for the number of young women who get onstage and take off their
shirts. ``Southern Devils'' was recently picked up for distribution
by major hip-hop label Tommy Boy _ these guys are going to be very,
very popular indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Sound: Raging guitars, raging hormones _ and old-school
turntable scratches, overlaying songs about hard, hard partying.
Lead singer Dirty K brags, at various points, of being ``white
trash,'' selling records, having mucho sex, doing a lot of drugs,
and living a life of almost total hedonism. And somehow, I believe
him.
</P>
<P>
   Nasty scale: Full-on 10. They want your daughter and they want
her right now _ and not for dinner and a movie, either.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman covers pop music for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
