<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4157 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     10-21 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEORY OF THINKING: AUTHOR REVISES, UPDATES POPULAR SIX HATS
METHOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Greeks were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Long ago, Aristotle, Socrates and Plato decided that arguing was
the best method of thinking, and that the more critical you could
be, the better.
</P>
<P>
   Westerners adopted their ideas as if they were written in stone
and have been arguing in conference rooms, offices and factory
floors ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Many reasoning methods have been conceived, but few have such a
documented track record as the one developed by conceptual thinker
Edward De Bono: the Six Thinking Hats.
</P>
<P>
   Before you dismiss this as some sequel by Dr. Suess, consider
what companies around the globe have accomplished since the Six
Thinking Hats method was first described in De Bono's book 14 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   IBM says the method has reduced its meeting times by 75 percent.
Siemens, which with nearly 400,000 employees is the largest
corporation in Europe, has 37 internal trainers using the method
and every department has an innovation unit using the six hats.
</P>
<P>
   NASA, DuPont, Shell, British Petroleum and Federal Express are
just some of the many companies that have incorporated this simple
thinking change designed by De Bono, a Rhodes scholar who has
degrees in medicine and psychology.
</P>
<P>
   Now out is a revised and updated version of his internationally
best-selling book ``Six Thinking Hats'' (Little, Brown and Co., 173
pages, $14.95). It joins a cadre of other bestsellers, including
``Lateral Thinking'' and ``Teach Your Child How to Think.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Six Thinking Hats'' is remarkably simple to read, given that
it deals with changing the way humans think. Although De Bono has
included recent evidence of how the concept is working in various
companies, he does not bog the book down with too many examples.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he offers a fresh look at a fascinating theory that he
says is being used on everyone from preschoolers to executive
managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, there is a huge amount of experience using the Six Hats
method,'' De Bono writes. ``It is no longer a matter of trying out
something new and exotic. It is now a matter of catching up with a
powerful thinking method that has been in use for fourteen years
across all ages, cultures and abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   With meetings taking up 40 percent of U.S. manager's time on
average, this nonconfrontational, most systematic method of
thinking can decrease that time by up to 75 percent, De Bono has
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Six Hats method is used, the advantages soon become
clear,'' he writes. ``Instead of rambling, ego-driven meetings,
meetings are more constructive, productive and much faster. ...
Thinking becomes a game with defined rules, rather than a matter of
exhortation and condemnation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Six Hats'' clarifies thinking by compartmentalizing it.
Each hat is a different color that represents a different way of
thinking. A white hat is concerned with objective facts and
figures, a red hat gives the emotional view, a black hat points out
weaknesses in an idea, a yellow hat covers positive thinking, green
represents creativity and new ideas and blue organizes the thinking
process and use of the other hats.
</P>
<P>
   People in the meeting are asked to think of wearing each hat at
a specific time, preferably for just a minute, to bring out all the
different aspects of a problem or idea. The result is a myriad of
information, data, feelings and moods, all brought out in a
controlled setting in a ``neutral and objective exploration,'' De
Bono writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confusion is the biggest enemy of good thinking,'' he writes.
``We try to do too many things at the same time. We look for
information. We are affected by feelings. We seek new ideas and
options. We have to be cautious. We want to find benefits. ...
Juggling with six balls at the same time is rather difficult.
Tossing up one ball at a time is much easier.''
</P>
<P>
   De Bono writes individual chapters defining each hat, as well as
the method of using the hats effectively in meetings. His writing
is so clear, you can easily finish the book and feel well-versed in
the theory in not much over an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Implementing the concept is also easy, although it may take a
bit for the different types of personalities to try it out, De Bono
writes.
</P>
<P>
   But merging those types of personalities into a thinking machine
is ultimately what the book is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``By going straight to behavior, the Six Hats method is much
more acceptable and effective and quick than methods that set out
to change personalities,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing you have to lose from trying such a theory is
time.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``What's Your Exit Strategy? 7 Ways to Maximize the Value of the
Business You've Built''
</P>
<P>
   By Peter H. Engel
</P>
<P>
   Prima Publishing, $25
</P>
<P>
   Every business will someday be closed or sold, and every
business decision should be based on the way the owner plans to
leave the business, according to entrepreneur Peter Engel. In other
words, ``just because you build a successful business doesn't mean
that you can become rich from it,'' he writes. The book covers
selling a business to a strategic buyer, selling to a financial
buyer, going public, selling to heirs or employees, liquidating,
enforced liquidation and managing for life, as well as other
related topics.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Million Dollar Selling Techniques''
</P>
<P>
   By The Million Dollar Round Table Center for Productivity
</P>
<P>
   John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $16.95
</P>
<P>
   Before you wonder further about this strange author, let me
explain that the Million Dollar Round Table is an international
association made up of the top 6 percent of life insurance
producers in the world. This group of 19,000 from 400 companies
obviously knows how to sell. Cold callings, listening, selling to
different types _ all of the basics of selling are covered clearly
in this well-crafted book.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare on Management''
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Corrigan
</P>
<P>
   Kogan Page, $22.95
</P>
<P>
   With management books pulling quotes from Moses to Attila the
Hun, it seems only natural that Shakespeare would eventually
appear. Of course, his writings are filled with household business
phrases _ ``Neither a borrower nor a lender be'' _ and so on, but
this book goes quite a bit further in taking major Shakespearean
characters and what they say and pointing to the business world. A
good gift for those in love with Shakespeare. Otherwise, this
academic study will be completely lost on the average
businessperson.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
