<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD-LUCK JETS HOPE FOR BREAK FROM RAIDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHELLE SMITH  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The only good break the New York Jets have
gotten this season is that the Yankees' and Mets' postseason runs
turned attention away from what has befallen a team that fell one
game short of the Super Bowl last season.
</P>
<P>
   But with the start of the World Series, the Jets are just days
away from becoming headline fodder once again in New York. At 1-5
as they go into Sunday's game against the Raiders in Oakland, the
headlines are destined to be really big and bold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never thought things would go this way,'' Jets star wide
receiver Keyshawn Johnson said. ``You look at everything on paper
and you think your team is going to be good and all of a sudden,
things turn for the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets were slapped with the Super Bowl contender label in the
preseason after having reached the AFC title game last January and
losing to Denver, 23-10. But expectations came crashing down in the
team's opening game when starting quarterback Vinny Testaverde
collapsed untouched on the turf with a ruptured Achilles' tendon.
</P>
<P>
   It has turned out to be only one of many injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Lucas, the Jets' third starting quarterback of the season
after the injury to Testaverde and the ineptitude of Rick Mirer,
suffered a severe ankle sprain in last week's game against
Indianapolis and will be out 3 to 4 weeks. That leaves Mirer the
starter.
</P>
<P>
   Starting safety Steve Atwater is questionable this week with a
pulled hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Otis Smith is out with a broken collarbone, running
back Leon Johnson is in street clothes with a knee injury, and wide
receiver Wayne Chrebet returned last Sunday after missing the first
five games with a broken foot and caught five passes against the
Colts for 51 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, and most seriously, there is safety Kevin Williams, who
was hospitalized for a throat infection that spread to his lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Head coach Bill Parcells has remade franchises. But he cannot
work miracles, although perhaps it's enough of a miracle that his
team _ riding the strength of its defense _ has stayed in nearly
every game. The Jets' largest margin of defeat is 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   Even the status of Parcells, who led the Jets out of the dregs
after a 1-15 record in 1996, has been the subject of speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells not only has health considerations _ he's had heart
surgery _ but the Jets' ownership situation for next season is also
unsettled and the team is $10 million over the 2000 salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't thought beyond this year, to tell you the truth,''
Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the injuries, Parcells has felt dissatisfaction from
every direction. The first utterances of Rich Kotite's name _ the
man who posted a 4-28 record as the Jets head coach in 1995-96 _
have been heard around town. And the now-defunct possibility of a
Subway Series in baseball couldn't even protect Parcells from the
proper New York media roasting he got after Sunday's loss to
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells started the day by announcing that Lucas would be the
starter just 2 1/2 hours before the game.
</P>
<P>
   During the game, with the Jets tied with the Colts 13-13,
Parcells called for a pass on first-and-goal at the Colts' 3-yard
line. Lucas' pass was intercepted, setting up Indianapolis'
game-winning field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what happens,'' Parcells said of the criticism. ``You
can't ever judge the wisdom of the calls by the results. Now
retrospectively, would I do it again? No.
</P>
<P>
   ``What went into that is we've been stopped on third-and-1 and
fourth-and-1. We had not been successful on goal-line offense
recently, we've been having some problems. But you can't explain
that to everybody. But who cares?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
