<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELARUS-BULLY-RESEND-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REIGN OF TERROR IN TIME-WARP BELARUS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (RESENDING from Oct. 20 for those needing)   (This compelling 800-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
International Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By LEE DEMBART  
 c.1999 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINSK, Belarus _ When I went down to breakfast in my hotel one
day last week, the maitre d' greeted me in good English and asked,
``How are you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fine,'' I said, though I had slept with my clothes on because
my room was so cold, and the heat had not yet been turned on. ``How
are you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not good,'' he whispered, looking around to make sure that no
was listening. ``Things are very bad in this country,'' he said.
``Very bad.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he might have added, they are getting worse by the day in
this former Soviet republic, which is ruled by President Alexander
Lukashenko, a Stalinist thug who is recreating a totalitarian
police state in the geographical center of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In more than 30 years in journalism, I have been around the
world, and I have visited many countries, in Africa and elsewhere,
with unspeakably poor living conditions, repressive governments and
little hope.
</P>
<P>
   But I have never been so moved as by the situation in Belarus,
whose 10 million people had thought in 1991 that they were finally
free after 70 years of domination from Moscow, punctuated by the
brutal and murderous rule of the Nazis during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in Minsk, some people wore buttons promoting an
anti-Lukashenko ``Freedom March'' on Sunday, and they furtively
passed around a small handbill with a caricature blending
Lukashenko and Hitler and the urgent plea, ``Stop Luka.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the 15 new countries formed by the collapse of the Soviet
Union eight years ago Belarus is in the direst political and
economic straits. Violations of human rights are becoming more
serious and more alarming.
</P>
<P>
   Four of Lukashenko's toughest opponents have disappeared off the
street in the last few months, and three weeks ago, the government
closed nine outspoken independent newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The government insists that freedom of the press exists, but
there is continuing harassment of newspapers not controlled by the
state and of companies that advertise in them.
</P>
<P>
   There are not many private companies to begin with, as
Lukashenko has imposed a top-down, Soviet-style economy. Protesters
have been beaten up, and so have the journalists who were covering
their demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lukashenko wants to destroy all of the institutions of civil
society,'' a newspaper editor told me.
</P>
<P>
   Coming to Belarus is like going through a time warp to the old
Soviet Union. The state is omnipresent and controlling. In the best
hotels, where foreigners stay, policemen stand by the elevators in
the lobby, watching who gets on and off.
</P>
<P>
   The Belarus ruble is suffering hyperinflation that is making it
virtually worthless. The average income in Belarus has fallen to
$30 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Food shortages are widespread and common, but Lukashenko tells
the people that the shortages are the result of their eating too
much.
</P>
<P>
   The official exchange rate, which was 50,000 rubles to the
dollar less than a year ago, was 330,000 to the dollar last week.
But the unofficial, black market rate was 540,000 to the dollar
Oct. 11 and had fallen to 600,000 to the dollar by Saturday. My
hotel bill for a week was 204 million rubles.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the people of Belarus look with envy and dismay at
their neighbors who have embraced liberal democracy and a
free-market economy and are doing well.
</P>
<P>
   Vilnius, the capital of Lithuania, about 160 kilometers (100
miles) away, is a thriving, vibrant city in stark contrast to the
gray and tired Minsk, which was almost completely destroyed during
World War II and was then rebuilt in grand Soviet style, with wide
boulevards and massive, hulking, nondescript buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are our people living as they are when their neighbors are
doing so much better?'' asked a prominent journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Lukashenko, 45, who had been a Communist functionary during what
is called ``the Soviet time,'' became Belarus's first elected
president in 1994. His five-year term would have ended last July.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1996, after a rigged referendum, he disbanded the elected
Parliament and declared that his term of office would start on that
date, thereby giving himself an extra two years by fiat. Now he
seeks to reunite with Russia, and he dreams of becoming head of the
combined union.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday morning, the militia were out in force throughout the
city. When thousands of people began their march, the militia
clashed with them, and dozens were injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting worse,'' the journalist said. ``People are
beginning to disappear. Newspapers are being shut down. The economy
is in shambles. The president is illegitimate.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 800-word article from the International
Herald Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is:
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
