u a BC-SIXTH-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     10-21 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIXTH-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SIXTH HAPPINESS': GROING UP WITH A DEFECT, AND CHARM AND
MISCHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Sixth Happiness,'' a boy who cannot grow grows up.
</P>
<P>
   Reminiscent of ``My Left Foot,'' this offbeat, beguiling English
production set in Bombay in the 1960s and '70s tells the story of
Brit, named by his sister for the brittle bones that characterize
the ailment he was born with: osteogenesis imperfecta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixth Happiness,'' based on an autobiographical fiction by
Firdaus Kanga, who portrays Brit Kotwal, is the story not only of
how the boy comes to terms with himself but also of his impact on
his family. In addition the film, directed from Kanga's screenplay
by Waris Hussein (``Quackser Fortune Has a Cousin in the Bronx,''
et al.), looks with affection and amusement at life among India's
Parsees, who are descended from the Persians of a millennium ago,
maintain their customs and enjoyed a special status under the
British.
</P>
<P>
   Brit's story, told with humor as well as pain, is one of
progress from the broken legs of his childhood through his
education to his sexual awakening and self-acceptance through
relationships with a lodger, Cyrus (Ahsen Bhatti), and Cyrus'
girlfriend, Amy (Indira Varma).
</P>
<P>
   Brit's journey to a literary career is also the story of his
relationship with his parents _ Sera (Souad Faress), his Anglophile
mother, who loves him without reservation from the moment of his
birth, and Sam (Khodus Wadia), his handsome father, a bank manager
who can never really come to terms with his deformed son.
</P>
<P>
   The film is full of vivid secondary characters, including Brit's
bright, funny sister, Dolly Kotwal (Nina Wadia), who amuses him
with photos of nudes and adores him. And the music, beginning with
an enigmatic tango and including songs like ``Always,'' is used
effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Presented without sentiment, Brit is no angel. He can be
manipulative and selfish as well as perceptive and funny. And as
Kanga and Hussein know, these qualities make him human and very
much worth knowing. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `THE SIXTH HAPPINESS' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Waris Hussein; written by Firdaus Kanga, based on
his novel ``Trying to Grow''; director of photography, James
Welland; edited by Laurence Mery-Clark; produced by Tatiana
Kennedy; released by Regent Entertainment. Running time: 97
minutes. This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Firdaus Kanga (Brit Kotwal), Souad Faress (Sera Kotwal),
Khodus Wadia (Sam Kotwal), Nina Wadia (Dolly Kotwal), Ahsen Bhatti
(Cyrus), Indira Varma (Amy) and Sabira Merhchant (Mme. Manckshaw) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
