<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFTWARE-CHINA-RESEND-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE SOFTWARE DEVELOPERS SEEK INVESTORS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (RESENDING from Oct. 20 for those needing)   (This 500-word ``separate buy'' article is from the International
Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``f'' financial news files.)  
  
 By THOMAS CRAMPTON  
 c.1999 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHENZHEN, China _ Although billed as a showcase for cutting-edge
technology, some of the most intriguing business plans being thrust
toward visitors at the Shenzhen High Tech Fair earlier this month
were adaptations of existing technology to unique niches in China's
vast consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Internet music may not yet be mainstream _ in China
or anywhere else _ but Shen Kum-tu is convinced his handheld MP3
player could quickly attract the millions of English-learners in
China.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most MP3 devices, which can only play music downloaded
from the Internet, the machine Shen is developing will also allow
simultaneous recording from a built-in microphone. His device will
also be designed to jump easily between tracks.
</P>
<P>
   These features aim the product at the already thriving market
for recorded language lessons in China.
</P>
<P>
   With his hand-held MP3 device, priced at 800 yuan ($97), English
students across China will be able to download CD-quality English
lessons featuring the latest in slang expressions and listen to
themselves in their own speaking accent.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, Shen and his company, Shenzhen Xinronghao
Industrial Co., are looking for a 20 million yuan investment to get
the device off the drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   In another area, one software developer said she believed she
had finally cracked the code on devising keystrokes for the
thousands of Chinese characters that have long restricted the
vocabulary available for Chinese-language documents written on
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a half-century of research by her father, an eminent
lexicographer, Zheng Long's company has created a computer input
system capable of writing 100,000 characters, more than triple the
standard computer vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the characters are esoteric terms rarely needed
for everyday use, they are essential for traditional Chinese
medicine and to accurately write Chinese names. Long said these two
uses alone could open lucrative markets for her father's lifelong
academic pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Long also plans to tap the market for traditional Chinese
medicine by setting up the only Internet site on which discussions
using completely accurate characters for traditional herbal
remedies can take place.
</P>
<P>
   Another company, Join Hands Century Technology Corp., is trying
to combat rampant product piracy in China with an anti-fraud
network.
</P>
<P>
   Infrared scanners linked nationwide by Internet will alert
manufacturers, suppliers, retailers and law-enforcement officials
when any member of the network inspects a product bearing a
fraudulent Join Hands label.
</P>
<P>
   Cash-strapped Chinese pager companies looking for gimmicks to
keep customers from migrating to mobile phones may find hope in a
new voice pager system now offered by Zhengzhou Aomei Electronic
Co.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which says it recently completed an operational
trial with 20,000 subscribers in Henan Province, claims several
advantages over competing Japanese products.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does Aomei's domestic manufacturing keep the price down
to 680 yuan a unit, but pager companies can upgrade their systems
without replacing the entire network.
</P>
<P>
   ``By only requiring an upgrade, we hope to attract companies in
China that cannot afford to fully change their network,'' said Zhu
Su-sheng, inventor of the system. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 500-word article from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is: weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
