<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWW.PALESTINE.CAMPS.COM-750&AMP;add-RESEND-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET IS A BRAVE NEW WORLD IN PALESTINIAN REFUGEE CAMPS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (RESENDING from Oct. 20)   (This excellent 950-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
International Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS A 150-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 750; TOTAL UNCUT IS 950
WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``i'' international news and ``a'' general news files.)  
  
 By FLORE DE PRENEUF  
 Special to the International Herald Tribune  
 c.1999 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DHEISHEH, West Bank _ Tapping into the Internet's ability to
abolish distances and knock down frontiers, Palestinian refugees
have begun a virtual gathering of exiles.
</P>
<P>
   A project called Across Borders is trying to bring together the
3.6 million-strong Palestinian diaspora, scattered across the
Middle East for the past 50 years, through a network of computer
centers and World Wide Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Dheisheh became the first online refugee camp a couple of months
ago, and camps in Gaza, Lebanon and Jordan are expected to hook up
to the Net in the future. Birzeit University is the coordinator for
the project, which is funded by contributions from aid groups.
</P>
<P>
   The founders of the project _ two West Bank Palestinians who
have spent part of their time in exile in the United States and
Australia, Muna Muhaisen and Adam Hanieh _ say they hope refugees
will use the immediacy of the Internet to let their political
demands be heard loud and clear.
</P>
<P>
   But by bringing computer technology to low-tech, run-down camps,
the project may ultimately prove more successful at introducing
Palestinian children to the wonders of the modern world than at
bolstering the Palestinian refugee cause.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Israel, a technologically advanced society with a
per-capita gross domestic product 10 times that of the
Palestinians, the West Bank and Gaza look like technological
wastelands.
</P>
<P>
   There are Internet cafes in most large towns of the West Bank
and Gaza, but only 20 percent of households had telephone lines in
1997, and a mere 4 percent had computers, according to the
Palestinian Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Dheisheh computer center was inaugurated in July,
only a handful of the camp's 10,000 residents had access to
computers. Now, for 6 shekels ($1.40) an hour, anyone with a bit of
training can surf the Web on one of the center's 14 computers
donated by the Canada Fund and other aid organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Across Borders encourages people to post news items and essays
and bits of oral history on the camp's Web site. But most of the
activity at the computer center _ where screen savers say
``Palestine'' _ has nothing to do with identity or politics.
</P>
<P>
   Children flock to the computer monitors to play games in which
they destroy imaginary enemies, not to mull over real-life
bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of being introduced to the concept of a computer
mouse, boys were visiting the Web site of their favorite soccer
player, Ronaldo, and downloading pictures of National Basketball
Association (NBA) celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Free computer classes for children and adults are intended to
ensure that as many people as possible will use the camp's computer
resources.
</P>
<P>
   So far, a student has done research on cloning, a hairdresser
has surfed the Web for new hairdos, and a carpenter has downloaded
designs, but by and large, ``not many people are aware of all that
there is on the Internet,'' said Jamal Abdulkareem, Dheisheh's
33-year-old Webmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisors and peer pressure in the computer room are supposed
to keep sites that mention sex, drugs and other topics offensive to
the community off limits.
</P>
<P>
   But at the center one recent day, a teenager quietly read an
innocent-looking, all-text Web page devoted to the merits of Viagra
_ seeming to suggest that walls will fall faster than the project's
founders imagine.
</P>
<P>
   To refugees, virtual travel is one of the Internet's most
tangible benefits. Palestinians in the West Bank cannot visit
compatriots in the Gaza Strip 110 kilometers (70 miles) away on the
Mediterranean coast unless they obtain hard-to-get permits from
Israeli authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're unable to go to picnics, unable to go to the sea,
unable to go to movies in Jerusalem, it's like being in a prison
cell,'' said Mrs. Muhaisen, a 39-year-old Palestinian-American
journalist who is one of the project's main architects. ``Your
world becomes very limited.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Muhaisen was born in Jerusalem but lost her residency
rights during her parents' time in exile. The Internet provides her
with a ``way out'' of the 1-square-kilometer camp.
</P>
<P>
   The camp's Web site is geared toward young Palestinians who have
spent all their lives in camps. A section called ``Villages of
1948'' ensures that children know where their family homes were _
even though those villages have mostly been torn down or
incorporated into Israeli cities by now.
</P>
<P>
   A section devoted to ``Martyrs'' commemorates the camp residents
who died during the intifada, the Palestinian uprising that started
in the late 1980s. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (150-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 750) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Web's wealth of information is important to many
Palestinians, with local media still heavily censored by the
Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not happy about what is happening to them, but they
need information,'' said Mrs. Muhaisen. She hopes alternate sources
of information will help refugees forget daily troubles such as
water shortages, blackouts and unemployment and focus on their
struggle to return to their former homes.
</P>
<P>
   Bookmarks on the Dheisheh computer center's machines link to a
wide range of Arabic newspapers online, representing all sorts of
political opinions _ including opposition to the Palestinian
Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian Authority does not tolerate criticism and
frequently shuts down newspapers and arrests journalists who
express dissent. But so far, unlike other authoritarian regimes in
the Middle East, it has not tried to block or filter access to the
Internet. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 950.) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next camp wired is scheduled to be Khan Yunis in the Gaza
Strip at the end of November. The computer center there will be
funded through a $48,000 grant by Oxfam, the British charity
organization, according to Hanieh.
</P>
<P>
   After that will come Shatila camp in Lebanon, perhaps by
December.
</P>
<P>
   The camp's Web site is at: www.dheisheh.acrossborders.org. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this intriguing 950-word article from the International
Herald Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is:
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
