<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRAZY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CRAZY IN ALABAMA': FREEDOM FIGHTING IN DIXIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Crazy in Alabama,'' a madcap woman named Lucille cuts off
her husband's head and heads off to meet her destiny, which she
hopes will involve the hit television series ``Bewitched'' (the
year is 1965) and an acting career.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the small Alabama town where most of the husband
remains, the Civil Rights Movement is challenging the segregated
status quo.
</P>
<P>
   The story, written by Mark Childress from his lighthearted
novel, insists that in some way Lucille and the black citizens of
the Alabama town are actually part of the same struggle, all
fighting for freedom.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bit of a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the film version of ``Crazy in Alabama'' takes an
antic tone. It presents Melanie Griffith as the kind of fanciful
creature who looks flirty even on her Wanted poster, and whose
escapades en route to Hollywood have a dizzy spin.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Griffith, in a black wig, has to strain for the requisite
spontaneity, but she plays would-be starlet with enthusiasm.
There's a more lifelike performance from David Morse, who plays her
brother, the proprietor of a funeral home.
</P>
<P>
   The story is seen through the eyes of Peejoe (Lucas Black),
Lucille's young nephew, whose own experiences ultimately count for
more than Lucille's. Peejoe witnesses the brave attempt by Taylor
Jackson (Louis Miller Jr.) to integrate the town's whites-only
municipal swimming pool, and sees the tragic aftermath of that
confrontation. Both young actors give the film a compellingly
serious side, as does John Beasley as Taylor's father.
</P>
<P>
   Bragging rights to the phrase ``the directorial debut of Antonio
Banderas,'' which has accompanied advertising for the film, are
within reason. Banderas directs capably enough to keep the film
lively, even if he lets a closing courtroom scene drone on
endlessly and allows Rod Steiger, as the judge, to chew up the
gavel. Though too many of its characters have personality to burn,
the film's own style is mostly unobtrusive.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Mazursky and Robert Wagner turn up in a Hollywood section
of the film that actually does land Lucille on ``Bewitched.'' Here
and elsewhere on the road (driven by a chauffeur who exclaims
``What a woman!'' over Ms. Griffith), Lucille is inconveniently
distant from the film's Alabama scenes. Banderas simply cuts back
and forth, over and over, until the heroine flounces home.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   CRAZY IN ALABAMA
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Crazy in Alabama'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It includes mild profanity and the implicit severing of
a head.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Antonio Banderas; by Mark Childress, based on his
novel; director of photography, Julio Macat; edited by Maysie Hoy
and Robert C. Jones; music by Mark Snow; production designer,
Cecilia Montiel; produced by Meir Teper and Linda Goldstein
Knowlton; released by Columbia Pictures. Running time: 104 minutes.
This film is rated PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Melanie Griffith (Lucille), David Morse (Dove), Lucas
Black (Peejoe), Louis Miller Jr. (Taylor Jackson), John Beasley
(Jackson), Rod Steiger (Judge Mead), Paul Mazursky and Robert
Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
