<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-JOE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JOE THE KING' IS AN AFFECTING FILM ABOUT INNOCENCE LOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This moving and woefully tender look at a young boy's troubled
adolescence, written and directed by actor Frank Whaley, shared the
screenwriting award at this year's Sundance Film Festival and was
nominated for the Grand Jury Prize as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe the King'' has enought simmering beneath its sweaty,
grimmy and disconsolate surface to be more than just another rite
of passage to young manhood missive set in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   It features a textured core performance by young Noah Fleiss,
who plays Joe, a 14-year-old who lives with his big brother Mike
(Max Ligosh), abusive and alcoholic dad Bob (Val Kilmer) and
tough-but-loving mom Theresa (Karen Young) in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Joe earns his street stripes in their downtrodden neighborhood
by committing petty thefts _ until he graduates to the big leagues
of crime in order to honor his family's debts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe the King'' swirls and swaggers with visual surrealness
through this suburban slum, introducing us to the residents,
friends and enemies Joe encounters. His tough veneer hides a soft
heart and Fleiss allows us a glimpse into a boy's burgeoning
confusion. Joe is confident, frightened and fragile and walks a
tightrope between conformity and doing the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   Whaley elicits fine performances from his supporting actors,
with Kilmer acting against type as a dangerously unpredictable,
beer-guzzling, unemployed father and Young emitting a forgiving and
emotionally frazzled fierceness as Joe's frustrated mom. But it's
Fleiss, with his vulnerable eyes and impenetrable gaze, who breaks
hearts. Though each character is allowed a moment to display the
softness that has been sanded away by life's sorry twists and
turns, none merits mention more than this young stage and screen
actor.
</P>
<P>
   Though Whaley has some first-time director's trepidations over
how to end his film (I counted three consecutive endings; the
first, a poignant reconciliation scene between Kilmer and his son,
is the best, most powerful and necessary to the narrative), he's to
be commended for taking an overworked formula and breathing new
life into it. He's crafted an affecting film about innocence lost _
tragically perhaps never to be regained.
</P>
<P>
   Joe the King. Directed and written by Frank Whaley. Cast: Val
Kilmer, Noah Fleiss, Karen Young, Ethan Hawke, Camryn Manheim.
Trimark Pictures. Broadway Market. 100 minutes. Rated R for
language, violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
