<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOONEY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'THE LOONEY TUNES HALL OF FAME': WITH THAT WASCALLY WABBIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Operatic rabbits, enigmatic frogs, vexatious birds and hotheaded
hunters and hombres are running amok in Manhattan, and there's
still more than a week to go before Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   In this instance, the mischief and mayhem are confined (barely)
to the screen of Cinema Village, where Bugs Bunny, the singing
Frog, Tweetie Pie, Road Runner, Elmer Fudd and Yosemite Sam, among
other cutups, are on the loose in ``The Looney Tunes Hall of
Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Valuable history and ample family fun, this compilation of 15
classic Warner Brothers cartoons spans the years 1940 to 1995, an
era of ingenious Hollywood animated shorts that began as program
fillers but earned acknowledgment as art, and of directors who
began their careers as Charles M. Jones and I. Freleng, then
achieved fame and accolades as Chuck Jones and Friz Freleng.
</P>
<P>
   Expressions like ``what's up, doc?'' and ``that's all folks''
entered the language through these films, and by giving memorable
voice to a multitude of characters, Mel Blanc, too, won
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   The energy, talent and creativity of Jones and Freleng are
everywhere in ``The Looney Tunes Hall of Fame,'' whose merry
madness includes two cartoons enshrined in the National Film
Registry: Jones' ``Duck Amuck'' (1953), a frenetic excursion into
the art of animation in which Daffy Duck finds out who's really
running the show, and ``What's Opera, Doc,'' Jones' sendup of
Wagner, with Elmer Fudd as the horn-helmeted hero and Bugs Bunny as
his blond-braided Brunnhilde.
</P>
<P>
   Here, too, are ``The Wild Hare'' (1940), the debut vehicle for
Bugs Bunny and Elmer Fudd as co-stars, with the shotgun-toting
Elmer as the hunter and Bugs as the frustratingly elusive quarry
who teaches him a lesson, and ``Bugs Bunny Rides Again,'' a clever
satire of westerns with Yosemite Sam and Bugs as the gun-packing
objects of mischief created by some of the fastest drawers in the
West.
</P>
<P>
   The enigmatic singing frog (``Michigan Rag,'' et al.) that is
recovered from a cornerstone at a demolition site by a construction
worker who dreams of glory as the amphibian's impresario turns up
not once but twice. Having driven his rescuer mad with his refusal
to sing in public in Jones' ``One Froggy Evening'' (1955), the
creature returns in a prequel and sequel that bound from earthly
prehistory to the interplanetary future in ``Another Froggy
Evening'' (1995).
</P>
<P>
   ``Rabbit Seasoning'' (1952), pitting Bugs and Daffy Duck against
Elmer Fudd; ``Knightly Knight Bugs'' (1955), in which a medieval
Bugs squares off against the dark knight of Yosemite Sam and his
not-too-bright dragon, and the climactic ``Rabbit of Seville''
(1956), another opera pastiche, with Bugs as barber and Elmer as
his prey, are among other highlights of an altogether entertaining
show.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `THE LOONEY TUNES HALL OF FAME'
</P>
<P>
   A compilation of Warner Brothers cartoons from 1940 to 1995;
released by Kit Parker Films. Running time: 105 minutes. These
films are rated G.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
