<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON THE ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas)   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Botticelli With a Hitch &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Timothy Potts became director of the Kimbell Art Museum in
Fort Worth a year ago, he began doing what museum directors
typically do: searching the world for great works of art to
acquire.
</P>
<P>
   Potts isn't concerned about filling gaps in the museum's
collection because the Kimbell doesn't bill itself as having
encyclopedic holdings. He is hunting art that would enrich its
world-class collection. But his mission isn't easy: there are few
outstanding paintings and objects left on the market, and when they
do appear there are often complications.
</P>
<P>
   Recently Potts jumped at Botticelli's ``Virgin Adoring the
Christ Child'' (circa 1480), which he hopes will be his first
acquisition for the Kimbell. Great Botticelli's are rare, and this
one comes with a particularly pristine provenance.
</P>
<P>
   The painting was owned by Lord Northwick, a great collector who
presided over two well-known stately English homes, Norwick Park in
Gloucestershire and Thirlestane House in Cheltenham. In 1859 Lord
Northwick sold the Botticelli to Lord Elcho, and the painting has
descended through his family, ending up with the present Earl of
Wemyss. The Botticelli has been at Gosford House, the Wemyss home
in Scotland, and has not been seen publicly for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Wemyss Heirloom Trust is the painting's legal owner. As with
many titled English families, the trust owns and oversees the
running of the family's two homes (the other is in England) and
needs money for preserving them.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is getting an export license to allow the painting
to leave Britain. While the National Gallery of Art in London has
seven signed Botticelli's, the National Galleries of Scotland has
none. An application for an export license is expected to be
deferred by the government to see if any British institution or
collector will match the price the Kimbell is willing to pay,
reportedly $24 million.
</P>
<P>
   Toby Sargent, a spokesman for the Department of National
Heritage in London, said an application for an export license was
expected. He predicted it would be deferred for three months; then,
if no one matchs the Kimbell's price, the Botticelli will go to
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purchase of the painting has effectively been agreed
upon,'' Potts said, implying that no sale contract had been signed
but that the terms had been ironed out. ``But the export permit
process can be a lengthy one. And the outcome is never assured.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts who have seen the painting say it is everything anyone
would want in a Botticelli: one of the great images of the
Renaissance artist, richly detailed and beautifully rendered.
</P>
<P>
   Simon C. Dickinson, the Old Master dealer who has galleries in
London and New York, has known the Wemyss collection for years, and
it is his firm, Dickinson Roundell, that is brokering the deal.
Rachel Mauro, the managing director of Dickinson Roundell in New
York, confirmed the gallery's involvement but declined to comment
on the sale.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimbell is not the first American museum to find itself
stymied by the Department of National Heritage. The J. Paul Getty
Museum in Los Angeles was able to get a Poussin landscape from
Sudeley Castle in Gloucestershire two years ago, but earlier it had
to wait five years before learning it could not have Canova's
``Three Graces.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be surprised and delighted if the money could be
raised for the Botticelli,'' Sargent said. ``But it's a colossal
amount of money, and I can't pretend to be optimistic about it.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ebay Goes Upscale &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to raise the price range of the merchandise it
offers, Ebay has created a new Web site, called Ebay Great
Collections. Users can click on Great Collections from Ebay's
original homepage (ebay.com), and buy and sell everything from
fossilized pine cones to Hepplewhite armchairs.
</P>
<P>
   Following the lead of Sotheby's, which this year announced its
online auctions plans in an alliance with Amazon.com, Ebay will
have dealers and other auction houses as partners. But while
Sotheby's counts on its brand name to lure buyers, Ebay hopes to
entice its registered 5.6 million users to keep spending bigger
sums of money.
</P>
<P>
   When Sotheby's site becomes available early next year, only
dealers will be able to offer things for sale, but on Ebay Great
Collections anybody can be a seller.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to be accessible to everyone,'' said Meg Whitman,
president and chief executive officer of Ebay. ``We've created a
level playing field at your fingertips where anyone can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Whitman said the company was taking its ``high-end buyers''
_ those who spend more than $250 _ and marrying them to higher-end
merchandise. She said she envisioned the price range to be from
$250 to $10,000 and that over time she expected it to go even
higher.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came six months after Ebay spent $260 million
for Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield, the San Francisco auction house.
</P>
<P>
   Ebay charges a 7.5 percent seller's fee but no buyer's premium.
Sotheby's.Amazon.com will charge a 10 percent buyer's premium and
no seller's fee. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moving Around &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neal Benezra, assistant director for art and public programs at
the Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden in Washington, has been
named deputy director of the Art Institute of Chicago and head of
its department of 20th-century art. He replaces Jeremy Strict, who
left Chicago in July to be the director of the Museum of
Contemporary Art in Los Angeles. Benezra begins his new post in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Weiss, a curator of 20th-century art at the National
Gallery of Art in Washington, has just been named head of the
gallery's department of modern and contemporary art. He is
replacing Marla Prather, who will become curator of postwar art at
the Whitney Museum of American Art in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
