<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JIANG-ELVIS-KARAOKE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JIANG: BEIJING'S `FLOWER POT' BLOOMS OUTSIDE THE HOTHOUSE  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This colorful 650-word ``separate buy'' profile of Chinese
President Jiang Zemin is from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By LORIEN HOLLAND  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Chinese President Jiang Zemin had no shortage of party
tricks to entertain his host Queen Elizabeth at Buckingham Palace
Tuesday night, for the man who heads up China's state, Communist
Party and army is also a past master at playing to the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   A deft hand at bridge and playing the piano, the 73-year-old
Chinese leader is also a demon karaoke fan and he may have even
crooned a rendition of Elvis Presley's ``Love Me Tender,'' as he
did back in 1996 when he visited Philippine President Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Jiang may have shown off his knowledge of
Western culture for the Queen with off-the-cuff recitals from
Shelly and Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as Oct. 1, he was stony-faced, inspecting troops in
a dour Mao suit for Beijing's 50th anniversary parade. But his
message for London and the Queen is that China means business, so
an immaculate Western business suit is the order of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang was propelled from Shanghai party chief into the hot seat
of Communist Party boss back in 1989 by the political purges that
surrounded the army massacre of pro-democracy students in Tiananmen
Square.
</P>
<P>
   At that time he was derided as ``the flower pot'' _ for being
decorative but ineffectual _ and many predicted he would not stay
atop the Chinese dragon for long.
</P>
<P>
   But Jiang's chameleon tendencies have served him well, and he is
looking to this European tour to put the finishing touches on his
ascendancy to the ranks of his two communist predecessors, Mao
Tse-tung and Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind those Buddy Holly glasses, Jiang is a very intelligent
and shrewd politician,'' said William Ward, a U.S. academic who
lived in China in the 1980s and often played bridge with Jiang when
he was the mayor and party secretary of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a communist revolutionary martyr, Jiang was born in
the southeastern coastal province of Jiangsu in the year of the
tiger 1926, making him an exact contemporary of the Queen In 1955.
</P>
<P>
   He spent a year in Russia at the labyrinthine Stalin Autoworks,
where he picked up a good knowledge of Russian _ he can still
recite the opening lines of ``Anna Karenina.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jiang hovered around the edges of the momentous political
events of his youth, surviving Maoist purges by keeping his head
down, and using his training as an electrical engineer to plod up
through China's heavy industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
   His political career did not take off until 1986 when he became
Shanghai mayor. In the same year, he had his first encounter with
the Queen, hosting her in China's financial center during her state
visit.
</P>
<P>
   But his next brush with British royalty did not come until 1997
when he met Prince Charles during the handover of Hong Kong. By
that time, he was fully installed in Beijing as the undisputed heir
to Deng, who had died earlier that year.
</P>
<P>
   His nation had recorded its fastest period of economic growth of
this century, and Western imports, from McDonalds to the Spice
Girls, abounded.
</P>
<P>
   But hopes that the third generation of Communist leadership in
China would lead to political reforms have not materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Jiang's frequent use of the word ``democracy,''
political dissidents are regularly imprisoned for expressing their
views. In July, Jiang outlawed the Falun Gong meditation group as a
threat to state security.
</P>
<P>
   Cadres have spent much of the summer bogged down in the ``Three
Stresses'' political campaign, which is designed to shore up an
awkward amalgam of socialist and traditional Chinese values.
</P>
<P>
   Amongst Jiang's performance repertoire is the Western church
organ. Maybe during his visit to Cambridge he will be permitted to
repeat the Chinese ``Ode to the Yellow River,'' which he bashed out
on Dutch and Finnish organs in the past, making an equally quirky
mixture of East and West. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this colorful 650-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please
call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
