<HEADER>
A4192 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-KAMIKAZE-DOLPHINS-IND     10-21 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAMIKAZE-DOLPHINS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN NAVY TO SELL OFF KAMIKAZE DOLPHINS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 600-word ``separate buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 By PATRICK COCKBURN  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Russian navy is to sell off dolphins who were
specially trained to blow up enemy ships as part of the rundown of
its armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   The dolphins were taught to approach a vessel from below and rub
its back, to which a mine was attached, against the keel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine that those dolphins could even distinguish
between the sound of the propellor of a foreign submarine and a
Soviet one?'' Viktor Baranets, who worked for ten years in the
General Head Quarters of the Soviet armed forces told the
Independent.
</P>
<P>
   Training of some ten dolphins started 30 years ago on the Black
Sea at a base at Balaclava near Sebastopol in the Crimea. It is not
clear how many dolphins were taught to attack enemy vessels, but
some half dozen survive today.
</P>
<P>
   They were kept in a military laboratory, but further development
of the project stopped with the breakup of the Soviet Union in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Now the dolphins are to be sold off, under a decree signed by
Vladimir Putin, the Russian prime minister, this week.
</P>
<P>
   Their sale is part of a general disposal of surplus military
equipment, such as old trucks, tanks, armored personnel carriers
and bulldozers, which the impoverished Russian army no longer needs
or can afford to maintain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have only pitiful remains of what we used to have in
the Black Sea dolphinarium,'' said Baranets. ``Only five or six
dolphins survived. They tried to keep couples _ male and female.''
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Kozir, a correspondent of the military newspaper,
Krasnaya Zvezda, says that the Soviet plan to train dolphins to
attack ships started as a response to information that the U.S. was
investigating the use of sea animals for military purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Soviet and American navies were impressed with the
ability of dolphins to perform complex tricks in circuses.
</P>
<P>
   Kozir says: ``They were trained to approach the ship from below
and to rub their backs against the bottom of the ship. The mine was
on the back of the dolphin.'' He added that some dolphins were
released into the Black Sea at the time of the breakup of the
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The naval department of the Russian Defense Ministry said
Tuesday that it could not confirm or deny accounts of the training
of dolphins to sink enemy ships, but it was opposed to their sale.
</P>
<P>
   Igor Dygalo, the navy spokesman, said: ``I just don't know
anything about dolphins, but even if we had such dolphins how can
we sell them?''
</P>
<P>
   His reason for opposing the sale of the dolphins is rooted in
the violence of Russian business rivalries and the possible use of
dolphins as an assassination weapon against businessmen who have
bought boats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine selling dolphins, which have had special
training, to a businessman who has enemies?'' asks Dygalo. ``He can
attach a bomb to a dolphin and direct him to anyone or anything he
wants to get rid of.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact the dolphins, trained for so long to carry out their
lone kamikaze missions, may have a more prosaic fate.
</P>
<P>
   Baranets says that he suspects that at the end of the day the
dolphins may not be sold to murderous businessmen but presented to
water circuses. He says: ``There is one at Sochi (on the Black Sea
coast) where you drop your wedding ring into the water and the
dolphins easily find it.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
