<HEADER>
A4194 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-POWELL-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     10-21 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWELL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDWEST WHOLESOMENESS, BIG-CITY WIT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, France)   By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dawn Powell was admired by critics like Edmund Wilson and J.B.
Priestley, and her stories were published in The New Yorker for
years, but if it hadn't been for the continuing labors of Tim Page,
it seems likely that Dawn Powell would be entirely forgotten.
Powell, born in 1896, was a satirical novelist whose books, as she
puts it in one letter in this collection, ``may be entertaining but
the content is important comment on contemporary affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Page, formerly a music critic at The Washington Post and at The
New York Times, has already published a biography of Powell and
``The Diaries of Dawn Powell.'' Now, this new volume of selected
letters shows Powell at her most intimate and also at her most
charming. She had a Midwestern wholesomeness about her, and that
combined with a contrasting sensibility, a habit of Menckenesque
mockery, to create a sympathetic, winsome and yet barbed epistolary
persona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nineteen is an ugly year, isn't it?'' Powell writes to her
aunt, Orpha May Steinbrueck, in 1915 on the occasion of a birthday.
``Now 18 was a round, even, complete year. I felt young and
debutantish. But 19! It's just a sort of gathering up of all the
tag ends of all the teens _ a Review of Reviews _ nothing new or
thrilling about 19.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of that letter Powell was a student at Lake Erie
College in Painesville, Ohio, from which place she would soon move
permanently to New York to begin her literary career. Her early
life had not been a portrait of Middle American bliss. Her mother
died when she was 7, and when her father remarried, her stepmother
was, Page says, abusive, and Dawn escaped to her aunt, who reared
her.
</P>
<P>
   One of the strongest elements of these letters, especially the
early ones, is their steadily cheery tone, the absence of
references to domestic travails. The teen-age Dawn wrote to her
aunt most often and to various other relatives and to school
friends, but there are no letters to her father. That may be
because no such letters have survived; still, it is clear that Dawn
was a kind of orphan, and she was to forge her life and her
relationships outside of any standard sort of family.
</P>
<P>
   She went to New York in 1918 and began writing stories. She
married Joseph Gousha, a poet and music critic who later became an
advertising man, and she had a son, Jojo, who was mentally impaired
and spent much of his life in institutions. The couple moved to
Greenwich Village, and their marriage, while it lasted, was
punctuated by separations and affairs.
</P>
<P>
   During the course of their first separation, Powell wrote
poignantly self-incriminating letters to Gousha cajoling him into
taking her back. ``Alone out here, I think of all the ways I have
failed you,'' she wrote from Long Island in 1928. ``It seems to me
I controlled my life until I got too happy _ you arranged that _
and then I just took a flying leap into the air and stayed there
while you waded through the mud.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell began publishing novels that satirized Ohio life and
later the New York social scene. She gained critical but not
commercial success, and she was accepted into the highbrow literary
world. By the time she was 30 or so, her correspondence evolved
into a witty running commentary on the republic of letters. She
communicated with Edmund Wilson, whom she called Wig, with the
novelist John Dos Passos (Dos) and with her editor at Scribner's,
the legendary Maxwell Perkins (Max). In these letters, Powell is at
her most exuberantly appealing. She writes to Dos Passos about a
Writers' Congress she attended in 1937 at which Ernest Hemingway
spoke:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ernest gave a good speech if that's what you like and his sum
total was that war was pretty nice and a lot better than sitting
around a hot hall and writers ought to all go to war and get killed
and if they didn't they were a big sissy. Then he went to the Stork
Club, followed by a pack of foxes.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade later Dos Passos and his wife, Katy Smith Dos Passos,
were in an automobile accident in which Katy was killed and Dos
Passos lost an eye. Powell wrote to him: ``I am thinking of you all
the time, and I find two things to be glad about. One, that you are
a writer so that agony is of service to you, cruel as our work is _
and another, that you have physical pain to dull the unbearable
other kind.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1950s, Powell lived in Paris for a couple of years,
and she assumed an attitude of gentle agnosticism toward the idols
of French literature. She writes to Wig about the annoyed departure
of a friend during cocktails at the Deux Magots: ``The reason he
left was my remark that Sartre was the Hopalong Cassidy of France,
and he said I should be more humble before French letters. ... I
returned that this view was not _ as he held _ the stupid view of
America toward France, but my own and based not on my brief but not
brief enough stay in Paris but on Sartre as a commercial enterprise
like cornflakes or Shirley Temple.''
</P>
<P>
   Much is notably absent from these letters. Powell lived through
the two world wars but says hardly a word about them. She has
terrible difficulties with her son but she rarely mentions that to
her friends, only to her husband and doctor. As she gets older, she
has health problems, which she writes about to Gousha, still her
husband, and to others. A certain elan seems missing as the letters
take on a sardonic and sometimes elegiac quality. She writes in
1963 to Edmund Wilson of Nabokov: ``His book on Gogol _ my earliest
literary idol _ infuriated me and I threw it across the room after
he had wallowed in the grisly ugliness of poor Gogol and jumped up
and down over him, then patted him to show Daddy alone loved him.''
</P>
<P>
   She talks of stomach pains in that same letter; clearly she is
reflecting on her mortality (she died of cancer two years later),
but she never loses her sense of humor. ``Words do not bring
happiness nor grammar good a poem,'' she tells Wilson. She
identifies this line as an ``Old Persian saying by Omar the shish
kebab maker.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is really Powell herself speaking at the end of a
life that brought many events but less fame and, it would seem,
less happiness than she deserved.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SELECTED LETTERS OF DAWN POWELL, 1913-1965'
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Tim Page
</P>
<P>
   373 pages. Henry Holt. $30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
