<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIZABETH DOLE GIVES UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Throughout her long, successful public career,
Elizabeth Dole has been proof positive that it's not true nice
girls finish last.
</P>
<P>
   But the presidency has always been a prize reserved for tough
guys, and Dole was not one of the boys.
</P>
<P>
   Her abrupt withdrawal from the contest for the Republican
presidential nomination does not mean that the country is not yet
ready for a female president. Some other woman might have run a
better race, and someday some other woman will.
</P>
<P>
   But the very qualities that have made Dole popular with men as
well as women _ a professional seriousness cloaked in ladylike
softness _ worked against her as a presidential candidate. It was
hard to envision her as commander-in-chief, no matter how hawkish
she sounded on national defense.
</P>
<P>
   She is, alas, far too feminine for the White House. This is not
in any way to denigrate her intelligence or her leadership ability.
She is a woman of formidable ability, as she demonstrated in two
Cabinet posts and as head of the American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   But she has an image problem. She just didn't look the part.
It's not fair, but there it is. Dole couldn't make it because she
is too sugary.
</P>
<P>
   A less cozy, more reckless female will someday break the gender
barrier. It will be someone like Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, former U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations Jeane
Kirkpatrick or California Sen. Dianne Feinstein, all of whom can
talk tough with the boys and get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   But Elizabeth Dole made her way in a man's world by being
non-threatening. She was never a leader in the women's rights
movement. She seemed, in fact, uncomfortable with the notion that
her audiences were mostly female and unsure how to capitalize on
that.
</P>
<P>
   Southern women of her era and proper upbringing got ahead with
charm and cunning. They simply did not get in the face of the male
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   She launched her campaign with a bold statement in New Hampshire
supporting limited gun control measures, signifying a dramatic
departure from her bland history of political caution and
orthodoxy. But the message got at best mixed reviews, powerful GOP
voices were raised in anger, and she quickly retreated into muddy
positions that left her without an identity beyond her gender.
</P>
<P>
   She advertised as a centrist, but her long years as a
tongue-tied candidate's wife were too much to overcome. She was so
mushy she proffered little red meat with which to arouse fans and
raise campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   Her inability to raise money was the specific reason she gave
for quitting before a single vote was cast. Texas Gov. George W.
Bush and billionaire publisher Steve Forbes have 80 times more
money in their campaign treasuries than she had in hers.
</P>
<P>
   But that was a symptom, not the cause, of a weak candidacy. Dole
was so carefully packaged and scripted that she was unable to
connect with Republican voters. If she had a spontaneous moment on
the campaign trail, nobody knows about it.
</P>
<P>
   And her No. 2 position in the polls had begun to slip in some
places behind that of Arizona Sen. John McCain, who has a
commanding presence and now stands to pick up some of her
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   There was also the awkwardness about Bob Dole. What to do with a
husband whose fame and political credentials were greater than hers
but couldn't keep his mouth shut?
</P>
<P>
   As the most recent GOP presidential nominee, Bob Dole could not
be hidden. But his wisecracks were not helpful to her candidacy. He
sometimes upstaged her with his own policy opinions, and his
presence didn't bring in the campaign money she needed.
</P>
<P>
   There was immediate speculation that she would make a nifty
running mate for Bush, but this idea does not seem likely to
survive the Republican National Convention next summer. It is not
clear what she would bring to the ticket. Her appeal to women was
overrated, and she has no regional or ideological constituency.
She'll make a great CEO for some big corporation.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
