<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4201 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      10-21 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUTHLESS IN A GREEDY WORLD. SOUNDS FAMILIAR DOESN'T IT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Becky Sharp meets Jos Sedley, the brother of her best
friend, Amelia, she sees what we do: a pudgy, pompous little man,
bound to be fonder of wine and food than he ever will be of a wife.
``He's very handsome,'' the calculating Becky confides to Amelia,
in what is just the beginning of the social hypocrisy that is the
world of ``Vanity Fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Becky of course is one of the world's great antiheroines, and
``Vanity Fair'' one of its most amusing, acerbic novels. A&AMP;E's
version is a pretty, diverting spectacle, but disappointing in its
lack of bite.
</P>
<P>
   What's missing is Thackeray's voice, that droll commentary that
turns the exploits of a ruthless, ambitious orphan into a panorama
of early 19th-century society. Thackeray writes of Becky, ``All the
world used her ill said this young misanthropist ... and we may be
sure that the persons of either sex whom all the world treats ill,
deserve entirely the treatment they get.''
</P>
<P>
   There may have been no way to translate such a wry narrative to
the screen. The problem is that nothing else fills the void here:
not the inner lives of characters, not enough suspense or dynamism
to sustain the six hours of this perfectly pleasant but bland
mini-series.
</P>
<P>
   Natasha Little is a smooth and appealing Becky, with her
open-faced smile and guileless manner. We might almost believe her
ourselves if we didn't see her, early on, pilfering jewelry from
Amelia before setting off for a dreaded life as a governess.
</P>
<P>
   As she courses up and down the social ladder, Becky encounters a
wealth of people Thackeray deliberately set up as caricatures.
George Osborne, a dashing cad in his red military coat, leaves
Amelia a widow, unaware that he would have abandoned her for Becky
in a second. His best friend is the steadfast William Dobbin, whose
love for Amelia is obvious to everyone except her. And there is the
sweet-natured Amelia herself, selfless and good to the point of
idiocy.
</P>
<P>
   The actors embody these types perfectly, especially David
Bradley as the man who employs Becky as a governess: the
wonderfully named Sir Pitt Crawley, slimy and drooling enough to
make anyone's skin crawl. Miriam Margolyes is his wealthy, obese
sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a great beauty myself once,'' she announces ludicrously,
explaining her affection for Becky. Sir Pitt's older son, also
named Pitt, is played by Anton Lesser as an amiable fussbudget,
touchingly susceptible to the slightest flattery.
</P>
<P>
   The penniless younger son, Rawdon, elopes with Becky, and they
set off on a life of living by her wits and his gambling. More than
anyone else in the series, Nathaniel Parker brings some complexity
to his character. Rawdon tacitly approves Becky's flirtations with
wealthy men, seeing only what he chooses to; he feels sorry for
their neglected son, but is too weak willed to do anything about
Becky's harsh treatment of the boy.
</P>
<P>
   The director, Marc Munden, exploits the cinematic qualities of
``Vanity Fair,'' as an active camera searches out the small touches
that create a rich texture, from Becky's lustrous hair to Dobbin's
lovesick gaze. At times the visual limitations become conspicuous,
though.
</P>
<P>
   During the Battle of Waterloo, in which both Osborne and Dobbin
fight bravely, the quick-cutting action focuses on these familiar
characters. The intimacy can't quite hide the fact that this should
have been an epic scene.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Little makes every one of Becky's situations believable.
Except for the blinkered Amelia, women see through her, while men
are snowed by her. (Some of Thackeray's types are vital even
today.) When Becky flirts with her rich brother-in-law, his wife
delicately asks, ``Pitt, my dear, you don't think that Mrs. Crawley
might have been flattering you for her own ends?'' But believing in
the pretty shallowness of Becky's character is finally no
substitute for being engaged by her story.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Davies, who wrote the screenplay, also did the dazzling
television adaptations of ``Pride and Prejudice,'' ``Moll
Flanders'' and ``Emma.'' With ``Vanity Fair,'' he came upon a
chestnut he couldn't crack. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANY DAY NOW
</P>
<P>
   Lifetime, Sunday night at 8 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Flat-footed and preachy as drama, the Lifetime series ``Any Day
Now'' has nonetheless been praised for its well-meaning subject:
two women in Alabama, one white and one black, who have been
lifelong best friends. In Sunday's two-hour special, the white
friend, Mary Elizabeth (Annie Potts), mistakes a black law student
for a waitress; the black friend, Rene (Lorraine Toussaint),
accuses her of racism.
</P>
<P>
   The story is more compelling than usual, as Mary Elizabeth
researches her family's racist past, including an uncle who is a Ku
Klux Klan member. But the special also reveals what is typically
best and worst about the series. Its strongest scenes are often the
flashbacks to the 1960s, when the innocent girls were learning
about color from their parents and society.
</P>
<P>
   The weakest element is the show's tendency to deliver canned
speeches about race. Ms. Potts sputters through them; Ms. Toussaint
brings a more natural delivery to hers. As Sunday's show proves,
``Any Day Now'' recognizes the subtle way that racism continues to
invade even the most open minds, black and white. And as the series
proves, good intentions do not automatically make for good drama.
</P>
<P>
   The show will be followed at 10 by a town hall meeting produced
by ABC News with Cokie Roberts and Deborah Roberts as anchors. That
program, not yet taped, has a noble but cliched title that sounds
like a real-life version of ``Any Day Now'': ``I'm Not a Racist but
... Small Steps Toward Healing the Hate.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `VANITY FAIR' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;E, Sunday night at 8 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Part 2, Monday night at 8) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by Andrew Davies based on the novel by William
Makepeace Thackeray. Marc Munden, director; Gillian McNeill,
producer. Michael Wearing and Suzan Harrison, executive producers
for BBC; Delia Fine, executive producer for A&AMP;E. An A&AMP;E/BBC
co-production. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Natasha Little (Becky Sharp), Frances Grey (Amelia
Sedley), Jeremy Swift (Jos Sedley), Tom Ward (George Osborne),
Philip Glenister (William Dobbin), Nathaniel Parker (Rawdon
Crawley), David Ross (John Sedley), Michele Dotrice (Mrs. Sedley),
David Bradley (Sir Pitt Crawley), Anton Lesser (Pitt Crawley),
Miriam Margolyes (Miss Crawley). &QL;
</P>
