<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEADS CONVEY SENSE OF HISTORY ACROSS THE AGES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Diamonds may be a girl's best friend, but beads are for
everybody. Their appeal is ancient, universal and primal.
</P>
<P>
   This much is evident in ``A Beaded Universe: Strands of
Culture,'' an exhibition that opened Thursday at the American Craft
Museum in New York. The show begins with a time line illustrating
that beads go back 40,000 years; then it documents this history
with displays of exceptional pieces on three floors.
</P>
<P>
   Elaborate beadwork and garments from every continent fill the
galleries. From the Yoruba culture in Nigeria there is a
magnificent eight-foot-wide priest's robe decorated with beads;
from South Africa there is a colorful Ndebele beaded wedding
costume and a Zulu apron with rows of memory beads. From Asia come
a pair of Indonesian wooden baby carriers covered in cowrie shells
and a Tibetan turquoise and coral neck collar.
</P>
<P>
   Some European beadwork will be less familiar. One of the
flashiest pieces is a Czech wedding bonnet with beads, sparkles and
sequins that were meant to keep away evil spirits. There are also
European purses that were beaded with motifs from Oriental carpets.
</P>
<P>
   From Japan there is a large collection of carved beads called
ojime, which were used to fasten the thongs on small bags. They are
made in the shapes of animals, monsters, even babies, in carved
coral, ivory and bamboo.
</P>
<P>
   North America is represented by a Navajo deerskin dress with
beaded tassels that comes from the Plains and a 1920s beaded
flapper dress that represents urban life at its most sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   The beadwork objects are on loan from the Bead Museum of
Glendale, Ariz., several private collectors and the Mingei
International Museum in San Diego, where this exhibition began.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tremendous fascination with beads, said Martha
Longenecker, the Mingei curator who organized the show. ``They are
tactile and warm. They endure. They are the ultimate recyclable
material; they get combined and recombined, like DNA. Beads are the
smallest portable object.''
</P>
<P>
   Beads can be made of any material: bone, wood, shell, amber,
turquoise, coral, pearl and metal. As Holly Hotchner, the director
of the Craft Museum, put it: ``A bead is anything with a hole in
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mingei/Craft Museum show came about as a result of Ms.
Longenecker's reading of Lois Sherr Dubin's comprehensive book,
``The History of Beads: From 30,000 BC to the Present'' (Harry N.
Abrams, 1987). Ms. Dubin, who is a landscape architect, said in an
interview that she became fascinated with beads as a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I am attracted to is the power of a rounded, shiny form
that you can wear and it makes you feel good,'' she said. ``The
connection is primal.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dubin began collecting beads when her work as a landscape
architect began to take her all over the world _ and she has never
stopped. ``For me, having quality, craftsmanship and design all in
one thing you can wear _ a string of beads _ is as good as it
gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dubin spent more than a decade researching and writing her
book, which has now been published in an abridged form. She said
that Abrams has sold more than 100,000 copies of the original work.
</P>
<P>
   Beads have always served many purposes beyond just decorating
their wearer. ``In ancient Asia, beads were scattered like seed
beneath temples, to induce bountiful harvests,'' Ms. Dubin said. In
the book she explained that beads were worn to commemorate status,
bind marriages, and protect the wearer against malevolence; they
were also a medium of exchange or barter. ``They've probably been
made and used by every culture in the world,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Over the millennia beads have tended to follow routes of trade
and conquest. Ms. Dubin tracked turquoise, agate and coral in the
Near East in 6500 BC, and lapis lazuli in Sumeria in the fourth
millennium. The Egyptians, famously accomplished jewelers, made
beads of amethyst, gold, carnelian and lapis. They in turn inspired
the Romans, who manufactured and traded glass beads on a global
scale.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dubin was imaginative in her research. When she wanted to
find examples of how the Byzantines wore their beads in the sixth
century, she studied the mosaics in the Church of San Vitale in
Ravenna, Italy. The mosaic walls there, from 547, boast full-length
portraits of Emperor Justinian and his wife, Empress Theodora. The
empress is wearing pearls, emeralds and sapphires in her tiara,
collar, necklace and earrings. Since the only Byzantines permitted
to don jewels were members of the Imperial Court, the Ravenna
mosaics are like a snapshot of the splendor of imperial authority.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dubin also devoted chapters to tracing the trade routes of
Venetian glass beads, which made their way to Asia, India, the
American colonies and Africa _ where they were traded for 1,000
percent of their value. Each culture adopted the beads but used
them in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   In the Middle Ages, when many Europeans considered wearing
jewelry to be pagan, rosaries were embraced. ``Healing powers have
been attributed to rosaries, as well as power to exorcise evil
spirits and ward off lightning,'' Ms. Dubin wrote. (She noted that
the Anglo-Saxon word bede means prayer.)
</P>
<P>
   Rosaries, of course, have been adopted by several religions:
Roman Catholicism, Buddhism, Hinduism and Islam. Buddhists, who
carved the wood of the fig tree to make prayer beads as early as
500 BC, employ 108 beads. Muslims use 99; Catholics, 150.
</P>
<P>
   In Tibet, Buddhist prayer beads called mala are made with disks
taken from the bones of a lama, or holy man. Ms. Dubin wrote that
the choice of human bone may be meant to impress upon the devotee
the transient nature of existence.
</P>
<P>
   This account notwithstanding, the historical section of the show
is cheerful and upbeat: a true reminder that beads do endure and
continue to change.
</P>
<P>
   David McFadden, senior curator of the Craft Museum, has
organized ``Beadz,'' a companion show at the museum, with 60
contemporary pieces of beaded artwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beads have come out of the handicraft closet,'' McFadden said,
``and it's the artists who are doing it. They like the idea of
complexity. Recent art has been so uninvolved with technique that
there's now a return to craft.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the beadwork in the show is meant to be worn. John
Eric Riis of Atlanta created a sculpture called ``Hands of the
Oracle,'' which is a gloved hand sheathed in hand-sewn pearls and
beads depicting the evil eye. Jan Yager made a bib called ``City
Flotsam.'' It is fashioned of crack vials that Ms. Yager picked up
on the streets of Los Angeles and turned into beads.
</P>
<P>
   Such works of art belong in a craft museum, Ms. Hotchner said.
``Our mission is to expand the definition of craft.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
