<SLUG> BC-TREK-LEONARD-NIMOY-OF-STAR-TREK-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RE-VULCANIZED: LEONARD NIMOY'S SPOCK DOUBLE FEATURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Leonard
Nimoy in a scene from ``Star Trek.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    You just can't keep a good Vulcan down.
 &HT;    ``Spock always seems to come back,'' Leonard Nimoy says,
laughing raucously. ``And you thought Bill Clinton was the comeback
kid.''
 &HT;    Trekkers who figured they'd seen the last of their green-blooded
hero are in for a treat, as Spock returns in material both fresh
and old.
 &HT;    On the fresh front, there's ``Spock Vs. Q,'' the long-awaited
Simon &AMP; Schuster audionovel version of an encounter between
``Trek's'' beacon of logic and its most impish alien raconteur,
played by John de Lancie, Nimoy's Alien Voices partner.
 &HT;    ``It's chaos vs. logic,'' Nimoy says by telephone from his Los
Angeles office. ``It just lends itself to that kind of wordplay. We
had a great time, John and I, and we had a conversation just this
morning about doing a sequel.
 &HT;    ``Radio-style acting gives you an opportunity to use acting
techniques that we don't get to use very often,'' he adds. ``We can
play multiple characters, create sounds, shift voices and also
change age, personality and ethnicity without heavy makeup or
disguises.
 &HT;    ``It's a very flexible form.''
 &HT;    Turning to the Spock of old, the pointy-eared one is all but
omnipresent on Paramount Home Video's DVD editions of the original
series. Volume IV, for example, features ``Charlie X'' and
``Balance of Terror,'' as well as their respective
original-broadcast preview trailers.
 &HT;    ``It's all back to the original quality and intent,'' Nimoy
says. ``It's really very, very good. They're digitized prints done
from the original negatives.''
 &HT;    Even when ``Trek'' kicked off nearly 34 years ago, Nimoy
acknowledges, nobody considered the show exactly a state-of-the-art
enterprise
 &HT;    ``The technology was pretty good, but I don't remember thinking
it was extraordinary,'' he says. ``What was special about the show
was the writing, the context, the subject matter, and not so much
the execution.
 &HT;    ```2001: A Space Odyssey' had extraordinary technology for its
time,'' Nimoy adds. ``We had to make a show on a weekly basis and
on a limited budget. Everybody knows that our sets looked like
cardboard.
 &HT;    ``If we did `Star Trek' today,'' he says, ``we'd have to have
today's technology. The audience's tastes have changed, and so have
their expectations. I don't think you could get away with not
having everything be state-of-the-art.
 &HT;    ``I'm not sure, though, even if everything were
state-of-the-art, that it would make any difference in the
watchability of the show or its impact.''
 &HT;    Beyond ``Star Trek'' tie-ins, Nimoy remains a busy man. He can
be heard on several television commercials, helped create an
educational pilot program designed to enable high-school students
to stage their own Alien Voices-style productions, is providing a
voice for Disney's upcoming animated feature ``Atlantis'' and has
displayed his photography at galleries in New York and Los Angeles.
 &HT;    Nonetheless, Nimoy says he doesn't care to run himself ragged
any more. He's 68 now, has money in the bank and a wife and
grandkids whose company he wishes to enjoy as often as possible.
 &HT;    That attitude was reinforced for Nimoy this past summer, when
his dear friend and ``Trek'' co-star DeForest Kelley passed away at
age 79.
 &HT;    ``I still remember vividly the days when we were making the
original series and there would be squabbles between Bill Shatner
and I,'' Nimoy says softly. ``We were like two hotheaded young
brothers who were very caring about each other and very
competitive. De would very calmly be in the middle and listen to
both sides, and he gave us a chance to air out our arguments.
 &HT;    ``He was a very stabilizing force on the show,'' the actor says.
``De was great. He was a wonderful person.''
 &HT;    And Nimoy understands the impact of Kelley's death on ``Star
Trek'' and all who love it.
 &HT;    ``It means we're all mortal,'' he says. 
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Spock Vs. Q,'' consult the
Alien Voices Website at www.alienvoices.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
