</P>
<P>
   DELTA-BOSTON _ Delta Air Lines is in talks to build a new $400
million terminal at Boston's Logan Airport, where it wants to
consolidate its domestic operations and also establish direct
flights to Europe. Boston would become Delta's fourth
trans-Atlantic gateway, along with Atlanta, New York and
Cincinnati. Details of the plan may be disclosed at Delta's annual
meeting next week in Boston, but negotiations may not be moving
quickly enough for such an announcement. (Thurston, Atlnta
Journal-Constitution). 16.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-EARNINGS _ Coca-Cola Co., whose bottom line has been under
pressure for much of the year, is expected to release its earnings
on Oct. 21. (Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOHAWK-EARNINGS _ Mohawk Industries releases its earnings on
Oct. 21. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GAPAC-EARNINGS _ Georgia-Pacific Corp. releases its third
quarter earnings. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   CIGARS _ The cigar craze has burned itself out. Due to glossy
magazines like ``Cigar Connoisseur,'' which featured hot Hollywood
stars like Demi Moore and Sylvester Stallone smoking stogies,
cigars had enjoyed a trendy revival. But for 1999, analysts predict
a 10 percent fall in sales of premium cigars. Three cigar companies
_ JR Cigar Inc.; General Cigar Holdings and Dimon Inc., showed
quarterly revenues down significantly from the same period in 1998.
Holt's, another cigar company, saw its stock downgraded by
Prudential Bache. (Poe, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-CHEMICAL _ WASHINGTON _ Citing a new report that many
smaller chemical businesses have not prepared for possible year-end
computer disruptions, the chairmen of the Senate Y2K committee
asked federal emergency and environmental officals Thursday to
alert state and local governments to be ``especially vigilant.''
(Geewax).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
