A4232 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-GUNS22-COX     10-21 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-GUNS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Both sides of gun debate should seek lower death toll
 &HT;    By John Head
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ OK, all you worthies on the other side of the gun
debate. Let's agree on at least one thing. Let's agree to do
everything we can to end the toll that guns are taking on our
children.
</P>
<P>
   An editorial in The Atlanta Constitution on Thursday laid out
the arguments for taking reasonable steps to protect children from
guns, and it suggested what those steps should be. The editorial
included the names and faces of just a few of the Georgia
youngsters who have been killed by guns. How could anyone see that
gallery of tragedy and not want to prevent other families from
suffering such losses?
</P>
<P>
   Yet gun groups _ principally the National Rifle Association _
have repeatedly thwarted legislation that could save the lives of
children. State Sen. David Scott, an Atlanta Democrat, has
spearheaded the effort to pass such laws for years.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, defeat has not diminished his determination. Scott has
gone as far to invite the NRA to the table to help draft
legislation. But it has been to no avail. There have been times
when he thought he had convinced the organization not to oppose a
bill, only to have NRA lobbyists work to kill it. He has seen the
NRA fight his legislation in the Georgia Legislature after it had
given its blessing to similar bills in other states.
</P>
<P>
   I don't believe the NRA or individual gun owners want children
to die. As fervently as they believe in the Second Amendment, I
don't believe they would accept the deaths of the 4,000 children
who are killed by guns in this country each year as the price for
preserving the constitutional right to bear arms. But there are
times when the NRA and gun enthusiasts give the appearance of
valuing guns over children.
</P>
<P>
   It is fine to teach children about gun safety. But children are
children, and they and their friends don't have the judgment to
always follow the rules for handling such a lethal object. There
are hundreds of ways adults try to protect children from
themselves. We require drug companies to put potentially harmful
medicines in child-proof packages. But the Georgia Legislature
won't mandate child-proof guns by requiring that they all have
trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   When a law is proposed to hold adults accountable for leaving
guns where children can find them and injure or kill themselves or
others, the gun lobby talks about infringing on the rights of
responsible gun owners. But why lump responsible gun owners with
the irresponsible? The law wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   The argument that makes the least sense to me is the one that
says legislation forcing people to put trigger locks on guns and
store them unloaded in a place that's inaccessible to children
would only make families less safe. Supposedly, those steps make it
impossible to use the gun against an intruder in the house.
</P>
<P>
   But statistics show that a gun brings greater danger into the
home, not safety. The chances that the gun will be used in domestic
violence, in a suicide or result in the accidental death of a child
are far greater than the chance it will be used to ward off an
intruder.
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse _ and it's mostly for worse _ the gun is
well established in American society. That there is some degree of
constitutional protection of the right to own guns is undeniable.
Most people who want to have guns are going to have them.
</P>
<P>
   But even those circumstances don't mean we have to tolerate
levels of negligence by manufacturers and irresponsibility by gun
owners that result in the needless deaths of 4,000 children a year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
