<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOOTEN-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Regulatory-agency bureaucrats can wield unrestrained power
 &HT;    By Jim Wooten
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you long for unrestrained power in a democracy,
start taking notes now.
</P>
<P>
   You can be a governor. Nice house, car with driver, suck-ups
galore.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can be filthy rich and create foundations. Those monetize
your values and execute your personal agenda and do it with
respectability. Thereafter, you can influence government, the
public and the media without drawing critical examination. A
foundation is a way to wash political money.
</P>
<P>
   A group called the ``Georgia Airkeepers Campaign,'' for example,
lists among its members a grab-bag assortment of nonrevealing
gibberish names, such as the Southern Organizing Committee for
Economic and Social Justice, and among its funding sources
``private foundation donations.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless you know the political agenda and composition of the
groups and the political agenda of the foundations, you really
shouldn't take them or their ``research studies'' too seriously.
Nor should you read the phrase ``nonprofit'' or ``nonpartisan'' to
mean ``unbiased'' or without a point of view. All that means is
that they're trying to hide their bias.
</P>
<P>
   The third route to unrestrained power is to become a
regulatory-agency bureaucrat. This is the wallflower's path. You
don't have to subject your opinions to public scrutiny, where the
really wacky ones get slaughtered. The power to write the regs is
the power to implement an agenda.
</P>
<P>
   An example, a small one, of the power of the unexamined
bureaucrat is an exercise now under way in Washington to redefine
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Under a new formula being considered by the White House Office
of Management and Budget, a family of four would be poor if their
annual income is less than $19,500 per year. The current level is
$16,500.
</P>
<P>
   With a stroke of the pen, the number of people defined as poor
would jump from 12.7 percent of the population to 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, the effort makes sense. Numbers that automatically
trigger some program or activity, whether the poverty definition
for benefits or the income tax burden, should be adjusted to
reflect inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But it does bear watching. As we've discovered, the power to
establish regulatory and program-triggering thresholds is an
enormous lever for those with an undeclared agenda.
</P>
<P>
   When the Environmental Protection Agency sets air and water
standards, for example, it represents an extraordinary power to
divert resources to its agenda to the exclusion of other worthwhile
needs. When the civil rights division of the Justice Department
interprets the Voting Rights Act to require a specified number of
minority-controlled districts, for example, it is dictating
outcome, usurping the power of elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   In all of these, bureaucrats who are really accountable to
nobody, and who are rarely even called on to justify their
reasoning, steal the power of elected officals _ often with the
concurrence of other elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   So a simple thing _ adjusting numbers to reflect current reality
_ can represent enormous power for those with unexamined agendas.
Ever wonder why it's impossible to kill off federal programs, even
after documenting that they don't work or that the need is not
there? The reason is that poverty supports a middle-class
management industry that prospers by constructing programs to serve
the ``poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Adjust the numbers, therefore, and the poverty-managing industry
is able to project the myth that only the rich are benefiting from
a good economy. The programs they design and administer, ergo, are
needed now more than ever. After all, 17 percent of Americans may
now be living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
