<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-MATCHUPS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL MATCHUPS FOR WEEK 7 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; GAME OF THE WEEK (1 P.M. SUNDAY) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Washington (4-1) at Dallas (3-2), 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   It will be only a matter of time before Dallas players start
complaining about what is now a struggling offense. Coach Chan
Gailey employs too many passing routes that go 5 yards downfield,
or asks running back Emmitt Smith to run outside when everyone
knows he no longer has the speed to do so. They are in trouble. And
the Redskins, losers to the Cowboys earlier in the season, have
been quietly talking about revenge all week. Dallas has won three
straight games against Washington. That streak ends this week.
</P>
<P>
   Redskins, 38-28
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY, 1 P.M. GAMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Chicago (3-3) at Tampa Bay (2-3)
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay has won five of its last seven home games against the
Bears, including the last three. That streak will continue. The
rookie quarterback Cade McNown gets the start for Chicago, and he
will quickly be reminded by a top Buccaneers defense that he is not
at UCLA anymore. Enis can expect to get at least 25 carries to keep
the pressure off, but McNown should expect a few visits from Warren
Sapp. Trent Dilfer update: He's still terrible.
</P>
<P>
   Buccaneers, 20-14
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati (1-5) at Indianapolis (3-2)
</P>
<P>
   What the Colts have lacked is a killer instinct; the common
refrain around the league is that they do not know how to close out
a game. That changed last week when Indianapolis was able to stop
the Jets and win the game. In that contest the young Colts grew up.
These games are usually close _ five of the last seven meetings
between the two teams have been decided by 7 points or fewer _ but
this game will not be. Indianapolis now knows how to win, which
means it will not lose to one of the worst teams in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Colts, 35-14
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland (0-6) at St. Louis (5-0)
</P>
<P>
   The league is still waiting for the Rams to fall. They will have
to keep waiting at least one more week. The Browns are trying _
they are losing by fewer points a game than they were earlier in
the season _ but their defense is no match for this scary St. Louis
offense. The Rams will be 6-0 for the first time since 1985.
Quarterback Kurt Warner's completion percentage leads the league;
the highest for a season is 70.55 by Ken Anderson. That's how
topsy-turvy the league is _ a former arena league player is
suddenly Joe Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Rams, 40-17
</P>
<P>
   Denver (2-4) at New England (4-2)
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the more crucial games of the week. The Broncos
plastered Green Bay last Sunday by 31-10. It may be that
quarterback Brian Griese is finally showing the skill that Shanahan
believed he has always had. Meanwhile the wheels are falling off
the Patriots, and people are quickly jumping from the bandwagon.
Last week's horrible loss to Miami is lingering like a bad meal.
New England still has not recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Broncos, 25-24
</P>
<P>
   Detroit (3-2) at Carolina (2-3)
</P>
<P>
   Carolina has won two of the its last three games and is starting
to gain some momentum. The reasons are quarterback Steve Beuerlein
and running back Tim Biakabutuka. The steady veteran passer has a
sharp 87.5 rating and Biakabutuka has rushed for 449 yards, second
in the conference. Carolina should have a good day against a Lions
defense that gives up 322 yards a game and against a battered
Charlie Batch, the much-pounded Detroit quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Panthers, 29-21
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans (1-4) at Giants (3-3)
</P>
<P>
   The Giants will be in the playoff chase all season, winning a
game here, losing a game there. After every victory like the one
against Dallas on Monday night, there will come a loss like the one
they will experience against New Orleans. The Giants are just that
kind of team. New York has the conference's third-ranked rushing
defense, so don't expect Ricky Williams to break loose. But the
Saints will have just enough offense to get by.
</P>
<P>
   Saints, 10-9
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia (2-4) at Miami (4-1)
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles may have beaten the Cowboys this season, but in light
of Dallas' offensive problems, that is not so impressive anymore.
Miami should win this one easily. The Dolphins have won 8 of their
last 10 home games and are 4-0 against Philadelphia, and Coach
Jimmy Johnson has won four of his last five against the Eagles.
Quarterback Dan Marino is questionable because of bone spurs in his
neck and a shoulder injury; Damon Huard probably gets the start.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins, 35-17
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco (3-3) at Minnesota (2-4)
</P>
<P>
   Vikings Coach Denny Green's decision to start the backup
quarterback Jeff George this week was a smart one. Randall
Cunningham, the best thrower in the league last year, was shot.
George may have cobwebs in the cranium at times, but his arm
strength and quick decisions under pressure _ especially when a
team blitzes _ will do the Minnesota offense wonders. This will be
a game when Randy Moss makes three touchdown catches against a
49ers defense that in the last three games has given up 22 plays of
20 or more yards. Steve Young sits this one out with a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   Vikings, 28-21
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY, 4 P.M. GAMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay (3-2) at San Diego (4-1)
</P>
<P>
   Mike Riley seeks to become the first head coach to open his
Chargers career with victories in five of six games. Riley is
riding his defense, which has not allowed a 100-yard rusher in 24
games. The defense has also allowed an NFL-low nine trips into the
red zone. The Packers have not seen a defense like this in years,
and quarterback Brett Favre will surely be bounced around. The
Packers must hope the injured thumb on his throwing hand stays
fairly stable.
</P>
<P>
   Chargers, 14-12
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo (4-2) at Seattle (3-2)
</P>
<P>
   Some teams are able to figure out Flutie and shut him down. A
team with an athletic front four can keep up with the Buffalo
quarterback, and that is why the Oakland Raiders beat the Bills
last week. Seattle has a similar front in defensive linemen Riddick
Parker (a sack in each of the last two games), Michael Sinclair and
Cortez Kennedy. Flutie will again be scrambling for his life.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks, 20-17
</P>
<P>
   Jets (1-5) at Oakland (3-3)
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are a disaster and Coach Bill Parcells is partially to
blame. By trading for Rick Mirer, he made a major tactical error,
because Mirer is the worst quarterback in New York since Tommy
Maddox. On 34 third-down opportunities this season, Mirer has
thrown three interceptions for a quarterback rating of 7.2. That's
single digits. With him at the helm, the Jets may not win another
game. Oakland's Tyrone Wheatley is tied with Jacksonville's James
Stewart for the AFC lead with five rushing touchdowns. The former
Giant is motivated to run over anything with New York in its name.
</P>
<P>
   Raiders, 30-10
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONDAY NIGHT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta (1-5) at Pittsburgh (3-3)
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are done as a playoff team, stuck in the dreary role
of spoiler. The Steelers, despite their offensive woes, can still
be a factor. Quarterback Kordell Stewart is struggling with just a
68.3 passer rating, but running back Jerome Bettis is starting to
get back on track. The Falcons' defense will put up little
resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Steelers, 17-9
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPEN: Arizona, Jacksonville, Tennessee &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
