<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4244 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-Y2K-CHEMICAL22-COX     10-21 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-CHEMICAL22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OFFICIALS URGE PLANNING FOR Y2K CHEMICAL ACCIDENTS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The overwhelming majority of small- and
medium-sized chemical plants are so unprepared to deal with the Y2K
computer bug that state and local emergency workers should
immediately begin ``contingency planning'' for accidents, the
Senate Special Committee on Y2K announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is running out,'' said Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.,
vice chairman of the committee. ``Developing viable Y2K contingency
plans in conjunction with state and local officials must be a top
priority in the chemical industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee cited a study conducted by Texas A&AMP;M University
researchers, who found that 86.5 percent of chemical companies
surveyed in Texas, New Jersey, Kansas and California ``weren't
prepared'' for Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K bug is a programming flaw that could cause older
computers and chips embedded in equipment to misread dates
beginning with Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   That seemingly small glitch could create big problems in plants
where the flow of hazardous chemicals is regulated by computerized
equipment. If the bug causes machinery to malfunction, dangerous
gases or liquids could be released.
</P>
<P>
   With about 85 million Americans living within five miles of one
of the nation's 66,000 work sites that make or use chemicals, many
people should be prepared to evacuate their homes in case of
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the probability of a Y2K-related disruption is low, the
potential harm even one chemical accident can cause means we must
be especially vigilant,'' Dodd said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Dodd and Sen. Bob Bennett, R-Utah, who chairs the Senate
committee, urged the Federal Emergency Management Agency and
Environmental Protection Agency to put state and local emergency
managers on alert.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas A&AMP;M survey results were characterized as ``grave'' by
Gerald Poje, a member of the U.S. Chemical Safety and Hazard
Investigation Board. He believes local fire chiefs should begin
``knocking on doors'' at chemical plants to get answers about
possible Y2K-related hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Poje says that fixing Y2K problems in the chemical sector is
difficult because the plants are so ``heterogenous'' compared with
other industries. For example, the electric power industry is
united by trade associations, connections on the power grid and
similarity of operations. Those links make it easier for industry
officials to share information and solve Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   But chemical plants are diverse, with some handling fluids,
others producing gases and still other using manufacturing solids
such as fertilizers. Indeed, many firms don't even call themselves
``chemical'' companies, even though they handle huge amounts of
chemicals. Paper mills are good examples, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When all of the plants that handle dangerous chemicals are added
up, the numbers run into the hundreds of thousands, he said. Even
if only a small percentage have problems, the consequences could be
great.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas study posed the question to chemical plant operators:
``What is the worst thing that could happen if you had a Y2K
failure?'' While nearly half of respondents said nothing of
consequence would occur, 4.1 percent saw the ``potential for a
catastrophic event.''
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Y2K and Society, a Washington-based nonprofit
group, urged the federal government to order a ``safety holiday''
for the chemical industry over New Year's Eve weekend. But Poje
said a shutdown would not necessarily solve problems, because some
plants become more dangerous when they interrupt continuous
operations and then try to restart. He believes each plant manager
should make his own determination about operating on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   But given that not every plant manager will make the right call,
local emergency officials should prepare for possible accidents, he
said. ``There is an urgent need for people to take this
seriously,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
