<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4248 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     10-21 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S POLITICALLY INCORRECT AND JUST PLAIN INCORRECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seemed to me I'd heard that refrain before.
</P>
<P>
   The political science professor delivered a broadside against
those whose world views incline toward the left for attempting to
curtail First Amendment rights and stifling public debate in both
academia and the real world.
</P>
<P>
   Waxing very righteously indignant, he stopped just short of
equating so-called political correctness, in his view an
abomination from the left, with the McCarthyism of the '50s. And he
suggested that the most dynamic political thinking in the country
today is coming from the right.
</P>
<P>
   That professor is widely viewed as a liberal, although some of
his published writings of late suggest otherwise. His recent strong
expression of support for school vouchers, for example, evidences a
right-ward drift.
</P>
<P>
   The professor delivered his slap at the American left during a
panel discussion last week of so-called ``political correctness''
at Tarrant County College's Arlington campus.
</P>
<P>
   He was, I presumed at first, just playing devil's advocate and
attempting to live up to his image as an equal opportunity
iconoclast. If that were the case, he played that role too well.
The professor made it appear that he thought he was displaying
considerable intestinal fortitude by accusing the left of poisoning
the well of public discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it doesn't take much in the way of political courage
to exalt the right and castigate the left deep in the heart of
politically conservative Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it did seem to me I'd heard that song before. Either
the professor had read and remembered a column that Paul Greenberg,
a former liberal of sorts, wrote back in April or another instance
of above average minds running in similar veins had occurred.
</P>
<P>
   In that column, the Arkansas curmudgeon, one of the nation's
most prolific Bill Clinton bashers, let fly a quiver of
porcupine-sharp barbs against contemporary liberals, all introduced
with the refrain, ``The trouble with the left. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg commenced his repetitive and often self-contradictory
diatribe with the silly (there is no politically correct way to
describe it) assertion: ``The trouble with the left is that it has
fallen out of love with freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arkansas pundit appeared to be much troubled by the efforts
of liberals to promote equal opportunity and verbal respect among
the diverse demographic elements of America's peoples.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trouble with the left is that it has come to believe in
privileged classes based on sex, race and class. ... The trouble
with the left is that it has confused fairness with political
correctness, and dialogue with rigged conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   It is, of course, Greenberg's First Amendment right to oppose
affirmative action and the various euphemisms now in vogue for
differentiating among people on the basis of race, sex, national
origin or sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, those on the troubled left also have the
constitutional right to characterize his views as intolerant,
insensitive and perhaps hypocritical.
</P>
<P>
   And that was the crux of the problem I had with the political
science professor's assertions about political correctness, liberal
oppression and the new interesting concepts coming from the right.
</P>
<P>
   The professor appeared to be saying that public discussion and
the learning atmosphere in academia could be enhanced if people
felt free to say anything they wish in any way they wish without
regard to any standards of civility.
</P>
<P>
   I submit that far more harm than good would accrue if people
went around hurling stereotypical and hurtful racial, sexual and
lifestyle adjectives at each other. Certainly the level of violence
would increase. It is possible to hold productive and heated debate
without sinking to such lows.
</P>
<P>
   The professor insisted, however, that he was more concerned
about the suppression of unpopular views. And that would be
something he should be concerned about were it happening to a
significant degree. But criticism, even scathing ridicule which is
the province of the right, is not suppression.
</P>
<P>
   One can still say anything one wishes in this country,
especially on talk radio, without fear of governmental retaliation.
And a really good teacher can find ways to stimulate debate among
students that remain within the bounds of civility.
</P>
<P>
   What most troubled me, of course, was the professor's
characterization of the right as the direction from which the most
stimulating new thought is coming today. In light of the
neo-isolationism, neo-sexism, neo-racism, neo-classism and
neo-fundamentalism emanating from the right, such an assertion is
not just politically incorrect, it's factually incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1748EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
