<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON WHAT'S NEW IN HOME VIDEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   See the U.S.A. In a Chevrolet &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like a nice copy to show my kids,'' said Monte Hellman,
the director of ``Two-Lane Blacktop.'' This week he got one when
Anchor Bay released that classic 1971 road film, starring James
Taylor, Warren Oates, Dennis Wilson and Laurie Bird, on tape and
DVD. Either way is fine with Hellman; the movie has never been on
video. But DVD is better, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On disk, ``they take pains to make it look as close to the way
it did as possible,'' he said. In the wide-screen format, the image
is flattened to its original rectangular proportions, allowing
figures lopped off for television back into the action.
</P>
<P>
   That's an advantage to any film, of course, but especially one
about a road race that takes off across the country. And there are
other ways DVD lends authenticity to a film half jokingly referred
to as the only existential allegory ever made for a studio.
</P>
<P>
   Hellman made the movie for Universal, but years later there was
trouble over video. Repairing to a closet-size room in the London
office of Gary Kurtz, the film's associate producer, Hellman and
Kurtz watched the film on a small television screen while they told
the story for a commentary track on the DVD.
</P>
<P>
   About five years ago, Hellman said, he was invited by Scarecrow
Video, a Seattle company, to show the film there. Astounded that
the movie wasn't on video, Scarecrow and other fans began a
petition. Hellman himself had been trying to find out why it wasn't
on tape. ``We never got a straight answer from Universal,'' he says
in the disk commentary.
</P>
<P>
   One problem was securing music rights for songs like ``Moonlight
Ride'' by the Doors and ``Satisfaction'' by the Rolling Stones.
Universal finally was of some help, but the task was carried
through by Anchor Bay, which could have substituted lesser-known
selections but stayed true to the original.
</P>
<P>
   Authenticity, laconic and haunting, is vital to every aspect of
the film, and the reflective, low-key commentary only adds to an
indelible sense of it. At the wheel of a hopped-up 1955 Chevrolet,
the Driver ( Taylor) challenges GTO ( Oates, who earned an Oscar
nomination) to a race. A good old boy, GTO is named for his
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The Driver is aided by the Mechanic ( Wilson of the Beach Boys).
Normally they roam Western tank towns taking money from the locals
at clandestine drag races. The race with GTO will be a long one,
all the way to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Along for the ride, as long as her whim dictates, is the Girl
(Ms. Bird). ``She doesn't seem to be breathing right,'' says the
Mechanic at one point. He means the Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   Made for $875,000, ``Two-Lane Blacktop'' cuts with aching
poignancy through forlorn towns of the late '60s and early '70s.
Bit players _ police officers, shopkeepers, filling-station
operators, boys playing baseball _ were ordinary citizens recruited
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor wasn't famous yet. ``He had his first hit, `Fire and
Rain,' when we were on location,'' Hellman said. Now films need
name actors to get made, but they didn't then. ``They just wanted
people who were right for the movie,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Blair Witch Project &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Definitely the camping trip of the summer, Daniel Myrick and
Eduardo Sanchez's pseudo-documentary, made in eight days with no
script, sends three film students into the Maryland woods in search
of legendary evil. Later the video they shot turns up as the sole
survivor.
</P>
<P>
   Lost and frozen, Heather, Josh and Mike stumble through the
woods in a steadily escalating state of confusion and panic as they
begin to realize they are inescapably in the hands of they know not
what. Operating on the tightest of budgets, Myrick and Sanchez,
students themselves not long ago, turn spareness to their advantage
by extracting the utmost menace from rocks and twigs gathered into
fetishlike harbingers of approaching doom. By the end, horror has a
new face in a film, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times,
``whose scrappy home-movie style is completely, even ingeniously,
appropriate.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Artisan. $22.98. 87 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release
date: Oct. 26. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Life &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Packing Eddie Murphy and Martin Lawrence off to a Mississippi
prison where they trade quips while doing hard labor may not sound
like an idea headed much of anywhere. But over 60 years Ray (
Murphy) and Claude ( Lawrence) develop a curmudgeonly feel for each
other, flashing back to the days when the two went on a bootlegging
mission and encountered racism.
</P>
<P>
   Evolving affectingly from a fast-talking hotshot into an old man
with the growl of venerable blues singer, Murphy ``seems to be
reaching for a greater opportunity than this lightweight material
can offer'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Universal. $107.37. 100 minutes. Closed captioned. R. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Never Been Kissed &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not enough of an abused jerk when she was in high school, Josie
Geller (Drew Barrymore) goes back to repeat the whole miserable
experience as a 25-year undercover reporter doing an article on
high school youth. The same old geek, Josie has better luck this
time, but Ms. Barrymore barely survives a film ``so hopelessly
cartoonish and wrongheaded in its details that there's not even a
semblance of reality for her to grab on to'' (Stephen Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Fox. $107.37. 107 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: Tuesday. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Metroland &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A male counterpart to Pearl in ``A Walk on the Moon,'' Chris
(Christian Bale) wonders why he settled down so early. ``You're not
original enough not to,'' says his wife Marion (Emily Watson).
Chris did try the artist's life in the Paris of 1968, but now it's
London in the '70s, and he can only envy his friend Toni (Lee
Ross), who writes poetry and roams the world.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Saville's film is plausible as a cri de coeur from a
trapped young husband, but ``its affectations are more galling than
Gallic most of the time'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Universal. $99.36. 105 minutes. Closed captioned. R. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE L.B.J. TAPES: THE JOHNSON WHITE HOUSE TAPES. Yes, L.B.J.
bugged phones and kept tape recorders whirring, too, and here are
some excerpts authorized by the Johnson estate and broadcast on the
History and Discovery Channels. Volume I, ``Hello, Mr. President,''
traces the Johnson taping practice back to when he took office
immediately after the assassination of John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Other cassettes focus on Johnson's relations with Robert F.
Kennedy, his conduct of the Vietnam War and his dealings with J.
Edgar Hoover and Martin Luther King Jr., and his drive to secure
passage of the 1964 civil rights bill. 1999. White Star. Four
cassettes, $69.95 for the set or $19.95 each. 60 minutes each.
Information: (800) 573-3782.
</P>
<P>
   GADJO DILO. This is the third film of Tony Gatlif's Gypsy
trilogy. (In 1994 he directed ``Latcho Drom,'' a kind of Gypsy
musical travelogue, and in 1997 he made ``Mondo,'' about a homeless
Gypsy boy in France.) In ``Gadjo Dillo'' (``Crazy Outsider'' in the
Gypsies' Romany language) a sophisticated Parisian named Stephane
(Romain Duris) ends up in a Gypsy household and with a Gypsy woman
on his quest to record his dead father's favorite singer. 1998. New
Yorker. $89.98. 97 minutes. French, Romanian and Romany with
English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   AND BABY MAKES TWO. Judy Katz and Oren Rudavsky's documentary
follows what eight New York women go through to have a child on
their own. 1999. First Run Features. $29.95. 60 minutes. No rating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
