<P>
   SNIFFER-WASHINGTON _ Officials of Barringer Technologies
demonstrate a hand-held device that they say can detect explosives,
narcotics and chemical weapon agents ``as small as on one-hundredth
the size of a grain of salt'' within seconds. (Hill, Cox News
Service). 14.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   GUNNISON-PARK _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton signs a bill
Thursday making the Black Canyon of the Gunnison River in Colorado
a national park. (Hill, Cox News Service). 16.
</P>
<P>
   FORWARD-FUNDING _ WASHINGTON _ Scrambling to get out of the
budget squeeze without drawing on Social Security, Congress is
borrowing from next year's expected surpluses. Such ``forward
funding'' has been used before, but never like this year's $20
billion. What critics and defenders of the practice say. (Malone,
Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-POVERTY _ In a New York speech, Bill Bradley proposed
spending $10 billion on programs to eradicate child poverty in ten
years. Bradley also called for raising the minimum wage and
indexing annual increases to the nation's median wage. Bradley's
proposals came a day after Vice President Gore announced his own
initiatives to reduce child poverty. Bradley aides accuse Gore of
seeking to preempt Bradley with ``campaign tactics''. that are
short on substance. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-EDUCATION _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush has taken much of his
recently unveiled education plan from none other than president
Bill Clinton's education policy advisor, formerly with the
Progressive Policy Institute. We take a close look at the evolution
of Bush's education policy _ a window onto the thinking behind his
``triangulation,'' and an interesting study in the ways Bush and
Clinton are looking more and more alike. (Heath, Cox News Service).
20.
</P>
<P>
   GORE _ MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Going a step beyond current policy,
Vice President Al Gore pledged Thursday, if elected, to ban all new
offshore oil drilling in federal waters off the coast of Florida
and California. ``This coastline is too valuable to not take action
now,'' he said. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
