<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4257 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS21-     10-21 3046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of current movies
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray, Bob Longino and Jill
Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grades range from A to F.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Adventures of Elmo
</P>
<P>
   in Grouchland'' G
</P>
<P>
   Starring Elmo (voice by Kevin Clash), Mandy Patinkin and Vanessa
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   A kind of extended episode of ``Sesame Street,'' this movie is
recommended to the very, very, very young. Essentially, little Elmo
(voice by Kevin Clash) must go to Grouchland to rescue his blanket
from a meanie named Huxley (a hammy Mandy Patinkin). Vanessa
Williams appears as the Queen of Trash. Fill in your own joke.
(ERG) 1 hour, 10 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Africa's
</P>
<P>
   Elephant Kingdom'' Not rated
</P>
<P>
   A documentary
</P>
<P>
   It has some eye-poppingly large pachyderms, but it isn't as
visually astounding as ``Everest.'' Still, this Imax film has its
share of lovely images, including time-lapse shots of the sun
setting on the dusty horizon and a massive storm whirling across
the plain. (SM) 40 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Alaska: Spirit of the Wild'' Unrated
</P>
<P>
   Narrated by Charlton Heston.
</P>
<P>
   It's big, it's bold, it's big ... The sheer size of the latest
Imax offering sometimes makes it an eye-opening experience.
Otherwise, this visit to the far, brrr-cold reaches of our biggest
state is just another Discovery Channel-style nature flick. The
film spans millenniums _ and throws in bits and pieces about the
ice age, the Klondike Gold Rush, caribou hunting and bears. (Bob
Longino)40 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Alma'' Unrated
</P>
<P>
   Featuring Alma Thorpe,
</P>
<P>
   Margie Thorpe and James Thorpe.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmaker Ruth Leitman's provocative 1997 documentary of a
peculiar Atlanta family. It's a slow, mesmerizing march from
curious looks at the family's eccentricities to the spell-bounding
horror imbedded in their history. (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 34 minutes.
A-
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty'' R (strong sexuality, nudity, profanity,
</P>
<P>
   violence and drug content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kevin Spacey
</P>
<P>
   and Annette Bening.
</P>
<P>
   A beaut. The ever-more-remarkable Kevin Spacey leads a stellar
ensemble cast (Annette Bening, Thora Birch, Chris Cooper) in this
scarily disturbing, daringly hilarious comedy-drama in this fin de
siecle tragifarce centering on Spacey as a man caught in a midlife
limbo. The movie is a hauntingly optimistic elegy for America the
Beautifully Screwed Up. (ERG) 1 hour, 58 minutes. A
</P>
<P>
   ``Autumn Tale'' Not rated but the theme may be
</P>
<P>
   too mature for children.
</P>
<P>
   Starring Marie Riviere
</P>
<P>
   and Beatrice Romand.
</P>
<P>
   Magali (Beatrice Romand), a long-widowed Frenchwoman in her
mid-40s becomes the object of matchmaking by her longtime best
friend (Marie Riviere) and by the young woman (Alexia Portal) who's
dating Magali's son. The film is overflowing with generosity, humor
and insight, and master director Eric Rohmer, now almost 80,
imparts wisdom that's aged to perfection. Subtitles. (ERG)1 hour,
52 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Bats'' R (profanity and intense sequences
</P>
<P>
   of bat attacks)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Lou Diamond Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   You'd have to have bats in your belfry to enjoy this cheesy
horror flick about genetically altered, man-eating bats. For the
record, Lou Diamond Phillips is the fearless sheriff of the Texas
town where the bats have come to roost; Dina Meyer is a
bat-ologist; Leon is her assistant; and Bob Gunton is a shady
scientist. (ERG)1 hour, 30 minutes. D-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Best Man'' R (profanity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Taye Diggs,
</P>
<P>
   Nia Long and Morris Chestnut.
</P>
<P>
   Better than ``My Best Friend's Wedding.'' In Malcolm D. Lee's
often funny, sexy and prickly new comedy-drama, Taye Diggs heads a
talented ensemble cast in a glossy wedding film punctuated with
soul-stirring music (Bob Marley, Stevie Wonder, Me'Shell
Ndegeocello, Maxwell), flurries of flesh and real dramatic bite.
The ensemble cast is all good. (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 58 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Streak'' PG-13 (profanity, violence
</P>
<P>
   and crude humor)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Martin Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   A decent, disposable Martin Lawrence vehicle. He's a crook
posing as a cop to recover a $17 million diamond he stashed years
ago. Basically a series of quick skits, there's enough action
scenes to mollify audiences who can't get enough of gunfire and
breaking glass. While it doesn't exactly streak along, at 93
minutes ``Blue Streak'' gets the job done. (SM) 1 hour, 33 minutes.
C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Body Shots'' R (profanity, sexual content, violence,
</P>
<P>
   alcohol abuse)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sean Patrick Flanery,
</P>
<P>
   Jerry O'Connell and Amanda Peet.
</P>
<P>
   Here's proof positive that being twentysomething isn't pretty.
Eight party-hearty twentysomethings (including ``Scream 2's'' Jerry
O'Connell) traipse L.A. nightlife, get superdrunk and start having
rampant sex. The big question for two in the group: was it
consensual sex or rape? Quick, brutal and ugly, the movie may not
be any fun, but it sure delivers the dramatic goods. (Bob Longino)1
hour, 42 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys Don't Cry'' R (sex, profanity, nudity and violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Hilary Swank
</P>
<P>
   and Chloe Sevigny.
</P>
<P>
   This intense, rawly unsettling film is based on the true story
of Teena Brandon, a 21-year-old woman who fiercely believed she was
a man. She cut her hair short, reversed her name and started
hanging out with some hard-drinking rednecks in rural Nebraska. The
movie, a bit unrelenting, a bit too low-budget
rough-around-the-edges, is still a remarkable achievement and
Hilary Swank gives a stunning performance. (ERG)1 hour, 54 minutes.
B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Breakfast of Champions'' R (profanity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Bruce Willis.
</P>
<P>
   A well-intended film of Kurt Vonnegut Jr.'s satiric novel about
America's consumer society consuming itself. But it's largely a
misfire, possibly because its adapter and director, Alan Rudolph,
is better suited to mood pieces than to the madcap energies of
Vonnegut's barbed but humanistic farce. (Jay Carr, The Boston
Globe) 1 hour, 50 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Bringing Out the Dead'' R (profanity, violence and drug use)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Nicolas Cage
</P>
<P>
   and Patricia Arquette.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Scorsese offers a savage, sorrowing look at a few days in
the life of a paramedic whose beat is Hell's Kitchen. As played by
Nicolas Cage, he's alcoholic, burnt-out and haunted by the spirits
of those he couldn't save. A kinda romance with Patricia Arquette
doesn't work, but there's excellent work by John Goodman, Ving
Rhames and Tom Sizemore as Cage's various partners. (ERG) 2 hours,
1 minute. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Crazy in Alabama'' PG-13 (violence, thematic material,
</P>
<P>
   profanity, sensuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Melanie Griffith,
</P>
<P>
   David Morse and Lucas Black.
</P>
<P>
   An odd mix of civil rights drama and Southern Gothic comedy that
goes down just fine. The movie splits time between the wild
adventures of Lucille (Melanie Griffith), who breaks out of a small
Alabama town and heads West, and a graver story back home. Griffith
does her best work since ``Working Girl.'' Antonio Banderas'
direction throws off some sparks, even if it doesn't fully catch
fire. (SM)1 hour, 51 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dinner Game'' PG-13 (profanity and sexual innuendo)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Thierry Lhermitte
</P>
<P>
   and Jacques Villeret.
</P>
<P>
   A feast of foolishness. Snotty Paris yuppies hold a weekly
dinner to see who can bring the biggest idiot as a guest. Publisher
Thierry Lhermitte thinks he's got a sure thing when he meets
Jacques Villeret, who builds scale-model monuments out of
matchsticks. Fate intervenes when Lhermitte throws out his back and
is forced to spend the evening with Villeret who systematically
wrecks his life. (ERG)1 hour, 22 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Double Jeopardy'' R (profanity, sexuality, violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ashley Judd
</P>
<P>
   and Tommy Lee Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley Judd plays a woman out to wreak justice on the husband
who framed her for murder, and Tommy Lee Jones is the parole
officer on her trail in this action flick with a gender twist. For
better and for worse, the movie is as professional, efficient and
aloof as Judd's performance. (SM) 1 hour, 45 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Everest'' Not rated
</P>
<P>
   A documentary by David Breashears.
</P>
<P>
   Breathtaking. Even filmgoers accustomed to the five-story Imax
format may gasp at the unearthly scale of ``Everest.'' David
Breashears'
</P>
<P>
   documentary was filmed at the same time as the 1996 storm that
killed eight mountain climbers, memorialized by Jon Krakauer's
best-selling book ``Into Thin Air.'' (SM) 44 minutes. A
</P>
<P>
   ``Fight Club'' R (violent antisocial behavior, sexuality
</P>
<P>
   and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Edward Norton,
</P>
<P>
   Brad Pitt and Helena Bonham Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Bound to be this fall's most controversial studio release, the
Brad Pitt-Edward Norton flick will have as many people loathing it
as liking it. Either reaction is justifiable. The film, about a
pack of guys beating each other to bloody pulps, is violent,
nihilistic, intoxicated by its own bad-boy humor. But it's still
one of those rare films that creates an electrifying alternate
universe onscreen. (SM) 2 hours, 21 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``For Love of the Game'' PG-13 (sexual situations, profanity
</P>
<P>
   and drinking)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kevin Costner and Kelly Preston.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how hard it tries to hit, Kevin Costner's baseball
flick whiffs a lot. Costner plays Billy Chapel, a Detroit Tigers
pitching god in his waning years who first learns his team is being
sold and he'll be traded and then that his girlfriend is dumping
him. As he pitches what could be a perfect game, he flashes back
over his life. (Bob Longino) 2 hours, 18 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Guinevere'' R (profanity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Stephen Rea, Sarah Polley
</P>
<P>
   and Jean Smart.
</P>
<P>
   A college grad (Sarah Polley) moves in with a 50-ish bohemian
photographer (Stephen Rea) who's made a career out of introducing
much younger women to the joys of sex, Sartre, jazz, art, etc. But
what sounds like grist for a feminist diatribe against our
culture's wink-wink approval of such liaisons is actually a sweet,
rueful love letter. The writing and direction is sharp as a tack
and the acting is gorgeous. (ERG)1 hour, 47 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Happy, Texas'' PG-13 (profanity and sexual situations)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jeremy Northam,
</P>
<P>
   Steve Zahn and William H. Macy.
</P>
<P>
   C'mon get ``Happy.'' This sunny crowd-pleaser stars Jeremy
Northam and Steve Zahn as escaped convicts who hide out in a small
town by posing as a gay couple who stage beauty pageants for little
girls. A last-minute plot device is a bad idea, but by then the
picture has built up so much good will you can't help but go along.
The cast is excellent, especially William H. Macy as the sheriff.
(ERG)1 hour, 37 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Limey'' R (violence and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Terence Stamp
</P>
<P>
   and Peter Fonda.
</P>
<P>
   A Cockney ex-con (Terence Stamp) comes to L.A. to avenge the
supposedly accidental death of his daughter. He hones in on a slimy
record producer (Peter Fonda). Plotwise, this is a revenge movie,
but thematically, it's an off-beat meditation on the nature of
Hollywood, especially what's left of '60s Hollywood as it demands
attention from an increasingly disinterested '90s Hollywood. Both
stars are superb. (ERG)1 hour, 37 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``My Life So Far'' PG-13 (sexual content and nude pictures)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Colin Firth,
</P>
<P>
   Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio
</P>
<P>
   and Irene Jacob.
</P>
<P>
   If this story of a 10-year-old boy and his family had emotional
charge to match its gorgeous Scottish scenery, it could be a small
classic. But under the pretty-but-prim direction of Hugh Hudson
(``Chariots of Fire''), it's not much more than a twee highland
travelogue. (SM)1 hour, 33 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Omega Code'' PG-13 (several scenes of shootings)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Casper Van Dien,
</P>
<P>
   Michael York, Catherine Oxenberg
</P>
<P>
   and Michael Ironside.
</P>
<P>
   Michael York and Casper Van Dien star in this overly talkative
tale reminiscent of the book of Revelation. As wealthy businessman
Stone Alexander, York steals and uses a secret biblical code to
effect a world takeover. The hammy Van Dien plays Gillen Lane, a
glam gadabout and motivational leader who uncovers York's plot and
must act to save the globe. (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 39 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``Random Hearts'' R (violence, sexuality and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Harrison Ford
</P>
<P>
   and Kristin Scott Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   A meandering mystery/drama/romance that never hits the right
groove. Harrison Ford is a cop and Kristin Scott Thomas a
congresswoman who discover their spouses, both killed in a plane
crash, were having an affair. The stars' ensuing romance never taps
beneath the surface. (SM)2 hours, 11 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Romance'' Unrated, but there is sex, nudity,
</P>
<P>
   bondage and a rape.
</P>
<P>
   Starring Caroline Ducey.
</P>
<P>
   A dull little French film with an undeserved ``hot'' reputation.
Upset because her boyfriend has stopped having sex with her, Marie
(Caroline Ducey) starts having lots of sex. Rough sex,
indiscriminate sex, quickie sex. Even bondage sex with her boss who
takes about an hour to tie her up (guess they don't have Boy Scouts
in France). The movie is very explicit and absolutely unerotic. In
French with subtitles. (ERG) 1 hour, 36 minutes. D
</P>
<P>
   ``Siegfried &AMP; Roy:
</P>
<P>
   The Magic Box'' Not rated.
</P>
<P>
   Featuring Siegfried Fischbacher
</P>
<P>
   and Roy Uwe Ludwig Horn.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Cirque du Surreal. Siegfried and Roy _ those
hocus-pocus, Las Vegas glam guys _ star in this dumbfoundingly
watchable 3-D Imax that's girded like some weird Wagnerian opera.
Elephants disappear. Furry white tigers leap over your head. Giant
metal dragons spew fire. Obviously, the concept of garish didn't
die with Liberace. (Bob Longino)
</P>
<P>
   At Regal Imax Theatre at the Mall of Georgia near Buford. 51
minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sixth Sense'' PG-13 (intense thematic material
</P>
<P>
   and violent images)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Bruce Willis, Haley Joel Osment and Toni Collette.
</P>
<P>
   A surprising, spine-tingling gem. Eight-year-old Cole (Haley
Joel Osment) can see ghosts, not the Casper variety but restless
phantoms with their skulls blown open. It's a fascinating, odd film
that speculates on what the relationship between the restless dead
and a liaison to the living world might be. Plus, this film has the
best, and loveliest, last-act twist of the year. (SM) At metro
theaters. 1 hour, 47 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Stigmata'' R (profanity, sexuality, intense violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Patricia Arquette
</P>
<P>
   and Gabriel Byrne.
</P>
<P>
   Let it bleed without you. This mishmash of ``The Exorcist,''
``The Omen,'' etc. stars Gabriel Byrne as a Vatican investigator
sent to examine a young woman (Patricia Arquette) who's showing
signs of the stigmata, the wounds suffered by Christ on the cross.
Unfortunately, the movie prefers sensationalism to making sense.
It's enough to make you long for the good ol' days of pea soup and
spinning heads. (ERG)1 hour, 42 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Story of Us'' R (profanity and brief sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Bruce Willis
</P>
<P>
   and Michelle Pfeiffer.
</P>
<P>
   Director Rob Reiner's breezy, laugh a lot, cry a lot, big hankie
of a movie with Bruce Willis and Michelle Pfeiffer as a couple
wondering if they'll survive after 15 years of marriage. It's a
steady stream of sex jokes, butt jokes and guy and gal pals
dispensing weak-willed truisms. It may not be deep, but it is
entertaining. (Bob Longino)1 hour, 38 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Superstar'' PG-13 (sex-related humor and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Molly Shannon,
</P>
<P>
   Will Ferrell and Elaine Hendrix.
</P>
<P>
   Whaddya know _ a ``Saturday Night Live'' big-screen transfer
that doesn't bite. As the ebullient Catholic schoolgirl Mary
Katherine Gallagher, Molly Shannon delivers a memorable mix of
adolescent brazenness and self-mortification. It's clear Shannon
loves this character, but she's never afraid to push the envelope
of outrageousness, whether talking baby talk to her breasts, or
fantasizing that a tree is her lover. (SM) 1 hour, 22 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Thomas Crown Affair'' R (profanity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Pierce Brosnan and Rene Russo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Windmills of Your Mind'' is still on the soundtrack, but
lots of other gimmicks from the 1968 original have been excised.
That's good. This remake is a guilt-free summer diversion. Pierce
Brosnan is an appealing billionaire gentleman rogue, stealing
priceless paintings. But it's really Rene Russo's film. As the solo
investigator hot on his trail, she prowls the screen savoring a
smart, sexed-up character. (SM) 1 hour, 45 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Kings'' R (graphic war violence, profanity,
</P>
<P>
   sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring George Clooney,
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wahlberg and Ice Cube.
</P>
<P>
   George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg and Ice Cube play three U.S.
soldiers in the Persian Gulf War who go after Saddam Hussein's
stolen Kuwaiti gold. Their consciences are tested when they see
anti-Saddam civilians rounded up by Iraqi soldiers. While the
film's script cynically bashes George Bush's political stance, its
visuals pop with energy. (Bob Longino)1 hour, 51 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Three To Tango'' PG-13 (sex-related situations
</P>
<P>
   and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Matthew Perry,
</P>
<P>
   Neve Campbell
</P>
<P>
   and Dylan McDermott.
</P>
<P>
   A perfectly pleasant extended sitcom trumped up with TV stars
and begging for bellylaughs. Matthew Perry (``Friends'') headlines
this mostly slapstick, throwaway love story about Oscar Novack, a
heterosexual Chicago architect who everybody thinks is gay. The
comedy is mostly a physical joke: spastic running, tripping over
coat trees, accidental pokes in the crotch and just plain barfing.
(Bob Longino)1 hour, 38 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Wolves'' Not rated
</P>
<P>
   A documentary.
</P>
<P>
   Not as visually stunning as some Imax films, this is a highly
instructive look at the once nearly vanquished gray wolf's gradual
reintroduction to Yellowstone National Park and other parts of the
American West. Covers a bit too much ground, historically and
geographically; the best parts show wolves ranging from adult pack
leaders to newborn cubs exploring and adjusting to the wild again.
(Jill Vejnoska) 41 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray, Bob Longino and Jill
Vejnoska writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
