<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4258 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-BASQUE24-COX     10-21 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BASQUE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Exploring the saga of an often misunderstood people
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 24
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who sent the first Spanish astronaut into space? The Basques, of
course. Blew that sucker right over the top of a building.
</P>
<P>
   Adm. Luis Carrero Blanco wasn't a space pioneer, but the No. 2
honcho of fascist dictator Francisco Franco. His unfortunate
liftoff occurred Dec. 20, 1973. On his way to morning Mass, he
pulled his car into its usual spot and ignited a 165-pound stash of
dynamite planted by the Basque terrorist group known as the ETA. It
was the sort of crime that ensured the Basques would be enshrined
in the world psyche as a bunch of bloodthirsty, beret-wearing
hoodlums.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Mark Kurlansky's ``The Basque History of the World''
makes a persuasive case that the Basques are anything but rude,
crude and lewd. Speakers of Euskera, Europe's oldest living
language, an arcane mixture of k's and x's that some say was used
by Adam and Eve and others claim caused the clamor at Babel, this
mysterious, long-lobed clan has variously been described as Celts,
Etruscans, the lost tribe of Israel, survivors of Atlantis and
direct descendants of Tubal, Noah's grandson. The Basques built the
strongest ships and caught the most whales, so naturally their
salt-of-the-earth, saltwater tales make riveting reading. The
Basque mystique, c'est chic.
</P>
<P>
   But Kurlansky's prime concern is to correct the onerous
propaganda that has dogged this fascinating civilization. To this
end, Kurlansky _ whose ``Cod: A Biography of the Fish That Changed
the World'' won a James Beard Award last year _ succeeds
handsomely. A rich mix of mythos and reportage, history and
anecdote, literature and etymology, culinary lore and recipes, it
may be the most important English work on Iberia since Robert
Hughes' ``Barcelona.'' Rigorously researched and accessibly told,
this Food &AMP; Wine columnist's effort ought to do for the Basques
what the Time magazine art critic's long-winded art history did for
the Catalans. It's as de rigueur as a visit to the Basque-built
Guggenheim Museum in Bilbao was a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Basques seem to be a mythical people, almost an imagined
people,'' Kurlansky says in the opening pages. ``Their ancient
culture is filled with undated legends and customs. Their land
itself, a world of red-roofed, whitewashed towns, tough green
mountains, rocky crests, a cobalt sea that turns charcoal in stormy
weather, a strange language, and big berets, exists on no maps
except their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Smaller than New Hampshire, Basqueland consists of three French
and four Spanish provinces that straddle the Pyrenees. Spiritually,
it has been held together by nothing more than its agglutinating
language, which, even after a post-Franco renaissance, is spoken by
only about 1 million people. The word ``honcho,'' or jauntxo, by
the way, is one of the few Basque words that has seeped into
English.
</P>
<P>
   From pil pil to the espadrille, the Basque contribution has been
significant, albeit little known.
</P>
<P>
   Though most of us learned in the sixth grade that Magellan was
the first person to circumnavigate the globe, he was actually
killed in the Philippines, leaving Juan Sebastian de Elcano, a
Basque commander, to complete the journey in 1522. Perhaps the most
famous Basque was Ignatius Loyola, who founded the Jesuit order in
1534. During the age of discovery, the Basques were among the
earliest Europeans to reach the Americas and Asia. They were the
first whale hunters and the first Europeans to grow tobacco, and
from the Americas they brought corn, beans, chile peppers and
chocolate to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Kurlansky, who caught the Basque bug while working as a reporter
for the International Herald Tribune in the 1970s, writes with
brevity, elegance and vivid imagery (Basque singers have
``chocolaty basses''). Alas, there are a few minor bumps. His
defense of the Basques can be strident and one-sided. While the
Spanish were nothing if not hypocritical, the truth is that both
sides committed crimes. As a storyteller, he sometimes interrupts
the flow by placing the reader inside, say, a war survivor's home
without giving a signal that the scene has changed. But as a
culinary historian, he's nearly peerless.
</P>
<P>
   How delicious to discover that the salt cod dish known as pil
pil was the result of a telegraphic error. In 1836, a Bilbao
merchant ordered ``100 or 120 top-quality salt cod,'' but it came
out on the other end as ``1,000,120.'' Yipes! With so much cod,
just a bit of olive oil and garlic and a technique in which the
fish is swirled over a flame in an earthen casserole, a lovely
sauce was born.
</P>
<P>
   And not since Edna Lewis' ``The Taste of Country Cooking'' has
hog killing been rendered so poetically. Before the women put the
sausage in the pot, they cross themselves, hoping the casings won't
break.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long goodbye for Pepe the pig: ``The men sat at the long
table, where crusty bread and bottles of Rioja wine had been
placed. ... First, porrusalda, a hot leek and potato soup, was
served, followed by salt cod and red pepper salad with slices of
garlic in olive oil. Then came slices of Pepe's grilled liver,
followed by grilled sliced fillet of victim, and then brazo gitano,
a custard-filled sponge cake. Then coffee, brandy, Cuban cigars.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus having filled us with history in its most palatable form,
Kurlansky leaves us to bask with the Basques.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   The Basque History of the World. By Mark Kurlansky. Walker and
Co. $25. 387 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Redefines the notion of armchair history.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Brock writes about food and culture for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
