<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4259 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-NASLUND21-COX     10-21 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NASLUND21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Under the spell of Herman Melville
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ Sena Jeter Naslund was 12 when she slipped a heavy
volume from the Birmingham Public Library shelf and read the
opening line, ``Call me Ishmael.'' From that moment, she was hooked
on Herman Melville. While her friends lay in bed reading Nancy Drew
mysteries, Naslund avidly followed the tragic voyage of Captain
Ahab in ``Moby-Dick,'' falling in love with an ocean she would not
see until she was 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were two things that appealed to me when I was 12,''
Naslund, 57, says after reading to a packed auditorium recently at
the Southern Festival of Books.
</P>
<P>
   ``One was the grand figure of Ahab and his profound searching. I
knew he was grand, and I knew he was doomed, and I wanted to
understand how those two things might exist in a single person. The
other thing that appealed to me was the ocean descriptions, the
beauty of the language.''
</P>
<P>
   What irked her, though, was the lack of female characters. So,
four decades later, after listening to a books-on-tape version of
``Moby-Dick'' with her 10-year-old daughter, Naslund determined to
tell the stories that Melville left out in an epic tale of her own.
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``Ahab's Wife'' (Morrow, $28), a critically
acclaimed novel that has become the literary event of the season.
William Morrow paid more than a half-million dollars for the book
in a bidding war, the Book-of-the-Month Club chose it as a main
selection, and reviewers from Time magazine's Pico Iyer to author
Wally Lamb have praised the writing with such phrases as ``lush and
luminous.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the intriguing line, ``Captain Ahab was neither
my first husband nor my last,'' the novel traces the life of Una
Spenser, a spirited 19th-century heroine who, at 16, disguises
herself as a boy and joins a whaling crew. Other adventures follow
as Una crosses paths with real people such as writer Margaret
Fuller and astronomer Maria Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used historical figures because I didn't want anyone to be
able to say that Una was an unlikely character of her time,''
Naslund says. ``So two of her best friends are Margaret Fuller and
Maria Mitchell. The stuff about them is carefully researched.
Mitchell, for example, tells Una that she wears only silks because
cotton rests on the slave trade, and she won't support that in any
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in Margaret Fuller's book, `Women in the 19th Century,'
she writes, `Let them be sea captains if they will.' That's the
attitude of Una. I wanted her to be authentic to her time and yet
speak to our time. Una is on a spiritual quest, and many women have
come up to me and said, `Thank you for writing this book.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Naslund, Paul Bresnick, the editor at Morrow who
handled her manuscript, was a Melville devotee who reads
``Moby-Dick'' aloud to friends once a year. Bresnick was dubious at
first, but then he read the opening sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was absolutely enthralled,'' Bresnick says. ``I took it home
with me on Thanksgiving weekend and I had to be dragged kicking and
screaming to the turkey dinner. I was struck by how thoroughly she
has imbued the spirit of Herman Melville and how it permeates every
page of her book. But one need not have read `Moby-Dick' to
appreciate this novel.''
</P>
<P>
   Naslund says she did meticulous research to make sure all the
details were accurate. She read biographies of Melville and books
about the weather on Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also went to Mystic, Conn., where they have a whaler. I had
already written the whaling sequence by then, and I was delighted
to find the ship exactly as I had envisioned it. And visiting Old
Sturbridge (Village in Massachusetts) and Mystic gave me an insight
into what everyday life was like. I learned about the way they
cooked, the furniture they sat on and their gardens. They have
heirloom gardens with authentic 19th-century plants.''
</P>
<P>
   Naslund's interest in storytelling is rooted in her childhood in
Birmingham. The daughter of a pianist mother and a doctor father,
Naslund began writing when she was barely 5. ``I wrote newspapers
for Cowboy Town,'' she says, laughing. ``There were robberies and
runaway horses and stampedes. The books I read growing up, such as
the Laura Ingalls Wilder (books), emphasized strong women. I also
read a lot of Dickens.''
</P>
<P>
   Naslund's creativity extended to the playground as well, says
Nancy Brooks Moore, who lives in Atlanta. ``She made up characters
for us to play and sometimes we'd pretend to be detectives and hide
in the rafters at the bus station. We were always getting into
fights with boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Even then, Naslund's reading taste ran to the literary, Moore
says. ``I was reading Nancy Drew and she was reading Dickens when
she was 9 or 10. She always wanted a Dickens book for her
birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Birmingham-Southern College and earning a
doctorate at the University of Iowa Writers Workshop, Naslund
landed at the University of Louisville. Married to her third
husband, physicist John C. Morrison, Naslund teaches creative
writing and edits the Louisville Review, which she founded in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, she has written two short story collections and two
other novels, including ``Sherlock in Love,'' in which she created
a romantic interest for the famous detective.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of a 36-city book tour, Naslund is looking forward
to resuming work on her next book, a novel about race relations set
in Birmingham in the late 1950s and early '60s. As for the future,
Naslund intends to heed the words of Ishmael in ``Ahab's Wife''
when Una praises the harpooner's gift as a storyteller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would suppose that you yourself have a story to tell,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed she does.
</P>
<P>
   Sena Jeter Naslund will read from her novel at 8:15 tonight at
Emory University's White Hall, Room 207. A book signing will
follow. 480 Kilgo Road. 404-325-1505.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
