<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4260 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS24-COX     10-21 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Virtues, vices of journalism and academia
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 24
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This particular book happened to be a biography of a certain
American president. With some argument we allowed that there was
this to be said for it and this to be said against it, but we
agreed on its essential worth with damning finality: ``Fascinating
but journalistic.''
</P>
<P>
   That said quite enough and we moved on, self-satisfied in not
letting sober judgment be debased by cheap thrills. There were
three of us: an academic, a journalist, and a man happy to be
neither fish nor fowl.
</P>
<P>
   What called us collegially together was a prize of considerable
note, but it was the temperaments we brought to the table that
pigeonholed us as much as where we hung our hats. Half an hour
earlier, a different book had been chewed on and sent on its way
just as summarily: ``Solid but academic.'' In short, a book you
might need to refer to one day but never read.
</P>
<P>
   There is something weasly about the two words: ``journalistic''
and ``academic.'' As everyday adjectives, they serve most
frequently as slurs and slights. Yet they imply settled habits of
mind and standards of judgment. They mark off mutually inhospitable
spheres of influence, a strange thing when you consider their
incestuous ancestry. You'd think they were opposite poles, each
with its own magnetic field. What is journalistic by definition
could not be academic; and what is academic had better not be in
the least journalistic if someone's looking to get tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you think journalism and scholarship honest professions
or just two more lines of work, there is a long tradition of
apostates and converts in both. Walter Lippmann went to Harvard
intending to become a professor of philosophy _ he was William
James' favorite student. George Will very much was a professor of
philosophy. There are always, of course, those who manage to work
both sides of the street. But you get the point.
</P>
<P>
   A writer may be serious or he may be trivial, but it is more
important to know whether he is a ``journalist'' or an
``academic.'' The issue is more than simply taxonomic. The species
now and then intermingle, and they each have their quadroons and
their mutants. But the labels stick. They tell, usually, more about
the labeler than the labeled. Which is why they are usually uttered
with telling intonation. ``Journalistic'' requires a prideful
sneer, ``academic'' a pitying chuckle. I am practiced at both, as a
matter of fact, and at different times have employed each as
survival demanded.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to think I use ``academic'' without libelous intent,
but let others judge. What I am certain of is that the two worlds _
journalism and the academy _ feed on their uneasy coexistence. I
think they actually enjoy it. It enables them to define themselves
by reference to what they are not. Vices found in another easily
testify to imagined virtues in ourselves. David Eisenhower is not,
ordinarily speaking, an unimpeachable witness. He wanted to be a
newspaperman when he was young and won an internship with the old
Philadelphia Bulletin. ``Journalists,'' he said after it was
finished, ``are not as interesting as they think they are.''
</P>
<P>
   The words sting, and yet I have known journalists dull as any
Republican. Even more surprising, I have caught in an academic the
occasional glint of what I think may have been wit _ it's hard to
tell against the academy's protective coloring.
</P>
<P>
   For all this, generalizations suggest themselves. There does
seem to be a kind of temperament that inclines one person toward
scholarship and another toward newspapering. Unless my experience
is grossly distorted, one difference is this: Many an academic in
the humanities is inclined inward rather than outward, and tills a
small patch of soil over and over while the world moves on without
his notice. A journalist by instinct looks outward to the world's
variety and change. He may have enough of a reflective sense to
seek out the past in the present and the future in both, but the
important point is that his perspective will be fluid, shifting
with the flow of events.
</P>
<P>
   These differences are scandalously sketchy and they are not
universally the case, but where they exist you are apt to find
others as well: The first-rate scholar is the more patient sifter
of evidence, with a broader sense of proportion. He is literate
rather than glib. The second-rate scholar is only a plodder, a
putter-to-sleep, a grubber of footnotes. His instinct is to seek
out the abstract, thinking it impressive, when what matters is the
concrete. I've known many who were first-rate, and many more who
were second-rate and did not know it.
</P>
<P>
   A journalist can have all these failings, but the good one has a
taste for the pith of human endeavor and is quicker to spot in the
passing moment what is of intrinsic interest. He can, on the other
hand, be nothing more than a trafficker in the transient and the
trivial, with all the depth of a thimble.
</P>
<P>
   If I am unfair in this, I owe apologies near and far. The first
would be to a biographer whose book I thought entirely fascinating,
journalistic or not. For him, unfortunately, the question was more
than academic.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
