<HEADER>
A4261 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SODERBERGH22-COX     10-21 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SODERBERGH22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Director Soderbergh's distinct style keeps him from boredom
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 10 years since he became an international sensation with
``sex, lies, and videotape,'' director Steven Soderbergh has been
working in Hollywood. But he's never exactly gone Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Even in mainstream films like his ``Out of Sight,'' the
Atlanta-born, Louisiana-bred filmmaker has sustained an edgy,
personal tone that distinguishes all his work. His latest, ``The
Limey,'' let him work with two '60s icons, Terence Stamp, as a
veteran British thief named Wilson who flies to L.A. to avenge the
death of his daughter, and Peter Fonda as the rich record producer
who may be responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were really inspiring,'' says Soderbergh, now 36.
``They've gone through a lot and kept their soul intact and are
happy to get up and go to work in the morning. I just thought,
`Wow, I hope I still have that spark when I'm that age' _ 'cause
it's hard. This business will beat it out of you if you're not
careful.'' (Maybe that's one reason he plans to relocate from Los
Angeles to New York next year.)
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Limey,'' Soderbergh tells the streamlined story with a
tricky, time-shifting style, using stutter-cuts and surprise
editing to give Lem Dobbs' script texture. Anyone who saw his 1998
heist flick ``Out of Sight'' will recognize the technique. He used
it to its strongest effect in a scene between its stars, George
Clooney and Jennifer Lopez, which was shot in multiple locations,
including a cocktail lounge and a hotel bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing happens in a scene between Stamp and Lesley Ann
Warren in ``Limey,'' a single conversation that Soderbergh shot in
three locations, then edited together. ``It's amazing to me how
easily it goes down with people, because it makes no sense
logically,'' he admits. ``But I think they understand on some level
that the whole film is a memory piece. It's like someone saying, `I
had this long conversation with this woman. We went walking and had
something to eat, and I don't remember where we were when she said
this.'''
</P>
<P>
   However distinct the style is, he's putting it aside for a
while. ``Not that there isn't more room to explore that sort of
fragmented narrative style, but I'm gonna drop that for a while,''
he says, calling from a Los Angeles editing room, where he's
putting together his next film _ one he says will make us
reconsider Julia Roberts as an actress, more than just a movie
star. (More about that later.)
</P>
<P>
   On top of its editing tricks, ``The Limey'' has a built-in depth
charge. Soderbergh bought the rights to the 1967 Ken Loach film
``Poor Cow,'' starring Stamp, and he uses footage from it as
flashback shots of Wilson. At first, you may think you're watching
a young actor who looks very much like Stamp. ``It's pretty
amazing,'' Soderbergh says. ``You can hear the ripple in the
audience when they realize, No, that's really him.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other directors, Soderbergh rarely repeats himself,
stretching his range from period drama (``King of the Hill'') to
surreal larks (``Kafka,'' ``Schizopolis'') to film noir
(``Underneath'') to staged performance (Spalding Gray's one-man
show ``Gray's Anatomy''). ``I'm restless, personally,'' he says.
``I get bored with the idea of doing the same thing again and
again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of Sight'' was his first big studio film, and while it
made many critics' Top 10 lists, it suffered by being released in
the summer against flashier movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a good experience; I was pretty happy with it,''
he says now. ``Do I think the studio should've put it out in the
fall when they were originally supposed to? Yeah, if we had come
out in October, I think we could've had a big hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe next time. The movie he's editing now is ``Erin
Brokovich,'' the fact-based drama about a single mother working for
a law firm, who uncovers information about a major
gas-and-electricity utility implicated in multiple illnesses in a
small community.
</P>
<P>
   ```Working-class' would be the polite term,'' Soderbergh says of
the character Roberts plays. ``And Julia was so inside the
character. She's amazing in the movie. I told her, `Your problem is
going to be following this, because you've reached a whole other
place now, and you can't go back.'''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to sum up his career after being a moviemaker for 10
years, he pauses a moment, then says, ``I just hope that I can keep
getting better. Only recently do I feel that I'm starting to
understand what I'm doing. I still feel my best work is in front of
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
