<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-FESTIVALS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Dahlonega, Ga. _ The annual fall concert sponsored by the
Wiggins Fund for Traditional Appalachian Music will feature Ralph
Blizard and the New Southern Ramblers Saturday at the Holly
Theatre. The Rounder recording artists combine Southern Appalachian
fiddle music and traditional vocals with mountain-style clogging.
Workshops in fiddle and clogging 6:30-7:15 p.m. ($5); concert 8
p.m. ($10). 706-864-6439.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Orlando _ One of the world's largest Halloween celebrations,
Halloween Horror Nights, will thrill guests for the ninth year at
Universal Studios Florida. The spine-tingling shows run Thursday
through Oct. 31. 407-224-6776 or www.uescape.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Florence, Ala. _ Medieval England comes alive Saturday and
Oct. 24 at the Alabama Renaissance Faire. A 16th-century
marketplace in downtown Florence will house more than 50 period
crafters, plus there will be strolling minstrels, acrobats,
jugglers, poets and magicians. The event is free. 1-800-648-5381.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Beaufort, S.C. _ The 15th annual Fall Festival of Houses
presents private historic homes in the Old Point District as well
as the Pigeon Point neighborhood of Beaufort through Sunday. Also
homes on Ribaut Road and Hermitage Road will have home tours Oct.
30. 843-524-6334.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Blowing Rock, N.C. _ Tweetsie Railroad's Halloween Festival
and Ghost Train continues nightly Friday through Oct. 31. In
addition to the haunted train ride, there will be a haunted house,
a black light show in Doc Tingle's Laboratory and Kid Zone and
Creepy Carnival for younger children. Gates open at 7:30 p.m.
1-800-526-5740 or www.tweetsie.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, N.C. _ The Craft Fair of the Southern Highlands is
Thursday through Sunday at the Asheville Civic Center, featuring
works by the Southern Highland Craft Guild. The semiannual event
features fine crafts for sale, demonstrations and entertainment
including traditional mountain music and storytelling.
828-298-7928.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, N.C. _ Michaelmas: An English Harvest Fair
concludes Saturday and Sunday at Biltmore Estate, which is reviving
the traditional feast day celebration dating to sixth-century
England. The event includes music and theatrical performances in
the Italian garden, crafts demonstrations and jazz concerts at the
winery. 828-255-1174 or www.biltmore.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gatlinburg, Tenn. _ The Gatlinburg Craftsmen's Fair, through
Sunday, features works by 150 crafters working in such traditional
art forms as quilting, woodcarving, pottery, broom and dulcimer
making, candle dipping and metalwork. 423-436-7479 or
www.craftsmenfair.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pigeon Forge, Tenn. _ The Harvest Celebration at Dollywood
continues through October. The outdoor festivities feature crafters
from around the country, fall foods, autumn decorations and the
Southern Gospel Jubilee, the country's largest Southern gospel
event. 423-428-9488.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Williamsburg, Va. _ ``Ghosts and Ghoulies: A Halloween Weekend
in Colonial Williamsburg'' Oct. 29-31 includes a stay at one of the
resort hotels and a program of activities including learning about
Halloween customs, ghost stories and tours of graveyards. Call for
prices. 1-800-447-8679 or www.history.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Augustine, Fla. _ ``Halloween Nights: Old Haunts in the
Old City'' Oct. 29-31 includes participating attractions (Ripley's
Believe It or Not Museum, 3-D World, Potter's Wax Museum, Oldest
Wooden Schoolhouse and A Ghostly Experience Walking Tour). $25 per
person. Also, a free children's costume parade and trick or
treating on Oct. 31. 904-471-9010.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dothan, Ala. _ Pioneer Peanut Day on Saturday in Landmark Park
will salute the Wiregrass peanut farmer. Includes an old-fashioned
peanut harvest, an antique gas and steam engine show, arts and
crafts, a tractor pull for 1960 and older tractors, wagon rides, a
children's pedal tractor pull and music by the Ripe N' Ready
Bluegrass Band and L.A. Country Band. Also, the exhibit ``Retiring
the Mule'' opens at the new Alabama Museum of Agriculture at the
park. 334-794-3452.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Birmingham _ ``Fashion Photographs'' by William Wegman at the
Birmingham Museum of Art runs through Jan. 8. The show features an
array of haute couture. Also at the museum is ``Searching for
Ancient Egypt,'' running through Jan. 16 and featuring a
3,000-year-old mummy and works of art from archaeological sites
from along the Nile. 205-254-2565.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mobile, Ala. _ ``Nicholas &AMP; Alexandra: The Last Imperial
Family of Tsarist Russia'' has been extended through Jan. 30. More
than 700 objects are on display in 14 galleries at the Mobile Civic
Center, including elegant gowns, uniforms, a gilded coach,
paintings, Faberge creations, love letters, diaries and old
photographs. Tickets: 1-888-395-0005; Mobile information:
1-800-566-2453.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Various Georgia locations _ ``Christmas Made in the South,''
featuring hundreds of artists and crafters from around the country,
will be at the Columbus Convention and Trade Center on Oct. 29-31;
at the Macon Centreplex on Nov. 5-7; at the Augusta Civic Center on
Nov. 12-14; and the Savannah Civic Center on Nov. 19-21.
1-800-683-3772.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Winston-Salem, N.C. _ ``Winslow Homer: Early Prints and
Paintings'' will be on display at Reynolda House Museum of American
Art through Nov. 28. 336-659-0234.
</P>
<P>
   _Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
