<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Oct 22, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like runners in a relay race, one low-pressure system near the
northern Great Lakes will transfer its jet stream support to
another low developing off the Carolina coast Friday. In between,
there will be a shrinking ridge of pleasant, bright weather.
Meanwhile, high pressure retreating into the Canadian Maritimes
will cause a moist onshore flow in New England bringing ocean
clouds inland.
</P>
<P>
   Intense low pressure moving east across Ontario will direct a
strong cold front toward the Appalachians. A band of gusty showers
will mark the northern section of the front from Ohio into western
New York. Brisk winds from the northwest will drive very cold air
across the western Great Lakes causing rain showers in Michigan and
Wisconsin. Snow will accumulate in the upper peninsula of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny, mild weather will dominate the South and much of the
Southeast. A storm developing east of Cape Hatteras will keep some
clouds near the coast. These clouds will eventually be drawn into
the Middle Atlantic states and Northeast as the front in the Ohio
Valley approaches.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure stretching from Saskatchewan to Utah will control
conditions over the West. Its clockwise circulation will draw
cooler, dry air into the central and southern Plains. Winds from
the east will bring desert dryness to most of California. Patches
of cirrus clouds and coastal fog may dull the weather along the
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Storm Jose may gain strength again Friday as the
shearing winds lessen over the storm. It should take a decisive
turn to the north by the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SHEARED JOSE
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Jose was downgraded to a tropical storm Thursday as
strong, upper-level winds sheared off the tops of thunderstorms
around its core. Inside thunderstorms surrounding a hurricane's
eye, massive amounts of heat are given off as water vapor in rising
air condenses into cloud drops. This release of heat makes the air
buoyant, allowing it to rise to great altitudes. At its apex, some
air sinks into the eye and warms on descent, lowering air density
and, in turn, surface pressure, which leads to intensification.
When thunderstorm tops are sheared off, however, the hurricane
weakens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
