<SLUG> BC-CORAL-REEF22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS URGED TO FUND PROTECTIONS FOR CORAL REEFS
 &HT;    BY SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress has not earmarked enough money to protect
endangered coral reefs in American waters, a Commerce Department
official warned lawmakers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A $37 billion spending bill approved by both houses late
Wednesday contains $2 million for coral reef conservation and
restoration. President Clinton had requested $12 million. The
president has indicated he will veto the bill, which finances the
operations of the Commerce, State and Justice departments, because
of disagreements primarily over the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   The reduced appropriation means the government won't be able to
implement the recommendations of a presidential task force to map
and monitor coral reefs and create coral reef reserves, said Sally
Yozell, deputy assistant secretary for oceans and atmosphere for
the Department of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lack a comprehensive federal program to map, monitor,
protect, manage and restore the nation's coral reefs,'' Yozell told
the House subcommittee on fisheries conservation, wildlife and
oceans.
</P>
<P>
   Yozell and local conservationists urged the panel to pass a bill
that would allocate $10 million a year for the next five years for
a grant program. The bill, sponsored by subcommittee chairman Jim
Saxton, R-N.J., would also require the government to provide
matching money for non-governmental projects to encourage state and
local involvement in the efforts to conserve coral reefs.
</P>
<P>
   Failing to preserve the Florida Keys coral reef system, the
third largest in the world, could have major economic implications
for Florida, said John Ogden, director of the Florida Institute of
Oceanography.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reefs are important to economies. U.S. coral reef ecosystems
in Hawaii and the Florida Keys alone produce more than $2 billion
annually,'' Ogden said.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that better management was needed in order to
sustain coral reefs and recommended implementing more effective
zoning laws to protect reefs from human destruction. Ogden also
stressed the need for long-term research and assessment of coral
reefs.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 percent of the world's coral reefs are being
degraded or destroyed, the panel was told.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental factors and human activities are responsible for
the poor health of coral reefs and the marine ecosystems they
support, Yozell said.
</P>
<P>
   Saxton added, ``These reefs provide essential habitat for
hundreds of commercial and recreational fish species, and they
support tourism that is the economic backbone of many coastal
communities. This bill is really only the first step.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
