<SLUG> BC-SNIFFER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SMALL DEVICE DETECTS TRACES OF DRUGS, EXPLOSIVES AND CHEMICALS,
MAKER SAYS
 &HT;    By Raven Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new hand-held device that the manufacturer says will detect
trace residue from explosives, narcotics or chemical weapons was
unveiled on Thursday in the fight the war against drugs and
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately the size of a hand-held vacuum cleaner, the
IONSCAN Sabre2000 was designed by the New Jersey-based Barringer
Technologies, Inc., to detect the smallest of physical particles
and the faintest of vapors.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement, customs, security officials and school
administrators can use the device rather easily in a variety of
ways, said Ken Wood, Barrringer's president.
</P>
<P>
   The machine works when a swab of paper with trace residue is
inserted into the machine for a reading, which takes about 20
seconds. Barringer spokespersons said officials then have an idea
of the type of explosives or drugs that have been found, making it
easier for them to assess the potential danger of suspicious
packages or people.
</P>
<P>
   Among the product's features are its mobility and reliability,
Barringer officials said. Even an expert bombmaker will leave trace
residue 95 percent of the time, said Mark Elliott, a company
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Barringer has marketed the machine to airports and national
government agencies, but said it also expected schools to be
interested in the device.
</P>
<P>
   The machine's mobility could allow school administrators to
examine hundreds of lockers, possible storage units for drugs and
explosives, Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   He said schools could test the outsides of lockers and, based on
the evidence, either confront the student, open the locker or place
the student under surveillance. Wood said he would recommend
cleaning the locker completely if trace residue is found and then
testing a week later for a more accurate reading.
</P>
<P>
   The device is currently priced at $20,000, but Barringer said
the company is working to make it more affordable, particularly to
state law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabre2000 works much like other detection tools, like
drug-sniffing dogs. But Wood pointed out one advantage of the
device:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dogs can't tell you what they're sniffing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
