<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4277 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MET-ANCIENT-NEAR-EAST     10-21 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MET-ANCIENT-NEAR-EAST-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEAR EASTERN GALLERIES REINSTALLED AT THE MET
</HEADLINE>
  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  (dal) 
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The reinstallation of a museum's permanent collection
may sound like a routine affair, pulled together in caffeine-fueled
sessions of wall painting and heavy lifting. But it takes at least
as much brain power as muscle to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of thinking has clearly gone into the splendidly revamped
ancient Near Eastern galleries at the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
As a result, a group of stellar, although under-visited objects has
been awarded a persuasive showcase, and more than 8,000 years'
worth of art has been coaxed into a semblance of historical logic.
</P>
<P>
   A few basics about the ancient Near East are good to understand.
Along with Egypt, this region produced one of the first great
historical civilizations. And its defining parameters are crazily
broad. In time they run from a Neolithic date of around 5000 B.C.
to the Islamic Conquest of the seventh century A.D., and
geographically from India to the Mediterranean, and from the
Arabian Peninsula to the Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
   It is also useful to know how much we do not know about the
dozens of cultures that fall within that framework. Some, like
those of Assyria and Achaeminid Persia, made a very loud noise for
a long time. Others passed like strangers in the night, without
leaving so much as a whisper of their identities behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important to realize is how beautiful this art is
and, despite its breadth, how much of a piece. Incised ivory
plaques, tissue-thin gold jewelry, colossal stone sculptures and
action-packed, micro-miniature cylinder seals may have been created
thousands of years and thousands of miles apart. But they are
linked by themes and styles that make Near Eastern art a
descriptively viable term.
</P>
<P>
   It is viable, however, only after intensive shaping and sorting.
And this is what it gets at the hands of Prudence O. Harper and
Joan Aruz, the curators of the new installation, who shrewdly
alternate moments of big-gun flair with an overall jigsaw-puzzle
ingenuity to insure as complete a picture as possible. The
arrangement is roughly chronological. Broad geographical shifts _
from Mesopotamia to Iran, for example _ are marked by changes in
wall color. In each major section outstanding objects are clustered
in the center of the gallery, serving as lures and as guideposts to
what lies beyond.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most dramatic sights comes toward the beginning, out
of historical sequence, in the Assyrian gallery just off the Great
Hall balcony. This once-gloomy enclosure has been opened up to
natural light from above, and its walls are lined with an imposing
series of the limestone panels that once adorned the audience hall
of king Ashurasirpal II (reigned 883-859 B.C.) at his northern
Mesopotamian palace at Nimrud.
</P>
<P>
   Two 10-foot-tall carved winged creatures with staring human
faces _ one with the body of a lion, the other of a bull _ flank a
doorway. The panels themselves depict figures in low relief. Some
are human, as in the case of the king depicted with dangle earrings
and what looks like a fancy clip-on beard. Others, like an
eagle-headed beast with a powerhouse man's physique, are fantastic,
even monstrous.
</P>
<P>
   Assyrian art is about winning through intimidation. The carved
narrative reliefs from Nimrud _ a selection of them visited New
York from the British Museum in 1995, but none are on view here _
obsessively dwell on hair-raising battles and sadistic wildlife
hunts. The half-human raptor in the Met frieze was intended to
advertise the aggressive otherwordly resources the king could
command.
</P>
<P>
   Like most official art, these images adhere to a formula, but
seen in isolation their stylized virtuosity stands out. The fringe
of the bird-man's robe and the bulging calf of his leg are
delicately executed. His ramrod pose has a courtly grace. In one
hand he carries a purse-size bucket of holy water; in the other he
dabs the air with a fruit that looks like a pine cone, as if
removing a pesky stain from the wall.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The formal ingredients of Assyrian art can be traced to other
Mesopotamian sculpture, early and late. The stiff stance and
spellbound eyes occur in the figure of a Sumerian temple worshiper
from the the third millennium B.C. The tendency to invest spiritual
power in animal forms persists in the polychrome glazed brick
reliefs of snarling lions that lined the route to Nebuchadnezzar's
palace in Babylon.
</P>
<P>
   And at least one ruler, the Sumerian king named Gudea, who lived
around 2100 B.C, chose to present himself in a fairly benign light
in a series of seated portraits that are among the best known of
ancient Near Eastern sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   In the Met's statue, which is the only one of its kind in the
United States, he is a clean-shaven youth with tapering fingers and
slender toes, and a large head fitted with an outsize pillbox
crown. His face is serene and alert, but his shoulders are slightly
hunched, and one bare arm is flexed. Everything about him is
tensed, as if he is holding his breath. Joining him in the
gallery's celebrity circle is another self-possessed personage, in
the form of a cast-copper head of a bearded man.
</P>
<P>
   Life size and weathered to a frosty green patina, the face bears
tiny asymmetries and fleshy swells of a true likeness. But no one
has any idea who he is, and although he turned up in central or
northwestern Iran, his true place of origin is debated. Wherever he
hails from, he is one of the museum's front-rank attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Iran itself was, along with Mesopotamia, a seedbed of Near
Eastern art, and its eclectic cultural history is amply represented
here. A third millennium terra cotta jar is one of the earliest
pieces, painted with a trio of ibexes in silhouette. Nearby is the
silver figure of a kneeling bull wrapped in a tight sheath skirt,
probably made around 2900 B.C. in the kingdom of Elam, on the
border of Mesopotamia and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   The entire installation concludes with another knockout silver
sculpture, this one the masklike head of a Sasanian king from the
fourth century A.D. Wearing a crown that swells like an onion dome,
he stares with mesmerized eyes straight out the gallery door toward
the museum's Islamic wing, where the story of Near Eastern art
after the Arab conquest continues.
</P>
<P>
   Long before that earth-shaking event, however, the Near East had
already been the scene of countless incursions, and exchanges. And
Ms. Harper and Ms. Aruz further enrich an already complicated
picture by folding several of these episodes into the mix.
</P>
<P>
   The influence of Egyptian art, for example, appears in sculpture
from distant Anatolia. The spirit of Greece and Rome lives on in
frescoes from Syria and in a charming terra cotta head from a
Buddhist site in Pakistan. From Spain comes a set of Phoenecian
ivory plaques, now owned by the Hispanic Society of America, among
several borrowed works in the galleries. And a fascinating handful
of items _ a shriveled leather boot, a nude male divinity carved in
wood _ are in New York on long-term loan from the Academy of
Sciences in Tajikistan, a former Soviet territory near the Chinese
border.
</P>
<P>
   Is the total picture a coherent one? Of course not. Culture is
an ungovernable thing, a series of flukish successes and failures
and slow fades, all of which are played out here. It is also a
network of fertile marriages, and they are evident, too. The Near
East collection provides a natural jumping-off point for visits to
the museum's permanent Indian and Islamic displays, not to mention
the magnificent ``Egyptian Art in the Age of the Pyramids''
exhibition, on view through Jan. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Or one may prefer to linger in the refurbished galleries
themselves, where many of those traditions connect and where,
thanks to the Met's careful planning, one can survey them from
fresh perspectives and in first-class style.
</P>
<P>
   The reinstallation of the permanent collection in the Ancient
Near Eastern galleries is on view at the Metropolitan Museum of
Art, Fifth Avenue at 82nd Street, (212) 535-7710.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4281 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     10-21 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Paramedic With a Pen
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Joe Connelly's father was a Greyhound bus driver,
and his mother was a nurse. ``I ended up doing the exact same thing
as my parents, a combination of both,'' said Connelly, left, who
was a paramedic and worked for nine years at St. Clare's Hospital
and Health Center in Manhattan. On the day his autobiographical
novel ``Bringing Out the Dead'' was optioned for a film by the
producer Scott Rudin, Connelly quit the job that had consumed his
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times you wondered if you've become as crazy as
what you're seeing,'' said Connelly, whose book is the basis for
the new Martin Scorsese film ``Bringing Out the Dead,'' which opens
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Adapted by Paul Schrader, the film stars Nicolas Cage as a
paramedic, following him over two days and three nights in the
early 1990s in New York. It tracks the Cage character to the brink
of collapse, as he is engulfed in a world of the dead and dying: a
world that is sometimes horrifying, sometimes funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst parts, for me, were the long stretches when nothing
seemed to be going right,'' said Connelly, who recently moved from
the Upper West Side to an apartment in Washington Heights in upper
Manhattan with his wife and 2-year-old son. ``You're always waiting
for that good call to pull you out of it. When you're saving
somebody's life, that's the greatest high in the world. Better than
drugs, better than anything. When you start to lose people, that's
despair. That sticks to you. That's what I call being stuck at 4
o'clock in the morning in Times Square all night long.''
</P>
<P>
   The book, like the film, is set in Hell's Kitchen, not far from
the Times Square area where Connelly often worked. Times Square had
not yet been rehabilitated, there were drug wars, and the crack and
AIDS epidemics were at their peaks. ``It was a wild time then,''
Connelly said. ``The system was a shambles, the pay was terrible,
the turnover outrageous. You were trying to shut down the stress in
your life. I had a partner who was buying crack on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike those novelists who complain bitterly about film
adaptations of their books (but cash the studio checks anyway),
Connelly, who was a technical consultant on the set, said he was a
bit overwhelmed at the movie's faithfulness to the book. ``Paul
Schrader used most of my dialogue,'' he said. ``I can actually
listen to people laugh and respond.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Scorsese also picked up every nuance of the book. ``What
happens as a paramedic is you don't know what's going to happen
next,'' Connelly said. ``Anything's possible. Anything's real.
Nothing makes sense. The character in this movie becomes a mirror
for the suffering he sees. With each day, he's dying a little bit
more. He can't help it. And he's waiting for that one call to bring
him out of it. He's a spiritual figure. And that's what Marty
Scorsese picks up on. And I couldn't be happier.''
</P>
<P>
   Connelly, 35, grew up in Queens, and Warwick, N.Y. He was
majoring in philosophy at Colgate University but dropped out after
three years. (``The cause was drunkenness and confusion,'' he
said.) For a year he traveled around the United States doing odd
jobs; he was even a bartender in Ireland for a while. When he
returned to New York, he worked first as an emergency medical
technician at Metropolitan Hospital Center in Harlem, then as a
paramedic at St. Clare's.
</P>
<P>
   He was still working on the late shift when he began writing
about his experiences. At the same time Connelly took a writing
course at Columbia University and met Colin Harrison, deputy editor
of Harper's magazine and a novelist. Harrison was so impressed with
Connelly's work that he found him an agent, who sold the book to
Knopf in 1996. A year later Rudin optioned the book, still in
galleys, for a Paramount film. The book was published in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly is now in the thick of another novel, ``Crumb Town,''
about a man whose life story is turned into a television movie,
which turns into a bleak experience. ``Very much unlike me,'' he
said. ``This film gave me the opportunity to commit myself to
writing full time, have a family and feed them. And I've worked
with some great artists on this film. I'm very fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Weddings and Lineage
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm D. Lee makes no effort to hide the reason he wrote and
directed ``The Best Man,'' a romantic comedy that opens on Friday.
``Quite honestly, I wanted to write a script that I thought I could
sell,'' said Lee, 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had seen that wedding films did very well at the box office;
look at `Four Weddings and a Funeral' and `My Best Friend's
Wedding,''' said Lee. ``I saw that films about middle-class
African-Americans, like `Soul Food' and `Waiting to Exhale,' could
be profitable. A wedding film about African-Americans was, I
thought, overdue.''
</P>
<P>
   So Lee sat down in his New York apartment and wrote ``The Best
Man,'' about a group of successful college friends who are reunited
for a wedding. The fact that the film's cast is almost entirely
African-American, like Lee, lends another dimension to the comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just tired of not seeing people I could relate to on the
big screen,'' said Lee, whose cousin, Spike Lee, was the movie's
producer. ``In too many movies the black characters are
marginalized and stereotypical: the black friend who imparts wisdom
to his white co-star, the black prostitute, the thug, the sidekick.
They tend to be one-dimensional. I wanted to go beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   The relatively low-budget film, which cost about $9 million to
make, stars Taye Diggs (``How Stella Got Her Groove Back'') as the
best man whose steamy novel about his friends throws the wedding
into turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to tell a story that was close to my own
experience _ about people who have been to college, people who are
pursuing careers and getting on with their lives,'' Lee said.
Besides, he said, ``people love to see folks getting married _ it
makes everyone feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It helps, of course, that Spike Lee is his cousin. The
well-known filmmaker endorsed Malcolm Lee's proposal that he,
Malcolm, direct the film, even though he was inexperienced. And the
studio making the movie, Universal, signed off on it partly because
of Spike Lee's involvement.
</P>
<P>
   But the experienced older director was relatively hands-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spike gave advice here and there about casting and the crew,''
Lee said. ``He had some suggestions on how to cut the film down.
But he never second-guessed my instincts. He wanted me to find my
way. And he wasn't around that much. I know he realized that the
director had to have total control.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who now lives in Riverdale in the Bronx, grew up in the
Crown Heights section of Brooklyn. His father is a retired junior
high school teacher, his mother a retired medical records clerk.
From the age of 17, he worked as an assistant on Spike Lee films.
At the same time, he attended Georgetown University and the New
York University film school. Later he won a screenwriting
fellowship at the Walt Disney studios.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said his next film will probably be ``Morningside Prep,''
about black students at a mostly white prep school. He has already
made a short film on the subject. In the meantime, he is nervous
about the current film's opening weekend. ``What we're trying to
say is this is not out of anyone's realm of reality,'' he said.
``Actually, the film has nothing to do with race. It's not a story
about the 'hood. It's a feel-good story about a wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   George as Director
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there's life after ``Seinfeld.'' Jason Alexander, forever
known as George Costanza, has directed a new film, ``Just
Looking,'' which is playing Friday at the Hamptons Film Festival
and is searching for a distributor. The film is a comedy about a
14-year-old boy named Lennie from the Bronx who spends a summer in
Queens and develops a crush on an older woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born in 1959 and grew up in Livingston, N.J., but I felt
I knew these people very well,'' said Alexander. ``I read this
script, and I understood this story personally. I'm not a director
to make an action or horror film. That's not for me. This is about
people and relationships, and it appealed to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, produced by Jean Doumanian, has a cast that includes
Patti LuPone and Gretchen Moll. It was written by Marshall Karp.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander rarely sees his ``Seinfeld'' colleagues. ``We don't
communicate that much,'' he said. ``What really bonded us was the
work. And we're really separated by distance. Julia is here and I'm
here and our life situations are similar _ she has two young
children and I have two young children. But when we were making the
show, we were all never really best friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Will George Costanza shadow his career? Alexander replied with
an anecdote. Several years ago he met William Shatner, who told him
that for many years he resented the fact that ``Star Trek'' had
left a permanent imprint on his career. ``But then Shatner said he
realized that he had been given something that most actors never
get: the chance to touch people beyond their own life and have a
body of work that he's proud of and will be there after he's
gone,'' Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's how I feel, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1808EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
