<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4283 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FUTURE-CARS-ART-(2TAK     10-21 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUTURE-CARS-ART-(2TAKES)-716words-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM OFFERS A SNEAK PREVIEW OF ITS CARS OF TOMORROW
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Detroit, Chicago, Los Angeles)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  (dal) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARREN, Mich. _ Determined not to be a wallflower at next year's
big parties, General Motors is trying on a rack of new outfits in
an effort to bedazzle those who haven't been asking for a dance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a move unprecedented in the auto industry, GM gave the press
a peek last week at nine so-called concept vehicles that it will
display at the industry's equivalent of debutante balls, the auto
shows in Detroit, Los Angeles, Chicago and Geneva in the first half
of next year. And next week, GM will give journalists a preview of
its glitzy display for the North American International Auto Show
on Jan. 15-23 in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   GM executives felt humbled at the 1999 show by an extravagant,
multilevel Ford Motor Co. exhibit that dominated the convention
hall and included products from the company's newly enlarged stable
of international brands. And the Chrysler Corp., now
DaimlerChrysler, has for years staged splashy product introductions
with, literally, rolls of thunder, flashes of lightning and even
minivans that played leapfrog on elaborate sets.
</P>
<P>
   GM, meanwhile, suffered a drought of new products that began
earlier in the decade as serious financial problems brought the
company close to bankruptcy. New car lines were canceled, and at
auto shows GM unveiled relatively few _ and fairly modest _ concept
cars, the vehicles that designers create to show off new ideas or
signal design styling trends.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a healthy balance sheet, GM wants the world to know it
is pumping money into new vehicles and taking some risks.
</P>
<P>
   GM's nine concept vehicles were shown to reporters as
three-dimensional computerized images at the company's virtual
reality design studio here in suburban Detroit. Although the images
looked like real vehicles, they existed only in digital form and
were viewed by wearing special glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Cherry, vice president for design and portfolio
development, said at the briefing that GM wanted to be the industry
leader in product innovation, ``and nothing stimulates creativity
more than generating concept vehicles to translate ideas into
forms.''
</P>
<P>
   The concept cars showed styling features specific to each brand
and point to GM's future direction in design. ``All of the concept
vehicles were developed in our advanced concept center, but all are
based on architecture we are looking at for the future or that we
currently use,'' Cherry said.
</P>
<P>
   These are the vehicles GM showed, in the order in which they
will publicly appear:  &QL; 
SATURN CV1  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saturn's first-ever concept vehicle will make its debut at the
Los Angeles auto show on Jan. 8-16. A cross of a minivan, station
wagon and sport utility, the CV1 seats up to seven people,
including two on rear-facing jump seats that fold out of the front
seatbacks. The rear seats also slide and fold to form a flat cargo
floor. There are large windows for a panoramic view, and bi-fold
doors that slide along tracks and can be opened at the front or the
rear.
</P>
<P>
   The CV1 will have an ultra-low-emission four-cylinder engine, a
continuously variable transmission for high fuel efficiency and
all-wheel drive. Body panels are plastic, as they are on other
Saturns.  &QL; 
OLDSMOBILE PROFILE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GM calls this wagon-like vehicle a new type of sports sedan.
Along with Olds styling characteristics like the long, narrow
headlamps of the Aurora, Alero and Intrigue, the Profile has power
sliding rear doors, sliding flat-folding split rear seats and a
mobile communication center that could provide real-time traffic
reports, voice mail and e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The Profile, which is also to be shown in Los Angeles, will have
a supercharged twin-cam 3.5-liter V6, all-wheel drive, a ``shift by
wire'' transmission with no moving parts and a stability-control
system. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BUICK LaCROSSE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This luxury sedan, which will be displayed on Jan. 15-23 at the
Detroit show, blends a futuristic look with traditional Buick
touches, including stylized portholes on the fenders. But it also
has a pickup bed under a rear hatch.
</P>
<P>
   The electronic hatch, tailgate and doors open or close in
response to spoken commands. Because all functions are controlled
by voice or a trackball, there are no visible gauges or controls
other than the accelerator, brake pedal and steering wheel.
Occupants would sit on leather club chairs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Also to be unveiled in Detroit, the GMC Terradyne has an
extended truck cab that is pushed far forward to make room for five
passengers. As the sliding doors open, a step automatically lowers.
The truck bed can be expanded to 8 feet, from 6, by pulling out a
drawer-like tailgate; lockable trunks line the sides of the bed.
The Terradyne uses industrial materials like stainless steel for a
look of industrial precision, and it has an on-board generator that
could send power to a home in a blackout. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHEVROLET SSR &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GM hopes that this hybrid of sports convertible and pickup will
be a show-stopper in Detroit. With its prominent fender flares, the
styling evokes Chevy pickups of the 1940s and 50s. Inside, the SSR
has a divided cockpit like those of early Corvettes, but there is
space in the center for a third person or a child seat. A
retractable power top drops behind the seats for open-air
motoring. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
OPEL CVC &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This concept vehicle from GM's European unit is based on the
highly successful Zafira minivan. The compact five-door van is
outfitted for wintry regions with permanent four-wheel drive, high
ground clearance, a roof rack for winter gear and a plastic hatch
lid that doubles as a toboggan. The CCV seats six and the seats can
be moved to different positions. The roof is glass, and there are
airliner-style bins along the sides as well as heated rear cup
holders. The CCV has a prototype direct-injection, four-cylinder
gas engine. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHEVROLET TRAVERSE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Traverse, a family sedan built on pickup truck architecture,
will appear at the Chicago auto show, Feb. 11-20. The five
occupants sit up high with a view of all four corners of the car.
The rear seats slide forward and backward to add more cargo or
passenger room. The seats also fold for a flat cargo floor, and the
tailgate drops and the hatch lifts skyward. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Traverse comes with all-wheel drive and a 4.5-liter V6
engine and four-speed automatic transmission with push-button
electronic controls. Like the SSR's, the Traverse interior has a
twin-cockpit design and Internet access. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PONTIAC PIRANHA  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Intended to be an affordable sports car with extra room and
practicality, the Piranha has a mini-pickup bed under a rear hatch
that pulls out for loading items like skis. The mesh seats can be
removed and taken to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Interior fabrics zip on and off for customization _ buyers could
select denim, leather or jersey, for instance. The roof panels open
sideways for open-air motoring; pop-up racks offer another way to
carry skis and snowboards. The front-drive Piranha will have a
supercharged four-cylinder engine and a five-speed transmission
that would be shifted by flicking paddles. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CADILLAC CONCEPT  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Next March 2-12 in Geneva, Cadillac will show a yet-unnamed
vehicle that will apply the division's ``Art and Science'' theme _
first used on the Evoq roadster this year _ to a luxury sedan. The
four-seat design will have the Evoq's crisp look and many gadgets,
including information and entertainment screens built into the
seats. The show car will have an infrared Night Vision camera like
that on the 2000 DeVille; all-wheel drive, and a supercharged
version of the Northstar V8 that produces an impressive 450
horsepower. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
