<SLUG> BC-TV-ANYDAYNOW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANY DAY NOW' SEEKS TO SPARK DISCUSSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nancy Miller, the creator of ``Any Day Now,'' admits that the
series isn't just there to wash over a supine sofa spud on a Sunday
night. It's expressly designed to foster dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outcome doesn't have to be agreement,'' Miller adds. ``It
only has to be understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, a lot of people don't want to engage in meaningful
discourse about something they've just seen on TV. Minimal
investment of brain cells is why many of them tune in in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   But some people do enjoy an occasional taffy-pull on their gray
matter, and ``Any Day Now'' does its best to comply, offering
evocative, provocative one-hour episodes each week. This Sunday,
fans get a bonus hour when Miller's poetic series about two
Birmingham, Ala., women who have been best friends since childhood
offers enough dialogue starter to keep tongues wagging for weeks on
the subjects of racial bigotry, hate crimes and white supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   Differentness and acceptance are always at the generous heart of
``Any Day Now,'' since the two friends of the piece are Rene
Jackson, who is black, and Mary Elizabeth ``M.E.'' Sims, who is
white.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's two-hour presentation titled ``It's Not About the
Butter,'' M.E. (Annie Potts) sets off a tempest while dining with
Rene (Lorraine Toussaint) in a restaurant. She asks a young woman
in white blouse and black skirt, the uniform of the serving staff,
for some butter. Turns out the woman is another patron who happens
to be walking past the table. She's also happens to be African
American, with a chip on her shoulder the size of the Lincoln
Memorial. The dressing-down she gives M.E. would make General
Patton proud.
</P>
<P>
   Stunned, M.E. insists it was an honest mistake, but Rene allows
that M.E.'s misstep could be taken as a racial affront.
</P>
<P>
   As the title promises, the back-to-back episodes really aren't
about the butter, but the opening scene is enough to keep a
dialogue going for days, fueled cleverly by the frequent flashbacks
to the '60s, when Rene and M.E. became friends despite prevailing
``adult'' sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a not entirely believable courtroom sequence near the
end, in which M.E.'s white-supremacist uncle is sued by Rene and
her mother for abhorrent antisocial behavior, this ``Any Day Now''
puts a big exclamation point on a TV season that began with lots of
noise about the number of minorities showing up _ or not showing up
_ in prime-time TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   With a straight face, the networks say there's no prejudice in
casting. Yet actors of color are routinely passed over for roles
that are supposedly color-blind. Just as M.E. and Rene's
interpretations of the butter scene are contrary, the networks'
view this situation and the spurned actors' views of it are
extremely divergent. But no one really talks about it unless the
NAACP raises a stink.
</P>
<P>
   This week's ``Any Day Now'' is brutally honest, with several
``nigger'' references that range from the seemingly innocent
childhood game of ``eenie, meenie, miney, mo'' to the humiliation
of Rene's mother by M.E.'s uncle during the turbulent '60s. The
latter is a scene so hateful that reams would be written about it
if ``Any Day Now'' appeared on the schedule of a major commercial
network. Because it's on Lifetime cable, ``Any Day Now'' is less
noticed, but the series, and especially this week's presentation,
are no less important.
</P>
<P>
   Any Day Now. Special two-hour presentation addressing bigotry.
Starring Annie Potts, Lorraine Toussaint, Mae Middleton and Shari
Dyon Perry. Sunday night on Lifetime. Parental guideline rating:
TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4289 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-GORE-OFFSHOREOIL-2NDL     10-21 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-OFFSHOREOIL-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE URGES BAN ON NEW OIL DRILLING IN CALIFORNIA, FLORIDA WATERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: FILED IN ``w'' and ``p'' categories.)  
 (EDs: INSERTS new 10th graf with reax from off-shore
association.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore, going beyond Clinton
administration policy on the environment, called Thursday for a
total ban on new oil drilling in federal waters off the coasts of
California and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said his proposal would enable a Gore administration to
make ``dramatic progress'' toward a cleaner environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The environment is much more than a policy position to me _ it
is a profoundly moral obligation,'' Gore said in remarks via
satellite to environmentalists meeting in Los Angeles. Gore spoke
from Rye, N.H., during a campaign swing for his 2000 presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have only one earth. And if we do not keep it healthy and
safe, every other gift we leave our children will be meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has imposed a 10-year extension of a
moratorium on leasing offshore oil tracts and a permanent ban on
leasing in national marine sanctuaries.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign position goes beyond this policy to halt ``all
new drilling'' in federal waters off California and Florida and to
prohibit drilling new wells in existing oil tract leases held by
oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will take the most sweeping steps in our history to protect
our oceans and coastal waters from offshore oil drilling,'' Gore
said. ``I will make sure that there is no new oil leasing off the
coast of California and Florida. ... I will do everything in my
power to make sure that there is no new drilling off these
sensitive coasts _ even in areas already leased for drilling by
previous administrations.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rubin, spokesman for the American Petroleum Institute, said
Gore's proposed ban would force American oil companies to shift
their new drilling abroad. This would make the United States more
dependent on foreign sources of oil and gas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line here is that because we are limited in our
access to federal lands, the companies are forced to spend their
exploration budgets overseas and this is going to simply further
that,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Ocean Industries Assn., a trade group representing
industries involved in oil and gas exploration and production on
the outer continental shelf, criticized Gore for ignoring the
rights of leaseholders who invested in the leases to explore for
oil and natural gas. Gore ``makes no mention of fairly compensating
them for what they would lose,'' the off-shore association said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   But Bruce Hamilton, national conservation director for the
Sierra Club, a prominent environmental group, said California and
Florida are ``two highly desirable places for complete protection.
It is great news to hear that a leader of (Gore's) stature is
taking a stand to protect both coasts.''
</P>
<P>
   A statement by Gore's campaign noted that the state of
California, led by Democratic Gov. Gray Davis, has raised concerns
about proposed new drilling off the coast. The Interior Department
has requested additional information from the oil companies
proposing new exploration.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Florida, led by Republican Gov. Jeb Bush, brother
of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a GOP candidate for president in
2000, has determined that proposed drilling off the Florida coast
``would be inconsistent with its coastal zone management plan,''
the Gore statement said. Chevron has appealed Florida's decision to
Commerce Secretary William Daley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am placing environmental protection at the very heart of my
campaign for the presidency,'' Gore said. ``I will have no higher
priority as president.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore faces a challenge from former Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., in
his bid to succeed Clinton as president. Gore's announcement may
help energize his natural constituency among environmentalists in
California, a key battleground with a presidential primary on March
7, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   A nationwide survey conducted for Cable News Network and USA
Today by the Gallup Poll that concluded on Oct. 10 showed Gore's
lead over Bradley shrinking to 12 percentage points, 51 percent to
39 percent. A survey in September showed Gore leading Bradley by 33
percentage points, 63 percent to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced a 10-year extension of the federal ban on new
oil and gas drilling off the nation's East and West coasts during a
visit to Monterey, Calif., on June 13, 1998. Clinton's compromise
position, seeking to balance environmental protection with the
economic interests of energy companies, disappointed some
environmental activists who had been seeking a permanent ban on oil
exploration.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., expressed disappointment at the
time. ``Our coastline deserves protection forever,'' said Boxer,
noting that Clinton's announcement moved the nation down ``the path
toward permanent protection.''
</P>
<P>
   The moratorium on new offshore drilling initially had been
imposed in 1990 by President George Bush, for 10 years ending in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1813EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0301 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4290 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GUNNISONPARK22-COX     10-21 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNNISONPARK22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    PRESIDENT SIGNS BILL DESIGNATING BLACK CANYON A NATIONAL PARK
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The world-famous gorges of the Black Canyon of the
Gunnison River reached a new status Thursday as President Clinton
signed a bill making the Colorado landmark the nation's 55th
national park.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other canyon in North America combines the remarkable
depth, narrowness and sheerness of the Black Canyon of the
Gunnison,'' the president said. ``It's nearly vertical walls,
rising half a mile high, harbor one of the most spectacular
stretches of wild river in America.''
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was especially sweet for Sen. Ben Nighthorse
Campbell, R-Colo., who has pushed for the national park designation
for more than a dozen years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels just wonderful,'' he said, minutes after attending
the White House signing. ``I'll tell you, there were a few times
that I was thinking maybe it wasn't worth the effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell introduced several bills through the years trying to
upgrade the 21,000-acre national monument to a national park. The
last Colorado park to receive the designation was the Rocky
Mountain National Park in 1915.
</P>
<P>
   The senator faced serious obstacles along the way _ many over
environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   A smiling Rep. Scott McInnis, R-Grand Junction, also attended
the White House signing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have for several years introduced this legislation,'' he
said. ``This year Ben and I sensed that we had the momentum and we
took advantage of it and it happened. It's signed today. It' s
official.... I'm in euphoria.''
</P>
<P>
   McInnis thanked Campbell and the Democrats in the Colorado
delegation for their help in getting the bill through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was touch and go even in the last three weeks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Canyon park, 12 miles east of Montrose, Colo., has
220,000 visitors each year that delight in its spectacular gorges
that cut as deep as 2,900 feet to the Gunnison River.
</P>
<P>
   The national park designation adds nearly 10,000 acres to the
canyon's boundaries. It designates about 4,100 acres inside the
canyon as wilderness, allows for 1,300 acres of conservation
easements along the rim views and establishes the 57,000-acre
Gunnison Gorge National Conservation Area at the park's borders.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the legislation streamlines federal management of
the Black Canyon by bringing together the National Park Service and
the Bureau of Land Management in a ``cooperative and fiscally
responsible manner, while recognizing existing land use plans,''
Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Campbell and McInnis will be at the Black Canyon park at
11:30 a.m Saturday (10/23 ) for a dedication ceremony near the
visitors' center at the south rim, overlooking one of it's
2000-foot deep gorges.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said Thursday he was ``delighted'' that Clinton gave
the park designation bill a formal signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``An area of this grandeur certainly deserves the trappings of
the Oval Office,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1814EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4291 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-OFFSHORE-OIL-2ND     10-21 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-OFFSHORE-OIL-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE URGES BAN ON NEW OIL DRILLING IN CALIFORNIA, FLORIDA WATERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: FILED IN ``w'' and ``p'' categories.)  
