NYT-10-21-99 1814EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4292 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-BIOTECH-TRADE-$ADV24-     10-21 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-TRADE-$ADV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GENE-MODIFIED FOOD DRIVING HUGE INTERNATIONAL TRADE DISPUTE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, Oct. 24.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Disagreement over the safety of using transplanted
genes in food crops is causing a major dispute between the United
States and its European trading partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is potentially a disaster,'' Rep. Gil Gutknecht, R-Minn.,
said Thursday after being told by a member of the German Bundestag
there was no way German consumers would accept U.S. food products
that contain genetically modified products.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made it very clear that we could negotiate all we want to
but in the end, he didn't think Europeans in general and Germans in
particular would ever eat products that had been genetically
modified.''
</P>
<P>
   That's about half of the soybeans produced in America and
one-third of the corn crop.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has taken the position that food
products made from genetically modified organisms, or GMOs, are
safe, and that restriction on their import into European countries
amounts to a violation of international trade law.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. position and the adamant refusal of European
governments to accept imports of products made from GMOs could
dominate a meeting of the World Trade Organization in Seattle in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Previous trade disputes, such as European resistance to American
beef from cattle treated with growth hormones and U.S. unhappiness
about European banana importing policies, have led the United
States to impose 100 percent duties on such European products as
beef, pork, canned tomatoes, cheese, mustard, leather goods, coffee
machines and batteries.
</P>
<P>
   But these disputes could pale compared to the row over GMOs, say
some economists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could derail not just trade in genetically modified crops
and not just agricultural trade,'' said University of Minnesota
farm economists C. Ford Runge. ``It could potentially affect the
progress toward trade liberalization, generally.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither an established European consumer movement against GMO
foods or a growing movement in the United States has been able to
point to specific dangers posed by genetically manipulated crops.
</P>
<P>
   Runge dismisses opposition to GMOs as ``phantasmagoric fears.''
</P>
<P>
   But the lack of labeling in the United States and a secretive
approach to the issue by U.S. regulatory agencies since the Bush
administration have fueled growing suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is under enormous pressure from the
companies that produce genetically altered seeds, the farmers who
plant them and the companies that manufacture food products from
the farmers' crops to hold the line in favor of genetically
engineered crops.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the growing movement of environmental and
consumer groups is questioning the effectiveness of the U.S.
regulatory procedures involved in approving genetically engineered
crop varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Such organizations as the Consumers Union, Greenpeace, Friends
of the Earth, the Sierra Club and Mothers and Others for a Livable
Planet have begun to demand that products containing genetically
engineered harvest bear label disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody told people they had to buy an Edsel,'' said Consumers
Union official Mark Silbergeld, referring to Ford Motor Co.'s
legendary automotive flop of the late 1950s. ``If it's an Edsel,
you can do two things: You can tell them it's not an Edsel or you
can put it out there and tell them what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers want the right to choose what they eat, he said, and
they will far less inclined to accept genetically modified products
when they learn that they have been eating them without knowing it
for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations such as the Grocery Manufacturers Association of
America contend that U.S. regulation of GMOs is based on the best
scientific information and is being assaulted by ``activists'' with
a political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acting together, food companies, lawmakers, scientists,
farmers and regulators must work to ensure that activists with a
political agenda do not kill the promise of biotech foods,'' said
Gary Kushner, the grocery group's Washington lawyer, in testimony
before the Senate Agriculture Committee this month.
</P>
<P>
   The association's spokesman, Brian Sansoni, said the ``political
agenda'' of such activists is simple: to kill the genetically
engineered food industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's fueled by anti-corporate sentiment or
anti-capitalism sentiment or (in the case of European groups)
anti-American sentiment or all of the above, their agenda is to
kill this technology, to stop it dead in its tracks,'' said
Sansoni. ``Right now, they're going after the mandatory labeling
route as a step toward their ultimate goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The grocery manufacturers, as well as seed producers, some farm
groups and some members of Congress, have criticized officials at
the Food and Drug Administration, the U.S. Department of
Agriculture and the Environmental Protection Agency for failing to
more forcefully defend U.S. regulatory practices.
</P>
<P>
   Partly as a result of that criticism, FDA has scheduled a series
of three hearings around the country in December to hear what the
public thinks of its genetic engineering policies and to try to
better explain them.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups have predicted the hearings will be flooded with
``thousands'' of Americans who are unhappy about the fact that they
have been unknowingly eating food from genetically engineered
crops.
</P>
<P>
   That could be interesting, since the hearings have been
scheduled for the same month that U.S. officials will be attempting
to persuade their counterparts from other countries at the Seattle
World Trade Organization meeting that U.S. policies ensure the
crops are safe.
</P>
<P>
   To some members of Congress, the scientific arguments may be of
secondary importance, given all that's at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me give you a scientific fact: We can't eat all that we
grow in this country. We have got to export,'' Gutknecht said.
``This is a huge challenge. We have got to figure out a way to
communicate and a way to negotiate with our trading partners.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
