<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4294 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-FORBES-2000-HNS &LR;      10-21 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES OUTLINES PLAN TO BOOST ECONOMY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Republican presidential candidate Steve
Forbes proposed Thursday a plan to boost the American economy by
overhauling the federal income tax and letting younger workers
invest their Social Security dollars in personal retirement
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning as a Washington outsider and a more conservative
alternative to Republican front-runner George W. Bush, Forbes also
pledged to fight for a longtime goal of conservative Republicans, a
constitutional amendment to require a two-thirds ``supermajority''
vote of Congress to raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time to remove the big government barriers that stand in
our way so that every American is free to take full advantage of
the new economy,'' the magazine publisher said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes announced his plan on the front lawn of Steve and
Katherine Frink's house after giving them a private briefing inside
with his wife, Sabina, performing one of the quadrennial political
rituals in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   He called his plan the ``first comprehensive approach to allow
Americans to realize the American dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Frink said he is still undecided in the presidential race, but
told reporters he likes Forbes' plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with him that he has the most substance on the
table,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said his tax plan would save the Frink family more than
$1,000 in federal income tax each year.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes vowed to ``dramatically'' reduce interest rates and
protect the soundness of the U.S. dollar by appointing Federal
Reserve Board members who ``understand that prosperity does not
cause inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   He also promised to impose new spending caps on nondefense
discretionary spending, tear down trade barriers, abolish the
departments of Energy and Commerce, and eliminate funding for the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The plan eliminates loopholes and corporate tax shelters and in
return, he says, reduces the business tax rate from 35 percent to
17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The cornerstone of Forbes' economic plan would be a flat tax,
which he said would remove 20 million low-income workers from the
federal income tax rolls.
</P>
<P>
   His proposal would provide personal exemptions of $13,000 for
each adult and $5,000 for each child. That means a family of four
earning $36,000 a year would pay no federal income tax, a savings
of $1,670 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said his proposal would simplify the tax system and wipe
out death taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said taxpayers would be free to file under the current
system or the new system but predicted, ``Most people will quickly
see how much they benefit with the flat tax.''
</P>
<P>
   The publisher promised to ``fully protect'' current Social
Security benefits for Americans 55 and older _ ``no benefit cuts,
no tax increases, no more raiding the Social Security Trust Fund.''
</P>
<P>
   But younger workers, he said, could choose to invest their
Social Security money into personal retirement accounts that they
alone would control.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would begin with one-third of their Social Security
taxes in 2002 and increase to two-thirds in 2006.
</P>
<P>
   According to Forbes' example, a single working mother who is 25
in the year 2000 could retire in 2040 with a nest egg of $1.2
million. He said she could use that money to buy an annuity that
would pay $100,000 a year, or $37,000 in 1999 dollars, almost twice
as much as she would receive from the current Social Security
System.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes also proposed the creation of a ``guaranteed safety net''
for those retirees whose personal accounts don't provide a minimum
level of benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican candidate also promised to ``dramatically expand
parental control of education'' by allowing states to control their
Title 1 federal education grant money, provided the states use the
money to give parents ``true choice'' in where to educate their
children, including private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' school plan goes further than that of Texas Gov. Bush,
who has proposed that if a school is low-performing for three years
in a row, the federal government would strip it of some of its
Title I funding and give that money to the parents directly. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Forbes predicted that U.S. economic growth, under his plan,
will surge from between 2.1 percent and 2.4 percent in 2001 to at
least 4 percent in 2002 and will average at least 4.5 percent a
year for the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted the economy will grow from $9.8 trillion in 2001 to
$17.2 trillion in 2010, a 75 percent increase. He also predicted
the creation of 24.5 million new jobs by 2010, higher wages and a
60 percent reduction in the federal debt by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term economic projections for Forbes' proposals were
developed by Fiscal Associates, a Virginia financial forecasting
firm hired by the Forbes campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dare not entrust our fate to the lawyers, lobbyists and
lifetime politicians who control Washington today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
