<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4307 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BUSH-PAPERS-HNS &LR;      10-21 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PAPERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PRESIDENT BREAKS TRADITION IN RELEASING 18,000 PAGES OF
PERSONAL DOCUMENTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ While Gov. George W. Bush tries to keep
part of his past under wraps, his father is exposing his own
history in a groundbreaking way.
</P>
<P>
   About 18,000 pages of former President Bush's letters, diaries
and other personal documents became available Thursday to
journalists, scholars and other researchers. They cover a 36-year
period, from World War II until just prior to Bush's terms as vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush donated his papers to the George Bush Presidential Library
and Museum at Texas A&AMP;M University a few years ago. More recently,
he agreed to release his personal items for study _ before his
death.
</P>
<P>
   That's what makes the gesture unusual. The other living
ex-presidents _ Gerald Ford, Jimmy Carter and Ronald Reagan _ have
their personal papers under seal while they are alive, according to
David Alsobrook, executive director of the Bush facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tells us a lot about him, that he does want people to come
and study his life,'' Alsobrook said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Bush documents are bound to turn political heads.
</P>
<P>
   The collection includes Bush's memos, as chairman of the
national Republican Party, to the Republican president, Richard
Nixon, in the year and a half before Nixon's resignation in August
1974.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said in one of the memos that Democrat Barbara Jordan,
serving then as the first black Congress member from Houston, had
volunteered as a secret, unofficial political consultant for the
GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbara has secretly offered to consult me on a
non-attributable basis about Black attitudes, Black problems,
etc,'' Bush told Nixon in February 1973. ``She'll undoubtedly fight
us on programs but she won't use this channel to embarrass me. She
conceivably could help in getting southern liberals to vote for
Republicans instead of conservative Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no indication from the documents whether Jordan ever
followed through. In the following year she voted for Nixon's
impeachment as a member of the House Judiciary Committee. She died
a steadfast Democrat in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the Bush documents coincides with the publication
of the 75-year-old former president's book, ``All The Best, George
Bush: My Life In Letters And Other Writings.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, Bush delivered a campus lecture about the
book.
</P>
<P>
   It is called ``the most intimate and revealing look at one of
America's most private public figures'' by its publisher, Scribner.
But the New York Times Book Review said it is devoid of ``a single
glittering sentence or brilliant observation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said the collection of letters is in lieu of a memoir
about his life in and out of the White House. Such a work, he said,
has already been written by his wife. It is called ``Barbara Bush:
A Memoir'' and was published in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The former president's new book starts with letters he wrote to
his parents from a Navy aviation school in 1942 and ends with
letters he wrote to friends as a retired grandfather enjoying life
in Houston this year.
</P>
<P>
   Soon to follow the ex-president's book is an autobiography by
his son George W. Bush, the leading GOP contender for president.
The Texas governor has already stated, however, that he will not
provide details of what he calls his ``young and irresponsible''
days.
</P>
<P>
   The papers released at the Bush Library cover the elder Bush's
career from 1943 through 1979, before he served as vice president
and president but including his stints as a pilot, businessman,
congressional candidate, ambassador, Republican Party chief and
director of the CIA.
</P>
<P>
   Of particular interest in the papers is Bush's ``Peking Diary,''
which he wrote while serving as the U.S. envoy to China 1974-75,
Alsobrook said. Scholars will likely consider it a trove for the
study of U.S. foreign policy, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   A few portions of the diary were removed in the interest of
national security, Alsobrook said. Also, the library has received
from Bush only the documents that he wanted to be disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is a departure from tradition. Other ex-presidents
have put some of their government documents on display during their
lifetimes but have arranged for personal papers to be held back
until after their death.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be stuff in there they don't want to be accountable
for in their lifetimes,'' University of Texas professor Bruce
Buchanan, an expert on the presidency, said of the tradition. ``And
there may be personal stuff they just don't think is anybody's
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Former President Bush apparently has a ``squeaky clean''
background that makes him less reluctant to release personal
papers, Buchanan said, so ``this sounds like something new and
different'' for scholars who study presidential papers.
</P>
<P>
   Alsobrook said the Bush papers could make other former
presidents re-think their adherence to tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be interesting to see, when we open ours, if the
others follow suit,'' said Alsobrook, who worked as the supervisory
archivist at the library housing former President Carter's papers.
</P>
<P>
   The 18,000 pages of Bush documents represent a smidgen of the 4
million pages that have been collected by the Bush Library. Much of
that comes from government sources and people who provided
information about Bush.
</P>
<P>
   About 300 researchers have examined Bush documents at the
library since it opened in January 1998. But the document release
Thursday caused no land rush: By mid-afternoon, the only person who
signed in to inspect them was a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Some of the materials are mundane collections of newspaper
clippings, and a mostly blank appointment book from 1968, the year
George W. Bush graduated from college.
</P>
<P>
   But the file on former President Bush's days as chairman of the
national GOP appears to throw new light on the Watergate scandal,
which led to Nixon's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   In handwritten notes about a Nixon ``enemies list'' put together
by White House aides, Bush said in July 1973 that the list was
``dumb, because those idiots that put it together were so knee-jerk
that they fouled it up _ they put people on the list who eventually
supported the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush expressed his faith in Nixon in the same memo, however,
saying that the president ``would not demean our constitution.''
Two months later, the documents show, Nixon sent Bush a note
thanking Bush for ``your constant loyal friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   In August 1974, however, Bush urged Nixon to resign _ as Nixon
did a day later. Bush quit as party chief a few weeks afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Two months after becoming chairman, Bush wrote to Nixon aide
H.R. Haldeman in March 1973 with suggestions about how to change
the image of the party's operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eliminate phone in car _ eliminate full-time driver _
eliminate liquor from premises (with personal reluctance because
after some of the backbiting, hand-holding days, I could use a
swallow),'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
