<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4310 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CLINTON-SENATE-HNS &LR;      10-21 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLIMTON CITES MORE DIFFERENCES WITH GIULIANI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton tried to poke
holes Thursday in New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's claims that an
economic miracle is buoying the fortunes of everyone in the
nation's largest city.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, expected to announce her New York Senate candidacy in
January, told leaders of New York's 265,000-member Civil Service
Employees Association at a meeting here that poverty is actually
rising in some neighborhoods in the city governed by her likely
Republican rival.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Giuliani have completed legal steps required to run
for the Senate, but they have not yet declared their candidacies to
succeed retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton drew issue-by-issue distinctions with positions taken by
Giuliani during her 28-minute address. It was the first time that
she has staged a public event here relating to the New York race.
</P>
<P>
   Her red-meat speech appeared to delight many in the audience of
1,100 leaders of the bipartisan union that represents state, county
and local government employees as well as some private sector
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go into New York City, you would think that everybody
is just enjoying the most amazing economic boom that the world has
ever seen,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   She agreed that for many New Yorkers, poverty is on the wane as
it is across the nation, thanks to the longest peacetime economic
boom in American history.
</P>
<P>
   But she said that ``in the midst of this incredible economic
boom there are neighborhoods in New York City that have not yet
realized the full benefits. So we have work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton praised a White House initiative that provides private
enterprises many of the same tax breaks and incentives to invest in
America's inner cities that have been available for years to firms
investing in markets overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time that we brought that economic opportunity back
to New York and around the country,'' she declared.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign spokesman, Howard Wolfson, said her remarks
were the third effort she had made in the past week to draw
distinctions between herself and Giuliani on certain issues. But
Clinton herself never mentioned Giuliani by name in her Thursday
speech.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that she supports hiking the minimum wage, expanding
the earned income tax credit for the working poor, strengthening
patient rights in health maintenance organizations and devoting the
federal budget surplus to bolstering Social Security and Medicare.
She said these positions contrasted with those of ``some who
believe'' that no action is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have work to do,'' Clinton declared, repeatedly
arousing ovations from the audience. ``We've made a lot of progress
together, but that progress could be reversed if people who don't
share those values hold office into the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady also discounted Giuliani's claims of being the
crime buster who made New York City safe for suburbanites. She said
White House programs, including one using federal funds to put more
police on the street, have driven the nationwide crime rate down to
mid-1960s levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a tremendous accomplishment, and I am pleased that
mayors and police chiefs all over America supported the president's
anticrime strategy,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Union President Danny Donohue said the organization has endorsed
Republicans and Democrats for office in New York state. He said
that in 1991 it gave Bill Clinton one of the earliest union
endorsements of his first presidential campaign. But last year the
union did not endorse either U.S. Senate candidate _ then-Rep.
Charles Schumer, a Democrat, and Republican incumbent Alfonse
D'Amato. Schumer won.
</P>
<P>
   As for Hillary Clinton, Donohue said, ``our members decide to
support candidates based on their positions on issues that we care
about, not based on the party of the candidate. People in New York
know that the first lady is right on most of our issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Guiliani has opposed moves in Congress to hike the $5.15 minimum
wage by $1 over the next two years because he said it might
jeopardize entry-level jobs being filled by former welfare
recipients moving into the work force. He also backed the
Republican-passed $792 billion tax cut over 10 years that President
Clinton vetoed.
</P>
<P>
   In New York Thursday, Giuliani took part in a $100,000 breakfast
fund-raiser with 1,600 ``Women for Rudy,'' many wearing lapel
buttons with a slash through a picture of the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Rep. Susan Molinari, R-N.Y. derided the first lady's
appearances around the state to listen to New Yorkers' concerns. In
contrast to ``months of listening by Mrs. Clinton,'' Giuliani has
demonstrated ``months of action,'' Molinari said.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
e-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
