<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4316 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ADVANCEFUNDING22-COX     10-21 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADVANCEFUNDING22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS USES ADVANCE PLANNING, DELAYED PAYING TO ASSIST
BUDGETING
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the squeeze to pass budget bills that fit under
this year's budget caps, Congress is increasingly planning to pay
later for what it promises now.
</P>
<P>
   That is, lawmakers are pledging funds for programs, including
education for the disadvantaged, job training and the Head Start
program for preschoolers. But some of those outlays would be put
off until the following fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advanced funding,'' as the technique is called, has long been
used by Congress on a limited basis for programs that cross over
into the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The practice has now become the most popular way to avoid the
tight spending limits for fiscal year 2000. The Congressional
Budget Office estimates that more than $20 billion in spending
authority from bills now moving through Capitol Hill would be held
over until the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
   That's roughly double the advance spending approved last year
and ten times as much as Congress approved for 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those gimmick indicators,'' said Robert Bixby,
executive director of the Concord Coalition, a nonpartisan watchdog
group on the budget. The delayed spending merely postpones the
problem of meeting spending limits, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're gambling that the non-Social Security surplus will be
higher next year and that they can therefore afford to put this
spending off into the next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Advanced spending won't necessarily bust the budget this year,
but it does little for the credibility of the budget-making
process, says Bixby and other budget watchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the appearance of cutting spending when they're
not,'' said James Horney, a senior fellow at the Center on Budget
and Policy Priorities, a liberal think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it makes the problem even worse for next year, when
the budget caps will be even tighter. ``When they get to '01,
they're back where they started,'' Horney said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Bixby said that the final result is still
uncertain because Congress is passing the spending bills based on a
vast array of projections for the $1.8 trillion federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably will comply with the goal of balancing the
budget on paper, and a lot of us will say it will only be with
gimmicks,'' Bixby said. ``We'll probably have to wait until next
year to find out how it all worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   en dit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
