<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Friday, Oct. 22 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan. (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   GORE-ENVIRON (Rye, N.H.) _ In the most dramatic proposal of his
candidacy, Vice President Al Gore said Thursday that as president
he would ban any new offshore drilling for oil and gas along the
California and Florida coasts. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-POVERTY _ Describing poverty as a ``slow-motion national
disaster,'' former Sen. Bill Bradley called Thursday for reducing
the number of poor children by half over the coming decade by
raising the minimum wage, increasing spending on child-care
programs and providing an array of tax benefits to poor parents who
work. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BIOGRAPHY (Washington) _ St. Martin's Press is withdrawing
a new biography of George W. Bush after questions about the book's
allegations of his drug use lead to the discovery that the author
is a convicted felon. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-POLITICS (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ In a act of
reconciliation and also of power politics, an emotional national
assembly on Thursday elected the highly popular Megawati
Sukarnoputri to the post of vice president, one day after voting
down her bid for the presidency. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-CARE (Washington) _ Early-childhood education has a
dramatic impact that lasts through young adulthood, affecting
everything from reading and math skills to the timing of
child-bearing, researchers in the first-ever study that tracked
participants from infancy to age 21 announced Thursday. By Jodi
Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ALZHEIMER (Undated) _ New findings on brain development open
up possibilities for treating Alzheimer's. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN-WEB (Undated) _ The launch of Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter's new online stock trading service was not as easy as
planned, and one reason involves a tangled tale of either youthful
innocence or cybersquatting. By Patrick McGeehan and Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DAIRY-FARMS (Los Angeles) _ As suburban sprawl once again
forces dairy farms to move beyond Los Angeles, one of the striking
things is that, just as happened in the move from Los Angeles
County several decades ago, a big increase in farmers' land values
is financing a transition that will result not in broken dreams or
the end of a way of life, but in a new generation of highly
efficient dairies that will only widen California's lead over
Wisconsin and the No. 3 dairy state, New York. In an odd twist, the
spread of all those new subdivisions and their backyard swimming
pools has proven something of a boon to the dairy industry. By
James Sterngold.
</P>
