<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-CADETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPS ENROLLMENT DOWN AT TEXAS A&AMP;M 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim, optional ending) 
 
By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M University's Corps of Cadets, which produces more
military officers than any U.S. school outside the service
academies, has seen a 10.7 percent drop in enrollment this fall,
officials confirmed this week.
</P>
<P>
   Only 1,962 cadets, including 149 women, are enrolled in the ROTC
program, compared with 2,197 last fall, said Doc Mills, spokesman
for the corps. The corps signed up 564 freshman recruits this fall;
last year there were 776 freshmen, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been ups and downs, ups and downs,'' said Mills, a
former cadet. ``This year, we had a down. Next year, we hope it
will be up again.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills and Will Schrank, the corps' recruiting director, said
part of the reason enrollment is down is that the College Station
university had an abnormally large freshman class last year, and an
unusually small one this year, shrinking the pool of potential
corps applicants.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a new standardized application form for all state
universities does not include a box to check if prospective
students want to indicate their interest in the corps.
</P>
<P>
   But Mills and Schrank said other factors also may be at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it could be the general unpopularity of military
service or military careers these days,'' Mills said. ``It could
also be the booming economy that makes civilian careers much more
attractive. A lot of these students come from the civilian economy
and they bring those attitudes with them when they come to
school.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the corps also declines when the U.S. military is
engaged overseas, Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this class was making the decision of what colleges to
apply to and whether to come into the corps or not, there was the
Kosovo air campaign, with people shooting at one another,'' he
said. ``Historically, we find that moms get a little jittery about
sending their sons to a military organization when there are people
shooting at each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills said the corps' goal, which is unlikely to be met, was to
reach 2,600 cadets by next year. That number would fill the 12
dormitories that are set aside for the corps. Currently rooms in
two of the dorms are occupied by civilian students.
</P>
<P>
   Schrank said that while he is watching the numbers, he's more
concerned about attracting quality cadets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going after the top students,'' he said. ``But beyond
the academic qualifications, we're looking for those who have been
actively involved in leadership positions in high school, whether
it be in athletics, or student government, or other organizations.
We're not going after those who have been couch potatoes for four
years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To attract such students, the corps staff and former and current
cadets mail out brochures and participate in ``phone pushes,''
using telemarketing techniques to persuade high school juniors and
seniors to come to campus and check out the corps.
</P>
<P>
   Prospective members are then invited to a ``Spend the Night with
the Corps'' program. Each year, 1,600 to 1,800 high schoolers
accept. They go to class with a corps member, stay overnight in the
corps dorms and meet with the university's admissions and financial
aid counselors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Aggie tradition may be the biggest reason A&AMP;M students
join the corps, Schrank said many cadets are attracted by the
corps' discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a more structured lifestyle with a major focus on
academic excellence,'' he said. ``A lot of students who want to go
to med school or law school are attracted to the corps because they
believe it's a place where they can focus on their studies, rather
than going out to bars, clubs or movies, or whatever else college
students do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Call to Quarters,'' a mandatory study hall, forces cadets to
sit at their desks and study for three hours a night, Sunday
through Thursday. And as students approach graduation, career
counselors help connect them with business people, many of whom are
former Aggies, who are interested in recruiting cadets for
internships and full-time jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Other cadets join for the instant friendship and camaraderie on
a campus with more than 42,000 students, Schrank said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can be part of a smaller tightknit group of students
where everybody in the dorm knows them by name, where upperclassmen
look out for them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And even though only 30 percent of the cadets sign up for
military service after graduation, Schrank said the corps in recent
years has improved its services for the other 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever they end up, they're going to have to know how to
work with people,'' he said. ``They're going to have to know how to
follow, how to lead, how to interact with people at work. Those are
skills they can learn in the corps.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Schrank said officials are now concentrating on recruiting for
next year, which is going well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have a goal to increase corps enrollment,'' he said,
``but I'm not discouraged by these numbers. I'm very optimistic
about where we're headed and about the future of the corps.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
