<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SARGENT-ART-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SARGENT PORTRAITS OF 9 MEMBERS OF A BRITISH FAMILY UNITED AT THE
JEWISH MUSEUM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The chutzpah of Asher Wertheimer! A rich London art
dealer and the son of a self-made German Jew, he commissioned John
Singer Sargent (1856-1925), then at the height of his fame as a
portraitist, to paint no less than a dozen likenesses of his
family. He willed that nine of them should join the pantheon of
great British citizens at the National Portrait Gallery after his
and his wife's deaths.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so much the portraits _ Sargent's biggest commission
from a single family _ as the ``gift'' to the nation that roused
the ire of English worthies. Too many and too much for some
officials _ one member of Parliament referred to the paintings as
``clever, but extremely repulsive'' _ the Wertheimer portraits were
exhibited as an ensemble for a short time, then sent to the Tate
Gallery, where they hung together in a room devoted to Sargent. But
the artist's reputation was by then in decline, and the
installation was eventually dismantled, with all but two of the
paintings consigned to storage.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in ``John Singer Sargent: Portraits of the Wertheimer
Family'' at the Jewish Museum here, all of the portraits are
together again, for the first time since they hung at the
Wertheimer's London residence more than 70 years ago. The dozen
works _ some dazzling, a few tepid _ done from 1898 to 1908, are
fittingly on view in what was once the drawing rooms of the Warburg
house, owned by a privileged Jewish family contemporary with the
Wertheimers that is now the home of the Jewish Museum.
</P>
<P>
   But why single out these Jewish subjects from the 600-odd
aristocrats, politicians, merchant princes, society ladies,
theatrical personalities and others, both striving and arrived, who
beat a path to this high-style virtuoso's easel? The Wertheimers
were not Sargent's only Jewish subjects; he had painted the
Sassoons and the Rothschilds, among others. But the Wertheimer
ensemble, because of its size and the less secure social footing of
its participants, raises interesting issues: among them the
position of Jews in English society; Sargent's clever adaptation of
English ``grand manner'' portraiture to flatter contemporary
climbers, and the efforts of the arriviste Wertheimer to gain
status for his family by insinuating their portraits into a museum
devoted to exalted Britons.
</P>
<P>
   Such matters as these are tellingly taken up in the catalog by
Norman L. Kleeblatt, curator of fine arts at the Jewish Museum and
organizer of the exhibition; Kathleen Adler, head of education at
the National Gallery in London whose research inspired the show;
Trevor Fairbrother, a Sargent specialist and deputy director and
curator of modern art at the Seattle Art Museum, and Michelle
Lapine, assistant curator of the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   As for the portraits themselves, there is Asher Wertheimer
(1898), depicted as a sensuous, convivial man with a cigar in his
left hand, his dog, Noble, large pink tongue hanging out, seated at
his right. (The Wertheimer family loved this portrait, and it has
always been a popular one with the museumgoing public.) There is
his wife, Flora (1904), looking sternly matriarchal in a proper
black dress as she sits in a sumptuous chair. There are group and
individual renderings of the 10 Wertheimer children, including a
double portrait of the two oldest daughters, Ena and Betty (1901).
Shown as the vivacious Edwardian belles they were, in a bravura
work that is today considered one of Sargent's masterpieces, they
too exude sexual vitality.
</P>
<P>
   It's the contention of Ms. Adler that Sargent _ who enjoyed an
affectionate relationship with the Wertheimers _ not disapprovingly
stressed their Jewishness in his portraits, giving them the slight
edge of caricature and stereotype that he conferred on many of his
subjects, Jewish or not.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, she writes, the exuberant portrait of the two daughters in
their decollete gowns alludes to ``a fantasy of the sexual Jewess''
held by non-Jews; the portrait of their father ``could be, and
indeed often was, regarded as the very image of the stereotype of
the rich Jew, excessively flashy and, since art dealing was viewed
as only slightly above moneylending, probably of somewhat dubious
honesty.''
</P>
<P>
   Sargent's depiction of a third daughter, Almina (1908), puts her
in a Persian costume holding a musical instrument from northern
India. ``The portrait is in many respects a parody, a play on the
stereotype of the Jewish (or Oriental) princess,'' writes Ms.
Adler.
</P>
<P>
   But Sargent, an ``outsider'' himself by virtue of his American
origins and his homosexuality, dined weekly chez Wertheimer and was
close to Asher and Ena. If he saw them as ethnically exploitable
subjects, he also took the view that they were ``interesting
models'' and ``reliable patrons,'' words he used about Jewish
subjects in general to a colleague. He observed to friends that he
preferred painting Jewish to English women because they had ``more
life and movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Adler adds that these portraits are not simply caricatural
nor do they simply subscribe to anti-Semitic stereotypes. Sargent's
knowledge of and affection for the family works to counter this
stereotype and his sitters, particularly Ena and Almina, appear to
have delighted in the opportunity to strike exaggerated poses and
wear fancy dress.
</P>
<P>
   But putting aside the ``Jewish'' issues surrounding the
Wertheimer portraits, the ensemble _ a whole greater than the sum
of all its parts _ gives a wonderful account not only of Sargent's
bold brushwork but also of his talent for finding and projecting
his subjects' individual identities. Despite the bombast of clothes
and settings, the family comes across as a very human company.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   There is yet another entry in the spate of recent Sargent shows
(the major spread was the Tate Gallery retrospective at the
National Gallery of Art in Washington and the Museum of Fine Arts
in Boston) that have been re-evaluating his career and reputation.
If you hurry, you can see ``John Singer Sargent, Draughtsman: Works
From the Corcoran Gallery of Art'' at the Grey Art Gallery of New
York University.
</P>
<P>
   With over 90 works on paper from the collection of the Corcoran
Gallery in Washington, the show ranges from European landscapes
made at the age of 12 (born to American expatriates, Sargent spent
his life abroad) to studies for mural commissions by the Boston
Public Library and its Museum of Fine Arts. Also included are
sketches _ poignant and mundane _ of soldiers and military
activities done at the Western front during World War I. Sargent
later used them in a major painting, ``Gassed'' (1918-19),
commissioned by the Imperial War Museum and in a commemorative
mural for the Widener Library at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   The drawings reveal Sargent's growing mastery of draftsmanship
and his concern with the expressive possibilities of line,
silhouette and shading. In later studies of the figure, he
relentlessly explored every conceivable twist or turn that human or
animal bodies could take. As his theme for the library mural
commission Sargent chose a history of the world's religions. Among
the painstaking male nude and animal studies he did for it is ``Man
Screaming'' (1895-1910), an affecting rendition of a man writhing
in agony, head down, mouth open, hands clenched in fists on his
chest.
</P>
<P>
   Compare this with the genteel classical maidens, ``The
Danaides,'' a series of women representing the many sources of
wisdom that he did as part of a mural decoration for the museum.
Using models said to have been drawn from the Ziegfeld Follies, he
drew the women, draped in classical garments, carrying jugs as they
paraded in ceaseless replenishment of the fountain of knowledge.
(The decorations were cited as ``ladylike'' by the art historian
Bernard Berenson.)
</P>
<P>
   Conveying as they do the ``bones'' of Sargent's style, the
drawings give a fascinating look beneath the sensuous surfaces of
his painting, revealing the masterly linear skills that accompanied
the seemingly effortless flow of his brush. Unfortunately, few of
his portrait drawings are here, but the show is a worthy addendum
to the splashier displays of Sargent on canvas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
