<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRUE WEST' ON BROADWAY; FUTURE OF `RAGTIME'; AN AUSTRALIAN IS
CAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``True West,'' Sam Shepard's dark comedy about a pair
of feuding brothers on the make in Hollywood, is coming to
Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Rehearsals will likely begin in mid-December for a February
opening at Circle in the Square. Casting was coming together late
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Kastner is the producer. The director will be Matthew
Warchus, who directed an acclaimed version of the play in 1994 at
the Donmar Warehouse in London and recently directed a film version
of Shepard's ``Simpatico.''
</P>
<P>
   A perennial favorite of angry young acting students and their
directors, ``True West'' tells the story of Austin and Lee, a
screenwriter and a layabout, whose fortunes reverse in a hail of
sibling rivalry and demolished toasters. The play had its New York
premiere at the Public Theater in 1980, but its seminal production
came in 1982 when two then-unknowns named Gary Sinise and John
Malkovich took the stage in an Off Broadway revival at the Cherry
Lane Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The news coincides with the announcement that the on-again,
off-again production of Yasmina Reza's ``Unexpected Man'' is off
again. The production was to have been directed by Warchus, but
producers said this week that they had not found a male lead to
play opposite the already confirmed Eileen Atkins, and would delay
plans for a January production at the Gramercy Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The Roundabout Theater Co., which was to have been the
co-producer of the play, said it had no replacement production, but
that a possibility was Martin Sherman's ``Rose,'' about one woman's
life as part of the Jewish Diaspora. The play, which ran at
London's Royal National Theater last summer, starred Olympia
Dukakis, who would likely appear in New York as well.
</P>
<P>
   A SOBERING SONG
</P>
<P>
   Might it be time for ``Ragtime'' to go?
</P>
<P>
   That's the question being mulled by producers of the show, a
big-budget musical that has seen its box-office receipts thin in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Discussions about the production's future have been going on
since August, when the show's original producer, Livent Inc., was
bought by SFX Entertainment, the country's largest producer of live
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've assessed all the information about the show,'' said
Miles Wilkin, chairman of Pace Theatrical Group, a subsidiary of
SFX, ``and we're in the process of coming to a conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkin would not provide specifics, but three options are being
considered. The first is to shrink the size of the production's
cast and other expenses to permit a longer run at the Ford Center
of the Performing Arts, where the musical plays. That would require
a six-week hiatus to adhere to Actors Equity union rules forbidding
sudden downsizing.
</P>
<P>
   In another scenario, the show would shrink, move to a different
theater, and the Ford Center would be rented to another production.
</P>
<P>
   The third option, and the least palatable one for the producers
and creative crew, would be to close the production altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkin said a decision could be made within the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   With a large cast, a lavish production and generous contracts
held over its Livent days, ``Ragtime'' has long had one of the
highest operating costs on Broadway. Before recent cost cuts, the
weekly expenses often exceeded $600,000. That number seemed
acceptable when the show was reporting grosses of more than
$800,000 a week, as it did for much of 1998 and early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But visions of a ``Cats''-style run have faded as recent
box-office figures have sagged. For the week ending Sunday,
``Ragtime'' grossed $600,010. In the second week of September, the
gross sunk to $420,902.
</P>
<P>
   Producers have received royalty concessions from the creative
staff and overtime concessions from stagehands, which have cut
operating costs to about $530,000 a week. A new marketing campaign
has also helped sales, Wilkin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is trying their hardest,'' he said. ``I'm not saying
it's rare in this business, but it has been encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a ``Ragtime'' closing and an available Ford
Center has prompted speculation around Broadway about who might
fill the show's large shoes. An oft-mentioned candidate is ``Jesus
Christ Superstar,'' the Andrew Lloyd Webber revival, which is
aiming for an April opening. Officials for the production said they
are still seeking a theater, but had no comment on the prospect of
moving to the Ford.
</P>
<P>
   UP FROM DOWN UNDER
</P>
<P>
   David Campbell may be the most respected young musical theater
star in New York to never actually perform in a full-scale
production.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Campbell, a 26-year-old Australian actor and cabaret
singer, has sung in such prized locales as Carnegie Hall and City
Center, and has been cast in workshops of productions from ``Don
Juan DeMarco'' to last week's ``Thoroughly Modern Millie.'' And in
each, the reports have been good to glowing.
</P>
<P>
   But for all that, Campbell has never been in a real show. The
closest he came was in February when he appeared in ``Babes in
Arms,'' part of the Encore musical concert series at City Center.
</P>
<P>
   That is about to change. Starting in January, Campbell is to
lead the cast of ``Saturday Night,'' the early Stephen Sondheim
musical making its New York premiere at Second Stage. Campbell will
play Gene, a character he describes as ``a young man who dreams of
other things and doesn't quite know how to get them.''
</P>
<P>
   That is certainly not the case for Campbell. In the last three
years, he has released two solo CD's, won a handful of cabaret
awards and has been named Young Australian of the Year (narrowly
outpolling Dame Edna).
</P>
<P>
   Most of his performing has been done alone, but ``I didn't plan
it this way, I promise,'' Campbell said. He added, ``It's going to
be good to be able to play with others.''
</P>
<P>
   IN THE PINK AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   The cast of ``James Joyce's `The Dead''' will perform a special
matinee this afternoon at 3 to make up for three performances lost
earlier this week. Marni Nixon, who plays Aunt Kate Morkan, was
sick and had no understudy so performances were canceled on Tuesday
and Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
