<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGING-INSTITUTE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY OF FLORIDA INSTITUTE TO FOCUS ON AGING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BRIAN GELLER   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ A new University of Florida institute will
devote itself to one of Florida's most salient issues: getting
older.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute on Aging, approved recently by the university's
board of regents, will serve as an umbrella organization to foster
multidisciplinary research, education and service, stimulate
increased funding and influence public policy, UF officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A university community really needs to be addressing the
important issues that confront a society,'' said Jeffrey Dwyer,
director of the new institute. ``Arguably, aging is one of those.
When you couple with the state of Florida, then you really begin to
see that the University of Florida ought to be viewed nationally as
a leader in this area.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.S. Census Bureau, the elderly will more than
double in population by 2050, to 80 million. A large part of
Florida's population is made up of people over 65.
</P>
<P>
   Aging-related research has taken place for almost 50 years at
UF. Today, more than 350 faculty members are involved in
aging-related teaching and research.
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer said the institute will coordinate research activity and
provide resources for faculty. The center also will identify areas
of aging-related research and education that UF should study. Then
it will recruit faculty to build those programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nowhere in the country that has the potential we have
at the University of Florida,'' said Dwyer, a professor and head of
the division of aging in the College of Medicine's department of
health policy and epidemiology. ``We're in the state of Florida,
where 19 percent of the population is age 65 or older. And other
states around the country are looking to the state of Florida as
the example of what they're going to be in the next 10, 15 or 20
years.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville, Fla., Sun is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
