<HEADER>
A4360 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-NIKKEI-OPTIMISM-JAPAN     10-21 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIKKEI-OPTIMISM-JAPAN-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SUN FINALLY RISES: JAPAN INC.'S LOSS IS NIKKEI'S GAIN  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Business Editors)   (This 600-word ``separate buy'' financial story is from the October
issue of ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her
e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been double-filed _ into the ``i''
international news and ``f'' financial news files.)  
  
 By TODD G. BUCHHOLZ  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last spring, after dissing Japan for most of the 1990s, I said
it was time to dip at least a toe, and perhaps even a left leg,
into Japanese equities. Since then, the Nikkei index has climbed
more than 30 percent, and choice stocks like Sony have surged more
than that.
</P>
<P>
   Optimism has arrived for a couple of reasons. First, the prices
of Japanese assets finally fell enough to make Japanese firms look
attractive to foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   GE Capital bought Japan Leasing, for example. Japanese firms
have started to see value in one another, too (in August, three of
Japan's biggest banks revealed their intention to merge). By late
spring, professional money managers in New York and London were
realizing they owned hardly any Japanese shares.
</P>
<P>
   Too many portfolio managers running international funds had
slipped up in 1998 by staying away from South Korea as that stock
market roared ahead, and they couldn't afford to make the same
mistake this year. So they have jumped into the Nikkei and driven
it up.
</P>
<P>
   A second transformation has helped matters. Government
bureaucrats _ those stuffy, overeducated drones at the Ministry of
Finance (MOF) and the Ministry of International Trade and Industry
(MITI) _ have finally been defanged and are now losing turf wars.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the MOF fought against tax cuts (it even raised the
sales tax in the midst of a decade-long recession). But recently
the MOF capitulated, and Japan's corporate tax rate was cut by 3.62
percentage points; individual tax rates have come down, too.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians have been happy to publicly savage the MOF, even
stripping the bureau of its name, soon to be known as the Ministry
of Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   To Westerners, this may sound like no big deal, but to MOF
veterans it's like changing Yankee Stadium to Yonkers Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   MITI, which had been overregulating trade and industry, has
softened in its resistance to foreign goods.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1980s, when Japanese firms bought everything from
Columbia Pictures to Rockefeller Center, American managers were
seen as lazy, bumbling barbarians. Presidents of American firms
that had been taken over had to fly to Tokyo regularly for
humiliating boardroom meetings conducted entirely in Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Americans are the cavalry, teaching the Japanese how to
compete and innovate in an economy based on software, patents, and
information technologies.
</P>
<P>
   This year MITI permitted Sumitomo Rubber Industries to form a
global partnership with Goodyear.
</P>
<P>
   An aggressive young company named Softbank owns a big piece of
Yahoo but doesn't meddle in the American company's affairs.
Instead, Softbank tries to create new business opportunities and
joint ventures for Yahoo. Yahoo is not a slave to Softbank; it's a
jewel that Softbank helps polish.
</P>
<P>
   Can this good news continue, or will the sluggish Japanese
economy drag the market back into the mire it has been stuck in
since its 1989 peak? (Remember, the Nikkei still hovers at less
than half of what it was worth ten years ago.)
</P>
<P>
   I am mostly optimistic. Sure, dangers remain. But stock prices
will continue to rise, despite occasional weeks of doubt that will
scare off some investors.
</P>
<P>
   Fiefdoms are being carved up. Government bureaucrats must answer
to the electorate. Corporate chieftains must answer to the
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The arrogance of the 1980s is being replaced by modesty. Japan
Inc. no longer aims to utterly dominate the world economy _ in
fact, there is no Japan Inc. anymore.
</P>
<P>
   While that frightens older Japanese workers, coddled by promises
of lifetime employment and protection from foreign competitors,
younger Japanese welcome the challenge and the opportunities in the
next century.
</P>
<P>
   So should investors. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Todd G. Buchholz, a regular contributor to WORTH,
is the president of Victoria Capital. His new book, ``Market
Shock,'' was just released by HarperBusiness.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this 600-word ``WORTH'' magazine article, it must
be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
