<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4370 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-GOP-ISOLATIONISM-HNS &LR;      10-21 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-ISOLATIONISM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS STEP UP EFFORT TO PAINT REPUBLICANS AS ISOLATIONISTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To hear Democrats tell it, Republicans want America
to turn its back on allies abroad and minorities at home.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the White House and Democrats stepped up their effort
to paint the congressional majority as dangerous isolationists on
foreign policy issues and as ``anti-minority'' on domestic issues.
</P>
<P>
   But conservatives counter that presidential politics is afoot as
the administration seeks to cover up its legislative defeats with
baseless accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger, the president's national security
adviser, planned a speech before the Council on Foreign Relations
late Thursday where he said ``the new isolationists'' are no longer
a fringe element but a dominate force in the Republican majority in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Berger's address, heavily promoted by the White House, came a
day after Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., stopped just
shy of accusing Republicans of racism for their insensitivity to
minority concerns. The White House earlier voiced the same theme on
race and isolationism.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the dual accusations were an attempt to counter Texas
Republican Gov. George W. Bush's ``compassionate conservatism''
slogan, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart responded, ``the one
person who has been absent in this debate is the author of
compassionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   Mindy Tucker, Bush's presidential campaign spokeswoman,
responded, ``These ongoing attacks from the president, the vice
president and the president's spokesman must indicate that Governor
Bush's positive and hopeful message is resonating with people of
all walks of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Party Chairman Jim Nicholson said: ``They are
essentially saying that we're racists. That's outrageous. There's
no place for racism in America or in American politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House and Democrats cite a series of examples. On
isolationism, they point to the Senate defeat of the Comprehensive
Test Ban Treaty, Congress' refusal to pay back dues owed the United
Nations, Congress' refusal to pay the United States' funding pledge
for the Middle East peace process and Republicans' refusal to
approve U.S. military action in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   On race issues, they point to attempts to eliminate bilingual
education, limit immigration, the Senate's slow action on minority
and women judicial nominees, and the fight over a banking bill that
would curtail laws barring ``redlining'' in minority areas.
</P>
<P>
   They also cite the effort by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., to stop
the nomination of former Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun, D-Ill., the
first black woman to serve in the Senate, as ambassador to New
Zealand. And, they cite the Senate's rare defeat of a federal
judicial nominee, Ronnie White, the first black man to serve on the
Missouri Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   And, an example of both accusations merging, they point to Rep.
Sonny Callahan, R-Ala., chairman of the House Appropriations
subcommittee on foreign operations, who suggested this week that
``everytime somebody walks in the White House with a turban on his
head'' the president offers them money. Callahan added he was going
to ``buy me one of those turbans'' and seek money for senior
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Bush should get involved in these issues ``because
sitting on the sidelines, he's not moving the ball one way or the
other. If he sides with Senator Helms and he sides with
Representative Callahan on these issues, if he has a problem with
people who wear turbans, he ought to step up and say he does. If he
doesn't, he ought to step up and say it's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Wittmann, a government expert with the conservative
Heritage Foundation, said the Democrats' accusations must be ``seen
in the context of the 2000 campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Democrats' charges of isolationism and racism are
attempts to cover their policy defeats in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the absence of a legislative legacy, the White House right
now is trying to gain a partisan advantage. Ultimately, the
administration views its legacy as retaining the White House and
regaining Congress,'' Wittmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans reacted angrily to Daschle's remarks, accusing him
of engaging in race-based politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Words like this only serve to open old wounds, not heal them.
If they are accusing anyone, they should name them,'' said John
Czwartacki, spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle defended his accusations, saying, ``There is a pattern
here that I think is very, very disconcerting. That was my only
point. It creates the perception that there is some very serious
questions relating to sensitivity towards minorities that continue
to come up with each and every one of these new incidents.''
</P>
<P>
   He again denied accusing Republicans of racism. ``All I'm saying
is that this continued pattern creates the perception that I think
is dangerous for society and is dangerous in our efforts to try to
progress as we have for the last several decades with regard to the
minority rights and the minority opportunity in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   In his address to the Council on Foreign Relations, Berger's
prepared text blasted Republicans for becoming ``new
isolationists'' who seek to hunker down at the very moment the
nation is at its wealthiest and most powerful.
</P>
<P>
   ``In effect, they believe in a survivalist foreign policy: build
a fortified fence around America and retreat behind it. And if
other nations complain that we're abdicating our responsibilities _
or if they start abdicating their own _ let them, because we are
stronger and richer than they are,'' according to an advanced text
provided by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
