<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4371 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-EDUCATE-COX     10-21 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EDUCATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush discusses education goals
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush is drawing from all sides as he
gradually unveils his plan to overhaul public education, an issue
Republican leaders believe they bungled in 1996 and one that Bush
is anxious to reclaim for his party.
</P>
<P>
   Among others sources, Bush has borrowed from the Heritage
Foundation, a conservative think tank, and from an April paper
written by Andrew J. Rotherham, an education expert who took a
leave from the Progressive Policy Institute, a centrist think tank
close to President Clinton, to work at the White House as an
education advisor.
</P>
<P>
   At the Institute, Rotherham worked the Heritage Foundation and
other groups to broker a compromise on how best to use federal
education dollars to help poor children.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his advisers understand that education is a potent
issue, capable of moving a wide swath of voters, especially women.
In 1996, Republicans were reeling from the gender gap _ female
voters' support of Democrats over Republicans. That year, men voted
almost evenly for Clinton and former Sen. Bob Dole, while 54
percent of women voted Democratic compared with 38 percent
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and others talked about strategies to close the gap at a
post-mortem Republican governors held in Michigan. Bush said the
party must recast its education message, then largely centered on
abolishing the U.S. Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that from a political perspective, he
(President Clinton) stole the issue and it affected the women's
vote,'' Bush said in 1996. ``But holding out the idea that the
federal government can solve the problems of education is wrong. We
should have challenged him on it. ... Republicans must say we're
for education.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Jennings, director of the Center on Education Policy, said
Bush has abandoned the hostile tone Republicans used when they
discussed public education. Instead, he proposes to link federal
dollars to better academic performance and to allow poor parents
whose children are in low-performing schools to use federal money
to pay for alternatives to public education. Critics have attacked
that proposal as a back door voucher program.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's clearly set about trying to prove to the public that the
Republicans will improve public schools while nodding to the far
right, 'Well, if that doesn't happen, we'll go to vouchers,'''
Jennings said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's education ideas are not new, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Bush is drawing on is stuff that has been in the policy
mill for awhile,'' Jennings said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not proposed an infusion of new money for the public
schools. Instead, in two of three planned education speeches, he
put forward a plan to restructure the Elementary and Secondary
Education Act. Signed into law by President Lyndon B. Johnson in
1965, the act provides nearly $14 billion to public schools each
year, their largest source of federal money.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest chuck _ $9.9 billion in Title 1 money _ goes to
boost the performance of the nation's poorest students. On
Thursday, the House voted to approve a bipartisan plan to
reauthorize the Elementary and Secondary Education Act. An effort
by House Majority Leader Dick Armey to attach a voucher provision
failed.
</P>
<P>
   Critics from all sides of the ideological spectrum have
questioned whether Title I dollars are buying better performance.
Rotherham's April article proposes shrinking the Elementary and
Secondary Education Act's 60 areas into a handful of block grants.
A similar approach is central to the plan Bush announced in New
York earlier this month. Under both plans, school districts would
have to prove that federal money was buying better academic
performance.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, Bush's plan would use the National Assessment in
Education Progress, an exam given to a sample of students. Third-
through eighth-graders would be tested annually in reading and math
as a way of auditing progress from state to state.
</P>
<P>
   Rotherham also suggests using the NAEP test in the absence of a
voluntary national test in fourth-grade reading and eighth-grade
math, a Clinton proposal that was anathema to conservates and died
on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the similarities, Bush's plan departs significantly from
Rotherham's, said Bruce Reed, chief-domestic policy advisor at the
White House. The Clinton adminstration has a separate plan that
also emphasizes accountability, but does not use block grants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is borrowing some of the rhetoric and looking for the
cover of new Democratic ideas, but going in a different
direction,'' Reed said. ``He's put together a voucher plan but
refused to say the word voucher. His emphasis on standards and
accountability resembles the Clinton agenda, but the fundamental
breaking point is over vouchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the administration hasn't pushed Rotherham's plan,
Reed called it, ``an interesting one,'' and said that the plans
share an emphasis on school accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also takes a page from a Heritage Foundation proposal that
would allow states to free themselves from virtually all federal
restrictions if they agree to meet particularly rigorous academic
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Nina Shokraii Rees, an education expert at the Heritage
Foundation, calls Bush's plan, ``very conservative'' and
Rotherham's plan, ``avant-garde and innovative.'' And a year of
``triangulation'' and other political ironies, the latest one
hasn't escaped her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration is not pushing the plan that this special
assistant to the president thought of,'' she said, ``whereas the
Republican frontrunner is.''
</P>
<P>
   Heath writes for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
