<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NORRIS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-21 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORRIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED LEARNS BARTENDERS ARE MORE POPULAR THAN BOUNCERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Alan Greenspan yesterday's hero?
</P>
<P>
   It was only eight months ago that Greenspan was on the cover of
Time as the most prominent member of ``The Committee to Save the
World,'' a man who had prevented a global economic meltdown by
reducing interest rates. Politicians fell all over themselves to
praise the Federal Reserve chairman while interpreting his
sometimes Delphic words as an endorsement of their views.
</P>
<P>
   But now his halo is slipping, and the muttering is increasing.
How dare he raise interest rates? Who is he to question the stock
market's valuation?
</P>
<P>
   William McChesney Martin Jr., the Fed chairman during the great
economic expansion of the 1950s and 1960s, once said that the role
of the Fed was ``to take away the punch bowl just when the party
gets going.'' Greenspan is learning what happens to Fed officials
who wait too long to try to grab the bowl. The revelers resent it.
</P>
<P>
   Deep into the longest peacetime recovery in American history,
business feels it has a right to continued economic growth more or
less forever. Deep into the biggest bull market ever, more and more
investors believe that 20 percent-plus annual stock market gains
are a birthright.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy years ago, another generation of Fed officials learned
the same lesson. In 1929, the Fed had the gall to tell banks to
reduce lending to stock speculators. The stock market plunged, only
to rally after Charles Mitchell, the president of National City
Bank, a predecessor of today's Citibank, defied the Fed and said
lending would continue.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell ``saved the day'' and averted calamity, said the
Financial Chronicle, a Wall Street publication. The Fed, it added,
``can act the part of a bull in a china shop and cause a lot of
destruction and damage, or, Samson-like, it can pull the whole
financial structure down about its head. But that is no reason why
it should not be checked in the attempt by those who would be
involved in the ruin.''
</P>
<P>
   That Fed quickly lost its nerve. The stock market rallied more
than 30 percent from the March lows brought on by the Fed's effort
to slow speculation. Then it crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan and his colleagues at the Fed face a difficult
situation now. There is scattered evidence that the economy is
slowing, and there is reason to believe that the current rate of
growth is overstated because it reflects inventory accumulation by
people and companies fearful of Year 2000 glitches. Both are
reasons not to raise rates.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, there is equally scattered evidence that
inflation is rising, and there is concern over the soaring current
account deficit. A failure to act could cause stock prices to rise
to completely unreasonable levels, making an eventual crash more
likely. Action, on the other hand, might scare jittery investors
and bring on a crash.
</P>
<P>
   Back when people remembered 1929, it was taken for granted that
the Fed should act to rein in a frothy stock market. It raised the
margin requirement _ the amount investors had to put down to buy
stocks _ when markets were high, and cut it when share prices were
depressed. The last change, from 65 percent to 50 percent in 1974,
came during a severe bear market.
</P>
<P>
   Because it no longer pays attention to margins, the Fed has
created the impression that stock prices are irrelevant and that
inflation is the only reason to apply economic brakes. Without
clear evidence of inflation, Greenspan risks losing popularity if
he keeps raising rates.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy years ago, the Fed backed down under attack from the
party crowd. Will Greenspan do the same?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1936EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4381 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-Y2K-CHEMICALS-HNS &LR;      10-21 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-CHEMICALS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL CHEMICAL PLANTS NOT READY FOR Y2K, STUDY FINDS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BILL DAWSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most small and medium-sized chemical businesses in Texas and
elsewhere are not yet prepared for problems related to the Y2K
computer bug, according to a Texas A&AMP;M survey released Thursday by
a U.S. Senate committee.
</P>
<P>
   Given the potential for accidents to jeopardize neighboring
communities, the committee's leaders urged the heads of the Federal
Emergency Management Agency and U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency to alert state and local emergency-response agencies about
the finding.
</P>
<P>
   In another response to the A&AMP;M study, the nonprofit Center for
Y2K &AMP; Society called for a ``safety holiday'' _ a shutdown of
operations just before and after Jan. 1, 2000 _ to be ordered at
most chemical plants.
</P>
<P>
   Some larger chemical companies have already indicated they were
planning or considering total or partial shutdowns around the New
Year's holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K bug involves the inability of some computers and devices
containing computer chips to read the 2000 date correctly. Such
failures could cause malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   In many chemical plants _ as well as other manufacturing
facilities such as oil refineries _ computers and chip-containing
devices are involved in a wide array of production, monitoring and
safety activities.
</P>
<P>
   The study was conducted by the Mary Kay O'Connor Process Safety
Center of the the Texas Engineering Experiment Station, part of the
Texas A&AMP;M system. The center interviewed officials of 281 chemical
companies with 200 or fewer employees _ 82 businesses in Texas and
the rest in California, Kansas and New Jersey. They were not
identified in the report issued by the Senate panel.
</P>
<P>
   Among the survey results:
</P>
<P>
   _ 86.5 percent of the firms are not completely prepared for Y2K
problems, while 4.1 percent thought a ``catastrophic event'' is the
worst possible consequence at their facilities.
</P>
<P>
   _ 85.6 percent have not coordinated their contingency plans for
Y2K-related emergencies with local officials.
</P>
<P>
   _ 79 percent had never previously been surveyed about their Y2K
readiness.
</P>
<P>
   Experts' earlier assessments of Y2K preparedness in the chemical
industry were based on the assumption _ also common for other types
of businesses _ that larger companies were probably doing more to
fix vulnerable equipment and make contingency plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a large degree, that assumption has been confirmed
(regarding chemical producers and handlers) by this in-depth,
independent report,'' said Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, chairman of
the Senate's Special Committee on the Year 2000 Technology Problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the probability of a Y2K-related disruption is low, the
potential harm even one chemical accident can cause means we must
be especially vigilant,'' said Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., the
panel's vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   With so little time remaining before Jan. 1, O'Connor Center
director Sam Mannan said special emphasis now should be placed on
contingency planning at smaller chemical businesses. He is also an
associate professor of chemical engineering at Texas A&AMP;M
University.
</P>
<P>
   Norman L. Dean, executive director of the Center for Y2K &AMP;
Society, said the A&AMP;M study is ``a warning that small and
medium-sized chemical plants face increased risks of explosions,
leaks and fires resulting from Y2K.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Mayhew, vice president for regulatory and technical affairs
at the Chemical Manufacturers Association, said a survey of its
member companies indicated a much higher level of readiness than
was found among those surveyed for the A&AMP;M report.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all CMA members have finished taking steps to make their
facilities ``Y2K-compliant,'' and all say they will be ready in
time, Mayhew said.
</P>
<P>
   But the association's members generally have more than 200
employees, he said, so it is likely the A&AMP;M survey mainly involved
non-member businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller chemical companies tend to make less use of automated _
and, therefore, Y2K-vulnerable _ systems, Mayhew said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the companies with fewer than 200 employees questioned for
the A&AMP;M study, 34.6 percent said they use Y2K-susceptible computers
to operate chemical processes, while 23.2 percent said they have
devices containing computer chips that might be vulnerable to the
bug.
</P>
<P>
   Chemical safety advocates have criticized state and federal
officials for failing to require corrective actions related to
possible Y2K problems. Instead, government agencies have emphasized
educational outreach programs, often conducted in collaboration
with trade groups like the CMA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
