<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4382 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-EARNINGS22-COX     10-21 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-EARNINGS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola's profit hits Wall Street target
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At least for the moment, investors apparently think
the worst is over for Coca-Cola Co.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the Atlanta-based beverage company rose 3 percent
Thursday after it met analysts' expectations for third-quarter
earnings and posted its first growth in case sales this year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Coca-Cola earned 11 percent less than it did a year ago _
the fourth consecutive decline in quarterly profits.
</P>
<P>
   The company earned $787 million, or 32 cents a share, compared
with $888 million, or 36 cents a share, in the same period last
year. Quarterly sales rose 9 percent to nearly $5.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an in-line quarter,'' said Andrew Conway, an analyst with
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``The earnings report shows signs the
business is stabilizing, but not accelerating at a dramatic rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch analyst Douglas Lane said the company is on the
mend.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's report, he said, ``confirms our thesis that the worst
is behind us regarding the impact of the recent global meltdown on
Coke's business, and that the key underlying fundamentals ... are
all improving.''
</P>
<P>
   The analysts' comments generally mirrored those of Coca-Cola's
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the trends are very encouraging,'' Chairman and Chief
Executive M. Douglas Ivester said in a statement. ``In the third
quarter, we sold more soft drinks than in any quarter in the
company's history.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the sales gains are modest, Ivester said, they
represent further evidence that economies in key markets around the
world are beginning to recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this sets the stage for positive momentum for our
business looking forward,'' Ivester said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ivester acknowledged the company has not been living up to
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This past year has not been what the company's shareowners or
its management, most especially me, want or expect. Both our volume
and profit results and our stock price have disappointed us all.''
</P>
<P>
   Coke shares rose $1.56 1/4 Thursday to close at $54.31 1/4. For
the year, the stock has dropped 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, case sales rose 3.5 percent, reversing
volume declines in the two previous quarters. The third quarter's
increase was aided by the company's recent acquisition of Cadbury
Schweppes brands in 161 countries outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no dramatic improvement in quarterly volume growth,
year over year,'' Conway said. He added, however, that the company
had a strong performance in ``two critical profit centers'' _
Germany and Japan _ where case sales rose 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, where Coca-Cola products were the subject of a June
recall after being blamed for making nearly 250 Belgians sick, the
company said it is seeing steady improvements. It expects sales to
be at pre-recall levels by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   For the third quarter, the recall cost the company an estimated
3 cents in after-tax earnings per share.
</P>
<P>
   While overall case sales rose 3 percent in Europe, the company
said ``very difficult economic conditions'' in parts of Eastern
Europe and Russia continue to affect its performance.
</P>
<P>
   In North America, increasing retail prices in supermarkets have
hurt case sales this year. In the third quarter, however, volume
started to improve, rising 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Latin America, case sales increased 5 percent, although the
company is still facing economic challenges in Venezuela and
Colombia, where volume declined.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, analysts expect the company to report its
first earnings increase for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Conway, for example, expects the company to earn 28 cents,
compared with 24 cents last year. But he remains ``cautious'' on
the stock in the short-term because he predicts that volume growth
will pick up only slightly in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, however, Conway believes the growth in case sales
will accelerate, leading to higher profits and stock prices. He
thinks the company will earn $1.50 per share next year, compared
with $1.29 this year. He predicts the stock price will rise to $75
by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Lane believes the stock will appreciate between 10 percent and
20 percent over the next year, and more than 20 percent after that.
</P>
<P>
   He predicts that in the summer of next year, the company will
start reaching its long-term goals of 7 percent to 8 percent volume
growth and 15 percent to 20 percent earnings-per-share growth.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
