<SLUG> BC-DELTA-BOSTON22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta discussing Boston expansion
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines is in talks to spend more than $300
million on a new terminal at Boston's Logan Airport, where it's
also considering adding flights to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Delta would use the new terminal to consolidate
its operations at Logan, the only airport served by the airline's
regular flights as well as its Delta Shuttle and Delta Express
units.
</P>
<P>
   Delta also may launch direct flights to Europe from Boston,
Chief Executive Leo Mullin said. Boston would become Delta's fourth
trans-Atlantic gateway, joining Atlanta, New York and Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin said Delta hopes to fly between Boston and four European
cities: Dublin, Ireland; Manchester, England; Rome; and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our domestic presence there, it's a very viable
gateway,'' said Mullin, a Massachusetts native who has run Delta
for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Talks on a new terminal have been under way for several months
between Delta and the Massachusetts Port Authority. Delta also is
in preliminary discussions about a new terminal at New York's
Kennedy International to replace the one it inherited from Pan Am
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals American and United also are upgrading facilities in New
York and Boston. The moves reflect hot competition for passenger
loyalties in the fragmented Northeast market, as well as the strain
of passenger growth on aging airport facilities. ``It's the
strongest and most contested air market in the nation,'' Delta
spokesman John Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta holds its annual shareholder meeting next week in Boston
and may use the occasion to tout its Logan plans. But talks may not
move fast enough for an announcement next week.
</P>
<P>
   A MassPort spokeswoman said the talks have been ``very
productive'' but declined to comment further. The agency is already
is in the midst of a $1 billion modernization at Logan, which last
year handled 26.5 million passengers. It includes a controversial
proposal for a new runway.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's Logan project would cost about $386 million, with Delta
footing about $336 million of the bill, according to the airline.
Work is likely to start no sooner than 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The plan involves replacing or redeveloping Terminal A, where
Delta Shuttle flights now operate. Other Delta flights operate from
Terminal C. Delta has 74 daily departures from Logan and flies
hourly between Boston and Atlanta. In recent years it has bulked up
schedules to major cities in the East, and its last new terminal
project was in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
