<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: EL DUQUE DESERVES TO OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees were a coin, its motto would be ``In El Duque We
Trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Orlando Hernandez will be starting two games in a
row after pitching the Yankees to the American League pennant last
Monday night in Boston and even though he has been pounded by the
Braves in his only two starts against them, the Cuban right-hander
known as El Duque will open the World Series Saturday night in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The more renowned Yankee starters don't seem to be envious of El
Duque's sudden stature as their No. 1 pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the pitchers to a man,'' said Joe Torre, the Yankee
manager, ``realize he deserves this; he's earned this.''
</P>
<P>
   David Cone, who was Torre's most trustworthy post-season starter
in other years, appreciates El Duque's attributes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the post-season,'' Cone said, ``you need a certain presence
and confidence. It's not something you can see as much as you sense
it and feel it. He's got it.''
</P>
<P>
   El Duque, who was 17-9 during the season, has been the Yankees'
best pitcher for three months, with the emphasis on being a
``pitcher'' rather merely a thrower.
</P>
<P>
   But in two starts against the Braves in interleague play, El
Duque hasn't had it.
</P>
<P>
   On July 16 at Yankee Stadium, he was strafed for six runs,
including four homers, in only four and two-thirds innings in a
game the Yankees lost, 10-7, when Mariano Rivera gave up four runs,
including Andruw Jones' three-run homer. In a 7-2 defeat at Yankee
Stadium in 1998, he was the losing pitcher to left-hander Tom
Glavine, the Braves' starter Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Torre is aware of El Duque's previous problems with the Braves'
batting order, but doesn't seem concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's not hitting his spots and he's not changing speeds,
he's had trouble,'' Torre said. ``We just want him to have the
command and the count on his side. And he's not afraid of
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Jorge Posada, who usually catches El Duque, those
problems with the Braves may be a blessing now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might be even more intense,'' Posada said. ``He'll want to
show what he can do because he hasn't done it.''
</P>
<P>
   El Duque hasn't done it against the Braves as yet, but in three
starts against the Texas Rangers and the Boston Red Sox so far in
this post-season, he has been virtually perfect: 23 innings, 14
hits allowed, 19 strikeouts, 12 bases on balls, 2-0 record, 1.17
earned run average, .171 opponents' batting average.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game in Boston the other night, he was amazing,'' Posada
said of the 6-1 victory that clinched the American League pennant.
``Whatever I called, he put it where I wanted it. When he's right,
I can go to any pitch in any count and it will still be a good
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   With another start very likely in the fifth Series game, El
Duque may have a chance to equal the record for post-season
victories _ four _ shared by seven pitchers, including El Duque's
half-brother, Livan Hernandez, with the Florida Marlins in 1997.
The others:
</P>
<P>
   David Wells with last year's Yankees, John Smoltz with the '96
Braves, Orel Hershiser with the '95 Indians, Jack Morris with the
'91 Twins, Dave Stewart with the '89 Athletics and Burt Hooton with
the `81 Dodgers (when a midseason strike created divisional
playoffs between first-half and second-half winners).
</P>
<P>
   So the World Series provides quite an opportunity for a pitcher
who only two years ago had been banned from Cuban baseball because
Fidel Castro's authorities believed he was about to defect. Which
he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so street smart,'' Posada said. ``If you go to eat with
him, he'll see somebody with a camera long before you do. He's
always looking. But other than talking about some Cuban players, he
doesn't talk about Cuba. He really has turned the page on that part
of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Posada, whose Cuban father moved to Puerto Rico about 30 years
ago, knows El Duque better than any other teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The language barrier keeps guys from knowing him, but he's
learning English slowly,'' Posada said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things in America are still all new to him. It's like being
blind for 20 years and now you can see; if you're told somebody is
wearing a blue sweater, you'll say, `Why is that blue?' They
brainwash you in Cuba. You don't know the why of anything there.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Cuba the right-hander known as El Duque learned the why
of pitching. That's why he's starting for the Yankees in the World
Series opener.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 1942EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0351 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4386 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CAMPBELL-SENATE-1STLD     10-21 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPBELL-SENATE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPBELL NEARS DECISION ON WHETHER TO SEEK SENATE SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: SUBS 9thgraf, Once conservatives, to correct attribution,
Rohrabacher sted Campbell; filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Tom Campbell, nearing a decision on whether to
run against Democratic Sen. Dianne Feinstein next year, says he
doubts his vote to impeach President Clinton would hurt him in an
state-wide election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not see it as a problem,'' says Campbell, 47, a
softspoken Stanford University law school professor who is expected
to announce as early as next week whether he will seek the
Republican nomination to run for Feinstein's seat. ``The matter has
evaporated, except for the occasional compliment.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, defending his impeachment vote last year, says he has
a clear standard for whether a politician is worthy of holding
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an individual intentionally did not tell the truth'' to a
federal grand jury, that ``incapacitates'' that person from holding
political office, Campbell said in an interview in his Capitol Hill
office earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   A 4th-term Republican House member known for breaking with his
party occasionally, Campbell says he applied the same standard to
former House Speaker Newt Gingrich and refused to back him as
speaker after Gingrich admitted submitting inaccurate information
to the House Ethics Committee. Campbell later joined an attempt to
oust Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., a staunch conservative who
shares a love of Irish pub music with Campbell and refers to the
two of them and Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., as the ``Tres
Amigos,'' says Campbell's support for gun control and abortion
rights will ``keep many conservatives away.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell says he's convinced California voters want a Senate
candidate who votes conservatively on fiscal issue and moderately
on social issues _ and that's how he describes himself.
</P>
<P>
   While Campbell might not be the top choice for conservatives in
the primary, he would be in the general election, Rohrabacher says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once conservatives understand the general thrust that Tom
Campbell has had in Washington, they will have no trouble
supporting him over Dianne Feinstein,'' Rohrabacher says.
</P>
<P>
   If Campbell runs, he would contend for the Republican nomination
with at least four conservatives _ Silicon Valley entrepreneur Ron
Unz, State Senate Minority Whip Ray Haynes, San Diego County
Supervisor Bill Horn, and businessman J.P. Gough.
</P>
<P>
   Unz would likely present the strongest challenge to Campbell,
according to John J. Pitney, a political scientist at Claremont
McKenna College.
</P>
<P>
   Pitney says Unz ``is one of the few people in the state of
California who is as smart as Tom Campbell. These are two of the
smartest guys in politics today. It would be good for the state to
see that debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell would face a steep fund-raising challenge to raise the
estimated $5 million needed for the primary and $20 million needed
for the general election.
</P>
<P>
   The state-wide Field Poll, released Thursday, showed Feinstein
with a huge lead over Campbell and other potential Republican
nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Among all voters in a hypothetical general election, Feinstein
won 55 percent of the vote, compared with 30 percent for Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Campbell had a tiny lead other possible
Republican nominees in matchups against Feinstein. Unz came in
second, winning 26 percent against Feinstein's 59 percent. Unz was
the prime mover behind the voter-approved Proposition 227 last
year, which put strict limits on bilingual education in state
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Field poll was conducted Oct. 8-17 among 514 likely voters,
with a margin of error of plus-or-minus 4.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders and Republican members of Congress confirm that
Campbell has discussed with them whether he should make the run.
However, Campbell dodges questions about his plans and refuses to
compare his record to Feinstein's, saying it is premature to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wise for me to make a decision and then go
forward _ as opposed to discussing it before the decision,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
