<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Friday, Oct.
22, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Bob
Schenet at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   PROSTATE-VASECTOMY (Seattle) _ Researchers in Seattle have found
that men who get vasectomies have no higher risk of prostate
cancer, and that men who take zinc, vitamin C and E may
significantly reduce their risk of getting the disease.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-MEMORIAL (Washington) _ In Japanese culture, cranes
represent happiness, good fortune and longevity. But in the
sculpture soon to rise here in the shadow of the Capitol, two
cranes will be shown fighting with their claws and wings to get
free of barbed wire and shackles. The sculpture will be at the
heart of a National Japanese American Memorial for which ground is
to be broken Friday. The memorial will offer a vivid reminder of a
painful moment in U.S. history, when during World War II Japanese
Americans were taken from their homes and sent to internment camps
because of their race.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (Story will move in the ``w'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FAST-JUBLIEE (Washington) _ His body so weak he could barely
stand, a retired minister from southwest Washingotn Thursday broke
his hunger strike rather than die. On his last night without food,
he won a meeting with House Majority Whip Tom Delay and a promise
of a floor vote on a measure for third world debt relief.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (Story will move in the ``w'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-TOURISTS (Seattle) _ Zagrahm Expeditions is booking
flights for the first tourist flights into space, but woudl-be
space travelers shouldn't pack their bags yet. Seattle-based
Zeagrahm Space Voyages has already lined up 145 prospective
clients, who say they are willing to pay $98,000 for a 2 1/2 hour
trip into suborbit.
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Nyhan. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-DEAD (Undated) _ Twenty-three years ago, director Martin
Scorsese and screenwriter Paul Schrader collaborated on a grim
portrait of a New York City loner called ``Taxi Driver. With
``Bringing Out the Dead,'' this partnership has reunited for a
long-time-in-coming follow-up. Clearly, they're trying to make
lightning strike twice in the same place. Unfortunately, it
doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-STRAIGHT (Undated) _ David Lynch is one of the few
successful American filmmakers who seems to have made little or no
concession to commercial considerations throughout his career.
Consistently, he makes whatever film interests him at the time.
This time, it is ``The Straight Story,'' a low-key, low-budget,
G-rated inspirational film for the Disney company about an old man
on a journey. I loved it, but it's exactly the kind of
underwhelming movie that seems guaranteed to get lost in the
multiplexes.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-TANGO (Undated) _ The vapid plotline of ``Three to Tango''
follows the same narrative arc as ``Tootsie'' but hasn't the heart
or purpose of that film, most because its script tries to stay
trendy by tossing in offbeat humor out of ``There's Something About
Mary.'' It's ultimately just a mish-mash of movie moments, played
by TV stars, without any fresh invention.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-JOE (Undated) _ ``Joe the King,'' is a moving and woefully
tender look at a young boy's troubled adolescence. It has enough
simmering beneath its sweaty, grimmy and disconsolate surface to be
more than just another rite of passage to young manhood missive set
in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CRAZY (Undated) _ Antonio Banderas brings a fresh
perspective to his directorial debut, ``Crazy In Alabama,'' a
quintessentially ``American'' movie that captures the elusive
essence of life in that loss-of-innocence time _ the 1960s. Adapted
from Mark Childress' 1994 novel about a boy's coming of age in the
turbulent, volatile Civil Rights-era South, the film is rife with
the sudden, harsh truths about the real world that emerges with
adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-ANYDAYNOW (Undated) _ This Sunday, fans get a bonus hour of
``Any Day Now'' on Lifetime. The poetic series about two
Birmingham, Ala., women who have been best friends since childhood
offers enough dialogue starter to keep tongues wagging for weeks on
the subjects of racial bigotry, hate crimes and white supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
