<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPBELL-SENATE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPBELL NEARS DECISION ON WHETHER TO SEEK SENATE SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: SUBS 9thgraf, Once conservatives, to correct attribution,
Rohrabacher sted Campbell; filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Tom Campbell, nearing a decision on whether to
run against Democratic Sen. Dianne Feinstein next year, says he
doubts his vote to impeach President Clinton would hurt him in an
state-wide election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not see it as a problem,'' says Campbell, 47, a
softspoken Stanford University law school professor who is expected
to announce as early as next week whether he will seek the
Republican nomination to run for Feinstein's seat. ``The matter has
evaporated, except for the occasional compliment.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, defending his impeachment vote last year, says he has
a clear standard for whether a politician is worthy of holding
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an individual intentionally did not tell the truth'' to a
federal grand jury, that ``incapacitates'' that person from holding
political office, Campbell said in an interview in his Capitol Hill
office earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   A 4th-term Republican House member known for breaking with his
party occasionally, Campbell says he applied the same standard to
former House Speaker Newt Gingrich and refused to back him as
speaker after Gingrich admitted submitting inaccurate information
to the House Ethics Committee. Campbell later joined an attempt to
oust Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., a staunch conservative who
shares a love of Irish pub music with Campbell and refers to the
two of them and Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., as the ``Tres
Amigos,'' says Campbell's support for gun control and abortion
rights will ``keep many conservatives away.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell says he's convinced California voters want a Senate
candidate who votes conservatively on fiscal issue and moderately
on social issues _ and that's how he describes himself.
</P>
<P>
   While Campbell might not be the top choice for conservatives in
the primary, he would be in the general election, Rohrabacher says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once conservatives understand the general thrust that Tom
Campbell has had in Washington, they will have no trouble
supporting him over Dianne Feinstein,'' Rohrabacher says.
</P>
<P>
   If Campbell runs, he would contend for the Republican nomination
with at least four conservatives _ Silicon Valley entrepreneur Ron
Unz, State Senate Minority Whip Ray Haynes, San Diego County
Supervisor Bill Horn, and businessman J.P. Gough.
</P>
<P>
   Unz would likely present the strongest challenge to Campbell,
according to John J. Pitney, a political scientist at Claremont
McKenna College.
</P>
<P>
   Pitney says Unz ``is one of the few people in the state of
California who is as smart as Tom Campbell. These are two of the
smartest guys in politics today. It would be good for the state to
see that debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell would face a steep fund-raising challenge to raise the
estimated $5 million needed for the primary and $20 million needed
for the general election.
</P>
<P>
   The state-wide Field Poll, released Thursday, showed Feinstein
with a huge lead over Campbell and other potential Republican
nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Among all voters in a hypothetical general election, Feinstein
won 55 percent of the vote, compared with 30 percent for Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Campbell had a tiny lead other possible
Republican nominees in matchups against Feinstein. Unz came in
second, winning 26 percent against Feinstein's 59 percent. Unz was
the prime mover behind the voter-approved Proposition 227 last
year, which put strict limits on bilingual education in state
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Field poll was conducted Oct. 8-17 among 514 likely voters,
with a margin of error of plus-or-minus 4.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders and Republican members of Congress confirm that
Campbell has discussed with them whether he should make the run.
However, Campbell dodges questions about his plans and refuses to
compare his record to Feinstein's, saying it is premature to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wise for me to make a decision and then go
forward _ as opposed to discussing it before the decision,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
