<HEADER>
A4396 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-BOOK22-COX     10-21 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BOOK22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Release of Bush biography held as author's credibility
questioned
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A new biography alleging that Gov. George W.
Bush was once arrested for cocaine possession was yanked Thursday
because of the publisher's concerns about the author's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   The book's author, J.H. Hatfield, served time in a Texas prison
for hiring a hit man to make a failed attempt to kill a former
boss, according to a published report. The author also may have
puffed up his writing credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Mr. Hatfield's credibility has been called into serious
question, we feel compelled to suspend publication,'' said Sally
Richardson, president and publisher of St. Martin's Press trade
division.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the publisher's announcement, the book was still
available Thursday afternoon at several Austin bookstores. All said
they had heard no word of the decision to suspend sales.
</P>
<P>
   The book, entitled ``Fortunate Son,'' details conversations
Hatfield had with anonymous sources. Those sources confirmed that
Bush had been arrested in 1972 for cocaine possession, he says. The
book says the case was dropped and the records expunged after Bush,
with intervention from his father, was allowed to perform community
service in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the elder Bush was a former congressman serving as
the United States ambassador to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-president Bush and Gov. Bush vehemently denied the cocaine
allegation. Bush campaign spokesman Scott McClellan said the
publisher's move was ``the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Hatfield, an Arkansas resident, could not be
reached for comment. On Wednesday, he told The Dallas Morning News
that he is not the J.H. Hatfield imprisoned in Texas for hiring a
hit man to kill a former boss in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Department of Criminal Justice records show that James
Howard Hatfield entered a guilty plea in 1988 to a charge of
solicitation of capital murder. Hatfield was sentenced to 15 years
in prison. He served five years and was released to federal
officials in April 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal Justice Department spokesman Stennett Posey said
Hatfield then served approximately one year in an Oklahoma federal
prison before being released to Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Hatfield alleged he hired a hit man in 1987 to
use a car bomb to kill a former employer. A bomb exploded in a
downtown parking lot, but nobody was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Cobb of Bentonville, Ark., Hatfield's parole officer,
declined comment Thursday. Earlier, Cobb told the Dallas paper that
the Hatfield under his supervision was the author of a biography of
actor Patrick Stewart. The Bush book identifies Hatfield as the
author of a book about Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   A news release touting the Bush book listed Hatfield as a
``syndicated columnist, free-lance Texas journalist and frequent
contributor to several Lone Star state newspapers and magazines,
including the Dallas Times-Herald, Houston Post, Dallas Observer
and The Texas Women's News.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Lyons, Dallas Observer editor, said Thursday there was no
record of Hatfield ever writing for the weekly publication.
</P>
<P>
   A computer search of the now-defunct Houston Post's archives
showed no record of a J.H. Hatfield writing anything in the paper
from 1985 until it folded in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Bode, who worked at the Dallas Times-Herald from 1977
through 1991 and was its editor when the paper closed, said he had
no memory of Hatfield.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
