<HEADLINE>
DIANA ROSS ON THE STRESS OF BEING SEARCHED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Diana Ross &LR; , arrested briefly recently after she allegedly
struck a security guard she said had improperly touched her when
she set off a metal detector at Heathrow Airport, told the
Telegraph of London that the incident had a profound impact on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened at the airport brought the fear of death to
me,'' she said. ``After Heathrow, I am scared of dying. I really
am. It opened up a lot of fears for me. ... When I got back to
Connecticut, I had to get a minister to pray for me over the
phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross said she plays spiritual tapes every day. ``I spend a lot
of time with my higher self. I am working on my spirit and my soul
a lot; it comforts me. It keeps me on purpose, reminds me of the
beauty in life. You know what? It's not about prosperity, it's
about self.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOBACCO ANTI-ADS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Advertising Age ad critic  &UR; Bob Garfield  &LR; describes a new ad in
which Lorillard Tobacco intends to dissuade teenagers from smoking.
The tag line: ``Tobacco is whacko if you're a teen.'' More
persuasive than the language, writes the critic, is the image of a
``60-ish man with brown teeth'' inviting a teenager to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``As anti-smoking spots go, this one is more resonant than most.
That's because it isn't about death, it's about ugliness. Mortality
data are nothing to teenagers, who think they're invulnerable. But
brown teeth ... that's a horror they understand, believe and
internalize in an instant. ... Many children will see this and be
put off from smoking, by a company that sells cigarettes. Which is
undeniably positive, and positively absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ In North Beach on Wednesday, &UR; Firat Yener &LR;  saw  &UR; Tony Bennett &LR; 
having lunch all alone at the Cafferata Piccola Cucina, surrounded
by posters picturing Tony Bennett. Bennett's a good friend of the
owner, the cafe confirms.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Stuart Hills &LR;  sends his sympathies to Novato, referred to
repeatedly in the hip magazine Wallpaper as the site of the  &UR; I.M. &LR; 
 &UR; Pei &LR; -designed Buck Center for Research in Aging, Novanto,
California.
</P>
<P>
   _ A string of best-selling crime thrillers written by  &UR; Dick &LR; 
 &UR; Francis  &LR; were mostly written by his wife,  &UR; Mary Francis &LR; , claims
biographer  &UR; Graham Lord &LR;  in ``Dick Francis: A Racing Life,'' just
published in England. Francis' publishers told the BBC that Mary
Francis has always helped with the research but the 78-year-old
author writes the books.
</P>
<P>
   _ Makeup artist  &UR; Kevyn Aucoin  &LR; told Soma magazine that he
doesn't see his job as slapping on blusher and mascara. ``I hope
that what I do has something deeper behind it,'' he said, ``and
that it's political as well as emotional and hopefully
provocative.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Seeking kids' entries for an ``All-American Salute to
Mothers'' greeting-card design contest, KFC says it's naturally
mom-centric: ``Mother's Day is KFC's biggest sales day of the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Playwright  &UR; Wendy Wasserstein &LR; , 49, gave birth to  &UR; Lucy Jane &LR; 
 &UR; Wasserstein  &LR; last month, reports the New York Post. No word on the
identity of the father; the baby weighed 2 pounds at birth but is
said to be growing steadily.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Richard Ogar  &LR; wrote down more of the names of those faux
``political tables'' set up at UC Berkeley for a movie scene:
``Rastafarian Cooking Club'' and ``Polititians for Peace'' (which
Ogar calls a ``truly Clintonian organization'').
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Alan Rickman &LR;  and  &UR; Natasha Richardson &LR; , preparing for roles
in ``Never Better,'' a movie about a hairdressing competition, have
been taking hairdressing lessons, says the Express. The
screenwriter is  &UR; Simon Beaufoy &LR; , who wrote ``The Full Monty.''
</P>
<P>
   _ This item appears without a place name, so a romantically
inclined city worker won't get into trouble with the brass:
 &UR; Michael Caldarola &LR;  noticed a graffitied ``Chuko 'n' Bunny'' in a
heart on his street one day. Within 24 hours, a civil servant had
painted over Chuko and Bunny with asphalt-colored paint but (sigh)
left the heart.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   `Why are we so upset about sex workers selling sexual acts to
consenting adults? We say that they are selling their bodies, but
how different is that from what athletes do? They're selling their
bodies. Models? They're selling their bodies. Actors? They're
selling their bodies. We do with our bodies what we see fit. We
live in a free country.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Dr. Joycelyn Elders, deposed surgeon general, in the preface
to ``Prostitution: On Whores, Hustlers and Johns'' (Prometheus;
$29.95), edited by James Elias.
</P>
