<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HICKS MIGHT NOT TRIM RANGERS' BUDGET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Two weeks ago, Rangers' owner Tom Hicks said
substantial budget cuts would be necessary, prompting the local
media to predict a massive clubhouse purge, starting with two-time
American League MVP Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   As of yesterday, however, the late Gilda Radner was needed in
Arlington to deliver her signature line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of his contractual status, Gonzalez remains a prime
candidate to be traded in the off-season, but what might remain the
same in 2000 is this year's $75 million payroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can improve next season's team for the same $75 million,
then, yes, I'm willing,'' Hicks said. ``If we can improve for
something less, I'd be even more pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking by airphone from his private jet, Hicks said he heard
``three hours worth of ideas'' from general manager Doug Melvin
this week. ``I like Doug's plan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks confirmed that Melvin presented him with a 2000 players
payroll budget of less than $75 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``That number gave us parameters to work with,'' Hicks said,
``but because of all the uncertainties in the baseball market, I
think it's necessary to be flexible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Staying within the budget is a goal, but depending on what
happens, we can go higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Hicks nor Melvin would reveal the 2000 budget number,
but it doesn't necessarily matter. Not if Hicks is again pledged to
be a ``player'' in the high stakes poker game of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ownership has given me flexibility if the right things come
up,'' Melvin said. ``While attempting to build a strong farm
system, maybe I spent more money \Ron the major-league payroll\S
than I should have.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with this commitment from Mr. Hicks, we can do what we
hope is right for both long-term and short-term _ establish a core
of solid frontline players and then attempt to build around it with
youth.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Hicks said the '99 financial losses for the
Rangers would be $15 million to $17 million. Also at that time, he
was attempting to deal with his team having been a postseason
offensive embarrassment in consecutive Octobers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't changed my thinking all that much \Rfrom two
weeks ago\S,'' Hicks said yesterday. ``The disappointment is still
there, and based on everything, I'd like the payroll to be lower.
But I also want to win, and the fans are our partners in this, and
we have to always try and do what's right for them.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question there has been fandom backlash for the
Rangers once the budget-slashing stuff hit print. The Rangers had
raised ticket prices three consecutive seasons, starting in '97,
although the Hicks' regime was responsible for only the 1999 hike.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance of 2.75 million was also a serious disappointment
this season, and Hicks has vowed an all-out push this winter to
build a very low season-ticket base.
</P>
<P>
   But is it possible for his team to slash its budget, move out
some key players and also improve attendance in 2000 by selling
more season tickets?
</P>
<P>
   Common sense says nada. But in Arlington, baseball is a
different animal.
</P>
<P>
   The fans are restless while waiting on postseason progress. But
during the long wait, it's a club that can draw 2.7 million to 2.9
million just by opening the doors for 81 games. Reaching higher to,
say, a profitable 3.3 million level, will happen if the Rangers
ever become a postseason factor.
</P>
<P>
   Give Hicks credit for this backing off a substantial bankroll
cut in 2000. With a payroll of around $55 million, he could have
been at a break-even financial point with a 2.8 million gate draw.
Instead, the dice might be rolled again.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the Rangers are several weeks away from setting ticket
prices for the 2000 season. Nothing is final, but tickets might be
reduced in well over half of The Ballpark in Arlington's 49,000
seats, with a small price raise confined to less than 5 percent of
the seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``An announcement will be coming around the first of November,''
Hicks said. ``I can promise we will be aggressive in selling
tickets and very fair in dealing with the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the Yankees-induced playoff agony still an unpleasant
memory, Hicks took an unexpected reverse step yesterday in the
direction of fan fairness. If another $75 million is needed, he's
willing to spend in a business gone crazy with spending.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
