<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4405 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COMPUTER-CHIPS-NYT &LR;      10-21 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-CHIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORTAGE OF CHIPS FROM QUAKE'S DEVASTATION ON TAIWAN IS BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By WAYNE ARNOLD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ The personal computer industry has a variety of
things to worry about these days, but it turns out that supply
problems from the deadly earthquake in Taiwan last month may not be
one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to foresight, providence and factory workers who toiled
around the clock through a traditional Chinese festival, the
disaster a month ago that killed more than 2,000 people seems not
to have caused the widespread shortage of semiconductors many
experts feared.
</P>
<P>
   And though several American high-technology producers have
warned that such shortages could crimp earnings and make it hard to
meet the coming holiday-season demands for personal computers, some
of the biggest suppliers to those companies say not only that they
are back to normal, but also that they have managed to fill most of
their September orders.
</P>
<P>
   Chips are the brains of computers, and warnings from computer
makers about the impact of the Taiwan quake may just reflect the
industry tendency of making cautionary predictions. But the stark
divergence between the appraisals from corporations in the United
States and the optimism close to the quake's center is leading some
analysts and executives to wonder whether the companies are perhaps
blaming Mother Nature for other, man-made problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime a company doesn't make its numbers, they try to come
up with a reason,'' said Dane Anderson, a manager at International
Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan companies are important subcontractors for
high-technology consumer products and components. They produce
electronics that go into some of the world's best-known brands,
including IBM, Motorola and Toshiba, and Taiwan is the world's
third-largest source of personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   This month, at least four U.S. companies warned of potential
problems caused by the quake. The chief executive of
Hewlett-Packard told analysts that the company was sure to suffer
disruptions and delays. Advanced Micro Devices said problems in
Taiwan had hampered production of its new Athlon microprocessor and
could slow sales this quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, though saying it expected no ``material impact,'' warned
retailers that it would be unable to fill all their orders this
month. And on Monday, Dell said a spike in prices for memory chips
would hurt earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for personal computers, particularly portables, has been
strong all year and the last three months of the year tend to be
the strongest. But fierce competition to offer buyers an array of
the latest features at lower prices has eroded profit margins and
forced manufacturers to keep less stock on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Taiwan quake, analysts said, personal computer
makers faced short supplies of hard-disk drives and of flat-panel
screens for laptops. The booming market for mobile phones,
moreover, has led some semiconductor makers to divert capacity from
making chips for personal computers to making more profitable chips
for phones.
</P>
<P>
   Though Taiwan's semiconductor companies largely avoided
structural damage, production was halted by a weeklong power
cutoff. And despite soaring prices for memory chips, Taiwan
represents relatively little threat to global supplies: it accounts
for about 12 percent of the world's production.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the greatest risk was a shortage of more complex
logic chips used to run computer graphics and sound, as well as to
control hard-disk drives. Companies would need weeks, they had
predicted, to recalibrate sensitive equipment and run tests to make
sure that their intricate chips functioned properly.
</P>
<P>
   Some delays remain inevitable. An executive at Acer Laboratories
in the United States said this week that the Taiwan-based Acer had
delayed shipments of chip sets, which link logic chips to the rest
of the computer, and that computer makers would probably fall short
of their production targets as a result.
</P>
<P>
   When the quake hit, it shut down the island's largest chip
producer, Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   That weekend was the Midautumn Festival, an event celebrated
across Asia. At Taiwan Semiconductor, employees who would normally
be home nibbling moon cakes worked through the night to put the
company's factories back in order, said Ron Norris, the senior vice
president for worldwide sales and marketing. Power was restored by
Saturday and by the following Tuesday, the company was back up to
90 percent of production. Roughly 23,000 silicon wafers, each
containing as many as 1,000 chips, had to be scrapped, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the company was fortunate: rather than store its wafers
in big open containers, it had begun keeping them in sealed ones,
Norris said, which reduced damage and contamination. Even so, he
said, ``There's about two weeks of production that are just gone.''
</P>
<P>
   That loss of supply should have affected Asustek Computer, a
leading manufacturer of motherboards, the circuit boards that hold
many of the chips in a computer. Asustek plugs the chips into
motherboards before they are installed, and it had only three or
four weeks of chips on hand when the quake struck. David Chan, a
company spokesman, said Asustek's employees worked through the
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   With power off during the day, employees fired up a generator
and turned off the lights and air-conditioners. Power came on at
night, so they set up a graveyard shift, he said. The result: the
company missed less than 1 percent of its September orders,
according to Chan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite damage in excess of $2 billion from the quake, soaring
demand for electronics enabled Taiwan to post a nearly 1 percent
increase in exports in September.
</P>
<P>
   Norris speculated that given the amount of inventory typically
built up between a chip's manufacture and the time it ends up in a
personal computer, Taiwan's electronics companies should be able to
meet this quarter's demand for PCs with few disruptions. ``That's
why I'm concerned about anybody placing any dramatic impact on
this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the quake has underscored the risks of
manufacturing on an island that straddles an earthquake fault line.
Taiwan's electronics companies are already taking steps to protect
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Winbond Electronics, another chip maker, said this week that it
was reconsidering building a new factory in the same industrial
park as its five other plants and that it was looking overseas.
Asustek said it would seek permission to build two plants in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
