<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIANA ROSS ON THE STRESS OF BEING SEARCHED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Diana Ross &LR; , arrested briefly recently after she allegedly
struck a security guard she said had improperly touched her when
she set off a metal detector at Heathrow Airport, told the
Telegraph of London that the incident had a profound impact on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened at the airport brought the fear of death to
me,'' she said. ``After Heathrow, I am scared of dying. I really
am. It opened up a lot of fears for me. ... When I got back to
Connecticut, I had to get a minister to pray for me over the
phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross said she plays spiritual tapes every day. ``I spend a lot
of time with my higher self. I am working on my spirit and my soul
a lot; it comforts me. It keeps me on purpose, reminds me of the
beauty in life. You know what? It's not about prosperity, it's
about self.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOBACCO ANTI-ADS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Advertising Age ad critic  &UR; Bob Garfield  &LR; describes a new ad in
which Lorillard Tobacco intends to dissuade teenagers from smoking.
The tag line: ``Tobacco is whacko if you're a teen.'' More
persuasive than the language, writes the critic, is the image of a
``60-ish man with brown teeth'' inviting a teenager to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``As anti-smoking spots go, this one is more resonant than most.
That's because it isn't about death, it's about ugliness. Mortality
data are nothing to teenagers, who think they're invulnerable. But
brown teeth ... that's a horror they understand, believe and
internalize in an instant. ... Many children will see this and be
put off from smoking, by a company that sells cigarettes. Which is
undeniably positive, and positively absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ In North Beach on Wednesday, &UR; Firat Yener &LR;  saw  &UR; Tony Bennett &LR; 
