<HEADER>
A4408 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-POVERTY22-COX     10-21 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-POVERTY22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    End of child poverty is Bradley's latest goal
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Invoking former Presidents Franklin D. Roosevelt and
John F. Kennedy, Bill Bradley on Thursday proposed spending $10
billion a year to ``end child poverty as we know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also proposed increasing the minimum wage $1 over two
years and tying future increases to the nation's median wage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, at a time of unparalleled prosperity, I look out over a
nation and I see that nearly one-fifth of our children are ill-fed,
ill-housed and ill-educated,'' Bradley told a mostly
African-American audience in Brooklyn, as he echoed the famous
words Roosevelt first said during the Depression. ``I am issuing a
simple challenge today. Let us eliminate child poverty as we know
it in America by the end of the next decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's speech on poverty came a day after Vice President Al
Gore, at a Washington, D.C., church, offered more modest proposals
on fathers who don't pay child support. It was the third time Gore
had spoken about a specific issue shortly before Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley didn't mention his rival for the Democratic nomination.
But afterward, aides accused Gore of waging a ``campaign of
tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Bradley talks about children and poverty every day,''
said Bradley aide Anita Dunn. ``He's never seen it as a tactical
maneuver to blunt an opponent. You just have to look at what Al
Gore is talking about and when it gets scheduled. Maybe if they had
more of their own ideas they wouldn't have to continually pre-empt
ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiki Moore, Gore's spokeswoman, said the Bradley campaign had it
backwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks as though (former) Senator Bradley's big ideas are
actually Al Gore's ideas,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's speech was the last outlining Bradley's domestic
agenda. Earlier, he proposed a $55 billion program to offer health
care insurance to those who can't afford it through the private
network of insurers that cover federal employees. He has also
proposed spending $2 billion on child care.
</P>
<P>
   All of the initiatives have been intended to cast Bradley, a
former New Jersey senator and Rhodes scholar, as a big thinker.
</P>
<P>
   They also make Bradley the freest spender of all the
presidential candidates. Altogether, Bradley has proposed more than
$70 billion in new domestic programs, funded out of the $1 trillion
in non-Social Security surpluses estimated over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   He has not said how he would pay for the programs if those
projections are reduced by an economic recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to speculate about different variables,''
said Bradley spokesman Eric Hauser.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley gave only passing mention to the fact that child poverty
has declined from 26 percent to 22 percent since 1994 while
President Clinton and Gore have served.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley characterized his proposals on child poverty as only a
``down payment,'' and he likened his goal of ending such poverty to
Kennedy's vow to put a man on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eliminating child poverty as we know it is a big goal,'' he
continued. ``But the first step is the commitment and I am making
that here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley won enthusiastic reviews from the hundreds who crowded
into the gym at Concord Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's right on target with the issues that may not be on the
agenda of most politicians,'' said Concord pastor Gary Simpson.
``He raises the bar.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said his proposals could put 3 million of the nation's
13.5 million poor children above the poverty line by 2004, and help
another 4 million by 2008. The poverty line is defined by the
government as a yearly income of $16,400 or less for a family of
four.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond raising the minimum wage to $6.15 an hour, Bradley
proposed a $4 billion expansion of the earned income tax credit, a
cash rebate claimed by about 10 million tax filers who earn less
than the poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   A family of three with one parent working full-time and another
working part-time would get $2,920 a year more, Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley proposed doubling the size of Head Start for
disadvantaged 3- and 4-year-olds to $8.7 billion over four years,
making it available to all eligible children.
</P>
<P>
   To lure teachers to underserved areas, Bradley proposed spending
$1.3 billion to pay the college loans of 50,000 teachers if they
agreed to work in poorer communities. He proposed scholarships for
10,000 high school students who agreed to seek teaching degrees and
work in poor areas for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, Bradley proposed spending $1 billion a year to fund
nonprofits that established after-school programs, serving up to
5.6 million children in 2,000 centers.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Edelman, an expert on child poverty who resigned from the
Clinton administration over passage of the 1996 welfare reform
bill, said the scope of Bradley's initiatives surpass anything Gore
is proposing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very coherent package,'' Edelman said. ``The vice
president is unfortunately in the same tradition of the Clinton
administration. The rhetoric sounds OK, but the proposals are
miniscule.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
