<HEADER>
A4413 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHECHNYA-ATTACK-BOS &LR;      10-21 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-ATTACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN 100 DIE AS RUSSIAN ROCKETS HIT CHECHEN CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Rockets slammed into a crowded street market and other
parts of central Grozny on Thursday, killing more than 100 people
in the worst day of violence in Moscow's military campaign to
reassert control over breakaway Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen military officials said the rockets were fired by
Russian forces advancing on the capital, which have been pounding
Chechnya with airstrikes and artillery for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Defense Ministry, as it has consistently done whenever
civilians have been killed in Chechnya, denied responsibility for
the attack. Moscow says its strikes are aimed at bases used by
Islamic militants, but the rocket attack made it clear that no
place in the separatist Caucasus region was safe for anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from Grozny described a scene of carnage and destruction
after as many as six rockets exploded in the market, which was full
of shoppers during the early evening attack. Bodies and body parts
lay among the wrecked and bloodied stalls. Hundreds of terrified
people, some of them screaming and crying, ran through the streets.
</P>
<P>
   At least four other rockets exploded in other parts of the city,
including one that hit a maternity hospital, according to Magomed
Magomadov, a senior official in Chechnya's separatist government.
Magomadov put the death toll at 118 and estimated between 300 and
400 wounded. Many of the wounded faced operations in hospitals
already crowded from the fighting, short of medicine and, like the
rest of Chechnya. without electricity. ``We were at the central
city hospital,'' said Reuters correspondent Maria Eismont, a
veteran Russian war reporter who was 50 yards away when she said
one of the rockets hit the central market. ``It was packed with
corpses. There were women. Children. At least 30. There are so many
corpses and injured. Every minute they are bringing more and
more.''
</P>
<P>
   The attack came as heavy clashes erupted between Russian troops
and separatist militants north of the capital, and the Russian
government issued a statement vowing to ``act decisively and
harshly to achieve the full restoation of law and order on the
whole territory of the Chechen republic.''
</P>
<P>
   Chechen officials appeared to have little doubt the rockets were
an expression of this harshness. Mumaidi Saidayev, chief of staff
of Chechnya's military, said the rockets were Russian
surface-to-surface missiles fired by forces who have advanced to
high ground outside Grozny that overlooks the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The blast came as more Russian troops were reported to be
crossing the Terek River, the border of a ``security zone'' federal
troops had set up around rebel-controlled southern Chechnya, and
heading towards the capital.
</P>
<P>
   But Russian leaders gave mixed signals as to whether they would
try to take Grozny by storm. Russian and Chechen military officers
reported clashes along the Terek, and a Russian commander told NTV
television that his unit had suffered ``many casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian Prime Minister Vladimir Putin on Thursday headed for a
meeting of European leaders in Helsinki where he could face tough
questions from an increasingly worried West over Russia's actions.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian premier has said Moscow's quarrel is with ``illegal
bandit groups'' and ``international terrorists'' it blames for two
recent armed incursions into a neighboring southern Russian region
and a string of bomb attacks in Moscow and other cities that killed
nearly 300 people. Chechen militant leaders deny involvement in the
bombings.
</P>
<P>
   But as the death toll among civilians rises, the conflict is
looking increasingly like a bloody repeat of the 1994-1996 war that
killed tens of thousands and ended when Russian troops were forced
to withdraw from the region, leaving separatists in control.
</P>
<P>
   Russian aircraft and artillery pounded Chechen positions in
three settlements north of Grozny, killing six people, Chechen
officials said. They said the southern city of Urus Martan had been
hit late Wednesday in an air strike that killed 28; overall, they
claimed nearly 60 had died.
</P>
<P>
   It was impossible to confirm the figures. Russian officials
often accuse the Chechens of inflating civilian death counts to
attract international attention; the Russians themselves appeared
to be exagerrating when they claimed their operation had killed
over 3,000 ``bandits'' since August. Russia admits to losing 350
men, a figure the Chechens, and some Russian lawmakers, say is
wildly deflated.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to Western reporters Wednesday, Putin repeated his
claim that federal troops have no intention repeating the bloody
fiasco of its last invasion of Grozny in early 1995. But Thursday's
missile attack was only the latest indication that Russia has no
intention of sparing the capital, either.
</P>
<P>
   Another one came from Moscow's newly appointed envoy to the
region, Nikolai Koshman, who told reporters Wednesday that Grozny,
devastated during the last war, is too heavily damaged and cannot
be rebuilt. Koshman said that when the current fighting is done,
whenever that is, he would advocate building a new capital in a
different location.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later federal forces will enter Grozny. If not
troops, then (Russian) authorities will,'' Russian Deputy Defense
Minister Vladimir Toporov said Thursday, adding to the speculation.
His boss, Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev, tried to quash it by
saying: ``Why do you keep bringing up Grozny? Who is going to storm
it?''
</P>
<P>
   Military officers and analysts agree that trying to take the
capital and its resolute defenders makes little sense.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts see two reasons why the military might try to
take the capital. One motive is revenge. Many of the generals in
the current conflict are the same ones who lost the last one. They
say that meddling politicians stole their victory.
</P>
<P>
   The other motive is politics. Putin's popularity has risen
dramatically during the conflict. To maintain that popularity for
an expected presidential run next year, he may feel the need for
the dramatic victory winning back Grozny would bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main mistake of the 1994-1996 war is repeating itself,''
commented the news magazine Itogi. ``The military leaders are in
the hands of people who are first and foremost concerned with their
political careers.''
</P>
<P>
   Western leaders have avoided openly criticizing Russia but have
urged talks. Putin, whose rating in opinion polls has risen during
the campaign, has rejected talks with Chechen leader Aslan
Maskhadov unless Maskhadov hands over guerrilla leaders Moscow
blames for the bomb blasts, Shamil Basayev and the Arab-born
Khattab. On Thursday, authorities in Moscow detained Maskhadov's
representative, Mairbek Vachagayev; no explanation was given.
</P>
<P>
   But Maskhadov has little control over what Basayev and Khattab
do. And after Thursday's attack, retaliation appeared likely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
