<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MEDICARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS REBUFFS CLINTON'S DISCOUNT PLAN AS SENATE PANEL PASSES
MEDICARE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (dal) 
 By ROBERT PEAR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress rebuffed a proposal by President Clinton
to steer Medicare patients to certain hospitals and medical
suppliers who offer discounted prices to the government. But
lawmakers said Thursday that they would re-examine the proposal
next year, when they consider bigger changes in Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The comments came as the Senate Finance Committee approved a
bill to increase Medicare payments to many types of health care
providers, including hospitals, nursing homes, outpatient clinics,
home health care agencies, doctors and health maintenance
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, undoing some of the cuts made by the Balanced
Budget Act of 1997, would cost $15.4 billion over the next 10
years. The committee did not specify any way to pay for the
increases.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare finances health care for 39 million people who are
elderly or disabled. Under current law, the trust fund that pays
hospital bills for Medicare patients is scheduled to run out of
money in 2015. Under the Senate bill and under a similar measure
moving through the House, the trust fund would be depleted a year
earlier, in 2014, Medicare officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Finance Committee rejected several proposals by Sen. Bob
Graham, D-Fla., to help cover the cost by giving Medicare officials
new tools to negotiate lower prices on the goods and services they
purchase for the elderly. Graham has espoused these ideas for
several years; Clinton embraced them in June as part of his
comprehensive plan to redesign Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said Medicare could save money and perhaps even improve
the quality of care by adopting some of the techniques of managed
care: sending patients to ``centers of excellence'' for complex
surgical procedures; hiring specialists to coordinate the care of
patients with diabetes and congestive heart failure; making a
single ``bundled payment'' for all the care provided to an
individual, and securing discounts through price negotiations and
competitive bidding.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals would force health care providers to compete
against one another, in terms of the price and the quality of their
services. By contrast, Medicare is now open to virtually any
medical suppliers and providers who accept the government's fee
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   The Finance Committee rejected the proposals, 18 to 2.
Republicans on the House Ways and Means Committee have set aside
similar proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Several senators said they liked the proposals, but felt the
timing was wrong. For example, Sen. John H. Chafee, R-R.I., said,
``If this amendment were adopted, the whole bill would bog down.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., said: ``I feel like Senator Chafee.
Senator Graham has some excellent ideas. I hope we'll take them up
in the context of restructuring Medicare next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House may may try to push the proposals later this
year, when the House and Senate try to resolve differences in their
Medicare bills.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the White House press secretary, defended the
president's proposals, saying, ``These are very effective, very
reliable private sector practices that will save money.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart insisted: ``Quality will not be sacrificed under this
plan. Only the best and highest-quality health care providers will
be allowed to participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Jennings, the health policy coordinator at the White
House, said: ``When Congress refused to consider a prescription
drug benefit, it rendered any meaningful Medicare reform impossible
this year. The engine for true reform will be fueled next year by
the need for drug coverage under Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart M. Butler, a vice president of the Heritage Foundation,
said he saw merit in Graham's proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make the fee-for-service Medicare program work in a
cost-effective way, it has to incorporate some basic techniques of
managed care, just as Blue Cross and Blue Shield and other health
plans have done,'' Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   But, Butler said, if the Medicare agency, the Health Care
Financing Administration, is given this new authority, it must not
be allowed to set the rules for competition between the traditional
Medicare program and managed-care plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be like an umpire in the World Series working for
one of the teams,'' Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   Gail R. Wilensky, chairwoman of the Medicare Payment Advisory
Commission, which advises Congress on the health insurance program
for the elderly, said competitive bidding on standard items of
medical equipment was ``a perfectly sound strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, the success of any effort to steer patients to
specific hospitals will ``depend heavily on how you define quality,
because you don't want to end up just rewarding the low bidder.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William Roth Jr., R-Del., who is chairman of the Finance
Committee, blocked Democratic efforts to pay for the Medicare
package. ``This is entirely a Medicare bill,'' Roth said. ``It's
not a revenue bill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
