<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore vows oil drilling ban
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rye, N.H. _ Saying he will put environmental protection ``at the
very heart of my campaign for president,'' Vice President Al Gore
said Thursday he would block all new oil drilling off the shores of
Florida and California.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he selected those states because there is widespread
public opposition there to offshore drilling. He said he would work
to prevent more drilling even if companies already have been
granted leases to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to move faster in a bolder way,'' Gore told a
businessman who manufactures solar energy products, one of a group
of environmentalists who met with Gore at the Seacoast Science
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Gore repeated a pledge to push for ``the most sweeping
anti-sprawl legislation this country has ever seen,'' and said he
would spell out positions on other environmental issues in a series
of speeches over the next several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day earmarked for the environment. Gore talked about
the issue with a group of children posed against a scenic beach
backdrop. He included a group of California environmentalists,
teleconferenced in from Los Angeles, in his roundtable discussion.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also slammed Texas Gov. George W. Bush's
environmental record, saying Texas has the worst record in air,
water and land pollution. He called it ``troubling'' that Houston,
judged by the number of ozone alert days this year, now has the
nation's dirtiest air.
</P>
<P>
   He accused Bush of a ``lenient approach which has looked the
other way on the environment,'' but he declined to criticize the
environmental record of his Democratic opponent, former New Jersey
Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he would do everything in his power to block drilling
off Florida and California, ``even in areas already leased for
drilling by previous administrations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration already has announced a 10-year
extension of a moratorium on drilling off most of the U.S. coast,
but Gore said oil companies have proposed new drilling on existing
leases.
</P>
<P>
   An industry spokesman said Gore's proposal would force companies
to find new drilling sites overseas, increasing U.S. dependence on
imported oil and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make such a ban really ignores the need for natural gas and
oil to be produced domestically,'' said Mark Rubin of the American
Petroleum Institute. ``The bottom line here is that because we are
limited in our access to federal lands, the companies are forced to
spend their exploration budgets overseas, and this is going to
simply further that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bruce Hamilton, national conservation director of the Sierra
Club, said California and Florida are ``two highly desirable places
for complete protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore called for a ``gradual phasedown'' of the controversial
gasoline additive MBTE, and he promoted his proposal to provide $1
billion for ``smart growth'' initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   He also said there is growing evidence that his warnings about
the effects of global warming should be taken seriously. ``I find
more and more people who used to be skeptics about global warming
who now are convinced'' of the gravity of the problem, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
