<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-COMMANDMENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
41 LAWMAKERS TO POST TEN COMMANDMENTS IN OFFICES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By ANDREW BROMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Forty-one members of Congress agreed to post the
Ten Commandments in their offices Thursday as an endorsement for
legislation that critics say dangerously treads on the separation
of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   The Family Research Council will give the members a framed copy
of the Exodus version of the Ten Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   While some groups said such a campaign set a dangerous
precedent, Rep. Ralph Hall, D-Texas, saw no problem with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't push religion off on anybody,'' Hall said as he stood
behind a desk with a sign that reads ``pray.'' ``I don't think it's
a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Texas Reps. Sam Johnson, R-Plano, and Lamar Smith, R-San Antonio,
also agreed to post the commandments, although the three
congressmen have yet to receive them. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keeping religious items in the office is not a new development
for some members. Senate Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, has
kept a Bible and the commandments in his office for a couple years.
</P>
<P>
   Critics worry that Armey and others set the sort of example that
will give Congress momentum to pass legislation eliminating
barriers between religion and school. The House passed an amendment
to a juvenile justice bill in June that would permit states to post
the commandments in public places, including schools. The bill is
now in a Senate and House conference committee, where members will
negotiate a final version of a bill.
</P>
<P>
   Catharine LeRoy, public policy director for People For the
American Way, said her organization opposes the posting of the Ten
Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that this is part of a much larger campaign.
This is just sort of a symbolic piece of that whole agenda to go
against the founders of the Constitution,'' LeRoy said.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1980 case, the Supreme Court struck down a Kentucky law
requiring schools in that state to post the Ten Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   The House passed the Ten Commandments amendment in the wake of
the Columbine school massacre in Littleton, Colo., in an apparent
effort to reduce violence in schools.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Parshall, spokesperson for the Family Research Council,
said the group plans to capitalize on a shift in the nation's
attitude toward religion that developed after Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   ``When parents wake up in the morning now days, they don't worry
about the Dow. They worry about whether their kids' school will be
safe.''
</P>
<P>
   She said critics of religion in schools are out of touch with
what Americans want.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who are suffering from theo-phobia,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
