<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON REPORTS $169 MILLION NET LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. on Thursday reported a third-quarter net loss of
$169 million after charges because of delayed orders and shrinking
oversees profits.
</P>
<P>
   The loss for the Lexington, Mass., defense contractor was in
line with warnings it issued last week, and came despite a 7
percent rise in total sales for the three months ended Oct. 3.
Those revenues totaled $4.7 billion, up from $4.4 billion for the
same period a year ago with the hike driven by more payments from
defense and engineering programs.
</P>
<P>
   But fiercer competition forced down margins on some of those
projects, the company said. Raytheon also included a pretax charge
of $599 million for the period to account for disappointing
international orders, construction delays, and problems at a unit
of its Raytheon Aircraft Co. that retrofits jets for business
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon also said it will take pretax charges of about $39
million in the fourth quarter, and about $30 million in the first
quarter of 2000, as previously estimated. Some of these charges
will cover severance payments to about 2,380 workers the company
previously said it plans to lay off, including about 340 at
facilities in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's loss for the quarter of 50 cents per diluted share,
compared to a profit of $11 million, or 3 cents per diluted share,
for the same period a year ago after charges.
</P>
<P>
   The latest loss comes as Raytheon tries to assimilate defense
units purchased from Texas Instruments Inc. and Hughes Electronics
Corp. two years ago. The acquisitions doubled the company's size
but have yet to produce the big profit margins forecast by Raytheon
CEO Daniel Burnham.
</P>
<P>
   Announcing the expected charges last week, Burnham conceded the
company's integration efforts ``tried to do too much too fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's advance warning of growing losses sent the company's
shares down 44 percent on Oct. 12, to close at 24 1/4, a fraction
of the high of 74 15/16 reached in July. Raytheon closed Thursday
on the New York Stock Exchange at 29 1/4, up 3/16 for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts earlier expected the company to earn up to $4 a share
next year, but reduced their forecasts almost by half after last
week's warnings. Thursday's formal earnings report including ``no
surprises,'' said analyst Paul Nisbet of JSA Reserach Inc. in
Newport, R.I., but underscored how much ground Raytheon must still
make up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future is half as bright as it was before last week,''
Nesbit said. He said he hopes the company might trade around $36 a
share by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Among its problems Raytheon cited slower-than-expected orders
for its Patriot ground-to-air missile from customers such as Greece
and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Patriot orders can bring in $1 billion apiece, but Thursday, in
a conference call with analysts and reporters, Raytheon chief
financial officer Frank Caine said the company expects between $600
million and $700 million in revenues from the Patriot this year,
slightly below expectations, and less next year.
</P>
<P>
   To offset those declines, Raytheon has vowed to cut more costs.
</P>
<P>
   Caine said he also plans to hire an outside company to conduct
internal audits. ``More frequent and more direct business reviews
are becoming part of the landscape here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Caine said the company also will continue paying down debt it
took on to complete its acquisitions, expecting to have about $9.3
billion still outstanding at the end of the year, compared with
about $10.4 billion at the end of the third quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
