<SLUG> BC-GAPAC-EARNINGS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Storm effects gnaw at strong G-P profit
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia-Pacific Group has enjoyed a good run in
building products this year, although the boon may fade as the year
ends.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based company turned in a strong third-quarter
profit report Thursday, thanks to surging home construction in late
summer. But price drops and effects of Hurricane Floyd hurt
earnings at the end of the quarter, and these problems could
linger.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a confluence of events in the last few weeks
that have taken some of the bloom off the rose,'' incoming Chief
Financial Officer Danny Huff said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific shut down several plywood plants and lumber
mills because of flooding and wet weather from Hurricane Floyd and
other storms. Some mills are still closed, Huff said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, prices for lumber and structural panels took a
``precipitous drop'' that crunched inventories near the end of the
quarter, he said. The sharp declines are expected to hurt the
company's fourth-quarter results.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific Group's stock closed Thursday at $38, down
$1.75, or 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Huff said lumber prices should flatten out as the fourth quarter
progresses and as weather-related effects begin to subside.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, some analysts cut their estimates for the third
quarter due to concerns about higher prices and bad weather.
Georgia-Pacific Group, which excludes the company's timber
business, beat those reduced estimates. The company posted
third-quarter net income of $230 million, or $1.31 a share, against
the year-ago profit of $39 million, or 22 cents a share.
Georgia-Pacific was expected to earn $1.22 a share, based on a
survey of analysts by First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect the company to earn $1 a share in the fourth
quarter, according to First Call.
</P>
<P>
   The projected slowdown in building products will be offset by
the company's surging pulp and paper business, analysts said. In
the third quarter, operating profit in Georgia-Pacific's pulp and
paper segment rose sharply to $81 million, compared with $18
million one year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific's new paper distribution segment reported profit
of $43 million. Huff said profit will likely decrease in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The company's timber business beat expectations. Timber Co.
posted net income of $49 million, or 59 cents a share, compared
with $41 million, or 46 cents a share in the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   Timber Co. was expected to earn 49 cents a share, according to
First Call. The stock closed at $23.56 1/4, up 12 1/2 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
