<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION LEADER CHOSEN TO BE INDONESIA'S VICE PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ The day after voting down her bid for the
presidency, the National Assembly on Thursday elected Megawati
Sukarnoputri, a popular leader of the opposition to the ousted
Suharto regime, to the post of vice president.
</P>
<P>
   In a gesture of reconciliation _ and of pragmatic politics _
Mrs. Megawati was nominated for the post by the frail Muslim leader
chosen over her as president, Abdurrahman Wahid. Mrs. Megawati's
defeat on Wednesday fired an angry protest by her bitterly
frustrated supporters, and they had massed in the streets again
during Thursday's parliamentary session, threatening more violence
if she lost.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, as Mrs. Megawati _ the daughter of Indonesia's founding
leader, Sukarno _ stood before the assembly on Thursday evening in
a lavender silk dress to take her oath of office, her supporters
paraded through the dark streets of the capital, gunning their
motorcycles, setting off firecrackers and shouting her nickname,
``Mega! Mega!''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Megawati, who had appeared to be reluctant and unskilled at
back-room maneuvering and was visibly uncomfortable during the
parliamentary votes, seemed at ease on Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   She paid special tribute to the students and others whose
stubborn and often dangerous protests had helped bring down Suharto
17 months ago and had championed her candidacy in the months since
then.
</P>
<P>
   But now, she said, the time had come to restore normalcy and
calm to a nation that has remained on edge as the political and
social forces released by the departure of a dictator threatened to
tear it apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``To all my children throughout the nation, I beg you sincerely
to return to work,'' she said. ``Do not be goaded into emotional
actions, because what you see here today is your mother standing
before you.''
</P>
<P>
   In the voting, Mrs. Megawati defeated the leader of an
influential Moslem party, Hamzah Haz, by a vote of 396-284, with
five abstentions. That ballot followed more closed-door maneuvers
in which two stronger challengers were persuaded to withdraw _
Akbar Tanjung, the leader of the old Suharto party, Golkar, and
General Wiranto, the military chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   The voting on Thursday was accompanied by cheers, chants,
prayers and finally the tearful singing of the national anthem. It
was an outpouring of emotion that seemed to reflect a sense of
relief that Indonesia had weathered a long and turbulent transition
from the repressive autocracy of Suharto to a government that was
beginning to listen to the voices of its people.
</P>
<P>
   But some Indonesians who have struggled hard for reform said
this was still not the kind of democracy they had been working for.
Mrs. Megawati won a plurality of 34 percent in a general election
in June but was defeated by Wahid _ the fourth-place finisher _ in
the closed-door horse trading of the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday was a very difficult day for us; yesterday was a
demonstration that the election did not mean anything,'' said Emmy
Hafild, an environmental campaigner, referring to the vote in June.
``The political elites are the ones who decide the outcome, and not
the election. I know this is the best we can do for now, but it's
hard to accept.''
</P>
<P>
   Though enormously popular among Indonesians and respected for
his championship of tolerance, Wahid is largely untested as a
national leader, and in poor health. In contrast to Mrs. Megawati,
whose politics were defined largely by opposition to Suharto, Wahid
is regarded as his own man, as one of the few major figures in
Indonesia who gained prominence independent of either his
connection with or opposition to the Suharto government.
</P>
<P>
   The hermetic corridors of power are an arena where Wahid has
shown himself a master _ a man who can joke and jive his way into
seemingly mutually exclusive partnerships as he did in the past,
simultaneously embracing Suharto and Mrs. Megawati.
</P>
<P>
   But now he faces the tasks of charting a new course, choosing a
Cabinet, forging political alliances and seeking solutions to a
daunting array of problems that have been largely set aside over
the past months of political crisis.
</P>
<P>
   As he does so, he will need to satisfy the unlikely coalition of
Muslim parties, old-guard members of Suharto's party and possibly
the military, which gave him his victory in the secret ballot on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid has maintained good relations with the armed forces and
was expected to be able to work well with it. But in Indonesia's
militarized society, with the loss of East Timor still a source of
great bitterness to many officers, the military was certain to
remain a force to reckon with.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
