<HEADER>
A4425 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-21 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: LET RUDY BE RUDY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rudolph Giuliani needs to sit down and take deep
breaths before he decides to run for the Senate. Sure, he could
probably do the job. Don't worry about people who tell you he lacks
a collegial temperament. Have you seen the Senate lately? Half the
members are impossible and the other half are in a permanent sulk
because they aren't president.
</P>
<P>
   But would he be happy?
</P>
<P>
   ``If people agree with what I've done ... That's exactly the job
I'd do in the Senate,'' Giuliani told 1,600 people at a Women for
Rudy fund-raiser Thursday, offering his traditional rundown of his
fights against crime and city bureaucrats. It was hard to figure
out how he'd employ those skills in the Capitol, unless he is
planning to arrest Ted Kennedy for jaywalking.
</P>
<P>
   The speech was fine if you wanted to hear about the mayor's war
against taxi drivers, the war against drug dealers, the war against
welfare agency bureaucrats, and of course the current
all-engrossing war against the Atlanta Braves. But it was a wee bit
short on signals about exactly what he was interested in doing in
Washington, or even any strong indication that he was aware the
planet extended beyond the bounds of New York City, the place
Giuliani likes to call Capital of the World.
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Susan Molinari, who served as master of ceremonies,
also seemed a bit befuddled. She rhapsodized about his performance
on the present job. (``Mayor Giuliani is there, no matter what
problems confront us, whether it's traffic or crimes or fire.'')
</P>
<P>
   But when it came time to switch gears, Ms. Molinari had trouble
rounding the rhetorical bend. She settled for urging the guests to
make sure ``whoever we send to the U.S. Senate has the dignity, the
honesty, the courage to work to make sure that New York State is in
the best hands it can possibly be in.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah yes, the state. Can you imagine how much fun it would be to
have Rudy Giuliani as governor of New York? You could sell tickets.
All the agencies would be headed by former assistant federal
prosecutors _ think of the excitement in the highway department
alone. The traditional decision-making by three guys in a room
would be replaced by one guy with a subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has been showing signs of burnout lately, probably
because there is no longer anyone left in the city of New York with
the energy to fight with him, nobody left he can sue all the way to
the Supreme Court, a body that by now must have a separate wing for
its Giuliani files. You can't tell me he doesn't fantasize about
what it would be like to go to Albany, where the legislators and
bureaucrats still confidently walk around with their soft
underbellies exposed.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Republicans have certainly fantasized about what it
would be like to have Rudy Giuliani at the helm of state
government, and it was that very image that caused most of them to
endorse Giuliani for a job that would ship him far, far away in the
opposite direction. But they still expect the mayor to show that if
he went to Washington, he would demonstrate some modicum of party
loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Giuliani, the Republican senators have been
behaving lately in a manner calculated not only to terrify soccer
moms, but frighten the hockey dads as well. Thanks to Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, the mayor has loyally gone on the
record as saying he would have voted against the nuclear test ban
treaty last week.
</P>
<P>
   He has also been forced to announce that he thought the $792
billion Republican tax cut would have been ``great'' and that he
has grave, grave reservations about raising the minimum wage. If
Lott wants to do Giuliani any more favors, perhaps he could try
banning the Harry Potter books.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Giuliani has always been an apolitical crusader at heart.
It's almost painful to watch him trying to bow to the yoke of party
discipline after a lifetime of making other people obey his rules.
It's too bad cities can't hire mayors, the way they used to hire
sheriffs.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani could make a career of riding from town to town,
pummeling every municipality in America into perfect order, one by
one. If Hillary Clinton can be a candidate in New York, Rudy
Giuliani ought to be allowed to run in Baltimore or San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
