<SLUG> BC-ALTA-VISTA-REDESIGN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERHAUL IS SET FOR POPULAR INTERNET SEARCH ENGINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the Internet's most powerful search engines is getting an
overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   In a ceremony in New York on Monday, AltaVista Co. will reveal a
major redesign of its service, with enhanced shopping and
multimedia search features, and an expanded listing of Web pages.
CMGI Inc., which bought 83 percent of AltaVista in June, is buffing
up the site for a planned public stock offering early next year.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI, based in Andover, Mass., also hopes to attract a new level
of public interest in AltaVista. The site has a strong reputation
for comprehensive Internet searches; according to the Web-site
rating firm Media Metrix, AltaVista attracted 9 million visitors in
August, making it the 15th most-visited site on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, that puts AltaVista far behind industry
leader Yahoo, with its 33 million visitors, or even the 14.8
million visitors of eighth-ranked Lycos, of which CMGI holds a 17
percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista executives refuse to speak directly about their site's
makeover, but industry-watchers who've seen it say major efforts
have been made to simplify Web searching. AltaVista's powerful
search technology often turns up tens of thousands of ``hits'' for
every inquiry _ far too much information to be truly useful. One
source who insisted on anonymity says that the new AltaVista will
offer categorization features to make it easier for users to narrow
down their searches.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Cassar, an analyst for Jupiter Communications Inc. in New
York, said AltaVista has made major changes in its Internet
shopping services. Up to now, AltaVista has featured merchandise
sold by Shopping.com, an Internet retailer purchased by AltaVista's
former parent company, Compaq Computer Corp., earlier this year.
CMGI acquired Shopping.com along with AltaVista, and in the process
picked up a few new headaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shopping.com didn't have the best reputation in the world,''
said Cassar. Before Compaq and then CMGI bought the company, the
Better Business Bureau had received hundreds of complaints against
Shopping.com related to late delivery of purchased items.
</P>
<P>
   Cassar says that in the new AltaVista shopping portal,
Shopping.com will be merely one of many merchants on the site.
Visitors in search of a particular item will be able to shop a
number of on-line stores simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly an improvement over what they have now,'' said
Cassar.
</P>
<P>
   But Cassar also noted that the new shopping feature won't be
much different from existing services from Yahoo or Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's interesting to me,'' he said, ``is that the commerce
sites and the portals have all started to look a lot like each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Bane, an analyst with the Yankee Group in Boston, agrees
that major portals have all rushed to offer similar features, until
it's difficult to distinguish one from the other. But after seeing
a preview of the new AltaVista, Bane said the redesigned site will
be easier to use than many of its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the market's going to be pleasantly surprised with
AltaVista,'' Bane said.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista isn't an island. CMGI owns interests in about 50
Internet companies ranging from on-line merchants to software
developers, and CMGI chairman David Wetherell is determined to
weave them into an integrated network of companies.
</P>
<P>
   For example, CMGI recently acquired Engage Technologies Inc.,
which creates anonymous profiles of Web surfers that can be used to
precisely target advertising to likely customers. AltaVista will
use Engage's software to collect profile data on its millions of
visitors; the site also will use the Engage profiles to govern
which ads are displayed on visitors' computer screens.
</P>
<P>
   If the new look at AltaVista leads to more visitors, this can't
help but improve prospects for the planned IPO, said Ullas Naik,
who tracks Internet firms for First Albany Corp. in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think that they acquired this property for $2.5 billion and
could spin it off for a valuation somewhere north of $4 billion, is
a pretty good return on investment,'' Naik said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
