<HEADLINE>
OUR MEMORIES ARE REFRESHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good news: Researchers think the adult brain generates new cells
every day. The previously accepted theory had been that man gets a
set allotment of neurons and when they go, they go.
</P>
<P>
   Many a person celebrating a birthday beyond age 40 has reflected
upon the state of his or her brain cells and wondered about the
count, particularly when celebrating with alcohol, which, according
to a report that came out a few years ago, depletes the supply with
each glass.
</P>
<P>
   But Princeton biologists, who published their findings in the
journal Science last week, gave the world the happy news that in
monkeys, at least _ and most likely in human beings, although that
research has yet to be done _ new brain cells just keep on coming,
like fresh air. They grow in the stem cell region of the brain and
spread to the areas of the cortex involving memory and decision-
making.
</P>
<P>
   The findings offer hope to people with degenerative diseases,
for someday scientists may be able to direct new cells into any
part of the brain that is deteriorating. The report also punctures
dreary conventional wisdom about aging, for brain cells need no
longer be thought of as the mental equivalent of fading flashlight
batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Positive brain news is always a relief because most people
understand little of what is going on up there. They use their
brains the way they drive their cars _ the stuff under the hood is
incomprehensible, but if somebody tells them they're getting better
mileage than they thought, they're delighted.
</P>
<P>
   The brain is a kind of Oz, a fantastic kingdom that scientists
keep probing, much like scouts on the frontier. Periodically they
report back, announcing that people are using only a fraction of
the space. Such reports are always worrisome. But envisioning a
cavalry of vigorous neurological reinforcements galloping to the
aid of anyone having a ``senior moment'' can put a spring in a
person's step and a smile on one's face.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
