<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MONEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BOTTOM LINE IN WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The corrupting influence of money in American politics is on
dramatic display.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, senators who benefit disproportionately from
special-interest campaign contributions killed a bill to make
politics fairer and more open to average voters.
</P>
<P>
   At least the senators got to vote. Wednesday morning, dollars
actually supplanted votes as a financially strapped Elizabeth Dole
ended her presidential candidacy before a single ballot had been
cast. ``In the real America, it's more important to raise issues
than to raise campaign funds,'' she said. But in a national
campaign, ``the bottom line remains money.''
</P>
<P>
   This ugly chapter began last week when Senator Mitch McConnell
challenged Senator John McCain, a lead proponent of reform, to back
up his charges that the system is corrupt by naming names. McCain
wisely demurred; his target is the system, not specific people.
Still, examples are rife:
</P>
<P>
   --On June 22, airlines contributed $115,000 in soft money to
Republican committees. The next day, a Senate committee gutted a
strong passenger rights bill, essentially making it voluntary.
Before night, the airlines contributed $95,000 more.
</P>
<P>
   --Out of the many questionable contributions to President
Clinton's reelection campaign, a House committee has pointed to
$220,000 from Yah Lin Trie and his family as possibly influencing
administration policy toward China.
</P>
<P>
   --Walt Disney CEO Michael Eisner gave $1,000 to Senator Trent
Lott the very day Lott signed onto a bill extending the copyright
on Mickey Mouse. Disney sent $25,000 more to a GOP group later.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell can argue all he wants that the influence of campaign
donations does not meet the legal definition of bribery. Sometimes
outright bribery does occur, but the point of reform is to change a
system that is corrupted legally.
</P>
<P>
   Congress demonstrates every day that special interests can buy
results. More broadly, Dole's departure shows how big money is
stealing democracy from the people. That is corruption or the word
has lost all meaning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
