<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-HEALTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORT FOR MEDICAL EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Health care financing in the United States is a mess. Pending an
overhaul that encourages every American to obtain health insurance
and spreads the cost of care across the population, the federal
government should not hack away at programs that sustain important
medical institutions. Congress would be wise to restore some of the
cutbacks affecting hospitals, especially those that train the next
generation of physicians.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Finance Committee and the House Ways and Means
Committee are working on proposals that would undo some of the
damage caused by the Balanced Budget Act of 1997. That law was
essential for fiscal stability, but many members of Congress agree
that it went too far. With the economy strong and Medicare spending
less than expected, it is time to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   The Ways and Means Committee is considering a bill that would
make many health care improvements, chief among them an extra $1.2
billion over five years for outpatient services. A key feature of
the Finance Committee bill is its allocation of $1.8 billion more
to train physicians. The final bill ought to provide significant
support for medical education.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare bears a disproportionate burden in supporting hospitals
and medical education because it is the only federal program that
covers the health care needs of a large cross-section of the
population. If Congress extends the same opportunity for coverage
to other Americans, it would be appropriate to consider changing
the funding mechanism for hospitals. Until that time comes,
Congress needs to make sure Medicare provides enough support to
maintain the financial health of these vital institutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
