<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV07-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., NOV. 7, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I built a small workbench in my garage where I work on my
hobby of building model boats. I use several different types of
small electric tools and small lamps in my work.
</P>
<P>
   There is an electric outlet on the wall nearby, but this is
really not enough as I need to have three or four tools and
appliances plugged in at the same time, so I have been using an
extension cord and multiple plugs.
</P>
<P>
   This is messy (too many wires and plugs that keep falling out)
and probably unsafe. Is there a better _ and safer _ solution you
can suggest without having to pay for an expensive electrician?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can buy multiple-outlet strips that can be permanently
mounted on a wall or other surface. These are connected by a
flexible extension cord to an existing outlet so that you can plug
in anywhere from four to six separate tools or appliances at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   However, all the electrical plugs will be relatively close to
each other (such strips usually vary from about 12 to 18 inches in
length) which is not always convenient.
</P>
<P>
   A better and more permanent solution is to install some
``surface wiring'' of the type shown here. Available at all home
centers, this system consists of surface-mounted raceways or
channels that contain the wires on the inside and permit you to add
as many outlets as desired.
</P>
<P>
   But remember that this does not increase the amount of power
available (if you connect up to a 15 amp circuit you will still
have a total of only 15 amps available).
</P>
<P>
   The raceway starts at an existing wall outlet and is ``hard
wired'' (permanently connected) to that outlet. A switch can be
installed as shown to control power to the new receptacles.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My basement walls are made of cement block and there is a
white chalky powder on the surface near the bottom of two walls.
What is this material and what if anything should I do to get rid
of it before I paint?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is undoubtedly efflorescence _ a condition often
encountered in masonry when there is moisture present. Alkaline
salts which are always present in masonry are leached out by the
moisture and this is what you see.
</P>
<P>
   The efflorescence should be removed before painting by scrubbing
with a dilute solution of muriatic acid (one part acid to five
parts water). Wear rubber gloves to protect your hands and goggles
to protect your eyes. Rinse off with lots of water.
</P>
<P>
   However, the condition could return (even after painting) if you
don't get rid of the moisture problem.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have plastic covered kitchen cabinets with a wood finish.
The cabinets are in good condition but some of the doors are sticky
around the knobs due to handling. Ordinary washing doesn't seem to
remove this. What can you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's likely that this is simply grease and soil, possibly
embedded in the wax or polish that you have applied to the cabinets
over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The sticky residue can usually be removed by washing with a
household detergent or spray cleaner, but if this doesn't do the
trick then you can clean it off by wiping down with a solvent such
as paint thinner. This is highly flammable so make sure you observe
all precautions against fire.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a good idea to test the solvent first on an
inconspicuous corner to make certain it will not affect the finish.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have a plumbing problem in our new house. When someone is
in the shower and a person runs the cold water somewhere else in
the house, the shower turns scalding hot, while if that person runs
the hot water, the shower suddenly runs cold. What causes this?
</P>
<P>
   A: It is possible that the water pipes are not large enough to
provide a full flow of water to more than one fixture at a time.
</P>
<P>
   An even more likely cause is that the incoming water pressure
from the main line is not adequate to provide a full flow of water.
You should have your local water company check this.
</P>
<P>
   If you cannot solve the problem then you may want to think about
having a special temperature-controlled shower valve installed
(this will control the temperature regardless of pressure
variations).
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``ELECTRICAL WIRE RACEWAY'' goes with
this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: `Surface wiring' allows for multiple outlets positioned
where needed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
