<HEADER>
A4440 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CALIF-DAIRY-FARMS-ART     10-21 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-DAIRY-FARMS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CHINO, Calif.: growing metropolis.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Dairying became so important to the local economy that when a
county seal was created in the 1950s, the business was honored on
the emblem. On the seal were figures representing the pillars of
the local economy, including, among other things, an oil well, a
tuna and a cow. Her name was Pearlette.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its density, another quirk of the dairy industry
here was that it was operated almost entirely by immigrants. The
largest group were Dutch immigrants, many of whom came before and
just after World War II and quickly adapted their northern European
techniques to the hot, dry climate. In addition, there were many
Portuguese immigrants, mostly from the Azores, and a handful of
French Basque farmers.
</P>
<P>
   These days, many farmers, like Mrs. DeBoer and her husband,
Fred, still speak Dutch and visit relatives in their homeland
periodically. They also have built extremely tight-knit
communities, with their own churches and schools. To this day, the
industry in Southern California is dominated by the Dutch, and the
dairy industry in northern California, toward the top of the
Central Valley, is dominated by Portuguese families. As the Dutch
immigrants in Chino have moved to Tulare, among the first things
they have done is construct a new network of churches and schools.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the industry was forced to move, it also pulled up
stakes in a hurry. Joel Splansky, a professor of geography at
California State University at Long Beach and the author of a
history of the dairy business here, said that as recently as 1962
the town of Dairy Valley, one of the centers of the industry in Los
Angeles County, had 3,505 people and 85,000 cows.
</P>
<P>
   It was not long after that that rising taxes, changing policies
regarding the use of land and environmental concerns over growing
manure piles forced the farmers to build their larger and more
efficient operations in the Chino Valley. Today, the town of Dairy
Valley is called Cerritos. It has a population of 53,240 people,
and no cows.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the growth of the industry in the Chino Valley was
encouraged; there were few restrictions or environmental concerns.
There are now about 880 cows on average on each farm in Chino, with
many having 2,000 or so, compared with a national average of fewer
than 50 cows per farm.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The farms are operated with machine-like precision and a pure
business philosophy. Asked if their cows had names, the farmers
here chuckled.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a lot of those farms in the Midwest and back East, every
cow has a name,'' Koopman said. ``They're sort of pets. It's not
like that here. A cow's a piece of machinery. If it's broke, we try
to fix it, and if we can't, it gets replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, every cow has a number and a page on the computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. DeBoer said she has never milked a cow by hand, and never
expects to. In the factory that is her barn, the employees, almost
entirely Latino, manage the incessantly humming machinery. ``It's
just a factory is what it is,'' she said. ``If the cows don't
produce milk, they go to beef.''
</P>
<P>
   One result is a conspicuous flow of wealth to the north. Modern
milking plants cost about $5 million to build in Tulare, but the
farmers, and their bankers, think nothing of constructing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are some of the most profitable times ever,'' said Larry
Zivelonghi, manager of agricultural lending at the Citizens
Business Bank, the biggest local farm lender here. ``Feed costs are
low, milk prices are high. There's a lot of money going to these
farmers now.''
</P>
<P>
   The average farm here, Zivelonghi said, generates about $250,000
to $300,000 a month in milk sales, and loan default rates have been
minimal. ``The risk of lending in this business has been nominal,
almost zero,'' he said. ``I don't know how many businesses you can
say that about.''
</P>
<P>
   But now the barns are being replaced with handsomely designed
entry gates topped with fluttering sales banners and signs offering
houses at $200,000 and up. Within a mile or so of Mrs. DeBoer's
farm are several new shopping centers with everything from a giant
Ralphs supermarket to a handful of dry cleaning shops, a Tasty Wok
restaurant and a 24-hour fitness club.
</P>
<P>
   A huge billboard in front of a 360-acre spread bulldozed
billiard-table smooth, proclaims: ``The Corona Valley. Worth the
Wait.'' The former dairy is being turned into a planned community.
</P>
<P>
   Such grandiose projects have accelerated the county's pressure
on the remaining farmers to clean up the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the farms are surrounded by berms meant to contain the
spread of water contaminated with manure when it floods in the
winter. The county is also demanding that the dairies ship out the
900,000 tons of manure they produce every year, as well as the 2
million tons of manure currently stockpiled in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 25 years I resisted it,'' said Feenstra, of the Milk
Producers Council. ``We finally realized we needed to take some
responsibility. Within maybe five years, this will be largely
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It's a way of life for these people. It's a gene.
But it's not the land, it's the business they love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
