<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-INDONESIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW LEADER IN INDONESIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Indonesia, the nation most battered by the Asian financial
collapse of 1998, has selected a new president, the moderate Muslim
leader Abdurrahman Wahid. A respected advocate for pluralism and
human rights, Wahid will confront two interlaced challenges: to
nurture the nascent institutions of democracy and to make the
structural changes needed to convert Indonesia from a thieves'
paradise into a modern market economy endowed with the transparency
and accountability that can attract investors, create jobs, and
lift millions of people out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of Wahid's selection by an Assembly vote of 373
to 313, Indonesian markets exhibited anxieties about his health. He
has suffered a stroke and is nearly blind. But the more salient
concern should be for Indonesia's rehabilitation from the
authoritarian system presided over by the strongman Suharto, who
used his nearly absolute power to enrich his family and his inner
circle for more than three decades.
</P>
<P>
   As unruly as the selection process may have been and as
resentful as supporters of candidate Megawati Sukarnoputri are that
she was not selected, Wahid becomes the first Indonesian leader
since independence to be selected in a free and contested election.
The Assembly that picked him also made the praiseworthy gesture of
ratifying East Timor's overwhelming vote for independence.
</P>
<P>
   If Wahid is to succeed in establishing a durable democratic
polity for Indonesia, he will have to circumscribe the powers of
the military. The most promising sign Wahid could give of his
willingness to establish civilian control over the military would
be to end cross-border raids into East Timor by army-backed
militias operating out of Indonesian territory in West Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever came to power in present-day Indonesia &UR;  &LR; would confront
the same need to cultivate democratic values and institutions,
cauterize the old culture of corruption, and create a national
unity rooted not in coercion but in the principles of fairness,
freedom, and representative government. Indonesians deserve a
leader who is up to this challenge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
