<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIGARS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cigar trend up in smoke
 &HT;    By Sheryll Poe
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The cigar craze has burned itself out.
</P>
<P>
   Cigars had enjoyed a trendy revival in the late 1990s, in part
due to glossy magazines like ``Cigar Aficionado,'' which featured
hot Hollywood stars like Demi Moore and Sylvester Stallone smoking
stogies.
</P>
<P>
   But for 1999, analysts predict a 10 percent fall in sales of
premium cigars. Three cigar companies _ JR Cigar Inc., General
Cigar Holdings and Dimon Inc. _ reported quarterly revenues down
significantly from the same period in 1998. Holt's, another cigar
company, saw its stock downgraded by Prudential Bache.
</P>
<P>
   ``People with extra money, the techies, today they like
martinis, jazz and cigars, tomorrow it's cars. They get bored too
easily,'' said Charlie Guluzian, owner of the Cigar Palace in
downtown Austin. ``The trend was because of the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The cigar business crested in 1964, when Americans were smoking
9 billion yearly. By 1992, government health warnings had caused
the industry to fall some 77 percent, to 2.1 billion cigars yearly.
</P>
<P>
   Then, suddenly, things changed. There was a 14.6 percent jump in
sales in 1994, followed by a 31 percent rise in 1995. In 1996,
sales of premium, hand-rolled cigars jumped 67 percent. In 1997,
they leaped another 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Cigar Association of America didn't compile figures for
1998. But, two years later, retailers and cigar manufacturers
report that fewer people are lighting up. The ``cigar great
awakening'' was bound to crash, said Gerald Celente of Trends
Research Institute in Rhinebeck, N.Y. The boom was
marketing-driven, rather than consumer-driven, and reality couldn't
sustain the imagery, he said, especially among women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unfeminine, and they stink,'' he said. ``Despite all
the hype and the glossy advertising, women were never going to
become cigar smokers en masse.''
</P>
<P>
   Cigar smoking has a heavy ``repulse factor'' that makes cigar
smokers a nuisance at parties and restaurants, Celente said.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't slowing down Guluzian. He plans to open a
10,000-square-foot Cuban club called Club Bolivar in December. The
club, to be located above the Cigar Palace, will feature cigars
from the store. A yearly membership will go for $5,000. Guluzian
said he has already had enough commitments from potential members
to assure the club's success. Mark Tiedeken, manager for Market
Wine &AMP; Spirits in Round Rock, said he has a lot of longtime
customers. ``Our sales are increasing,'' he said, ``but the trend
part is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Market Wine &AMP; Spirits expanded its humidor in February, adding
200 square feet, and is considering expanding again.
</P>
<P>
   Chet Butler, general manager of the Speakeasy cigar bar, which
opened in 1997, attributes the slowdown to a decrease in excess and
nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The swing thing slowed down at the same time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Butler plans to concentrate on local talent and live music
instead of the techno DJs he sees at other local bars. ``At this
rate, we may be the only one's with live music,'' said Butler.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never really prided ourselves on our cigars,'' said Butler.
``I'm not sorry to see the trend go. You have to evolve or get
crushed.''
</P>
<P>
   Cigar vendors are now left to count on the loyalty of long-term
smokers to carry them through the smoke-free trend. ``My customers
are not trendy people. They are lifelong smokers,'' Guluzian said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The craze is over,'' said Norman Sharp, president of the Cigar
Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   This article includes material from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
