<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOWDEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL IN THE FAMILY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes news Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ After 388 games as a football coach's wife
and countless more games as a sports mom, Ann Bowden should know
how to handle a momentous event. But having your husband coaching
against one of your sons in a game of historical significance isn't
covered in the Mother's Manual.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State at Clemson on tomorrow's schedule is more than
just another football game. For the Bowden Bunch, it's part family
reunion, part family feud. Papa Bobby Bowden coaches the
top-ranked, 7-0 Seminoles; son Tommy Bowden is in his first year as
the coach of the 3-3 Tigers. For Mama Bowden, the game is a
division of emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always pulled for my sons, and I get more nervous about
their games,'' Ann Bowden said. ``I don't think this is all going
to hit me until I walk into the stadium. It's going to be hard.
There's a lot at stake for us. We've got a shot at the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a very unusual situation.''
</P>
<P>
   College football's family feuds have been limited, in 13 games,
to brother vs. brother. But never has a father coached against his
son at the I-A level. And, adding to the drama, a victory would
give the 69-year-old Bobby Bowden No. 300 for his career, a
milestone reached by just four other Division I-A coaches _ Paul
``Bear'' Bryant (323), Pop Warner (319), Amos Alonzo Stagg (314)
and Joe Paterno (314).
</P>
<P>
   Terry Bowden, a former Auburn coach, will add a historical
footnote. As studio commentator for ABC Sports' college football
coverage, he'll be the first brother to comment on a game between
his father and brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be fun,'' said Terry, who because of his television
work will be the only one of Bobby and Ann's children not in
attendance. ``This family has always thought of college football as
being very special. Whatever happens is a win-win situation for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, Bobby and Ann Bowden will watch grandson, Ryan _
Tommy's boy _ play a high school football game. Tomorrow, Ann will
get her first look at the house being built by Tommy and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's as excited as she can be because of all the family
that's going to be together,'' Bobby Bowden said. ``She's
sacrificed a lot during our marriage; she's a football wife. I
think this game will be one of the highlights of her life. She
wants Florida State to win, but she'll want Tommy's team to do
well. She'd be happy if \RFlorida State\S won by a point.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Bowden said most of his family will be rooting for his
dad's team. Especially mom.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knows how much dad's bonus is if he wins the national
championship,'' Tommy, 45, said. ``That's shopping money, Christmas
money.'' \Nsubheds:Family affair
</P>
<P>
   Bumper stickers have been printed that read, ``This Ain't No
Family Picnic.'' A sellout of 85,000-plus is expected for the game
(6 p.m., ESPN). And it just seems as though 84,000 of them are
somehow connected to the Bowden clan or Florida State. Clemson
assistants Rick Stockstill, Reggie Herring, Brad Scott and Jack
Hines all played and//or coached under Bobby Bowden at Florida
State. Bobby's youngest son, Jeff, is the Seminoles' receivers
coach. Hines, Clemson's secondary coach, is married to Robyn, the
Bowden's eldest child.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bowden family, the football doesn't fall far from the
tree. Ginger, the youngest of the Bowdens, works in the Florida
attorney general's office. Her football connection? She married
John Madden, a former Florida State player.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby and Ann grew up a few blocks from each other in
Birmingham, Ala. Bobby quarterbacked the high school football team.
Ann was a cheerleader _ a true relationship cliche.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up thinking I wanted to be a cheerleader and marry a
football player,'' Robyn said. ``That's how it impacted me. I don't
remember it being a big deal having our dad be the football coach.
But football was just always something that was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bowden's head coaching career started at Samford
University in Birmingham in 1959. Robyn remembers going to games
dressed in cheerleader outfits. Terry and his brothers remember
road trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team traveled in buses and we would crawl up in the
luggage racks above the seats and go to sleep,'' Terry said. ``And
those players, we really looked up to them, they were big ol' guys
who made us laugh. We thought of 'em as old men and of course, they
were all just 19, 20 years old. We lived in a dream world.''
</P>
<P>
   Sort of like a 1950s TV sitcom. Father knew football best and
worked to build a successful career. Mother took care of the home
as a full-time mom and part-time dad.
</P>
<P>
   Steve, a private businessman who manages his parents' money, was
the sensitive, deep thinking older brother. Tommy, though a
prankster, was cautious, looking before he leaped. Terry was an
overachieving Type A all the way, leaping before he looked. Jeff
was the picked-on youngest brother. If there was a discipline issue
involving all four brothers, Terry often would take the blame. ``He
just wanted to get it over with to get on to something else,''
Robyn said.
</P>
<P>
   And it was football 24-7-365.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd go out to eat and dad would be drawing plays on
napkins,'' Terry said. ``And us boys, we'd be sitting there doing
the same thing, doodling formations. Everybody in this family can
draw perfect x's and o's and little squares and dotted lines and
arrows.''
</P>
<P>
   Following in father's coaching footsteps wasn't encouraged, but
considering Bobby Bowden's success, it's not surprising. In 34
years as a head coach, Bowden has had two losing seasons _ 4-7 at
West Virginia in 1974 and 5-6 at Florida State in 1976, his first
season with the Seminoles.
</P>
<P>
   In sixth grade, Tommy wrote a term paper in which he said he
wanted to be a football coach when he grew up. In 1998, in his
second season at Tulane, Tommy Bowden's team finished 12-0. In
1993, his first season at Auburn, Terry Bowden's team finished
11-0. That same season, Florida State finished 11-1 and won the
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a very insecure, stressful profession, we grew up with a
father who was very successful in his job,'' said Terry, who
remembers at age 14 making speeches talking about becoming a
football coach. ``That's really all we've been exposed to.''
\Nsubheds:Support group
</P>
<P>
   The bond of family and football led to an unofficial family
reunion last Thanksgiving. The clan gathered at Terry's house in
Auburn, Ala. A month earlier, after his Tigers had started 1-5, he
resigned because he believed he would be fired at season's end.
During the holiday gathering, little was said in actual support of
the overachieving Bowden son, but the family's presence spoke
volumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a difference between a minor setback and a major
tragedy. For Terry, that was a minor setback,'' Ann said. ``That
was a real defeat for him, and he's never really lost at anything
in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the coaching business, the family ties are what gets you
through the hard times. You know they love you and support you
regardless of wins and losses. I feel sorry for coaches that don't
have that kind of support system.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, contracts were signed scheduling Auburn against
Florida State in this season's opener. Terry's resignation canceled
the father-son matchup (and the game was never played; Auburn paid
$500,000 to back out).
</P>
<P>
   But in December, Tommy was hired by Clemson, like Florida State
a member of the Atlantic Coast Conference. Oct. 23 became the
calendar target and a quick check of the math showed that a 7-0
Seminoles start would have Bobby Bowden going for his 300th victory
against his son's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this game has the magnitude of the Florida or Miami
games. There is a special feeling this week,'' Bobby said. ``It's
amazing how this has all come together, how it matches up that I'm
playing Tommy's team with the chance to win 300 games. I never
could have imagined it like this.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
