<SLUG> BC-BORDER-AUSTIN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recruitment remains a problem for Border Patrol
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional budget negotiators want to hire an
additional 1,000 Border Patrol agents next year _ a plan consistent
with a sweeping 1996 immigration law _ but they are fraught with
ongoing recruitment challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, which must win President Clinton's
approval, an additional $48.5 million would pay for 1,000 new
border patrol agents in fiscal year 2000. Agents hired after Jan. 1
would get recruitment bonuses. If the Immigration and
Naturalization Service is unable to hire 1,000 agents by June 1,
some of the money could go to pay raises for career officers.
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol has grown from 5,878 agents in 1996 to 8,351
this year. But a healthy economy and the lure of better-paying law
enforcement jobs has not made it easy for INS officials to comply
with a 1996 law requiring them to hire 1,000 agents a year for five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Six hundred agents must still be found to meet the 1999 quota.
That sends INS critics into orbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fiscal year 1999, they hired 400 new additional agents.
Congress gave them money for 1,000,'' said Allen Kay, spokesman for
Congressman Lamar Smith, a San Antonio Republican and fierce INS
critic. ``If border security was a priority for the Clinton
administration, it would have been done.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison (R-Texas), who helped craft the
agreement, wants the Justice Department to update Congress on the
status of a lawsuit challenging Operation Rio Grande, a deterrence
effort that involves setting up two-dozen large lights along the
Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   INS spokeswoman Nicole Chulick said Thursday that the agency is
still reviewing the agreement. She said 52,825 Border Patrol
applicants passed an initial screening this year, up from 42,000 in
1998. Attrition remains at about 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with a really good economy and multiple job
choices for potential applicants,'' she said. ``The military has
not met their hiring goals, either, so it's been a problem across
the board.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency is now training Border Patrol agents to help search
out new recruits. Chulick said 200 agents completed a two-week
recruitment training course in July.
</P>
<P>
   Other immigration issues, such as raising the cap on H1B visas
for high-tech workers, could remain on the back burner. Smith, who
chairs a House subcommittee on immigration, still wants to adopt
plans to restructure the INS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are at the end of the budget year and things are
busy,'' Kay said. ``But that's still his intent and if there's any
way to do that, he will.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin American-Statesman staff writer Dave Harmon contributed
to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
