<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4455 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-5-QUESTIONS-ART-$     10-21 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-5-QUESTIONS-ART-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE QUESTIONS FOR JUAN SOMAVIA: MAKING MARKETS WORK FOR ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Questions may be italicized)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 24)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For decades, the International Labor Organization has been
derided as an ineffectual, anticapitalistic talking shop, when it
has been noticed at all. But its new director-general, Juan
Somavia, is intent on changing all that.
</P>
<P>
   With 2,300 employees and a $480 million budget, the Geneva-based
organization, an agency of the United Nations, has broad
responsibilities, among them leading the worldwide fight against
abuse of child labor, promoting job creation in poor countries and
defending workers' rights to form unions.
</P>
<P>
   Somavia arrived in March believing that the organization need
not be anti-business to achieve its objectives.
</P>
<P>
   With his thick beard, Somavia, 58, a Chilean diplomat, looks
like an Amish farmer, but he talks like a pragmatic politician and
social theorist. He served as Chile's representative to the United
Nations and was chief organizer of the 1995 World Summit for Social
Development in Copenhagen before taking his new post.
</P>
<P>
   Somavia took time from attending the AFL-CIO convention in Los
Angeles to discuss his plans. Here are excerpts from the
conversation. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why should Americans pay attention to the International Labor
Organization? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The ILO's Philadelphia Declaration from 1944 stated that
poverty anywhere constitutes a danger to prosperity everywhere. You
can't be indifferent to what's happening in the rest of the world.
The global economy is not distributing its benefits sufficiently to
people _ to workers in America or to workers around the world. If I
had to synthesize what the ILO is trying to do, it is, ``How do we
make markets work for everyone?''
</P>
<P>
   What does the ILO do when it finds that markets are not working?
We have to promote entrepreneurship. Unless you generate more work
in the world, we'll continue to have a series of problems. And to
insure decent work, there's no substitute for organize, organize,
organize. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The ILO has long had a reputation as a lethargic bureaucracy.
How will you reinvigorate it? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I want to basically do two things: focus and modernize. And I
plan to concentrate on four areas. First is protecting the rights
of people at work. The second is employment and job creation,
access to work. That's what people in the street want.
</P>
<P>
   The third focus is social protection like Social Security,
pensions, safe work. A central reality of the global economy is
that a majority of people don't have basic social protections of
any kind. The fourth focus is dialogue. The ILO is one of the only
places where you have employers, workers and government engaging in
dialogue, talking things out to find common solutions.
</P>
<P>
   The global economy is bringing ILO issues to center stage, and
consequently I arrive at a moment that we have a very good mandate.
But we have to be much more pointed in how we go about it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Sometimes your goals to create jobs and eliminate poverty
seem to overlap with those at the World Bank and International
Monetary Fund. How do you avoid conflict? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I was very glad to see the IMF and World Bank put the
elimination of poverty on their agenda. Our job is to be a social
pillar, to make sure they're taking care of the social dimension.
Many of the things that were done to make structural adjustment
work meant that an enormous number of companies went broke.
Somebody has to have an eye on what happens to people.
</P>
<P>
   We in the international community have to agree on the issues on
which we should all be pushing in the same direction. I suggest the
reduction of poverty, creating employment (it's the first step out
of poverty) and having more inclusive societies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How do you respond to critics who say your organization's
agenda is anti-business? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Our historical mandate is to look at life at work. Our
mandate is to promote workers' rights, but that's not the only
thing we're about. We're also about tripartism between employers,
workers and government. We're about dialogue, about creating jobs
and entrepreneurialism. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why is the new child labor convention so important? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There is a growing consciousness that we should not have
child labor. Child labor is a complex issue. It's strongly linked
to development and whether parents have a job or whether children
can go to school.
</P>
<P>
   The new Convention on the Worst Forms of Child Labor was
approved in June, and now it has to be ratified by different
countries. It was the first time you had global unanimity on child
labor issues.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of tensions on child labor, and some countries
have not ratified existing child labor conventions, but finally we
have been able to put together complete unanimity on the worst
forms of child labor that should be banned _ prostitution,
pornography, hazardous mining, serving as soldiers. The most
important thing is to ban all of the morally abhorrent situations
that no family would like its children to live through.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 2040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0401 </DOCNO>
