<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4457 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TIMOR-U.N.-NYT &LR;      10-21 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNCIL READY TO APPROVE TRANSFER OF EAST TIMOR TO U.N. 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ An international administration for East Timor,
backed by 10,000 troops, is widely expected to be approved on
Friday by the U.N. Security Council. That would open the way for a
formal transfer of authority in the territory from Indonesia to the
United Nations, officially ending a quarter-century of Indonesian
rule.
</P>
<P>
   A new national assembly in Jakarta decided by consensus on
Wednesday to relinquish Indonesian claims to the territory, which
it seized after colonial Portugal pulled out in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   The only possible delay in the Security Council, diplomats said,
could be from the Chinese, who are objecting to the enabling
resolution's support for an investigation in East Timor by the U.N.
high commissioner for human rights. Diplomats met Thursday night to
discuss how to overcome China's objections before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan is expected to name Sergio Vieira
de Mello as administrator for the territory, at least for an
initial period of up to six months.
</P>
<P>
   Differences of opinion in persist here about the nationality of
the long-term administrator, known as the special representative of
the secretary general, who may be in the territory for two or three
years and will enjoy sweeping powers.
</P>
<P>
   Vieira de Mello, a Brazilian, is an undersecretary-general who
coordinates relief and refugee affairs. He also set up the civilian
administration in Kosovo after the NATO bombing, before Bernard
Kouchner of France was appointed chief administrator there.
</P>
<P>
   With the approval of a peacekeeping force for East Timor and
another for Sierra Leone on the same day, the Security Council will
be putting the United Nations back in the active business of
peacekeeping in a big way _ in effect doubling the numbers of
troops in the field in one day's votes. A sizeable force for the
Congo looms in future planning.
</P>
<P>
   Annan was asked Thursday how the United Nations, short of cash
and other resources, would be able to handle several large new
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously the pendulum has swung, and I think all of us who
have been in this building were aware that when it comes to
peacekeeping and crisis management, you go through peaks and
troughs,'' Annan said. ``Now it is on the upswing. But we are not
looking for business. But once a crisis has broken out and we have
been given the mandate, we have to be given the resources to make
it viable. I encourage all the member states to bear that very much
in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I talk of resources, I talk of resources being given to
us promptly, because it is the early stages which can make or break
a mission,'' the secretary-general said. The United Nations is
still far behind in raising the money needed for the reconstruction
of civilian life and institutions in Kosovo, where tensions between
ethnic Albanians and Serbs still run high.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Miyet, the head of the U.N. peacekeeping department,
said recently that the reconstruction of East Timor, though smaller
and with far fewer people, could be even more difficult and costly
than the operation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   East Timor will literally have to be rebuilt after armed
militias opposed to independence destroyed most of its towns. The
United Nations will have to introduce services from sanitation to
new education and judicial systems, and without a trained corps of
local civil servants to draw on. Other fundamental issues like a
choice of language and legal code will have to be decided.
</P>
<P>
   East Timor's acknowledged political leader, Jose Alexandre
Gusmao _ who is considered likely to be the new country's first
president or prime minister _may return to the territory as early
as this weekend, according to reports from Australia. In an
interview here last month after his release from imprisonment and
later house arrest in Jakarta, Gusmao said that he and his council
expected to be involved in making these critical decisions about
East Timor's future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
