<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4460 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-LEHIGH-JEAN-ART-N     10-21 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LEHIGH-JEAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
9 YEARS AGO, AN ABANDONED BOY; TODAY, A LEHIGH FOOTBALL STAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By JOE DRAPE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, Pa. _ Buried inside the news pages of The Palm Beach
Post from Dec. 18, 1990, are 180 words. They tell of a 13-year-old
boy, Ronald Jean, barely 5 feet and 100 pounds, who was abandoned
by his mother at a Greyhound bus station three months earlier
because he refused to accompany her and his 3-year-old sister on a
trip to New York.
</P>
<P>
   The search remained unsuccessful. Jean was never officially
adopted. Nor has he found his mother, Charlene Bumere, or younger
sister, Tatiana.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly nine years later, the 5-foot-5-inch, 187-pound Jean
has found a home in the mountains of Eastern Pennsylvania at Lehigh
University. He has found a family, too. Actually, two families: one
in Ohio and one in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   And as a senior running back, he has grown into a professional
football prospect _ albeit a long shot _ whose strength and
determination cannot only be measured by dumbbells and stop
watches.
</P>
<P>
   So, what is more impressive about Jean? His 435-pound bench
press? His 40-yard dash time of 4.38 seconds? His 766 rushing yards
and 15 touchdowns for the 6-0 Mountain Hawks? Or that a child whose
mother abused and abandoned him, who was shuttled through foster
homes, will graduate in May from Lehigh with a degree in
psychology?
</P>
<P>
   ``The scouts know who Ronald is; they are impressed,'' said
Chris Demarest, a former Lehigh assistant who is now at Florida
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has had every excuse not to succeed, but he has never given
up,'' Demarest said. ``No matter what happens to him in football,
he already is the biggest success I've ever been around.''
</P>
<P>
   Those 180 words inside that newspaper never mentioned the scars
on Jean's body _ a long knife slash across his stomach among them _
from his mother's abuse. Nor could they foretell the series of
roadblocks on an improbable journey through football to college.
</P>
<P>
   Jean pulls his shirt above his 28-inch waist to reveal the
Zorro-like knife scar that marks his stomach. It is the reason he
made his first tough decision _ the one that still haunts him. He
said his mother beat him with extension cords. He said she drank
and smoked marijuana, perhaps even crack cocaine. But he said
things got worse when they arrived in South Florida from the
Bahamas in the summer of 1990.
</P>
<P>
   They were only there a couple of weeks when the knifing
occurred. So on Sept. 5, 1990, when Charlene Bumere took her
children to the bus station in West Palm Beach, Jean had made up
his mind. She wanted to get on a bus for New York. He did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had pushed me over my limit,'' Jean said matter-of-factly
in a soft lilting voice. ``I told her I wasn't going. She got on
the bus with my sister and left me crying.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper report nine years ago said the young boy appeared
to be from the Islands, perhaps Haiti, but no one in the local
communities knew anything of him. And authorities in New York could
not locate his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Jean was placed in a shelter and then into a foster home in
Pahokee near the Everglades. And then into another foster home.
Just as no one from his past would show up, it took a while for
someone in his future to step forward. He was small, shy and,
during junior high school, combative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fought with other kids in the foster homes,'' he said. ``At
school, kids would tease me that nobody wanted me, and I'd fight
there, too.''
</P>
<P>
   At one of his stays in a foster home, however, he discovered
sports when he befriended an older boy, Nathaniel Mosely, who was a
running back at Pahokee High School. Jean ran with him, lifted
weights and was introduced to football.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something I could do for myself, away from the people
who were smoking and drinking and getting in trouble,'' Jean said.
</P>
<P>
   In junior high, he learned how much he loved the game when he
was ruled ineligible for poor grades. Never again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided then I would do what it takes, study as long as I
needed, to play,'' said Jean, whose Lehigh team hopes to improve on
its unbeaten mark Saturday against Holy Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his freshman year in high school, Jean moved to a
foster home in Boca Raton. There, he got the attention of Jay
Minton, then the Boca Raton High School football coach, and his
wife, Susie. Jean, all 135 pounds of him, approached Minton as a
freshman and said he wanted to play on the varsity team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a little old thing, said Minton, now the coach at Wayne
High School in Huber Heights, Ohio. ``It made me smile. But he did
make the junior varsity that year, and you could tell he knew how
to get what he wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   In Jean, the coach saw a raw talent who had hit the weight room
to become a better football player and the books, too. Minton's
wife, on the other hand, saw a sweet, quiet kid desperate for a
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is really good at smiling you and getting his way,'' Susie
Minton said.
</P>
<P>
   By his senior year, Jean was living with the Mintons and their
two daughters. He gained more than 1,000 yards on an 11-2 team that
sent Khori Ivy to start at wide receiver for West Virginia and
Steve Bellisari to quarterback for Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   Demarest, then a Lehigh assistant, was looking at film of those
big timers when he kept noticing the tiny running back _ then 165
pounds _ skittering all over the field. He asked to meet him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew immediately there was something in his eyes I liked,''
Demarest said.
</P>
<P>
   Lehigh does not offer scholarships, but Jean was seduced by the
one-time steel town carved from the Pennsylvania mountains. Or at
least he thought he was on his visit. But three days after arriving
as a freshman, his bags were packed and he was ready to go home.
But where was that? The Mintons had moved to Ohio. In their place,
Walter and Mercedes Anderson stepped forward.
</P>
<P>
   Jean had befriended their daughter Melissa and son David, and
had become a frequent and welcome guest in their home. He liked the
noise and action at the Andersons; they liked his gentle presence.
</P>
<P>
   When he called to say he wanted to come home, Mercedes Anderson
said she told him the same thing she would tell her own kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called here in tears,'' she recalled. ``He was lonely. I
told him if he left, he'd never step foot in this house again. I
didn't mean it, but I wanted him to understand this wasn't a
challenge but the best opportunity he had ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehigh Coach Kevin Higgins, too, was shaken and moved by his
freshman's fears. He called him to the office and made him a
promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you've had an uphill battle the whole way,'' he told
him. ``But here at Lehigh no one was going to put you on an island,
academically, socially or athletically.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean stayed, sitting out his freshman year to focus on his
studies. He played sparingly as a sophomore behind Rabih Abdullah,
now a running back with the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Jean scored 14 touchdowns after taking the starting
position over in midseason. Returning to Florida for the summer, he
worked out alongside Chris Carter and Randy Moss of the Minnesota
Vikings, and a host of other National Football League players.
</P>
<P>
   Jean is a long shot for the NFL, but no one who knows him doubts
that he will make it.. Mercedes Anderson calls him a gift. Chris
Demarest says he is a survivor who can overcome any odds. And Susie
Minton credits him with teaching her how to forgive.
</P>
<P>
   He calls all of them his family, and phones each of them every
week. If not the NFL, Jean said he will go to graduate school.
</P>
<P>
   But there are a couple things left that Jean wants to do. He
wants to hug the sister he barely remembers. And he wants to find
his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell her I forgive her,'' he said. ``I want her to
know how my life has turned out.''
</P>
<P>
   That story will take much more than 180 words.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
