A4461 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FRAUDRING22-COX     10-21 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAUDRING22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    40 charged in fraud ring run out of recording studio
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They lured rap artist wannabes and strippers with a
posh recording studio, luxury cars and wads of cash. They used
sophisticated computer equipment to make false checks and driver's
licenses. They stole $2.5 million worth of checks that they used to
counterfeit for millions of dollars more.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors Thursday described the check counterfeiting
ring, operated out of a College Park, Ga., recording studio, as one
of the largest in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Forty people have been charged with defrauding banks and other
victims out of an estimated $8 million. Thirty were being sentenced
in federal court this week on convictions of mail fraud,
counterfeiting, bank fraud, theft and conspiracy. Two suspects _
Tony Underwood and Michelle Jackson _ remain at large.
</P>
<P>
   One ringleader, Joseph Jones, a 31-year-old man from Oxford,
received the harshest sentence: five years in federal prison and an
order to pay $522,651 in restitution.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, U.S. District Judge Julie Carnes, who is presiding
over the case, complained about an unsettling development: A
``rash'' of defendants became pregnant after pleading guilty and
are now asking for leniency. But the judge declined to reduce their
prison terms.
</P>
<P>
   According to an indictment, Jones moved to Georgia from Texas in
1995. He started the scheme almost right away; it ended last
February, court documents said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones worked out of Infinity Sound Labs in College Park and,
with others, recruited bank employees to steal personal and
corporate checks that had been mailed to banks, prosecutors said.
More than $2.5 million in checks were taken from Mellon Bank and GE
Capital mail lockboxes in the Atlanta area, according to court
documents.
</P>
<P>
   The stolen checks caused problems for many people, Assistant
U.S. Attorney Gale McKenzie said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This disrupted real people terribly,'' she said. ``Some people
whose checks were stolen had their electricity turned off. Some
businesses had their operations interrupted.''
</P>
<P>
   Using sophisticated computer programs, the ring made counterfeit
checks by using checking account information from stolen checks,
even adding corporate logos. That way, bank tellers could promptly
verify funds in the corporate accounts and cash them for the ring's
check ``passers.''
</P>
<P>
   Strippers at Atlanta area adult entertainment clubs and budding
musicians were recruited to pass the checks. Once they agreed to
join the ring, they were carefully trained.
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, the runners were told: Look in a
bank teller's eyes to detect suspicion. If the check is not cashed
in two minutes, leave the bank. Wear tennis shoes for running away.
Put super glue on fingers and palms to cover fingerprints. Cash
checks when tellers are busy.
</P>
<P>
   The luxury cars used by the ring had been stolen. Using fake
driver's licenses and IDs, members of the ring who were arrested
were able to skip scheduled court appearances after posting bond.
</P>
<P>
   During a sentencing Thursday morning, Carnes noted that great
trust is placed in bank officials. ``It's frightening we've seen so
many bank employees in this case tamper with bank records and
proceeds,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Carnes sentenced one former NationsBank teller, Toi Reid, to 10
months in prison. Over an 11-day period, Reid cashed 91 counterfeit
checks totaling $90,549, according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, noticeably pregnant, was among the women who asked for her
sentence to be reduced. She told the judge that she did not get
pregnant to dodge prison time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a rash of pregnancies, you can forgive me for
wondering,'' Carnes said. ``To decide to have a child to shave a
few months off your sentence is a very self-absorbed and reckless
thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Carnes did not reduce Reid's prison term, she did allow
her to report to prison in March, weeks after the baby is expected
to be delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
