<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0404 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4462 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-ENVIRON-2TAKES(T     10-21 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ENVIRON-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PROPOSES BAN ON NEW OFFSHORE DRILLING
</HEADLINE>
   (See also BRADLEY-POVERTY) 
(sw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RYE, N.H. _ Vice President Al Gore said on Thursday that as
president he would ban any new offshore drilling for oil and gas
along the California and Florida coasts.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton last year extended a moratorium on drilling
first imposed by President George Bush. But the proposal by Gore,
who is battling his presidential rival Bill Bradley for the support
of environmental groups, would go beyond that to apply to companies
that have already bought billions of dollars worth of leases but
not drilled yet.
</P>
<P>
   Such a ban could be implemented by executive order, but it would
immediately set the stage for major legal challenges to a Gore
administration. There are 36 existing leases off California, 146
off Florida and 19 off North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The ban would not cover drilling along the Gulf Coast, where oil
and gas exploration is central to the economy and more accepted by
government officials and residents, or off the Alaskan coast.
</P>
<P>
   Gore cast his controversial proposal, which he expected to be
``attacked'' for, as part of a bold environmental agenda that he
promised would be the centerpiece of his presidential campaign. The
campaign was preparing to broadcast a new 30-second campaign
commercial on the drilling issue on Thursday night in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to worry about oil washing up on the shores of
Santa Barbara or Monterey or on any coast, east or west, or on the
coast of Florida,'' he said to environmentalists here and via
satellite to a group in California.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's promise to elevate the environment to a priority is part
of an urgent attempt by his campaign to capture the support of the
nation's major environmental groups, which so far have not endorsed
anyone _ a blow to the vice president since he is a long-time
environmentalist and is perceived as a natural ally of the
environmental movement.
</P>
<P>
   By playing hard to get, the groups have forced Gore to make
promises that go beyond his administration's own policies. It is a
tactic that organized labor also used before the AFL-CIO endorsed
him at its annual meeting earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental community has been reluctant to jump on the
Gore train in part because of what it sees as the Clinton
administration's mixed record, complaining that over the years, the
White House has not done enough to fight global warming or restrict
logging on public lands.
</P>
<P>
   Some environmentalists also consider Bill Bradley, Gore's sole
rival for the Democratic presidential nomination, a staunch ally
who in fact achieved higher ratings in the Senate for his work on
environmental issues than Gore did. And there is concern in the
environmental community, as there is more broadly among Democrats,
that Gore cannot win a general election against Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas, the Republican front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club and the League of Conservation Voters, the
nation's top two mainstream politically active environmental
groups, have failed to rally on the vice president's behalf. The
groups' top officials, some of whom privately back Gore, say that
they never have endorsed candidates during the Democratic primary
process.
</P>
<P>
   A third national environmental group that gets involved in
politics, Friends of the Earth, has endorsed Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Deb Callahan, president of the League of Conservation Voters,
said, ``We're seeing the major party candidates fighting to capture
our hearts. What more do you want? The environmental community is
not a bloc, and most are standing in the middle waiting to be
wooed.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Pope, executive director of the Sierra Club, said that
neither Gore nor Mr. Bradley has articulated a comprehensive vision
for the future. ``The differences in their records doesn't warrant
our making a choice between them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that the environment is a central issue with many
voters, especially swing voters in the suburbs and women.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has a lifetime rating from the League of Conservation
Voters of 84 percent, a reflection mainly of his work on
environmental problems in New Jersey, which he represented in the
Senate for 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   Gore had a rating of 64 percent, which reflects several absences
from votes during his career, the large number of toxic Superfund
sites in Tennessee that have not been cleaned up as well as Gore's
father's position on the boards of coal companies that were
involved in strip-mining.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM STARTS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Even Gore acknowledged on Thursday that Bradley had a strong
record. ``I haven't challenged his commitment to the environment,''
Gore said. ``I think he has a pretty good voting record on the
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that the difference was that he was a leader on
various environmental issues, citing his role in passing the law to
clean up Superfund sites and his concern about global warming.
</P>
<P>
   But officials from the environmental groups are more skeptical
about his leadership than Gore suggests. ``Many environmentalists
feel Clinton-Gore have been lax in leading on global-climate
issues,'' Ms. Callahan told an audience in New York Tuesday night
that included Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Pope said that Bradley's problem was that he had not made clear
how central the environment is to his candidacy. He said Gore's
problem was that ``because he has said so much on the environment
in the past, it will be hard for him to say something bold and
new.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's other big problem, Pope said, is that ``Bill Clinton has
diminished Gore's environmental reputation over the last seven
years,'' and he needs to re-establish his environmental
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Gore was more assertive than he has been so far in
his campaign about staking his candidacy on environmental issues,
and noted that he was going farther _ ``significantly farther'' _
than the Clinton administration in banning the use of future
drilling leases.
</P>
<P>
   His statement brought swift reaction from the oil and gas
industries, which promised to keep pushing to drill in new areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a long way between now and Al Gore's inauguration,''
said Robert Stewart, president of the National Ocean Industries
Association, a trade group for offshore contractors.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM STARTS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the industry is already embroiled in a dispute over an
existing lease off of Florida owned by Chevron, which has asked
Commerce Secretary William Daley to overturn Florida's objection to
the company's drilling plan. Daley's decision could come early next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Gore mentioned the Florida conflict but did not give his view on
what Daley should do. A spokeswoman said the vice president thought
it would be ``inappropriate to interfere in the existing process.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla, said the vice president's position
``sends a loud message to the Commerce Department: reject Chevron's
off-shore drilling application.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Precedent exists for buying back leases given a change in oil
drilling policy. The Clinton administration in 1995 agreed to pay
$200 million to reacquire 73 leases off southwest Florida after
they were deemed to present an environmental risk to the state.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposal could have the broadest impact on drilling near
California, where various companies have obtained 40 leases off the
central coast, many off southern San Luis Opispo County.
</P>
<P>
   There are indications of vast deposits of oil under the sea bed,
perhaps up to 1 billion barrels. The rights, valued at about $1.2
billion, were obtained from 1968 to 1984. They have remained
undeveloped so far.
</P>
<P>
   In defense of his proposed ban on such leases, Gore said that
the benefits to all citizens of fishing, tourism and appreciation
of beautiful vistas ``far outweigh'' any monetary benefits to the
oil industry from ``the tiny little bit of extra oil'' that would
come from drilling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
