<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATS SEEK GAINS ON THE GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Bobby Grier said this week he thought he had
running backs who can do the job, which is why he didn't bid on
Karim Abdul-Jabbar, Napoleon Kaufman, or Barry Sanders before
Tuesday's trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' vice president of player personnel also had two
chances to obtain Jamal Anderson, the Atlanta Falcons star who is
on injured reserve with a torn anterior cruciate ligament. But he
thought adding Anderson would affect the Patriots' salary cap, and
he also thought rookie Kevin Faulk and the acquisition of free
agent Terry Allen would be sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Through six games, the Patriots have averaged 2.9 yards per
carry. Their longest run of the season is 22 yards. When Curtis
Martin was in New England, he presented the threat of a 50-yard
gain. So far, there's no sign of that happening.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the line, if you must, but three players _ Bruce
Armstrong, Max Lane, and Todd Rucci _ were good enough to play on
the Patriots' Super Bowl team that ran the ball effectively enough
to augment Drew Bledsoe's passing. The differences in the Patriots'
line include Zefross Moss, who spent most of his career blocking
for Barry Sanders, and rookie Damien Woody, who opened some
significant holes for Mike Cloud at Boston College. The Patriots
also use Heath Irwin, a mobile lineman who is supposed to be able
to run block.
</P>
<P>
   But at some juncture, the focus has to be on the runners.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have to hope Faulk emerges as the lead runner. But
with kickoff and punt return responsibilities, it's also asking a
lot to cast Faulk in that role.
</P>
<P>
   Faulk has been hampered by an ankle injury that kept him out of
the lineup for two weeks and ineffective in other games. The
Patriots knew they had a good returner when they drafted the former
Louisiana State star in the second round, but they were hoping he
could provide more than that. In the 1 1/2 games, Faulk was
healthy, he was tentative _ not hitting the hole with the authority
he had in training camp and the exhibition season.
</P>
<P>
   Faulk has gained only 31 yards on 20 carries (a 1.6 average).
His mentor, Terry Allen, has carried 92 times for 318 yards (a 3.5
yard average), and has fumbled twice. Third-down back Lamont Warren
has gained 58 yards on 17 carries (a 3.4 average).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're waiting around for (Faulk) to be at full speed,'' said
coach Pete Carroll. ``He had no setbacks this week. This is the
best he's felt in a long time. The little guys take longer to get
better. In our minds we want to use him more and more. We'd like to
mix it. Until we have both (Faulk and Allen) going at full go, it's
difficult to do what you've set out to do. I thought this would
happen 3-4 weeks into it, but we've had some problems and that
hasn't happened yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say all you want that you want to run the ball, but
talking about it doesn't get it done,'' said left tackle Armstrong,
whom the Patriots have run behind the majority of the time. ``We've
been talking about this for years, but you have to have the
attitude that you're going to do it and be successful with it. You
have to stick with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, however, don't stick with it. There's a school of
thought that you don't want Allen running the ball too much at this
stage of his career. But many running backs, such as Martin, get
better as they get into the flow of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But at which point is it the line's fault, and at which point do
the backs need to do a better job?
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots run some tosses with Allen, a play in which he has
to make a key move to spring loose. That hasn't happened too often.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have tried different running plays out of different
formations, but it seems they are always slow developing. They've
actually run their best out of the shotgun formation, where they've
gained 34 yards on six carries.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the line-running back relationship. The line has to
learn the back's tendencies and where he likes to run. That's why
some teams go with one back so the line knows exactly where the
back is going to make his cuts. The Patriots have a running
back-by-committee philosophy, which makes it that much more
difficult for the line to learn tendencies. The other issue is the
line rotation. The Patriots insert Max Lane in many spots. That may
be fine for giving players a rest, but that, too, seems to be
breaking the continuity.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is the Patriots can't seem to keep Chris Floyd
on the field. Cut from the same mold as former Patriots stalwart
Sam Gash, the 237-pound fullback could help fill the void created
by the loss of Gash after the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos lost Terrell Davis, arguably the best back in the
league, for the season and his backup, rookie Olandis Gary, carried
37 times for 124 yards against Green Bay last Sunday. No Patriot
has come close to a 100-yard game this season.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said the past two weeks the Patriots have been
``big-play'' oriented, thinking they could beat the opposition with
long passes. ``But when you don't hit those, you waste some
opportunities to run the ball. I'm not saying we'd be successful
running it, but when you have more balance and you're actually
running it, it puts you in a better rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason for us to give up on the run. I don't think
it's our production, it's our mix.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
