u a BC-COLO-COLUMBINE-THREAT     10-21 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-COLUMBINE-THREAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMBINE STUDENT IS ARRESTED AFTER THREATENING TO `FINISH THE
JOB' 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ A Columbine High School senior is to face
charges on Friday after threatening, the authorities say, to
``finish the job'' of the two classmates who in April shot to death
12 students and a teacher before killing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-year-old student, whose age has led the police to
withhold his identity, was arrested on Tuesday, one day shy of six
months since the carnage here. The authorities said he could be
charged with inciting destruction of life or property, a felony.
</P>
<P>
   The youth was transferred to a juvenile detention center on
Wednesday after a brief court appearance where bond was set at
$500,000. ``We asked for a large amount, for the safety of the
community,'' said Mark Pautler, chief deputy district attorney of
Jefferson County.
</P>
<P>
   That a student might try to mimic the acts of Eric Harris and
Dylan Klebold, the teen-agers responsible for the April shootings,
has been a widely shared fear at Columbine through the early part
of the school year. Many students acknowledged in recent days that
they were worried that something might happen on Wednesday, exactly
six months after the shootings, despite earlier efforts to upgrade
security at the school.
</P>
<P>
   Those fears prompted administrators to bolster Columbine's
security force on Tuesday, when they added two armed officers to
the one sheriff's deputy who typically patrols the school grounds
along with three unarmed guards.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators said Thursday that as much as half the student
body stayed home from school on Wednesday, or left early, after
learning of the arrest the day before. Attendance, normally 95
percent, was 86 percent on Thursday, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who skipped classes on Wednesday was Vernon Ragnone,
a 16-year-old sophomore. Speaking of the tension he had experienced
as the date precisely six months after the shootings approached, he
said: ``I didn't know what was going to happen, and I was kind of
freaked out. It's kind of scary to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Columbine students said they knew the youth arrested. Some
said he had taken a film class with Harris and Klebold in which the
three collaborated on videos, showing themselves dressed in long
black trench coats and pretending to shoot up the school. According
to published reports after the actual shootings, a student who had
worked with Harris and Klebold turned over such videos to the
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, the Sheriff's Department said an
investigation that led to the arrest on Tuesday ``was initiated
after a student reported that the youth had remarked that he would
`finish the job started by Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold' last
April 20.''
</P>
<P>
   John Dunaway, Jefferson County undersheriff, said of the youth
in custody, ``He may have had the intention, but it's not clear it
would have been possible to do what he desired to do.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials said they acted quickly on Tuesday to notify
parents and students of a threat once they learned from students
about rumors as to what the boy had said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows the system is working,'' said Marilyn Saltzman,
spokeswoman for the Jefferson County schools. ``We acted upon the
information promptly; students communicated with adults about the
information.''
</P>
<P>
   But some parents said they had not been notified, and criticized
Columbine administrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like they're hiding it, like it's a secret,'' said Connie
Michalik, the mother of a student who was injured in the April
shootings. ``They're trying to tell the world that they're taking
back the school and that it's back to normal. It's not. The kids
are still traumatized. They hear a loud noise, and everyone
jumps.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
