<HEADLINE>
INVESTING DIGEST, WITH FUNDS WATCH AND MARKETS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where Online Traders Find Satisfaction &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who's happiest with their e-broker? Online brokerage customers
of Fidelity Investments, according to a new survey by Spectrem
Group and NFO Interactive, two market research firms.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted in June, polled 857 online investors. It
first asked investors what they considered the most important
attributes of their e-brokers' Web sites. If the answer was, say,
speed of execution, the survey then asked them how satisfied they
were on that count.
</P>
<P>
   In the No.2 spot was TD Waterhouse, followed by Charles Schwab
and DLJ Direct, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   What were investors' top priorities? The respondents were most
concerned that e-brokers keep their personal and portfolio data
secure, offer uninterrupted access, have credibility, offer value
and execute orders speedily. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Richard Teitelbaum &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's Big Three Look Bullish on Technology &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These is some good news for whipsawed technology investors. The
three biggest mutual funds managed by Fidelity Investments still
appear to be bullish on the sector.
</P>
<P>
   According to the latest Fidelity Mutual Fund Guide, which
includes portfolio information as of Sept. 30, technology remained
the largest industry holding for each of the gargantuan offerings _
and all three had slightly increased their exposure to the sector
since August.
</P>
<P>
   The Magellan fund, with $92.19 billion in assets as of Sept. 30,
raised its technology holdings to 22 percent of its portfolio from
21.3 percent a month earlier. Its top 10 stocks include the
technology staples Microsoft, Cisco Systems, and Lucent
Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   The $45.99 billion Growth and Income fund increased its
technology exposure to 17.9 percent from 17.7 percent, with
Microsoft as its sole technology holding among its 10 top stocks.
</P>
<P>
   And the $41.04 billion Contrafund bumped up its technology
holdings to 21 percent of assets from 20.4 percent. The top
technology stocks in its top 10 holdings were Microsoft, Cisco and
Unisys. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Richard Teitelbaum
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
