<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, OCTOBER 22
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-BERGER-PROFILE-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Aug. 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Aug. 24,
about Samuel R. Berger, President Clinton's national security
adviser, referred incompletely to the context of a comment he made
in 1991 that ``grand strategies'' were mostly rationales developed
after the fact to explain successful ad hoc decisions. Mr. Berger
made that remark at a panel discussion in which he talked about the
10 years in which he was developing an international law practice
for his firm, Hogan &AMP; Hartson. After the article appeared, his
office said his comment applied only to the specific work of
putting together a law practice and not to his vision of American
foreign policy in his current job.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCOTUS-RDP-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Oct. 12)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Oct. 12,
about an agreement to hear Kenneth W. Starr's appeal of a case
growing out of his prosecution of Webster L. Hubbell referred
incorrectly to Mr. Starr's defense of an indictment of Mr. Hubbell
on tax charges. Mr. Starr argued that a grant of immunity applied
only to the act of producing documents and did not provide immunity
to the contents of the documents.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NOBEL-ECON-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Oct. 13)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Oct.
13, about the awarding of the Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic
Science to Robert A. Mundell misstated the amount. This year's
award is valued at $976,000, not $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-LEOPOLD-CONSERVATION-NYT (moved on Monday, Oct. 18)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Oct. 18,
about the legacy of the ecologist Aldo Leopold misstated the
location of the Gila National Forest, a protected wilderness area
he helped to establish. It is in New Mexico, not Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SINGLES-HOUSING-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Oct. 20)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Oct.
20, about the increasing number of single women who own and
maintain their homes misidentified the headquarters city of Owens
Corning, a manufacturer of building materials. It is Toledo, Ohio,
not Chicago.
</P>
</TEXT>
