<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-JORDAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLD BY CARDINALS IN 1996 HAUNTS JORDAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The slugger conducted interviews adjacent to the
batting cage, flashing a wide smile, doing his best to describe his
team's drive to the World Series without becoming hyperbolic. The
``eye of the tiger'' reference showed Atlanta Braves right fielder
Brian Jordan needed more help with his verbiage than his swing.
</P>
<P>
   In was the hours before Game 3 of the National League
Championship Series, and when he wasn't obliging numerous media
requests, Jordan engaged in banter with teammates. It was as if he
deemed it his job to say all the right things while keeping the
Braves loose and upbeat. Atlanta led the New York Mets, two games
to none, and Jordan wanted his teammates to be able to focus only
on the task at hand.
</P>
<P>
   He was in position to silence a memory that haunted him for
three years, a painful reminder of what happens to a team that
fails to finish a seven-game series when the opportunity presents
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have memories every day about 1996 with the St. Louis
Cardinals,'' said Jordan, the former Cardinal who watched the
Braves rally from a 3-1 deficit to capture the 1996 NLCS by
outscoring the Cardinals, 32-1, the final three games.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Atlanta went on to win Game 4 to take a 3-0 lead, and
surely Jordan must have been having flashbacks when New York won
the next two game close the gap to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves finished New York with an extra-inning triumph in
Game 6, and now Jordan has another shot when the Braves meet the
New York Yankees in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan did his part in helping the Braves to the NL pennant he
feels eluded him in '96. Jordan established a career high with 115
RBIs and matched his best output with 100 runs (he also scored 100
last season). At the All-Star break, he was hitting .295 with 17
home runs, 71 RBIs, and a .507 slugging percentage.
</P>
<P>
   He slowed down in the second half after being hit on the right
hand by a pitch from Montreal's Mike Thurman June 22. He dropped
off to a .266 average with 6 home runs, 44 RBIs, and a .405
slugging percentage after the break, but he had seven RBIs the last
week of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan performed well in the clutch, hitting a team-high .317
with runners in scoring position. He batted .299 with runners in
scoring position with two outs.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's Division Series against Houston, Jordan hit .471
with a home run and 7 RBIs. He drove in all five runs in a 5-3,
12-inning win in Game 3. In the NLCS, Jordan hit .200 (5 for 25)
with 2 home runs and 5 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   But he considers none of that now, focusing solely on helping
the Braves avenge their 1996 Series defeat to the Yankees. ``I
don't even think about (accomplishments) until after the season,
because my job has yet to be finished,'' said Jordan. ``Your goal
is to win the world championship. I will have a chance to reminisce
once it's all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was the catalyst in the Cardinals' run in the 1996 NLCS:
In Game 2, he went 2 for 4 in St. Louis's 8-3 win. In Game 4, the
Braves led, 3-0, behind Denny Neagle with two outs in the seventh,
but the Cardinals rallied to tie the score. Jordan provided the
winning run with a home run in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said at the time, he implored his teammates to capture
Game 5 and the Series while it was still in St. Louis. ``Before
(Game 5), I said we have to win now, because if we go back to
Atlanta, the experience of their pitching staff is going to take
over, and they definitely did,'' said Jordan. ``So, I don't want to
take anything for granted. I want to kick you while you're down. I
don't even want it to be close.''
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, those same '96 Braves had a two-game lead on the
Yankees in the Series, only to lose the next four.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why you have to have that attitude. I was so close once
before,'' said Jordan, who went 2 for 9 with no runs scored and no
RBIs over the last three games of the 1996 NLCS. The Braves won
Game 5, 14-0, and never looked back. ``We lost when we basically
had them, and that was the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   After battling several injuries earlier in his career, Jordan,
who was named an All-Star for the first time this season, said it
doesn't bother him that he doesn't garner as much attention as
other players with similar statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've proven myself many times,'' he said. ``You're not going
to get all the credit you deserve; that's no problem. The bottom
line is I want to win. That's when I can look back and say, `Man,
hey, I won the world championship. I have a ring. I put up some
great numbers in the playoffs.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
