<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4479 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-MORGAN-WEB-ART-865(2T     10-21 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-WEB-ART-865(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET FIRM FIGHTS SCHOOLBOY OVER WEB ADDRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT30 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN and MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Executives of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. have
been boasting this week about their new online stock trading
service and the head start they got on their competitors on Wall
Street. But when it came to the Internet address they desired,
somebody got a jump on them.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on who is telling the story, that somebody is either a
17-year-old schoolboy who created a Web site to share his passion
for mountain-bike racing, or an opportunistic ``cybersquatter'' who
registered dozens of Internet addresses in a scheme to exact
ransoms from big-name corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Typing in the domain name, or Web address, that Morgan Stanley
coveted takes a Web surfer not to its electronic brokerage but
instead to what appears to be a site dedicated to mountain biking.
It carries a photo of a helmeted cyclist under the title Mud
Sweat's Downhill World.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Wong, a senior at a private high school in Los Altos,
Calif., says he created the site and named it after Mud Sweat &AMP;
Gears, the shop that sold him his mountain bikes. ``Me and my
friends saw other sites on the Net,'' he said, sitting with his
parents in the dining room of their spacious home in the
Hillsborough hills overlooking Silicon Valley. ``We wanted to start
our own, with a bunch of pictures and videos and stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley filed suit in U.S. District Court in Manhattan,
alleging that Ivan's Web site infringes on the firm's trademarks.
Morgan Stanley is asking a judge to stop Ivan from using the domain
name.
</P>
<P>
   From a distance, it seems a touching anecdote about a boy who
stumbled into the path of a profit-seeking juggernaut. But turn the
page and the story veers away from David and Goliath into a tale
more characteristic of this get-rich-with-a-click era.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that a company set up by Ivan's father, Sau Wong,
has registered dozens of domain names, many of them derived from
the names of investment banks. Among them are
goldmansachsdirect.com and jpmorganonline.com. In Morgan Stanley's
view, the case is a blatant example of cybersquatting, the practice
of registering Internet addresses in hopes of reselling them to
companies or organizations that have a commercial use for them.
Some companies have paid hundreds of thousands of dollars, but
others, like Morgan Stanley, have gone to court to obtain addresses
that they claim are rightfully theirs.
</P>
<P>
   In a motion filed this week in its lawsuit, Morgan Stanley
alleged that ``the defendant in this case has targeted MSDW and the
New York investment banking community with particular precision and
malice.''
</P>
<P>
   But instead of walking away, as many cybersquatters do when they
are sued by large corporations, Ivan is holding his ground. ``We've
hired three teams of attorneys to fight this,'' said his father.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Wong said it was coincidental that the site had a name so
similar to Morgan Stanley's main Web site, www.msdw.com. ``It was
pretty ironic how they would have the same name as us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sau Wong's company, Smart Ideas, registered www.msdwonline.com
in May, several weeks before Morgan Stanley officials settled on a
new name for their online brokerage. In late July, a marketing
executive discovered that the obvious domain name for the new unit
was already taken. So the big securities firm had to introduce its
overhauled electronic brokerage, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter Online,
Thursday with a not-so-intuitive address on the World Wide Web,
www.online.msdw.com.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the firm, one of the biggest on Wall Street,
located the apparent owners and began negotiating with online
correspondents they believed to be Ivan and his 18-year-old
brother, Ben. They offered to pay what a company representative
called a ``reasonable fee'' for the domain name.
</P>
<P>
   The response that came by an electronic message: ``Give us an
offer we cannot refuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley quickly bid $10,000, a sum that Alejandro Levins,
who was representing Morgan Stanley, described to one of the boys
as ``a nice bag of money for a guy your age,'' according to
documents Morgan Stanley filed in court.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the tone of the online negotiations hardened,
according to the court documents. The sellers demanded $75,000 for
the domain name and when Levins balked, he received a message that
said, ``By the way, you are not dealing with a kid. I am the father
of Ben and Ivan...I am an entrepreneur myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Another dispatch to a Morgan Stanley executive, apparently from
Sau Wong, opened with this note, ``As you may not be aware, some
`useful' domain names can fetch as much as six (6) figures or
more.'' It went on to describe Smart Ideas as ``an innovative and
forward-looking company'' that had ``registered many relevant
domain names covering some of the major competitors of your parent
company. Our rationale is that all brokerage houses, which do not
have online trading today, will eventually provide that service.''
</P>
<P>
   Wong then lowered his asking price to $50,000 and later offered
to throw in another domain name his company had registered,
morganstanleydirect.com.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated, Morgan Stanley officials rescinded their offer of
$10,000 and filed suit on Aug. 13.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In court documents, executives allege that the mountain-biking
theme that now appears on the Web site did not appear there until
10 days after the suit was filed, ``in a transparent attempt to
conceal its fraudulent ransom scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   They now think they were dealing all along with Sau Wong, who
says he is a computer-chip engineer who has worked in Silicon
Valley for 25 years. But Wong and Ivan tried to dispel that notion
in an interview, saying the idea of registering domain names had
been Ivan's from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan said he had read an article that said the people who
register domain names can sometimes profit from them. ``In school,
we learned about freedom of speech,'' he said, adding that one of
his teachers had told him that ``if you got a (Web site) first, you
can sell it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how a 17-year-old came up with the names of so many
investment banks, such as Goldman Sachs, Ivan said his father gave
him the ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a Goldman Sachs account,'' Wong said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ivan and his father insisted that they didn't solicit
buyers for any of the domain names.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not beggars,'' Wong said. ``We do not need to beg.''
</P>
<P>
   Cybersquatting has created a storm of legal controversy.
Trademark holders are getting more support from the courts and from
Internet Corp. for Assigned Names and Numbers, a nonprofit
corporation that oversees the registration of domain names, legal
experts said. So many disputes over the rights to domain names have
landed in court that ICANN is trying to set up a mandatory
arbitration system to settle them.
</P>
<P>
   In one recent case, a 16-year-old Canadian boy incurred the
wrath of Apple Computer Inc. when he registered the domain name
www.appleimac.com after Apple introduced its iMac personal
computer. He said he would use it to draw traffic to his Web-based
business but would consider selling it. But after hearing from
Apple's lawyers, he renounced ownership of the name.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some judges don't see speculating in domain names as so
harmful, said Pam Samuelson, a professor of law at the University
of California at Berkeley. ``One could say that cybersquatting is
just another example of American ingenuity,'' she said. ``These
people are going out and creating things that somebody else might
find of value. In a sense, they're entrepreneurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Samuelson said that ``This doesn't seem to be an
open-and-shut case'' of trademark infringement. The trademark in
question, MSDW, is relatively new _Morgan Stanley merged with Dean
Witter in 1997 _ and not that famous, she said. A federal statute
enacted in 1995 was expressly aimed at stopping cybersquatters from
diluting the value of established trademarks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEAMSTERS-TRIAL-700&AMP;A     10-21 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-TRIAL-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAUD TRIAL BEGINS FOR FORMER TEAMSTER OFFICIAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN GREENHOUSE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal prosecutors detailed their case Thursday
against the Teamsters' former political director, William Hamilton,
accusing him of conspiring with Democratic Party officials, the
AFL-CIO's secretary-treasurer and others to siphon union money to
the 1996 re-election drive of Ron Carey, the Teamsters' former
president.
</P>
<P>
   In opening arguments at Hamilton's trial on charges of
embezzling union money, conspiracy, fraud and perjury, Robert Rice,
an assistant U.S. attorney in Manhattan, said Hamilton had worked
with two top Carey campaign officials to divert $885,000 in union
money to Carey's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Rice asserted that Hamilton had taken part in several complex
schemes in which Teamster money was donated to liberal political
groups, and in exchange long-time donors to those groups
contributed to the Carey campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Insisting that Hamilton and the Carey campaign aides had looted
the union's treasury, Rice said, ``The scheme can best be described
as a swap scheme, a quid pro quo, a you'll-scratch my back and I'll
scratch yours.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hamilton's lawyer, Robert Gage, responded that his client
was innocent of the charges, which were filed in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Gage asserted that Hamilton was the victim of swap schemes that
he said were orchestrated by Carey's direct mail consultant, Martin
Davis, to insure that the Carey campaign had money to pay the
$700,000 it owed Davis' firm for campaign mailings. Davis and Jere
Nash, Carey's campaign manager, have pleaded guilty to carrying out
the swap schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Gage described his client as an idealist who approved big
Teamsters donations to liberal groups, not to advance Carey's
campaign, but to help restore Democratic control of Congress and
elect a Congress that would be friendlier to unions.
</P>
<P>
   Rice said Hamilton, as well as Davis and Nash, carried out the
swap schemes, in which $735,000 was donated to three liberal groups
_ Citizen Action, the National Council of Senior Citizens and
Project Vote, which focuses on getting low-income and minority
people to vote. As part of those schemes, wealthy contributors to
those groups donated $185,000 to the Carey campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Carey narrowly defeated James P. Hoffa in the 1996 race for the
Teamsters presidency, but federal monitors ordered a new election
and ousted Carey from the office after determining that he breached
his fiduciary duty by not stopping his campaign aides from carrying
out the swap schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Rice described another scheme in which he said Hamilton approved
a $150,000 Teamster payment to the AFL-CIO. Days after, the labor
federation contributed $150,000 to Citizen Action, which in turn
paid $100,000 to Davis' direct-mail firm. The prosecutor said
Richard Trumka, the AFL-CIO's secretary-treasurer, had requested
the $150,000 payment.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two years, Trumka has insisted on his innocence
and has invoked the Fifth Amendment in declining to testify on the
matter. No charges have been brought against him.
</P>
<P>
   Rice also said Davis had approached Terry McAuliffe, the finance
chairman of the Clinton-Gore campaign, to propose that the
Teamsters would contribute large sums to the Democrats if DNC
officials got Democratic donors to give to Carey. Rice said
McAuliffe had Davis talk to two other Democratic finance officials,
Laura Hartigan and Richard Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Rice said that Sullivan sent Hamilton a list of suggested
contributions to state Democratic parties and that soon after, the
Teamsters donated $236,000 to various state parties. In the past,
federal investigators have said that the Democrats were
unsuccessful in finding donors for the Carey campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe, Ms. Hartigan and Sullivan have all repeatedly denied
any wrongdoing. No charges have been brought against any DNC
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton was planning on making the donations to the Democratic
state parties, Gage said, even before Sullivan made his request.
Gage argued that Davis and Nash knew of Hamilton's intention to
make large donations to the Democrats and that Davis parlayed this
knowledge to try to manipulate DNC officials so they would arrange
for Democratic donors to give to Carey.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many of the details laid out by prosecutors Thursday have been
made public, but the airing of those details in court is bound to
once again throw Democratic and AFL-CIO officials on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Collins, a spokesman for the Republican National
Committee, did not hide the Republicans intent to gain political
mileage from the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for the country to understand how a
million dollars in workers' money was diverted to the benefit of
the Clinton-Gore '96 campaign and the Democratic National
Committee,'` he said. ``What's going to be obvious is there are a
lot of people who should be sitting in the dock with Hamilton.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Backus, the DNC's press secretary, said, ``This matter
has been investigated by three Congressional committees as well as
the Justice Department, and these investigations turned up no
indication that any DNC employee or official acted in any improper
or unlawful way.''
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Rice called the defendant a ``Teamster
insider.'' But Gage countered by telling the jury that Hamilton,
57, had spent many years working for civil rights and abortion
rights and had more recently dedicated himself to fighting ``the
Gingrich Congress'' and rebuffing Republican efforts to undercut
workers' rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0416 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4486 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-BENSON22-COX     10-21 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BENSON22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Benson aiming to stay on track
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Winston Cup driver Johnny Benson is known for his
cool, calm and collected ways on the race track. His style remains
unchanged as he faces a near-crisis situation off the track.
</P>
<P>
   Benson and Ted Musgrave are the circuit's only full-time drivers
without a ride for next season. Opportunities seem to decrease by
the day, but Benson expresses only minimal concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like there are still opportunities out there,'' Benson
said. ``I'm not panicking, because I don't feel like I am in a
panic situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Albright has known Benson since they worked together on the
ARCA circuit in 1990. Albright, hired as Benson's manager four
years ago, said his client's laid-back demeanor is nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny's temperament is even in every situation,'' Albright
said. ``If there were any other way he was reacting to what is
obviously a highly stressful situation, then it wouldn't be the
Johnny Benson I know.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is it's probably tougher on him in the inside than he
ever shows on the outside. But he still has a knack for handling
difficult situations calmly. I mean, he's not concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both have faith that the Lord has got the best thing for us
out there, and we are just waiting to see what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson decided to part ways with the No. 26 Fords of Roush
Racing after the season's final four races, which includes Sunday's
Pop Secret 400 at Rockingham, N.C. He already has turned down at
least two rides for next year and politely declined to join A.J.
Foyt's new team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a couple of things I'm looking at,'' Benson said,
without revealing details. ``I know it's getting late in the year,
but, hopefully, I'll find something shortly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are continuing to pursue opportunities known to the public,
then there are others that the general public is not even aware
that exist, at this point,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   It is no secret that Benson was dissatisfied with his track
record at Roush during the past two seasons, and he went to great
lengths to dissolve the relationship. Benson had to buy out the
final two years of his contract. Because of a lucrative sponsorship
with General Mills, Benson walked away from a seven-figure income.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone can say a paycheck is not important, but
I think he is a racer, deep down,'' said Benson's father, John.
``He wants to race and do well. He is just not content with the
ways things are now.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson, 36, had a rapid rise through the racing ranks and was
considered the hottest prospect two years ago. He joined Roush
after two prosperous seasons at Ba'hari Racing, including an
11th-place finish in the 1997 points standings.
</P>
<P>
   Since arriving at Roush, Benson has regressed. He was 20th in
the points last season, 26th in the current standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to be racing better,'' Benson said. ``And for some
reason, it is not happening. Somebody had to do something. Nobody
wants to run 20th. I don't want to, and (Roush) doesn't want to.
So, a change needed to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   Roush, one of the top multicar teams in the sport, fields the
teams of Mark Martin and Jeff Burton. Unlike Martin and Burton,
Benson's shop is located in Liberty, N.C., nearly 100 miles from
Charlotte, which makes it more difficult to hire top personnel.
Owner Jack Roush promised to move Benson to the Charlotte area by
the beginning of this season, but it didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say `politically correct,' but Johnny has
handled this situation in the most positive way he could,'' said
Benson's sister, Barb, president of the driver's fan club.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just got to the point where he said, `Enough was enough,
and another year in this situation was not good for me, the team or
the sponsors,''' she said. ``I think he felt he did the best with
what he could do and with the decisions he could make, which
weren't many. He felt it was time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson declines to criticize Roush. He wants to keep a low
profile and quietly finish the season, then try to rejuvenate his
once-flourishing career with another team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny is not throwing rocks at Roush Racing or anybody on
that team,'' Albright said. ``As anyone in racing knows, it takes
30-35 people to have a successful race team. Sometimes it clicks,
sometimes it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
