<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brunette beats rap as poor skater
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The tag, Andrew Brunette suspects, has been with
him since he was filling up nets as a 12-year-old in northern
Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   ``A coach told me one day, `As you go on, don't let your skating
ever stop you from being successful,' '' the Thrashers forward
said. ``He was saying, `Don't get down about this.' Until then, I
didn't even know anything was wrong. Ever since then, it stuck with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Good hands, bad skates. It's the scouting report Brunette has
lived with throughout his career. Fortunately, he hasn't had to
hear too much about his skating recently.
</P>
<P>
   Brunette, the first forward under contract to the Thrashers,
also is first in scoring, with four goals _ three on the power play
_ and six points in six games. He has been one of the team's few
players who has worked himself into scoring position and has taken
advantage of it with a scoring touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see what kind of player he is below the tops of the
(face-off) circle,'' coach Curt Fraser said. ``For him to be
successful, we have to get him the puck down low. He's got fast
hands. In training camp for the first few games, we really couldn't
see where he could help us, because most of the play was in the
neutral zone. But now he's getting down low, and that makes all the
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Brunette, who usually skates on a line with center Ray Ferraro
and right winger Steve Staios, hopes he can be more consistent than
he was last year in Nashville, Tenn. He scored five goals in his
first 10 games with the Predators but went another 17 games before
scoring his sixth, and finished with only 11.
</P>
<P>
   His two primary aims this year are to exceed that total and, if
at all possible, stay in one place. Washington left him unprotected
in the 1998 expansion draft for Nashville. The Predators,
disappointed with Brunette's production _ he had 11 goals in only
28 games for the Capitals _ shipped him to Atlanta for a
conditional draft pick in 2000 a few days before the 1999 expansion
draft. After two expansion teams in two years, the safe assumption
is that Brunette has no desire to be a Columbus Blue Jacket or
Minnesota Wild next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really something you want to brag about,'' he said,
laughing. ``But there's a real positive side to being on an
expansion team and seeing it built up. Last year, we used it as
motivation. You would hear people say, `Expansion isn't good for
hockey,' and then we'd go beat Detroit. So how bad could it be?''
</P>
<P>
   Originally a draft pick by Washington in 1993, Brunette
estimates that he was called up from the minors and returned 23
times by the Capitals in three seasons. The move to Nashville was
more a rescue than a transaction.
</P>
<P>
   He is used to the knocks on his skating ability by now. It
didn't stop him from scoring 62 goals one year in the juniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always heard that I couldn't make it at the next level,''
Brunette said. ``When I was young I was told, `Well, you'll have a
hard time in the juniors.' In the juniors I was told, `You won't
make it in the pros.' In the AHL, they said, `You're OK at this
level, but you won't make it in the NHL.' But I tried to play smart
enough to not let that get in the way. I know I'm not going to win
a race with Sergei Fedorov, but I still think I can play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally I didn't think I was that slow. But when everybody
keeps telling you that, it gets in your head.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, speed isn't a requirement when you're situated 10
feet from the net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
