<HEADER>
A4504 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      10-21 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: NETANYAHU ON THE SPOT
</P>
<P>
   The police questioned former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
in a fraud investigation room in Bat Yam, outside Tel Aviv, a day
after raiding his home and office. It was the latest chapter in an
inquiry that began with bribery allegations involving Netanyahu's
relationship with a contractor who worked in his home. The
contractor, Avner Amadi, has turned state's witness, according to
local news reports. Netanyahu's friends say he is the victim of a
political vendetta.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: RABIN REMEMBERED
</P>
<P>
   On a warm autumn day at the Mount Herzl cemetery in Jerusalem,
Israeli officials marked the fourth anniversary of Yitzhak Rabin's
assassination, which is observed here by the Jewish calendar. Prime
Minister Ehud Barak, who sees himself as following in Rabin's path
as a warrior-turned-peacemaker, said: ``We are continuing exactly
from the point where it all was stopped by three bullets.''
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS
</P>
<P>
   ABM TREATY CHANGES OPPOSED
</P>
<P>
   China joined Russia and Belarus in asking the General Assembly
to demand that the 1972 Antiballistic Missile Treaty between Moscow
and Washington not be amended, as the United States proposes to do
to deploy more missile defenses. Hu Xiaodi, deputy director general
of China's Arms Control and Disarmament Department, told reporters
the treaty's fate affected all nations. ``The preservation of the
treaty, the integrity of the treaty, is of utmost importance,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: ANGER OVER BUDGET
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo presented to the Congress a $120
billion draft budget for 2000, provoking an outcry from opposition
lawmakers over the $9 billion to be spent to service the debt
derived from a government bank bailout. The $9 billion is twice
what Mexico spent last year on all antipoverty programs. The
government said it would try to achieve a growth rate of 4 percent
to 5 percent in 2000 while holding inflation to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA: FORMER LEADERS FACE PROSECUTION
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has ruled that corruption charges against
former President Jaime Lusinchi can be revived, overturning a lower
court decision that the statute of limitations had expired.
Lusinchi, who served between 1984 and 1989, has condemned the
action as politically motivated. The announcement came after
President Hugo Chavez said Lusinchi and another former President,
Carlos Andres Perez, should ``both go to jail and be sentenced to
many years of imprisonment for their crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: A HIGH-LEVEL SNUB
</P>
<P>
   Former Prime Minister Yevgeni Primakov refused an invitation to
meet with President Boris Yeltsin, citing policy differences.
Primakov, whom Yeltsin ousted from his post in May, has emerged as
a leading candidate to succeed Yeltsin. Though he did not provide
details, Primakov has opposed an all-out ground invasion of
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: FAYED LOSES BATTLE
</P>
<P>
   Mohamed Fayed, 66, the Egyptian-born businessman who owns
Harrods, lost another battle in his four-year campaign for a
British passport when the High Court turned down his latest appeal
as ``devoid of substance.'' Fayed had argued that Home Secretary
Jack Straw was ``inappropriately draconian'' in deciding in May
that he lacked the ``good character'' to become a British citizen.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: PESSIMISM ON PEACE
</P>
<P>
   Ulster's politicians entered the final phase of former Sen.
George Mitchell's seven-week attempt to rescue the faltering peace
settlement in Belfast today in an atmosphere of growing pessimism.
In an overnight visit to New York, Gerry Adams, president of Sinn
Fein, the political representative of the IRA, told a fund-raising
dinner, ``I think on balance that the Mitchell review will probably
not succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: BAN ON HEAD SCARVES
</P>
<P>
   Ruling on an issue that has become extremely sensitive in a
country where four million Muslims now live, France's highest
administrative court reaffirmed a ban on wearing Islamic head
scarves in public schools. A lower court had reinstated a Muslim
girl who had been expelled from a school in Nancy for refusing to
take off her scarf. The Council of State, however, ruled that
schools had the right to insist that pupils dress in a way that
allowed the proper functioning of the class.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
