r a BC-PROSTATE-VASECTOMY-SP     10-21 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSTATE-VASECTOMY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SHOWS VASECTOMIES DON'T INCREASE CHANCES OF PROSTATE CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Men with vasectomies can breathe easier now thanks to
new data that show they have no greater risk of getting prostate
cancer than men without vasectomies.
</P>
<P>
   The same study, the largest ever to look at prostate cancer risk
and vasectomies, also found that taking zinc, vitamin C or vitamin
E may significantly reduce the risk of prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The study was done at the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center
in Seattle, and was designed to resolve a lingering debate over
whether vasectomies predispose a man to prostate cancer. The
results are being published Friday in Cancer Epidemiology,
Biomarkers and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The body of evidence shows there's no association between
vasectomies and prostate cancer,'' said Dr. Janet Stanford, head of
the Prostate Cancer Research Program in the Hutchinson Center's
Public Health Sciences Division and lead author of the study.
``This should be very reassuring to all the men out there and to
physicians who do vasectomies.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford, who also is a research professor in the Department of
Epidemiology at the University of Washington, said previous studies
have given conflicting results.
</P>
<P>
   The debate began in 1990 after two studies showed a higher
frequency of vasectomies in men hospitalized for prostate cancer
than in men hospitalized for other reasons, she said. However, the
studies were flawed and their findings later questioned.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the National Cancer Institute paid for a $1.8 million
study to try to reach a definitive answer. Fred Hutchinson was one
of two centers chosen to look at the question, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 1,456 men aged 40 to 64 interviewed for the study, 753
were diagnosed with prostate cancer between 1993 and 1996 and 703
were men in the general King County population with no history of
prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The prevalence of vasectomies was about the same in each group.
Of men with prostate cancer, 39.4 percent had undergone a
vasectomy, compared with 37.7 percent of the non-cancer group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men who have had vasectomies don't need to continue to
worry,'' she said. Nationally, about 14 percent of currently
married men under age 45 have had vasectomies, a surgical
contraceptive procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer is the most frequently diagnosed solid tumor in
men. This year, an estimated 170,000 men will be diagnosed with the
disease in the United States, and 37,000 will die from it.
</P>
<P>
   Between 20 and 25 percent of all prostate cancer cases are
diagnosed in men under age 65.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to dispelling fears about vasectomies and prostate
cancer, the study also yielded some unexpected results regarding
dietary supplements and cancer risk.
</P>
<P>
   When men in the study were asked about their lifestyle habits,
fewer than one-third said they took a daily multivitamin. Only 21
percent said they took vitamin C, while 14 percent took vitamin E,
and 5 percent took daily doses of zinc, calcium or vitamin A.
</P>
<P>
   Men who took daily doses of vitamin C or vitamin E had a 23
percent lower risk of prostate cancer, while those who took zinc
daily decreased their risk by 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, researchers cautioned that the results were suggestive,
not conclusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so few studies of dietary supplements and
prostate-cancer risk that even with these results we still don't
know enough about it to make any recommendations,'' said Dr. Alan
Kristal, a member of the Cancer Prevention Research Program at Fred
Hutchinson and professor of epidemiology at the UW. Kristal led the
analysis of the supplement data.
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence that zinc levels are lower in cancerous
prostate tissue than in healthy prostate tissue, leading to
speculation that zinc may play a role in regulating healthy
prostate growth, Stanford said.
</P>
<P>
   The news on reducing prostate risk follows reports earlier this
week that scientists are making progress on a possible prostate
cancer vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Using a virus to insert new genes into cancerous cells,
scientists at Johns Hopkins Oncology Center have been able to trick
the immune systems of prostate cancer patients into thinking tumors
were ``foreign substances'' that should be attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists believe one reason tumors grow is that the immune
system fails to recognize the cancerous cells. The immune system
still sees the cancer cells as part of the ``self'' that should not
be attacked. By priming cancer cells with genes that signal the
immune system to form antibodies, scientists were able to create a
vaccine that triggered the body to attack the tumors. The results
were published in the October issue of the journal Cancer Research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
