<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4517 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-BIOGRAPHY-ART-NY     10-21 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BIOGRAPHY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISTRIBUTION OF BUSH BIOGRAPHY SUSPENDED AFTER QUESTIONS ABOUT
AUTHOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT24,29 _ are being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A major New York publishing house suspended
distribution and promotion of a controversial new biography of
George W. Bush on Thursday after a Texas newspaper reported that
the book's author was convicted 11 years ago of hiring a
professional killer in a failed attempt to murder his boss.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the publisher, St. Martin's Press, said they wanted
to conduct their own inquiry into the background and reporting
methods of the author, J.H. Hatfield, before continuing to push the
sale of his book, ``Fortunate Son: George W. Bush and the Making of
an American President,'' which began appearing on store shelves
this week.
</P>
<P>
   The book includes the claim _ attributed entirely to anonymous
sources _ that Bush, now governor of Texas and front-runner for the
Republican presidential nomination, was arrested for cocaine
possession in 1972 and that a judge promptly expunged the record as
a favor to Bush's father. Although both Bush and his father, former
President George Bush, unequivocally denied the accusation earlier
this week, it appeared in many prominent publications.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with St. Martin's Press said they were now concerned
about the reliability of the information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Mr. Hatfield's credibility has been called into serious
question, we feel compelled to suspend publication,'' Sally
Richardson, the president and publisher of the trade division of
St. Martin's, said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Ms. Richardson said Hatfield had told
an executive of the publishing house that he was being confused
with someone else and, contrary to what The Dallas Morning News
reported on Thursday, was not a felon on parole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to get to the bottom of this,'' Ms. Richardson
said. ``We just don't know what to think at this point. We are
struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatfield, reached by telephone at his home in Arkansas, said
lawyers had instructed him not to talk to reporters about the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment late last week when St. Martin's began promoting
``Fortunate Son'' on the strength of its final chapter, which is
devoted to the account of a cocaine arrest, Bush and his aides have
emphatically denied the accusation, pointing out numerous factors
that render it implausible.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times received an advanced copy of the book last
week, and reporters from the paper spent several days trying to
corroborate Hatfield's account. But they did not find any, and the
newspaper did not publish anything about the claim.
</P>
<P>
   Bush labeled it ``science fiction'' during an appearance in
Scottsdale, Ariz., on Monday. On Thursday, campaigning in
Spartanburg, S.C., he said that if Hatfield was indeed a felon,
``it reflects on his credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But then his credibility was nothing to me anyway,'' Bush
said. ``His story was totally ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Department of Criminal Justice in Texas,
where Hatfield used to live, provided records on Thursday showing
that a man named James H. Hatfield was convicted in 1988 of
solicitation of capital murder and served five years in a Texas
prison. The spokesman, Larry Fitzgerald, said that the man was
paroled in 1993 and put under the supervision of a parole agency in
Arkansas, where the book's author lives.
</P>
<P>
   The age and other biographical information of the convicted
felon _ who had wanted the hit man to use a car bomb _ matched
those of the book's author, the Dallas Morning News reported. An
Arkansas parole official told the newspaper that his records showed
that the convicted felon was the author of an unauthorized
biography of the actor Patrick Stewart, which is one of the books
attributed to the author of ``Fortunate Son'' in promotional
materials provided by St. Martin's.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the article in the Dallas Morning News appeared,
Hatfield seemed an odd fit for a biography of Bush. In addition to
the book on Stewart, the star of the television show ``Star Trek:
The Next Generation,'' Hatfield had written a mass-market paperback
on the actor Ewan McGregor, the star of the summer movie ``The
Phantom Menace,'' and trivia-style books on the television shows
``The X-Files'' and ``Lost in Space.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives with St. Martin's, however, noted that Hatfield's
resume also included the fact that he had contributed articles to
reputable Texas publications, and they said that his proposal for
the book had come from a respected Manhattan literary agency,
Richard Curtis Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Hatfield's agent, Laura Tucker, has since switched from that
firm to a new one, but declined to take a telephone call on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Executives with St. Martin's said that the publishing house
would not try to arrange any promotional interviews or appearances
for Hatfield until St. Martin's lawyers had resolved questions
about his past. They said that St. Martin's reserved the right to
resume the distribution and promotion of the book and had not made
any final decisions yet.
</P>
<P>
   The book had received a large first printing of 90,000 copies,
70,000 of which were already in stores or on their way there. The
20,000 copies still in warehouses would not be shipped for the time
being, Ms. Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   But it was unclear today how many, if any, sellers would pull
from shelves the copies of ``Fortunate Son'' that they had already
received. Mary Ellen Keating, a spokeswoman for Barnes &AMP; Noble
Inc., said late Thursday that the chain intended to continue
providing the book to customers.
</P>
<P>
   For years now, Bush, the leading candidate for the Republican
presidential nomination, has been asked publicly about persistent
rumors of drug use in his past. He has mostly refused to answer the
questions.
</P>
<P>
   But in August, he gave a little ground, saying that he could
verify that he had not used any illegal drugs in the past 25 years.
Hatfield wrote the final chapter of his book after that point and
tried to use that marker as a supporting point for his contention
that Bush was arrested 27 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunate Son'' had initially been scheduled for publication
in January, but was rushed into print to compete with ``First Son:
George W. Bush and the Bush Family Dynasty,'' a book by Bill
Minutaglio, a reporter for the Dallas Morning News, that Times
Books published this month.
</P>
<P>
   Minutaglio said in a telephone interview on Thursday that there
had long been a rumor about Bush being arrested in 1972 and that he
had done reporting to try to confirm it, but that it appeared to be
untrue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
