<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-FINAL-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Oct. 24,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE story &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOBEL-ISRAEL-THEATER (Jerusalem) _ The Israeli theater writer,
Yehoshua Sobol, 60, a former director of the Haifa Theater, looks
back on an earlier era of theater in Israel. His plays includes ``A
Palestinian Girl'' and ``The Jerusalem Syndrome.'' Today he is
concerned that a depressing commercialism has overtaken the Israeli
theatrical scene. By Deborah Sontag. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JOAN-OF-ARC-VIDEO (Undated) _ No particular reason comes to
mind, but on film and video there is a resurgent call for the
French peasant girl with, in the words of one critic in 1929, ``a
face supernaturally illumined by faith, with lips parched through
excitement and with a pair of eyes that see Heaven opening before
them.'' This is how he described the uplifted visage of Maria
(sometimes called Renee) Falconetti as Joan of Arc in Carl Theodor
Dreyer's silent classic ``The Passion of Saint Joan,'' released in
1928 and by far the most interesting of three titles about the Maid
of Orleans to be seen this fall. ``The Passion'' is to be released
on tape by Home Vision and on a fine DVD from the Criterion
Collection on Nov. 9. By Peter M. Nichols. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   CRAVEN-FILMS (Undated) _ From his cringingly inexpert yet
profitable debut with ``The Last House on the Left'' (1972), the
story of a Manson-like family of killers and the vengeance that is
wreaked upon them, through the imaginatively sinister and
profitable ``A Nightmare on Elm Street'' (1984), which established
the teen-age horror movie genre, and on to the witty and profitable
``Scream'' (1996) and ``Scream 2'' (1997), the second amusingly
deconstructing the first, Wes Craven could always be counted on to
spill an audience-pleasing ocean of blood. This was a source of no
small amount of frustration for him over the years, as producers
and studios ruled him out of consideration for projects merely
because of the images his name conjured up. But fortunately for
him, the success that so long pigeonholed him eventually sprang
him. Craven's new movie, ``Music of the Heart,'' which opens
Friday, stars Ms. Cheryl Streep as a music teacher in East Harlem.
It is based on a true story, is chock-full of feet-on-the-ground
characters and has heart and grit and genuine warmth. By Jame
Malanowski. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DAME-EDNA-THEATER (New York) _ Dame Edna Everage, the Melbourne
housewife, social anthropologist, talk-show host, investigative
journalist and self-styled megastar, has clearly outgrown the
control of her mentor, Barry Humphries. He's the Australian wizard
who, as a young actor and writer, created the character for a
Melbourne revue in 1955 and has been at her side ever since. The
extent to which this gloriously opinionated, mauve-haired golem has
taken over Humphries is now nakedly apparent in ``Dame Edna: The
Royal Tour'' at the Booth Theater on Broadway. By Vincent Canby.
(Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MONTALVO-DANCE (Creteil, France) _ With close to 20 years'
experience as a choreographer, Jose Montalvo is hardly a novice,
yet for a long time this tall simpatico Frenchman of Spanish
descent was known _ when he was known at all _ as a peripheral
artist more interested in experimentation than fame. Then he
created ``Paradis,'' a delightful multimedia, multicultural collage
of a work. After that, everything was different. Since its premiere
in March 1997, ``Paradis'' has been performed almost 200 times _
that's about once every four days _ in France and on tour in
Europe, the Far East and Latin America. Now the 60-minute work is
traveling to New York for eight performances at the Joyce Theater
starting on Tuesday as part of the New Europe '99 Festival. By Alan
Riding. (Moved).
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TENORS-MUSIC (Undated) _ For a generation Luciano Pavarotti
thrilled and amused us; Placido Domingo evoked undying admiration.
Jose Carreras gave us early hope, but unwise career decisions,
choices made long before a serious and unrelated illness, left him
with fame, money and a ravaged voice. Opera in general sharpens our
nerve endings, sometimes to the point of hysteria. Tenors, for
better and worse, drive us crazy. We need a couple of big ones. So
audiences and a music business operatives are now taking a hard
look at three new tenors, Roberto Alagna of Italy, Marcelo Alvarez
and, most recently, Jose Cura, both from Argentina. By Bernard
Holland. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   SYMPHONIC-ORGAN (Paris) _ Anyone familiar with organ music would
recognize the name. Aristide Cavaille-Coll (pronounced
cah-vah-yea-COLL) developed the ``symphonic'' organ in France and
died 100 years ago this month. The instruments he left behind could
fill vast spaces with sound as varied and powerful as a symphony
orchestra's, and they inspired composers from Cesar Franck, Camille
Saint-Saens, Charles-Marie Widor and Louis Vierne to Marcel Dupre
and Olivier Messiaen to play and write a dramatically expressive
kind of music for the instrument that pipe organs had never been
capable of before. By Craig R. Whitney. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOME-STUDIOS-RECORDINGS (subslug) (Undated) _ Since 1991, F.M.
Cornog in an upstairs room of his Summit N.J., home, has been
writing songs, recording them and releasing them under the moniker
East River Pipe. Every day, instead of going to work in an office
or factory, or, for that matter, a recording studio _ he goes to
this room and fiddles around and lays down ideas until he has
enough material for an album. East River Pipe's fourth and most
recent album, ``The Gasoline Age,'' released on the independent
label Merge, is a dreamy, Springsteenish meditation on suburban car
culture. By Karen Schoemer. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-MUSEUM (Jerusalem) _ It is never easy building a major
art museum from scratch, but Teddy Kollek, the former mayor of
Jerusalem, has good reason to crow. In less than four decades, he
has seen the Israel Museum evolve from an improbable fantasy into a
world-class institution whose collection now consists of some
500,000 objects _ roughly five times as many as the National
Gallery of Art in Washington. By Deborah Solomon. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POTTERS (Undated) _ Over the last 400 years, the
innovative potters of Puebla, a town east of Mexico City, have done
what potters do best: they have taken dazzling designs from the
ceramics of other cultures and reproduced them. Then, to mark them
as Mexican, they have added images of a cactus here, a parrot
there. The story of how Spanish potters succeeded in transforming
the traditional terra cotta ceramics in Mexico is the little known
story that is revealed in ``Talavera Poblana: Four Centuries of a
Mexican Ceramic Tradition,'' an exhibition at the Americas Society
Art Gallery, in Manhattan, through Dec. 12. By Rita Reif. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   SENSATION-ART (New York) _ New art has rarely had as many
reluctant champions as ``Sensation,'' the exhibition of work by
young English artists from the collection of Charles Saatchi, the
English advertising executive, at the Brooklyn Museum of Art.
People both inside and outside the art world have been defending to
the death the exhibition's right to be seen in a public museum,
while turning up their noses at the art it contains or dismissing
it wholesale. By Roberta Smith. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TSCHUMI-ARCH (New York) _ Alfred Lerner Hall, the new student
center at Columbia University, will plunge some baby boomer alumni
into a cool nostalgic bath. The architect, Bernard Tschumi, has
long made a touchstone of the events of 68: the student uprisings
that for many epitomize the turmoil of the 1960s. Columbia
University's architecture school was one of the epicenters of those
events. Today, the school is run by Tschumi, an architect whose
sensibility was formed by the Paris edition of those
demonstrations. No practicing architect of his generation has
identified himself more closely with the anarchic energies of that
era. By Herbert Muschamp. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CORWIN-RADIO (Undated) _ For more than 60 years, Norman Corwin's
radio dramas about the human condition and the state of the planet
_ America, in particular _ have helped shape the public perception
of who we are and what we're doing here. Through war and peace,
Corwin opened his microphone to big thoughts and the common man:
freedom, loyalty, courage, fear, despair, triumph. For nine years
at CBS _ 1938 to 1947 _ he presided over national catharsis at the
radio console. And now, with the last 1,000 years to look back on,
Corwin has come up with ``Memos to a New Millennium,'' a half-hour
script he calls a meditation for radio. Underwritten by the
Corporation for Public Broadcasting, it will be distributed
nationally at year's end by Public Radio International. By Charles
Strum. (Moved).
</P>
