<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RIVERA22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In postseason, nobody better than Rivera
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It blew up fast.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones walked. Brian Jordan singled and so did Ryan
Klesko. Next up was Andruw Jones, who finished the kill by slashing
a three-run home run.
</P>
<P>
   It all came down quickly in the ninth inning on July 16 in the
Bronx. Jones' second home run of the night sent the New York
Yankees _ and more specifically, Mariano Rivera _ to a 10-7 loss
after they had been leading by a run.
</P>
<P>
   The day is worth recalling, not just because the Yankees are
seeing the Braves again this weekend. That afternoon at Yankee
Stadium also marked the last time Rivera, New York's superb closer,
blew a save. It was his most calamitous inning of the year. Since
then, he has remained the most consistent player in pinstripes,
allowing just one run since that day and absolutely nothing since
July 21.
</P>
<P>
   As the World Series begins this weekend, fans will hear much
about Chuck Knoblauch's psyche, Derek Jeter's cachet, Paul
O'Neill's severity, David Cone's bionic arm. Save the last word for
Rivera, because he usually has it.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, thus far, have dodged the Astros' Billy Wagner and
coped with the Mets' Armando Benitez, but this series pits them
against the game's best closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, he has been so automatic,'' left-hander Andy Pettitte
said.
</P>
<P>
   After the beating by the Braves, Rivera went on to post a
major-league high 45 saves, the last 22 of them without incident.
He posted a career-low 1.83 ERA while allowing just five of 22
inherited runners to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to jinx him or anything,'' Pettitte said, ``but
he has been special.''
</P>
<P>
   Never more than in the postseason. With a couple of saves and a
victory against Boston in the ALCS, Rivera comes to Turner Field
with a string of 21 1/3 scoreless postseason innings. His October
ERA is 0.42, the lowest of any pitcher in major-league history with
a minimum of 30 innings. And he didn't close until two seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he first got the job in 1997 (after John Wetteland's
departure), it is a little different when there is nobody behind
you,'' manager Joe Torre said. ``Somebody cuts the safety net out
from under you, and you realize that when the ball gets by you, the
game is over. It took him time.''
</P>
<P>
   The telling period came in early 1998. Rivera allowed a home run
to Cleveland's Sandy Alomar in the eighth inning of Game 4 of the
1997 AL Division Series, allowing the Indians to tie the game, turn
the series around and eventually win in five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he came back the next spring, and (pitching coach) Mel
(Stottlemyre) and I made sure we talked about the home run and made
sure it didn't keep him from being the aggressive guy that made him
really good,'' Torre said. ``I think where the growing has come
from was probably from September of 1998, when he had discovered
with Mel's help, the movement on the fastball, instead of just
rearing back and throwing the four-seamer and thinking strikeout,
strikeout, strikeout.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera still throws the 97-mph fastball, but his 52 strikeouts
this season _ half as many as Braves' closer John Rocker _ reflects
his new reliance on the induced groundout. He has thrown fewer
pitches and has been available to pitch more often. Rivera was able
pitch six games in a row in one period this season.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera's personality also is the opposite of the Braves' closer.
Yankee Stadium rocks to Metallica's ``Enter Sandman'' when Rivera
walks in from the bullpen, but he didn't choose the song and
doesn't particularly like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not cocky,'' he said earlier this month. ``I don't have a
big head. That's not me. I just love to help the team in the best
way I can do it. And that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
