<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    O'Leary tinkering to try to jump-start Jackets
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech coach George O'Leary says he has made it
clear to the players he is far from satisfied with their recent
performances.
</P>
<P>
   Despite remaining in the Top 10, the Yellow Jackets have fallen
into a turnover and penalty slump on offense, and remain in a
season-long tackling slump on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're playing our best football,'' O'Leary said.
``We're basically sitting back and not reacting to the ball _ in
all three phases of the game. I just don't see us at that same
level of crispness we're used to playing at.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the shake-up O'Leary had indicated for his football
squad might better be described as a tuneup.
</P>
<P>
   Tech, which is ranked No. 8 but has been shaken by two
tougher-than-expected wins over ACC bottom-feeders North Carolina
and Duke, returned to practice Thursday after being out for fall
break.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets (5-1, 3-1 ACC) have this weekend off before
hosting North Carolina State, and O'Leary said the bye week could
not have come at a better time.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Players) re-charged their batteries and coaches re-charged
their batteries,'' O'Leary said. ``That's the nature of (being at)
midseason.''
</P>
<P>
   It also is a time for some tinkering, and in a surprising move,
O'Leary has switched All-ACC free safety Travares Tillman, who
missed the past two games with a back injury, to the
boundary-cornerback position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of hesitant about moving at first. I would have to
learn a whole new position with just five games left in my college
career,'' said Tillman said, who played some at cornerback as a
freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I practiced pretty well today, and I have to help the team
anyway I can. In a way, it probably will help me out with (NFL)
scouts because they'll see me in more man-to-man coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Cory Collins, the highly regarded freshman who had backed
Tillman at safety before pulling a leg muscle, lined up with the
first team at the other cornerback position.
</P>
<P>
   That left freshman Jeremy Muyres, who played well in the absence
of Tillman and Collins, at free safety and Chris Young at strong
safety. Jamara Clark, Troy Tolbert and Marvious Hester will have
time to reclaim starting cornerback berths, but O'Leary is set on
playing Tillman, Muyres and Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to keep the three guys in there who have proven they
deserve to be in there,'' O'Leary said. ``I'll take the next best
one and (at the cornerback opposite Tillman). I'm just trying to
mix it up a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Nick Rogers has moved back to outside linebacker,
while Guenter Kryszon, who had started at defensive tackle moves
out to end opposite freshman sensation Greg Gathers.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Edwards and Felipe Claybrooks, former starters at
linebacker and defensive end, respectively, will still see a lot of
playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moving Nick to linebacker gives us a lot more flexibility,''
O'Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the move that will probably excite Tech fans most
is the probability that freshman tailback Sidney Ford, who led the
state in rushing last year at Pepperell High in Rome with 2,595
yards and scored 34 touchdowns, will have to forgo a redshirt
season.
</P>
<P>
   With starting tailbacks Phillip Rogers and Joe Burns out for the
season with injuries, the Jackets cannot afford such a luxury.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go with what you need to win with,'' O'Leary said.
``Sidney understands that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with its losses and miscues, the offense remains the
nation's best, averaging 517 yards per game. And Heisman Trohy
candidate Joe Hamilton leads the NCAA in passing efficiency, while
the Dez White-Kelly Campbell receiving duo has 60 catches and eight
TDs. ``As long as we keep making big plays (with) our receiving
corps, we'll be able to score points,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
