u s BC-FBC-UGA-PICKS22-COX     10-21 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-PICKS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turnovers a big plus for Dogs' defense
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia's defense has taken its share of knocks
this year, on the field from opponents and off the field from
critics.
</P>
<P>
   But lost in the pile of yardage allowed and the close shaves
against supposedly outmanned teams is the ability of the defense to
fulfill coach Jim Donnan's most clearly stated mandate for the
season: Create more turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Saturday's game against pass-happy Kentucky, the
Bulldogs lead the SEC with 15 interceptions, have recovered five
fumbles and are No. 1 in the nation in turnover margin at plus-2
per game. That they are giving up an average of 348 yards per game
_ the third-highest total in the league _ seems less important to
Donnan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with our whole defensive philosophy,'' he said.
``What we said we were looking for was to create more turnovers,
take better care of the ball and have more snaps (on offense).
We've been able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the credit goes to three players. Cornerbacks Cory
Robinson and Jamie Henderson are tied for the team lead and are
third nationally with five interceptions each, and linebacker
Kendrell Bell has three interceptions and caused three fumbles.
Cornerback Jeff Harris and defensive tackle Richard Seymour also
have interceptions and fumble recoveries.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats, under coach Hal Mumme, bring to Athens the SEC's
most prolific passing offense (311 ypg) and the league's top-rated
quarterback, sophomore Dusty Bonner of Valdosta. The Bulldogs,
while opportunistic in the secondary, have proven vulnerable to
good passing teams. They are giving up 255.5 yards a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's still very correctable,'' said Kevin Ramsey,
Georgia's defensive coordinator and secondary coach. ``It's not
about ability; it's not about one guy being faster than the other.
A lot of it has to do with technique, and we're working on that. If
we can cut down the mental errors, we'll see what kind of defensive
team we really are.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Ramsey, the Bulldogs are playing a more aggressive defense
that emphasizes pressuring the passer and playing man-to-man
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   When it works, it's great. When it doesn't, it can result in big
plays for opponents. Georgia has given up 16 plays that gained 26
or more yards. Last week Vanderbilt had pass plays of 31, 41 and 58
yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this new aggressive defense, you're going to take some
risks,'' Robinson said. ``Sometimes, you're going to stump your
toe; sometimes, you're going to make a big play. It's not like
somebody's put up a bunch of points on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is giving up 19.2 points per game. The most was 37 to
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played more man coverage, and we've been burned deep on
some plays,'' Donnan said. ``But we've committed to a pressure
defense. We've had a lot of lost-yardage plays (37-113),
particularly against the run, and we had more sacks last week
(three) than we've had, and we've forced some turnovers. ... Hey,
Deion Sanders gets beaten sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
