<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4528 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SOUTHPOLE-RESCUER-ART     10-21 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHPOLE-RESCUER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLONEL ADDS SOUTH POLE RESCUE TO HIS RESUME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)  (See also SOUTHPOLE-DOCTOR) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. _ The call about the lady with the lump in her
breast first came to the New York Air National Guard's 109th
Airlift Wing in June.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't know she was a doctor at that point, just a lady
working for the National Science Foundation, stuck on the South
Pole, and their answer, regarding the possibility of bringing her
out, was no.
</P>
<P>
   Summer in New York _ yeah, they have summer in Schenectady, Col.
Ed Fleming, the vice commander of the 109th and the man who planned
the rescue, will joke _ is winter at the Pole.
</P>
<P>
   The day the call came in the weather at the Pole was minus 118
Farenheit. At that temperature, fuel starts to jell. There was also
no runway _ rather, no skiway, as the jets are equipped with skis _
and winter at the Pole means perpetual night. An Air Force plane
made a medical drop to the doctor, Jerri Nielsen, and she took the
extraordinary step of treating herself with chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, as the weather in the Pole was warming, Fleming
was told that due to a change in Dr. Nielsen's treatment she had to
be taken out of the Pole by Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Working with a team headed by Air Operations Officer Lt. Col.
Brian D. Gomula, who has had 10 seasons at the Pole, Fleming made
plans. He dispatched two LC-130 Hercules jets, equipped with both
skis and wheels, which give the 109th Airlift Wing the ability to
do something the 109th maintains no one else in the world can do:
land at the Pole.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming set up a schedule which allowed his crews to sleep. He
warned his people of an adrenalin rush from ``having the world
watching'' which might impair judgment. A rescue was made in 22
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   There was one factor, however, which Fleming, an easy going
fellow who listens to Borodin on his office computer and who did
his doctorate dissertation on Human Factors Error in a Cue and
Symbol Saturated Environment, did not consider.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never allow a rescue to become an accounting exercise,''
Fleming says. ``You have a crew of six going to rescue one, people
will always go, `Is that worth it?' We will go in for three, two,
or one. I have two sons, we all have loved ones. If anything
happened to them we'd want people to make every effort to rescue
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is a line you don't often see on a resume: ``300 Lives
saved,'' though being a modest and meticulous guy, Fleming, 51,
will call to amend that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually 293 lives saved,'' Fleming says, having checked.
``Pilots round things off. I don't want to sound too grandiose.''
</P>
<P>
   His career, nonetheless, has been impressive. Ten years in the
Air Force; 20 years in the Air National Guard, much of as commander
of the 106th Operations Group, a rescue unit on Long Island. There
has been tragedy _ a helicopter under Fleming's command went down
in 1991 and one man died. There has been triumph _ Fleming's
15-hour rescue of a sailor in '95 set the world endurance
helicopter rescue record. In that rescue Fleming was flying the
HH-60G Pavehawk, which, like all of the helicopters he has flown,
requires in-flight refueling from a tanker plane. To do this, the
pilot has to land a probe in a 27-inch wide target.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're eight hours out to sea, with a rotating wing that has
two hours of fuel, and you get so you have to live with that,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Liam Fleming did not grow up crazy with the desire to
fly, by the way. The son of a telephone foreman and a schoolteacher
in Buffalo, he majored in Chinese History at State University of
New York at Buffalo and planed a career in rehabilitation therapy.
Ask him how he ended up in the Air Force and his answer is
succinct: ``The draft,'' he says, meaning the war in Vietnam was
raging, and by enlisting he had some choice.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force trains Fleming in air rescue, which, he feels, is
not so removed from rehab. With the 31st Air Force Rescue Squad in
the Philippines, he flew Charles Lindbergh, after Lindberg had been
lost for 10 days in the jungle of Mindanao, in 1972. He piloted the
last active World War Two Japanese soldier, Lt. Hiroo Onoda, off
Lubang Island in 1974. Regrettably, he does not even remember
anything about the last active Japanese soldier.
</P>
<P>
   He does, however, remember the rescue of the Ukrainian sailor in
December of '94. The sailor's ship, a freighter called the Salvador
Allende, had gone down in a storm 750 miles from shore with a crew
of 31. Only two would survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figured if we had three tankers we could do it,'' Fleming
says. ``When we got out there, there was this guy in the water,
clinging to a wood cargo pallet, and maybe 60 life rafts around
him. Freighters, other aircraft, had thrown down rafts, but no one
had been able to get near him. We lowered one of my swimmers, you
should have his name, Doc Dougherty. The guy couldn't see, he'd
been blinded by the sun. He'd been in the water two days and given
up hope. Getting back was kind of scary. These aircraft aren't
really made for 15 hours. We had no relief tubes, the noise level
was so bad I couldn't hear. In the 13th hour we couldn't find our
tanker. That's when we had the most doubts.''
</P>
<P>
   His memories of the sailor? ``He was ecstatic,'' Fleming says.
``He writes me every Christmas and thanks us for getting him out.
He always sends a picture of his wife and two daughters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
