<SLUG> BC-INVEST-FISHING-GEAR-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISHING GEAR MAKERS BECOME A PRIZE CATCH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Ill., Okla., Iowa, Wis., Mich., Texas, Ind., Ala.,
Va.)   (af)  
 By KATE MURPHY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like toy and hardware makers before them, small manufacturers of
fishing gear are being acquired by aggressive competitors looking
to build economies of scale.
</P>
<P>
   The sports-fishing equipment industry has long been the province
of labor-of-love specialty companies _ supplying, say, just rubber
bait for catching walleye in the Great Lakes region. Although
several chief executives still answer their phones with a ``Howdy
do!,'' economic reality applies even to fishing tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't survive in this business working out of your garage
anymore,'' said William H. Wilson, chief executive of Pradco Inc.,
a privately held company in Fort Smith, Ark., which owns 11 popular
brands of fishing lures, including Smithwick and Quik-Hit, many of
them acquired in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Steve C. Greer, chief financial officer of the United States
division of the Rapala Normark Corp. of Finland, another maker of
fishing lures, said ``product distribution is driven by the major
marts and big-box sports chains who don't want to talk to you
unless you can supply a range of products in large volume.''
Analysts say mass-market retailers and a handful of equally
demanding cataloguers sell 75 percent of fishing tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Sales in the industry _ encompassing lures, rods, reels, line
and other accessories _ were estimated at $1.9 billion in the
United States in 1998, and close to $3 billion worldwide. ``It's a
lot of little stuff that makes up a very big market,'' said Tom B.
Doyle, vice president of information and research at the National
Sporting Goods Association in Mount Prospect, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Rapala, with $106.6 million in sales _ nearly half in the United
States _ went public late last year on the Helsinki Stock Exchange
and used part of the proceeds to buy a competitor, Storm
Manufacturing Inc. of Norman, Okla., for $13.2 million in January.
After 59 years as a closely held family business specializing in
hand-carved balsa wood lures, Rapala has ``moved into acquisition
mode,'' Greer said, to increase market share and capture ``that all
important peg space at Wal-Mart.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Pure Fishing, a privately held company in Spirit
Lake, Iowa, has bought out several tackle manufacturers, including
the rod manufacturer Fenwick in 1988 and, since 1995, the reel
maker Abu Garcia, the Red Wolf line of fishing accessories and
Coleman Family Fishing. Pure Fishing is known for its Berkley brand
of bait and fishing lines that was started in 1937 by the father of
the current chief executive, Tom Bedell.
</P>
<P>
   Also growing by acquisition are two other industry leaders, the
Zebco Corp. of Tulsa, Okla., and Johnson Worldwide Associates of
Sturtevant, Wis., which also produces other outdoor equipment and
is majority-owned by Samuel Johnson, the chairman of S.C. Johnson &AMP;
Son, the household products company, and his family.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-level players like the Mason Tackle Co. of Otisville, Mich.,
and the Castaway Rod Co. of Conroe, Texas, have also been buying
competitors. Typical is Mason's recent purchase of the Hildebrant
Corp., a Logansport, Ind., company that is more than 100 years old.
</P>
<P>
   It is better to buy existing brands than to create new ones,
because ``customers in this market tend to be extremely loyal to
the old names,'' said Jeff Pontius, president of Zebco, a division
of the Brunswick Corp. in Lake Forest, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been so much consolidation it's hard to keep track who
belongs to who anymore,'' said Deborah Johnson, managing editor of
Fishing Tackle Retailer, a trade magazine published in Montgomery,
Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Membership in the industry's trade organization, the American
Sportsfishing Association based in Alexandria, Va., has declined to
450 members from 600 members in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the number of products out there has remained pretty much
the same,'' indicating that the decline results almost entirely
from acquisitions, said Mike Hayden, president and chief executive
of the association.
</P>
<P>
   But consolidation is only one step in modernizing the tackle
industry. Fishing is a seasonal sport, and the required gear varies
by region and fish species.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very complex category to manage once you enter the
broader market,'' said Bedell of Pure Fishing, which invested $4.5
million three years ago in a computerized inventory system and
warehouse. ``Before we were just like most everybody else in this
business, writing out all the orders by hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Pure Fishing and others are also pouring money into research and
development _ building huge aquariums, for example, to test how
fish respond to new products.
</P>
<P>
   By increasing product lines and updating technology, tackle
companies are not only in a better position to serve the likes of
Wal-Mart. The efforts also help them enter the almost untapped
export market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our read is that the U.S. market is essentially flat, and we
need to look elsewhere to increase profits,'' particularly in
recreational fishing hot spots in Asia, Australia and South
America, said Pontius of Zebco, which has expanded its
international operations 33 percent in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Pure Fishing has set up divisions in 11 countries
since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, at Pradco, said this industry was ``kind of behind''
others in globalization and consolidation. ``It's probably because
we spend so much time fishing,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
