<HEADLINE>
HOUSE SENDS CLINTON ANOTHER SPENDING BILL HE'S SURE TO VETO 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the second straight day, the House of
Representatives on Thursday approved and sent President Clinton a
spending bill he is sure to veto.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, providing $14 billion for the Interior Department and
cultural programs in the fiscal year that began on Oct. 1, was
adopted on a largely party-line vote of 225-200.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was the 12th of 13 spending bills to go through
Congress. Through a bit of parliamentary magic, the last bill _ for
the Departments of Labor, Education and Health and Human Services _
is to be tied to a new version of a vetoed measure providing money
for the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Once that package, which was still being worked on Thursday
night, is completed, Republican leaders plan to add an
across-the-board cut of about 1 percent in spending for all
government programs for which Congress controls the annual
financing. That will enable Republicans to say they are abiding by
the party's recently adopted principle that no money raised in
Social Security taxes should be tapped for other programs.
</P>
<P>
   The final package is sure to be vetoed. The president opposes
across-the-board spending cuts. Congress also rejected his request
for money to pay for 100,000 new teachers in the nation's public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   On the Interior Department measure, Clinton objects to several
provisions that he maintains would damage the environment. These
are some of those provisions:
</P>
<P>
   _ It would overturn part of an 1872 mining law and allow
unrestricted dumping of mining wastes on public land.
</P>
<P>
   _ It would allow, at least temporarily, petroleum companies to
continue to pay below-market royalties on oil they take from public
land.
</P>
<P>
   _ It would automatically extend grazing permits on national
land, regardless of whether environmental impact studies had been
completed.
</P>
<P>
   _ It would override a ruling this year by a federal judge that
timber cannot be cut in national forests at the expense of wildlife
protection.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the measure includes less money than the president
requested for buying park land and for financing the National
Endowment for the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the House voted, 215 to 213, to send Clinton a
spending bill for the Departments of Commerce, State and Justice
that the president also plans to veto, this one largely on the
ground that it does not provide the money he sought for more
community police officers.
</P>
<P>
   The vote of approval Thursday for the Interior Department bill
was also well short of the two-thirds majority needed to override a
veto.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin, the senior Democrat on the
Appropriations Committee, called the Interior Department bill
``dead on arrival'' when it reaches the White House, and no one
took issue with that point.
</P>
<P>
   The aspects of the bill that the president opposes on
environmental grounds were added by the Senate, and the House
sponsors of the legislation made no effort to defend them.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Appropriations Subcommittee on Interior and
Related Agencies, Rep. Ralph Regula, R-Ohio, said he had tried
unsuccessfully to get the objectionable features dropped in the
conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to remember we have a two-house system here,''
Regula said. ``There has to be some degree of negotiation.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican, Rep. Zach Wamp of Tennessee, argued that it
was too late in the year to pick small fights. ``We're focusing on
a few narrow problems,'' he said, ``and on Oct. 21 we need to get
beyond them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
