<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-SENATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS AGAIN VOTES TO OUTLAW SOME LATE-TERM ABORTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the federal budget unresolved and time on the
congressional clock running out, the U.S. Senate spent a second
full day dueling over abortion Thursday, setting the stage for an
explosive fight on the issue in next year's congressional
elections.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate fate of a Republican bill outlawing some late-term
abortions was determined long before it was approved Thursday
night, with President Clinton vowing to veto it as he has twice
before. But as they debated the legislation, senators in both
parties made it clear a full range of abortion issues will not fade
before the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a big issue in the year 2000 race,'' said
Senator Barbara Boxer, a Democrat from California. ``When you're
thinking of picking up five seats in the United States Senate, it
could be a deciding factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Democrats accused Republicans of wasting time on the
issue to appeal to the party's conservative voters, a Democratic
member held a vote on the Supreme Court decision that legalized
abortion. In asking the Senate to vote on its support for Roe v.
Wade, Senator Tom Harkin of Iowa said he was building a record of
abortion-rights supporters to use in the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, which 48 Republicans opposed, said the 1973
Supreme Court decision to uphold Roe v. Wade was ``an appropriate
decision and secures an important constitutional right and such a
decision should not be overturned.'' After the ballots were cast,
Harkin hailed the widespread Republican opposition as a political
pot of gold, saying it ``lifted the veil of moderation that a lot
of Republicans were hiding behind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now clear what the true agenda of the anti-choice
members ... really is...They want to criminalize choice,'' Harkin
said. ``I think every woman in this country ought to know what is
at stake as we go into next year's elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, who is campaigning for president, also
saw political capital in the debate, issuing a swift response to
the proceedings Thursday afternoon. In a statement, Gore said the
debate should ``serve as a wakeup call to all Americans as to what
is truly at stake in this election.'' Without a presidential veto,
the ban on late-term abortions would become law.
</P>
<P>
   ``As president, I will always, always defend a woman's right to
choose,'' Gore's statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin's so-called ``sense of the Senate'' resolution on Roe v.
Wade passed by a razor thin margin, with all 45 Democrats, except
Senators John Breaux of Louisiana and Harry Reid of Nevada, voting
in favor of it.
</P>
<P>
   Eight Republicans _ including several Northeast moderates,
Senators Olympia Snowe and Susan M. Collins of Maine, John H.
Chafee of Rhode Island and Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania _ also
voted to pass the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The actual legislation at stake, sponsored by Senator Rick
Santorum, a Republican from Pennsylvania, passed by a larger
margin, 63 to 34.
</P>
<P>
   The same legislation, which would ban some types of late-term
abortions, passed twice before, and twice before the president
vetoed it. Few were surprised that Thursday's vote count was almost
exactly the same as the vote the year before, despite Santorum's
efforts to distance the late-term abortion provision from the
fundamental debate over abortion.
</P>
<P>
   According to Santorum, the bill would have banned late-term
abortion in cases where a fetus has left the mother's uterus almost
entirely, what critics call a ``partial birth'' abortion. Other
forms of abortion would not have been addressed, he said,
dismissing critics' argument that the late-term abortion ban was a
move toward revoking all abortion rights. ``We made it very clear
we're not talking any other form of abortion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To some conservatives with higher political aspirations, that
view was insufficient. Senator Bob Smith, an Independent from New
Hampshire who is running for president, spent hours on the Senate
floor passionately denouncing abortion and inviting any woman with
an unwanted pregnancy to call his Senate office for guidance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stabbing a baby in the back of the head is murder,
infanticide,'' Smith said. ``How many Beethovens have we killed?
How many great baseball players? How many entertainers? We'll never
know.''
</P>
<P>
   But with Clinton set to veto the measure, it was the Roe v. Wade
vote that drew the most attention, with Democrats claiming it was a
``first-ever'' referendum on the Supreme Court case.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Senate has voted on abortion issues reflective of
Roe v. Wade three times in the past _ most recently in 1983, when
Senator Orrin G. Hatch, a Republican from Utah, proposed a
constitutional amendment to overturn the court's ruling and send
the issue of abortion back to the states. Hatch, who is in his 22d
year as a senator, is running for president. So is Senator John S.
McCain, a Republican from Arizona who missed the vote on Roe v.
Wade because he was on the campaign trail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
