A4542 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-KIDS-AUTHORS22-COX     10-21 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-AUTHORS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stine, Scieszka big with young readers
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Young readers with a sense of humor and a love of
the frightful have reason to rejoice this week: Two of America's
most popular authors of kids' books are coming to town _ both for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   R.L. Stine is best known for his scary ``Goosebumps'' series,
and Jon Scieszka is best known for putting a new spin on classic
tales (``The True Story of the 3 Little Pigs and The Stinky Cheese
Man and Other Fairly Stupid Tales'').
</P>
<P>
   It's surprising that Thursday was Stine's first book-signing
trip to Dayton _ he grew up in Columbus, attended Ohio State
University and frequently comes back to Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done Columbus a million times,'' Stine says. ``I still
have lots of cousins and friends there. I usually head right from
the airport to Rubino's Pizza on Main Street; New York pizza can't
compare.''
</P>
<P>
   He started writing short stories, joke books and comics for his
friends at the age of 9 and later edited Ohio State's humor
magazine. Stine, 56, will be listed in the Millennium Edition 2000
of the ``Guinness Book of World Records'' as the author of the
best-selling children's book series of all time. His ``Goosebumps''
series _ there are 90 books _ has sold more copies in seven years
than the Nancy Drew and Hardy Boys series combined in 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is just to entertain kids and to make them love
reading,'' Stine says. ``It's worked very well. The millions of
books I've sold means that millions of kids are reading.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who work with kids agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``R.L. Stine was an immediate hit with boys,'' says Lisa Loftin,
a children's librarian for the Dayton and Montgomery County Public
Library. ``Until `Goosebumps,' most series targeted girls. These
appealed to boys and their delight in the scary and weird. And
series do encourage children to read.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The books I write have to be fantasies. The real world is a
pretty scary place for kids,'' Stine says. ``There are a lot of
twists and turns in my stories and they're very creepy but they
always have a happy ending. What's too scary is something that is
too real.''
</P>
<P>
   His new book, ``Nightmare House,'' includes 10 stories, each
illustrated by a different artist.
</P>
<P>
   He still incorporates humor in his books. ``Kids,'' he
believes,'' love to laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Scieszka, who arrives this evening and was an elementary school
teacher for many years, couldn't agree more. It's his wacky sense
of humor that appeals to kids _ and their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a wonderful sense of the fun and ridiculous, and
communicates it very well,'' says Loftin. ``Like everything else in
children, a sense of humor has to mature, and fractured fairy tales
are among the first jokes that kids ``get''.
</P>
<P>
   Scieszka (it rhymes with Fresca) says most humor is ``messing
around with your perception of the way the world is put together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what kids are doing all the time so they love to play
around with it,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   The books he produces with best friend, illustrator Lane Smith,
are funny in the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our books play around with the conventions of being books. We
mess up the way things should be: The dedication page is upside
down, we mess up the title page, the narrator.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The True Story of the 3 Little Pigs,'' for example, the
story is told from the wolf's perspective. The book has just been
rereleased in a 10th anniversary edition.
</P>
<P>
   Scieszka, 45, grew up in Flint, Mich., with five brothers (he
says he's the second-oldest and the nicest), and thought about
being a writer ever since his mom first read him Dr. Seuss' ``Green
Eggs and Ham'' and Ruth Krauss' ``The Carrot Seed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's All Greek To Me'' (Viking, $13.99) is the newest in the
Scieszka/Smith Time Warp Trio books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought time travel was kind of corny, but I love
history and that made me think: What if you could walk around with
King Arthur or hang out with Blackbeard?'' Scieszka says. ``Lately
we've expanded that notion to ask what it would be like to go into
one of your favorite books and meet up with Winnie the Pooh or the
Headless Horseman?''
</P>
<P>
   The Time Warp books will be turned into an animated television
series by WGBH-TV in Boston in 2001. ``It's All Greek to Me'' ends
with a list of Greek gods and goddesses and instructions for making
Orpheus's lyre or Zeus' thunderbolt (``1. Cut cardboard into the
shape of a thunderbolt. 2) Cover with aluminum foil. 3) Destroy all
monsters. Amaze your friends.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Having been a teacher, I take every opportunity to provide the
knowledge, but I try not to lecture them with it or make it so holy
they run away screaming,'' concludes Scieszka. ``Lane and I try to
reward the reader for looking closer and questioning.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
