<P>
   (NY-KLAN-SUIT replaces CHILD-CARE; adds RUSSIA-CHECHNYA) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, Oct. 22. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   GORE-ENVIRON (Rye, N.H.) _ In the most dramatic proposal of his
candidacy, Vice President Al Gore says that as president he would
ban any new offshore drilling for oil and gas along the California
and Florida coasts. Gore's proposal would apply to companies that
have already bought billions of dollars worth of leases and not
drilled yet. By Katharine Q. Seelye. (The story has moved in ``p''
news file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   The story runs next to a 3-column politics photo layout.
</P>
<P>
   reefer to: BRADLEY-POVERTY (Undated) _ Describing poverty as a
``slow motion national disaster,'' former Sen. Bill Bradley calls
for reducing the number of poor children by half over the coming
decade by raising the minimum wage, increasing spending on child
care programs and providing an array of tax benefits to poor
parents who work. By James Dao. (The story has moved in ``p'' news
file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead stories:
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-POLITICS (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ The day after voting
down her bid for the presidency, the national assembly elects
Megawati Sukarnoputri, a popular leader of the opposition to the
ousted Suharto regime, to the post of vice president. By Seth
Mydans. (The story has moved in ``a'' news file.) 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ALZHEIMER (Undated) _ New findings on brain development open
up possibilities for treating Alzheimer's. By Gina Kolata. (The
story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BIOGRAPHY (Washington) _ St. Martin's Press is withdrawing
a new biography of George W. Bush after questions about the book's
allegations of his drug use lead to the discovery that the author
is a convicted felon. By Frank Bruni. (The story has moved in ``p''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-KLAN-SUIT (New York) _ A federal court rules that the Ku Klux
Klan must be allowed to demonstrate in lower Manhattan this
weekend, saying that the Giuliani administration has violated the
group's First Amendment rights by refusing to permit the rally if
Klan members wore their traditional masks. By Benjamin Weiser.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DAIRY-FARMS (Chino, Calif.) _ As suburban sprawl once
again forces dairy farms to move beyond Los Angeles, one of the
striking things is that, just as happened in the move from Los
Angeles County several decades ago, a big increase in farmers' land
values is financing a transition that will result in a new
generation of highly efficient dairies that will only widen
California's lead over Wisconsin. By James Sterngold. (The story
has moved in ``a'' news file.) 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN-WEB (Undated) _ The launch of Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter's new online stock trading service was not as easy as
planned, and one reason involves a tangled tale of either youthful
innocence or cybersquatting. By Patrick McGeehan and Matt Richtel.
(The story has moved in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORY PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House, in a rare display of
bipartisanship, votes overwhelmingly to renew for five years the
largest federal program to help educate poor children. By Eric
Schmitt. (The story has moved in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ At least 10 bombs devastate a
downtown market and maternity hospital in Grozny, Chechnya,
according to reports from the breakaway Russian republic. The
explosions killed scores of people and injured hundreds more. By
Michael Wines. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
</TEXT>
