<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Thurssday, 10/21/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) GLENVILLE, N.Y. -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- SOUTHPOLE-RESCUER,
10-21 -- At the Stratton Air National Guard Base in Glenville, Col.
Ed Fleming of the 109th Airlift Wing stands on the tarmac in front
of an LC130, the type of aircraft used in the rescue of a woman
with a lump in her breast who was stuck at the South Pole. ``You
never allow a rescue to become an accounting exercise,'' says
Fleming, 51, whose resume lists ``300 Lives saved.'' (David
Jennings/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) CHICAGO -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24 --
BIZ-PROFILE-ROWE, 10-21 -- John W. Rowe, chairman and chief
executive of Commonwealth Edison, with a 2,600-year-old Egyptian
mummy casket in his Chicago office. In an industry best known for
its colorless, mealy-mouthed chief executives, Rowe has made
himself visible by wielding a blunt stick, and an even blunter
tongue. ``If everything had been nice and tidy at Com Ed I wouldn't
have gotten the job,'' he says. (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) CHINO, Calif. -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- CALIF-DAIRY-FARMS-2,
10-21 -- Gennie and Fred DeBoer plan to sell their 200-acre farm in
Chino and move their herd of 2,000 cows to a farm 180 miles to the
north. The DeBoers have become part of yet another exodus of a big
portion of the state's dairies, like factories on wheels whose
machines happen to be hulking black and white animals. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) CHINO, Calif. -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- CALIF-DAIRY-FARMS-1,
10-21 -- The spread of subdivisions in Chino is forcing many
farmers to leave, but it is also injecting new vitality into the
dairy industry. Farmers are selling valuable tracts to finance
larger operations elsewhere. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) POOLEY ISLAND, British Columbia -- Oct. 21, 1999 --
CANADA-FOREST, 10-21 -- A contractor removing old western red
cedars from Pooley Island, part of an area that environmentalists
are calling ``the Brazil of the north'' - a vast, barely disturbed
sea of trees, one quarter of the world's remaining temperate
rainforest. Over the next 25 years, 50 of the coastal forest's
largest valleys are scheduled be logged. (James Brooke/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) HILLSBOROUGH, Calif. -- Oct. 21, 1999 --
MORGAN-ONLINE-TEEN, 10-21 -- Ivan Wong, 17, at home with his
mountain bikes. Morgan Stanley filed suit in United States District
Court in Manhattan, contending that Wong's Web site, featuring
mountain bikes, infringes on the firm's trademarks by using its
letters as part of the domain name. From a distance, it seems that
Wong stumbled into the path of a profit-seeking juggernaut. However
it turns out that a company set up by Wong's father has registered
dozens of domain names, many of them derived from the names of
investment banks. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) MAITLAND, Fla. -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT.
24 -- TRAVEL-PLANNING, 10-21 -- Randy Warren, left, the chairman of
Global Travel International, and Michael Gross, its president, at
the company's offices in Maitland. ``Who's to say who's a travel
agent and who isn't, when there are no requirements for becoming
one?'' says Warren, whose company will give travel agent
credentials to anyone 18 or older who is willing to pay a fee.
(Todd Anderson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) ATLANTA -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- BUSH-BIOGRAPHY-2, 10-21 --
St. Martin's Press suspended distribution and promotion of this new
biography of Gov. George Bush of Texas, ``Fortunate Son: George W.
Bush and the Making of an American President,'' by J.H. Hatfield,
after questions about the book's allegations of Bush's drug use led
to the discovery that the author is a convicted felon. (Andy
Sharp/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Oct. 21, 1999 - SUB-SATURDAY-THEATER-REVIEW,
10-21 -- James Carpinello as Tony Manero in ``Saturday Night Fever:
The Musical.'' Your tappable feet and snappable fingers stay
alarmingly still during the adaptation of the 1977 movie hit. And
there arises an ominous feeling that any nostalgia on offer here is
not of the wet, warm, embracing kind but more of the freeze-dried
variety. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- BBO-YANKS-2, 10-21 -
Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter during a practice session on Thursday
at Yankee Stadium. The Yankees face the Atlanta Braves on Saturday
in Game 1 of the World Series. (Mary DiBiase Blaich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- BBO-YANKS, 10-21 - Yankees
pitcher Orlando Hernandez during a practice session on Thursday at
Yankee Stadium. Hernandez, who was named the American League
Championship's Most Valuable Player, will pitch against the Atlanta
Braves on Saturday in Game 1 of the World Series. (Mary DiBiase
Blaich/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) LOS ANGELES -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- ZAPOTEC-SCHOLAR, 10-21
-- Felipe Lopez, 37, outside UCLA where he is pursuing a doctorate.
Lopez, a Zapotec Indian, immigrated to the U.S. from Oaxaca,
Mexicio, 21 years ago in the trunk of a smuggler's car. Lopez, who
barely got through the 6th grade in his home village, has helped
author the Zapotec-English-Spanish dictionary that has charted new
ground in the study of Mexico's indigenous languages. (Edward
Carreon/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- BUSH-BIOGRAPHY, 10-21 -- A
portrait of Gov. George Bush of Texas during a visit to Atlanta in
late August. St. Martin's Press is withdrawing a new biography of
Bush after questions about the book's allegations of his drug use
lead to the discovery that the author is a convicted felon. (Andy
Sharp/Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- BANKS-GRAMM, 10-21 -- The
22-year-old Community Reinvestment Act, which encourages banks to
make loans in low- and middle-income neighborhoods, has been the
most contentious battleground in a stalemate over how to overhaul
the nation's banking laws. Critics led by Phil Gramm, the chairman
of the Senate Banking Committee, want to strip the law of some of
its teeth, arguing that it imposes unfair regulatory burdens on
banks. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) BETHLEHEM, Pa. -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- FBC-LEHIGH-JEAN-2,
10-21 -- What's more impressive about 22-year-old Ronald Jean - his
435-pound bench press, a 40 yard dash time of 4.38 seconds, his 766
rushing yards and 15 touchdowns for the 6-0 Lehigh University
Mountain Hawks? Or that a child whose mother abused and abandoned
him, who was shuttled through foster homes, will graduate in May
from Lehigh with a degree in psychology? (Tim Shaffer/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) BETHLEHEM, Pa. -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- FBC-LEHIGH-JEAN-1,
10-21 -- At 13, Ronald Jean was abandoned by his mother at a
Greyhound bus station. Though he was never adopted, the 5-4,
187-pound 22-year-old has found a home here in the mountains of
Eastern Pennsylvania at Lehigh University. And, as a senior running
back, he has grown into a professional football prospect, albeit a
longshot, whose strength and determination can't be measured by
just dumbbells and stop watches. (Tim Shaffer/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 21, 1999 - CLINTON-CRIME, 10-21 --
Rep. Bart Stupak, D-Mich., leans over towards President Bill
Clinton, while the latter reads over his presidential statement
prior to delivering a speech honoring top cops from all over the
country. The White House, angry that Congress cut its budget
request for community police officers by more than $1 billion,
accused Republicans Thursday of putting more guns and fewer police
on the streets.(Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) LONG BEACH, Calif. -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
OCT. 24 --BIZ-POLLY-COFFEE, 10-21 -- Bob Phibbs, left, who helps
independent businesses cope with chain-store competitors, talks
with Michael Sheldrake of Polly's Gourmet Coffee. ``The problem
with a chain is that it's like a mall: it's all mechanical, and
there's no relationship with the customers,'' says Phibbs, 41. ``I
think people are getting sick of the mega-stores.'' (Kim Kulish/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- THEATER-NOTES, 10-21 --
Starting in January, David Campbell is to lead the cast of
``Saturday Night,'' the early Stephen Sondheim musical making its
New York premiere at Second Stage. In the last three years,
Campbell, 26, has released two solo CDs, won a handful of cabaret
awards and has been named Young Australian of the Year. But most of
his performing has been done alone. ``It's going to be good to be
able to play with others,'' he says. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24 --
ABOUT-CARS-MULTIPLA/KA-1, 10-21 -- The short, maneuverable Ford Ka
nests in gaps that other cars pass up. The Ka was among the
futuristic cars on display in a recent exhibition at the Museum of
Modern Art entitled ``Different Roads: Automobiles for the Next
Century,'' which attracted large crowds before it closed last
month. (Richard L. Harbus/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
OCT. 24 --INVEST-WITH-RUBIN, 10-21 -- As chief investment officer
and co-chairman of Resurgence Asset Management, James B. Rubin
specializes in distressed companies. Is vulture investing worth the
trouble? ``I can by a dollar's worth of assets for 25 cents,'' he
says. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24 --
ABOUT-CARS-MULTIPLA/KA-2, 10-21 -- The Ford Ka's interior is bright
and functional, though some of the materials feel cheap. Though the
Ka has become relatively common on the streets of Europe and Latin
America, it is not destined to be sold here, where the faint demand
for such small, fuel-efficient and unusual-looking vehicles won't
likely justify the cost of adapting their designs to meet American
crash and emissions standards. (Richard L. Harbus/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 24 --
OPEC-CARTEL, 10-21 -- Left for dead two years ago, the oil cartel
is back, in a new, potentially more powerful form. But the world's
oil-producing and exporting nations are wielding power this time
around mainly because of a shove not from the Middle East but from
Mexico - and especially from its persistent energy minister, Luis
K. Tellez, a novice in the world of oil. (Fred R. Conrad/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- FUTURE-CARS-3, 10-21 -- The
Lacrosse luxury sedan, which will be displayed at the Detroit show
in January, blends a futuristic look with traditional Buick
touches, including stylized portholes on the fenders. But it also
has a pickup bed under a rear hatch. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- FUTURE-CARS-2, 10-21 --
Intended to be an affordable sports car with extra room and
practicality, the Pontiac Piranha has a mini-pickup bed under a
rear hatch that pulls out for loading items like skis. The mesh
seats can be removed and taken to the beach. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- FUTURE-CARS-1, 10-21 -- GM
hopes that the Chevrolet SSR, a hybrid of sports convertible and
pickup, will be a show-stopper at the Detroit Show in January. With
its prominent fender flares, the styling evokes Chevy pickups of
the '40s and '50s. Inside, the SSR has a divided cockpit like those
of early Corvettes, but there is space in the center for a third
person or a child seat. A retractable power top drops behind the
seats for open-air motoring. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BEIJING -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- CHINA-CHRISTIANS, 10-21 --
Gou Qinghui with her 18-month old baby boy Xiao Xuya. Ms. Gou, 37
and a devout Christian, says she is pretty certain why she was not
given a birth certificate for her son following his birth. Since
she was removed from her teaching post at the government-controlled
Yanjing Theological Seminary in 1994, she has thrown herself into
the illegal ``house church'' movement -- Protestants who worship in
homes and other locations, rejecting the authority of the official
church. Ms. Gou says was recently threatened with arrest for her
religious work.(New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) LOS ANGELES -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- ZAPOTEC-SCHOLAR, 10-21 --
Felipe Lopez, 37, outside UCLA where he is pursuing a doctorate.
Lopez, a Zapotec Indian, immigrated to the U.S. from Oaxaca,
Mexicio, 21 years ago in the trunk of a smuggler's car. Lopez, who
barely got through the 6th grade in his home village, has helped
author the Zapotec-English-Spanish dictionary that has charted new
ground in the study of Mexico's indigenous languages. (Ted
Soqui/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- ABORTION CONGRESS, 10-21
-- Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, meets with his colleague, Barbara
Boxer, D-Calif., on Thursday. A narrow majority of the Senate
voiced support on Thursday for the 1973 Supreme Court decision to
legalize abortion. The vote, sponsored by Harkin, was non-binding,
but supporters said it would be used in the 2000 elections against
senators who voted the other way. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 21, 1999 - CLINTON-MANDELA, 10-21 --
President Clinton and former South African President Nelson Mandela
after their meeting in the Oval Office of the White House on
Thursday. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- BANKS-CONGRESS, 10-21 --
Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala, left, confers with an aide while
sitting next to Senate Banking Committee Chairman Phil Gramm,
R-Texas, before the start of hearings on banking reform, Thursday.
The conference committee is putting the final touches on a bill
overhauling the nation's financial system. (Stephen Crowley/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 21, 1999 - CLINTON-MANDELA, 10-21 --
President Clinton and former South African President Nelson Mandela
pose for photographers before their meeting in the Oval Office of
the White House on Thursday.(Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WATERLOO, N.Y. -- Oct. 21, 1999 --
WOMENS-RIGHTS-WEEKEND-3, 10-21 -- The Jane Hunt house in Upstate
New York. Hunt, a women's rights advocate of the mid-19th century,
was instrumental in convening the first Women's Rights Convention
in 1848. (Elisabeth Bumiller/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) AUBURN, N.Y. -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- WOMENS-RIGHTS-WEEKEND-2,
10-21 -- The farmhouse of the abolitionist and former slave Harriet
Tubman. Tubman moved to this home in 1857 after leading hundreds of
slaves to new lives on the Underground Railroad. (Elisabeth
Bumiller/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SENECA FALLS, N.Y. -- Oct. 21, 1999 --
WOMENS-RIGHTS-WEEKEND-1, 10-21 -- The home of the suffragist
Elizabeth Cady Stanton. Stanton's house is a light and relatively
airy white clapboard farm house, with elements of modified Greek
Revival style. (Elisabeth Bumiller/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Oct. 21, 1999 -- MET-ANCIENT-NEAR-EAST, 10-21
-- A section of the splendidly revamped ancient Near Eastern
galleries at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. More than 8,000 years'
worth of art has been coaxed into a semblance of historical logic.
(Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
