<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4552 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COKE-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      10-21 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COCA-COLA EARNINGS SLID 11.4% IN QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a performance that indicated improving sales but not better
profits, Coca-Cola Co. said Thursday that its third-quarter
earnings fell 11.4 percent but that revenue rose 9.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported net income of $787 million, or 32 cents a
diluted share, compared with $888 million, or 36 cents a share, in
the quarter a year earlier. That quarter, plagued by volume
declines stemming from the Russian economic crisis, continued
sluggishness in Japan and other disappointments around the globe,
was the start of a decline that the soft-drink giant has struggled
to reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected Coca-Cola to earn 32 cents a share,
according to First Call/Thomson Financial, which tracks company
earnings. In September, Coke said its earnings would drop to 33
cents a share or less, thus failing to meet the estimates of 36
cents at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose 9 percent, to $5.2 billion, the company said. At
the same time, costs rose, including a 16 percent jump in Coke's
selling, administrative and general expenses. Part of that increase
came from efforts to market products in Europe after a recall there
in June that was the biggest in the company's history.
</P>
<P>
   The effect on after-tax earnings in the quarter was 2 to 3 cents
a share. Second-quarter earnings also lost 2 to 3 cents a share
because of the recall.
</P>
<P>
   Volume worldwide, measured in cases sold, rose 3.5 percent,
though about one point of that growth came from Cadbury Schweppes
brands that Coke acquired in July. The company had forecast an
increase of 2 percent, so its volume results were slightly better
than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had awaited this particular earnings report eagerly to
determine if Coca-Cola's fortunes had begun to improve; on
Thursday, they had mixed reactions. ``These aren't exactly heroic
numbers, but they sure look better than the first half of the
year,'' said Jennifer Solomon, an analyst for Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Branca, an analyst at Lehman Brothers, said, ``It's the
fifth consecutive quarter of lower operating profits at Coke, and
that certainly suggests that things have not yet begun to turn.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the company's chairman and chief executive, M.
Douglas Ivester, said: ``This past year has not been what the
company's share owners or its management, most especially me, want
or expect. Both our volume and profit results and our stock price
have disappointed us all, even recognizing the difficult
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, that he was ``optimistic about the long-term
outlook for the global economy, and thus our ability to deliver on
our stated long-term volume and earnings objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Share of Coca-Cola rose $1.5625 on Thursday, to $54.3125.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, where Coke bottlers, like their rivals at
Pepsi, raised prices at the retail level earlier this year, volume
rose 2 percent, compared with 4 percent in the period a year
earlier. But concentrate shipments fell 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Japan provided a surprising 10 percent increase in volume, the
first rise in several quarters. The company attributed the
improvement to a variety of factors, including its marketing,
vending acquisitions, an introduction of a new half-liter plastic
bottle and the ``slightly improving economic conditions,'' as well
as the growth from Cadbury brands.
</P>
<P>
   Volume also rose 10 percent in Germany, another big Coca-Cola
market. ``Germany benefited from a very strong month of September
resulting from integrated media and marketing programs focused on
building long-term brand equity of both Coca-Cola and Fanta,'' the
company said in its statement.
</P>
<P>
   Currency exchange rates cost the company 6 percent in earnings.
And equity income, or the income Coke derives from investments in
its bottlers, was just $11 million, compared with $51 million in
the third quarter a year ago. In the last nine months, equity loss
has totaled $72 million, in contrast to income of $103 million in
the same period last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
