<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4557 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-21 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LESSON FROM UNLIKELY SOURCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was just after noon and three men stood near
second base, fielding ground balls. I didn't travel to Yankee
Stadium to see them, but as I watched them throw Thursday, I found
myself playing a game of word association.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Derek Jeter: Graceful.
</P>
<P>
   Comedian Billy Crystal: Funny.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Chuck Knoblauch: Duck. Survive. Run, fool. Now.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I didn't come here to make fun of Knoblauch. For once,
he looked at ease as he threw with Jeter and Crystal (who is a
friend of Joe Torre's). If I could make it so fans weren't required
to wear fatigues and helmets when Knoblauch throws, I would do it.
That's my mission. To make things right. That's why I'm here,
trying to determine, finally, if the Red Sox should be here, too.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, the Yankees flew to Atlanta for Game 1 of the
World Series. They were supposed to be here, playing Game 7 of the
American League Championship Series with the Red Sox. Everyone
knows that. I was reading the paper the other day and saw that some
scrub wrote, ``I'll be in the Bronx'' to see Roger Clemens-Pedro
Martinez II. Many Sox fans still say the umpires took the series
away from them. Nomar Garciaparra refused to say the Yankees are
the better team. Dan Duquette said if the Sox had caught the ball,
they'd still be playing.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with these people?
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a point,'' said Jim Leyritz, a current Yankee and
former Sox. ``When I played for the Padres, we said the same thing
when the Yankees swept us in (last year's) World Series. If we
hadn't made a couple mistakes, they wouldn't have swept us. Boston
was right there in a couple of those games.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's not good enough. There are some New Englanders who
still can't recall anything from November 1986 because they haven't
gotten over what happened a month earlier. We can't have that now.
We must find the truth. We are going to do one of Torre's favorite
things: we are going to tinker and speculate.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, baseball is second-guessing,'' Torre said Thursday.
``Not only with the media, but with the fans.'' The Yankee manager
explained that everyone believes they have the ability to manage,
and that makes guesswork even more intense.
</P>
<P>
   So let's put justice in motion.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1, Rick Reed makes the correct call in the 10th inning.
Jose Offerman is safe at second base. Eventually there is a
showdown between Garciaparra and Mariano Rivera, who hasn't been
scored on since July. Torre loves to play games of managerial
chess, but when Rivera is in the game, he said Thursday, ``The
managing stops.'' That's how good Rivera is. He has a cut fastball
that, according to the Sox' Mike Stanley, ``you can only hope to
pop it up'' when the thing is working.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, Garciaparra breaks open a 3-3 game by pulling a
high cutter down the left-field line. The Yankees are so shocked
that they react slowly, so Offerman scores easily and John Valentin
scores _ unexpectedly _ from first. The Sox lead, 5-3. Rod Beck
allows a leadoff homer to Bernie Williams in the bottom of the
inning. (Sorry, some things I just can't change. Did you see that
fastball?) After some sweating, Sox win, 5-4. They lead the series,
1-0. A few thousand Yankees dissidents chant, ``Nomar's Better.''
</P>
<P>
   The next night, the Sox get a brilliant pitching performance
from Ramon Martinez, but waste it by stranding 13 runners. Jason
Varitek and Troy O'Leary just miss home runs. The series is tied,
1-1.
</P>
<P>
   After an off day, Pedro and Roger are ready for their matchup in
Boston. Most of the pregame hype reminds you of boxing. It's
fitting, because the only way Clemens would have won is if shady
boxing judge Eugenia Williams declared him the champion. The Sox
win, 13-1. They lead the series, 2-1. Clemens pitched only two
innings and allowed five runs. Torre says afterward that he will
not change his rotation and plans to go with Clemens if there is a
Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   (Note: Astute baseball fans will see that there is a lie in the
previous paragraph, a lie that will change the series. Here's a
hint: Earlier, Torre said that he ``would never'' take Knoblauch
out of the game for a defensive replacement. In Game 5 he took
Knoblauch, who had 26 errors in the regular season, out of the game
for a defensive replacement. If you double-talk like that on a
baseball field, you're Manager of the Year. If you double-talk like
that with your spouse, you're paying alimony.)
</P>
<P>
   After Game 4, fans and sportscasters offer to buy Tim Tschida a
drink. There are articles in both Boston newspapers about the good
umpires, the ones you don't hear about because of the bombastic
Richie Phillips. Tschida is praised because he made a tough _ and
correct _ call at second involving Offerman. Remarkably, the
Yankees pitch to Garciaparra with first base open and he hits a
two-run homer to put the Sox ahead, 4-3, the eventual final.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-1 Sox lead and a Game 5 shocker: Clemens starts against Kent
Mercker. He doesn't look great, but he goes seven, gives the Yankee
starters an extra day of rest and, most important, wins.
</P>
<P>
   Game 6: Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez over Ramon Martinez in a
well-played, 3-2 game.
</P>
<P>
   And then there would have been Thursday night. Pedro vs. either
David Cone or Andy Pettitte, working on three days rest. It's hard
to go against the best pitcher in baseball. But it's also hard to
go against a team with two World Series titles in the past three
years.
</P>
<P>
   It's funny, in the last few days many Sox fans have done to the
Yankees what they accuse others of doing to their team. They have
dismissed them, saying they are really not that good. Truth is, the
Yankees handle the basics so well that they should wear khakis
instead of pinstripes. When you handle details like that, it's hard
for bad umpiring to send you home.
</P>
<P>
   I guess I had to come to the Bronx to figure that out. Sometimes
you get lessons from the most unlikely sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the two best teams are playing right now,'' a tall man
observed Thursday. The man's name is Darryl Strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   Never thought I'd say this, but Darryl Strawberry is right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
