<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4559 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-STOCK-OWNERSHIP-ART-N     10-21 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCK-OWNERSHIP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY SAYS 78.7 MILLION OWN STOCKS IN UNITED STATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The number of stock owners in the nation soared to 78.7 million
people early this year, 85 percent more than in 1983 when the long
bull market was getting under way.
</P>
<P>
   Among households, 48.2 percent now own stock directly or through
mutual funds, more than double the 19 percent with such a stake in
1983, according to a survey by Investment Company Institute and the
Securities Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the increased interest in stock investing, a majority of
stockholders said they neither bought nor sold any securities last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nearly one in two households own equities today, and the vast
majority of these investors have a buy-and-hold investment
strategy,'' said Marc Lackritz, president of the securities
association.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, based on 4,842 responses of randomly selected
households in January and February, show just how much Americans
are relying on stocks to reach retirement and other financial
goals.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, which described stock ownership by income, assets,
location, sex and ethnic group, also found that investors who were
trading online in 1998 were considerably more affluent than people
who were trading the old-fashioned way through a broker. This
highly desirable group is the target of the big brokerage firms,
which are rushing to provide online service to compete with online
discount brokers.
</P>
<P>
   The report uses for comparison stock ownership figures for 1983
that were published by the New York Stock Exchange. While the
portion of stock owners has grown 85 percent in that time, the
population has grown far more slowly, 15.6 percent, between 1983
and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, The New York Times calculated that American
households had more assets invested in stocks than at any time in
at least half a century and had more value in stocks than in their
homes for the first time since the 1960s, based on an analysis of
Federal Reserve data.
</P>
<P>
   The survey released Thursday by the two trade associations found
that the typical stockholder is 47 and lives in a household with
annual income of $60,000 and total assets of $85,000. Most are
married college graduates; 53 percent have individual retirement
accounts and 80 percent have employer-sponsored pension plans.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more striking findings was how many stock fund
investors have multiple accounts. Twenty-two percent of people with
stock mutual funds own shares in seven or more stock funds, and 26
percent own four to six funds, suggesting they may have taken
diversification a little too far and created bookkeeping headaches
as well. Nineteen percent of fund investors hold just one fund, the
same percentage as hold two funds.
</P>
<P>
   Not at all surprising, however, was that holdings in stocks and
stock funds rise with age and household income. Median holdings of
those with incomes of $150,000 or more were $150,000, while those
earning less than $50,000 had holdings worth $20,000. The median is
the point where half a given group lies on one side, half on the
other.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that most stockholders had some seasoning,
though not necessarily by suffering through a real bear market.
Fifty-four percent bought their first stock before 1990, 28 percent
made their initial purchase during the first half of the decade and
only 18 percent jumped into equities since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have suggested that newcomers, despite telling
pollsters they were investing for the long haul, will panic and
bail out in a downturn.
</P>
<P>
   And although many of the newcomers have traded actively, some
quite visibly for very short periods, only 45 percent of all
stockholders did any buying or selling during 1998 and of these,
buyers outnumbered sellers three to two, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
   Only 11 percent of stock trades were over the Internet, though
this share undoubtedly rose as electronic investing became
progressively easier and cheaper as the year progressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The typical owner of equities is not a trader,'' said John
Rea, research director at the Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat surprisingly, the survey found that the South, not the
Northeast, has the biggest concentration of stock investors.
Thirty-three percent of stockholders live in the South, 26 percent
in the Midwest, 25 percent in the West and 16 percent in the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although fewest in number, Northeastern equity owners tend to
be older, have more household financial assets and have a greater
ownership rate for individual stocks outside retirement plans than
other equity owners,'' the researchers concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Decisions to buy stocks are shared in 54 percent of households,
but men make them in 26 percent of households and women in 20
percent. Men are more likely than women or joint decision makers to
own individual stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, 85 percent of stock-owning households own stock mutual
funds while only 54 percent own stocks directly, with 47 percent
owning only funds and 15 only individual stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The stock-owning population is 90 percent white, 5 percent
black, 2 percent Asian, 5 percent Hispanic and 2 percent ``other,''
the overlap reflecting the fact that Hispanic people can be of any
race. Black investors favor funds over individual stocks, Asians
the reverse.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that 48 percent of stockholders are baby
boomers, 28 percent are from the 55-to-74 age group, 19 percent are
members of Generation X _ the most aggressive investors in that a
greater portion of their portfolios are in equities _ and 5 percent
are 75 or older.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
