<SLUG> BC-CONSULTING-FIRMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSULTING FIRMS OFFER EXTRA PERKS TO KEEP TALENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)   (dal) 
 By DAVID LEONHARDT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Help wanted: prestigious firms, already offering six-figure
salaries, will now let employees take up to two months off each
year or get special access to Internet investment funds.
</P>
<P>
   This in essence is what the world's top consulting firms are
resorting to as they battle the E-commerce tide that is stealing
many of their best job candidates and employees, from college
campuses and even the corner office. In a range of initiatives just
under way, the firms are trying to hire and keep people by
emphasizing the advantages of a secure job while also replicating
some of the perquisites of a start-up.
</P>
<P>
   McKinsey &AMP; Co., which for years has had its pick of
business-school graduates, has decided to offer its associates
access to Internet start-up investments designed to mimic the
growth potential of stock in a new business. Among other options,
the plan could include letting the junior consultants buy stakes in
investment funds, possibly including venture-capital funds, that
would not normally be open to them, or buy stakes in a pool of
McKinsey clients that have given the firm equity instead of paying
cash, said Anil Kumar, a McKinsey director and one of the leaders
of (AT)McKinsey, its E-commerce practice. Details will be finalized
within two months, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mercer Management Consulting, meanwhile, is telling consultants
this week about new work rules under which Mercer will help them to
design a new business plan, and even leave the firm to launch it.
The rules will also allow consultants to take off up to two months
each year, to do anything from enrolling in a class to going
mountain climbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, it's been all the major consulting firms and all
the major investment banks going after the best and brightest,''
said Jim Down, vice chairman of Mercer. Now that E-commerce firms
have joined the fray, Down said, ``we certainly have lost some very
good people.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, turnover rates have risen at many large consulting
firms, including McKinsey. In September, George T. Shaheen, chief
executive of Andersen Consulting, the industry's largest firm, quit
to head up tiny Webvan Group, an Internet grocery in Foster City,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the firms are having to work much harder to
woo MBA's who now consider their heroes to be Amazon.com founder
Jeffrey Bezos and Yahoo co-founder Jerry Yang more so than titans
such as Jack Welch or Warren E. Buffet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost seems like it's the new gold rush,'' said Douglas
McCracken, managing director of the Americas for Deloitte
Consulting, which this week began an advertising campaign to
promote its month-old E-business unit, ``where everyone is going to
dot-com's expecting to get stock and get rich.''
</P>
<P>
   The new initiatives indicate just how attractive the start-ups
have become. Consultants for years have prided themselves on their
workaholic schedules, boasting about 14-hour days in far-away
cities. Now, to keep employees happy, Mercer is telling people to
take long vacations, with benefits but not pay, if they feel like
it.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Mercer is saying to employees who are interested in
one day starting their own company that it will help them plan, put
them in touch with venture capital firms, and perhaps even invest
in the business itself. The firm will also set up some consultants
with ``externships,'' one- or two-year assignments in outside
companies from which they conceivably might not return. ``It's a
big, big change,'' Down said.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, McKinsey was long extremely wary of accepting
equity in any of its clients, lest it find itself so tied to one
company that a rival would not hire the firm for a different
assignment. Even as Bain &AMP; Co. made big profits after starting Bain
Capital, a private equity firm, in 1984, McKinsey partners shunned
such a move, concerned it could call their independence into
question. Bain says its two units do not share information.
</P>
<P>
   But for the past 18 months, McKinsey has accepted small stakes
in start-up companies that could not otherwise afford its fees.
That gives it an entree into the Internet world and makes it more
attractive to MBA's, Kumar said. Now the firm is considering
allowing its own associates to invest blindly in those equity
stakes. ``We don't want the best talent to feel they don't have a
vehicle to join in this wealth creation,'' Kumar said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Webber, a former McKinsey consultant and now president of
Aurora Advisors Inc., a New York firm, said, ``For McKinsey, these
are very radical moves.''
</P>
<P>
   The investments, even if blind, raise the prospect of
conflict-of-interest problems because consultants would assume that
the firm, and perhaps even them individually, owned a piece of any
start-up for which it had done work. That in turn could make rival
start-ups uncomfortable about hiring McKinsey.
</P>
<P>
   Kumar said McKinsey was taking only small stakes in other
companies and that it planned to sell its shares as soon as
financially prudent. He also said consultants would not know which
start-ups they owned a piece of. ``We want to adhere to the highest
standards of professionalism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all of the other major consulting firms also accept
equity stakes from small companies that lack the cash to pay the
industry's high fees.
</P>
<P>
   The firms hope that having a significant E-commerce practice
will allow them to hire and keep people who are interested in
technology and may one day decide to join a start-up.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Overton is the kind of candidate the firms are hoping to
woo. A 28-year-old student at Columbia Business School, she worked
for a high-tech investment firm before going back to school and
then spent last summer at an Internet company. Now she is applying
to Bain and McKinsey, while also trying to launch her own
E-commerce business and talking to other start-ups, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always understood that the best students would want to
go to consulting, and there was no serious competitive industry,''
said Ms. Overton. Today, however, ``everyone is getting completely
intoxicated'' thinking about the Internet, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is particularly evident at Harvard Business School,
where a single graduating class of 800 once included more than 300
consultants. In 1996, 35 percent of MBA's took such a job, compared
to just 16 percent who went into high technology or venture
capital, the school said. Last spring, the portion going into the
new fields doubled, to 32 percent, while the share of consultants
dipped to 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the recruiting and retention battles should be kept
in perspective. Consulting is still the most popular job for
graduates of the top MBA programs, and the firms are growing,
causing them to hire more people than in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   Attrition ``has been rising, and it's related to e-commerce,''
Mercer's Down said. ``But we're not devastated or panicking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
