<HEADER>
A4563 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-ABORTION-CONGRESS-ART     10-21 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-CONGRESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE VOTES TO BAN A CONTROVERSIAL ABORTION PROCEDURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Ill., Maine, Calif., Iowa, Neb., Ark.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate voted 63-34 Thursday to ban a particular
kind of abortion procedure that its opponents call ``partial
birth,'' but fell slightly short of the votes that would be needed
to override President Clinton's expected veto.
</P>
<P>
   The passionate debate on the issue _ with graphic charts,
wrenching anecdotes and flashes of anger and emotion _ has become a
familiar Senate ritual, enacted many times since 1995. But the
Senate action was being closely watched as the first test of
strength on the divisive social and political issue in the 106th
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's supporters had once hoped that last November's
elections would bring them the extra votes to prevail. But
Thursday's vote for the ban indicated _ if several absent senators
do not change their stands _ that its advocates had picked up only
one supporter since last year and would have 65 votes for an
eventual override. That is two votes shy of the 67 that would be
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-nine Republicans and 14 Democrats voted for the ban, while
31 Democrats and three Republicans voted against it. Three senators
were absent.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would outlaw a kind of abortion in which, according to
the bill's supporters, a fetus is partially delivered feet first.
An instrument is then inserted in the skull and the brain is
removed before the fetus is fully removed. The procedure is used in
the second and third trimester.
</P>
<P>
   Since the ban first passed in 1995 and was vetoed by Clinton,
abortion opponents have found that their focus on this particular
procedure has been a successful political strategy for advancing
their cause.
</P>
<P>
   Various types of ``partial birth abortion'' bans have been
enacted in up to 30 states. But lower courts in two-thirds of those
states have either struck down the law or limited its
implementation. The issue is widely expected to reach the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, in a statement, said that the bill ``contains
the same serious flaws'' as past measures and that Clinton will
veto it once again. The president has objected in the past that the
measure does not contain an exception to protect a woman's health.
The bill's advocates argue that such an abortion is never medically
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., led the fight for the ban. He said
this type of abortion ``is not like abortion, it is like
infanticide,'' adding, ``This is a baby that is all but born and
then killed.'' He also tried to put the ban in a broader context,
arguing that by allowing ``this kind of execution,'' the Senate was
sending a message to young people that ``violence is OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Peter Fitzgerald, R-Ill., said: ``If people were sticking
scissors on the heads of puppies we would not abide it. In the name
of common decency and humanity, I implore my colleagues not to let
this happen to the young any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents called the bill unconstitutional and read letters from
doctors and physician groups saying such a law would tie the hands
of medical professionals in dealing with life- and
health-threatening pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are in the Senate,'' said Sen. Barbara Boxer,
D-Calif., ``a hundred of us and not one of us an obstetrician, not
one of us a gynecologist, deciding what procedures should or should
not be used, and under what circumstances, in a matter that should
be left to the medical profession, left to the families of this
country, left to loving moms and dads.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, told of a couple who learned they
were expecting a child with such abnormalities that it could die in
the womb. Should the government, she asked, bar the woman from an
abortion procedure ''that will protect her health and her future
fertility?''
</P>
<P>
   Santorum, the chief sponsor of the ban, tried Thursday to pick
up the final votes for an override by altering the language of his
bill in response to a recent ruling by the 8th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals that similar state laws in Arkansas, Iowa and Nebraska
were so vaguely and broadly written that they were
unconstitutional. Santorum defined the procedure as one used when
an ``intact living fetus'' is delivered ``partially outside of the
mother.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Boxer argued that even with this language, the law would
still be unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the debate, the two sides strove for the middle
ground and tried to make their opponents look extreme. Santorum
said those opposing him were really saying that abortion should be
performed ``at any time, any place, any manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats said supporters of the ban were actually
intent on overturning Roe vs. Wade, the landmark Supreme Court
decision in 1973 that created a legal right to abortion. To make
that point, Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, offered a non-binding
amendment voicing support for the 1973 decision, which narrowly
passed 51-47.
</P>
<P>
   The House, which has twice overridden the president's veto on
this legislation, is expected to consider the ban next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
