<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4569 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-HEALTHCARE-ART-$A     10-21 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-HEALTHCARE-ART-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 ALTERNATIVES FOR THE UNINSURED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic of service box with Web addresses and phone
numbers is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By STEPHEN L. COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The number of Americans without health insurance rose last year
to its highest level in a decade. More than 44 million people _ 16
percent of the population _ lack coverage of any kind, according to
the Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   And the problem is not limited to the poor. Despite a strong
economy and a low unemployment rate, more than 12 million Americans
in households with annual incomes of $50,000 or more are without
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Some programs exist to help the uninsured, but too few people
seem to be aware of them. One of the most ambitious efforts is the
Children's Health Insurance Program, or CHIP, created by Congress
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The program provides health insurance for children from working
families with incomes too high to qualify for Medicaid but too low
to afford private insurance.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D.-Mass., who was
co-author of the legislation creating the program, said that
``between CHIP and Medicaid, virtually no child in a low-wage
working family should be without health insurance.'' Yet, according
to the White House, about five million children who qualify for
these programs are not taking advantage of them.
</P>
<P>
   To increase participation, President Clinton has started a
campaign to enroll children through their schools. More than 1,500
schools have agreed to participate.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts are also being made to match uninsured adults with
medical services, because many people who qualify for programs like
Medicaid still struggling to navigate the health care labyrinth.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest complaints I've received relates to how
difficult it is to find and apply for programs like Medicaid,''
said Rima Cohen, a vice president of the Greater New York Hospital
Association.
</P>
<P>
   To address the problem, she is developing a Web site to help
uninsured people in New York State _ at least those with access to
computers _ in determining their eligibility for public insurance
programs and to find low-cost medical services.
</P>
<P>
   Because the rules vary widely from state to state, there is
little consistency in insurance coverage across the nation. But
some states have passed legislation to help the uninsured. In New
York, for example, health insurers doing business in the state are
required to sell individual insurance to anyone regardless of their
medical history.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers must also charge the same premiums to all customers in
a given area, regardless of health status, age, sex or occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Len Nichols, a health economist at the Urban Institute, a social
policy research organization in Washington, suggested that the
uninsured check with their state insurance departments to find
special programs for low-income workers. Community health centers
represent another important resource, he added, since they will not
turn away people without coverage. Public teaching hospitals can
also provide a haven where the uninsured can obtain both outpatient
and inpatient care. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nichols points to another useful strategy _ seeking clinical
care before medical conditions become serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the reason the uninsured problem is so hidden,'' he
said, ``is that the uninsured don't seek medical care until their
problems are much more severe.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many public hospitals are underfinanced and
overburdened by providing care to the poor, they represent one of
the few resources available to those who cannot afford to pay for
medical care. Some private hospitals, like Mount Sinai Medical
Center in New York City, have also set up special programs to help
the uninsured determine their eligibility for Medicaid or other
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmaceutical companies may provide an additional resource for
low-income Americans who cannot afford prescription drugs. Some
companies have special programs to provide free medication to
patients who meet specific income guidelines. Consumers can contact
the companies directly to apply.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the problem is not that people cannot afford
insurance, but that no insurer will cover them because of existing
medical conditions. In other words, while the purpose of insurance
is to spread the risk of high-cost diseases over a large
population, it fails to accomplish this goal if some patients are
excluded from coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Patients suffering from, say, asthma may be unable to buy
insurance at any price. To address the issue, 28 states have
created ``high-risk pools'' for people with serious health problems
who have been denied coverage from private insurers.
</P>
<P>
   The high-risk pools are not a panacea, since people in them may
have to pay substantially higher premiums than other consumers, but
the pools provide a crucial alternative for patients with serious
medical conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, since the pools serve less than 1 percent of the
uninsured population, many Americans still fall through the safety
net. And as some experts have noted, with so many people slipping
through the cracks, the net is becoming increasingly frayed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
