<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.H.-GORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE FACES UNDECIDED VOTERS IN FORUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, N.H. _ Vice President Al Gore began a new adventure in
campaigning Thursday night, answering questions from undecided
Democratic voters.
</P>
<P>
   Gore stood in the gymnasium at Dover Middle School and stayed
there for several hours, until the last of the 200 people in
attendance had finished grilling him. It was, aides said, a scene
reminiscent of the town hall meetings he used to hold in Tennessee
when he was first elected to Congress in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any of you who have any doubts about supporting me for
president, I want you to use this as an occasion to purge all
doubt,'' Gore said, half in jest, at the outset of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The people here politely queried Gore on several concerns:
prescription drugs, health insurance, missile defense, campaign
finance, special education, pornography on the Internet, the budget
surplus, and Gore's political legacy and morals, among other
things.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Malizia, who voted for Bob Dole in the last election,
wanted to know if Gore would embarrass the country the way
President Clinton had with in the Monica Lewinsky episode. ``I
fully believe our country is in a mess,'' she said. ``One of the
things I need in a president is an honest man and a moral man and
I'm very disappointed in this president.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he would bring his own values to the office of the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the disappointment that you feel, and I felt it
myself,'' Gore said. ``I think most people want to look to the
future, turn that page and move on. All I can do is tell you about
myself and tell you about my commitment to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore talked about his 29-year marriage to his wife, Tipper, and
about his mother and father and how they met. And he talked about
his respect for the democratic process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never betray it,'' Gore said. ``I'm in this because I
want to make a positive difference and I'm in this because I think
I can.'' Malizia said later she was impressed by the answer.
</P>
<P>
   For the forum, 2,800 undecided voters from Strafford County were
invited to attend, based on phone calls and canvassing that found
them unsure of who to support. All have a history of voting in past
Democratic primaries. About 20 Gore supporters were also invited. A
second open meeting is scheduled for Monday in Nashua; there is at
least one planned in every county in the state before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who said, `I'm with Al Gore all the way weren't
invited,' '' said Douglas Hattaway, Gore's New Hampshire spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Jaron Arnold, 12, who attends the middle school, told Gore that
many of his friends like to go on the Internet, visit Web sites
with pornography, and print it out. ``How would you prevent that?''
he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the school should be able to filter out inappropriate
sites from the computers. But in one of the evening's amusing
moments, the school's principal stood up to tell the vice president
that no student could access pornography in the school.
</P>
<P>
   Gore went back to the student and discovered that his friends
were accessing the pornography from home computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents, you've got to pay attention to this. You would not
let your children go out in big city alone in the middle of the
night in a dark alley, would you?'' Gore asked. ``Of course not. If
that's your attitude, you should not let them go alone, unprotected
and unfiltered on the Internet. There are a lot of dark alleys and
red-light districts and free-fire zones and you must protect
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he praised the Internet as a valuable resource, he also
said some material is inappropriate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4571 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BANKS-CONGRESS-ART-NY     10-21 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-CONGRESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKING BILL STALLED OVER RULES TO ENCOURAGE BANKS TO MAKE LOANS TO
THE POOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Miss., Ala., Calif.)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a week of difficult negotiations between Sen.
Phil Gramm and President Clinton's top economic advisers over a
bill to overhaul the nation's financial system, it became evident
Thursday that there would be no new law unless an agreement can be
reached over the legislation's effect on rules that encourage banks
to make loans to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case all week, Democrats and Republicans
appeared to be engaged in a political exercise Thursday fraught
with heavy symbolism over the effects of the legislation on the two
parties' traditional constituencies. At its core, some Republicans
want to ease the burdens on banks, while Democrats want to see
something in the legislation for minorities, farmers and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the exercise so unusual is that there is overwhelming
support among both Democrats and Republicans for virtually all of
the substance of the legislation, which would repeal Depression-era
laws that have made it expensive and difficult for banks to enter
the securities and insurance businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the effort by Gramm to limit the community lending
laws does not appear to have the support of the majority of the
banking community, which has profited handsomely from making loans
to the disadvantaged and underserved, but is based on the banking
chairman's view that the current law has led to unnecessary
excesses and burdens.
</P>
<P>
   The financial services measure, which was making great strides
in recent weeks after a 20-year struggle over its passage, stalled
Thursday when Gramm, R-Texas, failed to gain even a majority of his
Senate colleagues to support what he has said was a fair compromise
on the Community Reinvestment Act, a 1977 law intended to encourage
extending credit to minorities, the disadvantaged and farmers.
</P>
<P>
   By a 10-10 vote, the senators on the conference committee
defeated an amendment by Gramm that was essentially the same as the
proposal the White House rejected Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The vote fell almost entirely on party lines. Sen. Richard
Shelby, R- Ala., joined the Democrats because he said the amendment
did not go far enough in relieving small banks from the burdens
imposed on them by the Community Reinvestment Act.
</P>
<P>
   After the White House rejected Gramm's proposal, Gramm responded
by saying it would not be so bad if there were no bill at all this
year because he was confident he would have a better one next year
after George W. Bush, the governor of Texas, was elected president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grown men argue over periods and commas and clauses because
when you're talking about literally tens of billions of dollars, it
makes a difference,'' Gramm said. ``I hope the president will sign
our bill. But if he doesn't, we will have a new bill in 15 months.
I know who the president will be, and I believe it will be a
different bill.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last four days, Gramm, Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers and Gene Sperling, the president's economic adviser, have
talked for hours about whether the legislation should require that
banks expanding into new businesses maintain adequate lending
practices under the Community Reinvestment Act.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to break the impasse between Gramm and the White House,
other Republicans and Democrats Thursday began attempts at crafting
provisions on the act that would be able to both satisfy the White
House and garner enough moderates.
</P>
<P>
   But there were signs Thursday that Gramm's position on the
community lending had hardened and that it might be difficult to
revive the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Of the White House's insistence that the legislation not roll
back the Community Reinvestment Act, Gramm said: ``There's an old
saying where I come from _ don't take a hostage you're not willing
to shoot,'' Gramm said at an afternoon news conference. ``I don't
take hostages I'm not willing to shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm made the same comment last year soon before he killed a
similar bill supported by the White House proposed by Sen. Alfonse
M. D'Amato of New York.
</P>
<P>
   A passionate critic of the act, Gramm has opposed any effort to
expand it into new areas. The White House and Democrats in Congress
say that the financial legislation, with a bag of goodies for the
biggest and most powerful corporations in America, ought to at
least have something for the poor, and that at a minimum the price
for allowing banks to expand into the insurance and securities
business should be a requirement that those banks have satisfactory
ratings under the act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The banks and insurers and securities firms will be very happy
with this legislation, they have done more than OK,'' said Rep.
Maxine Waters, D- Calif.. ``I don't understand why it is that we
have done nothing for the people, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats and lobbyists said that in opposing the
Community Reinvestment Act, Gramm was handing his opposition a
strong political argument in the coming election that the
Republican party is largely unsympathetic to the plight of the
disadvantaged, and minorities in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gramm is the Democratic Party's single best unifier,'' one
longtime financial services lobbyist said.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the middle of the dispute between Gramm and the White
House are the three industries, which have tried for the last few
years to get legislation that would repeal the Glass-Steagall Act
and other laws that have limited the ability of banks, securities
companies and insurance firms from entering into one another's
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful of a train wreck that would derail the legislation, a
parade of lobbyists from the banking, securities and insurance
industries who have championed the measure trooped to Capitol Hill
Tuesday to implore Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the House majority
leader, and Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, his counterpart in the
Senate, to put off any final votes by the conference committee
until an adequate agreement could be reached with the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The lobbyists emerged from the discussions hopeful that there
would be no final votes until a deal could be reached on the
Community Reinvestment Act. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
