<SLUG> BC-BIZ-MIDSTREAM-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN LATE IS TOO LATE 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 24) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mo., Ind.)   (af)  
 By JAMES SCHEMBARI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As baby boomers, we have had amazing fortune. A strong economy
has given many of us comfortable careers and the stock market has
made us more comfortable still. Many in our group are successful,
wealthy and not nearly done yet.
</P>
<P>
   But that sense of endless possibility is causing us to make a
familiar mistake. Although we are prescient enough to prepare for
our children's education and our retirement, we have the same
inability as past generations to contemplate our own deaths while
we're young. That means many of us are not preparing wills or doing
the other things that smooth the way for our heirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boomers are probably the best generation as far as
investing,'' said Stuart Kessler of Goldstein Golub Kessler, an
accounting firm in Manhattan, ``but in other areas of planning,
like wills, they are one of the least-equipped generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Kessler said boomers were also falling short in other areas.
They lack disability insurance, a durable power of attorney if they
become incapacitated, or even a simple letter of instruction _
telling survivors where, for example, to find the key to the
safe-deposit box.
</P>
<P>
   I've bought disability insurance, but I lack the others _
including a will. I keep putting it off because it's not a
priority. Besides, if I die without a will, won't my wife end up
with everything anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Not true, Kessler said. In my state, Connecticut, assets held
solely in my name would be divided automatically among her and the
children. Generally, states divide the assets by giving the
surviving spouse a portion of the assets, often $50,000, then
splitting the remainder 50-50.
</P>
<P>
   New York and New Jersey do it that way; in Connecticut, the
spouse gets the first $100,000. When there are children of a
previous marriage involved, the formula is often adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   David M. English, a law professor at the University of Missouri
at Columbia, said 14 states, mostly in the Midwest and West, give
the surviving spouse 100 percent of the assets.
</P>
<P>
   A 50-50 split may sound benevolent, but my wife may need all the
money to keep the household running. Although the court would
appoint my wife to be the children's guardian, it may name someone
else, like a lawyer or a bank, to watch over their money until they
are 18. These guardians charge a fee for that service, which
includes making sure that money is handled appropriately.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the circumstances, Kessler said, some courts would
make the surviving parent pay for school, or the hiring of a nanny
while the parent worked, out of the parent's, not the child's,
share. Kessler recommends a will that leaves assets to the parent
and money in trust for the children, with the parent as the
trustee.
</P>
<P>
   Albert L. Sica, 37, of New York City, doesn't have a will, but
is seeing a lawyer about getting one. He always put it off, but now
that his children are 10 and 13, he recognizes the need to provide
for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we needed to get a will, but it's not like we have $20
million in the bank,'' Sica said. ``It was not in the forefront of
our minds, but, God forbid, if my wife and I were to die, what
about the kids?''
</P>
<P>
   Kessler said that having to make decisions about the children
sometimes kept people from making a will. One reason ``is that they
can't agree on the guardians for the children'' if the parents die
together.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Sabatino, assistant director of the American Bar
Association's Commission on Legal Problems of the Elderly, didn't
get a will until he and his wife were leaving for a trip overseas
many years ago, without their two children. The night before they
left, he said, they were in a lawyer's office signing documents.
The biggest point of discussion was who would take care of the
children. They decided on his sister-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ``People often don't start thinking about estate planning until
they have little kids and are about to travel,'' he said. ``Kids
are a great motivator.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest motivator may be our own parents. ``Boomers think
they'll live forever,'' said Scott R. Severans of Severans &AMP;
Bennett, an Indianapolis law firm specializing in the elderly.
``But we will see a surge of boomers getting wills when they
encounter their parents' failure to plan and the mess it creates or
the relief, at a moment of crisis, that their parents have a
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   James Schembari is an editor at The Times. His column on the
prime earning, spending and striving years appears the fourth
Sunday of each month. E-mail: jimschem(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
