<HEADLINE>
MINISTER DECIDES TO END FAST OVER THIRD-WORLD DEBT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ His body so weak he could barely stand, a retired
minister from southwest Washington yesterday ended a 45-day hunger
strike he began in an effort to persuade Congress to forgive the
debts of third-world nations.
</P>
<P>
   Late yesterday afternoon, 71-year-old David Duncombe of White
Salmon, Wash., stood on the grounds of the Capitol and broke bread,
literally, with a group of his supporters. Later he intended to eat
a spoonful of rice. He expects it will take him several days before
he can eat a real meal.
</P>
<P>
   Duncombe will return to Washington state this weekend without
seeing the result he wanted: Congress passing a measure to forgive
an estimated $970 million owed by 40 impoverished countries.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers supporting the cause said they are optimistic that
they may yet eke out a victory in the waning weeks of this year's
congressional session. A variety of religious leaders, including
Pope John Paul II and the Revs. Billy Graham, Jesse Jackson and Pat
Robertson, have called for debt forgiveness as a way to honor the
biblical injunction to forgive debts every 50 years as part of a
celebration called Jubilee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll pass it because it's a real window of
opportunity _ the year 2000, there are a lot of church groups
pushing this,'' said Rep. Spencer Bachus, R-Ala. ``Anyone who
studies this issue for any amount of time comes to the conclusion
that it's the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncombe said that yesterday, when he could barely walk, he
decided it was time to start eating, rather than risk death. But he
counted some successes _ he met with the powerful House Majority
Whip Tom Delay, R-Texas, for example, and came away believing the
House would vote on debt forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had the feeling in the past few days that things are
really moving,'' Duncombe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am, in my starvation, representing millions of faceless,
voiceless, powerless starving people, ten thousand of whom are
dying each day in the countries covered by this bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Numerous lawmakers joined Duncombe as he ended his fast and
praised his action.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the example of his own denial of the most basic element of
survival, he is reminding us that there are so many people ... who
every day have no choice,'' said Rep. Brian Baird, D-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the power within us to correct that. We are in the
richest nation in the history of the world ... and we give less per
capita than almost any other country in the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
