<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4580 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-STEELE-LADN     10-21 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-STEELE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S STEELE SAYS NFL CAN WAIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Linebacker Markus Steele first drew comparisons to
Chris Claiborne when he arrived at USC two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a valid assessment is debatable, but Steele is
already answering the same questions Claiborne did last year about
his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL wouldn't be bad, but I figure I can help myself more
if I stay and get my degree,'' Steele said. ``It's crossed my mind
a lot, but I'm at the point where I won't leave. I'll be back for
another season. It's tempting, but I just got here and I want to
experience college life.''
</P>
<P>
   USC fans will breathe easy with those remarks, because they
won't have to go through another early departure a la Claiborne,
who became a top-10 draft pick last season after winning the Butkus
Award as a junior.
</P>
<P>
   It's only this week that the NFL and Steele became a serious
topic, partly because of his 18-tackle performance against Notre
Dame. Steele also had one of the game's big plays when he dived
through Notre Dame's line and forced quarterback Jarious Jackson to
fumble as the Irish tried to run out the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came over the top of two blockers and got the ball out,''
USC coach Paul Hackett said. ``He continues to improve week after
week.''
</P>
<P>
   But not enough to leave for the NFL _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was to leave, I would have to be in the top 10,'' Steele
said.
</P>
<P>
   He's not there today, but his speed and size (6-foot-3, 220
pounds) make him attractive. He could probably even play strong
safety in the NFL because of his athleticism.
</P>
<P>
   It's one reason Steele leads USC with 59 tackles along with
three sacks, four pass deflections, one interception, three forced
fumbles, two fumble recoveries and a 46-yard fumble return for a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm doing a little better than I thought,'' Steele
said. ``I thought it would take longer to figure out our defensive
schemes.''
</P>
<P>
   USC linebackers coach Shawn Slocum said Steele's ability was
widely known, but he has impressed the coaches with his intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea what kind of toughness he would have,'' Slocum
said. ``Last week he was tired, but he came back and caused a
fumble. He's a guy with the ability to make plays all over the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obvious analogy to Claiborne, Slocum believes Steele
is too different a player to make comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris didn't look fast, but he was fast,'' Slocum said.
``Markus is just plain fast. Markus tends to come off the edge and
slither through. Chris would just go through people.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele's speed might also be a weakness of sorts, six games into
his college career. He is so eager to follow the ball that he
sometimes forgets his assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seem to overrun a lot of plays,'' Steele said. ``The coaches
tell me to relax.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe anyone would have to tell Steele to relax.
In person, he is so laid-back and mellow that when people meet him,
they rarely think he plays football.
</P>
<P>
   ``They figure I play some sport but not football,'' Steele said.
``Some people say I'm too nice to play that kind of sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele was actually a two-sport star at Chanel High in New
Bedford, Ohio. He played basketball against USC forward Sam Clancy,
who is also from Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was athletic,'' Clancy said. ``He had good hops and was
very strong. I could tell he would be good.''
</P>
<P>
   He just didn't act like a typical football player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to have football mentality in every moment of my
life. It's something I can turn off and on,'' Steele said. ``I want
to be a regular student like everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Before any one believes Steele is a wallflower, notice the
transformation when he discusses his love for football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I would like football. You can let a lot of anger and
frustration out on anything,'' Steele said. ``You get contact and
you don't have to sit down.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele was recruited by Ohio State and Michigan State, but his
high school grades were so poor he knew he couldn't attend a
four-year college. Instead, he called Pasadena City College and
asked for a game tape. While watching the tape, Steele was
intrigued by the opponent, Long Beach City College.
</P>
<P>
   He decided to attend Long Beach instead, and was soon touted as
the nation's top JC linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to get far away from home,'' Steele said.
``California is where the best talent is.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele liked California so much, he decided early in his
freshman year that he wanted to go to USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I visited Arizona State and Oregon, but I had my mind set I
would go to USC,'' Steele said. ``Ohio State called me again. But
you don't have to worry about the weather changing here. I did so
good here I thought I would stay. All I want to do is play here and
go to a major bowl game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
