<HEADER>
A4581 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FELLS-ACRES-BOS &LR;      10-21 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FELLS-ACRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY FIGURE IN CHILD-ABUSE CASE IS SPARED MORE PRISON TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ The case that came to symbolize society's
shifting views on prosecuting child sexual abuse ended Thursday for
Cheryl Amirault LeFave after a judge agreed not to send her back to
the prison where she spent eight years for molesting children at
her family's day care center.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprisingly placid finale to a highly charged case, both
LeFave's lawyers and Middlesex County prosecutors agreed that she
should not return to prison in the wake of a failed bid for a new
trial on charges she sexually abused children at the Fells Acres
Day School in Malden, Mass., in the 1980s. Superior Court Judge
Paul Chernoff concurred and released her.
</P>
<P>
   While LeFave will not have to serve any more of an eight- to
20-year sentence, her freedom comes at a price. In a deal with
prosecutors designed to shield the now-grown victims, LeFave agreed
not to appear on television to talk about the case and she cannot
profit from her notoriety during her 10 years on probation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, LeFave, who has been free on appeal since 1995,
must drop her 15-year quest to overturn her conviction, a crusade
that ended in August when the state's highest court reinstated her
1987 conviction for child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very difficult pill to swallow,'' LeFave said. ``I
gave up a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   There was never any possibility that LeFave would admit guilt in
exchange for concessions from prosecutors, and her lawyers said
that issue was never up for debate.
</P>
<P>
   LeFave, and her mother, Violet Amirault, were convicted and
sentenced to eight to 20 years in prison on the molestation
charges. Violet Amirault died of cancer two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   LeFave's brother, Gerald Amirault, was convicted in a separate
trial and is currently serving a 30-to-40-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of one of LeFave's victims, who is now 19, called the
deal to allow LeFave to remain free ``the lesser of two evils.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts closure to 15 years of this,'' she said. ``We don't
have to pick up the paper and turn on the TV and hear that they are
doing this and doing that. Had she gone back to jail, I'm sure
there would have been pardons and appeals and this and that. This
is the lesser of two evils.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Amirault's lawyers may ask to have his sentence revised
as well, but they admitted that could be difficult, given
prosecutors' stated reluctance to support a reduction in his
sentence. He is jailed at Bay State Correctional Center in Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference less than an hour after LeFave was freed,
Middlesex District Attorney Martha Coakley said she doubted her
office would be as supportive of a motion to revise Gerald
Amirault's sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his sister, Gerald Amirault has served less than half of
the minimum sentence on his conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are two separate cases and two separate defendants,''
said Coakley. ``He is serving 30 to 40 years in state prison. I see
nothing that would affect that sentence.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she said Gerald Amirault's conviction was a linchpin in
the overall case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do note that there are fewer female sex offenders, but when
there are women, there is often a primary male offender involved,''
Coakley said.
</P>
<P>
   She added that LeFave, 42, had already served a longer prison
term than many sex offenders and more time behind bars would not
protect the public or help the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Coakley said she consulted with former Middlesex District
Attorney Scott Harshbarger, whose office prosecuted the Amiraults,
and former DA Thomas Reilly, whose office handled appeals in the
case. Neither objected, she said.
</P>
<P>
   First Assistant District Attorney Lynn Rooney said the victims
and their families accepted the deal, which spares them further
parole board hearings and the specter of LeFave on television
proclaiming her innocence.
</P>
<P>
   When bizarre, horrific stories emerged in 1984 about toddlers at
Fells Acres being sexually abused, the arrest and prosecution of
the Amiraults became the first wide-scale case of child molestation
in metropolitan Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Using potentially suggestive interviewing techniques that have
since been retooled, investigators wove a sordid saga of
schoolhouse molestation, including claims that children were tied
naked to a tree in the schoolyard and sexually abused by a clown in
a ``magic room.''
</P>
<P>
   In the decade after their convictions, other cases of mass child
molestation crumbled amid concerns that the charges were grounded
in group hysteria and not solid evidence. The tide began to turn,
both here and nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Popular opinion and courtroom verdicts shifted away from the
once-unchallenged belief that children always tell the truth _ even
when coaxed by investigators or when their claims seem truly
unbelievable. The Fells Acres case became a flashpoint for those
who think investigators pushed too hard and accepted too much.
</P>
<P>
   LeFave's cause has been championed nationally, most notably by
the editorial page of The Wall Street Journal. Dorothy Rabinowitz,
a Journal editorial writer, even helped publicize a fund to pay the
legal bills of people, like LeFave, who say they were wrongly
convicted of child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of uncertainty, LeFave has put away the jeans and
underwear packed in the bag she expected to lug back to
MCI-Framingham.
</P>
<P>
   Since September, LeFave's lawyer, Jamie Sultan, had been
negotiating with Coakley over the remainder of her sentence. But
LeFave didn't decide to drop her quest for exoneration until
Wednesday, she said in an interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   LeFave said she is relieved that she will not have to return to
the prison where she shared a cell with her mother.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was on a visit to her mother's grave that she
meditated on the decision to give up further appeals in exchange
for freedom. She decided that her mother would have agreed with her
friends and lawyers and advised her to sign the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Forfeiting the book and movie deals she has been offered over
the past decade was not hard, she said. And the standard conditions
of probation for a sex offense _ such as not having contact with
children under age 16 or taking a job that would bring her in
contact with children _ did not faze her, she said.
</P>
<P>
   LeFave said she has accepted the fact that her victims believe
she is guilty and that she is unlikely ever to change their minds.
She has given up the notion of ever speaking to them directly but
hopes someday they will investigate the case themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she struggles with her failure to win vindication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel grateful to Martha Coakley for allowing me some
relief,'' she said. ``I'll take responsibility for what Martha
Coakley has offered me and respect it and try hard to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, some people hand her their babies as a gesture of faith
when they recognize her on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people have worked so hard for me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Since her conviction was reinstated in August, Harvard law
professor Charles Ogletree and a team of law students fashioned an
argument that was presented to Judge Chernoff: that LeFave's
original lawyers should have presented findings by social
scientists that show that long terms of probation are appropriate
in sex offense cases.
</P>
<P>
   Sultan said he turned to Ogletree after the SJC defeat, looking
for fresh strategies when there was no chance of revisiting the
guilty verdict.
</P>
<P>
   But as happy as Sultan and LeFave were to have her sitting in
his office Thursday rather than in a cell in Framingham, there was
no celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm grateful, but I just wish it was right,'' she said, her
eyes filling with tears.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
