<SLUG> BC-WHALE-DEATH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT WHALE DIES NEAR N.J. COAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than two months after a rescue team failed to free her from
fishing line that was cutting her shoulder, a Northern right whale
has died off the coast of northern New Jersey, in what might be the
second human-caused death of the rare animals this year.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 300 Northern right whales are left, making the death
of even a single animal _ especially a sexually mature female _ a
cause for concern about the survival of the species.
</P>
<P>
   Although the cause of death has not been determined, the autopsy
on the 45-foot, 60-ton animal is expected to focus on a 7-inch deep
gash in her shoulder caused by the fishing gear. A second female
whale, nicknamed Staccato, died last spring off Cape Cod after she
was struck by a ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very upset that this whale has died and we had a ship
strike earlier, but that doesn't mean that everything is broken,''
said Andrew Rosenberg, deputy director of the National Marine
Fisheries Service, the agency in charge of protecting the whale.
``Some good things are happening, but this is a long- term
proposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the private Center for Coastal Studies in
Provincetown, Mass., had been tracking the whale, known as 2030,
since May when mariners reported that rope and fishing net had
become wrapped around her body. A crew from the center tried to cut
off the lines in September, but was unable to remove the most
tightly wrapped line.
</P>
<P>
   Ship strikes and fishing gear entanglements, especially gill
nets and lobster lines, are the leading human causes of right whale
deaths, preventing the right whale population from coming back
despite 70 years of federal protection.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the National Marine Fisheries Service and
coastal states such as Massachusetts have stepped up efforts to
help the whales, temporarily closing some fisheries, requiring gear
that is less likely to entangle the animals, and requiring ships to
report when they are near the whales.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, 2030 was one of three right whales that became
entangled in fishing gear this summer in Canada's Bay of Fundy.
</P>
<P>
   And 2030's movements after she became entangled show how
difficult it is to protect such a far-ranging animal. Based on a
satellite tag the rescue crew place, 2030 swam 400 miles between
Nova Scotia and New York City in a matter of days.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Mystic Aquarium in Connecticut were scheduled
to begin the autopsy on 2030, on the shore near the Coast Guard
station in Cape May, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   If the fishing gear killed the animal, the National Marine
Fisheries Service could order a fresh round of fishing restrictions
since the killing of even a single right whale violates two federal
laws.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rosenberg said there are signs of new initiatives:
Because of lobbying by Massachusetts legislators, Congress just
approved $4.1 million for research into reducing ship strikes and
fishing gear entanglements.
</P>
<P>
   `We're doing everything we can to protect whales,'' said
Rosenberg, ``but we're not there yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
