<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELSIDE-RELSIDE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Religious Rights in the Workplace  &HT;     Sam McManis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The government and the private sector have yet to resolve
definitively which religious rights are acceptable in the
workplace. With the help of Howard A. Simon, employment lawyer at
Landels, Ripley and Diamond in San Francisco, and other experts,
here are questions and answers about religion in the workplace:
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: What constitutes a religion that is protected in the
workplace?
</P>
<P>
   A: According to Title VII of the 1964 Civil Rights code,
religion is any moral or ethical belief held as strongly as
traditional religious views, even if an organized religion does not
espouse such beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does that mean an employee could start his own religion and
be protected if she or he wants to leave early on Fridays?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Yes. ``It need not be part of any organized religion,''
Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR;  Q: Is vegetarianism considered a religion?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission says yes. In
1996, a bus driver for the Orange County Transportation Authority
was fired for refusing to pass out free hamburger coupons to
riders. Bruce Anderson said it went against his devout vegetarian
belief that animals should not be killed or eaten. The EEOC ruled
that Anderson had been terminated unfairly and violated his civil
rights. He was awarded $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can a religious institution, such as a parochial school,
forbid the hiring of workers outside the institution's faith?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Religious institutions are exempt from the provisions of
Title VII, and that position has been in upheld in several cases.
For example, in 1995, a Michigan court ruled that Catholic schools
do not need to hire Protestant teachers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is an employer always obligated to compensate an employee for
his absence from work for a religious holiday?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Generally, an employer is not required to pay an employee
for time off taken for an observance. The U.S. Supreme Court held
that merely allowing an employee unpaid leave for a religious
holiday qualifies as ``reasonable accommodation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are employees always allowed to wear religious garb and
symbols?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Not always. It depends on the job and the garb. For
safety reasons, the U.S. Occupational Safety and Health
Administration has ruled that machinists exposed to toxic gases
must be clean-shaven and wear masks, a regulation that has survived
tests by Sikhs. But OSHA recently did exempt Sikhs wearing turbans
from hard-hat rules.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
