<SLUG> BC-PROVIDIAN-PROVIDIAN </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Providian Quarterly Profits Up 83%  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Credit card giant Providian Financial, showing its earnings machine
is still in gear despite a high-profile consumer fraud scandal,
said yesterday that its third-quarter profit soared 83 percent from
a year ago.
<P>
   The San Francisco company blew past Wall Street estimates,
posting net income of $150.9 million ($1.04 a share) compared with
$82.6 million (57 cents) in the three months ended September 1998.
The nation's sixth-largest credit card issuer was expected to earn
95 cents a share in the most recent period.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said they were impressed by Providian's ability to draw
new customers and build customer loan balances in the teeth of bad
publicity. During the quarter, the company added 1 million new
accounts to reach a total of 11 million customers and raised the
value of its outstanding loans by $2.1 billion, a 13 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``They produced outstanding numbers'' said Todd Pitsinger, an
analyst with the Virginia brokerage firm Friedman, Billings,
Ramsey.
</P>
<P>
   Providian's growth took place amid a spate of private lawsuits,
as well as probes by bank regulators and the San Francisco district
attorney's office of Providian's business practices.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups charge the company with deceiving customers
about interest rates and product sales, and gouging them with fees.
Providian has never admitted wrongdoing but recently put in place
reforms to rewrite marketing sales language and make it easier for
customers to settle complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Providian Chief Financial Officer David Petrini told analysts
yesterday that the company has given customer service workers
authority to offer customers refunds or otherwise resolve problems.
As a result, he said, the company is settling more complaints on
the first call.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the company said consumers are lodging fewer
complaints against it with consumer and law enforcement agencies.
For example, the Better Business Bureau forwarded 38 complaints to
Providian in September, compared with 65 in March, before public
controversy erupted.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said it is too early to conclude that
Providian has fundamentally cleaned up its act. ``The bottom line
is that their customer base has expanded and it doesn't matter
whether the changes are significant or superficial,'' said
Charlotte Chamberlain, an analyst with Jefferies &AMP; Co. in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer activists said Providian has curbed the most extreme
abuses _ such as slapping customers with late fees even though they
paid on time _ but continues to use misleading sales tactics, such
as hiding annual fee disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, they said, the company gets too much of its profits
from fees, a sign it may be soaking customers. A recent Standard &AMP;
Poor's study calculated that the company gets 49 percent of its
income from fees, seven percentage points more than its nearest
rival.
</P>
<P>
   Said Pat Wallace, president of the Oakland Better Business
Bureau: ``They've made a couple of changes, but they're still doing
things that are not acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
