<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4589 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ANALYSIS-FELLS-ACRES-     10-21 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANALYSIS-FELLS-ACRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG CHAPTER IN CASE ENDS, BUT NOBODY WINS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 w/FELLS-ACRES   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It began in 1984 with the claims of a 5-year-old boy
and quickly spiraled into the biggest child sexual abuse case in
the state's history. Some 40 children said they had been fondled,
violated, and photographed nude at the Fells Acres Day School in
Malden, Mass..
</P>
<P>
   The trials of defendants Violet Amirault, the school's elderly
owner, and her two adult children, Gerald Amirault and Cheryl
Amirault LeFave _ against the backdrop of other sensational
child-abuse cases nationwide _ grabbed headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Justice seemed served when mother, son, and daughter were
convicted of molesting children entrusted in their care and slapped
with long prison tems.
</P>
<P>
   But by the early 1990s, similar day care sexual abuse cases
around the country slowly began to collapse. Wild claims by the
children were questioned and scrutinized. And techniques used to
investigate those claims were discredited.
</P>
<P>
   As public opinion shifted, supporters began to insist that the
Amiraults themselves were the victims: of public hysteria and
ill-trained investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Finally Thursday, after recently losing her last appeal to the
Supreme Judicial Court, LeFave struck a deal with the government:
She would gain her freedom, but would forever be known as a
convicted child molester.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as Gerald Amirault remains behind bars, serving a
30- to 40-year prison term for his 1986 conviction for molesting
nine children, the case still lingers.
</P>
<P>
   There remains suspicion in the eyes of the public that LeFave
and her brother were wrongly convicted by investigative techniques
that may have prompted the children to fabricate stories of sexual
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, prosecutors' efforts to gag LeFave by barring her
from TV appearances will fuel speculation that they want the case
to go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has endured injustice and unfairness, but made the
decision to preserve her freedom because the struggle to reclaim it
would have been extraordinarily difficult, if not impossible,''
said Elliot M. Weinstein, a criminal defense lawyer and past
president of the Massachusetts Association of Criminal Defense
Lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Although dozens of children contended they were abused at Fells
Acres between 1981 and 1984, only nine testified against Gerald
Amirault, and four testified against his mother and sister.
</P>
<P>
   The children, ages 3 to 6 years old, said the Amiraults had
sexually assaulted them, used objects to abuse them, and
photographed them in a ``magic room.''
</P>
<P>
   Some said Gerald Amirault dressed as a clown while abusing them,
and one 6-year-old boy said he was bitten by a robot at the school,
tied naked to a tree in front of teachers, and forced to watch
LeFave pull the legs off a squirrel.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers attacked the credibility of the children,
suggesting their claims were too fantastic, but jurors concluded
that the children were telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, however, some of the parents have acknowledged that
some of the bizarre claims may have been exaggerated by the
children. But they insist the youngsters couldn't have had the
knowledge to describe sexualy explicit acts unless they had been
victimized.
</P>
<P>
   Now the spotlight will shift to Gerald Amirault, who has
proclaimed his innocence just as loudly as his sister but has not
garnered as much public attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't think that women do these kinds of things so
there was a little bias there,'' said Thomas Hoopes, a lawyer who
predicted that people will now take a harder look at Amirault's
case. ``What's happened to her is going to be a wedge to reopen his
case.''
</P>
<P>
   In the deal with LeFave, however, each side gets something, but
nobody really wins.
</P>
<P>
   LeFave is free, but can never clear her name. The children who
testified against LeFave can now move on with their lives, knowing
the case involving LeFave won't be overturned so they'll never be
asked to testify again. But the woman convicted of abusing them now
walks free.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody's stomach is just a little less sick,''
Hoopes said. ``She gets her freedom and the government has already
gotten as much time for her in jail as anybody who would have been
convicted of this type of case normally would have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Laurence Hardoon, who prosecuted the cases against the
Amiraults and LeFave and is now in private practice, said the deal
does not mark a change in the government's view of LeFave's guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The district attorney has elected to pursue this resolution
for one reason and one reason alone _ to bring closure and finality
to the families involved in this case,'' Hardoon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the perspective of the parents, had (LeFave) gone back to
prison this case would have come up year after year after year as a
parole matter, and the parents would have had to confront it and
deal with it on an ongoing basis every year, and they were tired of
dealing with it,'' he said. ``The notion of finally cementing the
integrity of the criminal convictions and putting this matter to
rest was something that they wanted for themselves and for their
children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
