<SLUG> BC-WIND-WIND </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Wind River Buys a Top Competitor  &HT;     By Dan Fost  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Wind River Systems of Alameda, which makes software that runs
such everyday devices as cars, cameras and telephones, yesterday
bought one of its top rivals, Integrated Systems Inc. of Sunnyvale,
for about $445 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will give Wind River a stable of ``embedded software''
used in the telecommunications, consumer electronics, automotive
and aerospace industries. Perhaps even more importantly, it will
give the fast-growing company ISI's 728 employees, including many
hard-to-hire development and service engineers. Wind River employs
800 people.
</P>
<P>
   Wind River is best known for making the software that helped run
the Mars Pathfinder in 1997, but its operating systems are also
embedded in dozens of common devices.
</P>
<P>
   As computer chips proliferate in those devices, software is
needed to tell the chips what to do. Wind River and ISI make that
software.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, each share of ISI stock will be
exchanged for .92 shares of Wind River stock. ISI closed yesterday
up 13 cents, at $10.56. Wind River closed down 94 cents, at $20.06.
At that price, ISI would be valued at $18.45 per share, a 75
percent premium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a huge win for both organizations. It's a
situation where one and one equals three,'' said Matt Belkin, an
analyst with Hambrecht &AMP; Quist in San Francisco. ``It's something
they should have done a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal was initially proposed when the two companies' founders
and chairmen, Jerry Fiddler from Wind River and Naren Gupta of ISI,
had dinner together about six weeks ago. When Tom St. Dennis joined
Wind River as its chief executive last month, his first day on the
job included a meeting with his ISI counterpart, Chuck Boesenberg.
</P>
<P>
   St. Dennis will continue to run Wind River, while Boesenberg
will retire. Fiddler will remain chairman, with Gupta joining Wind
River's board as vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Fiddler said the driving force behind the deal is the growing
number of devices that provide access to the Internet _ from cars
to cameras to game consoles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is changing very, very quickly here,'' he said.
``We're moving beyond the world where most people access
information from desktop computers. Together, we're extremely well
positioned to do well in that world.''
</P>
<P>
   The market for such embedded systems is increasingly
competitive, however, particularly as software giant Microsoft
Corp. aggressively pushes its Windows CE operating system for
handheld computers, video game consoles and other gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   According to the industry publication Electronic Engineering
Times, Wind River's software, known as VxWorks, holds a 25 percent
market share in the embedded world, more than any other company.
ISI's pSOS System is No.2, with 11 percent. Windows CE trails about
10 other vendors with a relatively insignificant market share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their combination is going to put them far above and beyond
anything any of the other players are capable of,'' said Belkin,
the analyst.
</P>
<P>
   In its most recent quarter, which ended July 31, Wind River
reported net income of $8.5 million on revenues of $73.1 million.
For ISI, in the quarter that ended August 31, the company reported
a loss of $7.4 million on revenue of $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
