<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-BIOTECH </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Momentum Is Building for Biotech IPOs  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Maxygen Inc. of Redwood City yesterday became the latest Bay
Area biotech firm to file an initial public offering that will test
Wall Street's appetite for money-losing startups in the early
stages of drug development.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the year, prevailing wisdom has been that investors
were dot-com crazy and biotech averse. Indeed, biotech IPOs slumped
from a high of $1.5 billion in 1996 to just $369 million last year
and had only reached $316 million as of September, according to
Burrill &AMP; Co., the San Francisco investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   Companies believe the time is ripe for the IPOs because biotech
has been one of the stronger sectors in the market this year, and
they want to raise the money now rather than miss this market
opportunity. The money is needed to fund research and also to give
the companies' private backers a chance to recoup their investment.
</P>
<P>
   Tularik Inc. of South San Francisco decided to test the IPO
waters a week ago with a filing that would value the firm at about
$500 million. That is an aggressive market cap target for an
8-year-old company whose lead drug candidate is still in early
stage Federal Drug Administration trials.
</P>
<P>
   A few days earlier, Caliper Technologies of Mountain View, which
builds chips to analyze fluid samples, filed a $60 million offering
to see whether the window is open for early stage biotech
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know if the window's open until somebody tries to
jump through it,'' said Dave Flores, publisher of the BioCentury
Newsletter in San Carlos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to declare it a wide open window, but there
appears to be a crack,'' said Scott Morrison, life sciences
director in the Palo Alto office of Ernst &AMP; Young, who advised all
three IPO hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Slattery, who is life science fund manager for Amerindo
Investment Advisors in New York, said institutional buyers
``continue to look for companies with promising late stage
products,'' and suggested the current offerings face a tough sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of positive trends favoring biotech IPOs,
but institutions aren't getting breathless to buy,'' said Gayatri
Sondhi, with Boston Consulting Group. ``Each of these companies is
going to have to make their case on its merits.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxygen, which has hired Goldman Sachs to help it raise $80
million, bases its case on its ``molecular breeding'' technology.
Maxygen has shown that by mixing different proteins _ think of it
as shuffling two decks of cards _ it can produce chemicals with
stronger properties.
</P>
<P>
   The technology was conceived by Dutch scientist Willem Stemmer,
who founded the company in 1997 with help from biotech inventor
Alejandro Zaffaroni and venture capitalist Isaac Stein, who is also
chairman of UCSF Stanford Health Care.
</P>
<P>
   Maxygen, which lost $4.7 million last year on revenues of $5.2
million, is betting its molecular breeding technology will lead to
more powerful drugs and industrial chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Tularik, the best known of the three current hopefuls, spun off
from Genentech in 1991 to focus on research on drugs for cancer,
obesity, diabetes and other diseases. It was founded by David
Goeddel, the first scientist hired at Genentech, a man whom Forbes
ASAP has called ``biotech's original brilliant scientist.''
</P>
<P>
   But Goeddel's reputation was tarnished earlier this year when a
witness in a patent infringement case brought by the University of
California against Genentech testified that Goeddel had fudged an
experiment 20 years ago. Goeddel denied the charges and the case
ended in a hung jury.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Tularik is generally lauded for its scientific
prowess but has been criticized for failure to turn its ideas into
products. Its most advanced drug candidate is an anti-cancer
compound that it licensed from another drug developer and is still
in early stage human clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   But Tularik hopes that, with help from Lehman Brothers, it can
raise between $69 million and $81 million in December by selling
6.25 million shares at $11 to $13 per share. The company, which has
raised $160 million from private sources in its history, lost $10.5
million last year on revenues of $21.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Caliper is hoping to raise $60 million by exciting investors
with the potential of lab-on-a-chip technology. Its custom-designed
chips can analyze minute amounts of experimental fluids far faster
than conventional methods. Caliper contends it can develop a
thriving business from selling these time-saving devices to
industrial labs.
</P>
<P>
   Caliper is in the thick of competition with other startups that
make similar chips, like Aclara Biosciences of Hayward and Orchid
Biocomputer of Princeton New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Caliper lost $3 million in fiscal 1999 on revenues of $8.2
million. The company, whose IPO is being handled by Credit Suisse
First Boston, has not set a date or fixed a number of shares on the
offering.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
