<HEADER>
A4593 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-RELIGION-RELIGION_SFC     10-21 1702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-RELIGION </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Companies Struggle to Accommodate Workers of Different
Religious  Faiths Without Alienating Others 
 &HT;     By Sam McManis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Trouble at work started for Kathryn Hicks two years ago when she
married a man from Bangladesh, converted to Islam and legally
changed her name to Aysha Shahid.
<P>
   After she began wearing traditional Muslim dress (called a
hijab), she said managers at the Sam's Club store in Vacaville,
where she had worked since 1993, began harassing her constantly.
Some managers told her they thought she had joined a terrorist
organization and, she said, they asked her to stop wearing the head
scarf because they wanted to see her blond hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took pictures of me on Halloween and said `I think you'll
win the best costume contest,''' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Shahid didn't feel comfortable asking for
Friday afternoons off for prayer. Finally, in June, Shahid quit and
became one of the increasing numbers of workers to file a religious
discrimination complaint with the federal Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission.
</P>
<P>
   A Sam's Club spokeswoman confirmed that the company has received
the complaint but would say only that ``Wal-Mart has zero tolerance
for any type of discrimination.'' The EEOC reports that religious
discrimination complaints have increased in each of the past five
years. Of the 1,786 allegations filed in fiscal 1998, 325 had
favorable outcomes for the complainants. In 1996, 1,584 complaints
were filed, with complainants winning 165.
</P>
<P>
   Secularism no longer is the norm on the job. Seventy percent of
respondents to a Personnel Journal magazine survey believe that
spirituality has a place at work. And companies are struggling for
ways to accommodate workers of different faiths without promoting
proselytizing among workers or causing an undue hardship on the
company or its nonreligious workers.
</P>
<P>
   Spiritual expression has been the source of much conflict and
legal battles in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Cases have run the gamut, from a Jehovah's Witness waitress at
Chi-Chi's restaurant in Baltimore who objected to singing ``Happy
Birthday'' to patrons on religious grounds to a Sikh assembly line
worker in Durham, N.C., who refused to cut his hair or beard
because of religious edicts to a Roman Catholic in Iowa who said
her religious convictions dictated her to wear a graphic
anti-abortion button at work.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies, especially in culturally diverse regions such as
the Bay Area, have instituted flexible holiday scheduling so that
workers can celebrate Ramadan or the pagan solstice in lieu of
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies, such as Oracle in Redwood Shores, have set
aside prayer rooms for employees. Microsoft has noon Torah study
classes, and Boeing workers throughout California can study the
Bible, Koran and Hindu principles during break-time sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``High tech firms are familiar with different cultures, but
discrimination is still prevalent with small companies,'' said
Abdussalam Chouia, executive director of the Northern California
chapter of the Council on American-Islamic Relations. ``But a
Muslim who works in the retail or the hotel industry has it
tougher. It's just a matter of educating the employer.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco employment lawyer Mukesh Advani, a Hindu from
India, has represented Sikhs claiming discrimination because they
are not allowed to wear turbans or carry a kirpan, a 7-inch
ceremonial dagger. He said employers just need to be educated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sikhs have real problems in certain jobs, especially those
involving dealing with people, like in hotels or sales,'' Advani
said. ``If you go to a Sikh temple in the Bay Area, half the people
there will be clean-shaven because they say they have to be for
their jobs. Employers don't know it's a symbol of their faith.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 1998 Society of Human Resources Management survey of 750
human resource professionals, only 13 percent reported that their
companies accommodated religious attire.
</P>
<P>
   ``When businesses institute dress codes, they don't think about
religion, usually,'' said Hina Azam, a professor of Islamic studies
at St. Mary's College in Moraga and an official with American
Muslims Intent on Learning and Activism. ``We don't dress (in
hijabs) trying to make some point or to make others feel
uncomfortable. It's easier for me, working at a college. But in
corporate world, friends of mine have had real problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Court rulings have been split on whether companies must
accommodate employees' requests to dress according to their
religious beliefs. Few regulations are on the books, but the U.S.
Occupational Safety and Health Administration did recently exempt
Sikhs who wear turbans from its hard-hat rules.
</P>
<P>
   Howard A. Simon, a lawyer at Landels, Ripley and Diamond in San
Francisco who spoke at a recent ``Religion at Work'' seminar about
accommodation, said laws still are unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fluid concept,'' Simon said. ``(Employers) have to
tread carefully and use the same standard used under every other
kind of protected category under Title VII, based on race, gender
or nationality. It calls for reasonable accommodation for the
employee's beliefs unless to do so would create an undue hardship.
</P>
<P>
   ``UPS, for instance, has a policy whereby drivers may not have
facial hair. A Muslim challenged that policy. They gave him what
they thought was a comparable job _ same pay, but not driving. UPS
would have won the case for reasonable accommodation, except the
job wasn't available right away. There was a two-year waiting
list.''
</P>
<P>
   Other cases, though, have resulted in companies or organizations
changing dress codes without moving traditionally dressed employees
to behind-the-scenes jobs.
</P>
<P>
   On October 4, the Supreme Court upheld a lower court ruling
supporting the rights of Muslim police officers in Newark, N.J., to
wear beards despite a department policy forbidding facial hair.
</P>
<P>
   Chouia says some Bay Area employers comply after his
organization explains the religious significance of a female
worker's hijab. Two years ago, the Office Depot store in Santa
Clara suspended Elizabeth Castillon for violating the dress code by
wearing a head scarf, but she was reinstated after Chouia's group
called the company's human resources office.
</P>
<P>
   Most claims aren't so easily resolved, however.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammad Al-Sayeh, a Muslim, said he was fired from the Stevens
Creek Nissan auto dealership in San Jose in March because he
insisted he have Friday afternoons off to go to his mosque. He has
contacted the EEOC.
</P>
<P>
   ``They also were disrespectful to me,'' Al-Sayeh said. ``I was
attending a meeting in the conference room and one of the managers
cleaned the board with my prayer rug.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Van Binsbergen, general manager at Stevens Creek Nissan,
said Al-Sayeh's claim is false. ``He's making up a lot of stories
to cover himself for not being a good worker,'' said Van
Binsbergen.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just Muslims and Sikhs who face dress-code problems.
Vanessa McCauley of Allen, Texas, was a flight attendant for
Southwest Airlines for 12 years and wore a Christian cross
throughout her employment. It wasn't until a co-worker complained
in 1994 that Southwest officials told her to stop outwardly wearing
her cross and to cease carrying her Bible to read during down time
at airports.
</P>
<P>
   McCauley filed suit and won her case in 1996. The jury, though,
did not award her any damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't regret a thing,'' McCauley said. ``I wore my cross as
an expression of my faith in Jesus Christ. If you have a faith in
Christ, you're going to talk about it because it's important to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   In the private sector,  &LR; though, &LR; employees aren't allowed to
proselytize on the job, unless the person they are speaking to is a
willing participant, according to Simon. Employers also have some
control over the religious displays at the workplace, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That woman who felt compelled by her Roman Catholic beliefs to
wear a button showing graphic fetus lost her case,'' Simon said.
``The employer came up with clever accommodation. (It) gave her the
choice of wearing the button only in her cubicle, covering up the
button when she was out of her cubicle or wear an anti-abortion
slogan on (a) button without the graphic image. She said no to all
of it. The employer won the case because the accommodation offered
met her religious obligation to express her belief.''
</P>
<P>
   Laws also are nebulous on just how far an employee can discuss
and display their religious beliefs without harassing co-workers.
Simply overhearing a co-worker speaking about religion does not
qualify as harassment, precedents show.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Bernstein, director of the Bay Area chapter of the
Anti-Defamation League, said he receives many calls from Jews
complaining of workplace prayer and proselytizing by Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oftentimes, it's not so much a legal issue as a sensitivity
issue,'' Bernstein said. ``If a manager starts a meeting with a
Christian prayer, those in minority religions feel excluded and
uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fellowship of Companies for Christ International, an
organization based in Atlanta that instructs CEOs on ways of
implementing Christian values into their companies' corporate
cultures, encourages prayer in the office.
</P>
<P>
   `If you follow the Christ way, no worker from another culture
should have a problem with it,'' said David Jorgenson, the
organization's West Coast field ministry director.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Lynn, executive director of Americans United for
Separation of Church and State, said he is concerned about
companies that permeate their corporate cultures around religious
tenets.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's nothing we can do unless they reach the `hostile
environment' stage,'' Lynn said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say it's much easier for employees to convince a company
to accommodate them if they already have the job. That's why many
Muslims and Sikhs do not wear traditional clothing to interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they get the job, Muslim women will slowly try it out &LR; 
 &LR; wearing hijab and gauge the reaction,'' Azam said. ``They
shouldn't have to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
