<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPENDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE SETS STAGE FOR PRESIDENTIAL VETO ON SPENDING BILLS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite their agreement to negotiate a
comprehensive budget deal with President Clinton, House Republicans
continued to pass piecemeal appropriations measures Thursday that
are almost certain to draw presidential vetoes and prolong the
bitter fight over Year 2000 spending.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to wrap up the last of the 13 appropriations measures
before their self-imposed deadline of Friday, the House
reauthorized the $9.9 billion Title I education program designed to
help poor and disadvantaged schoolchildren compete.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, members rejected an amendment to Title I
offered by House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, that would
have provided vouchers worth up to $3,500 to help poor families pay
for private school education for their children.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-two Republicans joined Democrats in turning aside the
amendment by a vote of 257-166, dealing a blow to a proposal that
has long been the centerpiece of federal education reform efforts
pushed by conservative GOP members.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the measure said it would siphon off tax dollars
from a public education system in need of more funding.
</P>
<P>
   The Title I reauthorization was just one of several funding
measures Republican leaders sought to rush through the House late
Thursday night as talks with White House Budget Director Jack Lew _
aimed at reaching a consensus on overall government spending for
next year _ appeared to stall.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., described the talks
as ``fraudulent'' anyway because, he said, Republicans kept pushing
legislation containing ``problems'' they agreed to work out with
Clinton. He blamed House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, who is
leading the GOP budget effort, for refusing to negotiate in good
faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is apparent that Tom DeLay is running the strategy and the
show, and Republicans are not going to do what the president has
asked them to do,'' Gephardt said. ``They're going to continue with
their one-bill-at-a-time strategy and their continuance of
demagoguing about Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart also complained about
the Republicans' strategy of trying to force a presidential veto so
they can claim in next year's elections that Clinton killed bills
that included increased funding for important programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are also charging that Clinton's spending
priorities, such as hiring new teachers and police officers, would
eat into the Social Security Trust Fund next year even though he
has proposed paying for them by increasing the cigarette tax,
closing foreign tax loopholes and penalizing polluters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to make any progress as long as they're in
that mindset,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the president will continue to veto the bills that
``don't add up.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has signed into law only six of the 13 annual
appropriations bills needed to keep the government operating. The
House was still working on the last two bills to fund interior,
labor, education, health and welfare _ late Thursday night, three
weeks after the Oct. 1 deadline set by law for wrapping up the
annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has vetoed two spending bills already and is threatening
to veto at least three others because they do not meet his
priorities on education, law enforcement, foreign aid and the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans stress that their spending bills provide more money
for education and other programs than the president requested
without dipping into Social Security surpluses. But to keep their
pledge not to spend Social Security money next year, GOP leaders
are proposing across-the-board cuts in many programs.
</P>
<P>
   They are also borrowing from future budgets in an effort to pay
for some of the increases demanded by their own colleagues. In
addition, Republican members said Thursday that a plan put forward
by DeLay to spread out lump-sum earned income tax credit payments
to the poor over 12 months to save money is also being revived as
``a voluntary program.'' Those who receive the payments would have
the option of taking them in monthly installments.
</P>
<P>
   That proposal was shot down last month by Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, the leading GOP presidential candidate, who likened it to
trying to balance the budget ``on the backs of the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   The creative accounting methods have been ridiculed by both
sides of the aisle as well as the Congressional Budget Office,
which has said that the GOP bills could still end up borrowing $14
billion to $30 billion next year from Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Clinton would not accept borrowing from future
budgets, which he likened to paying ``for our vacation and our new
car'' by putting off the mortgage payment until later.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Republicans continued to contend that they are not
tapping Social Security money and are trying to lay ``what our
positions are'' by passing ``one bill at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we want to do that is that if (the president) has
specific disagreements, we can find out what they are. We want to
deal with these bills one at a time so that they retain their
identity,'' said House Appropriations Committee Chairman C.W.
``Bill'' Young, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've laid out what our positions are,'' added House Speaker
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill. ``The message is, talk to us.''
</P>
<P>
   By forcing Clinton to negotiate one spending measure at a time,
Republicans hope to avoid one large omnibus bill like the one they
agreed to last year that met the balanced budget guidelines but
still ended up giving the president more spending than Republicans
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Young said his party is simply trying to avoid a similar
``disaster,'' as he put, from occurring again this year.
</P>
<P>
   When they met earlier this week at the White House, Clinton and
Republican leaders said they wanted to wrap up their negotiations
by Tuesday. Lew, the president's budget director, said that it was
still possible to have a final deal by then. But he said the
Republican tactics so far are ``not constructive.''
</P>
<P>
   Lew said he was ``astonished,'' for example, that DeLay held a
news conference a day after the White House meeting and accused the
president of still trying to spend Social Security money even
though he agreed with Republicans in their meeting that the trust
fund would be off limits next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big differences between us are not money ... but policy,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
