<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORGAN STANLEY FINDS ITS DREAM ADDRESS TAKEN
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, trumpeting its new online stock
trading service, has discovered that somebody already has its
desired Internet address, www.msdwonline.com.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on who is telling the story, that somebody is either a
17-year-old schoolboy who created a website for mountain-bike
racing, or an opportunistic ``cybersquatter'' who registered dozens
of Internet addresses to exact big corporate ransoms.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSEHOLD STOCK OWNERSHIP SOARS
</P>
<P>
   The number of stock owners in the nation soared to 78.7 million
people early this year, 85 percent more than in 1983 when the long
bull market was getting under way.
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip stocks fell, with IBM hammered after an earnings
warning. The Dow Jones industrial average lost 94.67 points, to
10,297.69, but the Nasdaq composite index gained 13.82 points, to
2,801.95. The S&AMP;P 500 slipped 5.82 points, to 1,283.61.
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT SLIPS AT COKE; SHARES RISE
</P>
<P>
   Although Coca-Cola sales improved, third-quarter earnings fell
11.4 percent, to 32 cents a share, as forecast. Volume worldwide,
measured in cases sold, rose 3.5 percent, though about one point of
that growth came from Cadbury Schweppes brands that Coke acquired
in July. The company had forecast an increase of 2 percent.
Coca-Cola shares rose $1.5625, to $54.3125.
</P>
<P>
   GILLETTE ISSUES EARNINGS WARNING
</P>
<P>
   Gillette warned of an unexpected drop in fourth-quarter profit
and said that it might sell its Braun appliance and Paper Mate and
Parker pens businesses. Third-quarter operating profit fell 0.03
percent.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN CHIP SHORTAGE AVERTED
</P>
<P>
   The deadly earthquake in Taiwan last month seems not to have
caused the feared widespread shortage of semiconductors.
</P>
<P>
   MATTEL EARNINGS FALL, AS EXPECTED
</P>
<P>
   Mattel posted a 42 percent earnings decline, to 32 cents a
share, matching estimates. It cited a $105 million loss at the
Learning Co., a software maker for which it spent $3.8 billion five
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   TYCO PROFIT MORE THAN TRIPLES
</P>
<P>
   Tyco International, the world's biggest maker of electronic
connectors, said that its fourth-quarter profit more than tripled.
``Their free cash flow exceeded earnings,'' said Phua Young, an
analyst for Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   MERCK, UP 13 PERCENT, MEETS FORECASTS
</P>
<P>
   Merck's third-quarter profit rose 13 percent, meeting Wall
Street's forecasts, thanks to rising sales of its top-selling
prescription drug, the cholesterol-lowering pill Zocor.
</P>
<P>
   MANNESMANN CHIEF DEFENDS DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann, Germany's acquisitive telecommunications giant,
intensified the competition to dominate European mobile phone
markets, offering $33 billion in stock and cash for Orange,
Britain's No. 3 cellular operator. Investors sent Mannesmann's
stock down almost 8 percent in Frankfurt, even as Klaus Esser, the
chief executive, argued that Orange would grow more rapidly than
One 2 One, which rival Deutsche Telekom bought two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   SUBSIDIES TO RISE FOR RURAL PHONES
</P>
<P>
   The FCC voted to raise the subsidies that help make phone
service affordable for people in rural and expensive-to-serve
areas.
</P>
<P>
   A PLEA FOR CHILDREN BY PSYCHOLOGISTS
</P>
<P>
   A group of psychologists is calling on the American
Psychological Association to restrict psychological research by
advertisers pitching toys, video games, snack food and other
products to children.
</P>
<P>
   VIACOM TO STICK BY BLOCKBUSTER PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Viacom will stick with its plans to spin off Blockbuster, the
video rental company, to shareholders early in 2000, Sumner
Redstone, Viacom's chairman, said.
</P>
</TEXT>
