<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4600 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-MEGAWATI-BO     10-21 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-MEGAWATI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUGHTER OF NATION'S FOUNDING LEADER ELECTED VICE PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA _ Popular opposition leader Megawati Sukarnoputri was
elected vice president of Indonesia Thursday, walking off with the
consolation prize the day after her stunning loss of the
presidency. Her win appeased fervent supporters who had rioted in
fury and frustration when the daughter of Indonesia's founding
president was denied the top job by the 700-member national
assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Megawati's chief rivals for the vice presidency, the chairman of
the party that ruled Indonesia for 33 years and the armed forces
chief, withdrew from the race minutes before the vote, making way
for her victory in a move that was seen as putting aside party
interests to safeguard national stability.
</P>
<P>
   The vice presidency, given the frail health of President
Abdurrahman Wahid and the close friendship between the two, will
take on a significance and power it never had before.
</P>
<P>
   ``She probably will have to take up most of the responsibility
if his health fails, so in a way, this was the real presidential
election,'' said Smita Notosusanto, a political science lecturer at
University of Indonesia. The two ``get along very well. He
understands Mega the most _ others cannot work with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and others praised the new governing team of populist
nationalist Megawati and Wahid, a moderate Muslim cleric, as a
combination that would satisfy a broad spectrum of the public. The
pair will likely appoint a coalition Cabinet that includes the
former ruling party, religious conservatives, and the military that
made their victory possible.
</P>
<P>
   The public upheaval, backroom deals, and last-minute politicking
around Megawati's loss and subsequent win were visible birthpangs
of the world's third-largest democracy, the culmination of a
17-month transition since student riots drove the longtime autocrat
President Suharto from power.
</P>
<P>
   There was also hope Thursday night that the ascension to the top
jobs of the three main opponents of the former regime _ Megawati,
Wahid, and new assembly speaker Amien Rais, a reform-minded Muslim
leader _ and the absence of the military from the core of a
government long run by a general, would help this fractious,
frustrated society to settle down to a period of peace.
</P>
<P>
   Megawati's win inspired a late-night party in Jakarta's main
traffic circle, with cars honking and the urban poor and students
who form her power base celebrating with cheers and firecrackers
for hours _ a welcome contrast to the violence that claimed two
lives and injured dozens the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Critics and even some supporters had accused Megawati of growing
arrogance in the four months since her party won the largest share
in parliamentary elections, saying she refused to make deals with
other parties and expected the presidency to be handed to her on a
platter. It was unclear if she learned a lesson from her
humiliating loss _ that she cannot act as an aloof empress, but
must dig into the political trenches to make the new process of
democratic change work.
</P>
<P>
   Megawati's inaugural address graciously reached out to all the
losers, including B.J. Habibie, who had succeeded Suharto as
president last year, and earned her a standing ovation from the
national assembly that a day earlier had denied her the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech far more specific than Wahid's presidential address,
she hit the themes of political and legal overhaul, clean
government, national reconcilation and free-market economic
recovery. She promised to ``ensure that the military and police
will be guarantors of our security,'' and significantly, she urged
her followers to accept her second-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my children across the nation, please do not be goaded into
making emotional acts, because you see your mother is standing here
before you,'' said the 52-year-old erstwhile housewife whose calm,
maternal bearing is a major attraction for her loyalists. Revelers
celebrated downtown by hoisting a banner declaring, ``My Mother is
My President.''
</P>
<P>
   Megawati prominently thanked the students whose street
demonstrations were the catalyst for Suharto's fall from power and
the pressure on the government to release political prisoners, free
the press, loosen military control, and elect democratic leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
