<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS LOOK FOR THE ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Nine games without a win. A record of 0-5-4.
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly not the way the Bruins thought the season would
begin.
</P>
<P>
   It's their longest stretch without a victory at the start of a
season since they were 0-8-1 in 1964-65. In '64, they beat Chicago,
5-2, in Game No. 10 Nov. 1. The Bruins must beat the Sharks here
Saturday night to avoid an ingnominious spot in the record books.
</P>
<P>
   Offense has been the biggest problem. The Bruins have scored a
14 goals and allowed 23.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns has the remnants of a summer tan, but still
looks ashen. His players are clearly trying but aren't getting the
job done.
</P>
<P>
   To add insult to injury, Dmitri Khristich agreed to terms with
the Leafs on a deal that potentially could pay the ex-Bruin $10.34
million over four years. Boston wound up receiving a compensatory
second-round draft pick. Khristich will make $840,000 in salary
this year, to go with a $750,000 signing bonus. Next year, he'll be
bumped up to a $2.5 million salary and a $700,000 bonus. He will
receive $2.5 million in 2001-02, and if the Leafs pick up the
option for 2002-03, he'll earn $2.75 million, plus a $300,000
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Khristich was never going to play in Boston again after
the team said it wouldn't pay him the $2.8 million he was awarded
in arbitration. But there are those on the club who believe the
absence of Khristich, unsigned goalie Byron Dafoe, and center Tim
Taylor (now in New York) are part of the reason the Bruins are
struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a difficult time believing that,'' said
president/general manager Harry Sinden, when asked if he thought
missing those players was a factor in the club's malaise.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden believes the goaltending of Rob Tallas and John Grahame
has been solid enough to offset the loss of Dafoe. To counter
Khristich, Sinden points to the production from Dave Andreychuk,
who is on a 35-goal pace. In addition, Taylor has been hampered by
appendicitis and a concussion and had 2 goals and 2 assists in 8
games with the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said he thought it was a matter of his club finishing
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't score 14 goals in nine games,'' said Sinden.
``You're not going to win many games if you do, or in our case, any
games. We're spending too much time in our own end. You can see the
effort is there and they're really playing their hearts out. This
is not a lazy man's team at all, but somehow we seem caught between
going in and staying out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said when the team gets the lead, it's immensely fragile
and can't hang on. He wasn't blaming anyone and seems convinced
they'll work their way out of it. He said he supports the job Burns
is doing, and if he thought the club had laziness permeating parts
of it, he would make trades. However, right now, the Bruins' boss
seems content to let the team play its way out of its funk.
</P>
<P>
   As for Khristich, Sinden said he's not surprised he signed with
the Maple Leafs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, they can't stop themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Khristich levied a few shots at Sinden upon joining Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty mad right after the playoffs finished and Harry
went to the papers and blamed myself and (Jason) Allison because we
lost,'' Khristich told Toronto reporters. ``After that and after
the arbitration, him saying, `I'm not going to pay him,' that made
(for) really bad feelings. The team was fine and we were together,
but we didn't have the right management. I want to see him in the
playoffs this year. He was complaining about my meaningless goals
during the regular season and now they've got no goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Khristich said in his estimation, there's plenty of unhappiness
among the Bruins as a result of their personnel moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time will show, but it's not me who lost the playoffs,'' he
said. ``As a team we did pretty good and (Sinden) just had to blame
me because he was preparing for (a contract fight), that's his
problem. A lot of players are not happy with what's happening
there. They gave up on me and Byron just because of contracts and
they didn't get anything. I've heard the guys and the coach are not
happy with the management doing this kind of stuff to the team, not
willing to pay the price to win.''
</P>
<P>
   When Sinden was told Khristich didn't think he was treated
fairly in Boston, Sinden said, ``The feeling is mutual.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, though, there is a belief among a good number of Bruins
that they are a lesser team because of Khristich's loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're relying on guys who are not usually in a situation to
get 30-40 goals,'' said defenseman Kyle McLaren. ``It's tough for
them to get going. We're relying on guys who haven't been in that
situation in the NHL before. To have the pressure that they have
here, I think they're still learning that. I'm not going to lie.
Khristich was a huge (factor). Everybody knows it, the guys in here
know it. But we've got to pick it up. We need more guys to step to
the forefront and do more. Sergei (Samsonov) got his first goal
(Wednesday night), that's good. Anson Carter did. But we need
more.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaren said what has made it difficult was the struggle for
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal scoring is way down from last year (14 as opposed to
24),'' said McLaren. ``We haven't scored four goals in a game yet.
It's a big decline from last year. You can stick it in a closet but
it's not going to go away. Nine games is a young season but . . .
You try to ignore it but you can't. It's something you can't ignore
and it's not going to go away until something is done, until one of
these guys picks it up. If a guy gets 30 goals one year, who's to
say he's going to get 30 the next year? With Khristich basically
you knew it. You knew what you were going to get from him every
single year. It's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaren said some of the young players, and members of the top
two lines, are feeling the heat of the increased responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the best checkers in the NHL playing against you,''
he said. ``In the past, Dmitri and (Allison) took most of the
brunt. Everybody else played. Now it's more diverse, there's a lot
more pressure on Joe (Thornton) and Sammy. Even Landon Wilson and
those guys. It's tough in this league to get 20 goals, even 10
goals, and when you lose a guy who gets 30 on a consistent basis
and 70 points, that's a big hole right there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played nine games without him already. He's not going to
be back so we can't cry about it. But it's tough. It really is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
