<SLUG> BC-SCI-OLDEST-DINOSAUR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS FIND WHAT MAY BE OLDEST KNOWN DINOSAUR BONES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (lh) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists have unearthed a trove of fossils in Madagascar,
including the bones of two dinosaurs that may be the oldest ever
found.
</P>
<P>
   The fossils are from the Middle to Late Triassic period, 225
million to 230 million years ago. Together with remains of eight
types of reptiles that were also uncovered, they should help shed
light on this poorly understood period, a time when dinosaurs and
early mammals first began to appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get a handle on the initial diversification of
all dinosaur lineages,'' said Dr. John J. Flynn, chairman of the
geology department at the Field Museum in Chicago, who found the
fossils beginning in 1996 along with paleontologists from several
other institutions. The dinosaur bones, Flynn said, ``will help
tease apart when it happened, how fast and the processes that
caused it.''
</P>
<P>
   The dinosaurs are members of a group called prosauropods,
plant-eating beasts that are early cousins of the sauropod
dinosaurs, the largest land animals that ever lived. The new
dinosaurs have not been named.
</P>
<P>
   The exact age of the fossils is impossible to determine, since
radioisotopic dating has not been possible, Flynn said. Instead,
the researchers have relied on the classic technique of analyzing
the entire fossil record for the find and dating it by the presence
or absence of certain known species. Flynn likened it to trying to
get an approximate date for a photograph of a sports team by noting
the presence or absence of veterans and rookies whose years of
arrival or departure are known.
</P>
<P>
   Though that technique, Flynn said, ``we know that the fossils
are at least as old or older than other dinosaur sites.'' This
includes the sites where scientists found the remains of the oldest
known dinosaurs, Herrerasaurus and Eoraptor, which lived 228
million years ago. The new fossils, he said, are probably about 230
million years old.
</P>
<P>
   A report on the discovery is being published Friday in the
journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   The other fossils that were uncovered may help explain another
little-known aspect of the Triassic period: the early evolution of
mammals. Five of the reptile fossils show evidence of evolving
mammalian features, Flynn said.
</P>
<P>
   The entire fossil find should also provide clues as to how the
ecosystem changed during this period, when the huge land mass known
as Pangea began to fragment into what eventually became continents.
Primitive reptiles ruled the roost at first, Flynn said, but at the
end of the Triassic period, dinosaurs dominated the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, he said, the fossils ``will help us lift the fog
that has shrouded these evolutionary events.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
