<SLUG> BC-BERGER-FOREIGN-POLICY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S SECURITY ADVISER ATTACKS PRECEPTS OF `NEW
ISOLATIONISTS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JANE PERLEZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The White House national security adviser, Sandy
Berger, expanding on an attack initiated by President Clinton, said
Thursday night that ``new isolationists'' who defeated the nuclear
test ban treaty wanted to build ``a fortified fence around
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a policy, which Berger challenged in a speech at the
Council on Foreign Relations in Manhattan, is dangerous, because it
calls for devastating cuts to foreign assistance, would rely solely
on military defenses and fail to keep to commitments abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new isolationism of 1999 fails to understand precisely
what the old isolationism of 60 years ago failed to understand _
that local conflicts can have global consequences,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still stung by criticism of how the White House handled the test
ban treaty, which was supposed to have been a centerpiece of
Clinton's foreign policy legacy, Berger argued there was a silver
lining in the Senate vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes of our engagement in the world have been made
clear,'' he said. ``The lines have been drawn. And an old debate
has begun anew.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Clinton at his news conference last week, Berger did not
specify Republicans as the ``new isolationists,'' saying more
obliquely these beliefs were held by a ``dominant minority in the
Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that with this speech he hoped to spur a debate about
America's role, ``between leading the world and hunkering down.''
</P>
<P>
   At the core of Berger's argument was the failure of the ``new
isolationists'' to distinguish between America's power and
America's authority.
</P>
<P>
   There was little question, he suggested, about America's
overwhelming power. ``Power is the ability to compel by force and
sanctions,'' he said. ``There are times we must do so, but as a
final, not a first resort.''
</P>
<P>
   The policies of the isolationists, Berger said, undermined
America's authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Authority is the ability to lead, and we depend on it for
virtually everything we try to achieve,'' Berger added. ``Our
authority is built on very different qualities than our power, on
the attractiveness of our values, on the force of our example, on
the credibility of our commitments and on our willingness to work
with and stand by others.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger listed five precepts of the isolationists and quarreled
with each one. He said the isolationist idea that treaties
represented a threat to American sovereignty and continued
superiority was wrong-headed. ``Never mind that the alternative is
a world with no rules, no verification and no constraints at all,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A second plank of the isolationists was that ``burden sharing is
a one-way street.' Proponents of that idea ``rightly'' insisted,
for example, that the Europeans pay for most of the reconstruction
in the Balkans, because the United States had carried the main
military burden. ``But then they balk at doing our part.''
</P>
<P>
   He also took exception to the notion that ``we can't be a great
country without a great adversary.'' Berger scoffed at what he
called the revival of ``Russophobia'' and of making China ``the new
enemy No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger said it was untenable for the isolationists to call for
billions of dollars for defense but ``hardly a penny for
prevention.'' Thus, he said, Clinton had vetoed the foreign
operations bill, which allowed for $2 billion less than the White
House wanted for measures like paying for programs to back up the
Middle East peace effort and safeguarding the Russian nuclear
stockpile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
