<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIKE TYSON REMAINS A MAN OF CONTRADICTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Every time he speaks he seems to contradict himself,
but perhaps that is fitting coming from Mike Tyson, for whom
everything seems to be a contradiction.
</P>
<P>
   He talks of his desire to be a family man, has his picture on
the cover of Esquire kissing one of his children in a celebration
of Father's Day, then admits to spending far too much time in strip
joints in Phoenix and Las Vegas for a guy with four kids and a wife
2,000 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   He talks of never, ever wanting to see the inside of a courtroom
again, even on television, then says he'd bite a guy in the ring if
he felt threatened and unprotected like he did against Evander
Holyfield two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He talks with a reporter of the likelihood of repeating that
incident one day, and the next he tells a different reporter that
was all just an attempt to sell tickets.
</P>
<P>
   He talks of how celebrity is hurting his marriage, and then puts
himself smack in the middle of that most public stage he has trod
since age 14 by returning to boxing and the headlines again and
again and again.
</P>
<P>
   He is Mike Tyson, a fighter past his prime but still prime time.
But who is the real Tyson? Does anyone know? Does anyone even care?
</P>
<P>
   Is he the Tyson who warmly greeted familiar faces among the
print media last week, faces that have chronicled his rise, fall,
rise, fall, rise . . . well, you get the point . . . or is he the
Tyson who glowered at Orlin Norris after their press conference
Wednesday and then threatened Norris's manager, Scott Woodwirth, as
the they were leaving a ballroom at the MGM Grand?
</P>
<P>
   Is he both? Is he neither?
</P>
<P>
   Can he still fight? Will he ever again bite?
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Nobody knows, which is the reason the public still
finds him fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   Or do they?
</P>
<P>
   That is how it has been with Tyson, it seems, ever since he
gained the public's consciousness when he became the youngest
heavyweight champion back in 1986. Always the same. Always more
questions than answers.
</P>
<P>
   So it remains this morning, 36 hours before his showdown at the
MGM Grand Garden Arena with a 34-year-old former cruiserweight who
is a 12-1 underdog yet is still given a chance because no one is
quite sure who Mike Tyson is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing with this guy is, he's got to believe it and
have no doubts,'' longtime fight trainer Lou Duva said of Tyson.
``If his confidence is where it should be, I think you'll be
shocked by how good he looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps so, but is it where it should be? Does anyone know,
including Duva's son-in-law and Tyson's trainer, Tommy Brooks?
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's sense of confidence and Mike's ability depends on him
being able to perform, and being elusive, having the security of
knowing that the opponent isn't going to hit him, and he can hit
the opponent back whenever he wants, without just walking straight
in and trying to nail the guy,'' said Jay Bright, Tyson's boyhood
friend who is working on his second tour as one of Tyson's
trainers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the true confidence comes from, not from anybody
saying anything, or blowing a lot of hot air. His true confidence
comes from his security in his boxing ability, and that's what I've
been working on.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about this Brooks says that his fighter will knock Norris
cold one way or another, and that ``Mike has to believe in what
he's doing and believe in his ability as a fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously so. But does he? Like everything else about him, that
depends on when you ask him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel my focus is much better than it was for (Frans)
Botha,'' said Tyson, referring to the fight in which he lost four
straight rounds and was on his way to losing a fifth when he landed
one punch that left Botha twitching on the floor long enough to
make further rounds unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm coming out of a much more serene setting for this fight,''
said Tyson. ``I feel totally different. My timing and speed are
much better. Orlin Norris is a good fighter, but I don't care how
well he's prepared. I'm prepared to knock him out cold.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounds pretty confident, don't you think?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, but then he told the Los Angeles Times that he would
bite again if he feels under siege and admitted trying to break
Botha's arm in the first round of their fight in January. A day
later insisted, ``I was just talking smack. Just hyping the fight.
I was trying to sell some tickets. The Nevada State Athletic
Commission knew I wasn't serious. They knew the trauma I went
through. I won't do that in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never jeopardize my career, my life, again. It was
just fight talk. Anybody who knows the adversity I experienced
because of that ordeal would know I was just blowing off hot air.''
</P>
<P>
   That's reassuring. Or is it?
</P>
<P>
   Will he bite, can he fight? Is he the fighter he used to be a
decade ago or is he the guy who sleepwalked through much of the
1990s, fighting only 58 rounds, an average of 5.8 rounds a year?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just here to fight,'' Tyson said when asked to speculate
if the Tyson of 1988 still lurks somewhere inside him. ``I've put
in the work. I lost the weight (an estimated 60 pounds). I'm in the
perfect frame of mind to do well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the first fight (back from his suspension) I was
affected by ring rust but that got it out of me. But who cares if
I'm rusty? If I'm rusty I'm rusty. I'll still look sensational.''
</P>
<P>
   He has looked anything but in his last three fights, which in
fairness have been spread over the last four years, which is part
of the problem in trying to decipher who he is and what he has
left.
</P>
<P>
   In those fights he has lost twice to Holyfield, who beat him
senseless in their first fight and snapped his mind and forced him
to be disqualified in the second. That led to more than a year's
suspension and fines and lost revenue estimated at $20 million or
more.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Botha fight, which he appeared ready to lose until
he landed the bomb that saved him as it has so many other times in
life. But before he could build on that, he was back in jail
following a fender-bender accident during which he assaulted two
elderly men and was sentenced to a Maryland jail for six months.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was released, Tyson had ballooned to 274 pounds,
then three times delayed this fight before finally agreeing to get
in with the light-hitting Norris.
</P>
<P>
   This is not exactly a recipe for confidence building, either his
own or the public's. Yet twice this week Tyson decked his sparring
partners and was throwing the kind of whistling combinations in the
gym that were once his trademark. Those combinations have not been
seen in the ring for a decade, however, and may not be seen
Saturday night, either, because Tyson has looked good in the gym
before yet been unable to carry it into the arena.
</P>
<P>
   Too often this decade he has abandoned the daring but dangerous
style he was taught as a kid by Cus D'Amato, a style that requires
he work within an opponent's range and move his head and body
quickly enough to avoid punches while still being in position to
land. That requires a boldness he seems to no longer possess,
instead favoring a clumsy but safer search for a one-punch
knockout.
</P>
<P>
   That more plodding style still has worked over many of the
game's frauds because even today Tyson remains the most dangerous
knockout artist in boxing, but it was also seen as an unconscious
acknowledgment that he knows fear in the ring now and cannot
control it.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson seldom seems comfortable or relaxed when he's boxed in
recent years and never has he looked like the fighter he was the
night he destroyed Michael Spinks in 91 seconds in '88. Hence,
despite the hype and the hard-hits in the gym this week, mystery
still shrouds him as the second fight of his fifth comeback
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   It is a mystery for which even he doesn't seem to be sure of the
answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't fought in 2 1/2 years (before the Botha fight),''
Tyson said. ``That wasn't a good experience, but it was a
sensational ending. Not too many people could start over as many
times as I have.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but there's another contradiction, perhaps the last for
Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Not too many other people could start over as many times as he
has. Then again, not too many people ever had to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
