<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANTE GETS OPPORTUNITY WHILE REPLACING INJURED NIEUWENDYK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Stanley Cup sat in the middle of the room.
The champagne bottles were empty. It was 4:30 the morning after,
and the party had just begun.
</P>
<P>
   In that intoxicating moment, Derek Plante stood and poured out
heartfelt thanks to his teammates like the bubbly that had flowed
all night.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that Plante, who had been traded from Buffalo 98
days earlier, became a part of the Stars. It is now that he becomes
a player for the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   When Joe Nieuwendyk was sidelined by a back injury Wednesday,
Plante took over the role of second-line center. Nieuwendyk, who
missed Wednesday's victory against Edmonton, had a magnetic
resonance imaging (MRI) test yesterday to determine the extent of
his injury.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Nieuwendyk is listed as day to day, Plante is
preparing as if he is going to play tonight against New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just come to play every day, I guess, hoping I get a chance
to play,'' Plante said. ``Unfortunately, Joe got hurt, but for me,
I've got a chance to go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars already were missing five regular players because of
injury when Nieuwendyk hobbled off the ice after Wednesday's
pregame skate. The Starshad come to expect the worst this season
but were unprepared for this blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nieuwendyk's one blew me away,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said. ``We weren't ready for that. We had no idea. There was no
buildup to it or anything. It just, boom, it just happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Plante went into the pregame skate expecting to be a healthy
scratch for the fourth consecutive game. He came out of the pregame
skate on the No. 2 line with Jamie Langenbrunner and Aaron Gavey on
the wings. Plante, an offensive support player, earned his keep by
setting up the second goal in the Stars' 2-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks ago, Plante was not even sure his future was
with the Stars. Now, he could have the Stars' immediate future in
his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Derek is a very skilled player with a great sense for the
game,'' Langenbrunner said. ``I just think he needs an opportunity.
That's what he's been looking for. When he came into the league, he
was playing a lot at Buffalo and scoring a lot and became a
big-time player for them. He found hard times there, and I think
he's having a hard time finding his role so to speak, a place where
he can play just to get him some confidence. When he plays with
confidence, I think he's a very effective player.''
</P>
<P>
   Plante is not Joe Nieuwendyk. He does not have a Conn Smythe
Trophy as the playoff MVP as Nieuwendyk earned in last season's
Stanley Cup run. He admits he does not command respect as
Nieuwendyk does.
</P>
<P>
   But he is not without skills. In five full seasons with the
Sabres, he scored 56 points twice and had another season of 53
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that I can play if I get out there and get to play a
fair amount and get to get back into rhythm,'' said Plante, 28.
``You become a little bit erratic if you don't play. I've been in
and out of the lineup, and that's a little difficult sometimes,
too, to get anything constant going.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars traded a second-round choice for Plante last March,
but he played in only 10 games. He did not appear in the Western
Conference finals or in the Stanley Cup Finals against his former
team. That did not stop him from a heart-felt acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knew much about Derek even after we traded for him,''
Hitchcock said. ``When we won in Buffalo, Derek really endeared
himself into this group by what he said. He brought himself closer
to the group, because he said some things that I even remember what
he said now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just talked about what it meant to him personally to be
part of the group, what it meant to him to be able to learn about
playing with an organization, things like that. It meant a lot. He
spoke eloquently. He kind of stopped the party with what he said. I
don't even know if he recognizes what he did, but it was
impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, if only he can be as impressive on the ice.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
