<HEADLINE>
SANDERS NOT CONCERNED WITH TALK FROM REDSKINS RECEIVERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Yada, yada, yada.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Cowboys cornerback Deion Sanders feels about the
talk from Redskins receiver Albert Connell and Michael Westbrook.
They're saying they will not only challenge his All-Pro reputation
Sunday, but beat him.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, whose ability to trash talks is on par with his ability
to play cornerback, refused to be engaged in a war of words with
the receivers. What else are they going to say, Sanders asked.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, talk from receivers before the game is nothing new. He
said he would put more stock in it if it were coming from the
various quarterbacks, who have combined to throw two passes in his
direction the past three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always like that before the game,'' Sanders said. ``We go
through this same thing, the same scenario, the same old talk, the
same old walk. Until you get out there on the field and see No. 21
sitting out there on that island, things are different. It has
nothing to do with the way they \RWestbrook and Connell\S feel. You
need to talk to the quarterback who's making the throws. All
receivers feel they are open on every play.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   The only injury concern heading into Sunday's game against the
Redskins is free safety George Teague, who missed his second day of
practice with a strained neck and remains doubtful. Backup Izell
Reese will start if Teague can't go.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Chad Hennings (strained neck) and Sanders
(sprained ankle), who both missed practice Wednesday, returned to
practice yesterday and should be ready for the Redskins.
nn
</P>
