<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-BILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SLOW ROAD TO BANKING OVERHAUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For more than 20 years, financial service firms
have tried to steer an overhaul of the nation's banking laws
through Congress, only to get lost each time in the legislative
maze. This year, the path has not been any less befuddling.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate have passed bills that would tear down
Depression-era walls that generally keep banks, brokerages and
insurance companies out of each other's lines of business. But
lawmakers were still working Thursday night to settle a dispute
over one provision with President Clinton, and they seemed far from
an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has said the provision would prompt a veto,
because it weakens an existing law that encourages banks to make
loans in low-income and minority communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never been closer,'' said Dan Zielinsky, spokesman for
the American Insurance Association. ``The sides are almost so close
that they can see the whites of each others eyes.'' And yet,
lobbyists for financial services firms acknowledged that there was
a strong chance they would fail yet again.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate negotiators, sometimes joined by Treasury
Secretary Lawrence Summers, have been working for three days to
settle their differences, and their talks continued into Thursday
evening. ``We're at a very dicey stage right now,'' said Senator
John F. Kerry, one of the lawmakers working on the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would replace the laws passed after the stock market
crash of 1929 and the Great Depression that generally prevent
banks, brokerages and insurance firms from merging with each other.
Allowing these firms to buy each other, say supporters of the bill,
would create financial service ``supermarkets'' that could offer
customers more services, operate more efficiently and compete with
the megabanks of Europe and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Current US law does not treat each sector of the finance
industry equally. Banks can buy brokerages, for example, but
brokerages cannot buy banks. The new law will ``level the playing
field'' among the various sectors, supporters say.
</P>
<P>
   One major US deal, the $70 billion merger of Citicorp and
Travelers Group Inc., is credited with pushing lawmakers to work
harder on an overhaul. That deal could not fully take effect under
existing laws, and its announcement last year was considered a
signal that the business world had become impatient with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some people who support much of the bill are unhappy with
two provisions: one involving customer privacy and one involving
bank commitments to low-income and minority communities.
</P>
<P>
   Under a provision already agreed to by lawmakers and Clinton,
personal information about customers could be shared among the
banking, stock brokerage and insurance arms of a single company.
The company could also share that information with other firms,
though customers would be able to ``opt out'' and prevent that type
of disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   The companies say the information-sharing will allow them to
better serve customers. The company could market homeowner's
insurance, for example, to a person who asks its banking unit for a
home mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates wanted the law to require companies to ask
customers before sharing information. They held out hope Thursday
that White House would reverse course and demand tougher privacy
protections.
</P>
<P>
   The second major debate involves the Community Reinvestment Act,
a 22-year-old law that requires banks that collect deposits in
low-income and minority communities to make sure they offer loans
in those neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Phil Gramm, the Texas Republican who leads the Senate
Banking Committee, is a critic of the CRA, arguing that it gives
community groups too much power to demand cash payments from banks
and commitments to loan programs for low-income people.
</P>
<P>
   Without naming the group, Gramm has criticized the Boston-based
Neighborhood Assistance Corp. of America, which has persuaded banks
across the country to back its loan program, aimed at low- and
moderate-income home buyers. NACA now closes 300 to 400 loans a
month and manages $3.7 billion in loan commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm wants to revise the CRA so that the government audits
small banks for compliance every five years, rather than the 18
months to 24 months in current practice.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry said he was ``fighting extremely hard'' in private
negotiations to find an agreement on the CRA changes. ``We ought to
be able to embrace financial modernization as well as protect the
CRA,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Marks, chief executive of NACA, said that public
disclosure of his group's agreements with banks would have a
``chilling effect'' on bank commitments to loan programs for low-
and moderate-income home buyers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 2221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
