u a BC-MEDICAL-JOURNAL-CONFL     10-21 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-JOURNAL-CONFLICTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ENGLAND JOURNAL SCRUTINIZES REVIEW RULES  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Challenged for allowing researchers with a financial interest in
medicines review their effectiveness in its pages, the New England
Journal of Medicine took the extraordinary step Thursday of posting
on its Web site two letters about its policy governing potential
conflicts of interest for contributors.
</P>
<P>
   While most medical journals accept articles from authors with
ties to the drug industry, since 1990 the New England Journal has
been more stringent, with a policy against publishing editorials or
review articles written by researchers who had accepted money from
manufacturers of the drug or device reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   But the journal has violated its own strict policy numerous
times in the last several years, according to a Los Angeles Times
article Thursday. In eight of 36 ``Drug Therapy'' articles examined
by the Times that were printed in NEJM since 1997, researchers had
financial links to companies that marketed treatments reviewed in
the articles, even though that was not disclosed to the reader.
</P>
<P>
   In the Sept. 23 issue of the NEJM, Dr. Vera Price of the
University of California at San Francisco, wrote a favorable review
of hair-loss treatments, with no disclosure in the journal of her
financial ties to companies that market some of the popular drugs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the letters posted Thursday on the magazine's Web site is
from Price to the NEJM editor saying that she was allowed to write
the article even after she had disclosed her commercial ties in
writing to the NEJM. The other letter is by journal editors
accepting responsibility for the departure from policy.
</P>
<P>
   Interim editor-in-chief Marcia Angell said the editors will go
back and talk to past authors of review articles about whether
conflicts-of-interest should have prohibited them from writing a
review article. The strict disclosure policy won't change, said
Angell, but the journal plans to change procedures so its practice
conforms with its policy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, NEJM also acknowledged that it had run a review of a
book on environmental carcinogens by the medical director at
chemical giant W. R. Grace &AMP; Co., and in 1996 published a favorable
editorial on anti-obesity drugs by authors who were paid
consultants for companies selling one of the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main question is if the grant support is major,'' Angell
said in an interview. She said that it is the journal's policy to
allow review articles by writers who have had minor support or past
consultancies from affected companies, and the NEJM has not
disclosed those links. ``Almost everyone at one time or another was
an ad hoc consultant for a company. It would really be impossible
to exclude everyone who has ever been a consultant,'' Angell said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alastair J.J. Wood of Vanderbilt University, the editor of
the ``Drug Therapy'' articles, said the journal has different
conflict policies for original research articles and for review
articles like the ``Drug Therapy'' ones.
</P>
<P>
   In the former, if the research is paid for by a company, the
researcher is allowed to write the article while disclosing the
link. However, such a connection would prohibit someone from
writing an editorial or a review article for journal because it is
the opinion of the reviewer that matters, said Wood. ``We are
trying to see if the content of the article would influence a
financial gain,'' said Wood, who sends a letter asking for authors
to volunteer possible conflicts-of-interest before they write a
piece.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, the stringent policy is ``extraordinarily hard,''
said Wood. ``It's hard to know what's minor and major.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Price case, ``there have been some misinterpretations,
but we in Boston also reviewed it and OK'd it,'' said Angell, who
said that she is making some changes in procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Angell said that ``effective immediately,'' potential authors
will have to list all origins of grant support and past
consultations, including funding from the public sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can see how recent is recent, and how past is past,''
Angell said.
</P>
<P>
   Another change is that the journal will disclose even a
researcher's minor grant support from a company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it's pizza money, so readers can decide,'' Angell
said. The NEJM Web site is www.nejm.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
