<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4620 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-YANKS-NYT &LR;      10-21 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS, NOT WORDS, IN THE LULL BEFORE THE STORM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the Nielsen ratings were based strictly on the
Yankees' watching, then Atlanta's Game 6 victory over the Mets in
the National League Championship Series Tuesday would have had
complete viewership. In their homes in Manhattan, in Westchester
and New Jersey and Long Island, the Yankees were all watching, and
the Braves' aggressiveness on the bases made a strong impression on
them.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' success _ or failure _ at preventing the Braves
from running freely, stealing second and third, will be a critical
factor in the World Series, which starts Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, said Thursday at Yankee Stadium
that Orlando Hernandez will start Game 1, against the Braves' Tom
Glavine, in Atlanta; David Cone faces Greg Maddux in Game 2; Andy
Pettitte will pitch against the Braves' Kevin Millwood in Game 3,
when the series shifts to Yankee Stadium, and Roger Clemens will
throw against John Smoltz in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees worked for about two hours Thursday, position
players and pitchers taking batting practice, and they will fly to
Atlanta Friday morning and practice at Turner Field in the
afternoon. Before their workout Friday, the Yankees' scouting staff
will brief them on the intelligence gathered in the last six weeks.
Thick orange binders have been filled with pages of information on
where the Braves' hitters tend to drive the ball, what they like to
swing at, and what Glavine, Maddux and the rest like to throw in
specific situations.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees saw the Braves swipe five bases against the Mets
on Tuesday, and they are well aware that Atlanta _ attempting to
compensate for the loss of Andres Galarraga and Javy Lopez from its
lineup _ is committed to being aggressive on the bases and
challenging the defense. Two other significant factors will be the
Yankees' ability to exploit the free-swinging and sometimes
undisciplined Atlanta hitters, as well as the Yankees' success in
coping with a Braves bullpen steeped in left-handed relief.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves stole 14 bases in 6 games against the Mets, and have
18 steals in 10 post-season games. ``Their entire lineup runs with
the exception of their catcher,'' said Mel Stottlemyre, the
Yankees' pitching coach. ``It looks like a very good base-running
team; they're going to be aggressive, and we know that.
</P>
<P>
   It so happens that the Yankees' starting pitchers sometimes
struggled to hold runners on base this year. American League teams
are passive on the basepaths, by and large, but Hernandez
surrendered 19 stolen bases, Cone 22. Even Pettitte, who has an
exceptional pickoff move, began having problems containing base
stealers after runners learned that it's easy to swipe third on his
slow delivery to home plate.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, Cone and Clemens do not have good pickoff moves. What
they will do, said catcher Joe Girardi, is try to disturb the
timing of the base runners. Cone and Hernandez will often hold the
ball longer, stand on the mound and wait, poised to pitch, and they
will bob their heads, to distract the runner. Clemens will throw to
first base repeatedly, over and over, ignoring the jeers of fans so
long as he can force a runner to dive back to first repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   But Stottlemyre doesn't want his pitchers to become obsessed
with holding runners close and reduce their focus on making a good
pitch. The Yankees' philosophy, in calling pitches, is to ignore
the presence of the runner and make the best pitch possible to
retire the batter rather than just throw fastballs to increase the
chances of throwing out someone trying to steal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to still be comfortable in what you throw, even when
you're holding runners on,'' Stottlemyre said. ``We're hoping we
can stop their running game by not allowing runners on base.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre thought the Yankees did ``a fairly good job'' of
slowing Boston's running game in the American League Championship
Series. The Braves will be a far greater challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is like the Texas Rangers, capable of generating mass
numbers of runs; the Braves slugged 197 home runs, fourth-best in
the National League and more than the Yankees (193). But the
Braves, like the Rangers, are sometimes too aggressive. They ranked
third in the league in strikeouts, and their average of 3.56
pitches per plate appearance was far less than the league median
(3.71).
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' pitching staff has been able to take advantage of
that sort of aggressiveness in the post-season, when their starters
are armed with reams of scouting information _ Andruw Jones will
swing at anything _ and the type of control needed to capitalize on
the reports. ``I really feel like we probably do that as well as
anybody,'' Stottlemyre said. ``We get great information from our
scouting department, and it's up to us to put that in use. We have
risen to the occasion pretty well in the post-season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who averaged six runs per game during the regular
season, scored twice in six playoff games against the Yankees in
1998 and '99, while continually flailing at pitches just off the
fringes of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones is a tremendous threat, but he averaged 3.64
pitches per plate appearance, an extremely low figure for a batter
with 126 walks, and had 94 strikeouts. Brian Jordan, who bats
behind Jones, averaged just 3.51 pitches per plate appearance, and
struck out 81 times. Gerald Williams, the Atlanta leadoff hitter,
is notoriously aggressive, and the No. 2 batter, Bret Boone,
accumulated just 45 walks and 112 strikeouts, the sign of an
anxious hitter. They all have weaknesses the Yankees will try to
exploit.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' bullpen is blessed with three established
left-handed relievers, in the closer John Rocker and the set-up men
Mike Remlinger and Terry Mulholland _ and the Yankees have had
problems against left-handers all year.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill's .190 average against left-handers was the lowest
for any regular player in the American League, Bernie Williams'
right-handed swing has been hampered by the soreness in his left
shoulder, and even Derek Jeter _ a right-handed batter _ hit 84
points lower against left-handers than right-handers this season.
Jimy Williams, the Boston manager, exploited this weakness in the
championship series, calling on the left-hander Rheal Cormier to
pitch to everyone from Jeter to Tino Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   But Cormier was Williams' only left-hander; Bobby Cox, the
Atlanta manager, has three, and the Yankees' lineup is heavy with
left-handed hitters. After the sixth inning, Cox figures to call on
his left-handers against the Yankees, and could have great success.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker held left-handed hitters to a .140 average during the
regular season. They batted .205 against Remlinger. Mulholland was
slightly better against left-handed hitters (.290) than
right-handed ones (.299). The Yankees need to avoid situations in
which they have to come back in the late innings, because the
matchups are so unfavorable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
