<HEADLINE>
AIKMAN SAYS COWBOYS' OFFENSE HURTS FOR CONFIDENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Troy Aikman admitted yesterday that back-to-back
road losses by identical 13-10 scores have eroded the confidence of
the players on the Cowboys' offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what this whole league is about; it's about playing
with confidence,'' the Cowboys quarterback said. ``That's what we
have to get back.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's hard to make a ``first down'' with ``chin down''.
</P>
<P>
   But if there is a panic button located somewhere in Valley
Ranch, it isn't being pushed by owner Jerry Jones, who understands
how confidence can be lost in business, in life or on the football
field over a matter of a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something doesn't work, we look in the mirror and
second-guess ourselves. That's as human as breathing,'' Jones said.
``That doesn't surprise me at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, it has happened to some of Jones' most elite
players who represent the biggest chunk of his payroll _ the
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman said yesterday that he still believes in the Chan Gailey
offense; that most Cowboys players consider Sunday's game against
Washington a must-win situation (although Aikman added that these
same players also know that there are 10 games remaining after
Sunday); and that while everyone is working extra hard to get the
offense on track this week, there is no guarantee that anyone has
found the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that anybody has the answer,'' said Aikman, who
said he has had input into meetings this week with Gailey and
quarterbacks coach Buddy Geis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've shown, at times, that we're capable of doing what we did
\R541 yards total offense and 41 points against Washington Sept.
12\S, but we certainly haven't done it over the last two weeks,''
Aikman said. ``When you don't go out and do it, it certainly tends
to take away from your confidence as a group.
</P>
<P>
   So, he concluded, ``we have to go out and play consistently and
have some success, so that this group can start playing with some
confidence again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like the chicken-and-egg theory. Which comes first?
</P>
<P>
   How do the Cowboys go about jump-starting their confidence on
offense to be able to break this two-game skid and start winning
again?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good question. I don't know if there is any one way
to do it,'' Aikman replied. ``We've gone back and looked at what
we've done well, and we're trying to focus in on those things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, in their past two games combined (300 yards vs.
Philadelphia, 274 yards vs. the New York Giants) had only 33 yards
more than they rolled up in their season-opening victory at
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the Cowboys have scored 21 fewer points in two games
combined (10 each against the Eagles and Giants) than they scored
against the Redskins in that 41-35 opener that was decided in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey has made the decision this week to streamline the game
plan for Sunday and try to strike a happy medium with the running
and passing games. The Giants stuffed the Cowboys' running game
Monday night with the run blitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what has been decided to try to correct some of the
problems that we've had, and I'm in favor of that,'' Aikman said.
``Offense is so much playing with confidence, playing with timing.
The execution part is so important.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you lose any of that, it becomes very difficult to have any
kind of success.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gailey offense _ now 22 games old, including four games in
which the opposition has scored 13 points or less and ``won'' _
seems to be a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me just say, if you have to have somebody tinker with your
offense, Chan Gailey is the right man to do it,'' Jones said
yesterday. ``If you need to call a doctor, in my opinion, he's the
one I'd call.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Aikman: ``Based on what has happened the last two weeks
makes this game just that \Rmuch\S more important. If we're going
into this game 5-0 \Rinstead of 3-2\S, then the dynamics of the
game changes a little bit, even though it shouldn't. You go out to
win every single ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he want the players inside the Cowboys' locker room to
consider this a must-win situation?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone does,'' Aikman continued. ``Of course, the
only real must-win situation is when you get into the playoffs ...
but this is an important game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the question everybody seems to be asking this week,
Aikman concluded:
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is that it's frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``How frustrating?
</P>
<P>
   ``''Very'' frustrating.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
