<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: SELLING TO CHILDREN, OR MANIPULATING THEM? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., N.Y.)  (mk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deploring what they see as an unfair and conflict-ridden
manipulation of the young, a group of psychologists and other
professionals has called on the American Psychological Association
to restrict the use of psychological research by advertisers
pitching toys, videogames, snack food and other products to
children.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, written by Gary Ruskin, who heads Commercial Alert,
a Washington-based advocacy group, and Allen Kanner, a clinical
psychologist at the Wright Institute in Berkeley, Calif., was sent
to the association's president late last month. It urges the
association to issue a formal denunciation of the use of
psychological techniques in marketing and advertising to children,
and asks for amendments to the association's code of ethics that
would address the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, which was signed by 60 psychologists and other
professionals with affiliations ranging from Sonoma State
University to Harvard Medical School, also calls for ``an ongoing
campaign to probe, review and confront the use of psychological
research in advertising and marketing to children,'' which would
include promoting strategies to shield children from ``commercial
manipulation and exploitation'' by psychologists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regrettably, a large gap has arisen between APA's mission and
the drift of the profession into helping corporations influence
children for the purpose of selling products to them,'' the letter
stated.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the association said the matter had been
referred to its internal board on children, youth and family
issues, and that the board was scheduled to meet in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly there's no mention of the issue in our code of
conduct,'' said the spokeswoman, Rhea Farberman, adding that the
points raised in the letter had not been brought before the
association before.
</P>
<P>
   Kanner said he wrote the letter after becoming concerned,
through his own conversations with children and teen-age patients,
that they were, as a group, blatantly materialistic. ``I'll ask
kids what they want to do when they grow up, and lots of times
they'll tell me, `Make money,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for psychologists' role in that, he said research conducted
at the university level was frequently deployed in developing
commercials and other pitches to children. Since the stated mission
of the American Psychological Association is ``to improve the
condition of both the individual and society,'' he concluded that
permitting research to be used in advertising to children presented
a conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are taking this very sophisticated understanding of
children's relationships and what they respond to, and then really
tailoring it to the advertisement and refining it,'' he said.
``There's no indication that it's helping kids with their
relationships at all, but rather that it's manipulating them.''
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Kasser, an associate professor of psychology at Knox
College in Galesburg, Ill., who signed the letter, said he did so
because he saw ``a great deal of collusion between some members of
psychology and marketing, advertising and entrepreneurial firms
that are working together to try to understand how best to sell
things to kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasser said his research with a colleague, Richard Ryan of the
University of Rochester, had concluded that people who value goals
like money, fame and beauty are not only more depressed than
others, but also report more behavioral problems and physical
discomfort, as well as scoring lower on measures of vitality and
self-actualization.
</P>
<P>
   For children, the consequences can be similarly damaging, Kasser
said. ``When advertisers are using psychological principles to sell
products to children, they are not only selling that product, but
they are also selling a larger value system that says making money
and using your money for the purchase of material things will make
you happy,'' he said. ``That's what is really behind almost every
commercial message, that this product will make you feel happy, or
loved, or safe and secure. My feeling is that it is manipulation to
use children's needs to get them to buy these products.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every psychologist feels the same way. ``The whole point is,
if you're going to market to kids, do it responsibly and there are
a whole lot of opportunities to make a positive difference,'' said
Dan Acuff, who holds a doctorate in psychology and runs a company
called Youth Market Systems Consulting in Sherman Oaks, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Acuff, who called the goals stated in the letter ``anti-free
enterprise,'' published a book titled ``What Kids Buy and Why'' in
1997 that offers insights into how to create a successful
children's product. Included are discussions of neocortical
development, in which children start to rely more on intellect,
logic and reasoning and less on fantasy for their decision- making.
That, Acuff notes, in italics, ``has critical implications for
product and program development as well as marketing and
advertising to kids in the 8-through-12 age range.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is a line psychologists should draw, he added this
week. ``We turn down opportunities that would be damaging to
kids,'' he said, ``like toys with serious weapons in them _ guns,
bombs, rifles and things like that.'' Fantasy weapons, like those
carried by He-Man and Star Wars figures, were acceptable to him, he
added, but those based on ``modern technological weapons'' were
not.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Farberman, the association's spokeswoman, said psychological
techniques were also being used for ``socially redeeming issues,''
like advertising campaigns to urge people not to drink and drive.
``It's important not to lose sight of that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Halpin, the chief executive of Geppetto Group, which
specializes in children's advertising, said psychologists were
important in helping her company understand children and their
capabilities. ``For example, we learned that 6- and 7-year-olds
don't understand double-entendres,'' she said. ``They are simply
trying to learn one meaning of a word at that age. So advertising
copy that uses double-entendres as a clever device would not be
appropriate, or effective. It's things like that that help us do
the best job we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kasser raised a question: ``Maybe we're helping the
economy, but is that our mission as a discipline?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0489 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4631 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GARGANO-INQUIRY-ART-6     10-21 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARGANO-INQUIRY-ART-685(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATION CASTS PALL OVER N.Y. STATE ECONOMIC AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN and CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For five years, the Empire State Development Corp.,
the state agency charged with fostering a climate conducive to
business, has been credited with helping to rejuvenate New York
with its efforts to create jobs, eliminate red tape and direct
ambitious projects like the redevelopment of Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   But since last fall, the corporation has been buffeted by a
criminal investigation by the Manhattan district attorney's office
that has examined everything from the agency's role in
multimillion-dollar development deals to the travel logs of its
high-profile chairman, Charles Gargano.
</P>
<P>
   Month after month, the agency has been beset by subpoenas for
documents, and more than 10 current and former staff members have
been interviewed by investigators and a grand jury that is
examining the process by which state grants and contracts were
awarded.
</P>
<P>
   Subpoenas have also been served on companies that received aid
from the agency, restaurants that catered state-organized functions
and institutions like the Metropolitan Museum of Art that held
agency receptions.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the intensity of the investigation, its progress remains
unclear: Prosecutors will not discuss their inquiry, which to date
has resulted in a just a single attempted bribery charge against a
deputy commissioner, Paolo Palombo.
</P>
<P>
   To the agency's defenders, the very breadth and length of the
inquiry are evidence that the investigation is little more than a
fishing expedition initiated on the basis of vague whispers of
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   But the constant scrutiny has become an undeniable distraction
at the agency, where staff members say they fear that even an
unproductive investigation may tarnish the agency's record.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry also threatens to take a toll on Gargano, a wealthy
former construction executive who rose to political prominence
because of his success as a Republican fund-raiser. Gargano took
office in 1995, fending off accusations that he would use the state
agency that distributes business grants to reward campaign
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Now the inquiry, which has included an examination of his phone
logs, his business holdings and a trip he took to Italy last year,
threatens to delay, and could derail, his appointment to a
prominent position within the presidential campaign of George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Gargano told friends he expected to leave the
agency in early October for the Bush campaign. But the campaign has
yet to create a spot for Gargano, and he was all but invisible
during Bush's recent two-day campaign swing through New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Gargano's allies say his appointment is still imminent, although
there is some talk of naming him to a lower-profile state party
campaign post. A spokesman for the Bush campaign, Scott McClellan,
said, ``We have not made any decision on our New York leadership,
with the exception of Governor Pataki.''
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney's investigation began last year as a
modest inquiry into whether agency officials misspent funds from
annual state receptions to honor Italian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Within months, it had evolved into a broad exploration of issues
as diverse as the pending sale of state land on Long Island to
purchasers who include Republican campaign contributors, and the
nature of state-sponsored development deals in Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking at everything,'' said an official who worked
on one of the deals under scrutiny and said that Gargano's role was
negligible. ``He's been around the block. He wouldn't allow himself
to get hooked into anything that'll cause him a problem. He's been
pretty tough on deals, in my experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Gargano, who has not been charged with wrongdoing, declined to
be interviewed. Maura Gallucci, his spokeswoman, said the agency
was cooperating fully.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything done here at ESDC and by Charles Gargano is
completely appropriate and above reproach,'' Ms. Gallucci said.
``Is the DA's office using the investigation into Palombo as an
opportunity to randomly look into activities at ESDC and Charles
Gargano? I don't know the answer, but I hope not.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One of the subpoenas, for example, requested records on the
state subsidies given to Nine West, a shoe manufacturer that was
persuaded to move its headquarters from Connecticut to Westchester
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks before Gov. George Pataki announced the deal, in which
state and local governments provided the company with incentives
worth $7 million, the company's chief executive officer at the time
donated $15,000 to the Republican State Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation's focus was much narrower last fall when
prosecutors first began to hear complaints that bills from
state-sponsored Italian heritage celebrations had gone unpaid even
though various corporations like Coca-Cola and Banco di Napoli had
stepped in to help underwrite the affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The huge receptions, intended to honor Italian-Americans and
foster business and cultural ties with Italy, were held each year
at the Boathouse in Central Park, the Metropolitan Museum and other
stylish reception sites that could accommodate 1,500 business
leaders and politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Gargano at times made the initial contact to arrange for the
affairs, according to people who helped arrange the events. He left
the details like raising the money or booking the caterers to
Palombo, an old friend whom he had appointed the agency's deputy
commissioner for international business.
</P>
<P>
   Palombo and Gargano had known each other for two decades, their
lives entwined by a mutual interest in all things Italian. Palombo
was a talkative former baker and professor of Italian literature at
Fordham University who liked to be referred to as Il Professore.
</P>
<P>
   Gargano, who hired Palombo in 1995, relied on him not only to
lure foreign investment to New York, but also to write his speeches
in Italian, associates of the two men said.
</P>
<P>
   When vendors from the Italian heritage events began complaining
about unpaid bills, prosecutors began exploring how Palombo had
spent some of the money he had raised, according to people who have
been interviewed by investigators.
</P>
<P>
   One company, Roma View Catering of Queens, which had catered an
event aboard the aircraft carrier Intrepid in 1997, threatened to
sue the state because its $9,000 bill had gone unpaid for nine
months. The agency arranged to pay the bill as year after the
events.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also questioned whether Palombo had siphoned money
from a 1988 trade show for Italian artisans that had been held at
Cipriani Wall Street, a Manhattan catering site, according to those
interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Palombo had helped to arrange the event. Gargano had promoted it
as one of the fruits of the state's expanded business relationship
with Italy. A friend of Palombo's had been hired as the general
contractor who oversaw the budget for the show.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, last June, after being questioned about these
events, Palombo agreed to plead guilty to a bribery charge. The
complaint said that he had agreed to accept $30,000 from the
manager for an Italian sculptor who had sought Palombo's help in
getting one of the artist's statues, a bronze depiction of Ulysses,
placed on state property at Battery Park City.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Palombo say he used the money not for his own
purposes, but to pay expenses from one of the Italian heritage
receptions. Nonetheless, he was forced to resign from his $91,877 a
year state job in July.
</P>
<P>
   As the investigation continued, Palombo told prosecutors he had
used $6,000 of the money taken from the trade show to buy
first-class plane tickets to Italy for Gargano and the former Miss
America Phyllis George, according to people familiar with the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have a copy of a $6,000 check, drawn on a Palombo
family bakery account, that Palombo said he used to pay for the
trip last summer, the people familiar with the case said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Gargano nor Ms. George would discuss the trip or how it
was financed.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear that accepting such tickets violates the state
law that governs the conduct of public officials. The law prohibits
officials from accepting gifts of more than $75 if it can be
inferred that the gift was given to influence the official in the
performance of his duties.
</P>
<P>
   There is no provision that bars a supervisor from accepting a
gift from a subordinate, unless the gift could be shown to have
been given as an inducement of some kind.
</P>
<P>
   However, the law requiring officials to report all gifts of more
than $1,000 is quite clear. Gargano did not list any tickets or
gifts from Palombo on his state financial disclosure form for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Gargano's allies contend that Palombo is trying to divert
attention from himself. ``It is unfortunate, but not unusual, that
someone in his position would try to save himself by attempting to
point a finger at others,'' Ms. Gallucci said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, however, the investigation has roamed far from
areas where Palombo had a role. The Nine West package, for example,
was arranged by another division of the agency in 1996 to spur job
growth in Westchester County and to stabilize the commercial real
estate market in White Plains, where a third of the buildings were
vacant.
</P>
<P>
   The move by Nine West from Stamford to White Plains brought
1,200 jobs to the state and provided a new tenant for one of
Westchester's largest office complexes. But prosecutors have
subpoenaed the records of the deal from both the state and the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did receive a subpoena, and we responded to it,'' said Jeff
Howald, the company's chief financial officer. He declined to
discuss the deal further.
</P>
<P>
   At the time the deal was announced, the company's chief
executive officer at the time, Vincent Camuto, said Gargano's
personal intercession had helped persuade the company to make the
move. Camuto, who gave $15,000 to the state Republican Party 13
days before the deal was announced, did not return calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney has subpoenaed records on other deals as
well, including the pending $50.3 million sale of three parcels of
surplus state land on Long Island. The prospective purchaser of one
of the parcels is Arlen Contracting, whose principal, Alvin
Benjamin, is a veteran Republican contributor.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have also sought records on the construction of
Gargano's new million-dollar home in Bridgehampton, his son's
construction company, which built the home, the redevelopment deal
for downtown New Rochelle, and a casino company, Alpha Hospitality,
in which Gargano once owned stock and served as a director.
</P>
<P>
   The continuing barrage of subpoenas has left some executives at
the state agency exhausted and bewildered. Last April, when yet one
more request for records arrived at the agency, an executive
circulated an internal memo to top staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need your collective assistance,'' the memo said, ``in
responding to a grand jury subpoena (yes, another subpoena) that
ESDC has received from the Manhattan district attorney.''
</P>
</TEXT>
