<HEADLINE>
MANNESMANN SHARES FALL AFTER $33 BILLION CELLULAR PHONE BID 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Mannesmann AG, Germany's aggressive and acquisitive
engineering and telecommunications giant, intensified the
competition to dominate European mobile phone markets Thursday,
offering nearly $33 billion in stock and cash for Orange PLC,
Britain's No. 3 cellular operator.
</P>
<P>
   But investors frowned on the price, sending Mannesmann's stock
down in Frankfurt 9.5 percent, to 143.50 euros, or $155.27, even as
Klaus Esser, the chief executive, argued at a news conference here
against comparing the price for Orange with the $11.1 billion paid
by the rival Deutsche Telekom for One 2 One, the No. 4 British
wireless operator, two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should never compare apples and oranges,'' he said,
maintaining that Orange would grow at a much faster pace than One 2
One next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Mannesmann bid was supported by Orange's principal
shareholder, the Hong Kong-based conglomerate Hutchison Whampoa
Ltd., which controls 44.8 percent of Orange stock. The deal will
make Hutchison Whampoa the biggest single shareholder in
Mannesmann, with 10 percent of the stock and a board seat.
Hutchison agreed not to sell roughly 80 percent of its new
Mannesmann stock for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann said it was offering 0.0965 share and 6.40 pounds
($10.73) in cash and notes for each Orange share. The bid valued
Orange at 16.29 pounds ($27.31) a share at Wednesday's close _ a 22
percent premium to Orange's closing price on Monday before
Mannesmann confirmed it was negotiating a deal. In addition, it
will assume $3.34 billion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   The fall in Mannesmann's stock brought the bid price below 15.30
pounds a share. Mannesmann said it would finance the cash part of
the deal with interim bank loans totaling 12 billion euros, raising
further concerns about its high debt levels.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Orange, which has yet to make a profit since it was
created five years ago, rose 4.7 percent Thursday, to 14.47 pounds
($24.26) _ still below the offering price. Analysts said Mannesmann
is relying on Orange's growth prospects in a rapidly expanding
European market where it could become the leader with 20 million
customers _ including 3.5 million from Orange.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Orange would give Mannesmann a strong
presence in the three biggest European markets. That could be a
problem for Vodafone Airtouch of Britain, the world's biggest
mobile operator, which has 31 million customers worldwide, about 13
million of them in Europe, but also a sizable minority share in
Mannesmann's D2 network along with partnership deals in Italy and
France.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
