<SLUG> BC-IRS-CHARITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MOVES TO SHUT DOWN THE `CHUTZPAH TRUST' 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The government is moving to shut down the latest version of what
critics call the ``chutzpah trust,'' under which a legitimate
charitable-giving device is adapted to let wealthy donors escape
all taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The trust has been condemned by charity officials and estate
lawyers and by the National Committee on Planned Giving, all of
whom have called it so brazen that it invites Congress to tighten
the rules that benefit charities and their donors.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence H. Summers said that new regulations
were intended to end the trusts by taxing them. ``Shutting down
schemes like this helps us build a culture of compliance,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a normal charitable remainder trust an individual donates
property, often highly appreciated stock, to a trust that will pass
it on to a charity when the donor dies. The donor avoids capital
gains taxes and gets an immediate income tax deduction for the
donated property.
</P>
<P>
   He or she also gets back an annual stream of income, typically 7
percent a year. Federal tax rules require the donor to pay taxes on
the investment earnings that are used for these payments under a
tiered system that counts first earned income, then capital gains,
tax-exempt income from municipal bonds, any other income and then
return of principal.
</P>
<P>
   In a ``chutzpah trust'' the assets are invested so as not to
produce taxable income and the trustee borrows against the trust
assets to make the payments to the donor.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan G. Blattmachr, a tax partner in the law firm of
Milbank, Tweed, Hadley &AMP; McCloy in Manhattan, said the trusts
complied with the rules that Congress created at the request of the
Treasury Department that set tiers of income for taxing the stream
of payments from charitable remainder trusts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wrote the rules and now you have to live with them,''
Blattmachr said. ``You can't change the rules in the middle of a
card game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
