<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4781 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE     10-21 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 THE LIVES OF McCAIN-FEINGOLD  
(dal) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Oct. 22:
</P>
<P>
   Trent Lott declared the McCain-Feingold campaign finance reform
bill dead on Tuesday when it failed to overcome the roadblocks
thrown in its way by, among others, Lott. Mitch McConnell, the
Senate Republicans' chief fund-raiser, said the bill had made no
headway in gaining support. They were being deceptive. In fact, the
test votes this week reflected significant progress, with 55
senators _ including 10 Republicans, 3 more than were on board this
summer _ endorsing a soft-money ban in one form or another. That
base can be expanded if McCain and other supporters make good on
their promise to bring this measure up again and again, forcing the
Senate to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   If the issue were as dead as he asserted, Lott, the majority
leader, would have no need for the duplicitous, high-handed tactics
he employed to block it. This summer he promised McCain a full five
days of debate, and a full opportunity for amendments. In return,
McCain pledged not to bring the issue up again this year if it
failed to get the 60 votes needed to cut off a filibuster. But when
the time came, Lott simply reneged on his promise. He allowed
barely more than three days, asserting that introducing the bill at
dinnertime and then shutting down the Senate for the night counted
as one of the days of debate. Lott and McConnell obviously feared
that any extended debate might arouse the public's interest and add
to the pressure on Congress.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Feingold got some criticism for stripping the bill
down to a simple ban on unlimited contributions to political
parties for use by candidates. There were complaints about omitting
the original provision that applied fund-raising curbs to
independent groups that use the money for campaign ads. But the
tactic paid off. Senators Sam Brownback of Kansas, William Roth of
Delaware and Tim Hutchinson of Arkansas voted to kill the
filibuster against the simpler bill, panicking Lott and McConnell,
who then bludgeoned two longtime supporters of the soft-money ban _
Arlen Specter and John Chafee _ into opposing the debate cutoff.
</P>
<P>
   Lott is looking more and more like Newt Gingrich, who broke his
promises to let campaign finance reform be considered in the House
last year. House Republicans took the matter into their own hands,
forcing him to bring it to the floor. The wavering in Lott's caucus
could be seen Wednesday morning, when the majority leader tried to
change the subject of campaign reform to abortion and six
Republicans broke ranks and voted against the move. It is highly
unusual for senators to challenge their leader on a procedural
issue.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has made it clear that he now feels no obligation to
honor his promise not to bring up campaign reform again this year.
He and others have made the analogy to the civil rights struggles
of the 1960s, when it took innumerable cloture votes and threats of
filibusters to bring the issue to the attention of voters. With the
spread of more and more ``soft money'' _ the unlimited donations
from corporations, unions and rich donors _ the public's impatience
for reform will grow. Each new attempt at debate and amendment
could draw in senators like Chuck Hagel of Nebraska, whose
proposals to amend the bill, though flawed, suggest that he and
others might be prepared to back the bill in some form.
</P>
<P>
   Now that it is clear that the Republican fund-raising machine is
thwarting the will of 55 senators, the voices of Americans need to
be heard. McCain was right when he told his colleagues that sooner
or later reform would happen. It can happen sooner if supporters do
not give up now. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
