<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING DRASTIC CHANGES IS LESS LIKELY FOR RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rangers owner Tom Hicks has given general
manager Doug Melvin the flexibility to build next year's team
without cutting the $75 million payroll.
</P>
<P>
   The first step in Melvin's approach to doing that is addressing
the club's nine potential free agents. Only then will he get an
idea how much it will cost to put together the team and if they
need to trade outfielder Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need to do is talk to our own free agents and see if
they want to stay here,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said it is premature to talk about trading Gonzalez,
Rusty Greer or any other player until the Rangers see where what
appears to be a weak free-agent market is headed.
</P>
<P>
   With the flexibility given to him by Hicks, Melvin said: ``I
don't think our team will be drastically different. Our ownership
has given us the flexibility if the right thing comes up.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin and Hicks met earlier this week to outline the club's
course of action during the off-season. The Rangers have targeted a
payroll of less than $75 million, but Melvin and Hicks emphasized
that could change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get better,'' Hicks said. ``Doug has some very
good ideas. In fact, we went through three hours of his ideas. It's
a process that will be on-going.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has one year left on his contract at $7.5 million and
could be a free agent after next season. A National League
executive said last week, ``If the Rangers want to trade Gonzalez,
there will be teams interested.''
</P>
<P>
   But his future with the Rangers also could be determined by what
happens in Seattle. Mariners outfielder Ken Griffey Jr. and
shortstop Alex Rodriguez are also eligible for free agency after
the 2000 season and major-league officials estimate they could
command between $15 million and $20 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to analyze where the industry is going and what
happens with Griffey and Rodriguez,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are trying to re-sign both, but Rodriguez's agent,
Scott Boras, has said they won't sign a long-term deal this
off-season. Boras said that includes the Mariners or another team
if Rodriguez is traded.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bronner, Gonzalez's agent, is making no such public
statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever we decide to do, we're going to keep it between us
and the Rangers,'' Bronner said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   This is considered a weak free-agent market. The best players
available appear to be Cincinnati outfielder Greg Vaughn, New York
Yankees pitcher David Cone and New York Mets first baseman John
Olerud. The market looks much stronger after next season, with
Griffey, Rodriguez, Gonzalez, Baltimore pitcher Mike Mussina,
Cincinnati shortstop Barry Larkin, Cleveland outfielder Manny
Ramirez, Houston second baseman Craig Biggio, Toronto outfielder
Shawn Green and Toronto first baseman Carlos Delgado.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin has indicated his priority is still pitching. The Rangers
have interest in re-signing right-hander Aaron Sele, but Melvin
also wants to add at least one left-handed starter. The top
free-agent left-handed pitchers appear to be Kenny Rogers, Chuck
Finley and Darren Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   But priorities have a way of changing in the off-season. The
Rangers started last off-season trying to sign pitcher Randy
Johnson and trade for Roger Clemens, then ended up signing first
baseman Rafael Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time last year, I had no idea we would sign Raffy,''
Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin's plan right now is to look at his own free agents, and
second baseman Mark McLemore could move to the top of the list.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers expect to reduce payroll by going with rookies Ruben
Mateo in center field and Mike Lamb at third base instead of Tom
Goodwin and Todd Zeile, moves that would cut approximately $6
million from the payroll.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers aren't ready to commit to rookie Kelly
Dransfeldt at second base; he hit .237 this season at Triple-A
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to talk to Mark,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore is 35, but is coming off one of his best seasons. He
hit .274 with 83 walks and 105 runs scored and was fifth among
American League second baseman in fielding. He has had knee
troubles the past three seasons, but this year he played in 144 of
162 games.
</P>
<P>
   There are several options among free agents but no clear-cut
answers. The candidates include Mickey Morandini of the Cubs and
Braves utility man Jose Hernandez. Houston's Ricky Gutierrez and
Kansas City's Rey Sanchez both played shortstop this year but could
be converted to second base.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
