<SLUG> BC-RAC-MARTIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAINER UNDERSTANDS JOCKEY'S TOUGH CHOICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ James Lackey knows what Jacky Martin is
going through. Martin rode two horses trained by Lackey and
qualified them for the finals of the $212,350 Dash For Cash Derby
scheduled tonight at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   Okey Dokey Dale was the fastest qualifier in the trials two
weeks ago, but Martin chose fourth-fastest Heza Bold Man. Lackey, a
former jockey, knows why.
</P>
<P>
   Heza Bold Man ``slipped getting away from the gates and pulled a
shoe halfway off and had to run like that all the way down there,''
Lackey said. ``Both horses are doing really well, and I know it was
a tough decision for Jacky.''
</P>
<P>
   Lackey can look at Okey Dokey Dale and remember a time when he
didn't have to make a decision like that. Not only does Lackey
train Okey Dokey Dale, but when he was a jockey, he rode the two
horses that eventually produced Okey Dokey Dale. He rode Okey Dokey
Dale's sire _ First Down Dash _ to win the Champion of Champions in
1987. And the dam _ Okey Dokey Baby _ won the 1988 Kansas Futurity
with Lackey aboard.
</P>
<P>
   First Down Dash and Okey Dokey Baby never met on the track. But
if they had, Lackey would have picked First Down Dash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that Okey Dokey Baby wasn't a great horse,'' Lackey said.
``But First Down Dash won seven of eight races as a 3-year-old and
not only beat older horses, he won by a bunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``First Down Dash, when he went out to the racetrack, there was
no going slow at all. Okey Dokey Dale has the same hair color of
his momma, but I see more of his daddy in him physically and
mentally. When Okey Dokey Dale gets out on the track, he gets hot
and wants to go.''
</P>
<P>
   There's another local tie to Okey Dokey Dale. Jeff Hooper,
director of administration at Lone Star, was in the ownership group
that campaigned Okey Dokey Baby when she won the Kansas.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991021.0511 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4789 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-RAC-PRICEREPORT-TEX     10-21 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PRICEREPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIME TIME MIGHT BE OVER FOR FILLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Silverbulletday might be bumping into a
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Look out everyone. Bob Baffert is thinking out loud again.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert is wondering _ yes, out loud _ what he should do with
one of the fillies in his barn. But it's a lot simpler this time.
</P>
<P>
   The question is not, as it was earlier this year, if he should
place the filly against the boys. Chilukki's a 2-year-old, so that
decision might not bother anyone until next year.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, Baffert is wondering if he should even run
the filly Silverbulletday. We're 15 days away from the Breeders'
Cup, and Baffert doesn't know if Silverbulletday will even run at
all.
</P>
<P>
   In a year when horses such as Puerto Madero, Free House,
Charismatic, Silver Charm, Victory Gallop, Mazel Trick and Real
Quiet have flashed ever so briefly before coming up injured,
Silverbulletday has been this year's fantastic racehorse from start
to just-about-finish.
</P>
<P>
   No, she's not Horse of the Year. But she has been the most fun
to watch throughout the season, turning on that trademark
acceleration and stepping easily away from her generation and
gender with the mark of the divisional champion that she is.
</P>
<P>
   But her loss in the Beldame Stakes last week at Belmont Park has
put the brakes on in the mind of Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's peaked,'' Baffert said, ``and she might be
tailing off.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the first reaction is to think that Baffert is playing the
poor boy. Maybe he's like a political candidate, taking the edge
off the expectations just in case the votes come up short.
</P>
<P>
   But there's something to Baffert's concern. No matter how
spectacular the racehorse _ and Silverbulletday has been every bit
of that _ there comes a time when they hit the wall.
</P>
<P>
   If a horse gets good, the demand for its appearances by
racetracks across the country surges. It will travel and run a lot
_ maybe more than the average stakes horse _ and then the wall
looms. Go ask the two most spectacular horses of the decade, Cigar
and Skip Away.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Cigar had his 16-race winning streak snapped, it
looked as if he would win another Breeders' Cup Classic that year.
He got caught in a speed trap that day at Del Mar, but that didn't
keep him from winning the Woodward the next month.
</P>
<P>
   Then he lost to Skip Away in the Jockey Club Gold Cup, when it
seemed as if Cigar was struggling to cut into the margin. That day,
he ran second. He finished third in the Breeders' Cup, and then he
was retired.
</P>
<P>
   Like Cigar, Skip Away traveled coast-to-coast winning the Donn
Handicap and Hollywood Gold Cup. But he had trouble in the
Massachusetts Handicap, winning by a close margin. He lost in the
Gold Cup to upsetter Allen Jerkins' Wagon Limit. And he didn't even
hit the board at the Breeders' Cup.
</P>
<P>
   In each instance, it wasn't a one-race funk before the Breeders'
Cup. A series of races showed that the superstar was getting
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   And so, too, it could be happening to Silverbulletday. Her race
in the Gazelle Stakes that led up to the Beldame was flat. After
winning the Alabama at Saratoga by nine lengths, she struggled to
win the Gazelle by a couple lengths under late pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there was no way Silverbulletday was going to catch
Beautiful Pleasure and that easy lead of hers on a sloppy track in
the Beldame. Maybe that was it. Or maybe she's hitting the wall
right about now. Maybe we'll find out on Breeders' Cup day. SEND TO
LOS AL
</P>
<P>
   Through the first 11 days of Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie's
quarter horse season, it's clear that getting the simulcast signal
out to Los Alamitos Racecourse in California is a good idea.
Because state law in California restricts out-of-state simulcasts
to times when Los Alamitos is conducting its own live meet, Lone
Star can only send the simulcasts at night.
</P>
<P>
   The benefit is easy to see. On Thursday and Friday nights when
Los Alamitos is part of the network, Lone Star handles $737,000 off
track. On Saturday and Sunday when Los Alamitos is absent, Lone
Star handles $271,000 off track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agonized over this decision before the meet started,'' Lone
Star general manager Corey Johnsen said. ``We get more revenue from
live betting on track, and we get a lot more crossover betting on
our live product from people watching the thoroughbred simulcasts
here at Lone Star during the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Live betting on track, so far, is down from last year (from
$269,000 to $257,000). Johnsen said the current racing schedule
will remained unchanged this year. But it might change in favor of
more night racing in time for next year's quarter horse season.
Delightful dashes A Delightful Dasher, winner of the All American
Futurity last month, is scheduled to make his next start in the
trials of the $425,000 Golden State Futurity tonight at Los
Alamitos. The final is Nov. 5. CHECK OUT THE TIME
</P>
<P>
   Artax caught many an eye when he cut through 6 furlongs in 1
minute, 7 3-5 seconds to win the Forest Hills Handicap last week at
Belmont Park. The time broke the track record set a decade ago by
Texas-bred Groovy.
</P>
<P>
   But also last week, a horse named Lexicon rattled through 6
furlongs in 1:07 4-5 to win the Ancient Title Breeders' Cup
Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   The performance by Artax has to be deemed superior, and that's
not just because he went a tick faster. Remember that Santa Anita
has a hardpan of a racing surface compared to Belmont's ``Big
Sandy'' strip. CHANGE IN SCENERY
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughbred racing finishes Sunday at Retama Park near San
Antonio, and the thoroughbreds start running Thursday at Sam
Houston Race Park in Houston through April 9. Here are the
highlights for Houston:
</P>
<P>
   Texas Champions Day, with purses of more than $675,000,
including the $200,000 Gallery Furniture Texan Juvenile, is set for
Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The $150,000 John Connally Breeders' Cup Turf is set for Feb.
26.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-21-99 2316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
