<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES CRUEL SUB IN SUBWAY SERIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It could have been a historic Subway Series of
riveting drama and tabloid hysterics between the New York Yankees
and New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   It could have revived long ago memories when the Yankees so
often would spend their Octobers battling the Brooklyn Dodgers or
the New York Giants to determine the baseball champion of the
planet.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been the Bronx vs. Queens, the established,
aristocratic Yankees putting their sacred reputation on the line
against the sassy, resilient Mets, the controversial New York
mayor, Rudy Guliani, inflaming the passions of many of his
constituents by openly rooting for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   But those doughty Atlanta Braves, who have turned the World
Series into their private stage during the 1990s, ruined the New
York party Tuesday evening by eliminating the Mets to win the
National League pennant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toughest loss I've ever gone through,'' says Harry Minor, the
longtime Mets scouts
</P>
<P>
   from Long Beach. ``I've gone over that game 100 times in my
mind. Tough, tough loss.''
</P>
<P>
   The bereaved Minor is picking the Braves to continue their good
fortune against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Braves pitching is just too good,'' he says. ``And
pitching is going to wind up winning this World Series. I know the
Yankees also have good pitching, but they're not as deep as the
Braves. There are some questions marks about the Yankees' pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know (Orlando) Hernandez has been solid. But the
left-hander, Andy Petitte, has been erratic, although he's pitched
well lately. Coney (David Cone) isn't what he once was. And neither
apparently is Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Braves still have Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine and John Smoltz
to throw at you, as well as Kevin Millwood. I think overall the
Yankees might have a better ball club. But the Braves' pitching
just seems to shut everyone down.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have opened as minus $120 favorite in Las Vegas,
but, ironically, the Braves are minus $115 picks with Glavine
starting in Saturday night's World Series opener at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of two-way action on this series,'' reports
Jimmy Vaccaro, the well-known Las Vegas gambler. ``There really
isn't a clear-cute
</P>
<P>
   favorite.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   The Braves remind me so much of the 1988 Dodgers. Every break
and fortuitous bounce seem to go their way. ...
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones fans will disagree with me, but I think the best
player on either side is Derek Jeter. ...
</P>
<P>
   Whoever thought the day would arrive when Roger Clemens would be
referred to as the weak link of a team's pitching staff? ...
</P>
<P>
   There were those like me who thought the Braves would decline
when they lost their All-Star catcher, Javier Lopez. We were wrong.
If anything, the team is even tougher with the fiery Eddie Perez.
...
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre has ascended to genius status these days with the
Yankees. It's a level he never came faintly close to reaching when
he lost managerial jobs with the Mets, Braves and St. Louis
Cardinals. Funny what miracles George Steinbrenner's formidable
bank account can do for a person's baseball IQ. ...
</P>
<P>
   Rey Ordonez is as exceptional as a fielder as he is
unexceptional as a hitter. ...
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine's loyalty to Kenny Rogers that goes back to
their days with the Texas Rangers might have cost the Mets an N.L.
pennant. ...
</P>
<P>
   Those rushing to anoint Bobby Cox are suffering amnesia and seem
to have forgotten his countless playoff blunders in the past that I
think cost the Braves at least one or even two World Series titles.
...
</P>
<P>
   I get the feeling that the Yankees don't think anyone can beat
them, but the Braves' stout pitching quickly can change such an
attitude. ...
</P>
<P>
   I actually saw Bobby Cox play football and basketball, as well
as baseball, when he attended Selma High up in the San Joaquin
Valley. He was a terrific quarterback who had many scholarship
offers, but signed a contract with the Los Angeles Dodgers. ...
</P>
<P>
   If I were Jimy Williams, the Boston manager, I'd have been
kicked out long before Game 4 of the ALCS when the umpires blew two
more calls against the Red Sox. The Yankees didn't need help from
the umps to beat the Red Sox, but they certainly got it. ...
</P>
<P>
   A guy who didn't identify himself left a message on my answering
machine the other day wondering why Paul Hackett wore sun glasses
on an overcast afternoon at South Bend. Perhaps he wanted to shield
his eyes from the Trojans' latest collapse. ...
</P>
<P>
   The USC-Notre Dame match featured two men, Hackett and Bob
Davies, who I doubt ever will receive Coach of the Year
consideration. ...
</P>
<P>
   I've seen teams lapse into chaos during crisis time, but I don't
recall any more disoriented at such a juncture than Hackett's
Trojans. Now I have an inkling what happened to him at Pittsburgh.
...
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone care that Mike Tyson is fighting again this weekend?
...
</P>
<P>
   Will someone please tell my old radio pal, Chris Roberts, to
start using the proper articles during his UCLA broadcasts. He
mistakenly keeps using ``that'' instead of ``the,'' like, ``Cory
Paus scrambled to that
</P>
<P>
   20-yard line'' or the Bruins are all the way down to that
</P>
<P>
   10-yard line. Maybe that
</P>
<P>
   Chris Roberts is a rhetorical pioneer determined to alter that
</P>
<P>
   English language. ...
</P>
<P>
   The dynamic Long Beach State women's basketball coach, Dallas
Boychuk-Bolla, is celebrating her birthday today. Chivalry and not
being too lazy to look it up in the 49ers' press guide prevents me
from revealing her age even though she's not old enough yet for
such entitlement. ...
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Ortiz was given an ovation for his moving introduction of
the ailing former featherweight champion, Raul Rojas, at the World
Boxing Hall of Fame banquet last Saturday night in Los Angeles. ...
</P>
<P>
   There is no one who enjoys listening to Bob Costas talk more
than Bob Costas. ...
</P>
<P>
   I think the Raiders are the best 3-3 team in the NFL. ...
</P>
<P>
   I know a guy who bet against Miami the past two weekends, and he
suffered mightily in the wake of the Dolphins' final-second
victories over Indianapolis and New England. ...
</P>
<P>
   Now that Keri Nishimoto has become a top-flight setter, what's
the Long Beach State volleyball Houdini, Brian Gimmillaro, going to
do with the talented freshman, Brittany Hochevar, who was touted to
be Misty May's successor at the start of the season? I doubt
Hochevar will stand patiently on the sidelines for the next two
years waiting for Nishimoto to graduate. ...
</P>
<P>
   Wilt Chamberlain and I became friends after a heated argument in
which, in the impulsive stupidity of my youth, I actually invited
him to punch me. Fortunately, he declined, or else I wouldn't now
be typing out these words on my computer. ...
</P>
<P>
   Those who saw Joe McDonnell and Del Harris laughingly chatting
it up at Phil Trani's golf tournament last Monday were startled by
the sight, since McDonnell spent almost all his waking hours for a
couple of years cruelly vilifying the former Laker head coach on
his radio broadcasts. ...
</P>
<P>
   Optimism is oozing at Long Beach State about the men's
basketball team, and the law of averages certainly is on Wayne
Morgan's side. I mean, one of these years Morgan is bound to have a
winning season.
</P>
</TEXT>
