<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-21 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4794 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX     10-21 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MAYBE LAST TIME, IT'S THE HATFIELDS AND MCTRAITORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON  
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Let's be frank here. The idea of TCU playing
Rice for an inside track to all the conference's football marbles
is:
</P>
<P>
   A. a stunning example of NCAA parity.
</P>
<P>
   B. the plot of another wacky Dan Jenkins book.
</P>
<P>
   C. a joke that the Rice band won't be able to resist.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it's true. In this last year of the 1900s, it appears that
the planets have aligned, the Southwest Conference is spinning in
its grave, and tomorrow in Houston the TCU Horned Frogs will
actually play the Rice Owls in a game that brims with possible
postseason significance.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of game that the Frogs and Owls used to play
semiregularly when your granddaddy was at TCU. It's the kind of
showdown that prompted a once-princely edifice like Rice Stadium to
be built in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   It's for an upper hand in the (wince) WAC, that
Honey-They-Shrunk-The-Conference league. It's all about private
school pride and ``why didn't you call and tell me you were
leaving?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it's a big game,'' TCU coach Dennis Franchione has finally
admitted. ``What I've been telling the kids is that, yes, this is a
big game, but there could be bigger ones.''
</P>
<P>
   At 3-3, the Frogs are on a relative roll, having run roughshod
at home over San Jose State and Tulsa. Rice, meanwhile, has won
four consecutive against the likes of Navy, Tulsa, Hawaii and San
Jose State.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the same, granted, as knocking off Baylor and Texas
A&AMP;M, but neither Rice nor TCU is in a position to toss any fish
back. Rice hasn't been to a bowl game in 38 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Western Athletic Conference winner will earn a trip to the
Las Vegas Bowl. Both teams have legitimate shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls, like Franchione's Frogs, move the football best when
on the ground. Also like the Frogs, Ken Hatfield's Owls have
displayed a begrudging defense. The teams rank one-two in the WAC
in both rushing and total defense.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers don't lie. Life clearly is easier on the eyes when
you don't have to drive to Austin, College Station or Lubbock every
other week. Though they are bound, in the fall of 2001, for even
greener pastures, the Frogs should not deny that their football
fortunes have been enriched by competing in the rebellious WAC.
</P>
<P>
   But that brings up a sore point. Rice officials reportedly are
peeved that TCU has accepted an invitation to bolt to Conference
USA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Houston Chronicle'' this week reported that Rice
representatives called TCU officials to ask if it was true that the
Frogs were pursuing a C-USA spot. The Rice people claimed that TCU
said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the way we do business,'' Rice president Malcolm
Gillis told the ``Chronicle''.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not. But if Rice University had been so haughty and
serious about its athletic commitments, maybe the old Southwest
Conference would still be together.
</P>
<P>
   So it's a grudge game now, they're saying down in Houston. The
Hatfields and the McTraitors. Two longtime rivals _ TCU joined the
SWC in 1923, Rice in 1915 _ who might possibly be meeting on the
football field for the final time in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might be our most difficult game so far,'' Hatfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione, meanwhile, has nothing but praise for the
mini-miracle that Hatfield has put together at Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good coach,'' Franchione said. ``When you play Ken's
teams, you have to beat them, because you know that they won't beat
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchione contends that he thought the Owls would be in the
thick of the WAC hunt even before Rice's current four-game win
streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a different team when they're at home on the turf,''
he said. ``And I don't know why exactly that is.''
</P>
<P>
   He means Rice Stadium, of course, a gallows of a college
football home. With its worn turf and its rusted plumbing, the old
stadium abounds in Midnight Express decor.
</P>
<P>
   But Hatfield's Owls have reveled in it. Rice has won 12 of its
13 WAC home games, including its past eight. In addition, Rice's
current crop of seniors has never lost to a TCU team, either at
home or in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it's true. Tomorrow those two perennial Darrell Royal
punchlines, Rice and TCU, will meet in a football game of
late-October significance.
</P>
<P>
   A big game, in spite of all the years it wasn't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
