<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH SEASON FOR UCLA'S FARMER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This time last year, UCLA receiver Danny Farmer
had 33 catches for 659 yards. This year, he has 19 catches for 432
yards. He's missed two games because of a sprained ankle. He's
struggling to adjust to a quarterback not named Cade McNown, and
he's disappointed in UCLA's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Is this any way to spend a senior season?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have as many losses this year as we did the last two years
combined,'' he said, quietly. ``Things are a little sour now.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmer's latest problem is a strained groin. He didn't practice
this week and is questionable for Saturday's game at Oregon State,
but he remains optimistic about the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to have fun, since there's only so many games
left,'' he said. ``It's always difficult with a new quarterback,
but I think it's made me a better receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to concentrate more, run better routes and make sure
I'm open so Cory (Paus) can see me. It's actually made me a lot
better. I can see it watching tapes from last year and this year.''
</P>
<P>
   On tape, perhaps, but not in the statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: UCLA's daily medical report is so long coach Bob
Toledo ordered a rare no-pad practice Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most beat-up and sick I've ever seen a team this
late,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fullbacks Durell Price, Matt Stanley and Adam Geitner are either
hurt or sick or tired. One tight end, Mike Seidman, is out and
Bryan Fletcher is questionable. Receiver Freddie Mitchell is
hobbling. Farmer's questionable. Tailback DeShaun Foster and
cornerback Jason Bell are out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're as low (on manpower) as we've been since I've been
here,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Parting shot: Cal linebacker Sekou Sanyika is more impressed
with Washington, the Bears' upcoming opponent, than he was with
UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Washington) is much more physical than UCLA,'' Sanyika told
reporters. ``(The Huskies) like to hit people, and they don't shy
away from contact like some of the guys from UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   Lineup changes: Redshirt freshman Lovell Houston will start at
strong safety in place of senior Eric Whitfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lovell is like the quarterback: He's very inexperienced,''
Toledo said. ``He's going to make some mistakes, but that's the
only way you learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Ryan Nece has retained his starting job, but he'll
split time with freshman Marcus Reese, who specializes in pass
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Homecoming: UCLA's only Oregon native is reserve left tackle
Bryce Bohlander, a true freshman from Keizer, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Bohlander expected to redshirt when he arrived for training
camp, but injuries and disabled-parking suspensions left the Bruins
one tackle short. He plays 20-25 snaps per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I didn't want to play,'' he said. ``I thought I'd get
killed out there weighing 265 pounds. I didn't think I'd be good
enough to hold my own. But now, looking back on it, it's kind of
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Review of the week: Defensive tackle Pete Holland was overloaded
academically this week and did not review a book.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Toledo postponed naming captains until tonight's
team meeting, hoping someone would emerge. ``We need some
leadership,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are the least-penalized team in the Pac-10, but
they've committed the most turnovers (21) and have the worst
third-down defense: Opponents are converting 42 percent of their
third-down attempts.
</P>
<P>
   There's no official kickoff time for the UCLA-Arizona game Oct.
30 at the Rose Bowl. Yes, it could be a night game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
