<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Oct. 22 and thereafter. For questions about stories, please contact
Lori Stassi at (818) 713-3705.
</P>
<P>
   AMGEN-ALZHEIMER'S (Los Angeles) _ Researchers for Amgen Inc. and
the Harvard Medical School will publish an article in today's
edition of the journal Science that identifies a compound key to
the formation of plaques that the researchers say are the cause of
Alzheimer's disease. The discovery _ which a spokesman for the
Thousand Oaks-based biotech giant called ``the Holy Grail'' of
Alzheimer's research _ could lead to the formulation of a drug to
inhibit those compounds. By Jason Cohen (will move on the ``a''
national, ``n'' California and ``f'' financial news wires)
</P>
<P>
   BELMONT-VOTE (Los Angeles) _ In the wake of a divided
recommendation that the Belmont Learning Center go forward, only
one L.A. Unified board member said Thursday she would vote for the
high school's completion. Three other members said they would vote
to abandon the school being built atop a potentially explosive
former oil field. The three remaining board members declined to
state how they would vote in two weeks, but two sharply criticized
both the school and the recommendation to go forward. By Greg
Gittrich (will move on the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news
wires)
</P>
<P>
   BRUSH-DANGER (Los Angeles) _ With wildfire conditions the worst
since the drought several years ago, Los Angeles firefighters are
battling utilities and large land owners over a backlog of brush
clearance. The city and county are billing agencies to pay for
brush removal, but a backlog remains, endangering some areas. Wary
of wildfires, Tujunga residents like Mike Kruly clear brush
year-round and are angered that Southern California Edison ignores
overgrown vegetation along power line corridors well into one of
the region's worst wildfire seasons. By Michael Coit (will move on
the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news wires)
</P>
<P>
   GAMBINA-SHOOTING (Los Angeles) _ It was a quiet night. Ralph
Gambina was preparing to close his Tujunga store when two masked
men burst in with a gun, demanding money. Even as Gambina pretended
to be scared, telling them, ``No problem, man. Calm down, be cool.
Don't shoot me,'' he was just waiting for a split second opening to
pull his own gun and defend his store. From his hospital bed,
Gambina tells how he shot a robber and was injured. By Harrison
Sheppard (will move on the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news
wires)
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-CAMPUS (Los Angeles) _ The city of Glendale has initiated
the process of collecting information from agencies regarding Walt
Disney Co.'s Creative Campus, giving the project an official start.
If completed as proposed, Disney would turn an old airfield into a
huge campus that would employ thousands of workers. By Dave McNary
(will move on the ``a'' national, ``n'' national and ``f''
financial news wires)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
