<SLUG> BC-RAC-SANTAANITA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORES NEARS 2,000-WIN MARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ARCADIA _ A content and somewhat shy David Flores ended
Thursday just two wins shy of the 2,000-victory mark on North
American thoroughbred tracks.
</P>
<P>
   He's looking forward to hitting the mark by Saturday, when he'll
be aboard Prime Timber in the $250,000 Grade II Oak Tree Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Flores and Prime Timber drew the outside post for Saturday's
race, which will feature a nine-horse field. Flores is confident
that Prime Timber will fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``That horse ran impressively last time,'' the jockey said.
``Hopefully, he'll break good from that spot. I'll see what
(trainer Bob Baffert) tells me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The confidence is well-earned. After all, Flores, 31, has had a
very good 1999. His mounts have earned $10.1 million in 1,001
starts through the beginning of the week. He has won 182 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a good horse, you look good,'' Flores said.
</P>
<P>
   Flores' professional riding career began in the early 1980s at
Agua Caliente in Tijuana, but any wins he had there don't count in
his overall total.
</P>
<P>
   Through Thursday, Flores was the leading rider at Oak Tree with
20 victories.
</P>
<P>
   But, Flores, who began riding in Sonora, Mexico, at age 8,
admits he will be glad when the 2,000-win mark is behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough colony of jockeys,'' Flores said. ``I just
want to break my 2,000. It's a gift that I've gotten this far. I'm
lucky to be here because I love what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Top trainer: Halfway through Oak Tree, the best winning
percentage by a trainer isn't held by anybody named Baffert,
Mandella, Lukas, or even Spawr.
</P>
<P>
   It's Doug Peterson. Going into Thursday's race card, Peterson
horses were winners in five of the 10 races in which they were
entered. Seven of the 10 finished in the money.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, who is recovering from recent surgery, says the
success is due in large part to good fortune and teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   `I try to keep my horses in the worst company and myself in the
best company,'' Peterson joked.
</P>
<P>
   Four of his five wins have come in combination with jockey Matt
Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know what the magic is, but (Garcia and I) did
win four in a row,'' Peterson said. `Matt has a God-given talent on
a horse that many people don't see.''
</P>
<P>
   Feature winner: Dianehill won Thursday's Oak Tree feature,
overcoming several horses with a late stretch run.
</P>
<P>
   With the win in the 6{-furlong race for fillies and mares,
Dianehill paid $3.60, $2.60 and $2.20.
</P>
<P>
   Early favorite Honest Lady was scratched from the race Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Former Santa Anita Clerk of Scales Dean Scarborough died Tuesday
morning. He was 76.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime minor league baseball player, Scarborough coached and
managed in the Pacific Coast League. He began his racing career at
Caliente in the 1960s. He retired from Santa Anita in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   A viewing will be held Sunday from 4 p.m. to 9 p.m. at Memory
Garden Memorial Park in Brea. Burial will be Monday at 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The heat is beginning to take its toll on jockeys riding at
Santa Anita. Corey Nakatani, suffering from heat exhaustion, was
taken off his mounts after the third race Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On the up-side, he celebrated his 29th birthday on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Jockey Laffit Pincay entered Thursday 31 wins away from tying
Bill Shoemaker's record of all-time wins. He was not named to any
horses Thursday and will not ride today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
