r s BC-BOX-AYALA-TEX     10-21 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-AYALA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AYALA TRYING TO AVOID PITFALLS OF TITLE DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE SANCHEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Even before he steps into the ring tomorrow
night to face Saohin Srithai Condo, World Boxing Association
bantamweight champion Paulie Ayala has secured a place in Fort
Worth's boxing history.
</P>
<P>
   When he took the World Boxing Association 118-pound title from
Johnny Tapia on June 26, Ayala became the newest area champion. But
when he defends his title for the first time, he will be fighting
to break from a history that has staggered three homegrown
champions before him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they look back on me I want them to say I was a good
fighter,'' Ayala said. ``Long-term, I would like to stay undefeated
for the rest of my boxing career and be a great champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Still to be determined, however, is how Ayala will fit into Fort
Worth's boxing lore. Will he join Donald Curry, who held a world
title for most of a seven-year span beginning in 1983? Or will he
lose his belt quickly, as Gene Hatcher, Stevie Cruz and Troy Dorsey
did?
</P>
<P>
   Even before Ayala steps into the ring Saturday, he must try to
muster the hunger that won him the title and avoid the distractions
of fighting in front of a hometown crowd. A history of strange
first title defenses for the area's past champions also seems to
hang over Ayala.
</P>
<P>
   Mansfield's Dorsey won the International Boxing Federation
featherweight (126-pound) title on June 3, 1991, with a first-round
knockout against Alfred Rangel of San Antonio in Las Vegas. But
Dorsey's first defense proved disastrous. Fatigued and bleeding, he
lost a decision against Manuel Medina in Inglewood, Calif., only
two months later.]
</P>
<P>
   ``When I defended the title I had problems making weight,''
Dorsey said. ``I spent so much time in the sauna and not eating
that after the fourth round, I had no energy. I was out of gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``My big mistake was that I didn't eat enough. I would have one
meal a day; I'm talking a baked potato or a plate of rice.''
</P>
<P>
   His advice to Ayala is simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't lay back just because you're the champion,'' Dorsey
said. ``Let him know you are the champion. You can't let the
distractions of fighting at home get you out of your fight,
remember the hunger that got you here.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending his title at Will Rogers Memorial Coliseum proved to
be somewhat of a disadvantage for former WBA featherweight champion
Stevie Cruz, who lost to Antonio Esparragoza on a 12th-round
technical knockout in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a bundle of nerves,'' said Cruz, who had upset the
unbeaten Barry McGuigan of Ireland for the belt. ``It didn't
motivate me a whole lot to fight at home. I was going against the
No. 1 contender and it played on my mind. But it sounds like
Paulie's confident, and it will work in his favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Ayala: ``There is no nervousness. I am ready to fight. It's
taken me a long time to get my world title.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Hatcher, who won the WBA junior welterweight (140-pound)
title against Johnny Bumphus in June 1984, said that positive
attitude will aid Ayala in quest for a successful defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a defense you don't let the negative overrun the positive
attitude, '' said Hatcher, who needed 15 rounds to win his first
title defense against Argentina's Ubaldo Nestor Sacco in 1984 in
Fort Worth then lost a rematch seven months later. ``In that first
defense, that is a big thing. I just went out there with a positive
attitude, and that's what Paulie needs to stay with.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Paulie has going is his hunger. I can see it on his
face.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala was out of the gym for only two weeks after he defeated
Tapia and is determined to win, said Henry Mendez, one of Ayala's
trainers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paulie has worked harder than ever,'' Mendez said. ``Knowing
that he is the champion and knowing that people want what he's got
has made him work harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran boxing manager David Gorman, who worked with Ayala as an
amateur and is linked to several of Fort Worth's professional
champions, knows first-hand the difficulties of a first world title
defense.
</P>
<P>
   The champion must fight in his first title defense as if it is
his last bout, Gorman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way of telling if it can happen again,'' Gorman
said. ``All you can do is prepare the best you know how, and defend
your title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody plans on losing a title on the first defense. It's the
last thing on your mind.'' / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
